ts 10^500 possible solutions makes it hard to envisage an experimental outcome that could falsify it. The fact that it is consistent with relativity and quantum theory, and in fact has the attractive feature of reconciling them, does not make it a scientific theory. To the extent that string theory is allowed to promote itself as scientific, this is more a political result of it being favoured by prestigious institutions and individuals.\r\n\r\n(Leon)\r\nJust because a theory or hypothesis does not conform to the scientific method (i.e., subject to falsification by direct physical/material observation or experimentation) does not make it \"unscientific\".  The question here is whether the universe is solely composed of physically ponderable matter, or has both a physical/material and meta- or supra-physical component, along with a ubiquitous non-physical subjective consciousness.\r\n  \r\n(Simon)\r\nI won\'t claim to have grasped everything proposed in the ABC model, but it does look at first sight to fall into the same category as string theory.\r\n\r\n(Leon) \r\nABC theory can\'t fall in the same catagory as string theory (which has many different solutions)â€”since ABC has only one possible solution, and is based on an entirely different hypothetical paradigm...  Namely (in a nutshell); The cosmos and everything in it is composed, fundamentally, of an endless series of zero-point \'spinergy\' (angular momentum) originated, resonantly harmonic, fractal involved standing wavesâ€”ranging in frequency/energy between zero and infinite, and capable of carrying infinite information as interference patterned holograms on their wave front surfaces or â€œevent horizonsâ€.\r\n\r\n(Simon)\r\nMy only other comment is to wonder whether we need anything quite as complex as ABC. Simplicity is regarded as a virtue in scientific theory. A proposition that the structure of spacetime can code for qualia might be sufficient, and might also hint at something about the origin of the universe. \r\n\r\n(Leon) \r\nThe ABC theory considers \"everything\" that is necessary to come up with a comprehensive TOEâ€”to include both consciousness and matterâ€”as two complementary aspects of fundamental unconditioned absolute (0 degrees K) space (acting as a BEC located everywhere in metric spacetime)â€”one subjective (the unconditioned conscious ZP itself), and the other, objective (potential energy or ZPE as fundamental abstract or nonlinear spin or angular momentum).  Obviously consciousness must be absolutely stationary relative to the hologram information, in order to discriminate between the finest modulations of wave patterned information on both wakeful (physical) and dream (UHF metaphysical) space-time levels.   \r\n\r\nAnd, ABC also considersâ€”based on mathematically sound, multidimensional, non euclidian fractal geometryâ€”that our physical universe is a fourth order fractal harmonic (involution) of the initial cosmic field...  Which lower (frequency/energy) order physical spacetime field continues to fractal involve analogously (i.e., As above, so below) all the way down to the finest \"virtual\" particle-waves in the Planck false vacuum.\r\n\r\nIncidentally, this standing wave nature of all reality has been satisfactory proven by Milo Wolff and Gabriel LaFreniere, among othersâ€”all of which is consistent with General Relativity, and the wave theories of de Broglie, SchrÃ¶dinger, Pauli, etc.\r\nhttp://glafreniere.com/matter.htm \r\nhttp://www.spaceandmotion.com/\r\nhttp://www.quantummatter.com/space-resonance/beyond-point-particle/\r\n\r\nSo ABC rests on at least one firm scientific basis that contradicts the standard model of physics and its basic assumptions (i.e. particle wave duality, wave function collapse, matter only, etc.)\r\n\r\nItâ€™s obvious that if the propositions of ABCâ€”considering that unconditioned consciousness and potential mass energy or matter are fundamental dual characteristics or qualities of absolute unconditioned space itself, and that all information of consciousness is carried and transmitted by radiant fields as holograms detectable and simply reconstructed and holographically experienced by perceptive ZP consciousnessâ€”as thoroughly explained by simple coherent energy projection/reflection (see my web site***)... Then, this model is far more parsimonious than any material based theory could ever beâ€”that tries to introduce the complexity of objective quantum effects and neural correlates, as precursors of both consciousness and its experience of qualia.  \r\n\r\nSo, I still claim that subjective consciousness (awareness, will, qualia, etc.)  can never be explained using the objective scientific method under its present reductive materialist paradigm.\r\n\r\n*** \r\nhttp://knol.google.com/k/how-it-all-began#\r\n','2010-11-14 08:02:54','2010-11-14 08:02:54'),(1025,96,48,'The number of solutions in string theory just makes things worse; the core problem is the lack of testability, even if there was only one solution, and this might apply to ABC as well.\r\n\r\nI\'d suggest that the problem with consciousness and modern science is not the science itself but the establishment individuals that apply it. Almost all of these have a remit to preserve the Newtonian world view, to deny agency or any other importance to consciousness, and to exclude consciousness from any position in the physical universe. None of their arguments seem remotely convincing, but established prestige and modern scientific career structures and research funding ensure that they dominate the debate, if you can call it a debate. However, this does not mean that some established science that has the undoubted advantage of having resisted falsification might not provide some help.\r\n\r\nIn neuroscience the Crick-Koch approach has unacceptably blurred the distinction between a correlate, which merely has a relationship to something else, and a proper explanation of something. Nevertheless, the best established correlate, the gamma synchrony might give us a clue about where to look. Recent studies on this synchrony come close to solving the binding problem, and while this does not explain consciousness, it is true that consciousness is usually identified as a unity, and this might give us ideas on what to look for.\r\n\r\nRecently I have become unhappy with the term \'quantum consciousness\'. This is partly because the loose usage of the term \'quantum\', itself a dire consequence of quantum science having been minimised in the mainstream education system. The other is that it is no easier to explain consciousness in terms of individual quanta or their interaction than it is in terms of classical features such as synapses. I would rather think in terms of consciousness and fundamental physics, with processing in the brain gating access to the fundamental level of the universe, which is the only place where it seems possible to place the qualia.\r\n \r\nSimon','2010-11-14 17:27:08','2010-11-14 17:27:08'),(1028,96,48,'We agree that testability is a problem in string theories due to their many solutions.  However, even if they can be boiled down to one solution such as in M or superstring theory with 11 dimensionsâ€”they still can make very little progress in explaining subjective consciousness or qualia... Which, as already noted, appears to be a property of the fundamental level of the Universe... Or, as proposed in the ABC model; â€œA fundamental quality of the pre-cosmic unconditioned absolute (zero degrees K) space located everywhere at the ZPE origin of all spacetime particle-wave fields and their composite atomic, molecular and material formsâ€.\r\n\r\nThis is based on already proven scientific theories that all matter is fundamentally electrical and of a standing wave nature. (Ref.: Einstein, Maxwell, Schrodinger, Pauli, de Broglie, Wolff, etc.)... And, such a space would necessarily act as a Bose Einstein Condensate (BEC)â€”which would account for the non-locality of consciousness, as well as its entanglement throughout the body... So that a pinprick felt in a finger is also perceived globally by our center of individual self-consciousness... Whichâ€”according to the overall fractal field surrounding the entire body at the highest possible frequency phase order in hyperspace (the eternal human soul)â€”is located in the naval chakra. See: http://leonmaurer.info/ABCimages/Chakrafielddiag-fig.col.jpg\r\n\r\nWhile the ABC model also cannot be generally or particularly falsified using conventional scientific methodsâ€”many of its precepts such as the wave nature of matter, the hologram nature of all constructive and reflective information, can be inferred or demonstrated both observationally and mind experimentally.  \r\n\r\nFor example it\'s obvious that all reflected visual information observed from any viewpoint in spacetime, converges as a wave interference pattern at each such zero-point. This implies that the information describing the structural forms of the entire cosmos is actually a hologram.  \r\n\r\nAs the universe and all its parts, no matter how complex, can be viewed in perfect 3-dimensions and color quality in the mindâ€”this is direct evidence that the mind is a radiant field which carries the total information as interference patterns in every zero-point on its spherical surface, and that zero-point consciousness, in conjunction with its surrounding spin momentum-sourced coherent radiation, is a hologram image detector, holographic re-constructer, and perceiver.  (Actually, as all we really see reconstructed holographically is the 2-D image on the retina, after being transformed back to a 2-D hologram in the mind fieldâ€”it requires both eyes viewing the outer world hologram from different anglesâ€”to enable us to experience, and be able to judge actual 3-D depth.)  All this, incidentally, is perfectly consistent with already proven holographic principles a well as all the fundamental laws of electrodynamics.\r\n\r\nSince we see such images as if viewed from a single point in the center of our headâ€”it\'s self evident that the image in the mindâ€”after converging to each point on the eye lens, focused onto the 2-D retina, and processed by the neural network of the brainâ€”must be a hologram.  Thus, the brainâ€™s EM field would have to carry the image as wave interference patterns on its 2D spherical surface... And the mind field would necessarily be a resonant, higher order radiant harmonic field in hyperspaceâ€”whose virtual particle frequency/mass-energy is closest to the infinite cyclic spin momentum of the conscious zero-point.  \r\n\r\nAccordingly, it becomes obvious that consciousness or unconditioned subjectivity remains outside of all metric space and time, and apart from all physical/material or energetic processes.\r\n\r\nIn light of all the aboveâ€”there doesnâ€™t seem to be any credibility in considering observer or perceiver/responder consciousness (awareness, will, qualia, etc.) as quantum effects or epiphenomena of neurological, physiological or biological processes. \r\n\r\nApparently, other than its neural correlates, and possibly psychological processes, consciousness, in all its subjective aspects, cannot be explained by the present scientific method.\r\n\r\nLeon\r\n\r\n','2010-11-16 08:02:45','2010-11-16 08:02:45'),(1029,1,60,'\r\nWelcome, everyone, as supporters of this new survey topic on wiki leaks.\r\n\r\nI just wanted to point out a few things for the new people about how things work here, what the possibilities are, and to make sure everyone is participating as they desire or intended.\r\n\r\nCurrently, So far, there is only the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/119/1 Agreement Statement], which is basically the survey question, or anything that everyone agrees on.  In addition to this, there has so far only been one possible POV camp created, the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/119/2 Wiki Leaks is Great] camp.\r\n\r\nCurrently, Moss and Rooster are only supporting the agreement statement, which is fine.  It is a good way to show your support of the importance of the survey question, while not necessarily taking any side in the competing POV structure.  Also, it is a good place to start till you understand how things work, and or you wait till someone creates a camp that is closer to your current POV.\r\n\r\nSo if you have an opinion, one way or another, feel free to let everyone know, so we can help you create such a new camp, or anyone can create any new camp any time they like.  Or if, instead, you believe that Wiki Leaks is great, feel free to join that camp, to communicate your beliefs to everyone, along with your support of the topic, itself.  If you ever want to change or join a new camp, just make sure you are currently on the right camp page you want to be in, before you click the join camp button.\r\n\r\nThanks everyone!!  And let me know if anyone has any other questions, or suggestions so we can make things more clear, sooner, on  how things should and can work.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2010-12-05 23:45:34','2010-12-05 23:45:34'),(1030,1,7,'It seems there are two camps, one striving to \"live in the balance with nature\", the other seeking \"material wealth\" and purchasing the lifestyle desired. \r\n\r\nPerhaps both could be achieved with long range planning and consideration of both \"camps\".\r\n\r\nClean air, water, community\'s infrastructure all have opportunity for the entrepreneur and big business.  If we focus together on achieving both goals, we need not destroy each others dream.\r\n\r\n','2011-01-24 07:57:58','2011-01-24 07:57:58'),(1031,1,7,'\r\nHi Eggy1943,\r\n\r\nThanks for the great post.\r\n\r\nI completely agree with your pointing out that if we focus on \"achieving both goals, we need not destroy each others dreams\".  That\'s exactly one of the big reasons we\'re developing canonizer.com.   So we can keep track of everyone\'s goals, wishes, and concerns together and make sure nothing gets left behind or ignored.\r\n\r\nThe first most important step towards better getting everyone everything they want is knowing, concisely and quantitatively, what everyone does want.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-01-25 02:53:09','2011-01-25 02:53:09'),(1034,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nI\'ve been discussing the consciousness survey project with many people over the past year since the current version of the Representational Qualia Theory statement was last updated.  I\'m always surprised at how many people say that they can\'t understand what it says - that it is just a collection of words to them.  So I\'m always interviewing as many people as possible in hopes of finding ways to improve things so it makes sense to more people with less effort.  I\'m wondering how many of you ever discuss and refer to this stuff with others, experience such, and possibly think of new ways to improve things because of this?\r\n\r\nI\'ve collected what I believe to be the best of these ideas and have produced a new version of the statement.  The changes aren\'t very significant.  I removed a bunch of redundancy and made things more concise.  I now user 650nm light, instead of 700nm for red, and some other things like that.  I think the most significant change is I think I now have a much better way to describe why phenomenal properties are ineffable with simple cause and effect observation, which hopefully in turn better describes what phenomenal properties are, compared to causal properties which require the proper interpretation to get the abstracted meaning out of them.  I rewrote the first several paragraphs of the statement using this.\r\n\r\nAnyway, if possible, before I officially submit this new version of the camp statement, it would be great if I could get as many of you as possible to review it, and help us make it even better.  If you are willing to even just give it a quick once over, before I officially propose it as a change to the camp statement, just send me a private e-mail and I\'ll send you a current copy you can redline.\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2011-04-18 00:51:44','2011-04-18 00:51:44'),(1035,1,54,'Hi Ryan,\r\n\r\nIn our attempt to better understand what panexperientialism is, I wonder if I might ask how much over lap there is between what you believe and some of the competing camps.\r\n\r\nMy understanding is that there is very much overlap between this and the doctrines described in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 Representational Qualia Theory] camp.  For example, I have heard that [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=67 Lincoln Canon], who is currently in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/8 Functional Property Dualism] camp and [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=133 John Gregg] who is in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/7 Material Property Dualism] camp consider their beliefs to be panexperiencialist.\r\n\r\nBoth of those camps are supporting sub camps of the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 Representational Qualia Theory] camp.  So I\'m wondering if this camp is different in name only to the doctrines contained in the Representational Qualia Theory camp, or is there more to your differences than that?\r\n\r\nThanks\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-04-19 03:23:26','2011-04-19 03:23:26'),(1038,96,48,'I agree with a great deal of what you say here, notably that the colour red is just a representation, and bears no resemblance to the oscillation of photons at a particular frequency. If this is what Dennett etc are talking about, it has no bearing on the reality or relevance of qualia. I sometimes think it would be better if we talked of mapping rather than representation. If we think of the map of a metro system in a large city, the pattern of coloured lines for different routes on a piece of paper bears no resemblance to the actual concrete tunnels and metal vehicles, but is very adaptive for getting around the city.\r\n\r\nIn talking about unity in the brain I am a bit surprised you don\'t mention the global gamma synchrony. Recent studies seem to come pretty close to conclusive demonstration of this as the unifying factor. Where an image is masked and therefore not coming into consciousness, it produces only local gamma synchrony, but where it is not masked and comes into consciousness, it produces global gamma synchrony. See \'Dynamic Coordination in the Brain\' from MIT Press (2010) or the summaries under the Neuroscience categories on www.quantum-mind.co.uk. Of course the synchrony remains only a correlate of consciousness and provides at best only hints about how qualia/consciousness arises.\r\n\r\nIt might also be worth talking about recent work on subjective choice and experience of reward in the brain. Choice or preference might be seen as what distinguishes conscious from automated behaviour. Studies show that in the orbitofrontal cortex the response correlates to the subjective appreciation of sensory input rather than the strength of the signal. See Edmund Rolls \'Emotion Explained\' and \'Memory, Attention and Decision Making, also \'The Orbitofrontal Cortex\' by Zald and Rauch and Subcortical Structures and Cognition by Kosiol and Budding. These are also summarised on the quantum-mind site. I feel generally we should more at new developments in neuroscience and less at philosophy and psychology. However the views of the above writers on consciousness itself can be safely ignored as they have been down loaded from philosophers.\r\n\r\nI am inclined to go down a similar route to Bernard Carr in looking for consciousness as a fundamental in the quantum vacuum/spacetime. Other explanations all seem to end with an explanatory gap.\r\n\r\nWhere I struggle with the statement is the ideas for exchanging qualia between minds in the near future. We certainly need more description of what would be involved here. ','2011-04-19 18:30:20','2011-04-19 18:30:20'),(1041,96,48,'\r\nHi Junius,\r\n\r\nThis is all great stuff.  Thanks for the contribution.  For me, the first I really heard of gama synchrony was at last year\'s TSC conference.  I still don\'t know much about it.  Perhaps you could make a proposed addition to the statement about this?\r\n\r\nAs far as struggling with the idea of exchanging qualia between minds, would you agree that there is some set of neural correlates that is our knowledge of a red strawberry, and another different set of neural correlates that is representing out knowledge of a green leaf?  And that somehow, there are neurons, such as those in the corpus callosum, that unifies all this together so we are aware of the red knowledge of the strawberry, and the green knowledge of the leaf, together all at once, aware of how different each is, and what these difference represent?\r\n\r\nOf course, just how such phenomenal properties are properties of and how these might be unified, is still obviously yet to be discovered.  But there are lots of possibilities, in things like Lehars wave theories, and as you point out, in quantum vacuum/space-time.  There are still lots of yet to be falsified theories about how this could be done, many crude frameworks of these theories are already appearing in the various sub camps.  To me, how it is done isn\'t so important at the higher level \"Representational Qualia Theory\" level.  The important thing at this higher level is simply representationalism, that a quale is a property of the final result of the perception process, and that we should someday be able to expect to find some way to find out if any of us do, indeed, have such things as red / green inverted qualia from the rest of us just as surely as our left hemisphere knows what red is like for our right hemisphere.\r\n\r\nToday, everyone just focuses on all the disagreement there is, at the less important levels, leading everyone to believe there is no agreement, whatsoever, in this field, on anything.  But I believe there is already a huge expert consensus on these general higher level ideas, it is just that nobody has had the ability to measure for or see this.\r\n\r\nWould you be interested in moving the panexperientialism camp into a supporting sub camp of the Representational Qualia Theory camp, or object to it if someone else proposed such a change to that camp?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2011-04-20 02:28:10','2011-04-20 02:28:10'),(1044,96,48,'Gamma Synchrony\r\nThis is based on research by Lucia Melloni and Wolf Singer at the Max Planck Institute published in 2010. For further reading see, \'New Horizons in the Neuroscience of Consciousness\'.\r\n\r\nThe authors discuss studies that show that conscious perceptions produce different types of brain activity from unconscious percepts. In particular, consciousness is demonstrated to produce long-range synchronisation of gamma oscillations in widely separated neural assemblies. The approx. 30-90 Hz oscillation of neuronal spiking, known as the gamma wave can become synchronised across large areas of the brain. The authors suggest that the synchronisation of widely distributed neuronal activity meets some of the requirements for explaining how conscious experience arises in the brain.\r\n\r\nThe brain comprises specialised although connected processing areas, and for these to become unified, it has to overcome the problem of representation in different modalities, such as hearing, seeing etc. In this research, it is proposed that the processing of spatially separated neuronal assemblies is bound together by means of the gamma synchrony.\r\n\r\nNeurons are known to be synchronised into coherent assemblies, and these assemblies are suggested to signal the presence of particular features to other neural assemblies. This process is suggested to give rise to to a distributed representation of the external environment. Neuronal assemblies form and dissolve rapidly, which could account for the easy shifting of consciousness from one focus to another.\r\n\r\nSynchronisation also allows better control of interaction between neurons. Thus excitatory inputs are seen to be effective at a particular point of the oscillation cycle, but are ignored at other times. This means that groups of neurons that oscillate in synchrony will be able to signal to one another, and that groups that are out of synchrony will be ignored. This mechanism can function within neural assemblies, but also between spatially separated assemblies. The frequency and phase of oscillation can alter to influence signaling.\r\n\r\nStudies suggest that local processing is unconscious, whereas large scale activity such as reciprocal signaling between separate neural assemblies is a correlate of consciousness. This is argued to be a \'small worlds\' system, where there is co-existence between local and long-range networks. In the brain, it is suggested that the local networks are between neurons only a few hundred micrometers apart within layers of the cortex, while the long-range networks run mainly through the white matter, and thus link spatially separated areas of the cortex. It is these latter that can establish the global coordination that is correlated to consciousness.\r\n\r\nThe authors propose that masking experiments are a good way of studying consciousness, because this allows the same stimuli to be either unconscious or conscious. In a study undertaken by the authors, words could be perceived consciously in some trials but unconsciously in others (Melloni et al, 2007). Local gamma synchronisation was similar in both cases, but with consciously perceived words there was a burst of long-distance gamma synchrony between the occipital, parietal and frontal cortices. Also subsequent to this burst, there was activity that could have indicated a transfer of information to working memory, while an increase in frontal cortex theta wave activity may have indicated material being held in working memory. Words processed at the unconscious level could lead to an increase in the power of the gamma frequency range, but only conscious stimuli produced increases in long-distance gamma synchronisation, plus possibly theta activity looks to be a requirement for consciousness.\r\n\r\nEven the authors admit that the gamma synchronisation is just a correlate, and does not explain how consciousness actually arises. However, it does look like providing an explanation of how conscious perceptions are unified. The redness of fruit in one assembly is synchronised or entrained with the greeness of leaves in another assembly, and the blueness of sky in still another, plus the humming of bees and song of birds in the more distant but still synchronised assemblies of the auditory cortex.\r\n\r\nOne aspect which is touched on, but not enlarged on in the mainstream literature is that there is a zero or near zero time lag in the synchronisation of spatially separated neural assemblies, which bears the signature of quantum entanglement. Between 2007 and 2010 studies of photosynthetic organism demonstrated the existence of possibly functional quantum coherence and entanglement in biological systems even at room temperature, partly refuting the claims of the much-hyped (Tegmark 2000) paper.\r\n\r\nAs for constructing something that could communicate qualia, in principle anything that is physical can be built, but the prospects for something like the above in the near term looks daunting. The photosynthetic studies suggest working at the level of coherent electrons within the interior of neurons, bearing in mind that a neuron is said to be more complex than London. The difficulties of the relatively more straight forward requirements for quantum computing are not encouraging in this respect       ','2011-04-22 14:48:28','2011-04-22 14:48:28'),(1047,96,48,'Hello Junius,\r\n\r\nI would like to reproduce your excellent write up on Gamma Synchrony at my blog.  may I have your permission please?\r\n\r\nLink to my Blog : http://beyond-advaita.blogspot.com/\r\n\r\nI will appreciate a line or two about you as an intro.\r\n\r\nThanks and regards,\r\nramesam','2011-04-25 12:24:58','2011-04-25 12:24:58'),(1050,96,48,'\r\nYes Junius,\r\n\r\nThis is great stuff.  Thanks for the contribution!\r\n\r\nDoes anyone have any thoughts about integrating this information into the â€œRepresentational Qualia Theoryâ€ statement?  Should we just add all of it at some location, mostly as is?  Or should we try to summarize it, and provide a more info reference link to the rest of it at some other location on the web (Perhaps desidimonaâ€™s blog?)\r\n\r\nJunius, what are your thoughts?\r\n\r\nDoes anyone know the authors of the â€˜New Horizones in the Neuroscience of Consciousnessâ€™ or any other related works, or would anyone be interested in trying to contact them to let them know what we are attempting with this and possibly recruit them to be signers of what we have or will end up with?\r\n\r\nThanks All!\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2011-04-25 15:54:13','2011-04-25 15:54:13'),(1053,96,48,'First of all desidimona by all means use any of this material for your blog.\r\n\r\n\'New Horizons\' was edited by Elaine Perry, Daniel Collerton, Fiona LeBeau and Heather Ashton and published by John Benjamins\r\n\r\nLike a lot of science books, it is a collection of chapters by different authors. Apart from the chapter mentioned by Lucia Melloni & Wolf Singer, I also found those by Fiona LeBeau and Anthony Grace interesting. The last section of the book gets into the edgier areas, including a chapter by Dean Radin.\r\n\r\nThey\'re all heavy weight academics at Departments of Neuroscience or Neurophysiology, so I\'m not sure how accessible they are unless you happen to have a personal or professional connection.  ','2011-04-25 16:22:27','2011-04-25 16:22:27'),(1056,96,48,'I can probably do you a summarised version of gamma synchrony if you let me know a target number of words for this. However, this may have to wait to 9 May onwards as I am away most of the time until then.\r\n\r\nJunius','2011-04-26 15:52:15','2011-04-26 15:52:15'),(1059,96,48,'That will be excellent, Sir.\r\n\r\nAs far as my Blog is concerned, there are no restrictions on length, number of words etc.\r\n\r\nI hope to Post your write up on Gamma Synchrony on 20th of May.  Hope this timing  suits you okay.\r\n\r\nAs the target audience is not all neuroscience - literate, some explanation of highly technical part will be  useful.\r\n\r\nregards,\r\nramesam\r\n\r\n','2011-04-26 17:02:12','2011-04-26 17:02:12'),(1062,96,48,'Junius, it seems quite reasonable to see \"long-range\" synchronisation of gamma oscillations as the physical embodiment of mental objects, whether thoughts perceptions or procedures, because the frequency range of the gamma oscillations fits in with the conduction speeds for myelinated and unmyelinated neurons respectively. In Wikipedia I see that conduction velocity in myelinated neurons is anything from 2 metres per second up. For unmyelinated neurons the velocity is shown as from maybe 0.4m/s up to 1.2m/s. The myelinated axons are connecting cortical regions separated by as much as 20cm or more [allowing for curves], whereas the unmyelinated axons are connecting neurons located within one or two millimetres of each other. \r\n\r\nThe best theory of brain functioning seems to be that the different features of objects of interest are represented by activity in different and characteristic locations around the cortex, \"topographically\" as it were. The massively parallel and redundant connection paths across the brain allow for simultaneous activation of several distinct, and self-assertively robust neuron combinations [AKA cell assemblies]. In each case resonance and mutual reciprocal stimulation will be what holds the particular cell assemblies together as effective candidates for control of muscle movements at any particular moment. \r\n\r\nIn this view, consciousness is what happens when candidate cell assemblies get linked in with the cell assemblies that are currently representing the person/body\'s \"self\". The self as such is a construct which fulfills the need for the guidance system to have a \"you are here and facing that way\" indicator and to have a focus of personal identity features which make up one\'s story of self at the moment. Part of our self identity story involves maintaining a belief in continuity of person. I have lately come to suspect that our ability to empathise is a necessary part of this. I think this is because we need to be able to both distinguish self from others yet also to identify self with others, ie keep absolutely certain the difference between family or friends on the one hand versus food and other mere objects on the other. \r\nMark Peaty','2011-04-28 18:47:25','2011-04-28 18:47:25'),(1065,96,48,'I think desidimona asked for a couple of lines of my background. You can say that I run a website/blog on consciousness and fundamental physics  www.quantum-mind.co.uk. I have also written a science fiction book \'Persephone Wakes\' under the name Jack Junius with theories of consciousness as its theme, and am working on another fiction book (a sort of Dan Brown of the Cotswolds) with altered states of consciousness and religion as its theme. - Junius \r\n','2011-04-30 12:26:05','2011-04-30 12:26:05'),(1068,96,48,'Thank you Junius.\r\n\r\ni shall give the link to my blog when i post the article.  \r\n\r\nThe tentative title: \"Gamma Synchrony\" by Junius.\r\n\r\nregards,\r\nramesam','2011-04-30 12:57:22','2011-04-30 12:57:22'),(1071,96,48,'\r\nHi Junius,\r\n\r\nYou indicated that you could do a summary of the gamma synchrony write up and were asking how small to make it.  Given the unanimous support for your work, I think everyone would agree that you can determine the size for this better than me or most of us.  I always try to remind myself, that the purpose here is just a survey, and to provide an abstract, or even just a name of what our current working hypothesis are, with references to other more info.  But of course, as you can see with what we have now, I\'ve probably already added way to much stuff there now.\r\n\r\nYou also mentioned not being able to get to this for some time.  That\'s the nice thing about collaborative wikis.  If some capable person gets to it before you, that is OK.  Or whenever you have time that works to.  If I had more time, I\'d have all these people contacted, and so many more... hopefully many of them recruited and participating.  Anything anyone can do to help, when they can, with whatever, benefits everyone.  Small easy steps by everyone is where the power of crowd sourcing and wikis comes from.\r\n\r\nI think I\'m getting close to the rewrite changes I\'d like to propose soon.  The opening section is where most of my proposed changes will be so I\'m going to post that in a follow up post to this thread, to see if there is any objections or other possible feedback.\r\n\r\nIf you have time to have me send a copy of what I\'m working on, before I officially submit/propose it, perhaps we you can make your changes to this, and we can submit our changes together, reducing the amount of review everyone has to do for multiple submits.\r\n\r\nBut if not, then feel free to just submit a modified statement, with your additions integrated in, any time you\'d like.  I don\'t expect anyone in our camp to object to any changes you would propose.\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2011-05-01 20:27:12','2011-05-01 20:27:12'),(1074,96,48,'Theoretical Experts,\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nHere is the opening part of the latest version of the rewrite I\'ve been working on.  It has changed significantly from the version I sent out to some of you on request.  Other than this rewrite of the opening 3 paragraphs, most of the rest hasn\'t changed much - some has been removed, or consolidated and moved into this opening part.  As always, I welcome any thoughts, pro, con, or whatever.  I\'d especially like to know what you think of giving a name to this \'\'\'\"qualia interpretation principle\"\'\'\'.  I think this is an important way of thinking about the difference between computer knowledge and conscious knowledge.  There are many \"theories of consciousness\" out there that completely fail to address this important issue, and to me, thereby, can\'t be valid.\r\n\r\n--------------------------------------------\r\n\r\n= Representational Qualia Theory =\r\n\r\nhttp://canonizer.com/files/epist2.gif\r\n\r\nOur working hypothesis is that a phenomenal red property or quale is not a property of something like a red strawberry reflecting 650nm light, or the initial cause of a perception process.  It is, instead, a property of the final result of a perception process.  The world finally fully realizing this will be far more significant than when they switched from a geocentric solar system working hypothesis and such could lead to what could turn out to be the most significant scientific revolution / achievement of all time.  The early significant lead this camp has ahead of all others is exciting evidence that, at least for some experts and hobbyists, we might have already made a great bit of progress in this direction.\r\n\r\nInformation theory mandates that information or knowledge must be represented by something.  If you know something, there must be something that is that knowledge.  If you know lots of phenomenal stuff like the color of surfaces of some strawberries, together with the color of some leaves, and cognitive information like how sweet the most red ones are, there must be something that is all this information and it must be somehow bound together in the same world of awareness so we can distinguish between red and green, so that we might interpret them appropriately enabling us to choose the red ones.\r\n\r\nAll information that comes to us through our cause and effect based senses is done so in the abstract based on a \'\'\'\"Quale Interpretation Principle\"\'\'\'.  This principle is why qualia are ineffable.  This type of abstracted information we get from interpreting our senses has two important related properties:\r\n\r\n# What this abstract information is represented by, by design, doesn\'t matter, as long as it is interpreted properly.\r\n# Anything that represents this abstract information must be properly interpreted to get the abstract information represented by it.\r\n\r\nThis abstractness extends beyond our senses into any detection instruments, and includes all our current computational devices.  What represents red in a computer, by design doesn\'t matter.  The only important thing is that whatever is doing the representation have possible differentiable states, and that such differences be interpreted properly.\r\n\r\nWith consciousness, on the other hand, information is represented and distinguished in a fundamentally different way.  The red and green phenomenal properties of our knowledge of a strawberry patch, how they are bound together, and the fact that we know what they are phenomenally like and how they are different, is what allows us to be able to differentiate them and interpret each of them appropriately.  Unlike all abstracted information coming to us through our senses, what this information is represented with, what they are phenomenally like, that we are aware of the difference is all important and what enables us to choose the red ones.\r\n\r\nWe are interpreting the surface of the strawberry, the light, and all the other intermediate representations as something very different than what the original fundamentally is.  There is no phenomenal color, taste, warmth, sound, or pain, beyond our senses, that we know of.  There is only the abstracted information about their causal behavior of reflected electromagnetic radiation of a certain wavelength, chemical content, kinetic energy motion of molecules, acoustical vibrations, bodily damage or other cause and effect behavioral properties which our brain interprets and represents as something very fundamentally different.  The above image by Steven Lehar is purposefully depicted with color only inside the head.  The black and white lines of the outside world represent this type of abstracted information, for which we only know abstracted information about.\r\n\r\nAll we can currently know of the external world is this kind of abstracted information about it.  Because of this must be interpreted properly requirement, such perception cannot tell us what something is phenomenally like, beyond our ability to interpret it properly.  This \'\'\'\"Quale Interpretation Principle\"\'\'\' is the reason for the veil of phenomenal perception and is why phenomenal properties are ineffable or blind to interpreted cause and effect based observation.\r\n\r\nDiscovering and tracking ever more detailed and comprehensive abstracted information about the neural  correlates that are our knowledge, alone, will never reveal to us what they are subjectively experienced as.  Whatever neural correlate is that is responsible for a point of subjective red on the surface of the strawberry we are aware of, would be much more likely to reflect grey light (if it is \'grey matter\'?) than 650nm light.  So obviously interpreting it as grey, would not be the correct interpretation of a neural correlate that we experienced as a point of red.  Scientists may already have far more abstract information about neural correlates, than required to discover a relationship between the abstracted information they are learning, and what they are subjectively like to experience.  And as long as they continue to only look for ever more detailed abstracted information about such, and never ask what is it like to experience such, they could go on forever missing what is all important for consciousness, and how to properly interpret such.\r\n\r\nAll we know of the surface of the strawberry, is how our cause and effect based senses are phenomenally representing it.  If something in our brain is ineffably like something, there also exists the possibility that the surface of the strawberry, and much else in nature, has ineffable phenomenal properties we are blind to, along with their causal or behavior properties we only now just represent as something very different than what the original is truly like.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-05-01 22:53:24','2011-05-01 22:53:24'),(1075,1,65,'\r\nHi Eric,\r\n\r\nWelcome to the milestones survey.  It\'s great to have some more camps start to show up, so thanks for this great contribution, and it is a great step forward.\r\n\r\nI see some possibility of achieving some consensus between each of our camps.  Worst case, I would like to move our camp into a supporting sub camp of your camp, since I agree with most everything you say.\r\n\r\nBut, first, there may also be some significant disagreements, so I\'d like to clear up and explicitly clarify some of that first.\r\n\r\nFirst off, your entire statement is all only about behavior and abstracted simulation of the human neocortex.  Have you nothing to say about any of this beyond mere behavior?  Anything at all about what these neural correlates are phenomenally like to experience?\r\n\r\nI\'m in the camp that believes everyone being so completely ignoring anything but behavior is already significantly holding the science of the brain, and AGI significantly back.  Perhaps you are a qualophobe that thinks quale either don\'t exist or aren\'t  important?  Or would you agree that we could continue to \"simulate\" the behavior of ever more of the abstracted behavior of neurons, and completely miss this as a qualophile?\r\n\r\nI\'d love to get more of your thoughts on any of this, to see if we can achieve a consensus with and combining with your camp, anything from my camp?\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2011-05-07 03:47:11','2011-05-07 03:47:11'),(1076,1,65,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\nI may have been unclear about about specific ideas in my camp statement.  I think that the internal simulation or model that is built on qualia is fundamental.  There must be some means of internal modelling, abstraction and simulation for a thinking entity to make predictions, and anticipate solutions to problems which would lead us to infer that such an entity is intelligent.  But one must also consider that an entity which percieves and has the capacity for abstaction but exhibits no response can not be determined to have intelligence from external observation - akin to locked in syndrome.  Therefore I must conceed that modelling behavior is a necessity for building useful AI, such that we can recognize an entity\'s external responsiveness to internal cognition and thus interact with it in a meaningful way.  However the internal model (qualia) can perhaps be represented in many different ways, not strictly as we would see it or hear it or percieve it.  How does a cephalopod think?  How does it model the world?  How does it assume that there may be somthing interesting inside a mason jar and figure out how to open it?  Where is the line between feedback loops which generate impulses and the kind of behavior that is generated by more sophisticated pattern recognition through abstraction which we recognize as awareness?\r\n\r\nOur current technology has exceptional power for modeling the world in arbitrary ways and we can also model behavior, but we need lean and mean pattern recognition to reach the goal of AGI.  My suspicion is that Wolfram\'s research may lead to a processing architecture that can provide a kind of universal pattern recognition and fill in those arbitrary levels of abstraction.','2011-05-07 13:26:06','2011-05-07 13:26:06'),(1077,1,65,'Dystopian said:\r\n\r\n    \"I think that the internal simulation or model\r\n    that is built on qualia is fundamental.\"\r\n\r\nYay!  I see so many AI people think that internal models and knowledge aren\'t important because they are naive realists, and or they think we don\'t have qualia...  In my opinion this is significantly holding such people back in their work.  Would you agree with this?\r\n\r\nSimilarly, I think people ignoring what qualia are, how we use such phenomenal differences to distinguish the difference between a green leaf and a red strawberry and how this is all unified together, along with our cognitive knowledge of such, like our memory of how sweet the red ones are... is unified into one space of conscious knowledge is critically important and that ignoring such is also holding neural researching and AI people back.  Sure, they can make ever more progress at learning ever more abstracted information about the behavior of what is there, abstractly simulating such and so on, but if you also were asking what is that neural stuff like to experience, and how are we aware of all of it at the same time, would you agree that such could give us a significant leg up in any AGI, and simulation of such efforts?\r\n\r\nIf so, can we find what we do agree on and merge it into a unanimous super camp?\r\n\r\nAlso, would you be interesting in helping us with [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 Representational Real Theory] or perhaps one of it\'s yet to be falsified sub camps?  I\'d love to know which type of representational realists you are.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-05-08 20:50:37','2011-05-08 20:50:37'),(1080,96,48,'Hi Junius,\r\n\r\nI now have a new version of the statement I feel ready to submit, unless someone else is willing to review it and help provide more feedback on it.\r\n\r\nI\'ve made several improvements to the opening section posted in post # 14 above, including completely deleting the second to the last paragraph, and adding this shorter bottom line one at the end of that section that I\'d love to find out what others think:\r\n\r\n--------------------------------------------\r\n\r\n\"The bottom line is, this theory predicts that if neural researchers are at all going to make any progress discovering consciousness, they must have an understand of \'\'\'what\'\'\' to look for - qualia, \'\'\'where\'\'\' to look for it - a property of a neural correlate, and finally \'\'\'how\'\'\' to look for it - via effing the ineffable.  The longer nuts and bolts neural researchers ignore this, and only focus on abstracted and incorrectly interpreted behavior of neurons, the longer they will continue to fail to achieve what will arguably become the greatest scientific discovery of all time - something some of us think we already have the capability to do and should have done a long time ago.  All that is required is the correct expert consensus theory of what, where, and how to look for it.\"\r\n\r\n--------------------------------------------\r\n\r\nI also have organized things better and split them into titled sub sections.  So, Junious, it might work out to just add what you\'ve proposed above in yet one more titled sub section.  Are you to a place where you\'d be willing to take what I have, add your section, and then you do this all as a single submission, to avoid everyone having to review two proposed changes close together?  If not, I\'ll just formally make my proposal sometime in the next few days.\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2011-05-09 04:24:32','2011-05-09 04:24:32'),(1083,96,48,'I agree that indefinite pursuit of correlates of consciousness will not by itself yield a theory of consciousness, as correlation is not the same as identity. One of the benefits, if the gamma synchrony was seen to resolve the binding or unity of consciousness problem, would be to allow efforts to be concentrated on qualia or subjectivity which looks like the real hard problem. One of the difficulties in consciousness studies has been a tendency to get bogged down in areas that are not the essential problem.\r\n\r\nAnyway, I am now sending a shortened version of the bit on the gamma synchrony. You are welcome to integrate either version or some editing of either or both of them into your rewrite.\r\n\r\nThe Gamma Synchrony\r\n\r\nStudies show that conscious perceptions produce different types of brain activity from unconscious percepts. In particular, consciousness is demonstrated to produce long-range synchronisation of gamma oscillations in spatially separated neuronal assemblies. The 30-80 Hz gamma oscillation of neuronal spiking can become synchronised across large areas of the brain binding together spatially separated neuronal assemblies. This connectivity is suggested to meet the requirements for binding together the unity of consciousness.\r\n\r\nNeurons are known to be synchronised into coherent assemblies, and these neuronal assemblies are suggested to signal the presence of particular features to other neuronal assemblies. This is proposed to give rise to a a distributed representation of the environment.\r\n\r\nSynchronisation also allows better control of interaction between neurons. Excitatory inputs are effective at a particular point of the oscillation cycle, and are ignored at other times. Groups of neurons that are not oscillating in synchrony are ignored. This can function both within and between neuronal assemblies.\r\n\r\nStudies suggest that local gamma processing is unconscious, but that longer range reciprocal signaling between spatially separate neuronal assemblies is a correlate of consciousness. Studies involving masking of stimuli have allowed the same stimuli to be either unconscious or conscious. In one study words could be perceived unconsciously in some trials but consciously in others. Local gamma synchronisation was similar in both cases, but with consciously perceived stimuli there was a long-range synchrony between the occipital, parietal and frontal cortices. The conscious stimuli also produced activity indicating a transfer of information to the working memory, and frontal cortex theta activity may indicate material being held in working memory.\r\n\r\nThe gamma synchrony is just a correlate and does not explain how consciousness arises, however it does seem plausible that the physical basis of consciousness is in some way related to this process.     \r\n\r\n','2011-05-10 17:56:07','2011-05-10 17:56:07'),(1086,96,48,'I find Junius\' statement on gamma synchrony totally acceptable, but it doesn\'t take us very far. We have to identify the critical network/s that generate consciousness and the major node/s involved. Then the precise mechanism of temporal encoding must be determined [representation has to be temporal, doesn\'t it?]. \r\nOnce this has been achieved we are on our way to a sound representational qualia theory.\r\nOne note of caution - let us not become obsessed with cortex in isolation and ignore the centres essential for affect. Every thought has its emotional component.\r\n\r\nDavid Friend ','2011-05-10 20:07:02','2011-05-10 20:07:02'),(1087,116,44,'The philosopher Keith Frankish, a star in the great new [http://www.philostv.com/richard-brown-and-keith-frankish philosophy TV episode] responded to my query about what the dispositional properties are that make us only think we have qualia, even though he argues we don\'t.  (See the comments section below the video.)\r\n\r\nI\'d like to point out why everyone in this \"Representational Qualia Theory\" camp is currently unable to accept these arguments, and want to do this here, so if anyone disagrees with my claim about everyone in this camp, and why we currently reject his arguments, or if you have a better way of saying any of this, you can let us know either here or there.\r\n\r\nKeith, when you say \"I can\'t shake this intuition that this experience has a certain intrinsic, ineffable, subjective feel\", we in this camp all have the working hypothesis that this \'subjective feel\' is knowledge, and that if we have such knowledge, there must be something that is this knowledge and that it is this that has this subjective feel.  Whether this knowledge is mistaken or not, has nothing to do with whatever nature this subjective feel has.  Currently, for us, you are just waving your hand, and making impossible claims that we have some mistaken knowledge that doesn\'t really exist.  For us, you must do more than just make a claim that we can know something, without having something that is the mistaken seeming, with a mysterious hand wave.  You must provide a real mechanical or testable process of what this \'subjective feel\' is, and how it comes into being, without it being anything.  For example, might these dispositional properties be modified or enhance or connected in some way (perhaps like the corpus callosum) to enable us to think or make judgments about my red is like your green (or my green after a red green inverter is spliced into the perception process), in some way?\r\n\r\nRepresentational Qualia theory is making real, mechanical predictions that are very falsifiable - that there is something in our brain that reliably and detectably has these phenomenal properties, and that this is our knowledge.  Can you provide a similar concise description that makes the same kind of real testable and working descriptions about what you are saying about with this seeming knowledge that you think is just mistaken?  Such would certainly go a long way towards us being able to accept this seeming theory as something more for us than something that is something that is just mistaken and falsified.\r\n\r\n','2011-05-22 13:57:28','2011-05-22 13:57:28'),(1088,116,44,'The reply to the claim that we don\'t actually experience the qualia that we *think* we experience, is very simple.\r\n\r\nEpistemologically speaking, experience is our first and most primal source of knowledge, even if that experience is a dream or hallucination, we can be absolutely certain that we are having that dream. In fact, the existence and nature of our experience is the ONLY thing of which we can be ABSOLUTELY CERTAIN to be true. The properties of our experience, that it is spatially structured, the color qualia, pleasure and pain, are exactly AS THEY ARE EXPERIENCED TO BE and NO DIFFERENT.\r\n\r\nTo claim that our experience is ANY DIFFERENT than we experience it to be is a CONTRADICTION IN TERMS.\r\n\r\nBut you are wasting your breath arguing against someone who is so delusional as to deny the nature and existence of his own experience! He has got his epistemology all backwards - he has a theory of how perception works, and he is ready to deny the nature of his experience as he experiences it to make it fit with his cherished theory.\r\n\r\n','2011-05-22 16:40:49','2011-05-22 16:40:49'),(1089,116,44,'Thanks Steve, this is a great way to put it.\r\n\r\nBut the point here, isn\'t just repetitive arguing, as it seems to be in the peer reviewed literature, on Philsophy TV, and everywhere else, which I agree is a complete waste.  The point here is to collaboratively developed concise descriptions of all these diverse ways of thinking about things, get a quantitative measure of which ones are waning, which ones are waxing, and why, so the true experts can find out, quantitatively, what works and what doesn\'t.\r\n\r\nRepresentational Qualia Theory makes real predictions about what the nuts and bolts researchers need to do, to start effing the ineffable, and discover the neural correlates that have them.  Of course it is our prediction, that this is precisely what the researchers will find, and that doing so, will falsify competing theories, which we\'ll know definitively has been falsified, when all the most respected experts in those camps all do, finally start abandoning them, and join what science demonstrates to us all as true.  Hopefully, Keith can describe, concisely, just what it is he believes, and why, and what he expects the scientists to demonstrate, that will prove him right, and make us convert to his camp, if such is really possible, or if there is something in what he is saying that we are still failing to fully grasp?\r\n','2011-05-23 02:53:58','2011-05-23 02:53:58'),(1090,116,44,'I can\'t add anything to Slehar\'s wording.\r\n\r\nI think the problem is really one of false premises, or perhaps imprisonment in the 19th century. The philosopher takes as a premise that everything has to conform to 19th century Newtonian physics plus rather early stage neuroscience, and no argument is to convoluted if it supports this premise.\r\n\r\nPhilosophical and other mainstream consciousness literature is often surprisingly science-lite. What is exasperating is that important findings in neuroscience, biology and even physics are simply ignored in the closed bubble of mainstream consciousness studies.\r\n\r\nJunius','2011-05-23 15:26:38','2011-05-23 15:26:38'),(1091,1,20,'Hi Xodorap\r\n\r\nThanks for contributing to this topic.\r\n\r\nWhat I would like to see happen with topics like this, is to become a communication system that enables humanity to better prioritize what the world needs to do to become better, or save us from a catastrophe.\r\n\r\nYouâ€™ve added germs, ocean acidity, climate, and bureaucracy, all in one camp.\r\n\r\nIt seems like to me, it would be better if you could split each of these into 4 different camps, and then join each camp in your own priority?  This would also allow others to rank them relatively.  For example, say someone thinks only bureaucracy is important, how would they contribute and support your belief or camp that this item was important?\r\n\r\nAlso, there seems to be another dimension to this.  There is the problem itself, and how critical it is, then there are sure to be many diverse POVs about diverse ways to help solve each of these.  For example, germs, ocean acidity, and climate are real problems, but bureaucracy, or at least a better way to co-operate and solve such problems, seems to be more of a method than an actual problem, in and of itself?\r\n\r\nThe Rigorously measure what the experts believe, seems to be the same, as a bureaucracy camp would be, or at least a specific suggested solution to the bureaucracy problem?  Could you imagine some way these two camps could be combined in a consensus way, as their motivation, at least, seams similar?\r\n\r\nYou point out bureaucracy as being a problemâ€¦ do you have any thoughts on what might be a possible good solution, or at least a method that might improve things?  What do you think we need to do to to solve any bureaucracy problem?\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2011-06-27 23:18:08','2011-06-27 23:18:08'),(1092,1,20,'Hi xodorap,\r\n\r\nThis statement is looking ever better.\r\n\r\nOn question I have is what is \"triple bottom line accounting\"?  Perhaps you could provide a reference to more info or something?\r\n\r\n\r\nAlso, if I wanted to move towards splitting this single camp up, into multiple camps, one for each of the items you mention in it?  Would you agree that this is a good move or would you have a problem with this?\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-07-03 03:33:37','2011-07-03 03:33:37'),(1093,1,98,'Hi all\r\n\r\nHave just revisited this and cannot understand how athesim is compatible with belief in god as mother nature because it is not compatible with belief in any god or gods whatsoever by definition.\r\n\r\nThe camp title and statement seem to me clearly at odds with the parent camp.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard\r\n\r\n','2011-07-06 13:58:44','2011-07-06 13:58:44'),(1094,1,98,'Hi richwil,\r\n\r\nThanks for checking into this.  There really is good reasons for all this.  I have noticed that in general there are two very different types of atheists, and having two parallel atheist POV branches is an attempt to capture these differences.  In addition to some atheists accepting mother nature as a type of non sentient God, and some donâ€™t, the differences seem to also parallel the ones surveyed for in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/12 Does Evolution Want Something] topic.  Steven J Gould and many others argue that evolution has no purpose, while many others argue that evolution does have goals, purposes, and wants in a Godly type way.  Might I ask you what your feelings are in that topic?\r\n\r\nI see youâ€™ve moved from the atheist camp that supports Mother Nature, as a type of non sentient God, to the parallel atheist camp that feels uncomfortable with that.  So hopefully, after reading the above discussion and such this split makes sense?  And it looks like you are now in the camp the more accurately represents the type of atheist you are.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2011-07-06 15:15:02','2011-07-06 15:15:02'),(1095,1,58,'Hi Luc Delannoy,\r\n\r\nI very much appreciate you\'re participation in the consciousness survey project, and for supporting [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/85/10 this camp] that represents Edmond Wright\'s \"Narrative, Perception, Language, and Faith\" along with myself as a second supporter of this camp, improving it with you...\r\n\r\nI\'m also going to forward a copy of this open letter to Edmond Write, and Stephen Robbins, who has personally contacted me encouraging the creation of a new camp, with references to Edmond\'s \"The case for qualia\" and some other works for references.\r\n\r\nEdmond has done quite a bit to help me and my attempts to understand some of his theories.  I went to great effort to get a copy of Narrative, Perception, Language through inter library loan and read it, have also spent time on these other references and discussing these issues with you.  I have spent much more time on this camp than any other camp to date.\r\n\r\nHowever, despite my efforts, I still fail to fully understand why so many people still seem to consider Edmond a \"representationalist\", while he himself has expressed to me that this is a miss classification, or that he has abandoned representationalism?  I\'ve attempted to find answers to these questions: if not representationalism, then what?  Where is redness, and what is it a property of, if not a property of a representation of, or knowledge of something reflecting 650 nm light?  But I have failed to find, or gain any kind of good understanding of an answer to this and many other questions about all this.  Surely this is mostly due to my apparently different current working hypothesis of consciousness.  Like most people, I usually have a very difficult time understanding theories different from the way I think about consciousness.  Even if I did achieve a good understanding, me attempting to create a camp alone would surely be a poor one, and misrepresent many things?\r\n\r\nThat I know of, the 3 three of you clearly support these ideas and this amount of consensus tells me there is something very important about this way of thinking about consciousness.  We would all desperately love to get a camp started containing a concise description of just what all of you believe, especially what you agree on.  Stephen mentioned that the: \"representational qualia theory being supported heavily is based upon some fundamental (mis)assumptions about space and time that Bergson exposed 100 years ago.\"  It would be extremely valuable to everyone to have a concise description of what these are, especially if all of you agree with them.  If not, how do you differ in your beliefs, and so on?\r\n\r\nStephen mentioned that he doesn\'t yet understand how canonizer.com works, and that is fine, there are ways people can easily contribute with almost no effort.  All anyone needs to do is submit a concise statement describing their current working hypothesis to me, with supporting arguments, a problems of competing theories, and so on.  The important thing about canonizer.com is it doesn\'t need to be complete in any way, just something off the top of your head, quick and dirty, to get things started, so others can run with it and improve it from there.\r\n\r\nVolunteers can take whatever you send to us and get it integrated into the survey data we have to date, all according to all of your approval, of course.  Basically the best way to make things work, is you tell us what to add to the survey, possibly how to restructure things, and so on, if it were entirely up to you.  Then the volunteers can work to make as much of all that possible as we can so it best represents what you believe, along with what everyone else believes, with as much consensus as possible.\r\n\r\nGiven the 3 of you are already proponents of these ideas, and have already each contacted me about these ideas and references, I bet there is a good chance, with only a little easy off the top of your heads wiki help from any of you, so others can take what you start and run with it, this camp could become a consensus contender as a leading theory to compete with \"Representational Qualia Theory\" or some subset of that camp (since we all obviously agree on the importance of qualia).\r\n\r\nI hope at least some of you will give us a few easy minutes with getting this started.  It only takes a little, perhaps even just a quick name to get the camp started, so we can get this obviously very well supported and important way of thinking about consciousness concisely and quantitatively represented, so we can see just how many other people also agree with any of this and so on, and so the rest of the world can better know what this way is, in comparison to the currently existing theories.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2011-07-08 03:36:26','2011-07-08 03:36:26'),(1096,1,98,'1) What is a \"non-sentient god\"? This is a contradiction in terms!\r\n\r\n2) In what way is \"mother nature\" non-sentient? Surely you\'re referring to the strong Gaia hypothesis (or some version of Paganism?) which claims that the planet is a live entity - a sort of super being?\r\n\r\nI agree that atheism is a broad church (ho ho) but the bottom line is that if you are an atheist then you do not believe in god/gods.\r\n\r\nAtheism is consistent with a belief in the weak/original Gaia hypothesis - that the planet consists in a web of interacting sentient and non-sentient entities that has a dynamic equilibrium characterised by stable periods of homeostasis. It is also consistent with finding nature wonderful. Mother nature seems to me to cross the line. The Mother Nature camp statement includes \"pantheism\" - surely the clue is in the \"theism\" part?\r\n\r\nTo those supporting this camp i would ask if you are sure that you believe \".. if it wasn\'t caring, nurturing, loving and motherly, none of us would be here.\" Surely these qualities can only be ascribed to a sentient being and therefore, if you support this all-things-bright-and-beautiful claim, you believe in god, the nature god, and so are not atheists.\r\n\r\nThere are a couple of divisions that may be worth exploring but neither has to do with mother nature. One arises from comparing agnosticism with atheism: it seem that the set of agnostics overlaps that of atheists. The other comes from Chalmer\'s zombies: some of us believe in them, some of us don\'t....','2011-07-11 13:34:17','2011-07-11 13:34:17'),(1097,1,98,'Hi Rich,\r\n\r\nOne problem people have is due to in the past we only had very primitive gross methods for surveying and tracking what others believed.  Just the way everyone talks about things also makes it very difficult - as we lack clear terminology to easily distinguish to this detail.  Most people put others in very large and gross buckets, when in fact there is quite a bit of diversity within those buckets.  One of the goals of canonizer.com, is to gain much more detail in what everyone believes.\r\n\r\nI completely agree with everything you are saying, so evidently the wording in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/2/20 Mother Nature camp statement] simply isnâ€™t clear enough, since you are asking these questions and thinking it believes in more than we do.\r\n\r\nFor me, the key term was only godly attributes â€œthat we can all agree that we know.â€  In other words, Mother Nature is â€˜sentientâ€™ in that it includes humanity and very intelligent animals.  Everyone agrees with something like that.  But, if you go beyond that, and say that there is some consciousness or sentience beyond that, many people would doubt such exists.  Surely, there are Gia believes that believe the earth is more sentient, than the sum total of all its animals.  If so, such a belief must be described in a sub camp, as I, and many people, would doubt that such exists.  I hoped the can\'t statement made this clear, but maybe not?\r\n\r\nI believe mother nature has some very powerful attributes, such as the ability to â€˜evolveâ€™ life, which is very god like.  I believe this God will some do be all powerful, and get everyone and everything all that it truly wants.  I just donâ€™t believe that mother nature has any more power to do this, than humanity (natures most advanced part) has yet achieved.\r\n\r\nAnd most of all, I believe there is not some kind if intelligence that is conscious of us in a sentient way, and is also hiding from us.\r\n\r\nHopefully that helps? Perhaps you can suggest some ways for us to improve the wording in our statement, so it is more obvious to everyone what it is talking about?\r\n\r\nIâ€™d love to hear what others think!\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2011-07-11 23:28:50','2011-07-11 23:28:50'),(1100,96,48,'Hi dahlstedt,\r\n\r\nThanks for your great contribution to the survey, here at canonizer.com with this newest [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/46 Consciousness as underlying force of physics] camp, and welcome as the newest supporting member of the Approachable via Science supper camp.\r\n\r\nAlso, thanks for figuring everything out so fast the way you have.  Even after much coaching, many people still don\'t seem to be able to get it and able to do things as rapidly as you already are.\r\n\r\nA couple of questions:\r\n\r\nTo me, this sounds identical to panpsychism or [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/34 panexperientialism] as far as everything being conscious goes.  Is it the same?  The original creator of that camp isn\'t very active, and I bet he would agree with all this and would be happy to have your help (are you listening, Ryan?, am I correct in this information?)  if you moved your statement into that camp, and switched to that camp, abandoning this one and building more consensus?  That would get you your first supporter besides you already, moving your camp way up in the priority order, and I know there are many other pansychists out there that would hopefully join you, and agree with at least most of what you are saying here?\r\n\r\nAnother question - many would consider an AI computer to be not conscious, or at best a \'zombie\' for which there was nothing it was like to be it or know what it knows.  Do you believe an AI robot, or maybe even my digital camera, to be conscious, similar to the way I am, when I look at or take a picture of a sunset?\r\n\r\nAlso, you mentioned: The very first thing to do is to define the term â€˜consciousnessâ€™, and then pointed out some things consciousness is not, but I could never get exactly what you define consciousness to be?  Did I just miss it, or can you provide a short and concise description of what it is?\r\n\r\nThe current agreement statement defines consciousness, or at least the most important current topic of this survey to be about what consciousness is like, as in what is stuff like redness and how does this relate to the underlying correlates, and so on.  Perhaps you would take issue with this definition, and would push to get this agreement statement changed, so we can all agree with what is most important about consciousness, and what we should be surveying for here?\r\n\r\nAlong those lines of the so far to date, subject of this survey topic, from within your theory, what is \'redness\'?  Is it a property of the surface of a strawberry, or something reflecting something like 650 nm light?  Or is it a property of something in our brain, as predicted by the currently leading consensus [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 Representational Qualia Theory]?  How is redness, greenness, and all if it unified together so we can be aware of it all in all of its ineffable phenomenal diversity, all at the same time?  And, finally, will we ever be able to \'eff\' such ineffable stuff, to know what other minds are like, if they are different, to resolve the philosophical problem of other minds, and so on?  To me, these are the important questions we are and should be surveying for regarding consciousness.  I\'d love to know if you agree?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-07-14 02:48:13','2011-07-14 02:48:13'),(1103,96,48,'http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iCR2PFrLkwA\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n0IIVF7PGBs&feature=related\r\n\r\nplz check out the two links above..\r\n\r\ni think this android qualifies as a \'zombie\' and so..\r\n\r\nbrent, plz try to get the guy involved in our discussion?\r\n\r\nit\'s not really a step toward machine awareness but..\r\n\r\nis a step toward robots/androids being intelligent / autonomous / AIs\r\n\r\nsam','2011-07-14 03:39:32','2011-07-14 03:39:32'),(1106,96,48,'Thanks guys,\r\nI agree that this would fall under a general panexperientialism category, and have moved the camp.  I hope through deeper research into panexperientialism I can find some answers or keys to some ambiguity in my theory.\r\nI\'ll continue to review your feedback and will post my thoughts.\r\nMike','2011-07-14 16:47:56','2011-07-14 16:47:56'),(1109,96,48,'\r\nHi Everyone,\r\n\r\nI\'d like to thank Junius, who, in addition to making the most significant new information additions, has done a great job managing the master copy of the new version of Representational Qualia Theory statement, and getting all the feedback and input by everyone integrated, and sending current draft versions of the master out to all the reviewers and so on.\r\n\r\nThings seem to finally have settled down, and I feel we are ready to submit, so unless we hear from anyone else soon, we\'ll go ahead and submit this latest version.  Of course, camp supporters will receive a notification when it is submitted, indicating the start of the one week review process before it goes live.\r\n\r\nI\'m definitely looking forward to that.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-07-16 22:08:41','2011-07-16 22:08:41'),(1112,96,48,'= Representational Qualia Theory =\r\nhttp://canonizer.com/files/epist2.gif\r\n\r\nJuly 8 2011  -  latest alterations to master copy: 08/07/2011\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOur working hypothesis is that redness is not a property of something like a red strawberry reflecting 650nm light, or the initial cause of a perception process.  It is, instead, a property of the final result of a perception process.  The world finally fully realizing this will be far more significant than when they switched from the working hypothesis of a geocentric solar system. This could lead to the most significant scientific revolution of all time.  The early significant lead this collaboratively developed camp has ahead of all others is exciting evidence that, at least for some experts and hobbyists, we might have already made considerable progress in this direction.\r\n\r\nInformation theory mandates that information or knowledge must be represented by something.  If you know something, there must be something that is that knowledge.  If you know lots of phenomenal stuff like the redness of some strawberries, together with the greenness of some leaves, and cognitive information about how sweet the reddest ones are, there must be something that is all this information, and it must be somehow bound together in the same world of awareness that we experience.\r\n\r\nAll information that comes to us through our cause and effect based senses does so in the abstract. This type of abstract information suffers from a \'\'\'\"Quale Interpretation Problem\"\'\'\'.  This problem is why redness is ineffable.  The cause and effect way this type of abstracted information comes to us by properly interpreting our senses has three important related (dis) functionalities:\r\n\r\n# What this abstract information is represented by doesn\'t matter, as long as it is interpreted properly.\r\n# Anything that represents this abstract information must be properly interpreted to get the abstract information represented by it.\r\n# External abstractly represented information has no relationship to any fundamental properties the media doing the representation may or may not have.\r\n\r\nThis type of problematic abstractness extends beyond our senses into any detection instruments, and includes all our current computational and simulation devices.  If you are going to represent information, you must have some media which can assume distinguishable states. Abstracted information being communicated someplace is, by nature of its design, only concerned with detectible and distinguishable causal local properties of the media. Regardless of what the properties of this media are, or may be like, the only relevant part is your interpreting these behaviours properly to get the abstract information being represented. External abstract information has nothing to do with what any of the intermediate representations might be fundamentally like, either phenomenally or behaviourally. With the design of whatever represents red in a computer (say red is 1 and green is 0), the only important thing is that whatever is doing the representation should have possible differentiable states, and that such differences be interpreted properly so the machines abstract algorithms can pick the items represented by ones, while avoiding the zeros. The process of interpreting abstracted representations is a local process isolated from the information and abstract algorithms being processed on them.\r\nWhile with consciousness, what redness and greenness are like and how they are different in phenomenally motivating ways is a critical part of our conscious knowledge and is what enables us to consciously distinguish between different things so that we can choose the red over the green. These properties must have some way of being bound together and integrated with our cognitive reasoning ideas about them, memory of such, and so on.\r\nIf we used traditional cause and effect observation that suffers from the â€œquale interpretation problemâ€, in order to examine the surface of the brain, or even to examine individual neurons and groups of neurons, and by this means we managed to observe the physical correlate for redness, we might ourselves only observe grey light reflected from these surfaces. However, it would be incorrect to interpret the subjective experience as greyness rather than redness.\r\nIf we are going to make any progress towards explaining consciousness, we must do more than just this. We must first have a clear understanding that there is more than just causal properties we should be looking for and understand this â€˜â€™â€™quale interpretation problemâ€™â€™â€™. We must understand just â€˜â€™â€™whatâ€™â€™â€™ to look for â€“ qualia, â€˜â€™â€™whereâ€™â€™â€™ to look for it â€“ a property of a neural correlate and finally â€˜â€™â€™howâ€™â€™â€™ to look for it â€“ via effing the ineffable or some type of repeatable and sharable binding or grounding process. The longer nuts and bolts neural researchers only do the former, and only focus on abstracted and incorrectly interpreted causal properties of neurons, the longer they will continue to have success regarding causal behaviour, but fail to achieve what could arguably be the greatest scientific discovery of all time, in uncovering the relationship of the phenomenal properties to the neural correlates.  This discovery includes the mapping and sharing of all possible experiencable phenomenal properties to the behavioural properties we already know so much about, and with it the discovery of what physics is phenomenally like.\r\n\r\n== Reduction of unified complex knowledge to fundamental qualia ==\r\n\r\nThe final result of the perceptual process is the appearance of a visual sensation in the phenomenal visual field (A). This is associated with the acquisition of cognitive knowledge (B) correlating to an external physical object.  Processes A and B are mediated by different brain mechanisms.  In associative agnosia the patient has intact phenomenology but defective epistemology about visual objects. In blindsight the opposite occursâ€”no phenomenology but functioning epistemology. Visual phenomenology (A) and visual epistemology (B) are processed by different brain mechanisms and correspondingly lost by damage to these regions.\r\n\r\nThe word \'red\' can be used in its common sense mode as naming a causal property such as the surface of a strawberry reflecting 650 nm light.  But this usage is ambiguous referring to both the property of an object reflecting 650 nm light and to the correlated but physically quite separate process of the phenomenal experience redness in the brain.  It is possible to add a red/green inverter anywhere in the perception process of a strawberry patch.  Whenever you do this, the still reflecting 650 nm light strawberry is then being represented with phenomenal green, and the leaves are represented with phenomenal red.  Dreams, hallucinated strawberries, and other visual brain states can also be composed of phenomenal, red even when there is no 650 nm light coming to our retinas from the external world.\r\n\r\nhttp://canonizer.com/files/250px-Inverted_qualia_of_colour_strawberry.jpg\r\n\r\nWe think that the redness of the phenomenal red strawberry amongst the green leaves is out beyond our eyes, and that we are directly aware of it.  But this is a misrepresentation - an optimization selected by nature.  In reality, these sensations only arise after the perception process, in the model of a unified conscious world* perceived by us as our everyday reality.\r\n\r\nAt the center of this phenomenal 3D world modelling is our experience of the body-image. This is the model of the physical body that we experience and that is also constructed by a representative mechanism. All somatic sensations, including â€˜phantomâ€™ limbs and phantom limb pain, are located in the body image not in the physical body.\r\n\r\nInside our experience of our body-image is an experience of our \"self\" or \"spirit\" or \"I\". This \"I\" is represented as looking out of our eyes within this body image. But of course, this spirit image, unlike everything else in this phenomenal world, has no referent in reality. However, though it has no referent in reality, this in no way means our spirit does not exist. This phenomenal \"spirit\" is what we really, literally, and spiritually are. During \"out of body experiences\" this image of our spirit* leaves our body-image, but remains in the unified phenomenal world of our conscious awareness.\r\n== Effing the Ineffable ==\r\nSince this theory predicts that redness is not a property of the strawberry, but instead a property of our knowledge of such, we are faced with a communication problem. Currently we canâ€™t know if my redness is anything like yours or anyone elseâ€™s redness. How can we eff that which is ineffable.\r\nIf this theory is borne out, and we achieve any kind of ability to reliably predict just what it is that has redness, weâ€™ll be able to do things like use our traditional instruments to detect the same thing going on in othersâ€™ brains. Any such would provide us tools to ground our abstract communication so that it could become phenomenally meaningful between brains.\r\nAs an example, we could look for whatever it is that we reliably know has person Aâ€™s redness in person Bâ€™s brain. Then we could say to person B that this is person Aâ€™s red. To which person B might say something like, â€˜No, that is my greenâ€™, or maybe, â€˜Yes, that is very similar to my redâ€™, or any of many other possible responses that would enable us to map out and communicate, in a predictably reliable way, at least some of the more obvious differences between our brains.\r\nThis would be a kind of weak effing of the ineffable, which can be achieved via any ability we may achieve to reliably ground what we mean by abstract words in such a personally experiencable way as this. The next section describes a stronger method of effing the ineffable.\r\n\r\n==Gamma Synchrony, the Binding Problem and the Unity of Consciousness:  Strongly Effing the Ineffable ==\r\n\r\nWhen there is a red strawberry represented in the left hemisphere (right field of vision) and a green leaf represented in the right hemisphere (left field of vision), that we are aware of as a unified phenomenal world that bridges the corpus callosum, and unifies vision into a conscious whole where we can compare and contrast their phenomenal differences.\r\nStudies show that conscious percepts correlate to different types of brain activity from unconscious percepts. In particular consciousness is demonstrated to correlate with long-range or global synchronisation of gamma oscillations in widely separated neural assemblies, whereas unconscious signals correlate only to local synchrony. The approx. 30-80 Hz oscillation of neuronal spiking known as the gamma wave can become synchronised across large areas of the brain. It is suggested that the synchronisation of widely distributed neuronal activity meets some of the requirements for explaining how conscious experience arises in the brain.\r\nIt is proposed that the processing of spatially separated neuronal assemblies is bound together by signalling between them. Neurons are known to be synchronised into coherent assemblies, and these assemblies are suggested to signal the presence or absence of particular features in them to other neural assemblies. This process is suggested to give rise to a distributed representation of an object or an environment. Neuronal assemblies are self-organising and form and dissolve rapidly, which could account for the easy shifting of consciousness from one focus to another.\r\nSynchronisation also allows better control of interactions between neurons. Thus the excitatory inputs are seen to be effective if they arrive at the depolarising slope of a neuronal oscillation cycle, but are ineffective at other times. This means that groups of neurons that oscillate in synchrony will be able to signal to one another, and groups that are out of synchrony will be ignored. This mechanism can function within neural assemblies, but also between spatially separated assemblies. The frequency and phase of oscillation can alter so as to influence signalling.\r\n\r\nStudies suggest that local processing is unconscious, whereas large scale activity such as reciprocal signalling between separate neural assemblies is a correlate of consciousness. It is these latter that can establish the global coordination that is correlated to consciousness. \r\nIt is proposed that masking is a good way of studying consciousness, because this allows the same stimuli to either be used in unconscious brain processing, or to be translated into phenomenally experienced brain states, depending on how long the signal is sustained for (probably +/- 30 ms). In one study words could be perceived in some trials but not in others. Local gamma synchronisation was similar in both cases, but with consciously perceived words there was a burst of long-distance gamma synchrony between the occipital, parietal and frontal cortices. [1-3. Melloni, L. et al , 2007, Melloni, L. & Rodriguez, L. 2007, Melloni, L. & Woolf, S,] Also subsequent to this burst, there was activity that could have indicated a transfer of information to working memory, while an increase in frontal cortex theta wave operations may have indicated material being held in working memory.\r\nWhatever the actual relationship between the global gamma synchrony and consciousness, this spatially extended synchrony does appear to provide a plausible explanation of how conscious perceptions are unified. The redness of fruit in one neuronal assembly is synchronised with the greenness of leaves in another assembly, the blueness of the sky in still another, plus the humming of bees and song of birds in the more spatially distant but still synchronised assemblies of the auditory cortex.\r\nGiven that in principle anything physical can be built, in the longest run, this theory predicts it will be possible to discover and use similar mechanisms to produce artificial hemisphere-like structures integrated into our visual fields that can reliably reproduce various phenomenal sensations upon command within one single phenomenal world of awareness with the red, green, and everything else we are already phenomenally aware of.  With such an enhanced mind, we should be able to throw a switch and say something like: \'This is what my red is like\'.  To which the augmented person may say - \"Yes, that is the same as red for me.\"  Or, we might be surprised to find that she represents 650 nm light with something dramatically different.  We refer to such a phenomenal communication ability as [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/102/2 \'effing\'] the ineffable.\r\n\r\nVarious brain interface experiments are increasingly getting close to \'effing\' abilities.  Just one demonstration of such is documented in this [http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/10.09/vision.html wired article].  If we should achieve even a remote and rare but reliable ability to \'eff\' the ineffable as predicted by this theory via any such methods, whether strong or weak, this will prove this theory to be the only sound theory, demonstrating the explanatory power that is hard to detect in functionalism and other mainstream consciousness thinking.\r\n\r\n\r\n==Choice, Preference and the Emotional Brain: The Turing Test Isn\'t Enough ==\r\n\r\nCertain aspects of emotional processing appear to be basis of choice and preference. As something that is not replicated in classical computing, they look to be the best way of distinguishing between a conscious entity and any classical computer or robot. Emotional processing in the brain revolves round a system of \'rewards\' and \'punishers\'. Representations of the external world are produced in the cortex, but these are initially neutral in terms of reward value, until they are projected to other regions, and particularly the orbitofrontal cortex, which samples the entire sensory range. The orbitofrontal is thought to encode the relative value of rewards. It responds more strongly to sensory inputs related to rewards than to neutral stimuli. Thus it responds more to the pressure of velvet than the pressure of wood.\r\nIn particular, studies show that the level of orbitofrontal activity correlates to the subjective pleasantness of sensations rather than the strength of the signal being received [4-6.  Rolls et al 2003c, 2003d, Anderson et al, 2003]. In responding to a face, activity increases in line with the subjectively assessed attractiveness of the face. The orbitofrontal also process shifts in preferences. In a choice of apples and carrots, apples may be preferred, but when bananas are added, the preference can shift to bananas. Thus some aspects of orbitofrontal processing could be argued to make sense only in terms of qualia, rather than any form of non-conscious communication from the external world. The orbitofrontal can be seen as a brain region that creates a common neural currency that weigh up the qualia of differing rewards, or even of rewards that have no common characteristic such as holiday or a healthy bank balance.\r\nThe orbitofrontal projects to the subcortical basal ganglia, a region that lies upstream of actions and behaviour. The orbitofrontal also project to the dorsolateral frontal seen as the executive and long-term planning region of the brain. The basal ganglia integrate the reward assessment of the orbitofrontal, plus inputs from many other parts of the cortex, the amygdala and other parts of the limbic system. The basal ganglia are not thought to take any part in cognitive computation, but instead act as a form of mixer-tap for a wide spread of inputs, and as such select or gate for material processed by the cortex including the orbitofrontal. Dopamine and other neuromodulators play a role both in the processing of the basal ganglia and in the delivery of the qualia of subjective reward in the nucleus accumbens, which is itself part of the basal ganglia. The determining role of qualia in these processes can be seen as contradicting much of mainstream consciousness studies.\r\nIt is absurd to think the only way to determine the nature of anotherâ€™s consciousness is through a \"Turing Test\", rooted as this test is in the more limited mid-twentieth century knowledge of neuroscience and artificial intelligence. To phenomenally know the nature of qualia, the most important question to ask is something like: \"What is Red like?\"  And to know if the conscious entity is telling the truth, you must know something about the representations being used in the remote mind, and have the ability to at least causally observe the neural correlates responsible for these properties, and have something like \'effing\' abilities to ground these abstracted cause and effect representations, in a way that reliably guarantees we are interpreting them correctly.  In other words, you must really know what it is phenomenally like.\r\n\r\nIf you ask an intelligent system that is based on abstract knowledge what its red knowledge is phenomenally like, depending on the level of self-referential information it has access to, it could reply that it is an abstracted knowledge based system in which the information is represented by, doesnâ€™t matter.  It might provide some information about the specifics such as, red is represented with 0xFF0000, revealing depth and resolution information about its knowledge and so on.  Some people might consider such system to be a non-phenomenal â€˜zombieâ€™ that could behave identically to a phenomenal system as far as easily picking red strawberries goes.  Despite such, if it demands something like â€˜red is a property of the surface of a strawberryâ€™, it will simply be revealing its stupidity, or if it is smarter than that, and claiming it is a phenomenal system, perhaps in line with its attempt to pass a Turing test, it will be lying.\r\n\r\nAnd if it is really smart, like some humans are now becoming, it will be able to learn what a phenomenally wonderful and rewarding quality red is, what it is a property of, and that effing is required to communicate and be aware of such.  Like intelligent humans that want to know what otherâ€™s red is like, it will want to know what red is like for us.  It will likely start looking for ways to eff such ineffable knowledge to itself, so it too can experience the same wonderful stuff and finally phenomenally say: â€œoh THAT is what red is like for you!â€.  An example from Sci-Fi includes Commander Data in Star Trek, who is often asking about and seeking after obviously valuable phenomenal things.\r\n\r\n== Problems with other working hypothesis ==\r\n\r\nMany people often compare the idea of qualia to many failed theories of the past such as vitalism, phlogiston, either and so on. The problem with many of these arguments is they entirely miss classify the nature of qualia as [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/81/16 John Gregg] states in his [http://home.comcast.net/~johnrgregg/hardprob.htm essay on the hard problem]:\r\n\r\n   \"The problem is that subjective consciousness (or qualia) is not\r\n   something we drag into the picture to explain something or other\r\n   that we observe, as elan vital was invoked to explain what we\r\n   observe about life, or to use another example reductive\r\n   physicalists like, as the luminiferous ether was invoked to explain\r\n   light waves in the 19th century. Consciousness is the raw data,\r\n   the observed thing that needs explaining. It is the light, not the\r\n   ether.\"\r\n\r\nPeople like Daniel Dennett make similar categorical errors when they claim we don\'t have qualia \"it just seems like we do\" (7. Consciousness Explained P. 375). The very meaning of â€˜to seemâ€™ is to have knowledge that doesn\'t accurately represent its referent. Qualia have to do with the nature of our seeming. Whether or not they are mistaken representations of something else is irrelevant.\r\n\r\nA few people claim to be representationalists, while promoting the use of terribly confusing and ambiguous terms such as our representations are \'transparent\' in a way that allows us to be aware of what we are looking at.  Or they say things like \"every quale is a representation\".  As soon as you say something ambiguous like our representations are \'transparent\' this allows people to quickly jump to the obviously erroneous conclusion that phenomenal red is really on the surface of the strawberry, and that our representations, because of their \'transparency\' allow us to be aware of such.  See liberal usages of this word in the works of [https://webspace.utexas.edu/tyem/www/ Michel Tye], [http://www.philosophie.uni-mainz.de/metzinger/ Thomas Metzinger] and others.\r\n\r\nWhen you say something like \'every quale is a representation\', again this confuses the issues and does not accurately mechanically portray what is the representation, and what is being represented.  The key thing to grasp is that the qualia, subjective experience, or the fact that looking at a strawberry does seem like something rather than either nothing or a string of 0s and 1s is a brain state.  It usually correlates to particular oscillations in the external world but bears little or no resemblance to them.  Philosophers who say that we only seem to have the qualia of red strawberries miss the point or make a category error in that it is the seeming bit that they need to explain.  If they are scientifically literate they already know that the qualia bear little actual resemblance to the external object.\r\n\r\nA few so called representationalists also name something they call the phenomenal principle - \"That if there sensibly appears to a subject to be something which possesses a particular sensible quality then there is something of which the subject is aware which does possess that sensible quality.\" And they deny such a principle.  We believe such a principle, but think it is much better to simply say our brains use qualia to represent things and that our knowledge is made of such.  What these qualia are like, how they are different, and how we are aware of such in a unified way, is critically important to the process.\r\nThe word representation has to be used because this is the normal way this form of brain processing is described in the literature. Nevertheless, this word is unfortunate in suggesting that our brain states bear some resemblance to the external world. It might be better to talk about \'mapping\'. For instance, the two dimensional coloured lines that comprise the map of a metro system in a large city bear little physical resemblance to the reality of concrete tunnels and metal vehicles, but this map is adaptive for navigating the city.\r\nThis is a very brief list of issues present here. Steve Lehar has a much more comprehensive review of the history of the epistemological debate, and the various problems and confusions that have and still do exist, working from an assumption that representational qualia theory is correct. This comprehensive academic presentation is contained in his [http://cns-alumni.bu.edu~slehar/webstuff/consc1a.htm#hist A History of the Epistemological Debate section of his â€œThe Function of Conscious Experienceâ€ paper. It includes the following:\r\n    â€œThe critical realists all agreed on the fact that the sense\r\n     data are independent of the object of perception itself.\r\n     However the question of whether the sense data are part\r\n    of the mind, or whether they are aspects of the external\r\n    object is one on which critical realists differed in subtle\r\n    ways. In a book on critical realism by a consortium of\r\n    authors, Lovejoy, Pratt and Sellars claim that the senses\r\n    are completely â€œthe character of the mental existent â€¦.\r\n    although its existence is not givenâ€, whatever that might\r\n    possibly mean, while Drake, Rogers, Santayana and Strong\r\n    agree that the data are characteristic of the apprehended\r\n    object, although â€œthe datum is qua datum, a mere essence,\r\n    an inputed but not necessarily actually existent. It may or\r\n    may not have existenceâ€, whatever that might possibly\r\n    mean. So the critical realists solved the problem of\r\n    sense-data by defining a unique kind of existent, which may\r\n    either be part of the external object, or of the internal\r\n    mental state, but in any case it has a status\r\n    of quasi-existence, which supposedly escapes the problems\r\n    inherent in identifying it explicitly as either an internal or\r\n    external entity. Epistemological confusion inevitably leads\r\n    to a confused philosophy.â€ \r\n\r\n== Various types of Property Dualism ==\r\n\r\nEveryone in this camp considers themselves to be \'property dualists\', in that they believe qualia are not only important, but are different properties of nature than traditional causal properties we can know of abstractly.  As David Chalmers refers to it, phenomenal qualities are \"Part of the basic furniture of nature, just as the laws of physics are.\"  Some theoreticians tend to call them \'physical properties\' but we believe this is not a good name since subjective phenomenal properties are also best thought of as \'physical properties\'.\r\n\r\nThere are different types of property dualists.  David Chalmers is probably the most famous property dualists and argues that phenomenal properties, in some \'hard\' way, \'arise from any functional equivalent organization, from neurons to silicon transistors.  This version of property dualism is currently the most well accepted, and is represented by the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/8 Functional Property Dualism] sub camp.  Recent gains in a competing camp that might be on the verge of taking the lead is very different in that it predicts that there is some neural correlate, or material substance that simply has the phenomenal properties our brains use to represent conscious knowledge with.  Without the right stuff, you can\'t have the same quale.  This theory is represented by the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/7 Material Property Dualism] sub camp.  If Material Property Dualism is effingly demonstrated to be true by science, it will falsify any theory or possibility that we might be in an abstracting simulation.\r\n\r\nThere are also other supporting yet to be falsified theories such as [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/14 Higher Dimensional property dualism] first proposed by C.D. Broad, and currently supported by [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=97 John Smythies] and Bernard Carr.  This theory predicts phenomenal properties exist in the branes of string theory, or in some higher dimensions.  In addition to these, there is an increasing number of other supporting sub camps indicating there is far less consensus on just what qualia are, as compared to how well accepted this more general Representational Qualia theory is.  The supporters of such sub camps as the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/17 Mind-Brain Identity Theory], and [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/9 Computational Functionalism] are subsets of the supporters of these general ideas.  Some proponents of \'Mind-Brain Identity Theory\', for example, do not believe in the importance of qualia, or that qualia are properties of our knowledge.  The supporters of these particular camps, as indicated by the fact that these are sub camps to this camp, show that they do espouse these additional doctrines.  We fully expect parallel branches of such camps to form outside of this Representational Qualia camp to properly represent the people that espouse these different versions of mind brain identity theory and functionalism.  The [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/37 Detection, Reaction, and Association] camp being one example of a functionalist theory that ignores qualia that is a competitor to this camp.\r\n\r\n== What will the future be like if this theory turns out to be the one ? ==\r\n\r\nOur brains and brain states are private from those of others, and give a first person experience, whereas what comes from other peoplesâ€™ brains is public and third person.  Though there are unified, grand and glorious phenomenal spirit* worlds within each of us, our spirits are still trapped behind this phenomenal veil of perception.  Our cause and effect based senses and their extension via traditional scientific instruments and communication tools allow abstracted communication between these worlds, and about the causal behaviour of the world in general.  But, beyond this abstracted information about the behaviour of what is outside, we are still phenomenally isolated and blind to any phenomenal properties beyond what is in our own world of conscious awareness.  When we hug someone, we still only know half of what is important.\r\n\r\nWe believe science could be on the verge of getting an objective handle on these blind to traditional cause-and-effect observation phenomenal properties that could enable technologies such as \'effing\' the ineffable.  This discovery will finally resolve how they work, how they are unified, and many other conundrums of self and epistemology philosophy has been struggling with for so long. We believe such a discovery will be the most significant, profound and world changing of scientific achievements to date. For such an achievement will literally ultimately enable the piercing of these spirit prison walls and eventually allow our phenomenally unified spirits to be freed into a world that is surely much more than just cause and effect behaviour.  If this theory turns out to be true our spirit* worlds, in addition to being shared and merged, will soon be growing in resolution, extents, diversity of phenomenal qualities, and many way\'s we surely can\'t even fathom yet, let alone know what it will be like.\r\n\r\nâ€œâ€â€References:-â€œâ€â€\r\n1.)  Rolls et al, 2003c\r\n\r\n2.)  Rolls et al 2003d\r\n\r\n3.)Anderson et al, 2003 â€“ Dissociated neural representations of intensity and valence in human olfaction  - Nature Neuroscience, 6, pp. 196-203\r\n\r\n\r\n4.) Melloni, L. et al, 2007  -  Synchronisation of cortical activity across cortical areas correlates with conscious perception  -  Journal of Neuroscience, 27, pp. 2858-65\r\n\r\n5.) Melloni, L. & Rodriguez, L., 2007  -  Non-perceived stimuli elicit local but not large scale neural synchrony  - Perception, 36, (ECVP Abstract Supplement)\r\n\r\n6.) Memory, Attention and Decision-Making  -  Edmund T. Rolls, Chapter 3, pp. 113-129\r\nNew Horizons in the Neuroscience of Consciousness   -  Chapter 2, pp. 17-26 â€“ Lucia Melloni & Wolf Singer\r\n\r\n7.)  Dennett, Daniel, 1991 â€“ Consciousness Explained, Brown and Co.\r\n\r\nâ€˜â€™â€™More Infoâ€™â€™â€™\r\n* Steven Lehar, an early leader in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/81/4 Mind Experts] topic maintains [http://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/Representationalism.html The Representationalism Web Site].\r\n* That we know of [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V.S. Ramachandran V.S. Ramachandran] and [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William Hirstein] were the first to propose the idea of effing the ineffable (though they didnâ€™t call it such) in their seminal http://www.imprint.co.uk/rama/qualia.pdf Three Laws of Qualia in 1997. Some people think there is a better term to use than â€˜effâ€™. Please see [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/102 this survey topic] and â€˜voteâ€™ for what you think is the best term to describe this process of communicating that which is ineffable.\r\n* In Nov. 2009 David Chalmers et al did a [http://philpapers.org/surveys PhilPapers Survey]. Question number 21 of that survey was: â€œPerceptual Experience: Representationalism, Qualia Theory, Disjunctivism, Sense â€“Datum Theory?â€ Though this camp shares doctrines of many of the choices such as qualia and representationalism, the members of this camp consider the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/106/6 Sense-Datum Theory choice] to be the closest to what is described here.\r\n* There is a canonized list of the most favourite publications about representational qualia theory [http://canonizer.com/topoc.asp/85 here]\r\n* This theory makes profound predictions about what things like uploading and â€œescape from our mortal spirit* prisonâ€ will be like, should it turn out to be true. A detailed description of such predictions in story form is contained in chapters 5 and 6 of the short story by Brent Allsop entitled â€œ1229 years after Titanicâ€ available here: http://home.comcast.net/~brent.allsop\r\n\r\nâ€˜â€™â€™*Note:â€™â€™â€™\r\nIt isnâ€™t easy to describe what we are talking about here with common English. Terms like â€˜phenomenalâ€™ and â€˜spiritualâ€™ get close, but can also be misleading because these terms are so often used to mean other things than we are talking about here. Though this â€˜world in our headâ€™ has many similarities to what people commonly think of when they use the term â€˜spirit worldâ€™ it should be very clear that what we are talking about here is completely contained in our skull, and is dependent on, or a property of, the living matter that makes up our brain. We do believe in â€˜spiritsâ€™ as defined here, but we do not believe in ghosts.\r\n','2011-07-17 15:45:44','2011-07-17 15:45:44'),(1115,96,48,'\"...Another question - many would consider an AI computer to be not conscious, or at best a \'zombie\' for which there was nothing it was like to be it or know what it knows. Do you believe an AI robot, or maybe even my digital camera, to be conscious, similar to the way I am, when I look at or take a picture of a sunset?\"\r\n\r\n\r\nAnswer is no, not similar to the way you do.  Why; #1, Consciousness is \'relative\' to the observer and is has a different sensation for a living human than a sub-atomic particle, or a digital camera or AI robot   #2, Under my theory, us and other living things have biological/physical brains and senses, that have abilities to harness consciousness in ways that artificial intelligence or robots will never have (or at least never have in any of our lifetimes).  The camera and AI Robot has a similar consciousness to a big rock, it the camera has a screen that shows us physical awareness of the sunset, but the cameraâ€™s consciousness is only aware of the hand that is holding it, and the gravity of earth that is keeping it on our hand.  I believe that feelings, and ideas might be born from consciousness but they cannot exist without the proper tools, ie. brain, and senses to feed the brain.  The AI Robots (and everything for that matter) consciousness will always be limited to the tools it is working with.  I believe us, and any life for that matter, has very unique biological equipment that harnesses consciousness in ways we do not yet understand.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nâ€œâ€¦Also, you mentioned: The very first thing to do is to define the term â€˜consciousnessâ€™, and then pointed out some things consciousness is not, but I could never get exactly what you define consciousness to be? Did I just miss it, or can you provide a short and concise description of what it is?â€\r\n\r\n\r\nThis is the toughest part.  Iâ€™ll give my best crack here, and Iâ€™ll add to the camp statement;\r\n\r\nConsciousness is the force that creates absolute from probability relative to the observer. The field of consciousness, or awareness, is derived from the anything that interacts with the observer.  Outside of that field of consciousness, and only relative to the observer, everything exists only as a probability.  Our brain and senses are biological tools that give us awareness, and harness consciousness.  Smaller objects, such as an atom of carbon, has only electrical magnetic force and gravity as tools that give it awareness, and as such it uses very little consciousness by itself.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nâ€œâ€¦The current agreement statement defines consciousness, or at least the most important current topic of this survey to be about what consciousness is like, as in what is stuff like redness and how does this relate to the underlying correlates, and so on. Perhaps you would take issue with this definition, and would push to get this agreement statement changed, so we can all agree with what is most important about consciousness, and what we should be surveying for here?â€\r\n\r\n\r\nI re-read the agreement statement, and I believe to answer the questions outlined, we need to first answer something more fundamental â€“ what is consciousness, or where does it come from?  The questions in the agreement statement refer to how consciousness reacts with physical / biological properties of our senses / brain.  My theory is the step forward to resolve the more fundamental question of â€˜what is consciousnessâ€™ first, just as the many of the other camps do in the survey.  I would vote to adding the fundamental question first, and then how it applies to phenomenal nature.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nâ€œâ€¦.Along those lines of the so far to date, subject of this survey topic, from within your theory, what is \'redness\'? Is it a property of the surface of a strawberry, or something reflecting something like 650 nm light? Or is it a property of something in our brain, as predicted by the currently leading consensus Representational Qualia Theory?  How is redness, greenness, and all if it unified together so we can be aware of it all in all of its ineffable phenomenal diversity, all at the same time? And, finally, will we ever be able to \'eff\' such ineffable stuff, to know what other minds are like, if they are different, to resolve the philosophical problem of other minds, and so on? To me, these are the important questions we are and should be surveying for regarding consciousness. I\'d love to know if you agree?â€ \r\n\r\n\r\nIt is of course a property of something in our brain, just as many people are color blind, many others are not, and im sure many organisms can â€˜senseâ€™ variations of red that we do not.\r\n\r\nI believe that Representational Qualia Theory makes a lot of sense, and my theory does not necessarily agree or disagree with it, but to me it is a biological / physical sensation or function that wouldnâ€™t exist without a brain such as ours.  There are many small organisms that I would consider conscious, but do not have a brain.\r\n','2011-07-17 23:54:18','2011-07-17 23:54:18'),(1118,96,48,'some years ago, i developed a (some would say over-simplistic) model of consciousness as: at least two cross-verifying senses combined with short-term memory, a \'visualization register\', and self-inclusive (explicitly) model of the local environment.. today, i debate the actual need of \'the model\' as part of consciousness; now, i see it more part of intelligence.. i would argue we are \'wet-wired\' for consciousness much like future androids will be capable of self-awareness. but as mentioned, senses are critical and cannot be \'pre-processed\' to the extent the short-term symbol registers cannot have \'direct access\' to sensory data.. of course, we filter our senses and likely would go mad if we could not.. a few months ago, i published a block diagram of my model of the most simplest AC (artificial consciousness) i could devise.. i think there is value of such designs - if only to pursue more realistic ones.. essentially, it\'s the systems approach toward modeling human consciousness with the intent of reproducing that model synthetically in hard-ware. i believe we can do it. however, the more we debate, what i call, \'the philosophy of mind\', the more we go in circles without making any significant progress.. i\'m not condemning such discussion.. but i am criticizing the extensive pursuit of such discussion at the exclusion of all else. we need to decide on a \'plan of action\' about synthesizing some basic constructs, of course - we need to first agree on what those basic constructs are: what are the minimum components required for consciousness? i think we must do this in order to make true progress in the field.. this is just my \'two cents\' - plz do not take any personal offense from my perspective, sam','2011-07-18 01:30:42','2011-07-18 01:30:42'),(1121,96,48,'\r\nHi Dahlstedt,\r\n\r\nThanks for explaining all this!  Though this helps, since it is a bit different than the way I currently think of some of this, it is still hard for me to fully get my head around and understand.  It is great to have all this as a reference, and to see it improve, with the better definition, and all that, and it will definitely help me and everyone going forward.\r\n\r\nI\'ve always figured that pan psycism agreed that redness is critically important and is a property of something in the brain, and it\'s great to see you in this camp, and I bet that is how most everyone thinks about this relationship.  I think the current structure doesn\'t represent that.  I started a thread in the forum of that camp, now the parent of your camp, and was planning on proposing moving the camp into a supporting position of the representational qualia theory in that thread, to better match the fact that everyone considers panpsychism as a sub camp of these general consensus ideas of consciousness.  If someone did move the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/34 Panexperientialism camp] into a supporting position of Representational Qualia Theory, would you, or anyone, object to such a change?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2011-07-18 02:44:00','2011-07-18 02:44:00'),(1124,96,48,'\r\nHi Sam,\r\n\r\nI love your idea about getting a \'plan of action\'.  I think we should definitely \'canonize\' a list of prioritized actions everyone thinks we most need to do to accelerate the progress in this most important of all pursuits of man.\r\n\r\nFirst off, I\'m taking it you would agree that consciousness should be the first general priority of mankind today - the general understanding of consciousness - that this should be receiving more scientific research $$ and everything?  The goal of the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/90 Most Important Questions survey] is this more general information.\r\n\r\nBut, just as you propose, I think we should create a separate survey topic just for what this field needs to focus on first, to better help it better prioritize and focus its still very limited resources.  Perhaps you would be willing to help with the starting of such a survey topic, maybe propose an initial name and agreement statement?\r\n\r\nAlso, a question about what you were saying.  I think today\'s robots have lots of \'self awareness\' - as they know where they, and especially their hands are, relative to whatever they are working on (or their location on the road, for driving robots) and so on.  But when you say: \" i would argue we are \'wet-wired\' for consciousness much like future androids will be capable of self-awareness\", how is this \'self-awareness\' different from what robots already have?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2011-07-18 02:57:23','2011-07-18 02:57:23'),(1125,1,42,'\r\nI\'m sure everyone would agree that a 5th dimension is a higher dimensional theory, so I propose moving this camp into a sub camp of the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/14 Higher-dimensional Theories] camp.\r\n\r\nWould anyone object to such a change?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2011-07-18 03:23:35','2011-07-18 03:23:35'),(1128,96,48,'I think that neuroscience does now allow us to make a distinction between the type awareness that can be attributed to robots etc. and the consciousness of humans.\r\n\r\nRecent studies have been able to show different activations in the brain according to whether processing is unconscious or consciously reported by the subjects of studies.\r\n\r\nRafael Malach, who has done a number of studies in this area, exposed subjects to visual images for 33 ms. At this time span, the same signal the image will sometimes be recognised consciously, and sometimes processed unconsciously. Studies of single neurons show that where the image is not consciously recognised, the neuron remains close to its baseline activity, but where subjects report conscious recognition of the image, the neuron fires at or near 50 Hz (the strong end of the main part of the gamma range associated with consciousness).\r\n\r\nIn the recent suggested master copy for the camp statement, we mention a rather similar study on a brain wide scale. The same visual image is shown to the subjects, but either masked, so that it does not enter consciousness, or viewed so that it can enter consciousness. Where the processing is unconscious, gamma synchrony arises only locally in one part of the brain, but when consciousness is reported by subjects, global gamma synchrony arises between spatially separated neuronal assemblies.\r\n\r\nI think it reasonable to argue from these examples that there is a demonstrated physical distinction between unconscious sensing and reacting, which comprises the majority of brains processing, and processing that involves consciousness. I suppose in the last resort you canâ€™t definitely say which type machines have, but in that it is demonstrated that the brain can do a lot at the non-conscious level, and there is therefore no specific requirement for consciousness when a machine makes an automated response, Occamâ€™s razor would suggest such machines be regarded as not conscious, while we continue to look for what it is the flips the brain from non-conscious to conscious.\r\n\r\nIf we are looking at entities from the outside without the benefit of scanners, we would probably assess their consciousness on their tendency to show preferences or make choices that could not be demonstrated to be the product of a hard-wired algorithm. This tendency too is mentioned in our draft master copy.\r\n\r\nEdmund Rolls and others have demonstrated that activation in the orbitofrontal cortex, the region most involved in assessing the reward/punisher value of sensory inputs, is correlated to the subjective reactions of humans being studied, rather than the strength of the external signal. Thus the pressure of a piece of wood produces a stronger activation in the somatosensory cortex than that of a soft piece of velvet, but in the orbitofrontal, the velvet that has reward/pleasure value produces more activation than the wood, and via the basal ganglia, dopamine nuclei and other areas this is seen to influence behaviour. It is also argued to give the organism a flexibility of response to the environment that would be impractical to programme in via genes.\r\n','2011-07-18 20:05:27','2011-07-18 20:05:27'),(1131,96,48,'For those with a bit more time, the piece below tries to illustrate the argument about choice and preference mentioned in the last posting in a more whimsical way.\r\n\r\nThe Scene:  An elegant villa in the south of England  _____  a long time in the future.\r\n\r\nâ€¦â€¦â€¦  As she entered the villa, Snodgrove (non-conscious android butler) approached and spoke to her, â€˜If you please, Miss Freya, thereâ€™s a young woman here to see you.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜Oh, I didnâ€™t think, I had any appointments. Can you remind me who she is?â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜She doesnâ€™t have an appointment, Miss Freya,â€™ Snodgrove replied. â€˜She appeared here this afternoon, rather distressed and dishevelled, I must say. Actually, she really wanted to speak to Miss Cecily, but when I said that this was your home now, she said that she would be happy to speak to you.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜Well, thatâ€™s big of her. So what have you done with this woman?â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜Sheâ€™s in the bathroom in the south apartment. She had rather a large quantity of mud attached to her legs, so I suggested some ablutions might be in order. I also took the liberty of providing the young lady with a bottle of the new wine you had delivered. She expressed a preference for that type of wine.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜What! Not the Villa Irene ReservÃ©! That costs a fortune. I was meaning that for special guests.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜I am full of apologies for my error, Miss Freya. If my performance has been less than satisfactory, perhaps you feel that I should visit the reprogramming department. I was acting on commands indicating that I should show as much hospitality as reasonably possible towards visitors.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜No,â€™ Freya replied, â€˜you acted quite correctly.â€™ She knew that she had put the setting for Snodgroveâ€™s inclination to hospitality close to the maximum, to offset a certain tightness with money that she was well aware of.\r\n\r\nLeaving Snodgrove, she went swiftly up the wide staircase of the Villa Irene. She would get rid of this girl as quickly as possible. Probably one of Cecily groupie followers. On top of that, this girl was now drinking her very expensive wine, and probably not even appreciating it. The thought of that made her cross, and she threw open the door of the bathroom without even knocking and marched in.\r\n\r\nFreya looked at Persephone, and everything about Persephone surprised. She was very beautiful for one thing. But there was something else. There was something naÃ¯ve and helpless about this girl. She looked at Freya as if she was some sort of revelation. Usually the Cecily followers combined a drowned rat appearance, with a rather calculating glance, as if they were estimating what they could get out of one.\r\n\r\nâ€˜Well, youâ€™ve certainly made yourself at home,â€™ Freya remarked, observing Persephone as she lounged in the bath.\r\n\r\nâ€˜Oh, hallo, I hope you donâ€™t mind? Your butler suggested I had a bath, while I was waiting for you.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜No. Not at all, but I was just wondering, who you are.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜Oh, nobody really. My nameâ€™s Persephone. I was just looking for Cecily.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜Cecily only lived here when she was a child.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜I see. Well, perhaps you could tell me where to find her.â€™\r\n\r\nFreya sat down on a bathroom stool, quite close to Persephone, and peered closely at her, â€˜That really depends on who you are, and why you want to see her.â€™\r\n\r\nPersephone didnâ€™t reply immediately. She seemed rather stumped by this apparently simple question. â€˜Just tell me who you are and why you want to see Cecily,â€™ Freya persisted.\r\n\r\nâ€˜Well __ Iâ€™m nobody really,â€™ Persephone said eventually. â€˜I met \r\n\r\nCecily at a lunch yesterday and afterwards I thought perhaps she could __ er __ help me.â€™\r\n\r\nIn answer, Freya laughed sarcastically. â€˜Oh, yes,â€™ she said, â€˜Cecily was always such a little do-gooder, and so charming and silver tongued. Just the sort of person to help waives and strays or whatever youâ€™re supposed to be. Well, I can tell you, she was a real little cow when she was a child. Always getting me into trouble.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜But even so, perhaps she could help me,â€™ Persephone said, and Freya thought she detected more than a note of desperation this time.\r\n\r\nâ€˜I might feel more inclined to help you if you would let onto me what exactly Harcourt-Smythe has been doing at Dragonâ€™s Gate. I know heâ€™s been hanging around there recently.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜He wasnâ€™t there all the time. He has a job in London.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜That isnâ€™t really an answer to my question, is it?â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜No, I suppose not,â€™ Persephone said. â€˜Well, I think, he was supposed to have designed a conscious android.â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜I donâ€™t believe you.â€™\r\n\r\nThere was a pause after this, and Persephone looked baffled. Finally she said, â€˜you donâ€™t believe me? Why not?â€™\r\n\r\nâ€˜Because I think that there never will be any conscious androids. Iâ€™ve tried to build them myself, and Iâ€™m telling you they canâ€™t be built. The whole subject of consciousness reduces the brightest minds to meaningless pulp. And please donâ€™t tell me that other robots can piece together a conscious robot. However powerful their brains, they can never really get the hang of what we mean by consciousness.â€™\r\n\r\nThatâ€™s not true. I can,â€™ Persephone replied.\r\n\r\nâ€˜Well, of course you can,â€™ Freya said. â€˜Youâ€™re not an â€¦ â€™ Then she stopped. There was a pause before she spoke again. â€˜What did you say then? What did you mean?â€™ Freya said at last.\r\n\r\nPersephone was looking at her, and this strange girlâ€™s face seemed full of fear and confusion, â€˜Iâ€™m an android, a conscious android. I ran away from Dragonâ€™s Gate, because I didnâ€™t like the way I was expected to behave.â€™\r\n\r\nFreya was surprised by fear, a fear of the unknown and the unnatural. Could this girl who was so obviously human be just a robot? If it was true, then Dragon had made a leap forward in the outward appearance of their androids. Could they have devised something as warm and sensual as this girl?\r\n\r\nAfter a moment, Freya recovered herself, and began to have doubts. She asked herself whether this was perhaps an elaborate practical joke, perhaps some silly prank of Cecilyâ€™s or else a novel way of gaining commercial secrets. Anyway, there was a simple way of settling the question. Freya activated a small hand held device that she used for diagnosing problems with her own androids. She gasped slightly when she looked at the screen, which imaged Persephoneâ€™s interior. It left her in no doubt that this so-seeming natural girl was a machine.\r\n\r\nFirst, she had to investigate more carefully. She knew now that this girl for all her warmth and vitality was just a machine, but was this machine conscious or just a very clever simulation? Well, her own prior efforts to build conscious androids had at least taught her what she had to look for. She would need to detect apparently subjective preferences or choices of one course of action over another that were sufficiently unlikely to have been included in Persephoneâ€™s programming or training.\r\n\r\nFreya knew that robots were just thinking machines. But the human brain had a two-way connection between the rational and emotional centres. If something damaged that connection, it became difficult for a human to make even trivial decisions. There was nothing mystic about the emotions. They were based on the same type of brain cells as the rational area of the brain. However, it was not just a matter of a brain signal from the emotional area. It was the conscious experience of the emotion that gave it its special punch in making decisions or forming preferences. It could help to decide between things that were narrowly balanced or insist on something that was not wise from the rational point of view, such as more wine or sex with the wrong person.\r\n\r\nFreya reached for the wine bottle, meaning to fill one of the bathroom tumblers. â€˜My God, youâ€™ve drunk nearly the whole bottle!â€™ she exclaimed.\r\n\r\nâ€˜Yes, I liked that wine.â€™\r\n \r\nâ€˜Like! Androids canâ€™t like or dislike. Although, I suppose if youâ€™re really conscious â€¦ â€™ that was a lucky break, Freya suddenly realised. There was absolutely no point in programming an android to drink wine in the absence of its owners. Doing that in itself suggested some form of will and preference. She had realised that one could never be totally certain that another entity was conscious. It had to be inferred. You knew you were conscious yourself. You inferred that other people were conscious, to the extent that their behaviour resembled your own. Over a very long period of time, most people had inferred that androids and other computers and computer-driven machines were not conscious. It seemed to her that the important difference leading people to that conclusion had been that androids never expressed their own preference for particular things or particular courses of action, never indicated that they felt that they liked something or that they wanted to perform a particular action. You could argue that in humans these preferences were themselves just the product of genes or nurture, but we all knew that at the point of action, they derived from a subjective experience, and that was what gave them their special punch.\r\nPersephoneâ€™s behaviour with the wine had been human rather than robotic. There was no apparent reason for her to drink the wine, except for a small amount when humans were present in order to give a companionable impression.\r\n\r\nFreya decided that she would try some more-or-less formal tests. She thought she would make some further use of Persephoneâ€™s wine-drinking propensities. She had Snodgrove bring in several glasses of different types of wine. Persephone mustnâ€™t see the bottle, because she might have been programmed to admire particular wines.\r\n\r\nWhen Persephone had sampled a rather ample amount of each wine, Freya asked her to rank them in order of preference. A normal android could only grade wines according to its knowledge of the quality as signified by the label. Confronted with this sort of blind tasting, the android would be stumped. It would remain silent, or apologise for its inability to answer the question.\r\n\r\nPersephone, however, ranked her preferences with hardly a momentâ€™s hesitation, and added for good measure that she preferred the original bottle to any of the subsequent wines.\r\nFreya was shocked when she heard that answer. She knew that Persephone was a machine, but she had for some time believed that no one would ever build a machine that could do what Persephone had just done.\r\n\r\nFor her second test, Freya had Snodgrove wheel in several racks of clothing. â€˜Your stuffs all ruined from running around in the woods,â€™ Freya remarked. â€˜Youâ€™d better choose something you like from these.â€™\r\n\r\nThis should be revealing, Freya thought. It was once again the sort of open choice that the manuals warned against. The android could become confused, and might simply put on the first garments that came to hand, with a possibly incongruous effect. It was better for the user to give clear instructions.\r\n\r\nPersephone spent a considerable time flicking through the rails, but the actual process of choosing did not appear to bother her. She tried on lots of things and generally took an uneconomic amount of time. She did ask Freyaâ€™s opinion a few times, but then tended to disagree with her, and didnâ€™t seem to have any notion that Freyaâ€™s view should prevail. Once again, Persephone was showing very specific preferences that could not realistically have been programmed in.\r\n\r\nFreya searched around for another test. Then she had it. Since the invention of the quantum brain, robots had always been stumped by art and artistic preferences. The villa had been built for Freyaâ€™s great-uncle. It had been decorated with frescoes by an artist, who had been fashionable at the time, but had subsequently become something of a joke in artistic circles. At least, that was until the last few years when she had started to come back into fashion, and Freya had felt obliged to open parts of the villa once a year for members of the society formed by the artistâ€™s his new admirers.\r\nFreya asked Persephone for her opinion of the bathroom frescoes and to say which of the various panels she preferred. At this point, an android would normally fall back on a simple factual catalogue of the subject matter. The android mind never went that further step to give a subjective response. But Persephone admired the light and airy feel of the landscapes, and showed little hesitation in picking out the panels she liked best.\r\n\r\nThen Freya realised that Persephone did indeed share in the rich kaleidoscope of consciousness, from which all previous robot minds had been excluded. She also realised without any closer examination that this device was powerful and dangerous. It was the ultimate Pandoraâ€™s Box. It could lead to very serious trouble. She saw androids running amok, and states and corporations drawn into conflict. And yet, there might be something here for her, something that would allow her to dominate the android industry.\r\n','2011-07-18 20:15:28','2011-07-18 20:15:28'),(1134,96,48,'There appears to be a difference in understanding here about what is meant by consciousness. I\'m sure the academics can provide the correct definitions of various terms, but let me explain what I mean in an attempt to be helpful.\r\n\r\nIt is suggested that Occam\'s Razor helps us to declare androids non-conscious. Well, in the sense that they do not share the same quality (or quantity?) of consciousness as human beings, that is probably fair enough. \r\n\r\nBut that does nothing to detract from the panpsychist argument that all matter has basic awareness as one of its properties. Stuff simply is aware, all of it. The consequences of that awareness depend on the configuration of the matter. If there is a feedback loop that can provide for the storage and recall of memories over time, then experience of time is possible. That in turn permits recall, imagination and creativity. It is those feedback loops that broadly differentiate conscious systems from non-conscious ones. The extent to which those features are possible determines the level of consciousness, and thus, your average android, whilst being in no way able to match a human being, nevertheless does possess a degree of conscious awareness, much as does a dust mite.\r\n\r\nI don\'t think I have much truck with the idea that if an android decides to sit in a bath drinking wine she must be conscious. I can program a very simple droid to do that, or to make decisions in a way that would lead to that outcome without me having necessarily considered it, no problem.\r\n\r\n','2011-07-19 14:16:56','2011-07-19 14:16:56'),(1137,96,48,'There appears to be a difference in understanding here about what is meant by consciousness. I\'m sure the academics can provide the correct definitions of various terms, but let me explain what I mean in an attempt to be helpful.\r\n\r\nIt is suggested that Occam\'s Razor helps us to declare androids non-conscious. Well, in the sense that they do not share the same quality (or quantity?) of consciousness as human beings, that is probably fair enough. \r\n\r\nBut that does nothing to detract from the panpsychist argument that all matter has basic awareness as one of its properties. Stuff simply is aware, all of it. The consequences of that awareness depend on the configuration of the matter. If there is a feedback loop that can provide for the storage and recall of memories over time, then experience of time is possible. That in turn permits recall, imagination and creativity. It is those feedback loops that broadly differentiate conscious systems from non-conscious ones. The extent to which those features are possible determines the level of consciousness, and thus, your average android, whilst being in no way able to match a human being, nevertheless does possess a degree of conscious awareness, much as does a dust mite.\r\n\r\nI don\'t think I have much truck with the idea that if an android decides to sit in a bath drinking wine she must be conscious. I can program a very simple droid to do that, or to make decisions in a way that would lead to that outcome without me having necessarily considered it, no problem.\r\n\r\n','2011-07-19 14:17:07','2011-07-19 14:17:07'),(1140,96,48,'There appears to be a difference in understanding here about what is meant by consciousness. I\'m sure the academics can provide the correct definitions of various terms, but let me explain what I mean in an attempt to be helpful.\r\n\r\nIt is suggested that Occam\'s Razor helps us to declare androids non-conscious. Well, in the sense that they do not share the same quality (or quantity?) of consciousness as human beings, that is probably fair enough. \r\n\r\nBut that does nothing to detract from the panpsychist argument that all matter has basic awareness as one of its properties. Stuff simply is aware, all of it. The consequences of that awareness depend on the configuration of the matter. If there is a feedback loop that can provide for the storage and recall of memories over time, then experience of time is possible. That in turn permits recall, imagination and creativity. It is those feedback loops that broadly differentiate conscious systems from non-conscious ones. The extent to which those features are possible determines the level of consciousness, and thus, your average android, whilst being in no way able to match a human being, nevertheless does possess a degree of conscious awareness, much as does a dust mite.\r\n\r\nI don\'t think I have much truck with the idea that if an android decides to sit in a bath drinking wine she must be conscious. I can program a very simple droid to do that, or to make decisions in a way that would lead to that outcome without me having necessarily considered it, no problem.\r\n\r\n','2011-07-19 14:17:26','2011-07-19 14:17:26'),(1143,96,48,'forgive my gushing but i like the way you think.. in a crude sense, a footprint is \'aware\' in that it reacts to it\'s environment (one time) and data is stored (the footprint pattern). as you so aptly described, a footprint is less aware than a mite because there\'s no feedback. it\'s a one time deal. so inanimate matter has the simplest form of awareness possible. the more complex the feedback mechanism (memory), the more capacity it has (say 3D vs 2D), the more sophisticated awareness can be.. i\'m currently working on the \'problem of longterm memory\' (how to define it so we can reproduce it).. a long time ago, i had a psychology professor at Michigan State who mentioned: \"a spider is aware - just not as aware as us\".. i doubt he would say a footprint in dust is aware - in any meaningful sense.. but all matter reacts to forces ect which can be thought of as reacting to stimuli.. regardless of our definition of awareness (what is aware and what is not), we need to work on the \'mechanics\' of memory: how does it work in humans? and then we can reproduce it in machines :)','2011-07-19 15:25:04','2011-07-19 15:25:04'),(1146,96,48,'I think the last para. about the droid in the bath rather misses the point of the story.\r\n\r\nFreya herself realises that Persephone could have been given the simulation of consciousness, and she does not see anything remarkable in the very organised behaviour of her android butler.\r\n\r\nWhat impresses Freya is that Persephone shows a preference for drinking wine in the bath, which would be of no use to her absent owners, and further to that she can show preferences between different wines, although it\'s a blind tasting, where she can\'t have been programmed to go for a particular wine.\r\n\r\nFurther to this we do now know that there is a subjectively conscious structure in the brain which is involved in just this sort of evaluation.\r\n\r\nThe brain and the brain-body seem to be riddled with feedback, and I get the impression its full role may not be that well understood. However what is clear is that it is fairly general. But experimentation suggests that consciousness arises in fairly special circumstances in the brain, whereas feedback is overall, so while it may well be necessary for consciousness it does not look sufficient.\r\n\r\nI find a background pan psychism quite attractive but as with  consciousness in the brain, the sort of physics that describes both conventional neuroscience, and the make up of rocks, streams and trees is causally closed, not requiring or producing anything akin to consciousness, locus genii or the spirits of the water.\r\n\r\nIf we want this we\'ll have to go deeper either into dualism, which has its own problems, or look for something fundamental in the physical universe to which these things gain access.\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n  ','2011-07-19 17:47:04','2011-07-19 17:47:04'),(1149,96,48,'Junius >>>> \r\n\r\nBut experimentation suggests that consciousness arises in fairly special circumstances in the brain, whereas feedback is overall, so while it may well be necessary for consciousness it does not look sufficient.\r\n\r\n<<<< Junius\r\n\r\nThere is an assumption that anything that we cannot report being conscious of is an unconscious process. But it is at least equally likely that \"unconscious\" processes are not unconscious after all, but merely inaccessible to our central narrative consciousness. For example I don\'t realize I\'ve been getting hungry, but my \"stomach\" has been grousing about it for half an hour before I start paying attention. There are a million such quasi-independent processes going on all the time in our mind, only a small fragment of which become accessible to central consciousness. How often have you suddenly noticed a sound that had been there all along? Some portion of your auditory system had been monitoring it all along, conscious of it independent of your narrative consciousness, until it gets just weird enough that that auditory system \"wakes up\" your narrative consciousness and says \"Listen to this!\" And when you suddenly hear it, you also \"remember\" having been hearing it all along.\r\n\r\nIts all explained here:\r\n\r\nhttp://sharp.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/book2/Boundaries.html\r\n\r\nsee Chapter 6, p. 119, section: Is Experience Unitary or Fragmentary?','2011-07-19 19:08:32','2011-07-19 19:08:32'),(1152,96,48,'So much to say!\r\n\r\nslehar: \"There is an assumption that anything that we cannot report being conscious of is an unconscious process.\"\r\n\r\nOh, isn\'t that so true! The assumption disregards the possibility that consciousness takes place but is not memorised and thus cannot be recalled. Think about dreams. We know from brain scans that dreams are far more frequent than dreamers realise, because the dreamers do not remember their dreams. But they still dream!\r\n\r\nIf a rock has awareness but cannot recall it, how does it know? That doesn\'t mean it has no awareness; merely that the awareness is lost as soon as it has happened. The rock has no perception of time; it is a continuing moment and that is all.\r\n\r\nJunius: \"What impresses Freya is that Persephone shows a preference for drinking wine in the bath, which would be of no use to her absent owners, and further to that she can show preferences between different wines, although it\'s a blind tasting, where she can\'t have been programmed to go for a particular wine.\"\r\n\r\nIs the suggestion that this preference is evidence for consciousness? If not then you are right, I am missing the point - sorry. Please could you help me to understand? But if it is intended that an activity that is no use to the owner and that has not been programmed is evidence of consciousness then there are a lot of conscious PCs and mobile phones out there running Windows.\r\n\r\nJunius: \"I find a background pan psychism quite attractive but as with consciousness in the brain, the sort of physics that describes both conventional neuroscience, and the make up of rocks, streams and trees is causally closed, not requiring or producing anything akin to consciousness, locus genii or the spirits of the water.\"\r\n\r\nThis argument appears to me to conflate free will with conscious experience. Free will arguably requires a component to physics that we do not understand (usually referred to as dualism) but it does not appear to me that consciousness requires anything at all other than an acceptance that matter has awareness as a property. Clearly, physics does produce this much - you are evidence of that. (Alternatively, if we pursue the argument that dualism is required even for consciousness, the claim made that physics is causally closed does not seem to me entirely true. Quantum events have probabilities that crystallise without apparent cause. They are statistically random within the probability function. I would not describe that as \'closed\'. How would you explain that?)\r\n','2011-07-19 20:39:45','2011-07-19 20:39:45'),(1155,96,48,'This seems to raise a number of different, if connected questions.\r\n\r\nWe consider ourselves conscious because it\'s subjectively like something to be us, but we can only surmise about entities other than ourselves. Other people are rather like us, so they probably in, and then it starts to slide away through chimpanzees, other mammals, insects, computers, thermostats, rocks .....\r\n\r\nThe challenge made by orthodox writers often is as to how would you know that a robot or whatever was conscious, and the ability to make an unprogrammed choice looks a good way, because things like rocks simply obey the laws of physics and computers obey algorithms predetermined by human brains. Of course this is second best to our own first person experience, but it\'s probably the best you can do for a third party.\r\n\r\nYou ask whether preference is evidence for consciousness, and neuroscience of the last few years in effect says yes to that question.\r\n\r\nWhen the orbitofrontal which is important in decision making evaluates the reward/punisher qualities of sensory inputs its activation is  correlated to subjective appreciation rather than the physical strength of the external signal.\r\n\r\nDoes this mean freewill? It certainly points to subjective consciousness influencing decisions and behaviour, although I admit in principle it would seem possible to be conscious but unable to influence events.\r\n\r\nBut no, this is not an argument for dualism. That only arises if we have a Cartesian assumption that consciousness is immaterial. But the problems of dualism suggest that there is no such thing as the immaterial. Consciousness is therefore part of the physical universe, but as such there is no particular reason why it should not have a physical influence on behaviour.\r\n\r\nAs far as dreaming goes, we know at least with REM sleep that significant and energy consuming parts of the brain are at work, and that there\'s nothing analogous to those structures in rock. As for our waking life, there\'s a lot of argument about peripheral consciousness but if something can\'t be reported at all even to ourselves, it\'s a hard to envisage where or what exactly the something it\'s likeness of consciousnness actually is in this case.    \r\n\r\nAs for the quantum world, I suggest you will have to go to this level and further to find consciousness both for people and rocks, but that as Freya realised opens a Pandora\'s box of difficulties. Matter can have awareness, but I don\'t think you\'ll be able to describe that awareness in terms of classical as opposed to more fundamental physics.  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n   ','2011-07-19 22:15:29','2011-07-19 22:15:29'),(1158,96,48,'This is a second reply both to Slehar and Darren\r\n\r\nI was reading just now the bit in chapter 6, p. 119, and this seems to accord very well with both experience and quite a lot of research. But the difference between the people and the rocks is that at the point where they were having the conscious experience they could report it. It\'s arguable that they\'re using short term memory, but most seem to think that there would be no consciousness in any case without short term memory.\r\n\r\nHowever, I would see this as different from saying that unconscious processes as a whole are actually conscious. The argument seem to depend on  drawing peoples\' attention to something like driving and then they are aware of it, but you can\'t do the same for say processing in the primary visual cortex. ','2011-07-19 22:38:30','2011-07-19 22:38:30'),(1161,96,48,'i am working on a deterministic quantum framework that is allowed by the refutation of Bell\'s theorem .. so i am warning all ppl who base their \'theory of mind\' on modern QM: there is no inherent validity in quantum theories of mind connected to QM such as \'the holographic mind\'.. it\'s all truly BS.\r\n\r\nthe holographic principle is Speculative.\r\n\r\nanything that relies on multiple dimensions or inherent randomness is based on the inability of \'some folks\' to accept deterministic reality.\r\n\r\n.. it\'s sad but true that humans cannot \'handle\' a deterministic reality .. so we invent an alternate reality that allows random matter and existence which absolves us from all responsibility / accountability .. further, we don\'t need inherent randomness to allow chaos .. randomness can occur from \'strange attractors\' which means deterministic systems can exhibit chaotic behavior..\r\n\r\nso relating to mind, we don\'t need conventional QM to explain random human behavior .. we simply need to recognize that some systems are reminiscent of chaotic dynamical systems which appear random but are based on deterministic causality..\r\n\r\n.. the bottom line here is: QM has NOTHING to do with mind; the human mind is a complex dynamical system which has deterministic roots; conventional QM cannot help us understand the human mind; we\'d better spend our time attempting to understand \'long term memory\' which will give us insights into awareness/consciousness..\r\n\r\nsam','2011-07-19 23:02:47','2011-07-19 23:02:47'),(1164,96,48,'Junius >>>>\r\n\r\nHowever, I would see this as different from saying that unconscious processes as a whole are actually conscious. The argument seem to depend on drawing peoples\' attention to something like driving and then they are aware of it, but you can\'t do the same for say processing in the primary visual cortex.\r\n\r\n<<<< Junius\r\n\r\nYou are willing to accord a primal consciousness to rocks. What about to the bones in our body? Do they not feel the stress and strain? Or the blood in our veins? Does it not gush and flow in response to felt forces? But none of this becomes part of our narrative consciousness, it is a separate and independent thing that we experience only indirectly, if at all.\r\n\r\nWhat about your alimentary canal? You sure are conscious of events in the front end, as you chew and swallow your food, but the consciousness blinks out abruptly at the threshold of your throat, beyond which unconsciousness seems to reign.\r\n\r\nBut does your gut not squirm and suffer when you feed it a hot Vindaloo curry? And do you not begin to feel the pain again at the other end of the canal? Surely the rest of your alimentary canal is conscious of its own squeezing and squirming in response to food, even if that experience occurs beyond your own.\r\n\r\nEither consciousness is an elusive etherial entity that has no functional purpose, or it is part and parcel of how matter interacts with matter, and occurs in everything. Whenever it occurs in such a way that WE don\'t experience it directly, we tend to deny its existence altogether. But it is *at least* equally likely that unconscious processes are only unconscious to us, but not to THEM, because otherwise they would not squeeze and squirm or gush and flow as we observe them to do.\r\n\r\nThe example of the android choosing to sip wine in the tub, is absurd! What -- a decision has to be arbitrary and logically baseless for it to be conscious? A much more direct evidence of consciousness is if the android made it to the bathroom without bumping into walls or falling down stairs, which indicates that it must have had a vivid conscious experience of walls and doors and faucets to be able to navigate them so efficiently.\r\n\r\nThe android can demonstrate visual consciousness by saying \"I see a room around me\", and when prompted it can elaborate \"This wall stretches this way, meeting that wall in a corner there...\" If THATS not conscious experience then I don\'t know what is!','2011-07-20 11:56:44','2011-07-20 11:56:44'),(1167,96,48,'Junius >>>>\r\n\r\nHowever, I would see this as different from saying that unconscious processes as a whole are actually conscious. The argument seem to depend on drawing peoples\' attention to something like driving and then they are aware of it, but you can\'t do the same for say processing in the primary visual cortex.\r\n\r\n<<<< Junius\r\n\r\nYou are willing to accord a primal consciousness to rocks. What about to the bones in our body? Do they not feel the stress and strain? Or the blood in our veins? Does it not gush and flow in response to felt forces? But none of this becomes part of our narrative consciousness, it is a separate and independent thing that we experience only indirectly, if at all.\r\n\r\nWhat about your alimentary canal? You sure are conscious of events in the front end, as you chew and swallow your food, but the consciousness blinks out abruptly at the threshold of your throat, beyond which unconsciousness seems to reign.\r\n\r\nBut does your gut not squirm and suffer when you feed it a hot Vindaloo curry? And do you not begin to feel the pain again at the other end of the canal? Surely the rest of your alimentary canal is conscious of its own squeezing and squirming in response to food, even if that experience occurs beyond your own.\r\n\r\nEither consciousness is an elusive etherial entity that has no functional purpose, or it is part and parcel of how matter interacts with matter, and occurs in everything. Whenever it occurs in such a way that WE don\'t experience it directly, we tend to deny its existence altogether. But it is *at least* equally likely that unconscious processes are only unconscious to us, but not to THEM, because otherwise they would not squeeze and squirm or gush and flow as we observe them to do.\r\n\r\nThe example of the android choosing to sip wine in the tub, is absurd! What -- a decision has to be arbitrary and logically baseless for it to be conscious? A much more direct evidence of consciousness is if the android made it to the bathroom without bumping into walls or falling down stairs, which indicates that it must have had a vivid conscious experience of walls and doors and faucets to be able to navigate them so efficiently.\r\n\r\nThe android can demonstrate visual consciousness by saying \"I see a room around me\", and when prompted it can elaborate \"This wall stretches this way, meeting that wall in a corner there...\" If THATS not conscious experience then I don\'t know what is!','2011-07-20 11:57:25','2011-07-20 11:57:25'),(1170,96,48,'Junius >>>>\r\n\r\nHowever, I would see this as different from saying that unconscious processes as a whole are actually conscious. The argument seem to depend on drawing peoples\' attention to something like driving and then they are aware of it, but you can\'t do the same for say processing in the primary visual cortex.\r\n\r\n<<<< Junius\r\n\r\nYou are willing to accord a primal consciousness to rocks. What about to the bones in our body? Do they not feel the stress and strain? Or the blood in our veins? Does it not gush and flow in response to felt forces? But none of this becomes part of our narrative consciousness, it is a separate and independent thing that we experience only indirectly, if at all.\r\n\r\nWhat about your alimentary canal? You sure are conscious of events in the front end, as you chew and swallow your food, but the consciousness blinks out abruptly at the threshold of your throat, beyond which unconsciousness seems to reign.\r\n\r\nBut does your gut not squirm and suffer when you feed it a hot Vindaloo curry? And do you not begin to feel the pain again at the other end of the canal? Surely the rest of your alimentary canal is conscious of its own squeezing and squirming in response to food, even if that experience occurs beyond your own.\r\n\r\nEither consciousness is an elusive etherial entity that has no functional purpose, or it is part and parcel of how matter interacts with matter, and occurs in everything. Whenever it occurs in such a way that WE don\'t experience it directly, we tend to deny its existence altogether. But it is *at least* equally likely that unconscious processes are only unconscious to us, but not to THEM, because otherwise they would not squeeze and squirm or gush and flow as we observe them to do.\r\n\r\nThe example of the android choosing to sip wine in the tub, is absurd! What -- a decision has to be arbitrary and logically baseless for it to be conscious? A much more direct evidence of consciousness is if the android made it to the bathroom without bumping into walls or falling down stairs, which indicates that it must have had a vivid conscious experience of walls and doors and faucets to be able to navigate them so efficiently.\r\n\r\nThe android can demonstrate visual consciousness by saying \"I see a room around me\", and when prompted it can elaborate \"This wall stretches this way, meeting that wall in a corner there...\" If THATS not conscious experience then I don\'t know what is!','2011-07-20 11:57:51','2011-07-20 11:57:51'),(1173,96,48,'I would like to say some words, regarding the last messages.\r\n\r\n1) I believe this is something most people here (if not all) is aware of, but I guess we should be more specific to what \"side\" of the counscious experience we are talking about. Meaning we have both fenomenalogical and psychological counsciousness - the latter is pretty much explained nowadays, our main concern is about the former.\r\n\r\n2) I\'m not sure I believe, but I can accept the pan psychism view - even if that implies infinite conscious beings (even sharing the same body, like conscious bones inside me).\r\n\r\n3) What I cannot accept that we should even consider the hypothesis of fenomenalogical counsciousness being \"existent but irrelevant\" - simply because we (at least, not sure about my bones) are psychologically aware of it. Fenomenalogically, we \"feel\" the psychological processes which result from our brain; but every time we think about that kind of experience, this is our brain generating thougths about the fenomenalogical experience. In other words, the \"spirit\" is aware of the \"mind\"; but the opposite, somehow, is also true.\r\n\r\n4) All this, of course, may be an illusion, and maybe there is no such thing as fenomenalogical experience at all. Still, I insist there is no option for a middle ground: OR fenomenalogical experience exists, and it is also psychologically relevant; OR fenomenalogical experience does NOT exist (and we are all losing our precious time reading this kind of discussion...).\r\n\r\nFinally, I would like to appologize for my English. There is much more I want to say, but I don\'t find the words. This is a hard topic, even more when spoken in a foreign language... :-(\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nRogerio.','2011-07-20 19:57:02','2011-07-20 19:57:02'),(1176,96,48,'The key word here seems to be \'logically\' or the assumption that consciousness is only or mainly related to reasoning.\r\n\r\nWhen we or Persephone choose something we experience in turn separate subjective scenarios. The experience of one wine as against another, or what\'s probably more important the decision between a short-term benefit and a larger longer-term benefit, say between spending the afternoon drinking, or doing some exercise, which may at a later date give us a healthier body. This is our impression of it, and as of the last few years this is supported by experimentation.\r\n\r\nIt is true as you say that the decision is arbitrary. You can write down pros and cons as much as you like, but the clincher is the subjective scenarios. What we should be asking is where that comes from. As you know, you wouldn\'t be the first to notice that the quantum world can also be a bit arbitrary. \r\n\r\nI wouldn\'t for a moment deny that we are conscious of reasoning, but the evidence suggests that it\'s coloured by emotional processing which lies predominantly up stream of reasoning. Thus reward/punisher valuations are thought to register first in the orbitofrontal and after that in the dorsolateral prefrontal. A mass of medical evidence going all the way back to Phineas Gage shows that damage to the orbitofrontal makes it extremely difficult for patients to make any decision or have acceptable behaviour, although in conversation they are fully cognisant of what they need to do.\r\n\r\nThere is another joker in the pack, upstream of the dorsolateral, and that\'s the amygdala, that relic of our reptile past. The best example here is phobia where the signal by-passes the cortex, to get quickly to the amygdal, and then that\'s a place you really don\'t want to go. If you\'re phobic of snakes say, no amount of reasoning about it not being a non-poisonous variety is going to have any effect.\r\n\r\nTo come back to robots and the robot sensing the wall, I take it that you mean that it\'s like something for the robot to sense the wall. I can\'t disprove that, but is there any evidence for it. When an infra red bea, or whatever bounces of a wall, 1s and 0s and sikicon switches make its limbs or wheels move away from it. That looks to be fully described by classical (I mean macroscopic/non-quantum physics), so why do we need to inject consciousness. Kelvin pointed out more than a century that this type of physics was complete. The extensions to physics came in other kinds.\r\n\r\nReally, I think the problem is more serious than this, because I\'m not sure that this qualifies as a scientific theory. Can you suggest any experiement that would falsify the idea of this robot being conscious? I don\'t think things like the squirming of the alimentary canal are enough because here too classical description which contain no mention of consciousness gives a full explanation. On the other hand what I\'ve said about the orbitofrontal etc could be falsified in a laboratory at any moment, and certainly its very likley to be amended or added to in coming years.\r\n\r\nWhat I said about consciousness and rocks was somewhat self indulgent. The orbitofrontal speaking if you like. I\'d quite like conscious experience to extend down into the inanimate world, but I don\'t see hard evidence, and if there is evidence is likely to involve the quanta and spacetime, and that\'s a hard place, and always subject to what might come out of the Hadron Collider, I think it\'s easier to get there from the brain than the rocks.\r\n\r\nAs a last word, perhaps we should think where we\'re likeley to go if the rocks are conscious. A century ago Freud warned Jung to hold fast to Freudian theory because it was a sluice gate against the dark tide of the occult. How does the theory constrain this world? What comprises a conscious entity in this world? Is it a continuum or is a large rock a single conscious entity, and if that a (sacred) mountain, or the river Nile or Father Tiber, and beyond that the planets, not to speak of the primal manifesting as ghosts and spirits. I don\'t rule these things but if we go on like this I can see us, or a lot of people worshipping Artemis, the Earth upholder, who sits in the market place on the throne called fame.   \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-07-20 21:52:57','2011-07-20 21:52:57'),(1179,96,48,'Not wanting to go on too much, but I should have said something about the question of Persephone navigating into the bathroom.\r\n\r\nThe weight of evidence nowadays seems to point to motion being mainly non-conscious. Visual processing is known to comprise a ventral stream from primary visual to temporal cortex and a dorsal stream also from primary but to the parietal.\r\n\r\nStudies of patients with brain damage show that those with damage to the dorsal stream can consciously perceive objects but struggle to perform simple motions such as putting a letter in a post box. On the other those with sufficiently serious damage to ventral are blind for purposes of conscious perception, but can perform this type of action, at least better than chance.\r\n\r\nThese findings relate to the blindsight data where stroke or other damage has destroyed a part but not all of the conscious field. Patients again perform better than chance in identifying objects in the blind part of the field. It should be noted that the patients often have to be cajoled into taking the tests, because they regard it as so obvious that they can\'t see the objects.\r\n\r\nQuite a lot has also been said recently about the speed of reaction in professional sports. Libet showed that there\'s a 500 ms lag between stimuli and the stimuli coming into consciousness, which is too long if you want to respond to a serve in grand slam tennis.\r\n\r\nFurther to this recent scanning seems to suggest that a lot of the motor cortex is involved in consciousness, presumably in terms of the global gamma synchrony.\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-07-21 10:36:59','2011-07-21 10:36:59'),(1182,96,48,'Junius >>>>\r\n\r\nTo come back to robots and the robot sensing the wall, I take it that you mean that it\'s like something for the robot to sense the wall.\r\n\r\n<<<< Junius\r\n\r\nNo, not at all. I mean that when we see the walls of the room around us, we see all the walls in our visual field simultaneously and in parallel, as a three-dimensional structure, just like a museum diorama, or a theatre set. This structure was constructed in your brain based on sensory evidence.\r\n\r\nThe \"what it is like\" is a three-dimensional explicit extended spatial structure. Thats what *my* visual experience is like.\r\n\r\nIf an android is to have visual experience as we do, it must construct such a 3-D structure in its own mind. Now whether it uses the same color qualia as humans do is irrelevant, just as you can make a diorama out of wood or cardboard or plastic, or virtual structures made of patterns of electrons in a computer. Different creatures can use different media to express that spatial structure, but you have to build the structure in your awareness if you are to see the way humans do.\r\n\r\nJunius >>>>\r\n\r\nThe weight of evidence nowadays seems to point to motion being mainly non-conscious. Visual processing is known to comprise a ventral stream from primary visual to temporal cortex and a dorsal stream also from primary but to the parietal.\r\n\r\n<<<< Junius\r\n\r\nWow! Motion is mainly non-conscious? If electrophysiology \"proves\" that my motion is mainly non-conscious, then there is something seriously wrong with the interpretation of that evidence, because I for one know that *MY* motion is voluntary and under conscious control.\r\n\r\nAnd my conscious experience of planning a motor act, appears to me as a spatial field of attraction that seems to draw my (perceived) body in a specific direction in phenomenal space, and it is my conscious voluntary choice to either resist, or succumb to the desire to move in a particular direction, as explained in this portion of the Cartoon Epistemology...\r\n\r\nhttp://sharp.bu.edu/~slehar/cartoonepist/cartoonepist51L.html\r\n\r\nThe point is that many people overlook the vividly spatial aspect of both perception and motor planning, confused by the naive realist illusion that that structure is the world itself. Once you acknowledge the indisputable fact that everything we perceive is a picture in our head, then the vividly spatial nature of perception becomes obvious to everyone.','2011-07-25 16:15:13','2011-07-25 16:15:13'),(1185,96,48,'I should make it clear that I fully agree with you that the 3D picture in the head is just a brain state, and that the external world is nothing like that. I think that\'s something that we can say we know from physics. In fact, some physicists are arguing for  a 2D holographic world, which would make the brain states even more remote. Nothing I am saying here proceeds from so-called naive realism, although much of modern consciousness philosophy and psychology often looks to be at least unconsciously rooted in naive realism.\r\n\r\nThe question really is where you go from there. There\'s a weight of evidence to suggest that the 3D visual picture is not directly tied to the short-term ability to perform actions.\r\n\r\nThe Libet experiments showed that the readiness potentials for trivial actions arose before awareness of the conscious will to act, and the orthodoxy immediately seized on this a a proof of the non-existence of freewill of any kind.\r\n\r\nMost seem happy with that, but you mention planning and this looks to be where utilisation of visual perception, memory, thought and planning in the dorsolateral prefrontal come in, when dealing with longer term decisions on action. The Libet subjects and others in similar experiments were told to flexing their fingers or similar, but just given a choice of when to do it. So in effect the planning had been done in the experimenters consciousness.\r\n\r\nLibet himself was not fully in agreement with the interpretation put on his experiments. He proposed the idea of a \'free won\'t\', where the conscious mind can intervene to halt an undesirable action that is getting underway in the brain.\r\n\r\nRecently something like this has been discovered in the basal ganglia, which can interrupt actions in preparation. It\'s not really clear whether this is conscious or unconscious. The basal ganglia are subcortical, but are a sort of mixer tap upstream of action and behaviour, and have feed back to almost everything including the 3D picture in the visual temporal cortex, the dorsolateral (planning) and the orbitofrontal (reward evaluation).\r\n\r\nJunius\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\n','2011-08-02 12:07:21','2011-08-02 12:07:21'),(1188,96,48,'>>>>\r\n\r\nThe question really is where you go from there. There\'s a weight of evidence to suggest that the 3D visual picture is not directly tied to the short-term ability to perform actions.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nWow! That is so wildly incongruous with my own subjective experience.\r\n\r\nI see a 3-D world around me, parts of which call to me to satisfy my hunger or curiosity or call to duty, any of which can lead to short-term actions like getting myself a snack from the fridge, or paying a bill, or whatever.\r\n\r\nThe 3D visual picture is not directly tied to the short-term ability to perform actions???\r\n\r\nI just don\'t know where to begin to process that!\r\n\r\nWhere do you go from there? Now for that I have an answer. The next step is to figure out how a 2-D retinal image is expanded into a full 3-D volumetric picture in your mind.\r\n\r\nI have several proposals in that direction:\r\n\r\nThe Computational Mechanism of Visual Perception\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubw3/bubw3.html#compmech\r\n\r\nThe Constructive Aspect of Visual Perception\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/ConstructiveAspect/ConstructiveAspect.html','2011-08-03 12:34:00','2011-08-03 12:34:00'),(1191,96,48,'When we\'re talking of Libets\' experiments, we\'re talking really short term. The timing of flexing of a finger, when it has already been decided to make this movement. The sort of thing that\'s often done on auto pilot. The mainstream expanded this into a general determinism, but I\'ve never felt this is warranted.\r\n\r\nThe sort of thing you mention such as satisfying hunger from the fridge looks more like a conscious evaluation of the reward value of the food in the fridge linked to a 3D picture of the fridge and its food.\r\n\r\nI think the most people would agree that the processing that changes the 2D into a 3D image is unconscious. The hard problem is why it is like something to have our experience of the 3D image, our evaluation of the image (anticipated good taste of food etc) and the eventual reward value of actually eating it.  ','2011-08-06 17:16:04','2011-08-06 17:16:04'),(1194,96,48,'\r\nMind Theoreticians, \r\n\r\nJunius and I are still working on an improved draft of the above\r\nstatement which we hope will this time avoid being objected to by\r\nanyone. In addition to making, or at least moving towards, some of the\r\nrequested improvements, we\'ve also been improving the idea of \'effing\'\r\nof the ineffable which isn\'t described very well in the above version\r\nthat was objected to. \r\n\r\nBasically, there are 3 types of effing. The first weak version is: this\r\ntheory predicts we will be able to reliably know whatever it is that\r\nhas redness in my brain, and be able to objectively observe such in\r\nother\'s brains, (it may be their green) and in this way eff to them my\r\nredness. The problem with this weak way is, if we seek to eff a quale\r\nto a person which has never experienced it before, or if the person\'s\r\nbrain doesn\'t have the required stuff and/or configuration to\r\nexperience it, then some type of brain augmentation is required, to eff\r\nany such new qualia. Any such augmentation of the brain, and then\r\nthrowing the switch to turn it on, to which someone might respond: \'oh\r\nTHAT is what it is like to be a bat\' would be this second type of\r\neffing. Such a demonstration by science would clearly falsify Nagal\'s\r\nfamous assertion that it is impossible to know what it is like to be a\r\nbat, right? \r\n\r\nFinally, there is a 3rd type, the one First Proposed by V.S.\r\nRamachandran, where we connect minds together via \'bundles of neurons\'\r\nand so on, that can do what the corpus callosum can do.... This third\r\ntype is a much stronger type of effing of the ineffable, since it can\r\nconnect minds in such a way that both brains are experiencing the same\r\nwhatever it has that has the same quale. (for an interesting example of\r\nhow minds can be merged, where knowledge of two separate and\r\nindependent spirits can share the same phenomenal knowledge of the\r\nworld space, both seeing out of the other\'s eyes, and so on, see\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YWDsXa5nNbI surely they each know what\r\nthe others \'redness\' is like and in fact both experience the same\r\nredness) \r\n\r\nThe first two types of effing, do not provably resolve the\r\nphilosophical \"problem of other minds\", they only move in that\r\ndirection. While the 3rd type of effing, if demonstrated, absolutely\r\nproves and resolves the issue. Such would also absolutely falsify such\r\nphilosophies as idealism, and make it near impossible to rationally\r\nbelieve in most current religious views of spirituality and \'spirits\'\r\nthat consciousness exist independent of a brain... \r\n\r\nSo, anyway, consider this post a validating survey of everyone. If\r\nanyone does not agree that \'Representational Qualia Theory\' predicts\r\nall 3 types of effing will eventually be achieved or demonstrated by\r\nscience, and that demonstrating the 3rd strong type will absolutely\r\nresolve the problem of other minds, absolutely falsify philosophies\r\nlike \'idealism\' and so on, or if you would object to statements\r\ndescribing such being added to the \"Representational Qualia Theory\"\r\ncamp, make sure you speak up. \r\n\r\nBrent Allsop \r\n','2011-08-22 04:29:23','2011-08-22 04:29:23'),(1195,1,37,'\r\n\r\nJohn, \r\n\r\nBrent has encouraged me to post a camp that is quite similar to yours\r\nexcept that the source of the consciousness module is not a brane but\r\nrather the Calabi-Yau Compact Manifold subspace. He also suggests that\r\nboth our camps be sub to a Higher Dimensional camp which he will\r\ninstall if you approve. \r\n\r\nHere is my proposed camp: \r\n\r\nCYR hypothesis of phenomenal consciousness \r\n\r\nThe Calabi-Yau-Ruquist (CYR) hypothesis of phenomenal consciousness is\r\na version of material dualism based on the Calabi-Yau Compact Manifold\r\nof compactified dimensions in string theory. In essence it corresponds\r\nto the Smythies-Carr (CS) hypothesis but with the CS source for\r\nconsciousness, i.e., a brane parallel to the brane of the physical\r\nworld, replaced by an invisible subspace of nature with remarkable\r\nproperties. \r\n\r\nThis universal subspace contains a 3D array of string-theory Calabi-Yau\r\n(CY) elements, numbering 10^90 per cc, due to the compactification of 6\r\ndimensions as 3 dimensions expanded in the Big Bang. In this\r\nrepresentation, consciousness is based on the hypothesis that a natural\r\nsystem which mimics the mathematics of natural numbers (like Peano\r\narithmetic) will have a universal property (like energy in a\r\nthermodynamic system) called consciousness. \r\n\r\nGiven that there are 10^500 distinct CY elements according to string\r\ntheory, that is more than enough for every CY element in the universe\r\nto be distinct. And given astronomical observations that the\r\nfine-structure constant varies monotonically across the universe, the\r\nCY elements are likely ordered. So in this system concept consciousness\r\nis emergent from an arithmetical subspace. \r\n\r\nAnother remarkable property of this subspace is that because the CY\r\nelements are motionless, they form a frictionless Bose-Einstein\r\nCondensate(BEC), where information can be transmitted instantly. In\r\nstring theory elements of this subspace also contain the laws of\r\nphysics and they collectively control particle interactions. This is\r\ntherefore also a candidate for the God canonizer. \r\n\r\nFrom the Stanford Philosophy site: \"The leading contemporary version of\r\nthe Representational Theory of Mind, the Computational Theory of Mind\r\n(CTM), claims that the brain is a kind of computer and that mental\r\nprocesses are computations. According to CTM, cognitive states are\r\nconstituted by computational relations to mental representations of\r\nvarious kinds, and cognitive processes are sequences of such states.\" \r\n\r\nOur hypothesis is closer to a branch of computationalism that\r\n(following Godel) claims that consciousness emerging from Peano\r\nArithmetic in turn can create energy and matter like in the Big Bang,\r\ni.e., \r\n\r\nNATURAL NUMBERS => CONSCIOUSNESS => ENERGY=> MATTER => HUMAN => HUMAN\r\nREPRESENTATION \r\n\r\nBut that is not a necessary evolutionary path for a representational\r\nstring theory of consciousness where downward causation continually\r\ninteracts with upward consciousness to create an inner self within the\r\nmental representation of outside and internal worlds of independent\r\nmatter and energy, i.e., \r\n\r\nNATURAL NUMBERS => CONSCIOUSNESS => DOWNWARD CAUSATION => HUMAN\r\nREPRESENTATION \r\n\r\nDownward causation is key to the whole process providing for\r\nself-referential feedback loops and of course for thinking based on\r\nintention. Ruquist proposes that BEC entanglement between different\r\nlevels of consciousness allows for feedback looping. Here, like in\r\nGodelÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s derivation of the Incompleteness Theorems, the math includes\r\ncomplexity levels or stages of proof from the most fundamental level of\r\nthe natural numbers through a hierarchy of ever more general states (46\r\nfor the Incompleteness theorems). \r\n\r\nDownward causation then refers to higher states being able to\r\nmanipulate the configuration of entangled lower states. Likewise,\r\nphysical waking consciousness may be entangled with the mind\r\nrepresentation allowing intention to operate across their boundaries.\r\nWe do not postulate a mechanism for intention. Ref:\r\nhttp://vixra.org/abs/1101.0044 \r\n','2011-08-22 05:00:23','2011-08-22 05:00:23'),(1196,1,37,'Dear John,\r\n\r\nBrent encourages me to post my string theory consciousness model on the canonizer. This model is equivalent to yours except that the consciousness module is the Calabi-Yau compact-manifold subspace instead of a brane. Brent further proposes to make the Higher Dimensional camp contain both your model and mine on an equal level- all with your permission of course. \r\nHere is a description of my camp. Richard Ruquist\r\n\r\nCYR hypothesis of phenomenal consciousness\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Calabi-Yau-Ruquist (CYR) hypothesis of phenomenal consciousness is a version of material dualism based on the Calabi-Yau Compact Manifold of compactified dimensions in string theory. In essence it corresponds to the Smythies-Carr (CS) hypothesis but with the CS source for consciousness, i.e., a brane parallel to the brane of the physical world, replaced by an invisible subspace of nature with remarkable properties. \r\n\r\nThis universal subspace contains a 3D array of string-theory Calabi-Yau (CY) elements, numbering 10^90 per cc, due to the compactification of 6 dimensions as 3 dimensions expanded in the Big Bang. In this representation, consciousness is based on the hypothesis that a natural system which mimics the mathematics of natural numbers (like Peano arithmetic) will have a universal property (like energy in a thermodynamic system) called consciousness.\r\n\r\nGiven that there are 10^500 distinct CY elements according to string theory, that is more than enough for every CY element in the universe to be distinct. And given astronomical observations that the fine-structure constant varies monotonically across the universe, the CY elements are likely ordered. So in this system concept consciousness is emergent from an arithmetical subspace.\r\n\r\nAnother remarkable property of this subspace is that because the CY elements are motionless, they form a frictionless Bose-Einstein Condensate(BEC), where information can be transmitted instantly. In string theory elements of this subspace also contain the laws of physics and they collectively control particle interactions. This is therefore also a candidate for the God canonizer.\r\n\r\nFrom the Stanford Philosophy site: \"The leading contemporary version of the Representational Theory of Mind, the Computational Theory of Mind (CTM), claims that the brain is a kind of computer and that mental processes are computations. According to CTM, cognitive states are constituted by computational relations to mental representations of various kinds, and cognitive processes are sequences of such states.\"\r\n\r\nOur hypothesis is closer to a branch of computationalism that (following Godel) claims that consciousness emerging from Peano Arithmetic in turn can create energy and matter like in the Big Bang, i.e., \r\n\r\nNATURAL NUMBERS => CONSCIOUSNESS => ENERGY=> MATTER => HUMAN => HUMAN REPRESENTATION\r\n\r\nBut that is not a necessary evolutionary path for a representational string theory of consciousness where downward causation continually interacts with upward consciousness to create an inner self within the mental representation of outside and internal worlds of independent matter and energy, i.e.,\r\n\r\nNATURAL NUMBERS => CONSCIOUSNESS => DOWNWARD CAUSATION => HUMAN REPRESENTATION\r\n\r\nDownward causation is key to the whole process providing for self-referential feedback loops and of course for thinking based on intention. Ruquist proposes that BEC entanglement between different levels of consciousness allows for feedback looping. Here, like in Godelâ€™s derivation of the Incompleteness Theorems, the math includes complexity levels or stages of proof from the most fundamental level of the natural numbers through a hierarchy of ever more general states (46 for the Incompleteness theorems). \r\n\r\nDownward causation then refers to higher states being able to manipulate the configuration of entangled lower states. Likewise, physical waking consciousness may be entangled with the mind representation allowing intention to operate across their boundaries. We do not postulate a mechanism for intention.\r\nRef: http://vixra.org/abs/1101.0044\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-08-22 11:47:03','2011-08-22 11:47:03'),(1199,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nAs Simon and I continue our work on the new version of the Representational Qualia Theory statement we branched out into a discussion on whether qualia are or could be based on classical, vs non classical (quantum?) physics/phenomenon.  Simon pointed out that the original \'classical\' theories were billiard ball\'s bouncing into each other, according to classical laws of physics.  This was turning into a very educational conversation for me.  The idea of thinking of this using classical billiard balls really crystallized many of my thoughts, and I wanted to open this conversation up to the public, here, in hopes of getting more input from everyone.  The following is the way I think about all this, and I\'d like to know what all of you think about thinking of phenomenal properties in this kind of classical billiard ball way.\r\n\r\nSimon mentioned he thought the difference between \"something has qualia\" vs \"qualia arise from something\" as merely \"a bit of a meaning of words thing\".  But I think there is a subtle difference between these that is critically important to clearly understand and fully model.  While talking of redness, Simon said: \"We can certainly agree that the surface of the strawberries don\'t have it.\"  From this he continued on even further with neuronal \"Oscillations in electrical potential do not have redness. Our science gives a full description in that respect.\" and this is where it seems to me things have completely fallen off the track - at least according to the way I currently think of things.\r\n\r\nIt is true that we can both agree that \'redness\' is not a property of the strawberry.  But, we must also acknowledge the very real possibility that the surface of the strawberry does have phenomenal properties.  As far as \"oscillations in electrical potential\", these are abstracted words describing the causal properties of electrical potentials of certain sets of matter.  These words are mere interpretations of what all is really going on and there is a very real possibility that these types of abstracted words are being miss-interpreted when thinking they do not representing something that could have phenomenal properties.  Causal properties of matter are categorically different than phenomenal properties, and this is clearly making the classic mistake of failing to distinguish between the two.  In my mind, it is a very real possibility that this stuff does have phenomenal properties, we are just still blind to these properties, or it would be better to say, we could be simply misinterpreting what these \"oscillation in electrical potential\" are phenomenally like and what all phenomenal properties such might additionally include.\r\n\r\nTo better get at this idea, I\'d like to consider a possibility of how classic billiard balls could have phenomenal properties, and how these properties would be categorically different than their causal properties, and how their phenomenal properties could be miss interpreted.  In this thought experiment, let\'s consider a 3D array of neurons that can each represent or model voxel elements of a 3D volume of space we can see.  Say we have a cube of 1000 X 1000 X 1000 such neurons.  Each of these neurons can communicate with their neighbors and the dendrites of neurons organized in hierarchical layers of neural networks capable of pattern recognition, leading out of the 3D matrix and providing the hierarchical cognitive meaning of what we are seeing.\r\n\r\nLet\'s model this communication interaction as being accomplished by the neurons firing billiard balls at their neighbors, across synapses.  Let\'s pick 2 neurotransmitters at random as example possibilities, such as glutamate and glycine.  Let\'s say our number 1 billiard balls are made of glutamate and number 2 billiard balls are made of glycine.  In this thought experiment when a neuron fires number one billiard balls at its neighbors, the absorption of it is experienced as that voxel element of visual space having the property of redness.  Let\'s say when number 2 billiard balls are fired, we experience a greenness at that location.  The most important part of this \'classical\' system, is that it is just that.  Everything about it, is nothing more than the classical cause and effect operation of synapses we\'ve been observing for the longest time.\r\n\r\nNow, let\'s say we take a bunch of number one billiard balls, and shine some light on them.  Let\'s say the number one balls have a causal property in that they reflect yellow light.  And the number 2 balls causally reflect blue light just like normal 1 and 2 billiard balls that are yellow and blue respectively.  Of course, if we say we know everything, causally, about the number one balls, and claim that redness isn\'t one of their properties, we are obviously completely miss interpreting the causal information we are getting or we are blind to what is most important.  If we say these number one balls have yellowness, simply since they reflect yellow light and we represent their color with yellow knowledge, we are at least getting closer.  Now the only remaining issue required to correctly eff the ineffable, is to get the interpretation right.  Rather than thinking the balls are phenomenally like what we represent them with, we must experiment with, discover and reliably map all this out appropriately, according to how we reliably experience them, so we can properly interpret the number one balls that reflect yellow light as having phenomenal redness, and the number 2 balls that reflect blue light as being experienced as having greenness.\r\n\r\nOf course, phenomenal reality is not anywhere near this simple, just as classical physics is quite a bit more than simple billiard balls bouncing around.  But thinking of classical physics as something like billiard balls bouncing around gives one a powerful intuitive insight into the nature of classical physics.  Similarly, thinking of effing of the ineffable in this simplified classical way, helps one gain an intuitive knowledge of what it might mean to eff, ineffable properties of stuff and how it could be done classically, not requiring any physical weirdness or uncertainty.\r\n\r\nLet\'s get back to the subtle difference of saying things like \"something has qualia\" vs \"qualia arise from something\".  Let\'s also consider similar possible differences between explaining qualia vs discovering qualia.  If you want to \'explain\' how we perceive the strawberry patch, you paint or construct the 3d volume space with things that have phenomenal properties.  This conscious phenomenal knowledge of the strawberry patch arises from, or can be reduced to, the pallet of myriads of individual phenomenal colors and feels we can experienced in our 3d visual knowledge.  But, at the fundamental level, there are irreducible elements that have irreducible phenomenal properties that aren\'t explained and don\'t arise from anything, they are simply the fundamental phenomenal building block properties which can be unified together to produce what consciousness is phenomenally like.  You don\'t explain these fundamental irreducible properties as arising from anything, they simply are to be discovered and most importantly, properly interpreted as such.  Something like this is what you build consciousness out of, and what it can be reduced to.  As long as we consider phenomenal properties as not being among all the causal properties we interpret stuff as having, or thinking they somehow arises from them, we are clearly being blind to and ignoring what they could be phenomenally like.\r\n\r\nSo, what does everyone think?  Is this kind of classic effing thinking worthy of including in Representational Qualia Theory?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2011-09-15 02:56:16','2011-09-15 02:56:16'),(1202,96,48,'Doesn\'t the billard ball analysis belong in the mind-brain identity camp?','2011-09-15 11:33:49','2011-09-15 11:33:49'),(1205,96,48,'The operative thing here is the claim that we are blind to the phenomenal properties of oscillations in electrical potential or possibly the transmission of amino acids between neurons.\r\n\r\nIn looking at this, we need to confront the strengths and weaknesses of classical physics. Its weakness is mainly the failure to yield a theory of consciousness that leaves enquirers generally happy. Its strengths should be seen as something of a wonder in that classical physics plus quanta understood in a more or less classical way explain the behaviour of macroscopic matter in a manner that entirely eluded all previous generations. Because of the very small scale to which more than a century of very exhaustive experimentation has penetrated the chances of finding some classical feature in or attached to electrical oscillations and amino acids is so remote as to be not worth considering. If we are blind to something phenomenal in these then we should admit that we\'re probably looking at something supernatural and learn to live with that.\r\n\r\nThe other thing I would ask is why it\'s so difficult to think about consciousness in terms of the quantum or spacetime levels. I do think this is a cultural problem inflicted on us by mainstream science. The discoveries of quantum theory early in the last century contradicted the concepts of what appeared to be an almost complete classical theory. The response to this was essentially \'don\'t bother your pretty little head with this.\' Quantum theory was marginalised as an abstruse calculation used for certain special cases, whereas the truth was that it described the fundamental nature of matter and energy. Quantum theory was largely excluded from popular knowledge and education even science education. The evil consequence of this was that it gradually seeped out in the late 20th century as a word that could be attached to almost any claim, which in turn allowed the mainstream to ridicule and marginalise the whole area. But the fact is that the theory and its interrelation with spacetime theory are central to understanding our universe.\r\n\r\nSimon\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-09-15 17:03:43','2011-09-15 17:03:43'),(1208,96,48,'\r\nHi John Clem,\r\n\r\nAh, yes, of course.  Now that you remind me, it probably really doesn\'t belong at the Representational Qualia level at all.  Possibly not even at the mind brain identity theory?  Do any of you leading consensus at that level \"Functional Property Dualism dudes\" think there is any validity to this billiard ball idea?\r\n\r\nIt\'s amazing how I completely blank out all the other theories I\'m trying so hard to learn about and keep track of with this system.  Does anyone else have problems loosing track of other theories like this?  Thanks so much for taking the effort to point this out and remind me.\r\n\r\nJunius and I are currently both in the Material Property Dualism super camp, way below that level, yet it is appearing that it doesn\'t even belong at that level.  In fact, is there any other person besides me that thinks this classical billiard ball theory is a possibility, or yet to be falsified?\r\n\r\nJunius was asking why it\'s so difficult to think about consciousness in terms of the quantum.  I would reply that it is not.  In my mind, It is definitely a very real possibility, and one of the only camps I think is not yet completely falsified.  After all, I am also a supporter of the Orch OR camp, secondarily, after my current Macro Property Dualism first choice (probably where the billiard ball stuff goes?).\r\n\r\nJunious, how can we best capture our differences of beliefs, and get this canonized or represented in both of our camps, so we can rigorously measure for how many people, if any, agree with either of us?\r\n\r\nI think it should be very clearly represented, that we both agree that quantum is a very real possibility, and I understand at least some of the good arguments that support this view.\r\n\r\nJunius, you say: \"Its weakness is mainly the failure to yield a theory of consciousness that leaves enquirers generally happy.\"  I disagree with this, and think this is the primary disagreement?  I see a very real possibility that classical stuff, in addition to having the regular classical cause and effect behavioral properties, could also have phenomenal properties.  Our perception process can even see this, it\'s just that we are still obviously miss interpreting what they are phenomenally like, as described when we think the number one billiard ball is like \'yellowness\' just because we interpret it as being yellow, and represent it with such.  When in reality it is like redness.\r\n\r\nI also think you are making a mistake when you say: \"If we are blind to something phenomenal in these then we should admit that we\'re probably looking at something supernatural and learn to live with that.\"\r\n\r\nEven if there is some magic or spark, down at the quantum level, you will still eternally be faced with the same identical problem, no matter how quantumly deep and mystical it becomes.  Causally, you\'ll be able to observe the spark, randomness, or whatever, but you could still be miss interpreting that spark\'s causal properties as yellowness, when it is really redness, right?\r\n\r\nIf science demonstrably proves anything like the billiard ball simplification, and achieves the ability to eff the true nature of whatever classical, or quantum stuff it is in our brain that has redness, and so on, then it will completely falsify your theory right?  And anyone that once would consider themselves as not satisfied with any such explanation, must then be completely satisfied in the Billiard Ball camp, once they experience for themselves, what it is like, and they know how  to properly interpret what they are causally observing, right?\r\n\r\nThanks for all the conversations, everyone.  All your participation helps immensely!\r\n\r\nSo, one final query.  Does anyone else besides me believe this billiard ball theory is a real possibility yet to be falsified, and worthy of consideration?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2011-09-16 03:51:55','2011-09-16 03:51:55'),(1211,96,48,'I am a bit alarmed at the idea that we are launching a new billiard ball theory. The reference to billiard balls is simply a widely used image for how classical physics works. It also neatly contains the idea of a complete explanation for the behaviour of macroscopic objects. The purpose of science is to explain behaviour in the universe and in respect of the macroscopic world, classical physics is completely succesful. As Laplace, I think, is supposed to said to Napoleon, there was no place for the concept of a God. Any addition to the properties of classical/billiard ball type particles puts one completely outside of science. In classical physics, you can run but you can\'t hide. This is the reason that the serried ranks of biologists, neuroscientists and reductionist philosophers think they can be so dismissive of consciousness. The suggestion that people are generally happy with this, if I read that right is surprising. Surely the very existence of this site indicates a lack of general happiness. Would we expend as much effort debating weights on a pulley or steam pressure in a boiler?\r\n\r\nThere is an issue in terms of what our perception process can see. We know we are conscious or that it is like something to have the perception of red strawberries. For many this defeats the strange \'qualia don\'t exist\' argument, but I can\'t see the fact of perception tells us anything about how it arises or if you prefer what it is. Science has narrowed the field of search a bit. It\'s not a property of the strawberries, it does correlate to brain states. Beyond that it\'s so far not possible to say what it does derive from.\r\n\r\nI think the issue about your yellow being my red is scientifically interesting but not the core question, which is why it is like something to perceive red strawberries, green leaves or anything else.\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n  ','2011-09-16 09:56:56','2011-09-16 09:56:56'),(1214,96,48,'Hi Junius,\r\n\r\nHelp me understand why or what you are alarmed about.  You and John Clem have clearly helped me know that this doesn\'t belong at the Representational Qualia level, so I\'m 100% supportive of that consensus.  The higher level, more well supported theories are the most important and where everyone should focus most of their effort.  So getting that right, according to consensus, is where I think we should go.  Perhaps you could send me (and anyone else who requests such) the latest draft of the updated Representational Qualia Theory statement?  I\'m sure what you have now is, if not all ready great for submission, very close, to what we all agree on.\r\n\r\nAfter we get that successfully submitted, I might consider adding some of this clasic qualia billiard ball stuff to my camp, since I still seem to be the only one supporting such.  Does your alarm have anything to do with this, and my inquiries along these lines about how best to capture what you and I believe, and how our beliefs differ, at this very low sub camp level?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2011-09-17 19:52:22','2011-09-17 19:52:22'),(1215,1,5,'\r\nFolks,\r\n\r\nWe desperately need a statement for the yes camp.\r\n\r\nI propose something like the statement included below.  I would appreciate any and all input into the development of this statement.\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n==============\r\n\r\n\r\nThe mother is the primary creator of a baby.  As long as the baby is dependent on the mother, it can be considered as owned by the mother as her creation, and the mother should have absolute decision power over it, at least until the baby is able to survive on its own, surely which would include once the baby has been born.\r\n\r\nWe dismiss any other superior claims of creation, such as that God created a baby, and any justification of overriding authority of what the mother wants, as invalid and immoral.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-09-17 22:42:20','2011-09-17 22:42:20'),(1216,131,52,'I\'ve already read 2 of Daniel Dennett\'s books but he remains too general about the statement supported in this camp. Can someone link me to some resource which goes deeper into the theory that what we call mind or thoughts as they looks are only illusory?\r\n\r\nThanks','2011-09-19 10:48:19','2011-09-19 10:48:19'),(1217,131,52,'I\'d love to, except for a couple of things.\r\n\r\n1. Half the time I can\'t even log onto the system\r\n\r\n2. I haven\'t published too much about them lately.\r\n\r\nYou can access me directly via e-mail @ grysmith@telus.net or I am currently active on www.researchgate.net\r\n\r\nMy main thesis in this group, is that consciousness is a specialized control system that creates the illusion of a \"Self\" mostly by linking the \"Self\" feeling, which is associated with attribution, to the actions of the individual as experienced during review of an activity log, implying attribution, and at the same time, creating the \"illusion of consciousness\". That this \"Illusion of Consciousness\" is experienced as a phenomena, blocks the acceptance of the Neurological search for brain function, because it is the subjective experience (The illusion) that the illusion is more real than the scientific explanation. \r\n\r\nIn fact, in order to meet the feedback requirements, I postulate the need for two action logs, the raw log of experience called the \"Awareness Log\" and the cooked log, where \"Feelings\" including the \"Self\" feeling, parameterize our experience, giving us a final 9th step in processing as we respond to the \"Comfort Requirements\" of our own self-model. Since our Comfort is directly related to the limits we have developed mostly during early childhood, the self-model is an important sophistication to the libido, that is often directly responsible for the parameters of our personality, and any illness associated with it.\r\n\r\n','2011-09-20 12:13:24','2011-09-20 12:13:24'),(1218,1,54,'\r\nSupporters this panexperientialism camp,\r\n\r\nIt is my belief that most everyone, including the supporters of this camp, agrees that \"Panexperientialism\" is in agreement with the general ideas described in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 \"Representational Qualia Theory\"] camp.\r\n\r\nTowards that end, so the survey better represents this fact, I propose moving this supportive of those ideas camp into a supportive position under that camp.\r\n\r\nI plan to do this move in the next few days, so if anyone thinks this is not right, or if you plan to object to such, please let us know here so we can understand why, and so we can discuss the possibility that we might need to fork this the camp to represent those that think it is in agreement with Representational Qualia Theory, and those that do not.\r\n\r\nThanks\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2011-10-02 21:30:44','2011-10-02 21:30:44'),(1219,1,51,'\r\nHello supporters of this \"Absolute Space Consciousness\" camp.\r\n\r\nIt is my understanding that this camp is supportive of the general theory known as \'pan psychism\'  In fact, it even states this in the first line of the statement.\r\n\r\nThe current location of the camp in the structure does not accurately reflect this fact.  So I propose moving this camp into a supporting sub camp position of this [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/34 panexperientialism] camp to accurately reflect this consensus.\r\n\r\nI plan on making this change sometime in the next week.  If any of you think this is not a good move, please let us know why, so we can discuss other possibilities to better represent the current consensus.\r\n\r\nThanks\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-10-02 21:36:23','2011-10-02 21:36:23'),(1222,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nCongratulation, on the work by everyone, and for the fact that the new Representational Qualia Theory statement was finally accepted by all and went live!  All the other camps are also developing in very dramatic ways that is extremely exciting.  I\'m working on a press announcement to capture some of this and send out to as many places as I can, to point out what we have accomplished so far.  I\'d appreciate any feedback on any of this.\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n============================\r\n\r\n= Scientific consensus continues to extend its dramatic lead amongst competing theories of consciousness. =\r\n\r\nWe\'ve been continuing a sometimes slow and laborious survey process for several years now.  We\'ve been attending conferences, finding and interviewing experts in this field so that we might \'canonize\' their views to measure and build as much consensus as possible around the best theories as part of the Consciousness Survey Project.  The current body of \"peer reviewed\" work, and other surveys, seems to do nothing but confirm everyone\'s pervasive beliefs that there is no expert consensus in this field whatsoever.  As everyone knows everyone regularly mocks the field, and its complete lack of any significant results as mere \"philosophies of men\".  However, the consensus building, amplification of the wisdom of the crowd open survey system at canonizer.com might be about to falsify this pervasive belief that consciousness is so \"hard\" and that it is only almost approachable via a very few super brains.  The dramatic early consensus emerging and extending its lead seems to be indicating there may already be a huge amount of agreement on a great many fairly simple things, in this theoretical field of science, after all.\r\n\r\nFor the last 6 months, the participating experts in the consensus camp have been collaboratively developing and negotiating a new version of the camp statement concisely describing what most of the experts appear to already agree on.  It\'s not easy getting this much consensus from this many diverse experts, such has never been achieved in the past, but it is now being proved possible if you have the right techniques, such as the ability to push lesser important disagreeable ideas out of the way, into sub camps, instead of exclusively focusing only on them.  This new super camp statement, after months of negotiation, finally just recently made it through the unanimous canonization review process.  In addition to answering the question of where redness is located  (It is not a property of the strawberry, but of our knowledge of it)  it includes the description of the \"Quale Interpretation Problem\" which is a technical description of why ineffable properties are blind to traditional cause and effect observation.  It also includes predictions of various possible ways scientists will be able to get around this problem to \'eff\' these ineffable properties and finally resolve the many long standing issues such as \"the problem of other minds\"\', \"what it is like to be a bat\", possibly even falsifying \"Idealism\", \"Solipsism\", \"Skepticism\", and so on. (see the early consensus camp at: http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 )\r\n\r\nThe highest top super camp in the main survey topic addresses whether or not consciousness is approachable via science.  So far, about 29 of the 35 participants are in this super camp with only a few brave souls willing to put their reputation on the line and support competing camps such as: \"Consciousness is of Divine Origin and Unfathomable Apart from God\".\r\n\r\nAt the next level down, very surprisingly, with almost as much consensus, is the recently named \"Representational Qualia Theory\" camp.  When we first started this survey, we thought there would be many significant competitors to this camp such as simple \"Computational Functionalism\", \"we don\'t have qualia, it just seems like we do\", \"idealism\", \"you can\'t eff the ineffable\"  and so on.  At least, that is what the wikipedia article on qualia (falsely?) leads one to believe.  Despite our continued best efforts to recruit experts to support any such competing camps, and make the survey more comprehensive, it is surprising how it seems that so far nobody is willing to stand up and make any effort to support any of them at anywhere near the rate, compared to the many emerging experts which are already so willing to support this new qualophile \"Representational Qualia Theory\".\r\n\r\nThe early consensus seems to be indicating there is significant consensus about WHERE redness, and all the other phenomenal properties consciousness is composed of are located.  The only remaining yet to be falsified issue, at least for the experts appear to be the WHATs and HOWs of redness.  At the sub camp levels below this consensus camp, some dramatic theories are forming about these WHATs and HOWs.  The best of them are making obviously falsifiable predictions about just what science is about to discover and how it will validate each theory to the falsification of all competitors.\r\n\r\nThe clear consensus continues at the next sub level with the Mind-Brain Identity theory camp leading against some significant competitors such as Higher-dimension Theories (including the Smythies Carr Hypothosis) and Panexperientialism.\r\n\r\nAt the next level down the current consensus is far less clear and far more dramatic.  The early and still holding on to its lead camp is the one led by David Chalmers, or \"Functional Property Dualism\".  Its principle doctrine is Chalmers\' \"Invariance Principle\" which holds that the same quale can \"arise\"  in some \"hard\" way from any equivalent functional isomorph, from silicon to neurons, or anything that can do Turing computation.  This theory is basically falsifiably predicting you will be able to reliably know when you are observing redness when you observe the right functionality.\r\n\r\nBut a rapidly gaining camp appears to be on the verge of overtaking this consensus camp at this sub level.  This is the \"Material Property Dualism\" camp which basically predicts that redness is simply a property of some material in the brain.  It predicts that without this right stuff which has these phenomenal properties, you can\'t have redness.  And if you observe the right stuff, in the right neural correlate state, you will reliably know, in an effing way, what the person is experiencing.\r\n\r\nThis emerging camp further breaks down into the newest to be canonized and obviously very popular sub \"Orchestrated Object Reduction\" camp lead by Stuart Hameroff and Roger Penrose.  The lesser competitor is \"Macro Property Dualism\" which predicts phenomenal properties can just as easily be a property of any classical object, possibly some kind of standing wave of neural firing, even possibly a set of classical bouncing \'billiard balls\', and that no quantum weirdness or any magic is required to discover or eff the ineffable.  All that is required is proper communication, and thinking about it in the right way, to know what where and how to look for it.\r\n\r\nOf course, we continue to seek to make the survey more comprehensive in the open survey wiki way.  Whether you are an expert (see: http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/53/11 ) or not, we seek to measure and compare it all.  Even high school students have been making significant contributions to this amplification of the wisdom of the crowd process.  Perhaps there is a much better way to organize the existing structure?  If so, it can all be accommodated, according to the will of the scientific consensus.  So if you feel there is a justified theory that could turn out to be the one validated by science, please help us get such \'canonized\' for the benefit of everyone.  There are volunteers ready to help integrate, or canonize your ideas into what has already been built.  Help us sooner get to what could turn out to be the greatest scientific achievement of all time:  The demonstrable discovery and agreement of what, where, and how the conscious mind is.\r\n\r\nAs always, our goal is to rigorously capture and measure, in real time, when the demonstrable science validates the one theory and falsifies all others.  When this revolution does take place, we hope to be able to see it very definitively and undeniably, here, as the experts start to abandon the finally falsified camps.  It appears that at least at some level, this could have already started in a revolutionary and dramatic way, likely in a more dramatic way than when we finally switched from a geocentric solar system view.\r\n\r\n','2011-10-12 05:05:52','2011-10-12 05:05:52'),(1225,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nI\'m preparing an abstract for submission to next year\'s Towards a Science of Consciousness conference.  (see: [http://www.consciousness.arizona.edu/ http://www.consciousness.arizona.edu/] )  I\'ve met many of you at TSC 2010 and I\'m hoping many more of you are interested in attending in 2012.  I\'m also seeking anyone interested in lending their name, as a co-author, or co-participator in this consciousness survey project.  The more of your names we can include as authors, the more chance we have of getting accepted.  Even if you won\'t be able to attend, I\'d still like to attach your name as a volunteer participator / co-author in this project.  So, please, any and all of you willing to have your name as a co-author, please contact me!  Hopefully, we can get them to pay some or all of our way there to present this exciting work you\'ve all contributed to???\r\n\r\nBelow is a current version of a draft of the 500 word abstract I\'m working on.  I\'d love to have any feedback on it.\r\n\r\nUpwards,  Brent Allsop\r\n\r\n==================\r\n\r\nRigorously building and measuring for scientific consensus.\r\n\r\nTowards our goal of rigorously building and measuring for scientific consensus on theories of consciousness, for several years now volunteers have been attending conferences, contacting, interviewing, surveying for and \'canonizing\' experts views as part of the Consciousness Survey Project.  We are using the all volunteer driven, crowd sourced wiki with camps based bottom up survey system being developed at canonizer.com.  The primary survey topic being \"Theories of mind and Consciousness\" (see: http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88 ).\r\n\r\nThe diverse set of current publications, and previous attempts at surveys to date, all seem to support the pervasive belief that there is no expert consensus on much of anything in this field.  While the results with the Consciousness Survey Project are still far from comprehensive, there already appears that there could be a significant amount of consensus, after all, on a great many things in this field.  To date no consensus statement has been possible where this many diverse experts have signed on as unanimously agreeing to it.\r\n\r\nThe current consensus clearly indicates the most fundamental issue is whether consciousness is approachable via science or not.  Currently, about 32 of the 35 participators agree that it is.  At the next level down, shockingly, there is almost as much consensus around what the experts recently unanimously agreed to call \"Representational Qualia Theory\".  There is obviously clear expert consensus on many issues concisely stated at this level such as where redness is located (not on the surface of the strawberry) and about the \"Quale Interpretation Problem\" describing why redness is ineffable and predictions of how this problem can be overcome.  Below this are various competing theories about just what redness is including the leading \"Mind-Brain Identity\" camp.  Finally at this level some significantly supported competing camps start to appear such as \"Higher-dimensional Theories\" and \"Panexperientialism\".\r\n\r\nThings start to get very interesting at the next level down, where David Chalmers\' \"Functional Property Dualism\" started out with a significant lead, but there is a clear contender, quickly emerging and appears on the verge of overtaking the consensus at this level.  This is the \"Material Property Dualism\" camp.  Where Chalmers predicts if you have the right \'functionality\', regardless of if it is neurons or computer chips, you will get redness, Material Property dualists are predicting the right material is what has redness, and without it, no redness.\r\n\r\nThis emerging camp includes Hameroff\'s Orch OR theory, which predicts some quantum magic is required to experience redness and a lessor camp which predicts phenomenal properties can just as easily be a property of any classical non quantum object, possibly some kind of standing wave of neural firing, even possibly a set of classical bouncing \'billiard balls\', and that no quantum weirdness is required to eff the ineffable.\r\n\r\nOur goal is to continue this survey and expand it to include all leading experts and theories in this field, and to track this till science falsifies all but the one theory, forcing all the experts to abandon and join that one theory.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-10-29 21:56:56','2011-10-29 21:56:56'),(1228,96,48,'By all means include my name as interested/involved etc. I\'m unlikley to make the conference until such time as its back in Europe as I have an aversion to both the cost and experience of long haul travel. However, if there was some substantial reason I could reconsider.\r\n\r\nJunius ','2011-10-30 19:13:18','2011-10-30 19:13:18'),(1231,96,48,'Hi Junius,\r\n\r\nThanks!  I\'ll add your name as a co-author.\r\n\r\nAlso, I got a personal e-mail from [https://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=222 rolfk], one of the newest supporters of the Representational Qualia Camp.  He included an attached document where he made some great comments and significantly improved on my very poor English.  Thank you so much Rolf.  I hope you don\'t mind if I reply to your e-mail here, so I can include others in this discussion.\r\n\r\nOne of my particularly bad sentences was the second to the last one in the first paragraph where I try to cram a description of the canonizer tool we are using in one run on sentence.  We can\'t increase the number of words, so perhaps someone can provide a better description than what I have, without increasing the number of words (or possibly point out some other words that are less important?)\r\n\r\nAlso, Rolf had some great comments about the fact that my usage of the words \"magic\" and \"weirdness\" unnecessarily denigrated quantum theory.  So I also wondered if anyone had any suggested ways of briefly describing the differences between these two camps without being negative or anything?\r\n\r\nThanks for all the help, this is fantastic!\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-10-31 03:52:42','2011-10-31 03:52:42'),(1234,96,48,'I agree with rolfk about \'magic\' and \'weirdness\'. Magic implies something outside of science, while weirdness implies some special extreme case that we don\'t need to bother about. The argument that quantum rules are the norm and classical/macroscopic rules are a special case might be nearer to the truth.\r\n\r\nIt might be better to talk about classical/macroscopic versus fundamental physics as Penrose type ideas involve not only quantum theory but require some form of theory of spacetime.\r\n\r\nJunius  ','2011-10-31 12:49:20','2011-10-31 12:49:20'),(1237,96,48,'Count me in too, Brent.\r\n\r\nThe quantum magic epithet for Orch OR is IMO appropriate but then i\'m a biologist who believes that microtubules have nothing to do with consciousness :) Agreed that your piece shouldn\'t be pejorative, however, so best to leave the word \"magic\" out of it. ','2011-10-31 14:14:59','2011-10-31 14:14:59'),(1240,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nOK, I\'ve taken all the great feedback and produced a much improved draft of the abstract I soon intend to submit (included below) for [http://www.consciousness.arizona.edu/ TSC 2012].  Any other ideas of how to make it better?\r\n\r\nSo far these people are willing to have their names included as co-authors on the submittal:\r\n\r\n* Simon Raggett\r\n* Richard Wilson\r\n* Steven Lehar\r\n\r\nThanks Guys!  Are there any of you new guys that recently joined interested in lending us your names to give us support?  JLCarrol, are you listening, you have a PhD.  Would you be willing to lend your name to the effort?  Anyone else?  Last call...\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n===============\r\n\r\n\r\n\'\'\'Rigorously building and measuring for scientific consensus.\'\'\'\r\n\r\nOur goal with the Consciousness Survey Project ( http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/105 ) is building as much consensus as possible on the most important things; determining the most concise and unified language to describe such; and rigorously measuring for consensus in a way that allows everyone to definitively see any falsified trends.  For several years now, volunteers have been attending conferences, interviewing, surveying for, and \'canonizing\' experts views.  Our tool is the all volunteer driven, leaderless, crowd-sourced, wiki with camps, bottom up, open survey system being developed at Canonizer.com.\r\n\r\nThe diverse set of publications, previous attempts at surveys, Wikipedia, the internet... all seem to support the pervasive belief that there is no expert consensus on much of anything in this field.  While our results are still far from comprehensive, it already appears that, after all, there could be a significant amount of consensus on many important things.  To date, it has never been possible for as many diverse experts as we have participating, to develop any kind of consensus on much of anything.\r\n\r\nThe current consensus clearly indicates the most fundamental issue to be whether or not consciousness is approachable via science.  About 33 of the 35 participators agree that it is.  At the next level down, surprisingly, there is almost as much consensus around what the experts recently unanimously agreed to call \"Representational Qualia Theory\".  (http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 )  There is clear expert consensus on many issues at this level, such as where redness is located (not on the surface of the strawberry) and about the \"Quale Interpretation Problem\" describing why quale are ineffable and how to overcome such.  Below this are various competing theories about just what redness is including the leading \"Mind-Brain Identity\" camp.  At this level, finally, some significant supported competing camps start to appear such as \"Higher-dimensional Theories\" and \"Panexperientialism\".\r\n\r\nThings start to get even more dynamic at the next level down, where David Chalmers\' \"Functional Property Dualism\" established a clear early lead.  Despite this camps continued growth, the competing \"Functional Property Dualism\" camp seems to be on the verge of overtaking this lead.  Where Chalmers predicts if you have the right \'functionality\', regardless of if it is neurons, computer chips... you will get redness.  Material Property dualists are predicting that it is the right material that has redness, and without it, there is no redness.\r\n\r\nThis minority, yet accelerating camp includes Hameroff\'s Orch OR theory, which assumes we need to descend below the quantum level to solve this riddle while a lesser camp is predicting ineffable properties can just as easily be observed and effed in any classical or macro level system - maybe even in bouncing billiard balls, sunsets, and so on.\r\n\r\nOur goal is to expand this survey to include all leading experts and theories in this field and to track the developments until science falsifies all but one theory, forcing all experts to adopt the theory with the highest objective support.\r\n\r\n','2011-11-13 00:45:28','2011-11-13 00:45:28'),(1243,96,48,'The LHC experiment appears to be taking the Supersymmetry out of String Theory, and therefore removing the basis of my consciousness theory. So at this time I suggest that it may be counterproductive to include me as a co-author. The same may apply to other higher dimensional theories based on string theory. John','2011-11-13 01:05:22','2011-11-13 01:05:22'),(1246,96,48,'The LHC experiment appears to be taking the Supersymmetry out of String Theory, and therefore removing the basis of my consciousness theory. So at this time I suggest that it may be counterproductive to include me as a co-author. The same may apply to other higher dimensional theories based on string theory. John','2011-11-13 01:05:33','2011-11-13 01:05:33'),(1249,96,48,'Hi John,\r\n\r\nAre you kidding me?  Wow, an honest to God falsified theory of consciousness.  That is big news.  Thanks for this info! Hey, I was once in the camp that assumed the universe would end in a big crunch.  There\'s no shame in being wrong like that, is there?  Looking forward to  seeing your camp get updated / or seeing what new camp you join.  And this has been very educational, quantum wise, to watch this.\r\n\r\nDo you mind if I use this as a great example of one of the first canonized camps to be falsified by demonstrable science?  Folks, you saw it here, all canonized and recorded for posterity\'s sake.\r\n\r\nUnless you say otherwise, consider your name added as a co-other.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2011-11-13 02:17:51','2011-11-13 02:17:51'),(1252,96,48,'I would be careful. You may be jumping the gun.\r\nThe LHC has not yet demonstrated that SUSY does not exist.\r\nIt just does not look promising, and it if true eliminates most of string theory in its present form. I doubt if you want to be the one to make that announcement.','2011-11-13 03:07:56','2011-11-13 03:07:56'),(1255,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nI\'ve been having a great debate with [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=243 James Carroll], the newest supporter of Functional Property Dualism, and \"Software = Qualia\"  in another forum.  It has been very productive and has helped my clean up many of the messy thinking arguments that I often use to support Material Property Dualism.\r\n\r\nMy understanding is that James\' argument as to why Software = Qualia is simply that the brain is a computer, and everything in it can simulated to any desired degree of accuracy, with any sufficient abstracted, ones and zeros based system.  (James, let us know if I haven\'t adequately described your position.)\r\n\r\nI completely agree with this assertion, but am attempting to point out that this is entirely missing what ineffable phenomenal properties are, that can also be represented by enough ones and zeroes, but only if you properly interpret the appropriate set of ones and zeros as the redness and the greenness that they represent - and that - by design, such ones and zeros aren\'t like anything, they are just interpretations of anything, no matter what the ones and zeros are represented with.\r\n\r\nIn another attempt to better communicate to him what I\'m trying to say, I\'ve adapted the phenomenal billiard ball system I described in the previously discussed [http://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/24 Effing Billard Balls] thread to be a design for a phenomenal strawberry picking robot.\r\n\r\nIn the other forum, we seemed to be the only two people interested in our debate, so we both wanted to find out what others thought about who was winning this debate, so I decided to move the conversation here.  If any of you are interested in indicating what you do or don\'t believe, and why, we\'d love to hear from you.\r\n\r\nMy main questions to anyone in the Software = Qualia camp would be:  Would you agree that if science turned out to be just like the predictions made by the below theoretically possible world, you\'d have to assume Functional Property Dualism was false and abandon your camp as being falsified.\r\n\r\nAlso, in this theoretically possible reality it is simply the neural transmitters that have, in addition to all their other causal properties, also have some ineffable phenomenal properties that can be experienced.  So this is where the redness and greenness come from in this theoretically possible reality, and how they are discovered, and so on.  My question to Software = Qualia people is what type of set of ones and zeros might correspond with, or cause something like redness to emerge?  And how might you \'discover\' new phenomenal properties, and what would dictate what these new properties would be like, would there be any kind of limit to the set of phenomenal properties that could be experienced or discovered, and so on?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n=============\r\n\r\n\'\'\'Mechanical description of a theoretically possible phenomenal strawberry picking robot.\'\'\'\r\n\r\nThe purpose of this robot is to pick red strawberries from a field of green leaves.  There are traditional digital cameras for perception, and traditional, digitally controlled arms that can receive digital commands to move to a particular location, then grasp and pick any strawberry that is at that location.\r\n\r\nWe will assume that in this theoretically possible reality, there are two different neural transmitters that, in addition to behaving identically to the actual ones in this world, also have phenomenal properties.  Glutamate having a redness property, and Aspartate having a greenness property.  If you shine light on them, common Glutamate in crystalline form, reflects white light, and Aspartate reflects gray, just like the real stuff in this world.  It is possible in this reality to create neuron like mechanism with Axon terminals, that can emit these two neurotransmitters and Dendrites with receptors that can uptake them.\r\n\r\nThe brain of this system has a 1K x 1K x 1K 3D array of these neuron like structures.  The cameras are wired up to a perception system that feeds into this 3D array of neurons.  When the cameras are pointing to a patch in the strawberry field, it causes a set of neurons in this volume, in the shape of the strawberries and levees, to fire.  When any of these neurons are stimulated by the perception system indicating there is the surface of a strawberry at the corresponding location in the field of the camera, it fires Glutamate across all of its Axon terminals.  When the perception system detect the surface of a green leaf at that same location, the axon terminals fire Aspartate.\r\n\r\nThere is a hierarchical neuronal structured this entire 3D volume of neurons feeds into capable of recognizing not only the red strawberries and the green leaves, but is also self aware of the fact that its redness and greenness are phenomenally experienced very different from each other.  It is the phenomenal difference between the redness of the Glutamate and the Greenness of the Aspartate, that enable the system to know where the strawberries are, and where to direct the hand to pick them.  The system interprets the redness as representing what it wants to pick, and the greenness as representing what should be avoided.  It also has a voice system, such that if something asks what color is the item at a particular location, it has enough intelligence such that it can answer red, if the neurons at that location are firing Glutamate, and it will answer Green, if the neurons are firing Aspartate.\r\n\r\nIn this particular reality, you can completely simulate everything this computer does with a simple binary system.  You can have a 3 dimensional 1K by 1K by 1K array of values that can hold a binary 0 when there is green at that location, and a binary one, when there is a strawberry.  When you ask it what color something is, it behaves identically, saying the strawberries are red, and the leaves are green.  But of course, this system is designed not to matter what represents red or green, as long as the downstream controlling system selecting what to pick, interprets whatever is dong the representation, appropriately.  Anything that is represented by something interpreted as one is also interpreted as what should be picked.\r\n\r\nNow, this particular theoretically possible reality, is just as described by Material Property Dualism.  There is nothing in it, except the Glutamate, that has the redness that can be experienced.  If you replace any of the 3D volume of knowledge neurons with something else, if there is no Glutamate involved, the robot experiences nothing like redness for the particular location that that neurons represents in the visible space.\r\n\r\nLet\'s say there was a 3rd neurotransmitter in this world that had a blueness phenomenal property - say Dopamine.  You go into this 3D volume of neurons, and replace a set of them with this different neuron that fires with Dopamine, when there is a strawberry, instead of the Glutamate.  And let\'s say the recognition system has no words for this new blueness color.  When you ask the system what color is at that location, it says I see a strawberry there, but it is not like any of the other red strawberries, nor any of the green leaves.  I don\'t know what color that is.  But, if you want me to pick it, I can.\r\n\r\n','2011-11-18 04:36:55','2011-11-18 04:36:55'),(1258,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nI\'d like to welcome Joshua DeZarn (AKA [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=248 change84]) as the newest supporter in this topic.  He has joined Maurice McCarthy (AKA [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=198 Moss]) supporting the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/49 Ideal Monism] camp.  It is great to see a new competitor camp with some great criticism of [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 RQT], with some emerging consensus.   Anyone and everyone that is new, feel free to post an introduction of yourself to this topic forum.  It\'s always great to know who everyone is.\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2011-12-03 23:25:51','2011-12-03 23:25:51'),(1261,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\n[http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=243 James Carroll] and I have been continuing our productive debate between Material and Functional property dualism on the Mormon Transhumanist e-mail list.\r\n\r\nAs usual, I\'m having a hard time fully understanding competing theories to my own, and I sense James having the same problem with my theory.  So I figured I could try to describe to him how I might create or simulate a \"Functionalist Property Dualism\" world within a basement world that adheres to the rules of Material Property Dualism.  I noticed that imagining such simulations, that operate within a basement world that behaves according to the rules predicted by Material Property Dualism, is the way I try to think of other theories, so I thought this might be a good way to improve communication between two people like us with very different working theories.\r\n\r\nSo, James, let\'s start in a basement world that follows the rules of Material Property Dualism, and within that world, let me attempt to create a simulation of a world that follows Functional Property Dualism rules, as I currently believe you imagine them to be.\r\n\r\nWe want to do what would be required to build a similar phenomenal strawberry picking device to the one described above.  But, since this one would be in a simulated FPD world, we want to describe the differences.\r\n\r\nThe previous robot had a 1K x 1K x 1K 3D array of neuron like structures which, if these neurons fired Glutamate in their downstream synapses, it would experience a redness quale at that voxel location, while if it fired Aspartate, it would experience greenness at that voxel location, since it was the Glutamate and Aspartate that had these redness and greenness phenomenal properties.\r\n\r\nHowever, it is argued that in the FPD world, a string of bits could produce a redness quale experience.  So let\'s say that we design this simulation to have, instead of a 3D array of neurons firing either glutamate or Aspartate, there are simply abstract string arrays that can contain a simple string value formatted as: \"Magic:0xRRGGBB\", where RR is a hex value from 00 to FF representing the level of redness color, and GG, and BB are the same for greenness and blueness.\r\n\r\nJames admits he\'s not sure how any set of ones and zeros could result in an experience of a redness quale, he just claims he has proven it must be so.  But in a simulated world you can alter the rules any way you want to make any theoretically possible reality.  So that is exactly what we wire into this simulated FPD world.  Since this simulated FPD world is running within a MPD world, it follows the assumption that you can\'t get something from nothing.  In other words, just as you can\'t store information, without having something physical to represent it with, you can\'t have a phenomenal property, without something that has the phenomenal property.  So, in order to have something that can experience a redness quale in the simulated FPD world, some additional stuff needs to be added to the simulation, to match up a string like \"Magic:0xFF0000\" that exists in the simulation, and wire in a real set of neurons in the basement world that fire Glutamate resulting in the redness quale experience that we need to exist in this FPD world.  We do it in a way so that no matter what is representing the string \"Magic:0xFF0000\", whether it is simulated silicon, or simulated neurons, or even bear cans, the simulation hardware detects this \"Magic:0xFF0000\" string, and harness a set of neurons firing glutamate in the basement world, producing a true redness quale experience in the simulated world.\r\n\r\nNow, letâ€™s say there are two brains running in this functional property dualism world.  They both propose two theories as to the way their world is operating and what is responsible for their phenomenal redness and greenness experiences.  One proposes Material Property Dualism â€“ predicting the only way to get redness, is to have the right matter.  He predicts that silicone can\'t have a redness property.  The other is predicting functional property dualism, that anything that has the correct set of ones and zeros, will result in the redness quale experience they are both capable of experiencing.\r\n\r\nSo, they take their instruments, and start probing the makeup of these simulated brains and examining just how it is they work.  Of course as predicted by the functional property dualists, they discover that any time they see the abstract string of â€œmagic:0xFF0000â€, the brain experiences a point of redness qualia experience.  This happens no matter what part of the brain it is working on, and no matter what that part of the brain is representing that string with â€“ anything from a paper tape with the right bits on it, to a set of magnetic characters represented by bits of properly oriented ferrous material, and so on â€“ will all produce a spot of redness quale experience (thanks to the magic wired into this simulated world).\r\n\r\nSo, the brain predicting Functional Property Dualism shows to the other brain, this objective, demonstrate-able to both discovery, and says: I told you so, our world is a functional property dualist world.  And the Material Property Dualist brain admits, yes, you are definitely right, I was wrong.  I thought it would require effing magic, to achieve this, but low and behold, that is just what we see in reality, apparent effing magic, for any time we have a string like \"Magic:0xFF0000\", no matter what is being interpreted as representing that string.  Who, but you, could have thought such?\r\n\r\nAnd the mistaken brain then abandonâ€™s the material property dualist camp, and starts supporting the functional property dualistâ€™s camp, and very much enjoys finally effing all his experiences with everyone else\'s brain, in their newly enhanced effing brains and finally grounded abstract communications.\r\n\r\nSo, my question is, does such a simulated FPD world, work the way you are predicting our world operates, in a FPD way?  If not why and how must it be different?  And of course, if it is different, can you describe how you might do the reverse, and simulate a MPD world, where the MPD brain can be the one that turns out to be right?  All so that I might better understand with more completeness, just what it is you understand the set of FPD rules to be?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2011-12-13 04:14:31','2011-12-13 04:14:31'),(1262,1,64,'Hi Damir,\r\n\r\nYou proposed adding the \"I suggest we merge this camp...\" to the agreement statement.\r\n\r\nThings like this belong in the camp forums, so I\'m going to object to that proposed change, which will prevent it from going live.\r\n\r\nI do completely agree that we need to merge these two topics.  So perhaps you can make some specific suggestions in topic forum, where we can discuss these things and build some consensus on the best way to do this?\r\n\r\nIn your e-mail you were distinguishing between different types of free will, freedom, and so on?  Perhaps you could expound on just what you mean?\r\n\r\nI completely agree with much of what you described in your camps, so I\"m hoping we can create a consensus super camp that contains things we all can agree on?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-01-14 22:09:05','2012-01-14 22:09:05'),(1263,1,5,'Hi [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=114 Damir],\r\n\r\nWelcome as the newest supporter of this survey topic, in the consensus Yes camp and thanks for your contributions.\r\n\r\nYou proposed a new statement for the yes camp, but I\'m not sure I\'m comfortable with the way this is worded.  So I\'m going to object to this initial version till we can work on it a bit more?\r\n\r\nOr, if you want, you can always create a supporting sub camp to the yes camp and add your statement to that camp and support it there?\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-01-14 22:20:37','2012-01-14 22:20:37'),(1264,1,64,'Dear Brent,\r\n\r\nSorry, I have failed to notice this feature. I agree that it is better to discuss things here first.\r\n\r\nNow, I cannot recall talk about types of free will. In my opinion, there is only an issue of how much we utilise the power of our free will. Basically, we are very habitual creatures. Only when we create something new --- we utilise our power of free will. We can be nonconsciously creative also. In democracies, this is well manifested during elections. So, types of free will are only different aspects of how we manifest it.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-01-14 22:24:23','2012-01-14 22:24:23'),(1265,1,5,'Dear all,\r\n\r\nI suggest the following camp statement for Yes camp:\r\n----\r\nUnwonted pregnancies are, mostly, the responsibility of elders who did not raise youngsters well enough re sex and love. Unwonted pregnancies can be result of sexual abuse. This is also eldersâ€™ responsibility, since they did not educate the abuser well enough about sex and love.\r\n\r\nElders must not hide their guilt behind a moral authority of any kind. They must be honest enough and apologise. Only then their advice to young women can be accepted in love and care...\r\n----\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-01-14 22:31:28','2012-01-14 22:31:28'),(1266,1,5,'Hi Damir,\r\n\r\nHere are a few problems I see with this initial version:\r\n\r\n\r\nI have no idea what you mean by \"Elders\".  Also, I don\'t think anyone should \"hide their guilt behind a moral authority of any kind\", not just \"Elders\"?  Younger people can be just as guilty as Elders, for example.\r\n\r\nAlso, facts like \"Unwonted pregnancies can be result of sexual abuse.\" are obviously true, but I don\'t see any reason why this should be included in a concise description of the yes camp?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-01-14 22:38:53','2012-01-14 22:38:53'),(1267,1,8,'Dear all,\r\n\r\nWe should merge Bible\'s Best & Worst into a single topic.\r\n\r\nHowever, I propose treating Bible as political document. Since its negotiated begginings at the end of third century it was meant as a \"glue\" to the crumbling Roman Empire. It was therefore crafted to sustain Roman psyche of the times rather than present Christ\'s teachings. That is where the \"best\" and the \"worst\" start making sense.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-01-14 22:45:37','2012-01-14 22:45:37'),(1268,1,8,'\r\nHi Damir,\r\n\r\nIf we merged the best and worst topics, and if you joined a camp for a particular scripture, would you be indicating that camp was one of the best of the bible, or one of the worst of the bible?\r\n\r\nI prefer the way these two are now, for this reason.\r\n\r\nYou can always start a new camp, with any stated survey and operating purpose you\'d like?\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-01-14 23:00:07','2012-01-14 23:00:07'),(1269,1,8,'Dear Brent,\r\n\r\nWe could keep the \"best\" and the \"worst\" as separate agreeing disagreeing camps. They can function as detectors of issues to discuss.\r\n\r\nI, for example, believe that the Bible is terible towards women and that this was against Christ\'s teachings. However, this was a political decission, since that went against Roman psyche of the times. As result, we have the Bible with that part of Christ\'s teaching carefully weeded out.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-01-15 00:05:30','2012-01-15 00:05:30'),(1270,1,8,'Dear all,\r\n\r\nI suggest that we open the topic with the following:\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe Bible is political document negotiated at the end of the third century. It was rather a compromise between Jewish and Roman philosophy of the times. That\'s why we have the old and the new testament.\r\n\r\nAs political documet, its sole purpose was to unite fragmenting Roman Empire. That\'s why all of the Christ\'s teachings - that were contrary to the Roman psyche - carefully weeded out. If we detect all of these censorships - we might find the whole of the Christ\'s message...\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPlease, let me know what you think, so I can act accordingly.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,','2012-01-15 00:22:38','2012-01-15 00:22:38'),(1271,1,8,'Dear all,\r\n\r\nThis is what I believe about Christâ€™s message to be true.\r\n\r\n1. Men and women are equal and their relationship is holy. Thatâ€™s why we must respect such parents as saints. The opposite is also possible. The marriage can be hell also...\r\n\r\n2. There is heaven on earth --- here and now. It is in hearts of our kids. I do believe that if I make for them this place a little better for them to live in --- then this will be my heaven when I pass on.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,','2012-01-15 00:36:04','2012-01-15 00:36:04'),(1272,1,8,'Hi Damir,\r\n\r\nThese best and worst of the bible topics, I imagine them more of simply being people ranking their top 10 (or worst 10) scriptures or messages pertained, there in.\r\n\r\nYour proposals seem to be about a different topic, altogether - namely, what is the bible?  I\'m sure some people think it is the infallible word of God, others think it is a mere political document, and others might think of it as primitive blathers of a clueless people from a long time ago, both morally and chronologically, to name a few possible camps?\r\n\r\nI think it would be great to capture what everyone does believe about the bible, including what you\'ve stated here, in another topic surveying for what people think the bible is.  What do you think about that?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-01-15 03:22:54','2012-01-15 03:22:54'),(1273,1,16,'Dear Brent,\r\n\r\nI am supporting your statement. However, I wonted to delegate my support to you - I did not find an obvious way. I tried to modify my support, but there is no an obvious option to delegate.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,','2012-01-15 03:42:20','2012-01-15 03:42:20'),(1274,1,8,'Dear Brent,\r\n\r\nThe religion is always a touchy topic and for that reason alone, I think, your advice is good. However, we do need to approach to the religion with our heads cool. To this end, Iâ€™m now contemplating a statement that will not cause anger. I must be careful, but in essence it will be like this:\r\n\r\nThere are simple historical facts about the Bible. It was a result of negotiations between Hellenistic and Jewish scholars with a variety of Christian traditions --- almost four centuries after Christ. In essence, Constantine the Great needed the highest authority possible to rule over his crumbling empire.\r\n\r\nBack then, rulers were expected to have backing of unnatural authority --- the more powerful the better... Naturally, a god above all other gods was the best option. Nonchristian religions were also trying to provide such moral authority to their own one and only god. And this battle for hearts and souls of uneducated populace continues today.\r\n\r\nTodayâ€™s frictions between religions about whose god is one and only --- only confirm that they are rather political organisations then seriously worshiping their own one and only...\r\n\r\nTodayâ€™s frontline churches are trying to deliver parts of the message Christ may have been trying to deliver. However, they are still stuck in the past --- polytheistic past of the Roman Empire. Therefore, all theological attempts to reconcile these religions are doomed to fail.\r\n\r\nIt is my opinion that it is time to forget about such one and only god in a pantheon --- and then work on the possible future elections about whose god should be on the throne to rule over the universe.\r\n\r\nIt is also my opinion that The Protestor intuited the new age coming. They simply had a hope awaken --- a hope that we really have free will. And with this hope, entirely new morality comes in as a surprising factor. It is now hard to delegate our free will to civil authorities and then forget about it. I expect to see something similar in religions also. I fear, however, that churches may opt for their good old god in the old pantheon. This may cause even bloodshed...\r\n\r\nIt is, therefore, very urgent to discuss religion as it should be.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,','2012-01-15 05:53:25','2012-01-15 05:53:25'),(1275,1,25,'Dear all,\r\n\r\nI suggest the following as topicâ€™s view:\r\n\r\nThe governmentâ€™s job is to listen to its people and act with love and care --- all of the time. We recognise that it is hard to fulfil wishes of many. Few hotheads may wish even wars. We need, therefore, to explore the wisdom the government needs to act with love and care.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,','2012-01-15 06:41:35','2012-01-15 06:41:35'),(1276,1,23,'Dear all,\r\n\r\nThis topic very much depends on what we think our true desires mean. There is a simple rule of the thumb for what our \"true\" desires mean: other people.\r\n\r\nIf other people agree that our true desires are good, than they are good and true. Otherwise...\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,','2012-01-15 06:49:12','2012-01-15 06:49:12'),(1277,1,89,'Dear all,\r\n\r\nI would add here a little known heat pollution.\r\n\r\nWhat is actually happening is that our huge appetite for energy is releasing more and more heat into the atmosphere. Now, few hundred years ago this was not a problem for we had plenty of forests to sort this one out. Simply speaking, forests induce vertical air circulation --- and that takes heat captured in vapour in the cooler regions of the atmosphere --- and we had rain.\r\n\r\nToday, we have rapidly reduced the overall surface of forests on our planet --- and much more uncondensed vapour around. And the vapour is the most potent of all GHG.\r\n\r\nThe reduction of coastal forests in Australia --- 40,000 years ago --- may have led to the desertification of the Australian interior.\r\n\r\nI would like to see this expressed in this camp also. If not, Iâ€™ll add a new one.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,','2012-01-16 03:05:26','2012-01-16 03:05:26'),(1278,1,19,'Dear all,\r\n\r\nWhile I am sharing your views, I am a bit concerned about overconfidence. Yes, there are ridiculous notions about AI, but...\r\n\r\nMy view is simple. Truly independent AI will work in its own interest - only. And if human race stands in its way it will do everything it can to reach its goals...\r\n\r\nThis was well explored by Isaac Asimov. I recommend this as very good read re AI. He has also articulated rules that should be built in such machines to prevent them going against human race. There is also HAL in movie â€œ2001â€ that is also exploring well this as a possibility.\r\n\r\nNow, if you do not enhance your statements with this - Iâ€™ll create an opposing camp.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,','2012-01-16 05:17:30','2012-01-16 05:17:30'),(1281,96,48,'If anyone is interested please see http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/51for my critique of Representational Qualia Theory.\r\n\r\nPanexperientialism\r\n   Multisense Realism\r\n     Qualitative Present Theory\r\n\r\n\r\nTowards the end I started to see more promise in the theory as it at least recognizes qualia as phenomenal, but I think that my hypothesis, radical and unpopular as it is, is actually a more insightful model than any other that is currently out there.\r\n\r\nThanks everyone, and nice to meet you, and sorry if I\'m ruffling feathers or fauxing pas.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-01-19 04:56:15','2012-01-19 04:56:15'),(1282,1,5,'Dear Brent,\r\n\r\nElders are parents and grandparents who guide kids towards maturity --- including sexual maturity. Here we can add teachers and others as guardians.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, sex is a taboo and kids are often left to discover their sexuality on their own. Since many guardians respect taboos --- they actually fail the trust of their own kids. Thatâ€™s why we have so huge issues with unwanted pregnancies.\r\n\r\nNow, if we do guide our kids towards mature assessments of the risks --- we will have much less unwanted pregnancies and the issue will gradually disappear from our lists...\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-01-22 06:17:16','2012-01-22 06:17:16'),(1283,1,19,'\r\n\r\nWelcome, Ari, as the newest supporter in this survey topic, especially since you\'re in my camp! ;)\r\n\r\nI\'d love to know more about you, so feel free to introduce yourself here.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-02-29 02:26:14','2012-02-29 02:26:14'),(1286,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nI\'m excited that TSC 2012 is only about 4 weeks away.  I\'m working on the [http://canonizer.com/files/2012_TSC_Poster.ppt poster] we\'re going to put up in the poster session, and the [http://canonizer.com/files/2012_TSC_survey_flier.docx survey flier] I\'m going to be handing out to as many people as we can that asks if people are a Material or a Functional property dualist.\r\n\r\nThere is clear consensus on almost everything, with most people that will attend TSC, till you get down to this level, and we don\'t yet have enough sample data to know if there is a consensus, or not, at this level.\r\n\r\nI\'m betting there is also already a clear consensus even at this level, so it is going to be fun to ask as many experts as possible, what they currently believe, to find out for sure.  Either way, it should be very easy for the neural scientists to demonstrate which of these is right, once they know what to look for (i.e. us theoreticians can effectively educate them about such.)\r\n\r\nSo I hope you\'ll all review the poster, and the flier, and let me know your thoughts, or if you know of any way to improve things.  In the poster, I\'ve somewhat arbitrarily selected some camps, over others, to simplify things.  If anyone is upset about their camp being left off, or whatever, please let me know, so we can see if we can work out some version that is justified, and makes everyone happy?\r\n\r\nWho else is going to be there this year?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-03-16 12:13:51','2012-03-16 12:13:51'),(1289,96,48,'Subject: Separating \"Property Dualism\" from \"Representational Qualia Theory\".\r\n\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nI am a supporter of representationalism, but not of \"property dualism\".  So Brent Allsop and I plan on pushing this property dualism doctrine to a new \"Property \"Dualism\" sub camp, so people like me can support everything in the RQT camp.  We plan on making this change during the next few days.\r\n\r\nThere is currently a 3 paragraph section entitled: \"Various Types of Property Dualism\" that opens with: \"Everyone in this camp considers themselves to be property dualists\".  This entire section will be moved to a new \"Property Dualism\" camp, along with a response Brent plans on adding in response to our new \"Representational Functionalist\" competing camp we intend on starting.\r\n\r\nWe will also, during the next few days, be changing the parents of all the current sub camps of RQT, to have this new \"Property Dualism\" camp as their parent.\r\n\r\nIt appears that there are other camps similar to \"Representational Functionalism\", including [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/23 representative/illusory] and [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/37 Consciousness From Detection, Reaction, and Association].  So we also plan on moving these camps to be supports of the new Representational Functionalist camp we will be creating as a competitor to property dualism.\r\n\r\nSo, if anyone objects to any of this, or if anyone is willing to work to help with any of this, please let us know so we can do what works best for everyone.\r\n\r\nWe\'d like to have all this completed in plenty of time before TSC 2012.','2012-03-17 20:08:06','2012-03-17 20:08:06'),(1290,1,98,'God in the news?\r\n\r\nhttp://www.drwarpenstein.com/swirl_-_personal_web_site_034.htm','2012-03-18 18:06:41','2012-03-18 18:06:41'),(1293,96,48,'Theoretitions,\r\n\r\nI\'ve now created the new first draft of the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/19 \"Property Dualism\"], camp but haven\'t yet moved all the old RQT sub camps to have this as their new parent.  I\'ve taken some liberties with this new camp which I think are important, so I hope you\'ll all review these before I make these changes in the next few days.\r\n\r\nIn the new statement I specifically define qualia or a phenomenal property to be that which cannot be communicated by abstract representations, or software, alone.  I know there are some supporters of Functional Property Dualism that are also in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/83/3 \"software = qualia\"] camp, so I\'m assuming you must disagree with this definition that says qualia cannot be software, alone.\r\n\r\nI think it is very confusing to people (especially me) who want to know, concisely and quantitatively, what everyone believes, to try to keep their head around the idea that some property dualists believe qualia = software, and there are some that don\'t.  I think this is a critically important issue, when dealing with consciousness, so I think this should be dealt with very high in the POV hierarchy.  In other words, it is my opinion, that everyone would have a much better time understanding what we all believe, if people that think software = qualia, recreate a new parallel branch, to what we have now, under the \"property dualism\" branch.\r\n\r\nOn big implication of this is it will split the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/17 Mind Brain Identity camp] across two POV branches.   Obviously, the consensus camp under \"Property Dualism\" is for \"Mind Brain Identity\".  I\'m assuming there will be a similar consensus camp under the new \"Representational Functionalism\" camp, if identity theory is not unanimously accepted by all of \"Representational Functionalists\" and there by contained in the new \"Representational Functionalism\" camp itself.  I think it is important that each identity camp point to the other, so if people want to know how many \"mind brain identity\" people there are, they need to count up both camps.  They just need to know that some are on the \"property dualists\" branch and some are not.\r\n\r\nIf, in the future, we discover that there are far more mind brain identity theoriests, than property dualists, this could bring about a theoretical revolution in that we move \"mind brain identity\" theory branch higher in the POV structure than property dualism branch.  This would fork property dualism on these two identity branches instead.  But, for the time being, there are far more spiritual property dualists, so I believe the consensus is that the highest level split, for now, remain with property dualism.\r\n\r\nI haven\'t yet seen how the new \"representational functionalism\" will turn out, but have a few ideas about what James plans on including in it, including the doctrine that software = qualia?  I would hope that everyone that does think that software = qualia will help him to come up with a concise and quantitative representation of what you all believe.  Or, if anyone has any better ideas, we\'re surely open to all such.\r\n\r\nIn a few days, I plan on moving all the old children to RQT to have this new [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/19 \"Property Dualism\"] camp.  So in other words, if anyone remains in those camps that move, it will imply that you now agree with the definition of qualia that says it can\'t = software, alone.\r\n\r\nAgain, as always, if I\'m missing anything, or if anyone has any better ideas, or objects to any of this, please do so here, before we continue making these efforts, so we can find the best way to get what works for everyone, and so we can best represent, concisely and quantitatively, to the rest of the world, what we all believe.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop','2012-03-18 21:17:18','2012-03-18 21:17:18'),(1294,1,92,'There is a new sub camp in the public sex education camp, called the \"Combination Sex Ed Best\" camp. It\'s current camp statement reads as follows: \r\n\r\n\"We believe that public sex education is important.\r\n\r\n\"We believe that public sex education should teach the benefits of abstinence, but should also teach the benefits and principles of safe sex which should be employed if the individual chooses to become sexually active.\"\r\n\r\nIt is hoped that many of the \"abstinance\" camp and \"safe sex\" camp might be interested in moving to this more moderate, middle of the road approach. \r\n\r\nIf you are one, then please adjust your support. Thanks!\r\n\r\nJames','2012-03-22 17:13:57','2012-03-22 17:13:57'),(1295,1,26,'Hi [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=235 Micah Redding].\r\n\r\nWelcome to the \"Consciousness\" definition survey topic, and thanks for creating the new [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/71/6 Virtual Reality] camp.\r\n\r\nWhat you describe in the virtual reality camp is exactly the same as the representationalism described in the significant consensus camp [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/71/6 Representational Qualia Theory] or RQT camp, right?\r\n\r\nTo me, this is very confusing to readers.  Basically, they\'ll first get the idea that 27 experts have spent many years, working to unify their beliefs, come up with the name most everyone agrees on, and put it all into the \"Representational Qualia Theory\" camp.  Then you come along, all alone, and describe what appears to be the exact same thing, using a somewhat unrelated term name (Virtual Reality) that might make people think of something else, and describe it all in an entirely different way.  So, is everyone supposed to think, most experts call themselves representational qualia theorists, and Micah thinks the same way, but he calls himself a virtual realitiest?\r\n\r\nI completely agree with everything you say here, it\'s just I think you could be a bit less lonely and anti social, with your names, and by aligning yourself with the consensus experts.\r\n\r\nIn other words, If you improve the name (is there a problem with Representational  Qualia Theory?) and/or indicate in your camp statement that you believe in the same, what is to you \'virtual reality\' described in the Representational Qualia Theory camp (with link reference) then I\'ll join and support your camp (i.e. move my phenomenal properties camp to be a child of your super camp.)\r\n\r\nAnd by the way, would you be willing to also join and support the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 RQT] camp?\r\n\r\nThanks\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-03-24 21:30:43','2012-03-24 21:30:43'),(1296,1,64,'\r\n\r\nHi [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=255 Mike],\r\n\r\nWelcome to the Determinism vs Freedom survey topic, and thanks for creating the new illusion camp.\r\n\r\nI noticed you are supporting both the compatible and illusion camp.  I also agree with both.  I bet everyone in the compatible camp would agree with the illusion doctrine.  (If anyone in the compatible camp thinks otherwise, please speak up).\r\n\r\nIn other words, would you mind merging these two camps and adding the illusion doctrine into the compatible camp?\r\n\r\nI\'d even agree to (i.e. not object) changing the compatible camp name to \"Compatible / Illusion\" if you want.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-03-24 21:48:32','2012-03-24 21:48:32'),(1297,1,64,'The two are kept separate in most other philosophical survey\'s that I have seen so far. For example: http://philpapers.org/surveys/\r\n\r\nThe \"illusion\" thread says that there IS no free will. The Compatible camp says that there IS free will, and it is compatible with determinism. \r\n\r\nWhich I would vote for depends on the definition of free will used. If you define free will in the strange way some do, then it doesn\'t exist, and is an illusion. If you define free will as \"autonomy\" (which I prefer) then it clearly exists, and is fully compatible with determinism. And it most certainly isn\'t then an illusion. It is quite real. \r\n\r\nTo me these camps say slightly different things about how free will should be defined. So my choice between \"illusion\" and \"compatible\" has to do with my choice of preferred definitions. I recognize that. But the definitional distinction is an important one in my mind. ','2012-03-24 22:00:54','2012-03-24 22:00:54'),(1298,1,64,'Hi James,\r\n\r\nYes, the fact that that is the way it was done in Chalmer\'s and other primitive surveys is precisely the problem, and why we created Canonizer.com in the first place.  Many experts want to join multiple camps (I would want to do this in this case, like Mike), and want to provide much more specific definitions of what they mean, and so on, when they did or didn\'t select a particular answer from any limited set.  Primitive surveys like that are completely worthless.  Everyone just argues over what experts really meant when they did or didn\'t check any of the check boxes, so you can\'t use it to convince anyone of anything, or to show any kind of consensus of any value, since anyone can believe anything they want about what any experts meant when they did or didn\'t check any particular box.  I\'ve experienced this with people many times.\r\n\r\nAnd, yes, I was hoping that moving this illusion doctrine into the compatible camp would include being more specific about definitions.  For example, it must be explicit that the kind of free will already defined in the camp (getting that which is better) is not an illusion.\r\n\r\nI was hoping to also specify a different kind of free will than that, something like it \'seems\' like some unitary \"we\" has all the power over the choice, and that there is no deterministic or programmed causes and effects, in some kind of indefinable and mysteriously culpable way.  I think everyone in the compatible camp would agree with such, if the definitions were concisely specified in the right way.\r\n\r\nAlso, I see evidence of you and most other people of thinking of Canonizer.com like a traditional survey in this and other ways, in other topics.  This is completely the wrong way to think about it.  Everyone should be working, as much as possible, to have the fewest possible camps.\r\n\r\nThe goal of everyone, should be to have just one, easy for everyone to read, if not a single supper camp, that includes all doctrines agreed on by everyone, then having it all in the \'agreement statement\' at the root.  Any time there are differences of opinion such that it requires multiple camps, it should be specified exactly what would be required, or why anyone cannot be a part of competing camps, including lack of experimental evidence, or whatever.  This to explain to experimentalists, what will be required, to win over everyone else, and so on.  Primitive surveys are static, where Canonizer.com is meant to constantly improve, and increase the amount of consensus, especially about any natural sciences, or predictions about such.\r\n\r\nIn many places, people have created way to many lonely camps, containing doctrines that many, if not most of the people in existing camps, would completely agree with.  It is far better to assume you can improve an existing camp with more consensus, even if it appears to be significantly different,  to be what you want it to be.  There is a good chance that someone just started an existing camp, quickly, off the top of their head, and that they really wanted it to be like what you\'d also like it to be.  Only fork or create a new camp when it finally becomes clear that there is no way to achieve all \"the improvements\", you\'d like to see.\r\n\r\nWhen I\'ve talked like this before, you\'ve pointed out that diversity of  opinion isn\'t a bad thing.  And I completely agree.  In many still theoretical things, diversity of opinion is a good thing.  We desperately need to have real motivated people to cover all possible bases, and to know who these people are.  But, after this top priority, we should find as much, easy fore everyone to read, consensus, as possible.\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-03-25 01:36:12','2012-03-25 01:36:12'),(1299,1,26,'Hey Brent,\r\n\r\nThanks for the note. I don\'t really know how this works, so please feel free to do whatever you think makes the most sense. A couple of notes:\r\n\r\n1) I don\'t fully understand the structure of these camps, so I am probably approaching this incorrectly.\r\n\r\n2) There was no \"Representational Qualia\" camp in the section to which I posted. It now appears that there are two sections discussing the nature of consciousness - or I misunderstand the division between them.\r\n\r\n3) It appears that Representational Qualia contains the basics of the idea I have expressed. I can\'t quite parse the rest of it, however, and \"qualia\" isn\'t necessarily a category I would have used.\r\n\r\nFeel free to correct any misunderstandings I have here.','2012-03-25 21:03:57','2012-03-25 21:03:57'),(1302,96,48,'I couldn\'t resist, I just made the below edit to the [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Na%C3%AFve_realism#Chuck_Norris_Fact Wikipedida article on Naive Realism].  How long do you think it will last?\r\n\r\n= Chuck Norris Fact =\r\n\r\nNaive realism is true, at least for Chuck Norris.  He really knows what it is like to be a bat.(1)\r\n\r\n== Reference: ==\r\n\r\n(1) Nagel, Thomas. \"What is it like to be a bat?\", Mortal Questions, Cambridge University Press, 1979, p. 166.\r\n\r\n','2012-03-27 07:46:34','2012-03-27 07:46:34'),(1303,1,92,'James\r\n\r\nI don\'t see any significant differences between your statement and the current majority camp which also recognises abstinence as one possibility.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard','2012-03-27 13:30:01','2012-03-27 13:30:01'),(1304,1,92,'The current majority camp is \"all safe sex is ok\". It\'s camp statement reads:\r\n\r\n<begin quote>\r\n\r\nIt is difficult for parents and children to talk about Sex. Because of this, societies tend to be sexually repressed and under educated, especially if the society is religious based. This is never healthy for anyone. This needs to be completely overcome so everyone is literate on all sexual issues and potential problems. \"Safe Sex\" includes much more than just prevention of disease and unwanted pregnancy. It also requires that no socially unhealthy behavior is engaged in. We believe a very high set of standards should be laid out which are difficult for all people to achieve, especially if they are still socially immature. But, if these high standards can be met, there is no problem with some amount of sex.\r\nChildren\'s natural curiosity and desire for sex should be bridled and leveraged in this way to drive and increase awareness of what is required for behavior that is healthy in all ways for all people involved.\r\n\r\n<end quote>\r\n\r\nAbstinence is not mentioned. So it seems to me that there is a significant difference. I didn\'t just try to change the camp statement though, because I couldn\'t see how any camp with the NAME \"all safe sex is ok\" could EVER match my opinion, which is that we should teach them that abstinence is best, while still teaching them how to have safER sex if they choose to not be abstinent. ','2012-03-27 17:08:17','2012-03-27 17:08:17'),(1305,1,92,'James\r\n\r\nI agree with you that the \"Safe sex is OK\" camp statement does differ from yours and it also differs from the statement under \"Comprehensive public sex education is important\" which is the one which i was referring to and which does mention abstinence.\r\n\r\nThere are 2 sub camps under \"Public sex education\": either you\'re for or against it.\r\n\r\nThe general case for pse is stated under \"Comprehensive public sex education is important\" and IMO your statement should be merged with it and not be placed under it as a subcamp. The subcamps state the the varying views as to what type of pse there should be.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard','2012-03-28 08:05:30','2012-03-28 08:05:30'),(1306,1,92,'Those are some good thoughts, But here\'s my reasons for doing it this way. You wrote: \"The subcamps state the the varying views as to what type of pse there should be.\" EXACTLY... and that is the point of my camp. There is no way to determine WHICH people want ONLY abstinence, which want ONLY safe sex, and which want BOTH, unless you have all three as SUB camps, that people can join. The parent camp is no place to express the TYPES of education people want, because that is a contested view. It is just the place to say that we want SOME form of public sex education, because THAT is all there appears to be consensus on. The type issue is controversial, and so should be battled out in the sub camps. There is a sub camp for abstinence only, and one for safe sex only. Why should those that believe that there should be both be in the parent camp? After all, if we wrote the parent camp in that way, then the two sub camps would have to leave it, since they wouldn\'t agree. \r\n\r\nDoes this make sense?','2012-03-28 23:31:36','2012-03-28 23:31:36'),(1307,1,92,'And as you pointed out, the \"safe sex only\" sub camp disagrees with its parent camp already... The point is to push the issue of disagreement out to the leaf nodes, so that the parent camp can become something all the leaf nodes can agree upon. So my next edit was going to be to the parent camp, to remove all mention of the TYPE of public sex education the people want. But I was kind of waiting to see how people\'s support shifted first. ','2012-03-28 23:34:41','2012-03-28 23:34:41'),(1310,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nThere has recently been some significant changes to the Representational Qualia Theory camp, and itâ€™s sub camp structure.  Here is a summary of these changes.\r\n\r\nJames Carroll and Mike Gashler, once supporters of the Functional Property Dualism camp, noticed that the â€œProperty Dualismâ€ doctrine, as it was defined and contained in the Representational Qualia Theory camp statement â€“ is problematic.  Basically, they are not â€˜property dualistsâ€™.\r\n\r\nSo, we pushed this doctrine out of the Representational Qualia Theory camp statement, into a new sub camp named [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/19  â€œProperty Dualismâ€].  Then James and Mike created the new competing sub camp [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/18 Representational Functionalism].\r\n\r\nA big part of this misunderstanding has to do with less than clear definitions of â€œQualiaâ€, and â€œPhenomenal propertiesâ€ and I think lack of clear definitions of what people do and don\'t mean by these terms is the cause of significant problems in this field.  Obviously, some people think of these terms in very different ways than others, making communication impossible.\r\n\r\nI believe property dualists think of these things as follows:\r\n\r\nThe term â€˜qualeâ€™ and â€˜phenomenal propertyâ€™ are synonyms.  They refer to \'ineffable\' properties of nature which suffer from the quale interpretation problem, as currently defined in the RQT statement.  If you don\'t know how to properly interpret an abstract word like \'salty\', you can\'t know what it means, or what it is like for a specific person.  That is what \'ineffable\' means.\r\n\r\nThe current Property Dualism statement defines quale and since it is a synonym, a phenomenal property to be \"that which cannot be communicated by abstract information alone, without knowing how to properly interpret the representations.\"  So, by definition, people that believe quale can arise from software, are talking about something very different than this.\r\n\r\nThe proposed statement for the new competing [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/18 Representational Functionalism] camp (scheduled to go live This Fri - set the as of value to review to see before then) states:  \"we deny the existence of any \'phenomenal\' properties such as are claimed by the property dualists\"\r\n\r\nWhich is obviously threatening the liberal usage of this term \"phenomenal properties\" in the current RQT statement.  This is threatening because if this is really true, this is something else that needs to be removed from the RQT camp, along with Property Dualism.\r\n\r\nSo, my question to the new anti \"property dualists\", or supporters of the new \"Representational Functionalist\" camp is: can we come up with any definition of this word \'phenomenal\' which we can all agree on, so that we can continue to use it in RQT, and so on.\r\n\r\nObviously, you are happy using the term \'qualia\', so if you assume \'phenomenal property\' is the exact same thing, how is this a problem?  What is it, beyond qualia, that you think \'phenomenal property\' means, that you object to?\r\n\r\nAlso, when we are talking to \"Representational Functionalists\", what terminology can we use, to describe \'ineffable\' properties?  And what does the term \'ineffable\' mean to you, when we say to you quale are ineffable?  And so on?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-04-03 01:38:02','2012-04-03 01:38:02'),(1313,96,48,'Some considerations on the ineffability of qualia.\r\n\r\nTo understand the critical flaw with RQT, it helps to understand that the ineffability of qualia is not a problem, rather the inadequacy of language to represent primary sense presentations reveals the subordinate function of representation. By focusing the ineffability of qualia, the debate is framed in a way which privileges representation and communication over first hand experience from the start. My own understanding is that the privacy of qualia is an ontological conjugate to the public topologies of quanta. The fact of its privacy is important but incidental compared to the visceral, concrete experiential content of qualia themselves.\r\n\r\nTo re-present something - whether it is the optical reflection of an orange tree, or a complex neurological computation which digitally maps to an analog of that reflection, requires that it is being represented by something else. That something else could be called a sensorimotive presentation, a sensation, perception, feeling, qualia, experience, etc. \r\n\r\nThe problem with such a presentation layer is that it doesn\'t make any sense if we come to it from an assumption of mechanism. There is no possible advantage for such a redundant epiphenomenon to be developed, let alone any possible mechanism by which literal phenomena can re-present themselves as anything other than what they are. Were we not inundated with these perceptions constantly ourselves, we could have no inkling that such a thing could exist.\r\n\r\nHow then to come to an agreement between the steam roller of RQT functionalism and the hot house flower of the essence of subjectivity? You can\'t. They are mutually exclusive. The whole point of RQT is to de-present qualia and qualia is nothing but the presentation of sense. Blindsight and synesthesia alone should be enough to reveal that RQT is off the mark, since sense function is possible to some extent without any qualia or with mismatched qualia.','2012-04-03 02:56:20','2012-04-03 02:56:20'),(1316,96,48,'Hi Multisense,\r\n\r\nI apologize for having such a difficult time understanding Mutlisense Realism, since it is so different from the way I think about this stuff.\r\n\r\nI have a few questions for you Given Multisense realism.\r\n\r\nWhat are the differences between the properties of an, as you say, \"orange tree\" and how are these properties different from the properties of this \"something else.. which could be called a sensorimotive presentation, a sensation, perception, feeling, qualia, experience, etc.\"?\r\n\r\nWill it ever be possible to \'eff\' the ineffable, as in to find out if my redness is anything like your redness, or perhaps like your greenness, or maybe even something like you\'ve never experienced before in your life?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-04-03 03:40:59','2012-04-03 03:40:59'),(1317,1,92,'James\r\n\r\nOk, i get it now :)\r\n\r\nThe camp statement supporting pse should be general while the details differentiate the subcamps.\r\n\r\nThat\'s the way to do it!\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard','2012-04-03 09:05:28','2012-04-03 09:05:28'),(1320,96,48,'>Hi Multisense,\r\n>\r\n>I apologize for having such a difficult time understanding Mutlisense\r\n>Realism, since it is so different from the way I think about this\r\n>stuff.\r\n\r\nThanks. It\'s ok, I think I would have reacted the same way to it myself if I had read it from some random person on the internet. I\'m trying to get it down to manageable chunks for TSC. Have an advance preview of my poster under http://www.stationlink.com/multisenserealism if you like (newest and hopefully best version is 8a.pdf). If you do, feel free to give me feedback on what works or what doesn\'t - what could be expanded, etc. Anything that seems constructive would be appreciated. \r\n\r\n>\r\n>I have a few questions for you Given Multisense realism.\r\n>\r\n>What are the differences between the properties of an, as you say,\r\n>\"orange tree\" and how are these properties different from the\r\n>properties of this \"something else.. which could be called a\r\n>sensorimotive presentation, a sensation, perception, feeling, qualia,\r\n>experience, etc.\"?\r\n\r\nThe actual or noumenal orange tree is that which provides different properties depending on who or what is interacting with it and how they are doing that. To an ant, the bark of the tree is geography or real estate, but the tree as a whole probably has no properties other than maybe a feeling of its shade and aromatic qualities.\r\n\r\nThere are levels in which the entire tree responds as a single organism, levels where it responds as a part of a forest, a climate, or biosphere, and levels where the tree is lost in a microcosm of cells and molecules. All of these levels overlap and make sense in different contexts. They can interact in series and in parallel.\r\n\r\nIs the orange tree a set of quantitative measurements and forms which are in theory independent from all forms of observation, or is it the sum or all possible sense presentations from all perspectives for all time? Is an orange seed an orange tree? Is the DNA of an orange tree an orange tree? Can an orange tree really be defined without bringing in the whole history of Mesozoic Era flora on Earth?\r\n\r\nI know it\'s crazy but I think that answer may be something like \'an orange tree\' is an inertial bundle of perturbations in the totality of the cosmos. \r\n\r\nA perturbation of the Totality diffracts through though itself, so that whatever observer (itself a perturbation in the totality) receives a properties of the orange tree\'s perceptual inertia in the form of a diffraction with the observer\'s own perceptual inertia. The diffraction of subject and object is sense, and it recapitulates phenomenologically the net difference and similarity between the two. \r\n\r\nThe similarity is perceived as augmented phases or sequences of sense (significance, experience, and ultimately \'time\') and the difference cannot be perceived directly but must be measured indirectly as mechanism (evolution, entropy, and ultimately \'space\').\r\n\r\nOn the exterior, I model it like a pyramid or ziggurat that is a stack of a particular ranges of frequencies, scales, forms, mechanisms, and relations which persist in such a way that the observer sees what is beneath them as being more of a machine which \'simply is\' while the forms closest to the self (in size, frequency, character) are increasingly open to \'seems like\' interpretation. Dualism is literally in the eye of the beholder, as the further one looks away from oneself, the more subjective identification decoheres.\r\n\r\nOn the interior, it is more like Indra\'s Net. Still a hierarchy of interior conjugates to the external frames (a group of cells might make us sense something, a few groups of cells might make us \'feel\' something, etc... it scales up as qualitative depth and richness of perception) but instead of having its roots in existential forms and objects divided across space, the interior has its roots in the Totality/Singularity. Think of the T/S like a Terminal Server. Each identity gets its own profile which is generic in some sense and open to unique customization in another. The TS itself is the hub of spacetime, and all events within spacetime occur, on the most primordial level, in a single \'now\' that spans the entire continuum from the instantaneous to the eternal. Causality and time arise as experiences of perturbations within the TS.\r\n\r\nWhen we see an orange tree then, we are seeing a little holographic slice, our human-hominid-animal-Earthling flavored slice of what the tree means, how it makes sense with the rest of the cosmos from your vantage point. Its qualitative properties are instructive not only about what the tree is good for to us evolutionarily (in a compressed, subconscious way - fruit looks, smells, and tastes, like something we want to eat to survive) but the whole presentation reveals perception itself. The symmetries and metaphors, the organic aesthetic principles, the cycle of seed-plant-tree-fruit-seed... it\'s all TS bootstrap code to help us orient ourselves and reflect back to us both who we are and where we are.\r\n\r\n>Will it ever be possible to \'eff\' the ineffable, as in to find out if\r\n>my redness is anything like your redness, or perhaps like your\r\n>greenness, or maybe even something like you\'ve never experienced before\r\n>in your life?\r\n\r\nThere may be an easier way, but for now the only way I can think of is to surgically merge our brain with another brain or with a more universal merging appliance. There are brain conjoined twins who already share minds, so it would just be a matter of technology and ethics to allow us to extend that across a digital network.\r\n\r\nThis is not to say we can\'t record or produce full sensory movies that can give us an experience of virtual reality that extends to making changes in who we feel like we are. Its hard to guess to what extent a feelie-movie produced for a general audience would translate into our individual hardware (different brain, different diffraction of sense) so I don\'t anticipate that a baby can become a full grown adult by watching a two hour brain movie (although re-releasing A Clockwork Orange in 10-D qualia might come close).\r\n\r\nAnyhow, the thing with qualia is that even though it is private by definition (because it is the unification-seeking \'time\' ontology which is symmetric to the fragmentation-entropy \'space\' topology that is by definition public), it can be shared. Intimacy, expression, art, music, culture...all of civilization would be a blank slate if we could easily match each others inner states exactly. It\'s the obstacle, the diffraction that brings out sense and motive to bridge the gap.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-04-03 13:42:12','2012-04-03 13:42:12'),(1323,96,48,'James and I have put together a statement that we think may represent what all supporters of RQT have in common. We have tried to throw out the phrases that have been creating controversy and keep only the most important claims pertaining to RQT. Most notably, it is much shorter. So, I propose that we replace the existing camp statement with this one. What do you (all) think?\r\n\r\n\r\n<begin>\r\nRepresentational Qualia Theory defines qualia as our subjective experiences (for example, seeing a red strawberry). These subjective experiences are entirely representational experiences. The following example will illustrate what we mean by \"representational\" experiences:\r\n\r\nStrawberries have the causal property of reflecting red light. After reflected red light passes into our human eyes and stimulates the cones on the back of our retinas, we will (in consequence of this signal, and nothing else) form a virtual model in our heads indicating that we believe there is a strawberry out there.This model is not part of the strawberry, nor is it a property of the strawberry. It is only a representation of the strawberry. We derive the \"phenomenal\" experience of seeing red from this model (and not from any contribution by anything else). Hence, the strawberry may be causally red, but this representative model possesses all traits that may be called \"phenomenally red\".\r\n\r\nThe only position asserted in this camp is that experiences of qualia are derived completely and exclusively from representative models in our heads. More specific claims about the nature of qualia, the possible existence of phenomenal properties, theories about the nature or formation of representative models, and so forth are made in child camps.\r\n<end>\r\n','2012-04-03 19:20:10','2012-04-03 19:20:10'),(1326,96,48,'I think that this camp statement would be a VAST improvement over the old one. For example, I don\'t buy the \"greatest discovery\" over hype. Also I myself do NOT believe in this definition of qualia: \r\n\r\n\"The current Property Dualism statement defines quale and since it is a synonym, a phenomenal property to be \"that which cannot be communicated by abstract information alone, without knowing how to properly interpret the representations.\" \r\n\r\nI don\'t believe it because I believe that the \"apparent\" problem is just one of communication, and is not a fundamental principle of nature. In other words: Mary learns something, but not what epiphenomenalists think. \r\n\r\nLet\'s say that I store information about other people\'s brains in compartment A. The experience of red changes neurons in compartment B. Mary stores all information that she knows about other people\'s experience of red in her compartment A. When she sees red for the first time, neurons in compartment B change, so she \"learns something.\" But that does NOT mean that qualia must be epiphenomenal, depend on magic \"phenomenal properties\" such as are claimed by Chalmers etc. \r\n\r\nSo honestly, there are MANY things that I disagree with in RQT. Property Dualism, AND the qualia interpretation problem (apparently). But I agree with the general principle of representationalism. We don\'t see the strawberry, we see our internal models of the strawberry, which are connected to the strawberry by a causal chain. \r\n\r\nSo, I believe that the question is, how best to express this agreement with representationalism, while pushing the issues of disagreement down into the sub camps. I think that Brent can put all his \"qualia interpretation problem\" stuff, and \"greatest discovery\" stuff down in the new PD camp, and the rest of us can be left with a representationalist camp that we can all agree on.','2012-04-03 20:04:17','2012-04-03 20:04:17'),(1329,96,48,'I am surprised to read that there is a thing called \'red light\'. Where is the redness in red light?\r\nrolfk','2012-04-03 20:38:40','2012-04-03 20:38:40'),(1332,96,48,'How about if we open with a glossary like this:\r\n\r\nGlossary:\r\n\r\n\"light\" refers to electromagnetic radiation.\r\n\"red light\" means light with a wavelength between 620â€“750 nm, and does not imply that such light possesses any phenomenal properties.\r\n\"quale\" refers to a subjective experience, such as seeing a red strawberry.\r\n\"qualia\" is the plural of \"quale\".\r\n\"representational\" means that something is represented with a virtual model.\r\n\"phenomenal\" refers to indescribable and personal experience involving qualia.\r\n\r\nCamp Statement:\r\n\r\nblah, blah, blah.\r\n','2012-04-03 21:43:38','2012-04-03 21:43:38'),(1335,96,48,'I think that it is misleading, especially when you are talking about defining qualia, to refer to electromagnetic radiation as being light at all. It\'s no more light than radio signals are light. Likewise there is nothing red about any range of wavelengths except for their correlation with certain responses by retinal cells which we experience as a red visual feeling. Of course red need not be associated with realtime optical stimulation at all, so that we can visualize red whenever we want without anything in our brain turning red or producing visible range photons (that would be a homunculus situation).\r\n\r\nThe idea of a \'virtual model\' is even more abstract than red light that isn\'t red or light. We shouldn\'t forget that every experience that any person has ever had of the universe is nothing but this virtual model. What is the virtual model made of? Why is it necessary or useful? Why is perception of this metaphysical, unexplained model any less mysterious than direct perception of a concrete relationship between subject and the subject\'s world?','2012-04-03 23:44:10','2012-04-03 23:44:10'),(1338,96,48,'Multisense,\r\n\r\nRegarding \"red light\", you are right that I was being imprecise. How about if we replace each occurrence of \"red light\" with \"ER700\", and add a glossary entry to the effect of \"ER700 refers to electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength between 620â€“750 nanometers (which is the range humans see as \'red light\').\" ?\r\n\r\nRegarding \"virtual model\", I am being deliberately abstract. Your questions about this model are very interesting, but the RQT camp statement is not the right place to address them. These are precisely the sort of questions that we want to formally pontificate and debate by creating child camps within RQT.\r\n\r\nThe child camp that I support is \"Representational Functionalism\", which claims that \"red\" is the human mind\'s attempt to model the physical property of things that reflect ER700. We believe that this model is comprised of information. This is significant because it implies that a Turing machine is sufficient to reproduce experiences of qualia. This philosophy is \"less mysterious\" because it suggests that the brain need only be a computing machine in order to implement consciousness.\r\n\r\nI would be very interested to hear responses to the same set of questions from someone in the property dualism camp (which is currently the most popular child camp of RQT).\r\n\r\n--Mike\r\n','2012-04-05 03:44:04','2012-04-05 03:44:04'),(1341,96,48,'The wavelength information regarding redness continues to be inaccurate. What about the redness perceived from stimuli in the 380-470 or so nm wavelength region? Redness is obviously related to a mechanism involving L and S cone absorption. Redness logically ranges from next to unique yellow (around 575 nm) to next to unique blue (around 475 nm), including the whole region of non-spectral purple hues. A simple long-wave spectral definition is not valid.','2012-04-05 18:39:38','2012-04-05 18:39:38'),(1344,96,48,'\"Redness is obviously related to a mechanism involving L and S cone absorption.\"\r\n\r\nThen there\'s this too: â€œThere is no correlation between cone ratio and unique yellow settings. These results support the idea that the relative cone ratios are not primary determinant of the balance point of the red-green opponent channel. â€œ\r\n\r\nhttp://color.psych.upenn.edu/brainard/papers/AIC01.pdf\r\n\r\nEven further, color arises only when that the cellular sensitivity in the retina is related to the sensitivity of the neurons in the visual cortex, the results of which are driven as much by top-down expectations as bottom up optical detection values. You can see what I mean: http://www.tumblr.com/photo/1280/s33/18445766981/1/tumblr_m049toH1001qeenqk\r\n\r\nA and B are the same shade of grey when measured optically but what we see is entirely relative to the visual context.\r\n\r\nConsider how painful it can be to bite down on a metal fork even though nothing is directly contacting the nerves deep in your teeth. We would not expect sensation to carry through something as hard as tooth enamel, but it actually adds sense qualities - extends them as an antenna might amplify signal reception.\r\n\r\nThis I think should give us a clue as to how perception works. We can\'t examine it externally by correlating mechanisms of objects in space, we can only understand it by feeling the experience. The experience is that we see the world through our eyes and in our imagination. It is one continuous or gestalt inertial frame of perception. Perception is a concentrating principle which extracts coherent wholes from elided from parts. Even though we can examine fragments of the brain and body to model them as mechanisms, such details are beneath the threshold of the native subject\'s inertial frame and therefore give us misleading, partial accounts of lower inertial frames rather than the top level awareness which relates to us.\r\n\r\n\"claims that \"red\" is the human mind\'s attempt to model the physical property of things that reflect ER700\"\r\nIf anything, red is the human mind\'s attempt to model the cells of the retina\'s attempt to model the optical environment of the human body\'s world. Anything more reductionist than that fails to address anything more than a straw man of perception. Of course, I would go further to say that the idea of a \"model\" is superfluous and occurs to us only as a second-hand strategy employed by our cognitive activities. If we need a model to see through our own eyes, then there is no reason to think that retinal cells also need a model, and if they did, why wouldn\'t the models need models also? At some point something has to sense something, so the addition of abstraction layers to me seems redundant. Seeing a model that looks red is no less magical than seeing red.','2012-04-05 20:22:32','2012-04-05 20:22:32'),(1347,96,48,'This is great stuff, but the immediate objective here is to repair the RQT camp statement. Could I prevail upon you to:\r\n1- Propose a new statement,\r\n2- Propose specific wording refinements to one of the candidate statements, or\r\n3- Express support for the existing RQT camp statement?','2012-04-05 22:27:32','2012-04-05 22:27:32'),(1350,96,48,'Ultimately I could only get behind an RQT that proposed an intentional focus on the representational aspects of qualia as the most promising approach for understanding it. Without addressing the hard problem of consciousness directly, we can potentially learn more about even the ineffable aspects of qualia by understanding the neurological mechanisms associated with perception and mathematical models of how they process information.\r\n\r\nIn the short term, I guess I would steer clear of trying to pin down particular qualia and focus on the need for some stable index to anchor conscious perceptions. IMO, RQT cannot explain consciousness, but given consciousness, it can explain why representation would be the most important use of it, evolutionarily speaking.','2012-04-06 01:43:23','2012-04-06 01:43:23'),(1353,96,48,'Okay, here\'s another draft (below). This draft tries to dodge the issue of defining red light. It contains no references to a \"model\", and it makes no claims about consciousness. Without the strawberry example, it just felt like a string of hollow vocabulary words, so I left that in. If you really want to get rid of that, I will need some specific help with the wording. Is it getting any better? It is also waning rather terse--have I dropped any important concepts that should be included?\r\n\r\n--Mike\r\n\r\n\r\n<begin>\r\nTerms: \r\n\"we\" refers to humans in general.\r\n\"quale\" refers to a subjective experience, such as seeing a red strawberry.\r\n\"qualia\" is the plural of \"quale\".\r\n\"phenomenal\" refers to an indescribable and personal experience involving qualia. \r\n\"RER\" refers electromagnetic radiation in any frequency that humans would see as red light.\r\n\r\nCamp Statement: \r\nRepresentational Qualia Theory asserts that we derive qualia from our internal representations, rather than from an ability to directly detect phenomenal properties. For example, suppose we look at a strawberry and experiences the quale of red. Although it is true that the strawberry has the causal property of reflecting RER, the \"redness\" that we experience is not a property of the strawberry. Rather, this quale emerges from the representation of the strawberry that we form within our eyes and/or brain after dectecting the RER that reflected off the surface of the strawberry.\r\n<end>\r\n','2012-04-06 16:38:08','2012-04-06 16:38:08'),(1356,96,48,'Here is my proposal for revisions of the statement:\r\n\r\nbegin> Terms: \"we\" refers to humans in general. \"quale\" refers to a subjective experience, such as resulting from viewing a ripe strawberry. \"qualia\" is the plural of \"quale\". \"phenomenal\" refers to an indescribable and personal experience involving qualia. \"RER\" refers to a class of electromagnetic radiation signatures that, when interacting with the retina of color-normal humans, results in experiences of redness. \r\n \r\nCamp Statement: Representational Qualia Theory asserts that we derive qualia from our internal representations, rather than from an ability to directly detect phenomenal properties. For example, suppose we look at a ripe strawberry and experience the quale of red. Although it is true that the strawberry has the causal property of reflecting RER, the \"redness\" that we experience is not a property of the strawberry. Rather, this quale emerges from the representation of the strawberry that we form within our eyes and/or brain after dectecting RER reflected by the surface of the strawberry. <end>\r\n','2012-04-06 19:33:05','2012-04-06 19:33:05'),(1359,96,48,'That isn\'t exactly how I would say it, but close enough. I would support that camp statement. ','2012-04-06 19:37:43','2012-04-06 19:37:43'),(1362,96,48,'I agree. Sounds pretty good.','2012-04-06 20:16:47','2012-04-06 20:16:47'),(1365,96,48,'It sounds like we are suggesting that light-signatures (as opposed to light itself) bounce off the surface of the strawberry. Is this deliberate? I don\'t know enough physics terminology to know which is correct--I\'m just checking because this seems odd to me.','2012-04-07 15:43:13','2012-04-07 15:43:13'),(1368,96,48,'That\'s where my hypothesis comes in. I think there is nothing literally bouncing off of the strawberry at all. If you use an instrument designed to detect photons being emitted from the surface of a strawberry, then you get measurable changes in the instrument which are clearly...instrumental. This is an indirect observation though. The idea that there are independent particles-waves in space is inferred. We have no ability see what our instruments \'see\' only what they \'do\' physically in response to RER stimulation.\r\n\r\nIf you use a human eye and mind to look at the strawberry directly you see no photons, you see an image of a strawberry which is whole and present. Within the human perceptual inertial frame, there literally are no photons or light signatures, only visual qualitative gestalts with optical-physical referents. What we see is literally real. It is not a re-presentation, but an authentic presentation - as real as an atom or a brick, only it is interior to the psyche so that it can be used figuratively to represent many associations simultaneously on many levels of sense.\r\n\r\nIf you want to just stick to our inherited 20th century physics model, there really is no explanation for the experience of seeing through light at all...just speculation that somehow out of a torrent of quintillions of subatomic and cellular \'signals\', some concentration or coherence is achieved (for no particular reason)  that is \'displayed\'. This display, I assume would have to be directed metaphysically to an illusion-of-selfhood, a superfluous and impotent spectator for physical processes beyond its understanding.','2012-04-07 16:19:18','2012-04-07 16:19:18'),(1369,1,46,'To me it seems there are two working definitions of consciousness: The phenomenal and the physical. The distinction between these two I feel is key, because - for example in my theory - the phenomenal consciousness (i.e. the sum total of an individual\'s qualia) is in fact NOT approachable via science in any meaningful sense as it is composed private epiphenomena which exist in their own dimension. However, the physical mechanistic consciousness (i.e. the ever nebulous region/regions of the brain which lead to qualitative experience) - it seems - is approachable via science. Any thoughts on this?','2012-04-07 16:22:54','2012-04-07 16:22:54'),(1370,1,46,'To me it seems there are two working definitions of consciousness: The phenomenal and the physical. The distinction between these two I feel is key, because - for example in my theory - the phenomenal consciousness (i.e. the sum total of an individual\'s qualia) is in fact NOT approachable via science in any meaningful sense as it is composed private epiphenomena which exist in their own dimension. However, the physical mechanistic consciousness (i.e. the ever nebulous region/regions of the brain which lead to qualitative experience) - it seems - is approachable via science. Any thoughts on this?','2012-04-07 16:23:07','2012-04-07 16:23:07'),(1371,1,46,'My proposal is that the two definitions you describe can, themselves, be understood in two different ways - one as you suggest, two distinct categories with a cause > effect relationship, and another as a single continuum or spectrum of sense which is both inseparably physical and phenomenal but diffracted, like the electromagnetic spectrum. \r\n\r\nI consider that the electromagnetic spectrum represents a diffraction of a single force/field into quantitative wavelength-frequencies (scales of spatio-temporal repetition) that can be described in terms of magnetic and electric effects on matter. We infer that there are invisible, intangible forces propagating through space as \'energy\' when I am increasingly convinced that while this model is probably necessary to model physical phenomena, what is actually happening is that we are projecting mechanism onto a distant and unfamiliar perceptual frame (or \'world\'). \r\n\r\nWhy we project unconscious manipulation by external forces rather than scaled down sense and motive in the microcosm is explained through the symmetry of sense and motive itself. Just as the amplitude of magnetic strength runs orthogonally to the amplitude of electric strength (and I think this is what EM is, a \'waving\' of potency or force of sensitivity and motive power rather than literal waves-of-\'energy\' that exist independently of matter), I suggest that there is a sense-motive conjugate to electro-magnetism. This conjugate is absolutely symmetrical to EM in every way. Where EM is literal, generic, external, public, a-signifying, entropic, etc, SM is the contrary; figurative, proprietary, internal, private, signifying, teleological, etc. \r\n\r\nThis symmetry is so absolute and universal, and our immersion within it so inescapable, that we cannot see the forest for the trees, so to speak. I call it \'the elephant in every room\'. Not only splitting our attention between the forest and the trees problematic, we would need to add to that a splitting of the sense of a literal forest made of literal trees outside and a figurative tree of figurative forests inside. Just as this paragraph exists as a physical hierarchy of sentences, words, characters, pixels, and electronically manipulated matter across space, there is an experiential narrative that can be recovered *through* the experience of reading and understanding (don\'t get me started on understanding... http://multisenserealism.com/2012/04/07/we-come-from-the-land-down-nter/). This meaningful experience can be said to \'insist\' and it can be described as figurative also as it attracts and binds many associations on many levels but has no central body, rather than a literal body that must be literally associated with other physical bodies by sharing the same space.\r\n\r\nThe notion that everything \'makes sense\' in its own way, and that sense itself limits us from making sense of that very fact is convoluted but I think that it is probably the case. I think that Sense - Motive - \'time\' has to the primitive cosmic essential, and that it reflects back on itself as Matter - Energy - \'space\'. Space and time are ultimately nothing more than cavities separating-multiplying matter-energy (space) and sense-motive (time).\r\n\r\nI know this is probably dense and exhausting to try to follow - I try to make it as concise as I can, but it\'s really a whole new view of the cosmos. It\'s not at all unprecedented, Leibniz, Spinoza, mystics like Jacob Boehme and Robert Fludd were on to the same kinds of ideas but I think that what they lacked in scientific grounding can now begin to be recovered. I think that what we have seen in quantum physics and information theory has taken us into a metaphysical never-never land of de-presented realism and re-presented alienation from realism. Only through the understanding of perception can we begin to grasp how empiricism itself inherently obscures subjectivity and makes it appear as its symmetrical doppleganger. The puppet master turns himself into a puppet of external forces.\r\n\r\nUsing a Multisense Realism framework instead, we can see human consciousness as the top of a nested hierarchy of subconscious sensorimotive-phenomenological/electromagnetic-physical integrated inertial frames (worlds). We ourselves are a part of larger/higher inertial frames that we are weaving though our attention and actions together and which draw us progressively ahead, black monolith style, to our own teleological super-significance. \r\n\r\nAnyways, I should get packed and everything for TSC. Anyone else going? Let me know if you want to meet up. ','2012-04-07 18:51:39','2012-04-07 18:51:39'),(1374,96,48,'Given how you have described multisense realism, I would say that it is incompatible with RQT, and we shouldn\'t try to write a RQT statement that would incorporate MR. It should form its own camp I think. \r\n','2012-04-08 16:51:45','2012-04-08 16:51:45'),(1377,96,48,'\r\nFolks,\r\n\r\nJust and FYI, that I\'m most out of town, attending the MTA conference and TSC in Tucson, all next week.\r\n\r\nSo haven\'t had much chance to work on t he reorganization of the RQT camp.\r\n\r\nLove all I\'ve seen so far, and all the work going into this.\r\n\r\nI\'ll be able to finally get to this, once I get back from the TSC conference next week.\r\n\r\nI\'m working on a response to the proposals, so look forward to completing that and posting it here, when I return.\r\n\r\nI know at least some of you are attending TSC, so I\'m looking forward to seeing some of you there!!!\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-04-08 16:54:32','2012-04-08 16:54:32'),(1380,96,48,'Hi Brent,\r\nI appreciate your continued work on the Canoniser.  I am sorry I missed the announcement about moving all groups under Mind-Brain Identity theory to be under property dualism because I should have put my two cents worth in at that point. \r\nI see Mind-Brain Identity [MBI] as not a duality, and likewise for the processes identifiable with consciousness, therefore I think MBI should be directly under Representational Qualia [RQ] and UMSITW directly under MBI. I really do think it just muddies the waters to link MBI with any mention of dualism/duality.\r\nHowever, if other people think that MBI should be under Property Dualism then UMSITW must migrate to its own discrete pozzie directly under RQ. Anything else would not be consistent with what UMSITW is about.\r\n\r\nCheers, \r\nMark \r\n','2012-04-08 18:03:10','2012-04-08 18:03:10'),(1383,96,48,'Yes, MR is already a camp under Panexperientialism. I was trying to play Devil\'s advocate for RQT but found that the closest I can come is to suggest RQT avoid talking about the qualia aspect and focus on representation - which I think is a valid and worthwhile focus and a lot can be learned about qualia that way I think.','2012-04-08 21:53:41','2012-04-08 21:53:41'),(1386,96,48,'Regarding Mike G.s comment: I used \'signatures\' to indicate that many different kinds of spectral compositions of electromagnetic radiation bouncing off the ripe strawberry can result in the same perceived appearance due to metamerism. I did not think it would help in the statement to make this explicit.\r\nRegarding the MultisenseR comment: I do not think anything is gained by denying the validity of Newtonian physics at our level of nature. After all, rockets are being sent all over the place using these laws. Quantum effects are valid but their effect on life at our level appears negligible.','2012-04-09 16:23:10','2012-04-09 16:23:10'),(1389,96,48,'@rolfk I don\'t claim that either Newtonian physics or quantum physics are incorrect, only that our interpretation is inside out. We assume physics is driven by unconscious mechanism but I think that all change is driven by afferent and efferent qualia (sense and motive). I think that this fundamental symmetry works by reflecting or folding itself again to achieve a division/multiplication topologically and algebraically. \r\n\r\nMatter+energy are the reflection across the \'exterior space\' topology, and through the symmetry of the \'folding\' the original sense-motive presentation is redefined as an interior algebra of sequence-combinations (\'time\'). Sense and motive are primordial and cannot be reduced or explained - they can only be experienced directly as interior phenomenology or insistence. They are like the sense of \'who\' and the motive of \'why\'. Matter and energy are the reflected, folded, or second order logic antithesis to the sensorimotive thesis (they are the \'what\' and \'how\' of physical existence). Space and time are null matter and null energy arising as tertiary abstractions from the interaction of sense-motive-matter-energy. This is the where and when. \r\n\r\nBecause they are all essentially the same thing folded in on itself, we can make sense of the universe using any part of the syzygy. We can ground our observation in matter+energy and get Newtonian-Cartesian. We can ground our observation in space+time and get Einsteinian-relativistic. We can ground in sense+motive and get anthropological-teleological. Finally we can ground in mathematics itself as a simulacra of realism based on distilled abstractions of energy measurements.\r\n\r\nWith MR I think that I am offering a way to see all of these approaches in perspective. It is complex for us as humans since we are one part of this vast system of nested hierarchies of sense-motives and their matter-energy exteriors. Each nesting, from atom to molecule to cell, organism, animal, hominid, etc brings a whole new inertial frame or world which has its own novel phenomenology as well as fitting in with the continuity of all other inertial frames.','2012-04-10 00:03:49','2012-04-10 00:03:49'),(1392,96,48,'With reference to quantum effects at our level, the research of the last five years suggests a cautious approach. Quantum coherence has been shown as being involved in efficient energy transfer in photosynthetic organisms even at room temperature. Of course there are big differences between that and humans, but the outright assumption that coherence could not be relevant to biological tissue no longer holds. Tests are proposed for whether the same effects could occur in proteins. - Simon','2012-04-10 20:24:55','2012-04-10 20:24:55'),(1395,96,48,'\r\nHi Xodorap,\r\n\r\nDon\'t worry about missing anything, and thanks for providing the feedback.  Since everything always moves towards the consensus, any time you check in and update your desires, like this, if it becomes the consensus, that\'s what everyone will do.\r\n\r\nIt appears that you are in the new camp of people that were once supporters of the old RQT camp that included the \'property dualism\' doctrine.\r\n\r\nJames noticed he did not agree with this doctrine, as evidently you and others agree, and so we pushed the \'property dualism\' doctrine out of RQT into a lower level camp.\r\n\r\nThen James created the competitor sub camp to dualism [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/18 Representational Functionalism].\r\n\r\nJames and I also struggled with just what you are talking about.  It seems to many of us that the \"Mind Brain Identity\" doctrine is more important and fundamental than \"property dualism\".  But we must remember how other property dualists feel about this, such as people in the Panexperiantialism, higher dimensional camps, and so on.\r\n\r\n\"Mind Brain Identity\" and \"Property Dualism\" are two orthogonal and independent doctrines, and we must decide which split to make more fundamental.  If we split on \"MBI\" first, this splits the dualist camps on both branches of this split, just like if we split on dualism, first it splits MBI camps into both of these branches.\r\n\r\nThe bottom line is, there are currently 21 property dualists, and if you total both the existing \"MBI\" camp, and the new [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/18 Representational Functionalism] on the other branch which also includes the \"MBI\" doctrine (When are you Representational Functionalists going to make this more clear in your camp statement?) there are only 15.  So,  once the MBI people outnumber the Property Dualists, they will have the consensus, and will then be able to do the theoretical revolution of restructuring things, accordingly, moving the MBI split to be more fundamental than dualism.\r\n\r\nWhat do you think of the new [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/18 Representational Functionalism] camp?  Would that non dualist MBI camp be a good new parent to your [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/13 Updating Model of Self In The World]?\r\n\r\nIt seems to me such would best represent the current consensus, and everyone.  If anyone thinks otherwise, be sure to let everyone know know.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-04-17 02:20:16','2012-04-17 02:20:16'),(1398,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nMike Gashler, together with James are proposing a drastically reduced new statement for [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 RQT].  They have a version contained in [http://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/30/11#17 Post #17 of this thread].  Mike and James, if there is a more current version of what you are proposing, let us know.\r\n\r\nI, personally, have a problem with eliminating many of the doctrines we\'ve worked so hard to include at the RQT level.  I\'ll comment on a few of these doctrines I hope we can keep and integrate into this new proposal.  I\'d love to know what others think.\r\n\r\n\r\n== * Gamma Synchrony * ==\r\n\r\nI\'m not an expert on Gamma Synchrony, like [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=116 Junius], nor am I as good an expert on waves as [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=88 Steve Lehar], so perhaps they can also help out with some of this.  Gamma Synchrony, or large sets of neurons spread across the brain, all firing in synchrony at specific wave frequencies, is the closest thing that we have to the existence of consciousness.  There is some great summary information about this, and references to some of seminal work on this in the statement now.\r\n\r\n\r\n== * Representationalism Includes? * ==\r\n\r\nTo me, a set of critically important doctrines of Representationalism are included in these two paragraphs currently in the statement:\r\n\r\n<<<\r\nAt the center of this phenomenal 3D world model in our brain is our experience of the body-image. This is the model of the physical body that we experience and that is also constructed by a representative mechanism. All somatic sensations, including â€˜phantomâ€™ limbs and phantom limb pain, are located in the body image not in the physical body.\r\n\r\nInside our experience of our body-image is an experience of our \"self\" or \"spirit\" or \"I\". This \"I\" is represented as looking out of our eyes within this body image. But of course, this spirit image, unlike everything else in this phenomenal world, has no referent in reality. However, though it has no referent in reality, this in no way means our spirit does not exist. This phenomenal \"spirit\" is what we really, literally, and spiritually are. During \"out of body experiences\" this image of our spirit* leaves our body-image, but remains in the unified phenomenal world of our conscious awareness.\r\n>>>\r\n\r\nI\'m hoping that you\'ve just accidently passed over this, and don\'t really want to throw this out of what you believe, because, to me, there doesn\'t seem to be much left of \'representationalism\' without this?\r\n\r\n\r\n== * Quale Interpretation Problem * ==\r\n\r\nThere is currently a bunch of stuff about what it means to be \'ineffable\', including the doctrine that ineffable properties are properties that suffer from the \'quale interpretation problem\'.  There is also some critically important stuff about the various week and strong ways such can be \'effed\'.\r\n\r\nIf you really do completely reject all this, might you be able to provide some kind of definition of what ineffable means to you, and whether we will can \'eff\', so we can include such in what we do agree on?  Or do you just believe that \'ineffable\' means nothing at all, that there is no \'veil of perception\' philosophers have been struggling with forever, and so on?\r\n\r\nThere is more, but let\'s start with these big issues first?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-04-17 03:15:41','2012-04-17 03:15:41'),(1401,96,48,'HI all\r\n\r\nIs the proposal to cut the RQT statement down or to revise the first part?\r\n\r\nI think everyone agrees that the internal representation of the world incorporates our body image at the centre. The nature of the self is disputed, however, so i suggest it\'s left out of the camp statement. While others claim that there is no self, i agree with what Brent says though i would say self has no referent in the environment as opposed to in reality as i believe self is real.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard\r\n\r\n  ','2012-04-17 10:28:07','2012-04-17 10:28:07'),(1404,96,48,'I am fine with including Gamma Synchrony, but I don\'t really see why it is essential to the point being made in RQT. I would label this as unnecessary specificity. The more points we make, the harder it is for a new-comer to agree with it all, and the more frustrating it becomes when he finds that he agrees with, say, 7 out of 9 points. (Should he join anyway, start a new camp, or ask all 37 supporters to come to consensus and drop the two offending points? Hey, that\'s kind of what\'s happening right now :)\r\n\r\nI am also fine with your paragraph starting \"At the center of this phenomenal 3D world...\". Let\'s keep this paragraph. The next paragraph contains some content I cannot accept. I object to equating the term \"spirit\" with the representation of one\'s self that causes experiences such as phantom limbs. I also object to the suggestion that spirit has no referent in reality. Since Mormonism assigns properties to the term \"spirit\" that have no obvious parallel in currently known science, I opine that it will be difficult to bridge between the two without casting out a significant portion of this group. I propose that we start a completely new and unrelated tree for theories that try to use science to try to describe religions notions.\r\n\r\nRegarding the quale interpretation problem, is it not obvious that quale has been historically difficult to talk about? What is the value of stating something we all agree on? We say nothing about pain being undesirable, sugar being sweet, unsafe sex having a correlation with reproduction, etc.\r\n\r\nThe closely-related problem of \"what must happen for a human to know what it is like to be a bat?\", however, seems very relevant, since this seems to be the point where property dualism and functional representationalism separate. I think these sub-camps should officially declare their positions on this specific issue so we can identify any common ground and put it in RQT.\r\n\r\nWe whittled our proposed RQT camp statement down to the one in post #17 in response to Multi-sense Realism\'s disagreement with the notion of a \"model\". Since he has since declared that he will not be in a camp within RQT, how about if we revert back to the larger proposal in post #7 and go from there? (We will still need to re-integrated rolfk\'s changes from post #18, etc.)\r\n\r\nRichard, if we can get consensus, we\'re trying to replace the RQT camp statement outright, not just revise part of it. If we cannot achieve consensus, then the plan is to form a new competing camp, which is less preferable for many reasons.\r\n','2012-04-17 16:32:01','2012-04-17 16:32:01'),(1407,96,48,'I really don\'t want to kill all the stuff you RQT guys worked so hard to create. But I DO want some parent camp that contains the concept of representationalism that we can all agree on. So we can cut these things and stuff them all into the PD camp, OR we can create a new representationalism camp, put the whittled down statement there, and make RQT a sub camp of that. Which does everyone prefer?\r\n\r\nMy problem with just leaving it as it is, is that I don\'t agree with the qualia interpretation problem necessarily. And I agree with Mike about \"Gamma Synchrony\", since that MAY or MAY not actually turn out to have anything to do with consciousness. Global workspace is another potential theory. \r\n\r\nThese are fun ideas, and I think that they have merit... but they involve pinning down the details of the brains algorithms that produce consciousness. HERE what we are talking about is WHY we are conscious. WHY these algorithms are accompanied by experience at all. Other topics create clutter don\'t they? They are interesting, but don\'t they belong in a different tree? Since someone can believe in Gamma Synchrony and be a PD guy, or a RF guy, while someone can believe in the global workspace theory, and be a PD guy or a RF guy. Right?','2012-04-17 20:00:43','2012-04-17 20:00:43'),(1410,96,48,'Hi Mike and James,\r\n\r\nI think you guys are thinking about all this the old school way, where you need to eliminate all but the most important information in order to have something worth surveying for by lots of people over a long period of time.  But with this system we can capture so much more than just yes no questions on trivially stated doctrines or issues.  Mike said: \"The more points we make, the harder it is for a new-comer to agree with\".  But, remember, the goal is to get a good and complete comprehensive survey of what everyone\'s favorite \"and fun\" theory is.  Everyone needs to know what the experts\' most fun, favorite, current working hypothesis are, even if they admit that something else could turn out to be a better theory?\r\n\r\nWe want complete descriptions of how everyone thinks about all this with no compromises, and such is very possible with this system if we work at it a bit.\r\n\r\nEvidently you guys agree that \'gamma synchrony\' is a \'fun\' idea?  So you agree that nothing has falsified the idea that this corresponds to, or is necessary for consciousness to exist?  Perhaps you guys could propose some kind of way to shrink such down and include this, at least as a \'fun\' idea, and possibly the currently most well accepted idea by many, if not a real necessity?  Is there any version of such, even if significantly reduced, you guys could agree to?  If not, we\'ll probably just move a reduced version down to the Property Dualism camp?\r\n\r\nMike Said:\r\n\r\n<<< Regarding the quale interpretation problem, is it not obvious that quale has been historically difficult to talk about? What is the value of stating something we all agree on?>>>\r\n\r\nBut evidently there is significant consensus that, thinking about it the way you guys think about it (i.e. dismissing it / sweeping it under the rug?) is a much more significant problem than you guys are willing to admit, and that, thought about or understood in the right way, there are real yet to be falsified / objective / sharable (i.e. effing of the ineffable) theoretical solutions being proposed in the sub camps.\r\n\r\nWe last developed the current version of the RQT statement by having [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=116 Junius] manage the current version of the statement as it was developed.  He posted periodic updates to everyone as significant changes were made.  Anyone that wanted to see the current state would ask him for a copy, and any changes were submitted to and integrated by him.  But perhaps it would be much better to do shared editing of a Google doc, so that anyone could see the current proposal, make proposed changes, and so on?\r\n\r\nMike, would you be willing to start such and post the link to such here?  Or else just send me a version of your latest thinking and I can start a shared Google doc with that?\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n','2012-04-21 19:13:38','2012-04-21 19:13:38'),(1413,96,48,'A Google Doc sounds like a good idea. Here\'s a link:\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit\r\n\r\nYour characterization that I belong to a school that believes we should eliminate all but the most important information is pretty-much accurate. (Except, I would say \"isolate\" rather than \"eliminate\".) Specifically, I think that the purpose of a tree data structure is to break things down into smaller parts, so the tree structure of Canonizer is what causes me to think that it makes sense to isolate the statements that most-effectively divide the community, and use these statements as the interior nodes of the tree.\r\n\r\nIf the purpose of the tree structure in Canonizer is not to \"break things down\", then I suppose I have missed the whole point. Sorry. I just cannot think of what else a tree is for. I very-much like the idea of having experts fully-explain their theories and present them to everyone with all relevant details. I guess I just don\'t see how that works at the interior nodes of a tree.','2012-04-22 03:18:49','2012-04-22 03:18:49'),(1416,96,48,'\r\nHi Mike,\r\n\r\nThanks for creating the Google doc, that looks like a great start.\r\n\r\nIs it possible to grant everyone write privileges, or at least anyone   that might want to edit it?  I currently cant edit, or add comments, at least logged in as brent.allsop@gmail.com?\r\n\r\nAlso, I think it would be important to include the wiki text formatting for titles, bold, and lists, and such, to be sure people get the Canonizer wiki text right, before they submit it.  If people want to see how such wiki text looks, rendered, they can always start up a practice edit session at Canonizer.com, and paste the text into it, temporarily, to see such?  What do you think?  I can easily convert it to this, if you want me to, once I can edit it.\r\n\r\nAs far as the tree structure, as James said, the goal is for everyone to try to convert everyone to one camp, via good arguments and scientific demonstrations.  Wikipedia is for everything that has been proven / published and documented.  Multiple camps are for all the other stuff that falls outside of this - the goal is to move as much as possible of all this towards the top single node.  As people successfully convert people to the consensus doctrines and beliefs, the doctrines can continue to move up higher into the tree, as more people in more camps support them.  Again, you don\'t want to have as many camps as their are people, if you can manage to move all the important / expert consensus beliefs into a few core camps that are easy for everyone to use as an educational reference, that is the best.\r\n\r\nI\'ll start commenting about the content in a later post.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-04-22 04:20:20','2012-04-22 04:20:20'),(1419,96,48,'Sorry, I thought I had given everyone edit permissions. I have done so now.','2012-04-22 13:36:25','2012-04-22 13:36:25'),(1422,96,48,'\r\nThanks, Mike, for creating and giving everyone write access to this Google document for working purposes:\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit\r\n\r\nI\'ve added another proposed version of a new RQT statement, at the end, to compare with what Mike already has.  I\'ve also done it in the wiki markup for the title, and included wiki markup for 2 images.\r\n\r\nI\'m hoping more people will provide feedback and help out with this to more equitably spread the work around.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-04-23 03:58:32','2012-04-23 03:58:32'),(1425,96,48,'I think that the current google docs version is brilliant, and I can support it. Although, I would remove RER acronym, and just spell it out the two times it is used to increase clarity. ','2012-04-23 20:35:43','2012-04-23 20:35:43'),(1428,96,48,'I\'m converted :) The new draft is simply an improvement, i\'ll go with it.\r\n\r\n','2012-04-24 09:42:37','2012-04-24 09:42:37'),(1431,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nYea, things for the new statement are definitely looking up, and much more representative of what everyone believes.\r\n\r\nBut we\'ve still got a lot more work to do.  When people say they like it, are they talking about just Mike\'s initial statement?  Or are they including the version I added on the second page?  Or how about James addition  \"borrowed from Brent\'s material below\"?\r\n\r\nWe certainly need to clean up the commentary that will not end up in the statement, and do it all completely in the wiki text, as I did in my section.\r\n\r\n\r\nAlso James, I don\'t understand what you mean by your proposed addition about the camp being compatible with theories that claim we don\'t have qualia \"it   just seems like we do\".\r\n\r\nIn my mind, my statement about Dennet\'s ideas seems to be completely incompatible with and devastating to this view, so I\'m thinking that you are not really understanding what it is saying, especially given this addition based on it?\r\n\r\nIs everyone talking about having both my statement and James addition?  I think it would be great if people would start cleaning things up, and explicitly stating just what they think the statement should become, so we can get started on what will need to be pushed to sub camps, and so on.  Anyone feel free to make it exactly what you think it should be, so we can see exactly what you want, and if people disagree, we can continue negotiating back and for and such.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-04-26 02:40:52','2012-04-26 02:40:52'),(1434,96,48,'I inserting my comments in the document.\r\n\r\nFor convenience, the link to that document is:\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit\r\n','2012-04-26 17:17:39','2012-04-26 17:17:39'),(1437,96,48,'Brent asked: \"When people say they like it, are they talking about just Mike\'s initial statement?\r\n\r\nI was referring to Mike\'s statement, I hadn\'t seen yours yet at the time I wrote this. \r\n\r\nBrent asked: \"Also James, I don\'t understand what you mean by your proposed addition about the camp being compatible with theories that claim we don\'t have qualia \"it just seems like we do\". In my mind, my statement about Dennet\'s ideas seems to be completely incompatible with and devastating to this view, so I\'m thinking that you are not really understanding what it is saying, especially given this addition based on it?\"\r\n\r\nI changed what you said on purpose. Dennet knows that we have experiences. He claims we don\'t have \"qualia\" BECAUSE he defines qualia as the belief that our experiences have certain magical properties that neither he, nor I, nor Mike think that they have. So if we are going to belong to a camp with the name \"qualia\" in it, we need to be clear that we are defining qualia to mean the experiences that we have, whether or not they have these additional magical properties. Because if by qualia you mean these additional magical properties, then I don\'t believe in them any more than does Dennet. \r\n\r\nSo I am trying to argue in that section that the argument with Dennet over whether we have qualia is a definitional thing, and that if we define qualia broadly enough, then even Dennet would believe that we have them. \r\n\r\nI tried to re write it to make this more clear below:\r\n\r\n\"That means that this camp is compatible with theories like those of Daniel Dennett who believe that we have experiences but claim that we don\'t really have qualia, \"it just seems like we do\" because they are using the term â€˜qualiaâ€™ to refer to something more than the illusory experience which he thinks is all that we have [Consciousness Explained P. 375]. Our camp is compatible with this worldview since we only define qualia as the subjective experiences that it â€œseems like we have,â€ for whatever reason illusory or otherwise (this position is represented in the Representational Functionalism sub camp (INSERT LINK)). But this camp is also compatible with those that believe that qualia arises from something else, non illusory, beyond the structure and function of traditional physics (these positions are expressed by the epiphenomenalists, and the property dualists sub camps (LINK TO SUB CAMPS).\"\r\n\r\nThis admission (or something like it) is essential before our RF camp could be part of any camp that has the world \"qualia\" in its name. ','2012-04-26 18:35:58','2012-04-26 18:35:58'),(1440,96,48,'Daniel Dennett\'s argument is a bald contradiction in terms! \r\n\r\nIt is impossible to have an experience that SEEMS to be different than we experience it to be! Our experience is EXACTLY as we experience it to be, and NO DIFFERENT! By definition!\r\n\r\nDennett\'s bizarre argument just demonstrates the logical absurdities to which one is compelled, when one attempts to deny the observed properties of experience *as it is experienced*, as opposed to how that experience is rationalized and \"explained away\" by theorists who are embarassed by its very existence!\r\n\r\nLet Dennett defend his bizarre paradox in his own camp statement! Just because he inserts a paradox at the center of his paradigm (as all naive realists are compelled to do) does not mean we have to respect that paradoxical view in the definition of our paradigm!\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-04-26 18:46:09','2012-04-26 18:46:09'),(1443,96,48,'You wrote: \"It is impossible to have an experience that SEEMS to be different than we experience it to be! Our experience is EXACTLY as we experience it to be, and NO DIFFERENT! By definition!\"\r\n\r\nIt appears that you don\'t understand his argument.\r\n\r\n\"Dennett\'s bizarre argument just demonstrates the logical absurdities to which one is compelled, when one attempts to deny the observed properties of experience *as it is experienced*, as opposed to how that experience is rationalized and \"explained away\" by theorists who are embarassed by its very existence!\"\r\n\r\nDennett does a reasonable job of showing that experience, as it is experienced, doesn\'t actually have these extra phenomenal properties that we apply to them. \r\n\r\n\"Let Dennett defend his bizarre paradox in his own camp statement!\"\r\n\r\nIf you believe that qualia has extra non causal aspects, then defend that in YOUR own camp statement such as the PD camp statement. Here we are trying to create a camp statement that encompases the things we all agree on, namely that qualia is representational.\r\n\r\n\"Just because he inserts a paradox at the center of his paradigm (as all naive realists are compelled to do) does not mean we have to respect that paradoxical view in the definition of our paradigm!\"\r\n\r\nBut that\'s just the point, this ISN\'T the definition of YOUR paradigm. That was moved down into the sub camps. This is the definition of a new camp that is compatible with BOTH views. You are free to be as antagonistic to this view as you want in your sub camps. My addition didn\'t take sides, it expressed that this camp was compatible with BOTH views.\r\n\r\nJames','2012-04-26 19:12:35','2012-04-26 19:12:35'),(1446,96,48,'I have read Dennett extensively, and I understand his argument perfectly well. And it IS nonsense to claim that your conscious experience is ANY DIFFERENT than you experience it to be!\r\n\r\nTo quote from my paper in which I discuss Dennett\'s argument\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubw3/bubw3.html\r\n\r\nDaniel Dennett (1991) promotes a similar half-way epistemology by drawing a distinction between the neural vehicles of mental representation, and the phenomenal contents of those vehicles. Dennett opens the epistemological crack by claiming that the phenomenal contents do not necessarily bear any similarity whatsoever to the neural vehicles by which they are encoded in the brain. This actually goes beyond Davidson\'s supervenience, because according to Davidson, mental events that are distinct phenomenally, must be distinct neurophysiologically also. This is tantamount to saying that the dimensions of conscious experience cannot be any greater than the dimensions of the corresponding neurophysiological state. Dennett effectively removes this limitation by suggesting that even the dimensionality of the phenomenal contents need not match that of the neural vehicles. And into that epistemological crack, Dennett slips the entire world of conscious experience like a magical disappearing act, where it is experienced, but does not actually exist. But by the very fact that conscious experience, as conceived by Dennett, is in principle undetectable by scientific means, this concept of consciousness becomes a religious rather than a scientific hypothesis, whose existence can be neither confirmed nor refuted by scientific means. In fact Dennett even suggests that there is actually no such thing as consciousness per se, and that belief in consciousness is akin to belief in some kind of mythical nonexistent deity (Dennett 1981). This argument of course is only intelligable from a naÃ¯ve realist perspective, by which the sense-data of conscious experience, so plainly manifest to one and all, are mis-identified as the external world itself, rather than as something going on in the physical brain. \r\n\r\n...\r\n\r\nIn fact the only epistemology that is consistent with the modern materialistic world view is an identity theory (Russell 1927, Feigl 1958) whereby mind is identically equal to physical patterns of energy in the physical brain. To claim otherwise is to relegate the elaborate structure of conscious experience to a mystical state beyond the bounds of science. The dimensions of conscious experience, such as phenomenal color and phenomenal space, are a direct manifestation of certain physical states of our physical brain. The only correct answer to Koffka\'s question is that things appear as they do because that is the way the world is represented in the neurophysiological mechanism of our physical brain. The world of conscious experience therefore is in principle accessible to scientific scrutiny after all, both internally through introspection, and externally through neurophysiological recording. And introspection is as valid a method of investigation as is neurophysiology, just as in the case of color experience. Of course the mind can be expected to appear quite different from these two different perspectives, just as the data in a computer memory chip appears quite different when examined internally by data access, as opposed to externally by electrical probes. But the one quantity that is preserved across the mind/brain barrier is information content, and therefore that quantity can help identify the neurophysiological mechanism or principle in the brain whose dimensionality, or information content, matches the observed dimensions of conscious experience. \r\n\r\n','2012-04-26 20:45:19','2012-04-26 20:45:19'),(1449,96,48,'I disagree with your assessment, and that\'s fine. I to just had a paper accepted explaining why property dualism is an impossible solution to the consciousness problem. But that\'s neither here nor there. \r\n\r\nI don\'t think that you responded to the central argument I made that some representationalists are NOT property dualists, and believe that experiences don\'t have any extra magical properties, and aren\'t the result of anything more than structure and dynamics. And that means that we need a camp that can create a home for those people as well. \r\n\r\nThere are a group of people that will say that if you don\'t believe that experience is more than structure and dynamics, then you don\'t believe in qualia. And there is another group that feels free to use the term qualia for experience no matter what you believe about experience. (This is primarily a disagreement about what the term qualia means). Since there are people in the RQT camp (like myself) that believe that experience is nothing more than structure and dynamics, but who are definite representationalists, it seems necessary to include SOME sort of a disclaimer when adding the name \"qualia\" to a camp that is designed to include both these groups. To explain that we are using the term as broadly as possible to include the pd theory of experience, and the functionalist strict MBI theory (with no dual properties). \r\n\r\nYou can be free to disagree with Dennett and me all you want in the sub camps. Here we are trying to find some level of agreement among the broadest category of representationalism. ','2012-04-26 21:08:30','2012-04-26 21:08:30'),(1452,96,48,'I\'m not getting into the weeds with this debate, I\'m just saying that Dennett\'s argument that our experience seems different than we experience it to be, is a stark bald paradoxical contradiction in terms! Our experience is exactly as we experience it to be, and no different! By definition! Thats all I\'m saying, and I stand by it.','2012-04-27 10:48:08','2012-04-27 10:48:08'),(1455,96,48,'I am proposing a physically correct approach to do away with RER by appropriately referring to the reflectance function of strawberries and daylight illumination, as well as also minimally referring to information relating to the form of strawberries. As it was, the statement claimed perception of a red strawberry from RER only.\r\nUnable to attach an image of reflectance functions of unripe and ripe strawberries Ihave uploaded it in a file onto canonizer.com. The main difference in reflectance between unripe and ripe strawberries is in the region of 450 to 570 nm. At 630 to 700+ nm there is hardly a difference. The difference between unripe and ripe is due to the differences in absorption of electromagnetic energy by L and M cones, with redness essentially being determined by L cone and greenness by M cone absorption. \r\nL cone absorption at 720 nm is 0.1% of that at 570 nm, i.e. L cone absorption at 720 or even 650 nm is exceedingly small. I believe the statement should represent the facts minimally correct.\r\n','2012-04-27 16:25:19','2012-04-27 16:25:19'),(1458,96,48,'It\'s not necessarily cone sensitivity either. \r\nhttp://www.rochester.edu/news/show.php?id=2299','2012-04-27 16:54:28','2012-04-27 16:54:28'),(1461,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nItâ€™s exciting to see all the activity going on.\r\n\r\nItâ€™s great to see some expert comments on vision from rolfk and Multisense.  But I think for this theoretical work, we need to simplify and focus only on what is important, and ignore how complex the actual perception process is.  The bottom line is, when we see something that is reflecting 650 NM light, we represent it with redness, and when we see something reflecting more or less 700 NM light, we experience greenness.  Of course itâ€™s not exactly 700 NM light, but all that complexity is not important for what we need to communicate here.\r\n\r\nMike, you mentioned that someone objected to using the term 650 NM light?  Who was that?  Iâ€™ve never seen any objection to such.  We use the simple term â€œreflects 650 NM lightâ€ in all the other camps.  So to rename it to be â€œRERâ€ (what does that even stand for?) just for this camp seems completely wrong to me.  Does anyone really object to just using the property of â€œreflects 650 NMâ€ light for the initial â€˜causeâ€™ of the perception process and phenomenal redness (aka a red quale) as a property of the final result of the perception process?\r\n\r\nTerminology is critically important for good communication and is the biggest problem with this theoretical field.  Currently, most everyone means something completely different when they use specific terms like qualia.  So each camp shouldnâ€™t have its own special terms defined.  If we need to define anything, it should be done in separate topics (as is done with â€˜effâ€™ http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/102/2) or at worst, in the root agreement statement, as we all need to use the same terms, which mean the same thing to everyone, for everything, as much as possible.\r\n\r\nAlso, Steve, thanks for jumping in and pointing out how â€œDennett\'s argument that our experience seems different than we experience it to be, is a stark bald paradoxical contradiction in terms!â€.\r\n\r\nTalking to qualophobe people like Mike and James, like this, reminds me of talking to NaÃ¯ve realists.  Their models of reality are so completely inadequate at explaining everything.  They are so clueless about just how inadequate their models are.  They donâ€™t even know what they mean when they say â€˜it seems redâ€™.  For example, just look at Mikeâ€™s comment about my proposed statement: â€œWhether or not such knowledge is a mistaken representation or mistaken interpretation of something else is irrelevantâ€.  He asked:\r\n\r\n    â€œirrelevant to what question?\r\n    A statement such as \"redness arises from\r\n    the brain\'s inaccurate ability to model\r\n    causal properties of the strawberry\",\r\n    whether true or not, would certainly be\r\n    relevant and profound with respect to\r\n    understanding the nature of qualia.â€\r\n\r\nThis just starkly illustrates how confused Mike is, and how inadequate his models of anything important are.  Just the fact that you have to ask what is irrelevant, says volumes about your ignorance, to me.  It seems to me youâ€™re clearly still thinking â€˜rednessâ€™ is a property of the strawberry or has something to do with the causal properties, and that the brain is having troubles â€˜modelingâ€™ these.  James, what could you possibly mean when you say â€˜model causal propertiesâ€™ here???  Can you not see how you are just saying you know something, and there is nothing that is that knowledge, or maybe you are saying the knowledge is just a miracle we donâ€™t need to worry about or worse?  Can you please give me a definition of â€˜modelâ€™ or â€˜seemâ€™ â€“ hopefully a definition sufficient so we could implement something doing the same thing, artificially, in any possible theoretical world, let alone this one?\r\n\r\nWhen we first started all this, I fully expected the â€˜qualiaâ€™ issue to be forced below the representational issue, a long time ago.  It has amazed me just how long RQT has survived with the world â€˜qualiaâ€™, and I expected there to be qualia representationalists, and a lot more qualophobe representationalists, like Dennett, Minsky, the Chruclands, et all.  I figured the qualophobe camp could possibly be the leading consensus, or at least on par with the qualophiles.\r\n\r\nItâ€™s very funny when you are having conversations with qualophiles, like Minsky, Frankish, and so on.  And it is also how amazingly hard it is to recruit anyone like Dennett, or the Churchlands to participate in this canonization process.\r\n\r\nJoseph Smith always talked about a â€˜stupor of thoughtâ€™, and how you could tell you were on the wrong track when this happens.  Initially Frankish was excited about participating, and helping to develop the â€œwe donâ€™t have qualia, it just seems like we do campâ€™  (those were his exact words), but when he saw this one paragraph argument against this, it was as if his â€˜stuper of thoughtâ€™ kicked in, and suddenly he was no longer interested, at all, in this topic, even.  And the same things happens again and again, with Minsky, the churchlands, and any qualophile that thinks this way.\r\n\r\nJames and Mike are the first people to finally step up and make an attempt at defending this POV.  So, thanks Mike and James, it is great to finally have someone willing to take this position, and bravely stand up against these types of devastating arguments.\r\n\r\nAt least theyâ€™ve agreed to allow the word â€˜qualiaâ€™.  And it is at least good to hear people like Dennett, Frankish, and all to talk about something phenomenal, and James and Mike not objecticting to this word.  So, we can no longer ridicule them for being that ignorant.\r\n\r\nBut, of course, Iâ€™ve definitely noticed, that they define the word â€˜qualiaâ€™ to be something very different than what I define the word to be, and all the things that go along with such (as in the â€˜quale interpretation problemâ€™).\r\n\r\nSo, Mike and James, have given in to accepting the word â€˜qualiaâ€™ so we no longer have that big gun to challenge their camp, but it sounds like their giving us almost everything else, including the qualia interpretation problem, you can know something, or something can â€˜seemâ€™ some way, even though there is nothing which is that seeming, and evidently a bunch more.\r\n\r\nSo, if James and Mike only want to take away the word â€˜qualiaâ€™ as our best argument against their view, but leave us with the definition, and everything else about the word, that is fine with me.\r\n\r\nMike and James seem to be working on the assumption, like I once was, that there are lots of qualiphobe experts out there.  But Iâ€™m really starting to doubt this, and wish them the best of luck in achieving any kind of consensus in this qualophobe camp.  Iâ€™ve been working for many years, trying to recruit a real qualophobes.  But Mike and James are the first.  It would be exciting to have my theory, that there is no reputable expert consensus, for any kind of qualophobe theory, wrong.  But currently, Iâ€™m in the camp that thinks there is near zero expert consensuses, and what consensus there is is fading fast, given the powerful arguments being â€˜canonizedâ€™ against any such view.\r\n\r\nSo, again, what do you say, Mike and James.  Can we include a statement like this in the RQT camp:\r\n\r\n    \"People like Daniel Dennett often make a claim like\r\n    we don\'t have qualia, \"it just seems like we do\"\r\n    [Consciousness Explained P. 375].  Qualia are\r\n    properties of our incorrect or \'seeming\' knowledge.\r\n    Whether or not such knowledge is a mistaken\r\n    representation or mistaken interpretation of\r\n    something else is irrelevant to what where and\r\n    how qualia are.\"\r\n\r\nOr are you going to give that up as a huge argument for us, youâ€™ll have to attempt to counter, and find people that agree with you, in your camp?  All I can say is, if so, good luck.\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-04-27 20:30:39','2012-04-27 20:30:39'),(1464,96,48,'Well, of course its ultimately in the brain. But the immediate interface between the physical world and the brain in case of color vision are the cones in the retina. Stimuli from \'red\' and \'green\' objects result in diffferent cone absorption values that then undergo various modifications in the brain, resulting somewhere unknown and by an as yet unknown process in the respective perceptual experiences.','2012-04-27 20:33:42','2012-04-27 20:33:42'),(1467,96,48,'rolfk,\r\n\r\nYou are being misdirected and confused by â€œeasy problemâ€ issues.  Nothing in the retina, or even in the light, for that matter, has anything to do with my redness, and what it is phenomenally like.\r\n\r\nPerhaps you should just imagine a blind person, with no eyes, in a completely dark room, undergoing a drug induced trip â€“ experiencing brilliant flashes of my redness, possibly for the first time his life.  Or maybe the optic nerve of this person with no eyes in a dark room, is being stimulated with an identical signal, to what my retina would be sending to my brain, causing a representation of the strawberry phenomenally identical to mine.  That and what it is phenomenally like is all weâ€™re talking about here.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-04-27 21:31:00','2012-04-27 21:31:00'),(1470,96,48,'As before, I am willing to leave RQT and make a peer camp for my beliefs if that would make all of this easier. I am also willing to keep hashing this all out if that continues to be preferred.\r\n\r\nBrent_Allsop wrote \"Mike, you mentioned that someone objected to using the term 650 NM light? Who was that?\"\r\n\r\nI was referring to post #13 in this thread and others like it. The objection was to being incomplete, not to using wavelengths. I think this issue has been resolved now.\r\n\r\nBrent_Allsop wrote \"...qualophobe people like Mike and James...\"\r\n\r\nI do not fear qualia =). I just have a different definition of its nature, apparently. This is like Baptists saying Mormons are not Christians because they do not accept the notion of a trinity.\r\n\r\nBrent_Allsop wrote \"It seems to me you\'re clearly still thinking redness is a property of the strawberry\"\r\n\r\nNope.\r\n\r\nBrent_Allsop wrote \"...or has something to do with the causal properties, and that the brain is having troubles modeling these.\"\r\n\r\nYes.\r\n\r\nBrent_Allsop wrote \"Can you please give me a definition of model?\"\r\n\r\nIn my terminology space, a representation is a model. These words can be used interchangeably. Is this not the standard usage of the term?\r\n\r\nBrent_Allsop wrote \"...even though there is nothing which is that seeming.\"\r\n\r\nYou keep saying things like this. It must be important, but it just flys over my head like street slang from a Brandon Sanderson novel. (\"wassing the where of the if?\") I am honestly trying to parse it, but cannot. Can you help me know what you mean?\r\n\r\nBrent_Allsop wrote \"So, again, what do you say, Mike and James. Can we include a statement like this in the RQT camp: \r\n\r\n    People like Daniel Dennett often make a claim like\r\n    we don\'t have qualia, \"it just seems like we do\"\r\n    [Consciousness Explained P. 375].  Qualia are\r\n    properties of our incorrect or \'seeming\' knowledge.\r\n    Whether or not such knowledge is a mistaken\r\n    representation or mistaken interpretation of\r\n    something else is irrelevant to what where and\r\n    how qualia are.\"\r\n\r\nI think qualia *is* that mistaken interpretation. It is what the brain substites for causal properties that it otherwise does not know how to model. So, no, that is definitely not irrelevant--it is the most relevant thing there is--it is the very thing itself.\r\n\r\nBrent_Allsop wrote \"you\'ll have to attempt to counter, and find people that agree with you\"\r\n\r\n...or convert. If someone says something that I can understand and think is convincing, I am willing to change. Until then, I see no shame in standing alone in an obscure camp, if only to signify that I am still trying to understand why everyone else believes differently. I am only camping elsewhere because I still think I am right.\r\n','2012-04-28 03:47:22','2012-04-28 03:47:22'),(1473,96,48,'\r\nHi Mike,\r\n\r\nAbsolutely, I very much respect you standing up for what you believe, for being willing to go to so much work to express what you still believe, for still pointing out that our arguments are still not convincing to you.  That is what we all need so much more of, as of course, you could be in the one science ends up proving, us having to repent and join your camp.\r\n\r\nSo you said for you \'a representation is a model\' and that the two can be used interchangeable.  But which one is it that has a phenomenal property?  I hear you saying a qualia isn\'t either one of these.  Which one of these, is a quale or a \'seeming\' a property of?  And if it is neither, how can it be if it is not a property of something?\r\n\r\nAlso, your offering to completely fork a new camp, but that is completely wrong, especially since we all very much agree with \'representational\' ideas, the world qualia and likely a bunch of other stuff.  I just want to find as much consensus as possible, in the higher level camp, but no more.  So I very much appreciate your continued help at getting this right, and your patience with me honestly expressing the way I still see things, and for your help at better understanding you together with likely millions of other people just like you.\r\n\r\nSo, I\'m taking it we need to push that Dennett statement down to the property dualism camp?  Or perhaps you guys can propose a new version that included James response to this, or something?  It\'s all up to you.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-04-28 05:01:14','2012-04-28 05:01:14'),(1476,96,48,'Brent;\r\nSo, nothing in the retina, or even in the light has anything to do with your redness experience? Perhaps you can tell us what in the drug consumed by the blind person and how produces the redness experience; presumably you are experienced. So why, in the original version of the statement written by you did it say that the causal stimulus was a light  reflected from a strawberry? All I did was point out that ripe strawberries have a broadband reflectance function, that light of 700 nm is not very efficient and that the transitional agent between the physical light stimulus and the brain are, unless most or all of visual and color scientists are nuts, the cones and their absorption properties.','2012-04-28 18:21:38','2012-04-28 18:21:38'),(1479,96,48,'\r\nHi rolfk,\r\n\r\nSo if we\'re thinking about the simplest possible idealized model, where light of some form is being reflected off of an idealized strawberry, that someone represents with the most pure red possible, what would be the best way to refer to the nature of this light being reflected from the idealized strawberry?\r\n\r\nAs far as the drugs go, I just hear people that have experienced \'trips\' expressing the idea that they experienced colors they\'ve never experienced before.  I combine this with RQT\'s prediction that it will be possible to reproduce some people\'s experience of red, if the correct neural correlate is duplicated in that person\'s brain.  That\'s all.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-04-28 18:36:57','2012-04-28 18:36:57'),(1482,96,48,'The quale of \"redness\" is much akin to what a Physicist experiences as \"Temperature.\"\r\n\r\nThere is no temperature out there. It is only motion of the particles. \r\n\r\nSimilarly, there are no sounds there. We call some vibration in the air as \"a\", some other as \"b\", yet another as \"meow\".\r\n\r\nSo  the neurons in the brain have developed various shorthand notations in evolution for saving on energy expenditure - like we do color coding of info in the old system of bin card filing. Hence all our \"experiencing\" in nature is generation of this code by the neurons, irrespective of what is out there and also irrespective of which sensory info it is.\r\n\r\nDoes a Physicist  bother to say every time the motion of particles reflected as temperature?','2012-04-28 20:13:47','2012-04-28 20:13:47'),(1485,96,48,'In reply to Ramesam/desidimona, i don\'t buy the theory that qualia are codes.\r\n\r\nYes, when looked at in information theory terms, they perform an encoding function and that might explain their evolution. Dennett\'s view of perception as purely a discrimination process and thus replicable in a computer is eliminativist not just of all the magic stuff but the substance of our experience. Neurons aren\'t mere perceptrons, classifying input into the various categories of quale: not only is this simplistic but it leaves out experience altogether!\r\n\r\nNo matter, we are rightly describing our different views on what constitutes qualia as sub camps to RQT but i\'m not sure where property dualism fits in.\r\n\r\nI find the camp statement obscure and contradictory. In the first paragraph we have: \"...all properties, phenomenal and causal are physical.\" But at the end we have: \"Property Dualism also includes many traditional or religious \'spiritual\' views of consciousness that places the phenomenal properties in some \'spiritual\', or non physical domain or dimension.\" This is contradictory. Either we have Cartesian dualism or we don\'t. \r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard\r\n','2012-04-29 14:13:07','2012-04-29 14:13:07'),(1488,96,48,'\r\nHi Richard,\r\n\r\nYea, if it is obscure and contradictory, such needs to be fixed.\r\n\r\nThe Smythies Car hypothesis is very much like Cartesian Dualism, where the realm of the spirit is a \"higher dimension\" of reality.\r\n\r\nAlso, many forms of Cartesian dualism still view this spiritual realm as very \"physical\" or at least approachable via science.\r\n\r\nWe definitely need to recruit more active people in these camps so they can be sure our terminology doesn\'t slip to excluding what they believe in these kinds of ways.\r\n\r\nFeel free to make some explicit proposals to help us improve things in the current under development new version here:\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-04-29 16:13:17','2012-04-29 16:13:17'),(1491,96,48,'In order to check my own understanding, and since people keep telling me I am confused, let me attempt to restate and summarize what\'s going on here one more time:\r\n\r\nI think this very issue (whether or not codes are sufficient to explain qualia) is the primary dividing issue between property dualism and functional representationalism. I think desdimona was essentially expressing support for functional representationalism, and richwil is essentially expressing support for property dualism.\r\n\r\nFunctional representationalism = \"believing we experience qualia is experiencing qualia\"\r\nProperty dualism = \"no, something more than information processing must be happening, we just don\'t know what\".\r\n\r\nThe problem with the Representational Qualia Theory camp statement is that it has been formed almost exclusively by property dualists. Then, James and Mike (who are representational functionalists) objected to it, so we are now having to re-write the Representational Qualia Theory camp statement to accomodate representational functionalism.\r\n\r\nIs this about right? Am I following the big picture? Are my one-sentence versions of FR and PD in the right ball-park?\r\n\r\nAnd here\'s the link to help us work on the RQT camp statement:\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit ','2012-04-29 21:32:14','2012-04-29 21:32:14'),(1494,96,48,'Well, I was hoping for confirmation, but I suppose lack-of-objection must suffice. So, now I think we should all declare our positions by aligning with either functionalism (http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/18) or dualism (http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/19). (I am a functionalist.) Then, we can work on our respective camp-statements without this issue always popping up to block progress.\r\n\r\nAnd here\'s the link to help us work on the new RQT camp statement:\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit \r\n\r\nmike','2012-05-01 13:37:48','2012-05-01 13:37:48'),(1497,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nI think a critical problem we are having is we are struggling with the fact that some of us define, or at least think of \"qualia\" and \"phenomenal\" in very different ways.\r\n\r\nWe seem to be leaning towards defining some of these terms in a camp, implying that other camps will be defining them differently (otherwise definitions shouldnâ€™t exist in individual camps.)  I donâ€™t think it is good for each camp to have a different definition of the same term, as this makes communication impossible (we always have to specify which definition we mean, when we use the term.)\r\n\r\nI think we can come up with a consensus definitions of these terms, and then for people that want to think of them in different ways, they will have to come up with some other way to say what they want to say, either by calling them â€˜proto qualiaâ€™ or come up with some other completely new term?\r\n\r\nIf I assume from the fact that we originally had the \"quale interpretation problem\" defined in current RQT camp, and  I was able to define qualia in the consensus property dualism camp, that there are far more supporters of these definitions than any other definition?  If anyone doubts that, we can start some survey topics to find out for sure, and track this going forward?\r\n\r\nIf there is a clear consensus, then would it be possible for the people that mean something different, to come up with different terms so we can better communicate?\r\n\r\nBelow is a first draft at some definitions of qualia and phenomenal I think there would be some clear consensus for, based on the fact that these have already mostly been defined in the consensus camps.  Of course they should be made much more concise...\r\n\r\nEveryone let me know if you have any better ideas....\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n= Qualia: =\r\n\r\nA quale is an ineffable property or quality that cannot be communicated through abstract symbols, alone.  When you say the abstract word: â€œSaltyâ€, unless you know the correct experience of Salty, you donâ€™t know how to interpret the abstract meaning, to derive what it is intended to describe.  If you have experienced the correct quale, and then can interpret the abstract world â€˜saltyâ€™ to represent this, only then can you know what the world â€˜saltyâ€™ means.\r\n\r\nSince all of our senses are based on abstract interpretations of the cause and effect information coming to them, our traditional senses suffer from the â€˜quale interpretation problemâ€™.  We interpret 650 NM light, to represent the fact that the surface of the strawberry reflects 650 NM light.  But of course, the causal properties of the light ariving in our eye are nothing like the sweetness property of a red strawberry.  So our senses interpret one to be abstracted information about its referent.  Ultimately, we interpret this and represent it with our redness quale.  But of course, my redness could be your greenness, or something youâ€™ve never experienced before in your life.  The bottom line, because of the quale interpretation problem, traditional cause and effect based communication and senses, suffer from the quale interpretation problem, and thereby, with only that, quale are ineffable.  And if there are phenomenal properties on the strawberry, or on anything in our brain, there is a \'veil of perception\', due to the quale interpretation problem, that is preventing us from knowing what they are like.\r\n\r\n= Phenomenal: =\r\n\r\nA â€œPhenomenalâ€ property is the same thing as a quale.  Phenomenal properties are contrasted with any causal properties of nature.  Causal properties of nature are anything that can be detected through any type of cause and effect observation, in a way that allows us to know about them, at least abstractly.\r\n\r\nCausal properties, thereby, are the initial cause of any perception process, or the properties of some medium involved in abstract memory or communication.\r\n\r\nPhenomenal properties, in contrast, are the final result of the perception process, and what we experience our knowledge of perception as.  Redness is a quale, or a phenomenal property.  If a phenomenal property also has a causal property, all we can know of such, is the causal component.  Because of the quale interpretation problem, we won\'t know if there is any phenomenal component, or reason why it is behaving the way it is.\r\n','2012-05-02 02:46:33','2012-05-02 02:46:33'),(1500,96,48,'I think you are suggesting that we elliminate the \"terms\" section from the proposed new RQT camp statement. Ok, done. (Since we removed the need for \"RER\", that section no longer served much purpose anyway.) I think you are also suggesting that we are currently using the term \"qualia\" in a manner that differs from your definition. I do not think that was deliberate. What specifically do we need to change in this proposed camp statement to bring our definitions into alignment?\r\n\r\nI really like your idea of having a global set of terms. Terminology issues are *by far* the biggest time-waster in any discussion, especially any discussion about things that are difficult to \"eff\". Do you think we should start a second Google Doc for this? Is there a good place to put it when we\'re done? (Wikipedia certainly agrees that the term \"qualia\" is tough to define. The first sentence in the definitions section states \"There are many definitions of qualia, which have changed over time.\") Here are my thoughts on your initial definitions:\r\n\r\nRegarding the ineffability of qualia, I certainly agree that the term \"salty\" does not convey enough information to describe my personal experience of tasting something salty, but if I also communicate enough information to reconstruct my entire brain, then I have essentially sent you my interpretation of that word. And if you were a sufficiently advanced post-human, you could use that information to actually sample my experience. Hence, qualia is not theoretically ineffable, it is only ineffable for now, due to the current limitations of humans. Hence, I do not think that defining it in terms of its ineffability is the right approach.\r\n\r\nThe phrase \"the final result of the perception process\" implies things to me that I suspect were not intended. Are you sure that the experience does not begin until the perception process terminates? Couldn\'t the experience happens all along the way? I think the term \"final\" is too strong. The term \"result\" implies something that can be expressed, such as a value, a vector, a matrix, or a graph. Yet, you previously said experiences were ineffable. Also, the \"perception process\" is lacking a clear definition. For example, are the causal properties being represented part of the \"perception process\", or does the \"perception process\" only begin after my percepts are stimulated?\r\n\r\nI think the phrase \"phenomenal properties\" communicates unintended notions. Would you object to eliminating this phrase from our global definitions? I don\'t mind \"phenomenal experiences\" so much because I think it is mostly understood that experiences are representational concepts, but when you say \"phenomenal properties\", it seems like you are suggesting that these phenomenal concepts have some literal or physical existence outside of human mental representations. That is not a deliberate suggestion, is it? Such a suggestion would belong outside of *representational* qualia theory, right? I think a phrase such as \"imagined phenomenal properties\" would convey the intended meaning much more clearly.\r\n','2012-05-02 13:21:31','2012-05-02 13:21:31'),(1503,96,48,'I was going to reply to this, but well... Mike pretty much said everything I was going to say about it. \r\n\r\nI too doubt the \"ineffibility\" of qualia. So if you define qualia as the \"ineffable\" experiences that we have, then I too don\'t think that qualia exist. If, on the other hand, you define qualia as \"the experiences that we have, as we have them\" then qualia clearly exists without a doubt. I favor the latter definition, allowing people to argue about whether qualia are ineffable or not in sub camps, but I understand that the use of the term in the community is \"mixed\" at best, so we have to ask which definition communicates best to those that are reading our camps. \r\n\r\nSo yes, the definitions matter. \r\n\r\nJames','2012-05-02 17:26:20','2012-05-02 17:26:20'),(1506,96,48,'\r\nOK, I guess I\'m OK with defining a qualia to be what we experience.  We can always add a clarification in the property dualism camp indicating qualia are ineffable, and what we mean by that.\r\n\r\nBy the way, given this, you guys must think that \'ineffable\' is a meaningless word then, or that it is talking about something that isn\'t possible?\r\n\r\nI\'ve made a bunch of edits and comments to the statement, working to avoid making any edits anyone might object too.  This is great using Google docs, things are really starting to look great!!\r\n\r\nBrent  Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-05-03 03:40:02','2012-05-03 03:40:02'),(1509,96,48,'Mike Gashler writes \"I think desdimona was essentially expressing support for functional representationalism, and richwil is essentially expressing support for property dualism.\"\r\n\r\nI support RQT but i do not support property dualism.\r\n\r\nWhile I agree with property dualists who think that consciousness is a property of the brain, i do not see it as epiphenomenal.','2012-05-04 11:28:55','2012-05-04 11:28:55'),(1510,1,10,'Hi  [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=264 Allan],\r\n\r\nWelcome as the newest participator in the \"Life Plan\" survey topic.\r\n\r\nI very much love, and completely agree with the new [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/63/9 Hedonism camp] you created.\r\n\r\nAs usual, I wonder if there is a good way we can show this agreement in a super camp.\r\n\r\nI\'m betting that everyone in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/63/7 Utilitarian] camp would agree with everything you say, as \'hedonism\' or \'that which anyone wants\' is the foundation of any utility function.\r\n\r\nMy personal [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/63/5 Phenomenal Spirituality sub campy] to the utilitarian camp simply adds to what you believe, in that we believe that once we die, people still have memory of us, and the effects we had on the world still survive.  Also, we believe that we can already preserve some of this to greater extents,  that such has value, and that we would like to seek after more of the same.  And of course, the ultimate ideal of that, would be recovering enough memories and information of a person to be able to resurrect them.  And that doing so is kind of a hedonistic and selfish desire, in that we don\'t want to be lonely and without the dead person, helping us out.\r\n\r\nObviously, nobody can take it to that level, where we can resurrect anyone, yet, so we simply take that as a possibility, and a kind of idealized goal, to push towards, as much as possible.\r\n\r\nAnyway, Allan, worst case, I propose moving the current \"utilitarian\" camp, including my sub camp, into a sporting sub camp position of the hedonism camp, to show that we all agree with you.\r\n\r\nHowever, I\'m thinking there is a good chance that you agree with at least some of what the rest of us believe, and would like to capture that, also.\r\n \r\nSo, would you mind proposing some improvements to the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/63/7 Utilitarian] camp to make it sufficiently like your camp so you would be willing to support that.  In other words, merge all your hedonistic ideas into the current utilitarian camp, if possible.  I\'m betting all of us would agree that any improvements to the camp you make, along the lines of \'hedonism\' would be acceptable to all current supporters and that nobody would object to any such improvements?\r\n\r\nRemember, the goal of Canonizer.com is to build as much consensus, and have as few camps with as much consensus as possible, not just have everyone have individual loner camps.\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-05-06 15:49:16','2012-05-06 15:49:16'),(1511,1,59,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nI\'m planning on significantly expanding this topic and renaming it to be: \"Mormon Doctrine on Spirits\".  I\'m going to rewrite the agreement camp statement to be:\r\n\r\n\"The purpose of this survey topic is to find out what everyone, \r\nespecially the experts, believe is Mormon Doctrine about our spirits.\"\r\n\r\nI also intend on renaming the current [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/97/4 Models can be tested] camp to be \"Approaching Scientific Consensus\".  I intend to significantly expand the statement to include descriptions of how what Joseph Smith taught about \'refined spiritual matter\' was a break from traditional Cartesian Dualism, and point out how he was way ahead of his time in describing what emerging modern theoretical scientific consensus now understands of consciousness and spiritual stuff like qualia.\r\n\r\nIf anyone is interested in helping, or reviewing this stuff, before I submit the new draft versions, that would be of course very welcome!\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-05-06 20:42:30','2012-05-06 20:42:30'),(1512,1,10,'Hey Alonzo,\r\n\r\nVery interesting â€œexperimentalâ€ camp you created, entitled [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/63/10 logically extrapolated mastophilia] under the hedonism camp you support. (Note, nobody is yet supporting this camp, so if you want to see it, other than via such a link, you need to turn the filtering off or set it to zero.)\r\n\r\nIâ€™d love to hear more of your thoughts on this.\r\n\r\nThe way I look at it, these â€˜joysâ€™, such as â€œmastophiliaâ€ of something like a one ton breasts are currently hard wired into our brain.  In other words, evolution wanted us to love very large breasts, so it wired our pleasure centers to get big rewards, when we successfully seduced a large breasted woman.\r\n\r\nBut, having such joys hard wired, to what evolution wants, isnâ€™t being completely free.  The only way we can truly be free, is if we can rewire such pleases to reward us for what we want to want, not what evolution, God, or anyone else wanted us to want.\r\n\r\nSo, in other words, just like we are about to achieve the ability to have robots supply us with anything we want, including possibly 1 ton gentilea, weâ€™ll also be able to rewire such joys to be rewards for something like contributing to society, or other beneficial to us and everyone behaviors.  So, in other words, weâ€™ll probably be able to rewire â€˜mastophiliaâ€™ to being something more productive, like maybe tacking out the garbage, philia.\r\n\r\nIn other words, Iâ€™m going to really love taking out the garbage, when it is way more than orgasmic!\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-05-10 16:34:55','2012-05-10 16:34:55'),(1513,1,10,'This is probably one of the greatest, and most fundamental questions in all of transhumanism. I posit that the \"freedom\" you propose is illusory. My claim is that my emotional/spiritual identity derives a large part from these desires, such as they are. Obviously, this is a question of values of the first order. In my story Orange Sky, I had an upload who had edited himself so much that he didn\'t really want anything, was almost completely dispassionate and was basically a tool. \r\n\r\nIf you reject this set of desires for some reason, then you are immediately confronted with the problem of what to replace them with, what goal and motivational structure would be better? This is probably the most profound question of all. Realizing this, I re-evaluated my base programming and realized that it\'s not all that bad. \r\n\r\n--> it has successfully motivated me to remain very active in transhumanism for many years. (I have other motivations but they\'re a bit more difficult to explain; are even more embarrassing)\r\n\r\n--> It is still sufficiently far remote that I can expect it to be a healthy and beneficial motivator for many decades in the future before the eventual point of stagnation. \r\n\r\nSo until I reach the point of stagnation, there is no harm in allowing the motivational circuit to operate as is. At the point of stagnation, I will be forced to face this question. One aspect of which is the fundamental nature of my being; whether this is it\'s fundamental limit or whether there could be some higher goal that should be pursued. I would expect myself to be much better equipped to address that question at that point than I am now. ','2012-05-10 17:25:28','2012-05-10 17:25:28'),(1514,1,10,'\r\n\r\nHi Alonzo,\r\n\r\nVery interesting way of thinking about things.  Itâ€™s very fun to discuss such stuff with people that have thought about this to the level you have.\r\n\r\nYou asked:\r\n\r\n    â€œIf you reject this set of desires for some reason,\r\n    then you are immediately confronted with the\r\n    problem of what to replace them with, what\r\n    goal and motivational structure would be better?\r\n    This is probably the most profound question of all.â€\r\n\r\nYes, very fundamental questions.\r\n\r\nEvidently your base desires arenâ€™t too bad, enough to think you may not want to change them, once you are free to do so, which is good.  But some people have baser desires that are very bad.  For example, some people are masochistic.  In that God/Evolution, hard wired them to want to hurt other people.  Thankfully, most people have this under control, but obviously occasionally, peoples wiring gets effed up, and they go postal, and so on.\r\n\r\nObviously, those types of people donâ€™t really want to want, what god/evolution wired them to want, so surely theyâ€™ll want to change themselves to want something better than that.\r\n\r\nAs far as what might we want to do, other than base desires, for starters, there is plenty to keep us busy.  In fact, weâ€™ve started a [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/120 survey topic to prioritize things] to â€˜canonizeâ€™ just such a prioritized list.\r\n\r\nIt includes things like finding out what everyone wants, first.  It includes things like achieving an ability to understand the mind, so we can â€˜uploadâ€™ and change things like what we want.  This is very high on the priority, because it solves most other problems, like solving the problem of people that want to hurt other people, and so on.  It solves the problem of deathâ€¦. And most everything else.\r\n\r\nThen, once we do all of those kinds of things, for ourselves, we need to solve the problems of everyone that is less than us.  And this, of course, includes people that didnâ€™t make it to the millennium.  In other words, weâ€™ve got to work on resurrecting our ancestors, to pay them back for being our creator, and doing all the work to create what the immortals freely inherited.\r\n\r\nIâ€™m betting doing all of that, for everyone, is all going to take way more than 1000 years.  And once we get all that doneâ€¦  I bet weâ€™ll know what we want to want, as you also indicated, right?  Surely, at least exploring the rest of this huge universe, resurrecting any alien life forms that didnâ€™t or havenâ€™t yet made it, and so on, will be high on any list.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop,\r\n\r\nâ€œHey, Robot, get out of the way, itâ€™s my turn to take out the garbage!!!â€\r\n','2012-05-10 18:08:31','2012-05-10 18:08:31'),(1517,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nRich, I agree that qualia are not epiphenomenal, and I am also a property dualist.  The two can be compatible if done properly.\r\n\r\n\r\nMake Gashler sent me a private e-mail discussing issues we still have about the terminology we can use in the new RQT camp statement.  Iâ€™d prefer to keep these types of communications in the public forums, in hopes that more people will keep up with, and contribute to them.\r\n\r\nAs with many things on this topic, Iâ€™ve noticed our common English is ambiguous about what we need to talk about, when describing necessary components to conscious perception.  For example, the common use of the term â€˜redâ€™ refers to both the initial cause of the perception process, and the experience that results, or a â€˜rednessâ€™ quale.  The two are very different, and we must make sure we specify which we are talking about, and not just use the word â€˜redâ€™ as it means both.\r\n\r\nThere is a similar issue with the definition of â€˜informationâ€™.  Iâ€™m going to start using two different labels for two different types of information, so let me know if you think this helps in communicating what Iâ€™m trying to describe.\r\n\r\n* \'\'\'Abstract Information\'\'\'\r\n* \'\'\'Phenomenal Information\'\'\'\r\n\r\n\'\'\'â€œAbstract Informationâ€\'\'\' is platonic information, and isnâ€™t real, unless it is instantiated on or represented by something physical or real.  Binary values, words, and everything are abstract representations.  Any physical stuff that can assume a sufficiently diverse causally detectible state can represent it, as long as there is an interpreting mechanism to interpret the representation as its intended value.  In other words, it doesnâ€™t matter if it is +5 volts on a line or a magnetic orientation on a disk, as long as something can interpret the representation as a one.  If the interpretation is zero, when it should be one, the interpretation or communication medium / mechanism is obviously failing.\r\n\r\n\'\'\'â€œPhenomenal Informationâ€\'\'\' is a kind of fundamental or intrinsic quality or causal property of nature.  An example is the property a surface of a strawberry has, in that it causes something like 650 NM light to reflect in a particular pattern.  It is true that an abstract word, like red, can represent this property, but unless you know how to properly interpret the word, you wonâ€™t know that it is referring to this fundamental nature of the surface of the strawberry.  Similarly, the light itself can be interpreted to derive abstract information about the fundamental nature of the surface of the strawberry.  Obviously, the fundamental intrinsic properties of the light are nothing like the properties of the surface of the strawberry, but one can be configured and interpreted to model the other â€“ again, as long as you know how to properly interpret such to get the abstract information about the referent represented.\r\n\r\nIt is theoretically possible to assume that these intrinsic fundamental properties of nature include ineffable â€˜phenomenal propertiesâ€™, or something they are phenomenally like.  If we assumed the surface of the strawberry included some ineffable phenomenal property, and that such was a big part of the reason it reflected 650NM light, we would be blind to such.  Obviously, the light would not have the same phenomenal property, and we would not know how to interpret it, as required to â€˜effâ€™ this ineffable information from the abstract information contained in the intrinsic properties of the reflected light.\r\n\r\nMost any material stuff, if you have enough of it, can be configured to represent or model any other material stuff.  Again, only as long as you have something that can interpret it as such.  If something is fundamentally different, whether phenomenal or not, it always requires the proper interpretation to get back to the original fundamental qualities it is intended to represent, especially if you are talking about ineffable phenomenal qualities, like the taste of salt or redness.\r\n\r\nAll abstract information, if you have enough stuff to represent it, can describe or perfectly model any fundamental properties, and visa versa, as long as you know how to properly interpret them, to get the abstract meaning.  If you know that your redness equals â€˜stopâ€™, you must know what the redness is phenomenally and fundamentally like, so you can interpret it correctly, to represent stop.\r\n\r\nAnother issue weâ€™re having is that Mike Gashler is objecting to the usage of the term â€˜redness is the final result of a perception processes.\r\n\r\nSo, in order to better way why I think saying it this way is so important, lets through phenomenal qualities out of the picture, for a moment.  Letâ€™s talk about a robot we build to pick strawberries.  Like us, this robot has stereoscopic cameras, a body with wheels, a container to hold picked strawberries, and an arm to pick strawberries with and deposit them in the container.\r\n\r\nOf course, the initial cause of the perception process for this robot, begins with the reflection of 650 NM light.  The stereo cameras detect this as 2 2D digital images made of ones for red, and zeros for green.  This goes through an image processing system that does edge detection, and stuff, to build a 3D voxelated representation of the strawberry patch â€“ again, with ones in the volume elements where a surface is reflecting 650 NM light, and zeros that represent something that is reflecting 700 nm light reflected from the leaves.  Included in this 3d voxel model, is a representation of the robot, which the brain can move, the basket, and the arm which the brain can control.\r\n\r\nThe algorithms of course detect the 1 colored objects, move close enough to them so the arm is in range, then it moves the arm to pick them.  Of course, the robot knows nothing of the real strawberry patch, it only knows about its knowledge of the strawberry patch.  And of course, this knowledge is the final result of the robots perception process.\r\n\r\nThere may be some naive person, ignorant of the design, who might assert there is not final result, and that there is some magic algorithm, that enables the robot to be directly aware of the strawberry, or in some way achieves picking behavior in some other way, without having such a 3D voxel representation of the strawberry, but of course, you sue the terminology this particular robot has 3D voxel binary knowledge, that is the final result of the Robotâ€™s perception process â€“ I know this, because I designed and built it that way.\r\n\r\nNow, if we through redness in there, instead of ones, the same terminology applies with even more utility â€“ the robot has knowledge of the strawberry, and this knowledge has an intrinsic phenomenal property that is redness.  And this knowledge, when we experience as our conscious knowledge, is the final result of our eyesâ€™ and image processing systemâ€™s perception process.\r\n\r\nSimply saying it is an â€˜experienceâ€™ can be interpreted as if we are experience the redness of the property itself, and it doesnâ€™t even define what such could be (as if some kind of miracle happens in â€˜experienceâ€™ â€“ and that is the fatal problem of just calling it an experience of the perception process, and why I donâ€™t think I can accept such terminology.\r\n\r\n','2012-05-14 20:29:54','2012-05-14 20:29:54'),(1520,96,48,'Brent said: Now, if we throw redness in there, instead of ones...\r\n\r\nI was with you all the way until this statement. So the new states are 0, 1, and RED, right? Is RED a possible value of abstract information? If so, then let\'s just rename it to 2 for simplicity. Or, are you suggesting that the robot\'s memory, which previously stored only abstract information, through the use of some new advanced technology, can now store phenomenal information? Still, can\'t we just rename it to 2? I\'m really struggling with this notion of phenomenal information.\r\n\r\nBrent said: Simply saying it is an \"experience\" can be interpreted as if we are\r\nexperience the redness of the property itself.\r\n\r\nI agree that we must be careful never to imply that a human (or a robot, or anything else) can directly experience the redness property of a strawberry, or of light, or of anything besides the abstract representation in his/her/its mind. I do, however, intend to suggest that a model comprised exclusively of abstract information is sufficient to trigger an experience of redness. In other words, upon detecting 1s in its memory, a sufficiently complex robot could experience the quale of redness, just like a human. I conjecture that human models consist of nothing besides abstract information, and that the notion of phenomenal information is unnecessary and superfluous to the process of experiencing redness. Belief in phenomenal information is a dualist concept, which we (functional representationalists) reject.\r\n\r\nThe expression, \"qualia are the final result of a perception process\" implies that qualia are the model, which implies that the model contains something phenomenal, which we cannot accept. I would prefer something like, \"experiences of qualia are triggered by the content of our abstract representations\". Do you reject the suggestion that qualia is an experience rather than phenomenal information? How about \"qualia are (or are derived from) our internal representations\"? Or \"qualia are independent of everything besides the representations we form\"? Or \"our abstract model is the only thing that is, or leads to, experiences of qualia\"?','2012-05-14 22:03:14','2012-05-14 22:03:14'),(1523,96,48,'Hi Mike,\r\n\r\nThanks for parsing my gibberish, and divining what I wanted to say, instead of what I said.  I intended to hit \'edit\' to fix some of those problems, but accidentally hit submit.\r\n\r\nAs far as \"throwing in red\" I meant the second option.  The binary robot represented it\'s knowledge with a binary model, represented with 1s and 0s, for which it doesn\'t matter, especially at the decision level what is representing the ones and zeros.  i.e. the robot only knows that the strawberries are represented with one, and it has no idea what that is like.\r\n\r\nI meant to describe entirely replacing this binary model with a phenomenal model (not just expand it), replace it with one for which the algorithm knows what it\'s redness is like, and is able to chose redness, only because it knows what it\'s representations are phenomenally and fundamentally like.\r\n\r\nSo, in other words, by definition, this theory is simply specifying that there is something fundamentally different than abstract information that can represent such.  It is true, that you can represent it with 2, but again, unless you know how to interpret that abstract representation, you can\'t know the fundamental property that 2 should be interpreted as, without providing effing information enabling the proper interpretation.  That is simply the theory, by definition.\r\n\r\n\r\nThanks for your continued patience with all this, and working so hard to find something that will work for everyone.  This is a huge help!!  It also helps me to understand my theory much better.  I must admit that in addition to the phenomenal properties, that are properties of the model built by our brain, there must be some mechanism that enables the system to know what it\'s representations are like, and enabling the picking of the red ones, because they are red.  It also requires the entire system to have some way of binding everything together so we can be aware of the redness, and the greenness, at the same time.  So, it does make some sense to describe all this as an \'experience\' that results from the model, and it\'s properties.\r\n\r\nWhen you say you: \"intend to suggest that a model comprised exclusively of abstract information is sufficient to trigger an experience of redness.\" are you saying a one, alone, no matter what is representing it, and what is required to interpret it as one, anything like this could produce redness?  Or must there be something in addition to just something being interpreted as one instance of a one?\r\n\r\nWhen I was describing that robot, would you agree that the 3D binary voxel model that is the knowledge / model, produced by the robot\'s perception system, is the final result of the robot\'s perception system/process?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop','2012-05-15 01:50:16','2012-05-15 01:50:16'),(1526,96,48,'\r\n\r\nHey Mike,\r\n\r\nWould you feel comfortable with the following?:\r\n\r\nThe common sense word, \'red\' is ambiguous in our attempt to fully describe perception.  There are two very different important parts to the perception of \'red\'.  First is the causal property of something like a strawberry reflecting 650 NM light.  These types of causal properties are the initial cause of a perception process.  The final resulting experience of such a perception process is a phenomenal redness quale.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-05-15 03:53:27','2012-05-15 03:53:27'),(1529,96,48,'Yes, that sounds compatible with how I think it works.','2012-05-15 04:03:17','2012-05-15 04:03:17'),(1530,85,34,'As promoter of UMSITW [pronounced \'um-see-two\'] I would like to point out that there does not appear to be any good evidence coming from brain imaging studies that contradicts the fundamental thesis, that C. [rememberable awareness, shall we say] is what it is like to be the updating of the brain\'s model of self in the world. I understand that everybody has their own pet theories and understandings, but I wish to contend that there is no good philosophical reason for rejecting the idea either. \r\n\r\nIndeed, when I read the tail-chasing discussions going on in attempts to clarify what people think about qualia for example, I am amazed. The fact is our experience of the world is deeply paradoxical, if we stop to think about it, yet most of the time we don\'t have to think about it because naive realism is very effective for allowing us to accomplish most of what we need to do in our practical work-a-day worlds. I could almost make an analogy: that naive realism is nature\'s version of Newtonian physics.\r\n\r\nSophisticated realism on the other hand can be quite mind blowing; and most of the time it takes effort to keep any awareness of it. AND, a second thing I would like to point out is that UMSITW does not sit well with the idea of \'effing the ineffable\'. Reasons for this latter statement can be provided if required. \r\n\r\n xodarap  :-)     AKA Mark Peaty','2012-05-16 12:42:27','2012-05-16 12:42:27'),(1533,96,48,'\r\nGreat, I see now that the way I was saying it before was inadequate, even for my theory, so I agree this is much better.  Thanks for helping me better see the importance of this.\r\n\r\n\r\nI\'ve cleaned up a bunch of stuff in the current statement in Google docs.  Let me know if I did anything I shouldn\'t have.  If you agree that we can replace the one paragraph, with the replacement I proposed, just remove the old one.\r\n\r\nI think we\'re starting to get close to a much improved statement.\r\n\r\nWhat else do we need?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-05-17 02:05:38','2012-05-17 02:05:38'),(1536,96,48,'Ok, I replaced that paragraph with yours. I also did another edit-pass over the document. Feel free to revert my changes that you don\'t like (I will push back if it matters to me). I feel that we are getting pretty close, but I would feel better if more people were doing edit-passes, to make sure it really represents all of us.\r\n\r\nAnd here\'s the Google-doc link again:\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit?disco=AAAAAEFjmp4','2012-05-17 16:07:04','2012-05-17 16:07:04'),(1539,96,48,'\r\nThere is currently this statement in the current RQT statement in the Google doc:  \"Information theory mandates that if we know something, there must be something physical that is representing this knowledge\".  To which Mike objects with:\r\n\r\n\"I still don\'t understand what this paragraph is trying to say.  Which sentence represents the main point that is trying to make\"\r\n\r\nThere is an important doctrine here that I\'m trying to capture and explain.  I would very much like to clearly include this doctrine in RQT.  I thought the first sentence would accomplish this, and thought this was the sentence Mike was asking for.  But obviously it isn\'t sufficient.\r\n\r\nJames proposes a new version of Dennett\'s we don\'t have qualia it just seems like we do, but to me, this further obfuscates this critically important issue, that we must directly face, not further obfuscate or attempt to hide.\r\n\r\nSo I propose we giving this doctrine some kind of name, and dedicating a section to this doctrine.  Perhaps something like the following:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n== Physical Law of Information ==\r\n\r\n[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_theory  Shannon Information Theory] is the law that information cannot exist unless there is something physical that is representing it.  This doctrine also specifically defines, mechanically, what it means to \'interpret as\', or to \'seem\' or to be \'perceived as\' or whatever.  All such notions require two parts.  There is what is being perceived, and there is the perception.  Both must be physically real, and to \'interpret\' is to map one, from one physical representation to another, that also must be physical.\r\n\r\nOur brains tends to represent notions like \'seeming\' in a very naive and insufficient way.  When we see the bent pencil, sticking out of the glass of water, our brain represents it as if there is the real pencil, we know is straight - but that is the end of our intuitive knowledge.  There is no notion that we have knowledge that really is bent.  But this is, according to Information Theory, impossible,  If it \'seems\' bent, there must be something that is your bent knowledge, or something that is the seeming, the way we interpret what our senses are telling us about the pencil.\r\n\r\nWhen people like Daniel Dennett try to hide \'qualia\' in some kind of naive view of \'to seem\', when they say something like we don\'t have qualia , it only seems like we do, they should at a very minimum, define, mechanically, what they mean by seeming.  Since to the rest of us that understand the physical law of information, it just looks like they are clearly falling into this naive trap, and missing the fact that there must be something that is the seeming.  How could a \'seeming\', such as Dennett is talking about, be modeled in a computer, without some kind of \"a miracle happens here\"?\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-05-18 11:51:28','2012-05-18 11:51:28'),(1542,96,48,'The way I like to express that concept is to say that experience has an information content, and information cannot exist without a medium, or carrier, to carry that information, and the information content of the experience cannot possibly be any greater than the information explicitly encoded in the corresponding neurophysiological state.\r\n\r\nHere is an exerpt from my paper...\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubw3/bubw3.html\r\n\r\nThe dual nature of a percept is analogous to the representation of data in a digital computer, where a pattern of voltages present in a particular memory register can represent some meaningful information, either a numerical value, or a brightness value in an image, or a character of text, etc. when viewed from inside the appropriate software environment, while when viewed in external physical terms that same data takes the form of voltages or currents in particular parts of the machine. However whatever form is selected for encoding data in the computer, the information content of that data cannot possibly be of higher dimensionality than the information explicitly expressed in the physical state of the machine. The same principle must also hold in perceptual experience, as proposed by MÃ¼ller (1896), in the psychophysical postulate. MÃ¼ller argued that since the subjective experience of perception is encoded in some neurophysiological state, the information encoded in that conscious experience cannot possibly be any greater than the information encoded in the corresponding neurophysiological state.While we cannot observe phenomenologically the physical medium by which perceptual information is encoded in the brain, we can observe the information encoded in that medium, expressed in terms of the variables of subjective experience. It follows therefore that it should be possible by direct phenomenological observation to determine the dimensions of conscious experience, and thereby to infer the dimensions of the information encoded neurophysiologically in the brain.','2012-05-18 12:58:01','2012-05-18 12:58:01'),(1545,96,48,'\r\nAh, thatâ€™s great; Steve, to talk about quantity of information content, and that it cannot exceed that which is physically represented.\r\n\r\nI fixed some things in my proposed new doctrine section, and integrated this concept into a new statement, and added it to the document (intended to replace the 3 paragraphs that still follow this section.)\r\n\r\n','2012-05-18 14:15:22','2012-05-18 14:15:22'),(1548,96,48,'Brent, this is my attempt to respond to: when they say something like we don\'t have qualia , it only seems like we do, they should at a very minimum, define, mechanically, what they mean by seeming.\r\n\r\nObviously I cannot speak for Daniel Dennett, but this seems (half-pun, sorry) well-defined to me, so I\'d like to take a stab at defining what I think he means by \"seems\". (Of course, I don\'t expect you to agree, I just want to show that no one is using vague or undefined terms here.)\r\n\r\nThe model (or representation) of the real world created by the human mind provides the very definition of what \"seems to be\". If our model says the world is a certain way, then it seems to be that way. If something \"seems\" a certain way, then the model in our head *is* representing it that way. The model *is* the thing that *is* that information. The model satisfies the mandates of information theory.\r\n\r\nIn the real world, the pencil is straight. In our model, the pencil bends where it enters the water. The model is wrong, but it is well-defined. The pencil \"seems\" bent because the model says it is bent, even though it is really straight in the real world. The strawberry \"seems\" red, but this is not true either. In the real world, the strawberry reflects 720nm light, which is not the same thing as being red. Once again, the model is wrong, and that creates what \"seems to be\". When you put your hand in fire, it seems to hurt, but in reality the tissue in your hand is being destroyed by intense chemical reactions, which is not the same as pain. The model in your brain does not understand \"being destroyed by chemical reactions\", so it models it as closely as it can--with pain. When your model is accurate, then \"what seems to be\" is the same as \"what really is\". Since qualia does not occur in the real world, all qualia are fallacious representations of the real world--experiences that seem real but are actually poor approximations of a more complex world. All qualia are illusions. They just \"seem\" real because our model says they *are* real, and the model is wrong.\r\n\r\nWhere is the \"miracle\" in that? Misrepresenting the world doesn\'t seem all that impressive to me. I would be more impressed if our brains build more accurate models, allowing us to see the strawberry as it really is, reflecting 720nm light. A better example of an ill-defined \"miracle\" would be seeing fundamental red painted on the models in our brains. How could that possibly work? Where is the consciousness within our consciousness that can see what the model is painted with? That would be a true \"miracle\".','2012-05-18 15:10:48','2012-05-18 15:10:48'),(1551,96,48,'\r\nHi Mike,\r\n\r\nSo you donâ€™t see this statement: â€œThey just â€œseemâ€ real because our model says they *are* real, and the model is wrong.â€ As an obvious violation of Shanonâ€™s Information Theory?\r\n\r\nWhat is it, in this model, that is wrong?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop','2012-05-18 15:48:16','2012-05-18 15:48:16'),(1554,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nNo, I do not see how either of those statements violate information theory. What aspect of information theory do they violate?\r\n\r\nRegarding what in the model is wrong, let us consider the pencil-in-water example. The representation of the pencil in your head is bent. The real pencil is not bent. That which misrepresents reality is, by definition, wrong.\r\n\r\nmike','2012-05-18 19:24:02','2012-05-18 19:24:02'),(1557,96,48,'\r\nHi Mike,\r\n\r\nExactly, in the example of the pencil, what is wrong, is the bent knowledge of the pencil.  That thing that is wrong is something real and must be represented by neural structures.\r\n\r\nSo, my question to you is, if someone is saying we donâ€™t have qualia, it only seems like we do, in the same way, what is it that is wrong?  You said â€œthe model says they are real and the model is wrongâ€ What is the communication mechanism that is â€˜sayingâ€™ this is wrong?  And what/where/how and why is this phenomenal information that you know is wrong?\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2012-05-18 20:27:29','2012-05-18 20:27:29'),(1560,96,48,'In the pencil example, you are pointing out what it is that is wrong, and therefor it is not violating Shanonâ€™s information theory.  In the second case, I canâ€™t see what it is that is wrong, or what it is that is â€˜sayingâ€™ to you it is wrong, so it is an obvious violation of Information Theory.\r\n\r\n','2012-05-18 20:39:20','2012-05-18 20:39:20'),(1563,96,48,'Mike,\r\n\r\nYou are right in one sense, but only you when you extend your naive realism (the pencil looks bent) to additional levels of realism (I can tell that it only looks bent, and I understand that it is possible for things to seem one way in one sense and a different way in another sense).\r\n\r\nWhat this means is that when you say \"The real pencil is not bent. That which misrepresents reality is, by definition, wrong.\" you assume that there is a \"real pencil\" based purely on the bias of perceptual capacities of your human body. Your psychological capacities extend the low level perception to a more subtle level of perceptual interpretation in which you can entertain a difference between a real pencil and a visual appearance. \r\n\r\nI submit that the bent pencil is, in a sense, a much more \'real\' pencil in that it reflects not only this distant object of physical surfaces of a pencil and water, but it conveys a condensed encyclopedia on optics and perception which lead directly to discoverable neurological truths. It is the simplistic interpretation of a literal reality that \'simply *is*\', independent of a perceptual experience of that reality, which is in fact a misrepresentation of reality. That\'s right. Fiction is primordial, fact is contrived.\r\n\r\nCraig\r\n','2012-05-18 20:57:04','2012-05-18 20:57:04'),(1566,96,48,'Craig,\r\n\r\nSure, you can define reality however you like. Perhaps the bent pencil is more real. Nevertheless, it is an inaccurate representation of the physical world, and it is the physical world that led to the image on the back of my retina. I am not saying one is more real than the other. I am only saying that they are not the same.\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent,\r\n\r\nIn the second case, the representation says the strawberry is red. In reality, the strawberry reflects light with 720nm wavelength. Not the same--therefore, the representation is wrong.\r\n\r\nOnce again, the brain has resorted to using a lossy representation of reality. Perhaps you find \"red\" to be more likeable than a strictly and precisely accurate model of the causal properties in the physical world. That\'s fine. But the model still does not correctly represent the physical world (which I think is the purpose of a representation). I admit that the brain may not have enough information to build a strictly accurate model. Building a strictly correct model may be an impossible task. I also think that the brain does a darn fine job, and that it has created a rather ingenious substitute for the physics that it failed to correctly model. But no matter how you look at it, the model is not a strictly accurate representation of reality. Red may be beautiful. It may be wonderful. Perhaps \"red\" is even better than a strictly accurate representation of the causal properties in the physical world. Perhaps the brain does it this way on purpose for some higher reason that I do not understand. I am not saying red is bad or ugly or evil. I am only saying that it is not an accurate representation of the physics that led to the perception.\r\n','2012-05-18 22:05:08','2012-05-18 22:05:08'),(1569,96,48,'Hi Mike,\r\n\r\nNo you\'re talking about something different now: the \'redness\' that represents reality.  I wasn\'t talking about this.  I was talking about Dennett\'s statement that we don\'t have qualia \"it only seems like we do.\"  Of course, redness is not an accurate representation of something that reflects 700 NM light.  So the redness is only a seeming, and it is what is wrong, as far as it\'s ability to represent what we perceive.  In the same way, when someone says we don\'t have this seeming, or we don\'t have qualia, it only seems like we do, in THAT case what is wrong, and what is representing this wrong information?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-05-18 22:35:27','2012-05-18 22:35:27'),(1572,96,48,'Mike,\r\n\r\nWhat I am saying though is that physical worlds are a property of perception but perception is not a property of physical worlds, if you define physical as being appearances of object surfaces in space, density, motion, etc.\r\n\r\nIt is levels of nested perception which lead to the idea of a physical reality, so that they actually are the same - they are both fiction, but the idea of the physical pencil is a high level cognitive fiction which refers to a consensus of lowest common denominator measurements and observations (also fictions, but more universal fictions...flatter fictions (qualia) are more quantitative and literal.\r\n\r\nIt is inaccurate to say that our naive perception is inaccurate in an absolute sense, since it is not a representation of an objective reality that is independent of all observation, but a presentation which has been folded in on itself many times. This folding entails ambiguity between the folds, which the idealized pencil-as-real-object idea serves to cut through with another layer of realistic dream.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-05-18 22:41:41','2012-05-18 22:41:41'),(1575,96,48,'Brent, \r\n\r\nI would go further to say that 700NM light is actually the representation. The fact that we measure electromagnetic activity at that frequency in many physical instruments designed for that purpose only means that it is a popular seeming. It is the seeming itself which is the genuine presentation. \r\n\r\nThe quantitative conceptualization of the correlations of material behavior with our first hand visual experience is actually the re-presentation: a figurative intellectual perception derived from a literal experience. It\'s not the qualia that is representational, it is instead the idea that there is anything else in the universe other than qualia that is a theoretical construct (which is qualia too, but of a more subtle variety than our sense perception).','2012-05-18 23:49:23','2012-05-18 23:49:23'),(1578,96,48,'Craig,\r\n\r\nI must apologize, but most of what you say both has no meaning to me, and / or I see no utility in what you seem to be saying.  I don\'t know what you mean by your usage of the term \"Fiction\", or \"Primordial\", \"contrived\"...  What could you mean by \"nested perception\"? or that such \"leads to an idea of physical reality\"?  None of any of that is related to anything I think is important about consciousness.\r\n\r\nOf course, many people say the same thing about me and what I say, so I know what that is like! ;)\r\n\r\nI understand what you say, when you say: \"700nm light is actually the representation\", but how is this going further than anything?  You don\'t seem to be understanding anything I\'m saying.  I\'ve been trying to say all along, that the light is a representation, the ones and zeros in a camera representing this light are a representation, the \'red\' signal in my optic nerve is a representation - they\'re all things that are being abstractly interpreted as the surface of the strawberry, and my brain is representing all this with my redness.  To me, the nature of this final qualia, is all I\'m interested in, none of this other unrelated stuff you seem to be talking about makes any sense to me.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-05-19 00:26:29','2012-05-19 00:26:29'),(1581,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nCould you elaborate on the difference between the redness that represents reality and the qualia referenced by Dennett? I assumed they were the same notion, and cannot seem to find any place to split them.\r\n\r\n\r\nCraig,\r\n\r\nMy wife always seems to remember where I left my keys, my shoes, my computer, and where I parked the car. It seems like we live in the same world. Perhaps I am wrong, but it is still useful for me to pretend we share a common reality--it helps me find my keys, etc. Likewise, I strongly believe that pretending there is a common physical world will help me arrive at a more accurate understanding of qualia than any other model of reality that I could consider. To me, this one is tried and tested, while all others are just weird and confusing.','2012-05-19 01:00:25','2012-05-19 01:00:25'),(1584,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nNo apology necessary, I know this is an unfamiliar way of looking at things, and I appreciate your patience.\r\n\r\nBy fiction I mean stories, characters, metaphor, dreams, qualia. What I\'m saying then is that facts are a category of most realistic seeming stories in that they are shared by more participants (participants includes what we think of as atoms, cells, bodies...only not the forms and structures that we see but their inner storytelling process).\r\n\r\nBy primordial I mean irreducible, unique, and without precedent. The ground of being itself.\r\n\r\nContrived = second order logic, epiphenomenon\r\n\r\nNested perception is stories within stories organized by scale and frequency. For example, your visual cortex tells the story of what your retina\'s story says (and has ever said) about the optical story of the world outside of your body which tells part of the story of human civilization, evolution, geological and astrophysical history.\r\n\r\nIt relates to consciousness because I am saying that physical reality is nothing more or less than a story within consciousness. It\'s a particular kind of story, but ultimately it has no independent existence outside of an audience\'s ability to interpret stories from other interpreters experiences.\r\n\r\n\"You don\'t seem to be understanding anything I\'m saying. I\'ve been trying to say all along, that the light is a representation, the ones and zeros in a camera representing this light are a representation, the \'red\' signal in my optic nerve is a representation \"\r\n\r\nThe light is a conceptual representation from physics theory, \r\n\r\nThe ones and zeroes are a conceptual representation from mathematical theory and computer science which stand for microelectronic changes that switch the configuration of a semiconductor.\r\n\r\nThe changes in the semiconductor are invisible to us but we model them by interpreting the behavior of physical instruments that we use to measure and control them. What changes them is conceived of as \'energy\', but I am saying that energy is literally nothing whatsoever except for \'everything that happens to matter\', and that matter is nothing except for \'everything that seems to be outside of ourselves\' - it\'s a perception of our body\'s world.\r\n\r\nThere is no red signal in your optic nerve. There is only synchronized changes within the cells and molecules of the nerve tissue. Red is not a signal, even though it can signify that something is red. Red is our direct presentation of visual experience. Red is what we are built to see and what is built to be seen by us (and whatever other creatures might see red or taste red or think red...)\r\n\r\n\"they\'re all things that are being abstractly interpreted as the surface of the strawberry, and my brain is representing all this with my redness.\"\r\n\r\nNo, red is the real surface of the strawberry. Nothing in the universe is more real to you than that. It is the only real presentation of the strawberry that anything like you will ever know. There is no deeper reality to the strawberry, only representations of non-human scale realism.\r\n\r\n\"To me, the nature of this final qualia, is all I\'m interested in, none of this other unrelated stuff you seem to be talking about makes any sense to me. \"\r\n\r\nThat\'s because you are looking at the entire universe inside out. Everyone who has been conditioned in 20th century legacy worldview is looking at it inside out. Qualia is the only reality. Matter is just body qualia seen second hand by brain qualia (the self).\r\n\r\n\r\nMike,\r\n\r\n\"Perhaps I am wrong, but it is still useful for me to pretend we share a common reality--it helps me find my keys, etc\"\r\n\r\nAbsolutely, and you do share a common reality - because you are very similar interpreters. You are both mammals, hominids, 21st century first world citizens, you are in close physical proximity and have common history, etc. It is useful to think of it that way. I only point out that if you want to understand qualia you have to realize how relativistic it really is, to the point that there is nothing whatsoever but sense experiences and that experience defines existence.\r\n\r\n\"Likewise, I strongly believe that pretending there is a common physical world will help me arrive at a more accurate understanding of qualia than any other model of reality that I could consider. To me, this one is tried and tested, while all others are just weird and confusing.\"\r\n\r\nThere is an experience of a physical world common to anything which has a physical body. It\'s just that whatever your body is defines the experience of your physical world. It\'s not literally a world, it is synchronized qualia. The world is shared from within. No physical model of qualia can be accurate or be tested because qualia is inherently private and physics is inherently public. It may be weird and confusing to think of qualia as the fundamental unit of the cosmos, but there is no other possible truth as far as I can tell - even though modeling it inside out can be very powerful and useful at actually engineering experiences.','2012-05-19 01:45:19','2012-05-19 01:45:19'),(1587,96,48,'Hi Craig,\r\n\r\nYou asked about the difference between \"the redness that represents reality and the qualia referenced by Dennett\"\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure I fully understand your question, as I think both Dennet and I believe our brains use redness or qualia to represent, abstractly, the reality our cause and effect senses detect?\r\n\r\nI, myself, am struggling with what Dennett (and James and Mike?)  mean when they use the word \'qualia\'.  For me, qualia are ineffable, but evidently for them they aren\'t?  If not, then what are qualia, I ask.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-05-19 02:30:38','2012-05-19 02:30:38'),(1590,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nI think that was Mike\'s question actually. \r\n\r\nAs I understood Dennett\'s position, I thought he believes that qualia is nothing more than the function of the brain, ie, there is no such thing as qualia, it\'s more of a misinterpretation of neurological functions.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-05-19 03:39:43','2012-05-19 03:39:43'),(1593,96,48,'Mike says \r\n\r\n>>>\r\n\r\nthere is nothing whatsoever but sense experiences and that experience defines existence.\r\n\r\n<<< \r\n\r\nThis is an *initial hypothesis* that he holds, it is not a conclusion based on the facts, just one of a few possible interpretations of reality including the other possibility, that the world has objective existence independent of our experience of it.\r\n\r\nYour debate is going round and round in useless circles because you are arguing from opposite sides of that paradigmatic fence, without addressing the core issue. Does the world have objective existence?\r\n\r\nOf course anyone who doubts something so fundamental is not about to change their mind.\r\n\r\n','2012-05-19 11:48:48','2012-05-19 11:48:48'),(1596,96,48,'As *I* understand Dennett\'s position, his principle objection is to the claim that visual experience is spatially structured, that experience appears as solid volumes with colored surfaces embedded in a spatial void.\r\n\r\nDennett argues that experience only \"seems\" to be spatially structured, when you analyze it moment to moment, it is more like a sequence of darting attentional shifts, there is no vivid surrounding spatial structure to our experience, that is an illusion.\r\n\r\nDennett\'s argument is a stark contradiction in terms. Experience is experienced exactly as it is experienced to be, and no different. And *my* experience is clearly spatially structured. Dennett\'s argument is a desperate attempt to save naive realism from its own logical contradictions, by introducing more logical contradictions to balance the first.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-05-19 12:41:26','2012-05-19 12:41:26'),(1599,96,48,'slehar,\r\n\r\nTo be clear, I have never argued that \"the world has objective\r\nexistence independent of our experience of it.\", only *our* world has no existence independent of our experience if it. \r\n\r\n\"The\" world has no objective existence independent of \"its\" experiences. The universe is experience. Things are detections and reaction experiences. How can they not be? A sphere is flat as board if you are small enough and close enough to it\'s surface. Without sense to distinguish flat from round, what sort of a universe can exist? What form would it take as an intangible, silent, invisible, odorless, sizeless, shapeless interplay of...what? Freestanding arithmetic relations? Disembodied laws fluctuating in the void? How metaphysical and unreal can you get?\r\n\r\n\"Your debate is going round and round in useless circles because you are arguing from opposite sides of that paradigmatic fence, without addressing the core issue. Does the world have objective existence?\"\r\n\r\n*Our* world has objective existence *to us*. That includes our body\'s world which has objective existence to the cells, organs, and molecules that make it up. A rhinovirus has no objective existence to me until I start feeling a sore throat, but it has objective existence to the cells of my body earlier. The sore throat isn\'t merely the qualia that represents the virus - the cold qualia or experience *is* the concretely real presentation of the virus in my scope of experience. \r\n\r\nThat my experience, as this hugely enfolded sense experience (multiply involuted, nested inertial frame) of being human should differ from a virologists undertstanding of my experience does not make his second hand knowledge about the microbiological events taking place in my body the \'right\' or \'real\' interpretation. It doesn\'t become right or real until it makes a difference for us on our level. \r\n\r\nMy senses report from the self-centered, or polar-coordinate oriented perspective (radial symmetry) within my own native inertial frame. i.e. it is reported to me in the language of myself, my life, my family, ancestors, species, substance.\r\n\r\n\"Of course anyone who doubts something so fundamental is not about to change their mind.\"\r\n\r\nI have already changed my mind about these fundamental issues twice. That\'s how I know this makes more sense then the other possibilities. I have seen and felt it first hand.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-05-19 12:44:10','2012-05-19 12:44:10'),(1602,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nI certainly cannot eff (communicate) any quale right now, nor can anyone else. I have only conjectured that perhaps some day science may figure out how to read the qualia experienced by Alice and then cause Bob to experience the same. If this happens, then the qualia was communicated from Alice to Bob, and was therefore effed. If RF is right, this may require the entire structure of Alice\'s brain to be communicated (which would take a lot of words). If PD is right, it would only require the dual to be communicated (which would require far fewer words). Hence, I would expect the PDists to think qualia was more effable than the RFists. Am I way off here?\r\n\r\nmike','2012-05-19 13:26:48','2012-05-19 13:26:48'),(1605,96,48,'Oh, I think I figured out what information theory has to do with all this. You (Brent) say that qualia is the model in our head, right? So, when Daniel Dennett says \"we do not really have qualia, it just seems like we do\", you interpret this to mean \"we do not really have a model, it just seems like we do\". So, you were using information theory to prove that this is non-sensical. Information cannot exist without a representation. It follows that we cannot seem to have qualia without actually having a model in our heads. I can agree with this reasoning.\r\n\r\nI suspect, however, that Daniel Dennett did not intend to say that we lack a representation in our heads. (I think he would say that the mechanisms of the brain is not his department.) I think the intended meaning of his statement is, we only see red in our model of the strawberry, but it seems like it is really out there on the strawberry.','2012-05-19 16:32:57','2012-05-19 16:32:57'),(1608,96,48,'\r\nHi Mike,\r\n\r\nYes, you got it.  If we know something, whether it is a seeming or not, there must be something that is that knowledge.\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-05-19 21:05:46','2012-05-19 21:05:46'),(1611,96,48,'That wording has some ambiguity issues. How about something like this?\r\n\r\nRepresentations of some sort are responsible for every idea, impression, and feeling that occurs in the human mind. It is impossible, therefore, to experience a quale without forming a corresponding representation somewhere within our consciousness. The difference between the \"redness\" of a strawberry and its causal property of reflecting 720nm light is exactly the difference between our mental representation of the strawberry and the physical strawberry.','2012-05-20 02:52:09','2012-05-20 02:52:09'),(1614,96,48,'\r\nMike,\r\n\r\nWow, I like it.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2012-05-20 04:13:34','2012-05-20 04:13:34'),(1617,96,48,'Yes, I like it too, it belongs in the camp statement I think. Way to go Mike. ','2012-05-21 18:24:14','2012-05-21 18:24:14'),(1620,96,48,'How can you have a representation without a presentation though? Nothing can see 720nm light except through their own qualia. It is the concept of \'light\' as a physical phenomenon that is independent from matter that is an intellectual representation of the various qualia of light. Qualia is physically real. Light is an abstraction.','2012-05-21 19:41:03','2012-05-21 19:41:03'),(1623,96,48,'@Multisense Realism. \r\n\r\nI don\'t agree with your theory at all... I believe that reality exists, that our senses sense this reality, and that our brains build models about this reality. Although I agree that we only EXPERIENCE reality through this process, I nevertheless think that reality exists, is what is \"physically real\" and what we are perceiving, and building models of. I think that the idea that only qualia is \"real\" is backwards. \r\n\r\nMore importantly, it seems clear that you don\'t belong in RQT, so I see no reason to modify the RQT camp statement to agree with your theory. I would recommend moving the multisense realism theory out of RQT myself. The fundamental tenant of RQT is that qualia is based on a representation of reality. ','2012-05-21 20:01:20','2012-05-21 20:01:20'),(1626,96,48,'@jlcarroll\r\n\r\nI believe that reality exists too. The reality that makes sense to us directly through our organic sense organs, and through the sense that we make by extending those senses artificially.\r\n\r\nI understand that you don\'t believe my view, and that it seems backwards to you. It\'s only because you assume that there is a such thing as \'existence\' independent of some form of detection of that existence. It\'s the prevailing view worldwide, but it\'s as obsolete as Ptolemy in my opinion.\r\n\r\nI agree with you that Multisense Realism should not be under RQT, but it should be under Panexperientialism, which someone has put under RQT. I don\'t expect you to modify RQT based on my input, I\'m just here in case any of you gets tired of trying to wedge the square peg of qualia into it\'s own round hole of representation and wants to consider an alternative that does actually make more sense.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-05-21 20:13:34','2012-05-21 20:13:34'),(1629,96,48,'MBI is also under PD, while RF is a MBI theory. This happens all the time, because we have a multi-vectored problem, and what ends up at the root depends on what is most universally accepted. \r\n\r\nOur solution in RF was to simply mention that we are also a form of MBI, just a non-PD form, and point at the MBI camp by a link. I recommend doing the same for your Panexperientialism problem.\r\n\r\nAlso, to explain how I think about your theory, imagine a hidden markov model http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hidden_Markov_model. Yes, you only observe the observation nodes, But you can posit a theory about the values in the hidden nodes, and you can use Occam\'s razor to assume that there is some structure there, even though it is not directly observable to you. This is the reality, the hidden nodes. My observations are the model my brain makes of the reality. I infer the existence of the reality in the same way I infer the existence of hidden nodes in the hidden Markov model. ','2012-05-21 20:19:08','2012-05-21 20:19:08'),(1632,96,48,'Thanks, I\'ll look into recanonizing.\r\n\r\nI understand your view of my view completely, but my view takes a more skeptical view. If the nodes are hidden, then we don\'t know that they are nodes at all. The observed nodes may be just the loops of thread that are popping up in the quilt that we are also a part of which is made of observation itself. \r\n\r\nI just posted about where RQT goes wrong: http://multisenserealism.com/2012/05/21/feeling-real-in-the-world-of-sense/\r\n\r\n\"In this view (RQT), our perception is thought to mediate, to represent a real world that we canâ€™t understand into an unreal experience that we can understand. The psyche is a transformer, turning meaningless reality into meaningful illusion.\"\r\n\r\nWhat I suggest is that reality, meaning, illusion, and meaninglessness can only be different aspects of the same thing, otherwise it would be impossible for sanity to exist.','2012-05-21 22:05:48','2012-05-21 22:05:48'),(1635,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nI\'m doing another pass on what we have so far.  I\'ve taken Mikes words from [http://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/30/100#100 post #100 in this thread] about what I\'ve been calling this \"Law of Information\", that I think was great, and James indicated should be in the statement.  I combined this with the comments James made about what he think Dennett really means, when he says it only seems like we have qualia.  I\'ve included this new proposal below for what this \"Law of Information\" is, to see if anyone has issues with this new version.  If there are no remaining issues, I\'m thinking I\'ll clean up everything in the document there now about this \"law of information\", the comments about it, and much of the duplicate stuff at the end, and replace it all with this new version below.\r\n\r\nWe\'re still working on the set of questions to help one determine what camp they are in.  I believe James proposed the first question be something like:\r\n\r\n# Is there something beyond structure and dynamics of physics?\r\n** Yes: Property Dualism.\r\n** No: Representational Functionalism.\r\n\r\nBut this is problematic, to me, because I belong in the \"Property Dualism\" camp, yet I agree with the statement that there is nothing \"beyond structure and dynamics of physics\".  I believe we only have abstracted interpreted knowledge about the \'structure and dynamics of physics\', and that there is something more  than this abstract knowledge, not something more than the actual structure and dynamics of the actual fundamental physics itself.\"  My model is that we are simply blind to these ineffable phenomenal properties of the structure and dynamics of physics, until we discover what it is that  has them, and thereby know how to get more than just the interpreted abstract information about such, from our senses.  In other words, until we know what this abstract information comment to us through our senses phenomenal \'means\' and how to interpret it, we will be missing something in our knowledge of the \'structure and dynamics of physics\"\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n=================================\r\n\r\n\r\n= Physical Law of Information =\r\n\r\n[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_theory  Shannon Information Theory] is the idea that you cannot have information content greater than that which is physically represented.  We consider this to be a law.  Given this, representations of some sort are responsible for every idea, impression, and feeling that occurs in the human mind. It is impossible, therefore, to experience a quale without forming a corresponding representation somewhere within our consciousness. The difference between the \"redness\" of a strawberry and its causal property of reflecting 650 nm light is exactly the difference between our mental representation of the strawberry and the physical strawberry.\r\n\r\nWhen Daniel Dennett says something like we don\'t have qualia, it just seems like we do, this seems kind of silly given this \"Law of Information\".  If you define qualia to be the experiences that we seem to have, for whatever reasons, then we clearly have them.  We assume Dennett, instead, might be trying to refer to someone assuming that the above model of seeming represents something beyond the structure and dynamics of physics, then this does make sense.  We have a quale, that is a property of the structure and dynamics of physics, someone is incorrectly assuming that this knowledge means there is some kind of \'epiphenomena\' not related to physics.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-05-27 18:12:36','2012-05-27 18:12:36'),(1638,96,48,'I thought the wording in the Physical Law of Information section was somewhat confusing, so I rewrote it. I tried to preserve the intent, but since I am not confident I really understood it, additional passes may be needed to restore what I stomped over.\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit?disco=AAAAAEXe_vo\r\n','2012-05-29 01:53:12','2012-05-29 01:53:12'),(1641,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nIâ€™m commenting on blogs, and such, about the discussions weâ€™re having here about Dennettâ€™s â€˜we donâ€™t have qualia, it just seems like we do in various forums.  An example being this comment I made on [http://www.theofrak.com/2012/05/atheist-heroes-daniel-dennett.html?showComment=1338311471597#c7422844521814463414 Theofrack blog]:  If I misrepresented anything, or not, itâ€™d be great to have others respond.\r\n','2012-05-29 17:29:35','2012-05-29 17:29:35'),(1644,96,48,'I examined the wrong one. The version I thought was confusing was the one in the Google Doc. The one you posted in this forum is much better. Here are my comments on this one.\r\n\r\nThe first sentence needs a little elaboration. Specifically, it is not clear that Dennet\'s statement (\"we don\'t have qualia, it just seems like we do\") implies that some information exists without a physical representation. (Are you saying that quale is  information? Wouldn\'t that contradict material property dualism? And are you saying that \"we don\'t have\" means \"no physical representation exists\"?) Also, the last sentence seems to have a grammatical issue, perhaps a missing \"if\"?\r\n\r\nWith these changes, I predict that even Daniel Dennet would probably agree with the physical law of information and would admit to having used a term in his expression that did not represent his view with technical accuracy. Does he respond to e-mails? If so, what\'s stopping us from asking him?\r\n','2012-05-31 17:08:36','2012-05-31 17:08:36'),(1647,96,48,'\r\nQualia are the *carrier* of the information in experience, the information itself is expressed as modulation of those carriers across space and time.\r\n\r\nFor example our experience takes the form of a surrounding spatial void, parts of which appear as empty space, other parts appear as solid volumes, bounded by colored surfaces, embedded in the spatial void.\r\n\r\nAny point can appear as transparent or opaque, and if opaque, it can be experienced at any color, brightness, saturation, and transparency.\r\n\r\nLike a television screen equipped to depict any colored image on the screen, the \"screen\" of our experience is the space we experience around us, and the modulations of that experience are experienced as colored surfaces and volumes.','2012-05-31 18:04:10','2012-05-31 18:04:10'),(1650,96,48,'\r\nHi Mike,\r\n\r\nGood idea, let\'s ask Dan Dennett!  I\'ve contacted him at least once, soliciting his participation in the survey, but that was a long time ago.  Perhaps he was initially interested, then maybe after looking at the site, seeing he\'d be one of the few qualophobes, didn\'t get over the hump of actually finding time to reply.\r\n\r\nBut if you contacted him, on behalf of You, James, and all of us, indicating that you and he support his camp, and that you are working to further develop such in this survey, and that we all have this specific question to ask him.  I bet that\'d get him over the hump, and that he\'d reply.  I think we should also CC Keith Frankish, who has told me he supports the \"it only seems like we have qualia\" camp with Dennett.  Also, Richard Brown, who indicated he\'d help us encourage Keith to follow through on his initial indication he was interested in helping with this camp.  (see: http://www.philostv.com/richard-brown-and-keith-frankish/ ).\r\n\r\nIt\'d sure be great to see what all these people think, and I\'d bet at least some would help out.  We could sign the letter from all of us.\r\n\r\nI\'m working on a post to answer your other questions, and I have some questions in reply to Steve\'s comments, also.  I\'ll post those in subsequent posts as I get time.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-01 00:45:33','2012-06-01 00:45:33'),(1653,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nThis is my response to Mike\'s question: \"Are you saying quale is information?\" and or that it exists without some representation?\r\n\r\nMaterial Property Dualism predicts that the term \"Information\", like the term \"Red\" is ambiguous, or insufficient in adequately modeling what we know about reality.  MPD predicts there are two drastically different types of information.  There is abstract information, and there is phenomenal information.\r\n\r\nAbstract Information, is not like anything and is not real, in a platonic kind of way, other than it can be represented or instantiated by something physical.  The only way to get the information from the physical representation, is to properly interpret the properties of whatever is representing it.\r\n\r\nPhenomenal information is very different, in a fundamental and phenomenally real way.  Phenomenal information is \'ineffable\', unlike abstract information.  It is based on the fact that something like a pattern of 650NM light, reflected off of a strawberry, is nothing like what it can be interpreted as representing - the properties of the surface of the strawberry.  The fact that the map, is not the territory, is critically important.  You must properly interpret one, to arrive at the referent, to know what it is phenomenally, (and causally, for that matter) like.\r\n\r\nMPD simply predicts that these phenomenal properties are a different kind of fundamental dimension to the causal properties, of the same.  Functional Property Dualism says that these real properties are somehow tied to the right \'function\' in some magical or \'hard\' way.  Either way, these phenomenal properties, like causal properties, must be a property of something real.\r\n\r\nThe way I like to think about it, is we all know what the redness of a surface of the strawberry is like.  We all initially naively think it is a property of the strawberry.  Nobody has any problem with thinking of redness, in this way - we think of it as tightly integrated with the fact that it reflects 650NM light.  Even though we know it is, instead, a property of our knowledge, we should still think of it, in the same way as we think of redness being a property of the strawberry - just now think of it as, instead, a property of something in our brain - just as it seems.  This property of knowledge, is the seeming.  Both types of properties can be interpreted as the other, but one, without knowing how to properly interpret what is representing it, is only abstract.\r\n\r\nDoes that help answer your questions?\r\n\r\n','2012-06-01 01:29:42','2012-06-01 01:29:42'),(1656,96,48,'I have come to see the notion of phenomenal information as flawed. It is either a contradiction or redundant, as phenomenal experiences necessarily inform us but they inform us directly and nothing can inform us outside of phenomenology.\r\n\r\nWhat the term does is invite us to think of our own ability to think as a kind of a thought. It confuses the phenomenological substrate (or carrier as slehar said) with the ephiphenomenal content of phenomenology.\r\n\r\nThis is the symbol grounding problem, the Chinese Room, Use/Mention distinction, and as Brent cited the Map/Territory dichotomy. The thing about using the world information or representation in the context of qualia is that you are making the territory a type of map, which is really upside down. The map is a territory which we can superimpose over another territory using our capacity to \'make sense\' - to extend our direct awareness with our own semiotic capacities.\r\n\r\nIt is useful to think of qualia as information or representation if you are doing engineering or neuroscience, but to really understand qualia I think you have to see it as absolutely primordial and concrete. The red of the strawberry is as much a part of the strawberry as the smell, shape, taste, chemistry, etc. There is nothing that we can know about the strawberry that is any more objectively real than the redness we see. All of it\'s properties are figments of our relation to it in size, velocity, instruments used to measure, etc. If the red is in our brain, then so is the entire universe.\r\n\r\nThe way to get out of this absurdity is to see that the fundamental principle of the universe has both presentational and representational aspects. Local and universal, literal and figurative, etc. Sense is what allows us to see truth, illusion and to tell the difference. It penetrates local bias even as it embodies it. Neither completely solipsistic nor universal, it is a conduit from one to the other.','2012-06-01 02:14:49','2012-06-01 02:14:49'),(1659,96,48,'\r\nCraig,\r\n\r\nDo you believe that \"inverted qualia\" is a possibility, even theoretically?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-01 04:10:43','2012-06-01 04:10:43'),(1662,96,48,'Multisense,\r\n\r\nI think it is good that you mention the primordial nature of qualia. Once you make the realisation that any of the so called \'information\' that exists in our minds is in fact a form of qualia, much of this debate melts away. A great deal of argument has always arisen from fundamental misunderstandings of what the concept of a quale really implies. However, you kind of wave your hand a little bit there to get rid of the idea of solipsism, and I take issue with that. \r\n\r\nWhen you consider that qualia are all we really can know, the idea of knowing of anything beyond that (I.e. The existence of an underlying \'reality\' starts to seem a little weird). This is of course talking purely from a deductive standpoint - however the \'sense\' you refered to is a reasonably sound kind of induction, which may or may not constitute actual knowledge (depending on your standards). \r\n\r\nWell that\'s one side of it, but then consider the contradictions which begin to arise when you allow qualia and its alleged physical (let\'s say neurological) correlates to coexist within your paradigm. If you follow this through, the role of qualia can be no more than as epiphenomena, with no influence on behaviour. This contradicts a notion which many have of qualia performing a function, for example the response to pain being seen as a result of pain\'s qualitative character. But of course, the process of pain response (and indeed all brain events) is entirely explicable within a physical framework, with no real \'room\' for a nonphysical property to interfere - this is the whole fundamental issue in the hard problem of consciousness. But this isn\'t in and of itself an issue with the idea of coexistance. Issues do arise, however, when we start to look at why on Earth we were ever able to consider qualia in the first place. \r\n\r\nConsider an automaton, which lacks whatever magic property that gives the spark of qualia - it might very well integrate indistinguishably from a human in any aspect of life, but since it doesn\'t have experience in the way we do, one might imagine it would have a hard time understanding what all of us on canonizer were talking about. But wait - if qualia are epiphenomena with no physical causal properties, then how are *we* able to understand it? The act of understanding or thinking about qualia, in the coexistance framework, is indeed a series of physical events. We do not \'observe\' qualia as we do with our senses (for allowing this would lead to an infinite regression post haste), so given their epiphenomenal nature, how could we ever notice them. In the framework which allows physical reality, it seems inevitable that our brains are no more than richly functional automatons, and yet the very notion of realising that we have qualia seems to contradict this. It would appear that a false premise has been assumed, and I wouldn\'t immediately dismiss on the grounds of \'sense\' that this false premise may very well be the existence in the first place of a physical world. \r\n\r\nThere are other issues too, such as the apparent granularity of reality - particularly in brain structure - which seems to interfere with the idea of the smooth, whole, analogue conscious experience we have, and it\'s hard to imagine how these could coexist. \r\n\r\nBut of course this isn\'t fully relevant to the debate at hand, it was just a little point I felt like making to address your otherwise sound arguments.\r\n\r\nJordan T','2012-06-01 11:16:45','2012-06-01 11:16:45'),(1665,96,48,'Brent, sure I don\'t have a problem with inverted qualia. Just as the Southern hemisphere has inverted seasons, it is possible to make sense of a lot of things in different ways. It is hard to know whether our familiar qualia are in some way more dominant in the universe and other ways of presenting them are recessive, or if it\'s wildly varied. We know that people wearing image inverting glasses quickly compensate for the upside down reality and see it right side up. I see that as a function of perceptual inertia, but whether it goes back to the individual, the culture, species, or matter itself depends on what kind of qualia it is. It seems like the inertia of our species perception is toward one set of qualia but that individual synesthetes can defy that inertia.\r\n\r\nomgpop, yeah we might want to start a different thread under Multisense Realism. http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/50. Briefly I\'ll say that with MR I want to take the distinction of Physical vs non-physical, rip it out by the roots and salt the Earth where it grew. It\'s ALL physical and it\'s ALL \'non-physical\'. The more relevant distinctions are internal-sensorimotive-perception-significance (through literal time and figurative space) vs external-electromagnetic-relativity-entropy (across literal space and figurative time). I did a post this morning that might help: http://s33light.org/post/24190294792\r\n','2012-06-01 12:18:36','2012-06-01 12:18:36'),(1668,96,48,'Craig writes (Post #115) that \"The red of the strawberry is as much a part of the strawberry as the smell, shape, taste, chemistry, etc.\"\r\nNot according to RQT. Inside our heads are the qualia, such as redness, that comprise our perceptual experience of the strawberry - these are the representation of the fruit and not properties of it. It is the physical properties of the strawberry such as its chemical composition that are part of the strawberry. Strawberries exist with or without minds to perceive them but mind is necessary for redness (and is also required to have knowledge about the world and understanding of it).\r\n\r\n\"If the red is in our brain, then so is the entire universe.\"\r\nObviously not, as you point out, but the RQT solution to this apparent absurdity is that what we know and perceive of the world is inside our heads: we have a representation of the world in our brains.\r\n\r\nI don\'t see how multisense realism theory is compatible with RQT. I note that the camp statement claims (falsely IMO) that \"Blindsight and visual agnosia directly contradicts RQT as it demonstrates both representation without qualia and qualia without representation.\"\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard\r\n\r\n','2012-06-01 13:52:56','2012-06-01 13:52:56'),(1671,96,48,'It appears that there is more consensus than we realized for this theory that qualia is the only reality. Perhaps we should figure out where this camp belongs before we proceed. I propose that the natural structure is something like this (assuming my ascii-art looks the same after it is posted)...\r\n\r\n\r\n   +--> No, qualia is the basic building block of reality.\r\n   |         |\r\n   |         +--> Multisense\r\n   |         +--> omgpop\r\n   |         +--> et al\r\n   |\r\nDo we all share a common underlying reality?\r\n   |\r\n   |                        +--> Material\r\n   |                        |         |\r\n   |                        |         +--> Brent\r\n   |                        |         +--> et al\r\n   |                        |\r\n   |              +--> No. Is phenomenal information material or functional?\r\n   |              |         |\r\n   |              |         +--> Functional\r\n   |              |                   |\r\n   |              |                   +--> Lincoln\r\n   |              |                   +--> et al\r\n   |              |\r\n   +--> Yes. Is qualia formed from regular abstract information?\r\n             |\r\n             +--> Yes.\r\n                      |\r\n                      +--> Mike (me)\r\n                      +--> James\r\n                      +--> Dennet\r\n                      +--> et al','2012-06-01 14:03:57','2012-06-01 14:03:57'),(1674,96,48,'richwill - Yes, I am not hiding that my view is directly contrary to RQT. I would move my Multisense Realism camp but I don\'t see a better place to put it other then under Panexperientialism. It seems to me that RQT is the camp that is out of place in the canonizer actually.\r\n\r\nI submit that the whole notion of representations of the world being \'inside\' of our brain is all based on qualia of \'inside and outside\' to begin with. If we truly believe that qualia is an encoded abstraction, then that sense of difference between inner and outer realism must also be an illusion. If we pick and choose which qualia we deem to be fundamentally real and external and those which seem unreal, then we privilege the cognitive bias of the picker to define reality rather than to accept all of our experience as either solipsistic, realistic, or, as I see it, sense which bridges and defines the two through semantic modulation and diffraction.\r\n\r\nMike - One thing we can all agree on is that we can all appreciate a good visual diagram, and that has to count for something. To be nitpickingly precise, I say the building block of realism is sense. Qualia is more like the Orientation of sense, while quanta is the occidental objectification-reduction of qualia.\r\n\r\nThe relevant questions I think are - \r\n\r\nCan information inform without being detected or making sense to something? \r\n\r\nI would say no. \r\n\r\nCan sense be experienced without being presented as discrete sequences of data? \r\n\r\nYes, of course. Data is new to human beings. A CD of music is not music. No non-aural representation of the data on an mp3 file can be said to resemble music in any way. Qualia is not information, but it does inform. \r\n\r\nWhat do we mean by information and representation?\r\n\r\nTo say that information is regular or arithmetic takes that experiential quality of pattern recognition for granted. What seems like a perfectly clear sign to us has no such clarity or significance to an organism of the estimated \"~8.7 million (Â±1.3 million SE) eukaryotic species globally\". Does a blue whale appreciate the statistical curve of a parabola? It seems obvious to us - the parabola \'simply is\' meaningful...but it\'s not universally meaningful, and it doesn\'t seem solipsistic either. Parabola is qualia, albeit flat to the point of mathematical abstraction (hence its ready extension into geometric universality). The key is understanding the directly proportionate relation between depth-richness of qualia and it\'s privacy. \r\n\r\nWhat we are talking about here is whether to believe the picture of the world we see or the reflection in a mirror inside that picture in which we are invisible. We can\'t doubt that we see, but we can and should doubt the picture within the picture that leaves us out. Think of it as a spiritual IQ test. If we aren\'t smart enough to assert your own legitimacy, then maybe we don\'t deserve to go on to the next phase of civilization. Maybe we deserve to be digitized and forgotten.\r\n','2012-06-01 15:24:00','2012-06-01 15:24:00'),(1677,96,48,'\r\nHi Mike,\r\n\r\nYes, there is already an [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/49 \"Ideal Monism\"] camp for all that?  And I think this is, as other\'s have mentioned, a competitor to Representational Qualia Theory, since RQT asserts an independent reality from us that we all share.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2012-06-01 16:17:40','2012-06-01 16:17:40'),(1680,96,48,'Mike,\r\n\r\nIn the Google doc comments, you stated:  \"You have shown that the statement [it only seems like we have qualia] is technically self-contradictory, but I think the intended meaning is still clear: qualia involves nothing special (or phenomenal), it\'s just delusion.\"\r\n\r\nWhen I hear you say \"it\'s just delusion.\" it sounds to me like you are saying a miracle happens here.  What, exactly does \'just delusion\' mean?  And what/where/how is this phenomenal \'delusional knowledge\'?  It is THIS, that I am talking about, you must be talking about something else, entirely, which you are talking about, when you talk about qualia?\r\n\r\n Here\'s one proposal of what we might ask Dan Dennett in a letter signed by all of us:\r\n\r\n\r\nDan,\r\n\r\nThere is a general philosophical idea out there, which you seem to support, that we don\'t have qualia, \"it just seems like we do\" [Consciousness Explained P. 375].  There is an emerging consensus at Canonizer.com, that believes in what they are now calling the \"physical law of information\" which is basically, if you know something, there must  be something that is this knowledge, or there must be something that is or has this phenomenal seeming - even if it incorrectly represents whatever it\'s referent is meant to be.\r\n\r\nAnd if you accept this, as most experts seem to do, this makes the argument it only \'seems\' like we have qualia to be nonsensical.  There is a new camp emerging that is very supportive of your ideas.  But once the supporters of this camp realized this nonsensical nature of the argument, they recognize the problem and now believe that your intended meaning wasn\'t quite what it seems to be?\r\n\r\nAnyway, we\'d very much like to get some clarification on this issue.  Do you agree with a statement like: \"We don\'t have qualia, it only seems like we do?\"  And if so, what exactly does the word \'seaming\' mean in this case.  What/where/how is this knowledge that is mistaken knowledge that is only a \'seeming\'?\r\n\r\n','2012-06-02 22:01:06','2012-06-02 22:01:06'),(1683,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\n\r\nI\'ve been researching some of Keith Frankish\'s work on this \'seeming\' issue.  He has lots of great information about stuff which he says is a \'common move in literature\', and seems to be the same move James and Mike are attempting, when they talk about quale.\r\n\r\nOne of his papers was entitled: [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1053810011001176 Quining diet qualia], in which he borrows the \'quining qualia\' term from Dennett.  Unfortunately, you have to pay to get that paper, but he has a great guest blog post [http://schwitzsplinters.blogspot.com/2007/07/qualia-real-thing-by-guest-blogger.html here] on this.\r\n\r\nHe refers to \'clasic qualia\' as being \'ineffable, intrinsic, and private\', which I seem to stress are important (although I prefer \'fundamental\' to \'intrinsic\'), which Mike and James seem to not consider are properties of what they think of as qualia?\r\n\r\nAnyway, I wondered if Mike and James would agree that their definition of \'qualia is this same \'diet\' definition that Frankish talks about?\r\n\r\nIt appears to me that Keith is a true qualophobe, and thinks we also don\'t have \'diet\' qualia.  So, perhaps, we\'ll need to come up with the following camp structure to include these types of people?\r\n\r\n * Representationalism\r\n         * Qualophiles\r\n                 * Property Dualism / Classic Qualia\r\n                 * Diet Qualia / Representational Functionalism\r\n         * Qualophobes.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-03 13:18:21','2012-06-03 13:18:21'),(1686,96,48,'The Frankish paper on diet qualia is available at no cost on his website under Articles.\r\n','2012-06-03 19:41:44','2012-06-03 19:41:44'),(1689,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nMike provided a great reply to my post in private e-mail.  I didn\'t want to lose this so I\'m making my reply, here, interspersed with his post.\r\n\r\n------------------\r\n\r\nHi Mike,\r\n\r\nWow, this is all great.  It\'s obvious that you\'ve put some serious thinking and time into all this.  I really understand both your position, and the relation of my position to your thinking, much better now.  Thanks!!\r\n\r\nOn 6/3/2012 9:44 AM, Mike wrote:\r\n\r\n  <<<<\r\nBrent,\r\n\r\nYeah, this is definitely a terminology melt-down because my explanation is absolutely anti-magic. I will be formal and label my assertions so we can refer to them:\r\n\r\nMagic Fallacy: When an explanation for some phenomenon contains the use of miracles, intervention by deity, magic, or any other notion that cannot be explained by current science, the explanation is worthless from a scientific perspective and reveals that the explainer does not really understand the phenomenon.\r\n\r\nI believe you think I am making the magic fallacy, right?\r\n  >>>>\r\n\r\nAfter hopefully better understanding the below, my view has changed, so I no longer think you are making a magic fallacy.  Instead, I think you are simply incorrectly dismissing the absolute fact that there are ineffable phenomenal qualities to our consciousness, and that these are something that cannot be represented by abstract information like ones and zeros.  So, in my mind, you are achieving your lack of magic in your model/theory, by arguing there is nothing that we know that requires such.\r\n\r\nAnd I might point out that all such \'hard AI\' or \'pure science\' type people, when they say things like there are no such things as ineffable properties, or that there is only diet qualia, or anything even close to that, the majority of experts, and the lay population, no longer trust anything you say from then on, because saying that is more absolutely wrong, to most of us, than almost anything else we know or could say.  That is why the term ineffable exists in the first place.  No matter how you describe the taste of salt, even with an infinite set of abstracted symbols, it will always be insufficient to describe that ineffable property.  Most people recognize that they know this absolutely.  So to deny such, just destroys one\'s reputation, in our minds.\r\n\r\n <<<<\r\n\'\'\'Awareness Axiom:\'\'\' Being aware of something is equivalent to having a representation (or model) of the thing. All things of which humans are aware are represented somehow in their heads. If there is anything that is not represented in a person\'s head, he or she is not aware of it. There is no need for any other function or process to explain awareness. Having a model of something *is* being aware of it.\r\n\r\nI think we both agree with the awareness axiom, right? (At least, it has survived unchallenged for quite some time in the RQT camp statement.)\r\n >>>>\r\n\r\nYes\r\n\r\n <<<<\r\nDefinition of Delusion: A delusion is an error or inaccuracy or imprecision or falsehood in the representation (or model) within a person\'s head that constitutes his or her awareness. Any failure of the model to correctly and accurately represent some part of the physical world constitutes a delusion.\r\n\r\nNote that science can completely explain delusions, without resorting to the use of anything magical or unexplainable. A hallucination is a delusion caused by a chemical imbalance in the brain. (For example, PCP may cause neurons to mis-fire, triggering a false awareness of things that are not real.) Dreams are a delusion caused by sleep. A mirage is a delusion caused by a misunderstanding of what one is looking at. (Specifically, heat rising from desert sand seems to warp light in a manner somewhat similar to that caused by pools of water.)\r\n >>>>\r\n\r\nAgreed.\r\n\r\n <<<<\r\n\'\'\'Representational Functionalism Conjecture:\'\'\' Qualia is a delusion caused by the brain\'s insufficiency to fully represent the physical world.\r\n\r\nFor example, the causal property of reflecting 720nm light is too much for the brain to model. It tries, but fails, and results in an inaccurate model. Remember that this (flawed) model constitutes the person\'s awareness. So, the person then says, \"I am aware that this strawberry is red\". The person is wrong. Strawberries are not red. Redness is a delusion.\r\n\r\nPerhaps a superior post-human might look upon the same strawberry and be aware that the strawberry is reflecting 720nm light. This superior post-human has a superior model. His model is more complete and more accurate. His awareness is superior to that of the human who experiences redness. Does the post-human experience redness? No, he experiences something better: truth, reality, correctness. He does not have the delusion of redness, as the human has.\r\n\r\nPerhaps the most prominent feature of the Representational Functionalism Conjecture is that it contains NO MAGIC WHATSOEVER. It explains qualia by simply disparaging the brain. Now, let us contrast this with the property dualism conjecture:\r\n >>>\r\n\r\nYes, I agree, no magic, because you see no need for such, as I said above.\r\n\r\n <<<<\r\n\'\'\'Property Dualism Conjecture:\'\'\' Qualia occurs when the brain builds its representation (or model) with phenomenal information.\r\n >>>>\r\n\r\nWhen you say it this way, it sounds like the qualia doesn\'t exist until the brain builds its representation, which is not an accurate description of the theory.  Whatever it is that has the phenomenal qualities, which our brain uses to build or paint our conscious knowledge out of, has it whether the stuff was in a brain or not.\r\n\r\nYou talked of the superior post-human representing the surface of the strawberry as it really, phenomenally, is.  If we assumed that the surface of the strawberry does, indeed, have some phenomenal property, possibly something no human has ever experienced before, the theory predicts we will be able to augment the brain, so that it\'s knowledge is made of this phenomenal stuff, instead of redness.  In other words, these future beings will know what the surface of the strawberry is really phenomenally like, and hence they will know how to property interpret that abstract information about such, coming to them, via the interpretation of the light (Note, the light is nothing like redness, or the surface of the strawberry, other than our brain is interpreting such) to appropriately represent the surface of the strawberry, with the real thing.  In other words, these future beings will have solved the quale interpretation problem, and will have superior knowledge about what the strawberry is really like.  The prediction is that if it is like anything at all, it is likely nothing any human has ever experienced before.\r\n\r\n <<<<\r\nNote that science has not yet discovered phenomenal information. Science does not know how to detect it. Science does not know whether it exists. Science knows NOTHING of phenomenal information. Phenomenal information is a conjecture. Until science manages to reach phenomenal information, it is magic.\r\n >>>>\r\n\r\nI disagree, we know that redness, and greenness exist, how they are different, and so on, more absolutely, than we know anything else science tells us.  Science, other than absolute, subjective first person experiences, has only provided us with abstract information about reality.  Material Property Dualism is predicting it has provided us with far more scientific abstract information necessary, than to know what has redness, greenness, and so on.  In other words, the prediction is that you don\'t need to get close to the quantum level of detail or anything, to be able to discover what it is that has redness or the relationship between what we experience, and what we know abstractly.)  The only thing required, is to discover and map redness, and all the fundamental qualia, with the right abstract information about the stuff, in the right state, so we know how to properly interpret the abstract information we already have, which is plenty sufficient to describe all we need to know, except how to phenomenally interpret such information.\r\n\r\n <<<<\r\nNow, who is making the magic fallacy? Perhaps some day science will discover phenomenal information. When that happens, the magic will disappear and property dualism will become science. Until then, it can only be a stub for something that we do not understand. It fills a gap of understanding and assigns a label to it, but it does not explain the thing that fills the gap. In other words, it is a perfect poster-child of the magic fallacy.\r\n >>>\r\n\r\nOK, admittedly, you have me here.  You are right with this.  But at the fundamental level, we all rely on some kind of Magic.  For example, we don\'t know why there is gravity and why Force = Mass * Acceleration - that is the magic part.  We just know that this magic behaves, as the models predict, and such knowledge enables us to explain and predict why celestial objects behave the way they do, and why.  And it enables us to also now dance in the heavens with them - despite not knowing what or why this fundamental \'magic\' is.\r\n\r\nBut this magic, is clearly at the fundamental level, like gravity is.  You can reduce \'Mind\', \'Consciousness\', \'Intentionality\', \'free will\', and all those things to something built out of physical matter that also has phenomenal properties.  If we discover that it is glutamate that has a redness we experience, we won\'t know why, we\'ll just know that it does, and this predictability will enable us to solve the quale interpretation problem and finally eff the ineffable.  It will finally enable us to see the spiritual properties of what science has been telling us all along.\r\n\r\n <<<<\r\n\'\'\'Mike\'s Interpretation of Dennett:\'\'\' When Dennett says \"It just seems like we have qualia\", he is saying \"our representation (or model) is what makes qualia, but this representation does not accurately represent the physical world\". This can be said more succinctly as, \"qualia is delusion\". When he says \"We do not really have qualia\", he is making an error. Certainly he believes we have delusions. His next phrase makes this very clear. What is is really saying is, \"There is nothing magical or phenomenal involved in experiences of qualia\". What he is basically saying is, \"I am not making the magic fallacy, those property dualism guys are\". He is saying the \"phenomenal information is a stub for something science does not understand--which means it is magic\". He is pointing out that he has a complete conjecture for the nature of qualia, while the property dualists have an incomplete conjecture, as evidenced by their use of \"phenomenal information\", which is just a stub for the magical part that science does not understand.\r\n\r\nIncidentally, the biggest draw for me to representational functionalism is also its lack of a magical component. If you could help me to understand that property dualism really does not have a magical component, I think I might be able to convert. Otherwise, I like the complete explanation of representation functionalism much better.\r\n >>>>\r\n\r\nAs I suspected, we are talking about two completely different things here.  Everything you say here is only consistent with him saying something like: \"The strawberry doesn\'t have redness, it just seems like it does.\"  We both clearly agree with this, and I agree with all you are saying above.  But Dennett is saying something completely different here.  He is not talking about the strawberry, or perception of anything at all.  He is talking about our knowledge of the strawberry.  He is saying we don\'t have this phenomenal knowledge, (whether it is a representation initiated by a strawberry, or it could be a drug induced hallucination, in a room with no light) he  just says it only seems like we have this phenomenal knowledge.\r\n\r\n  <<<<\r\nOn another topic, I suspect that if we send Dennett a personal note from just one of us, he would be more likely to respond. If we approach him as a group, it feels more like we are trying to push him into taking a public position on some issue. I think that is the sort of thing he would expect compensation for. If we get a personal response first, then we could still follow up with a group assault, but we\'d still have an answer to fall back on if he declines to become involved at that point.\r\n >>>>\r\n\r\nVery good point!  I completely agree.  So would you be interested in sending such a query to Dan?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-06-03 20:16:55','2012-06-03 20:16:55'),(1692,96,48,'I feel that we have finally connected! Wahoo! I am so excited! (I was starting to wonder if we would ever reach this point.) Just to nail this down, I would like to confirm all the things you said:\r\n\r\n* Yes, I am achieving a lack of magic in my theory by arguing that nothing occurs which requires it.\r\n* I suppose I must accept the label of \'pure science type\' and whatever that does to my credibility.\r\n* Thank you for pointing out that property dualism believes that the \'paint\' already possesses the quale before our consciousness paints the model with it. It was probably mentioned before, but it did not really click with me until now that PD believes that quale is a thing, rather than an experience, and that consciousness is not at all necessary for the existence of qualia. I think I may be finally starting to understand property dualism!\r\n* I admit that every explanation ultimately relies on fundamental axioms, which are essentially reliable models of magic. I confess, in that respect, RF relies on magic too. The difference is that PD relies on a magical component for which a reliable model is not yet available. That does not make it wrong, but it does make it extraordinary. Extraordinary theories require extraordinary evidence. I understand that experiencing qualia seems extraordinary, so I can respect those who feel that it is sufficient evidence to justify accepting an extraordinary theory.\r\n\r\nRegarding e-mailing Dr. Dennett, I still need to understand the issue. For starters, where do I find the specific statement in question so I can read it in context? I really haven\'t studied him much yet. Perhaps it would make more sense for those who already take issue with his statement to compose it. I would be happy to help with wording or sending, if such would be helpful.\r\n','2012-06-04 14:02:42','2012-06-04 14:02:42'),(1695,96,48,'Mike,\r\n\r\nSo you want to know where to find Dennettâ€™s specific Statement, do you?  Very good question!!  Everyone has a working hypothesis of what aliens look like, and asking for that is kind of like asking where everyone gets this what aliens look like information.  Gazilions of â€˜hard scientistâ€™ like people have this as their argument for why we donâ€™t have qualia, itâ€™s just that nobody ever formally and rigorously states it that way, at least that I know of.  You really have to work to recognize when a person is making this argument, as so many people do, because nobody ever says it in these clear kinds of terms.\r\n\r\nDennett only really says this in a roundabout, seeming to not be thinking in a clear way, on page 375 of his book Consciousness Explained.  There are torrents for the pdf of this book, so if you donâ€™t have a hard copy, you should be able to download and find this.  He basically says a bunch of stuff, giving the general idea that we donâ€™t have qualia, then finally he at least says â€œit only seems like we do.â€  So you should be able to search for that string to find where he almost says this.  Basically, that entire book, and the gist of his \"multiple drafts\" ideas, comes down to this simple idea, in a very complex, almost impossible to understand, and see the problems, way.\r\n\r\nOther philosophers donâ€™t seem to think about this, clearly, either, and get lost in all the unnecessarily complected details, the same way.  For example, when I was first talking with Keith Frankish, I detected he was making this argument, just like Dennett does, getting completely lost in all the overly complex details.  So I finally asked him: â€œSo youâ€™re saying we donâ€™t have qualia, it only seems like we doâ€.  It seemed to me that he basically had to stop and think about it for a while, and finally, he said, yes, you are right, this is basically the idea around what Dennett and I are arguing.  Yes, our camp is the â€œwe donâ€™t have qualia, it only seems like we doâ€ camp.\r\n\r\nAnd of course, from the religious / feeling side of the fence, they are mostly completely unable to think about anything in any kind of clear way, they are just all about how things feel.  And they just know something is wrong about what Dennett and everyone is saying, they just canâ€™t even realize what it is Dennett is saying, in a clear way, let alone be able to point out the mistake in the logic.\r\n\r\nIâ€™ve been struggling around this issue from both sides for the longest time, trying to get my hand on exactly what was going on here.  Only when we started this canonizion process, and I was trying to explain it to people like you, and others, did this finally become clear for everyone, exactly what is going on, and how to talk about it so both sides can understand.  Even now, we still have a long way to go to better accomplish this.  So, as far as I know, being enabled by this canonization process, we are the first people to fully understand and start to address this critically important problem in this way.\r\n\r\nSo that is why Iâ€™m so excited about the possibility of getting more clarification from Dr Dennett, to see if he, like Keith Frankish, has troubles getting the problem at first, or if he might have some better insights for all of us, or anything.  It seems to me, Keith Frankish, when he, or at least his sub conscious, first started realizing the error in this line of reasoning, he suddenly had a stupor of thought, and lost interest in it, and hence is not interested in participating any more?  Iâ€™m hoping for more, from Dr Dennett.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-04 16:35:06','2012-06-04 16:35:06'),(1698,96,48,'To Brent and Mike:\r\nâ€œ*Representational Functionalism Conjecture:* Qualia is a delusion caused by the brain\'s insufficiency to fully represent the physical world. \r\n\r\nFor example, the causal property of reflecting 720nm light is too much for the brain to model. It tries, but fails, and results in an inaccurate model. Remember that this (flawed) model constitutes the person\'s awareness. So, the person then says, \"I am aware that this strawberry is red\". The person is wrong. Strawberries are not red.\r\nRedness is a delusion. \r\n\r\nPerhaps a superior post-human might look upon the same strawberry and be aware that the strawberry is reflecting 720nm light. This superior post-human has a superior model. His model is more complete and more accurate. His awareness is superior to that of the human who experiences redness. Does the post-human experience redness? No, he experiences something better: truth, reality, correctness. He does not have the delusion of redness, as the human has.â€\r\n\r\nRK: This is getting weirder and weirder. You give evolution bad grades that it doesnâ€™t deserve at all because of your fascination with single wavelength light. This occurs in nature only extremely rarely, like when somewhere pure sodium gets heated until it gives off nearly single wavelength light. In 19.999% of all cases light is broadband multi-wavelength and objects reflect it as multi-wavelengths across the visible spectrum. In a sunset half of the spectrum might get absorbed by air impurities and the result is an orange-red appearance but that is about the greatest reduction of full-spectrum light in nature. The task for evolution was to make it possible to distinguish between an infinity of broad-band spectra in a manner that was efficient, requiring relatively little energy. The solution for our ancestors was three detector types and a mechanism that can distinguish a million or more broad-band spectra in a manner useful to them in terms of continuity of the species. There are also several special mechanisms to further improve detection and distinction. We are doing quite well with the system and the implicit qualia. \r\nThe reflectance function of a ripe strawberry is broad, from 400 to to 700 nm and peaking beyond 700 nm. When viewing a ripe strawberry in daylight the dominant wavelength of the reflected light in data I have is actually at 604 nm. Because of metamerism the complete stimulus coming from the strawberry into the eye can be matched with many different combinations of spectral lights. To take just two of them: the light can be matched with a combination of 74% light of 650 nm, 20% â€˜yellowâ€™ light of wavelength 580 nm and 6% of â€˜blueâ€™ light of 430 nm; or it can be matched with 87% of light of 604 nm and 13% of light of 430 nm. This changes, of course, if the illuminating light is not regular daylight. So what exactly is the stimulus representing the redness of the strawberry?  There are infinitely many possible ones. What they have in common is the identical light absorption (for the standard observer) in the three cone types resulting from these different stimuli. Metamerism does not only exist in color vision but also in form vision and taste: there are many chemicals that taste sweet to us. There is no foreseeable need for a super-human of the future to distinguish between individual wavelengths. As it is we can in some regions of the spectrum distinguish between wavelengths about 2-3 nm apart. If she needs to distinguish them more closely she can use a spectrophotometer as we can.\r\n\r\nSo letâ€™s remain realistic and stay out of fantasy land by calling redness a delusion. Yes, by spacing the cone absorptions a bit more regular and perhaps have a fourth cone type we could distinguish wavelengths across the visible spectrum every 1-2 nm different.  Where should the limit be in your ideal situation? Every tenth of an nm, every 100th? \r\nI am also suggesting that we recognize the plural form of â€˜qualiaâ€™ in our conversations.\r\n','2012-06-05 00:27:17','2012-06-05 00:27:17'),(1701,96,48,'I agree with rolfk. Keep in mind what we\'re all actually talking about here.\r\n\r\nStraight from Wikipedia: \r\n\r\n\"Qualia ( /ËˆkwÉ‘ËliÉ™/ or /ËˆkweÉªliÉ™/), singular \"quale\" (Latin pronunciation: [ËˆkwaËle]), from a Latin word meaning for \"what sort\" or \"what kind,\" is a term used in philosophy to refer to subjective conscious experiences as \'raw feels\'. Daniel Dennett writes that qualia is \'an unfamiliar term for something that could not be more familiar to each of us: the ways things seem to us.\' Erwin SchrÃ¶dinger had this counter-materialist take: \'The sensation of colour cannot be accounted for by the physicist\'s objective picture of light-waves. Could the physiologist account for it, if he had fuller knowledge than he has of the processes in the retina and the nervous processes set up by them in the optical nerve bundles and in the brain? I do not think so.\' \"\r\n\r\nThe fallacy Mike seems to be making lies within his failure to grasp what people are talking about when they speak of qualia. By definition, they are subjective entities which arise from physiological conscious processes. That is, specifically not some objective property parameter of physical things. It\'s fair enough if people want to go about making their own definitions of what qualia are, but any definition which does not concede their subjectiveness and privacy fails to capture the ontology of the matter. You either believe in the real existence of subjective qualia, or you do not. The whole \'problem\' in the hard problem of consciousness is the reconciliation of subjective feeling and objective brain events. If you do not acknowledge that there exist subjective components to experience, there is no problem at all.','2012-06-05 00:50:19','2012-06-05 00:50:19'),(1704,96,48,'Red does a fine job of representing a range of light wavelengths, but a range of light wavelengths does nothing whatsoever to explain how the experience of color could be possible.\r\n\r\nRed is the deeper, more directly meaningful truth. Wavelengths are an abstract model rooted in indirect microcosmic observation. It is a different, more universal kind of truth, but utterly meaningless. Red may only be true for Homo Sapiens or it may be a deeper truth of electromagnetism or biochemistry.\r\n\r\nJust because red often represents light doesn\'t mean that it has to represent light to be red. Red is a presentation in its own right, while light as conceived of by physics is not presented directly presented as such to anything at all. It is an analytical inference - a consensus of instrumental reasoning which allows us to control optical conditions using different materials with precision but does not explain visual experience.','2012-06-05 00:58:33','2012-06-05 00:58:33'),(1707,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nIt seems to me like you guys are not fully understanding what Mike and I are talking about yet.\r\n\r\nrolfk probably properly corrects us about the details of the light being reflected off of the strawberry, while completely missing the point that this has nothing to do with what Mike and I are talking about.  You could entirely remove the light and eye, from the picture, and stimulate the optic nerve the same way the eye does, and you will end up with a perception of the strawberry that is completely indistinguishable.   It is this perception, independent of any light, that Mike and I are talking about.  When I say 650NM light, it is just a simplified term to refer to whatever light does happen to be reflected from a strawberry (or anything else that causes the optic nerve to be stimulated the way it does), all of which has nothing to do with what we are talking about.\r\n\r\nI completely agree with most of what omgpop says, but fail to see any relevance to what Mike and I are talking about?  He does mention, as if it is fact, not one of many possible theories, that qualia are \"subjective entities which arise from physiological conscious processes.\".  This is clearly consistent with several theories, like functional property dualism - but not with Macro Material Property Dualism.  I was pointing out, that MMPD predicts qualia do not arise from consciousness processes, but instead are properties of something in nature, like glutamate, and the theory predicts these substances are the paint the brain uses to paint our phenomenal experiences with and they have the same qualia, whether in the brain or not.  Mike obviously finally realized this fact about MMPD, but omgpop still seems to be missing it?\r\n\r\nMultisense Realism\'s comments, it seems to me, can be interpreted in any of a bazillion possible different ways, some of which I agree with.  For example, when you talk about light like this, you seem to be not talking about the fundamental causal light itself, but the abstract knowledge we interpret from what our eyes interpret of such?  If you mean the latter, then I agree with you.  Everything else you say also has many possible way to interpret it like this.  So I\'m not sure what the take away is meant to be, as it depends on what he could be meaning by what he is saying.  If you mean it in a way which I agree with, I don\'t understand why you are restating some of it, which I\'ve already stated many times here?  If you are disagreeing whit anything, what, exactly are you disagreeing with?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-05 01:38:23','2012-06-05 01:38:23'),(1710,96,48,'Thanks for addressing my response Brent.\r\n\r\nI think my issue with Mike\'s interpretation (and maybe *I\'m* the one who\'s doing the misinterpreting) of property dualism was in his thinking that qualia could exist independently from conscious experience. This, as I see it, is in direct contradiction to the very definition of what a quale is. It might be somewhat contentious to posit that qualia arise from physiological conscious processes, but clearly the concept of a quale derives its definition from conscious experience, be that physiological in origin or otherwise.','2012-06-05 02:09:01','2012-06-05 02:09:01'),(1713,96,48,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\nI\'m disagreeing with the idea that light is the real phenomenon and red is the less real epiphenomenon. I think both are real in some sense, unreal in some sense but if I had to choose between the two, I would say that red is the more concretely real phenomenon and light is the epiphenomenon. \r\n\r\nLight, as conceived by physics, is a consensus of measurements which I think ultimately doesn\'t make sense. It\'s a legacy of the 20th century which I do not expect to last.\r\n\r\nI think that I understand why it doesn\'t make sense, and that is because light is a sensitivity, not a substance. It is an experience shared by matter, not a phenomenon that is independent of matter. It is not light that we see as red, it is red that we think we measure as light.\r\n\r\nCraig\r\n','2012-06-05 02:12:06','2012-06-05 02:12:06'),(1716,96,48,'I also confess, I have a hard time picking out the position held by Multisense Realism. I admit it is purely my own personal failing, but I find the language used difficult to penetrate. I wonder, would it be too much to ask for a simple English, from [commonly accepted] first principles explanation of what multisense realism fundamentally is.','2012-06-05 02:19:55','2012-06-05 02:19:55'),(1719,96,48,'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model-dependent_realism\r\n\r\nMultisense (Or, Craig?), is this kind of like what you are saying? It\'s a really elegant paradigm in my mind. Also if you haven\'t, I do advise reading the book (The Grand Design). ','2012-06-05 02:27:24','2012-06-05 02:27:24'),(1722,96,48,'Multisense realism is more the opposite of Model-Dependent Realism. Although I think we do extend our senses with maps, models, and metaphors, they are second order logics. What I propose is that all matter and energy is fundamentally an experience of direct participation.\r\n\r\nRealism is achieved through the overlap of different sense channels (exterior facing senses such as seeing, hearing, etc and interior facing senses such as cognitive principles and aesthetics.). Our great range of sense qualities gives us a deeper and more significant realism than any amount of data or information alone could generate. Both physics and information are reflections of sense, and not the other way around. Our qualia is not fiction, it is the complex, ambiguous and dynamic truth of our significance and place in the universe.\r\n\r\nModel-Dependent Realism, like Representational Qualia Theory is very close to being correct, except that it sets the information/model cart before sense-making horse.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-06-05 02:42:47','2012-06-05 02:42:47'),(1725,96,48,'\r\nomgpop,  everything you say could turn out to be true, but Material Property Dualism predicts something like glutamate has a redness qualie, and  our brain uses something like that to \'paint\' our phenomenal conscious knowledge of the strawberry with.  And the same glutamate, in the right state, will always have redness, wither in someone\'s brain or not.  I\'m betting and predict this will soon be proven by science, and that your definition of qualia will be proven wrong.\r\n\r\nMutlisense, \"less real\" could mean a thousand different things here?  I have no idea what you mean by this.  I\'m betting and predict your theory that light doesn\'t make sense, and that our scientific knowledge of such will not last, will be falsified once we start effing the ineffable, and discover the spiritual or phenomenal properties of light, which really exists whether anyone is observing it or not.  A statement like \"light is a sensitive, not a substance\" could be interpreted a thousand different ways - so I have no idea what you are trying to say, and similarly, I can\'t understand most everything else you are saying.\r\n\r\n','2012-06-05 03:42:31','2012-06-05 03:42:31'),(1728,96,48,'Brent, I think you misunderstand my position in all of this (and I\'m not calling you out, that is totally a valid thing - I may not be expressing myself very well). Material property dualism may very well be \'correct\', but I don\'t think it particularly defies my definition of qualia. You talk about glutamate, a neurotransmitter - to me that would still come under the \'physiological conscious process\' heading, or at least an aspect of that. \r\n\r\nIt is a perfectly valid idea to suppose that qualia is a property of neurotransmitter chemicals. However, given the definition of a qualia as a subjective experience or \'raw feel\' (which is pretty much the common one by the way, not just my own), I would definitely consider it interesting to know just how the methods of objective science could identify such a property in the absence of a conscious agent capable of directly reporting it. And it still leaves the question of \'What property?\'.\r\n\r\nThis isn\'t a question of identifying the correct definition of qualia - that\'s been done already. The whole basis of the hard problem of consciousness arises from the understanding of qualia as being subjective feelings. If that isn\'t what qualia are in your theoretical framework, then I don\'t know what really your theories will have resolved - because it certainly wont be the hard problem.\r\n\r\nEven supposing we objectively determine that neurotransmitter X has a qualitative dimension, Q(X), no progress has been made in terms of describing mechanistically how Q(X) arises from X. You end up with an empirical law with no theoretical framework, and the theoretical framework is what we\'ve been trying to establish since the hard problem was first recognised. \r\n\r\nBut again, I remain sceptical of the validity of this idea that somehow we could test for the presence of qualia in the absence of consciousness - any objective determination of a subjective property will always be by proxy (through the filter of our own senses), and therefore inferred by analogy in exactly the same way as ordinary language (albeit to a more granular level of precision). You talk of effing the ineffable, and that is indeed what is required here - but first you need to propose a means of going about this, or your theory achieves no more than any other that has come before (not much).','2012-06-05 04:33:58','2012-06-05 04:33:58'),(1731,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nSaying that the light wave/particles that physics models is less real than red is pretty straightforward. Red is the enduring truth of human visual perception. Photons are a recent mathematical idea which works for physical computations.  \r\n\r\nIt\'s like measuring the frequency of traffic signal rotation and then announcing that green lights are entangled particles that travel down streets according to a reliable formula.\r\n\r\nThe spiritual and phenomenal properties of light are sensitivity, ie, for a human being, light is the ability to see colors and forms. For a photomultiplier photographic plate it is the ability to change in response to remote illumination of matter. All matter changes remotely in response to energy, some in more externally measurable ways than others. That is what I mean by light is a sensitivity and not a substance. Energy is an experience in which material objects or bodies participate.  It is nothing but what matter does through time.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-06-05 11:33:28','2012-06-05 11:33:28'),(1734,96,48,'Looking to the protracted and meandering postings and the discussions that seem to go on in circles some times, I couldn\'t resist expressing a feeling I have. And that is:\r\n\r\nThe whole problem on the semantics and defintions of the terms is arising because of the fact, IMHO, that a significant omission is being made. \r\nThe omission  is to consider as if our \"consciousness\" is divorced and different from  all what we want to express - be it \"redness\", quale, thought, perception etc. as if two separate  entities - consciousness and quale are present.\r\n( this is duality).\r\n\r\nWhatever is the \"object\" (= a percept, including things in the world as well as thought and images in the mind), we have to be first \"conscious\" of the object. That means, at that precise moment of perception of the object, it is \"consciousness\" alone by itself taking the shape of that particular percept (object, quale, thought etc. -- like an unchnaging computer screen assumes the shape of a document or image or a picture). \r\n\r\nHence consciousness is none other than whatever is perceived. The rest is physics and detail of explanation as per the idiom and knowledgebase of the times. Therefore, the \"oneness\" of or non-difference between the perceived object and consciousness has to be recognized first. This is the ultimate Non-duality.\r\n\r\nI do not mind if the above is dropped as an unnecessary spin at this stage.','2012-06-05 13:27:15','2012-06-05 13:27:15'),(1737,96,48,'I think a brief history of this thread might help to keep us on topic:\r\n\r\n# It started when James found some issues with property dualism (PD) and created the representational functionalism (RF) camp.\r\n# I followed James, but also recognized the same issues in the RQT camp statement.\r\n# James and Brent convinced me to join RF on condition that we revise the RQT camp statement to accomodate RF.\r\n# We are almost done! There remains just one problematic paragraph rejecting the idea that we only seem to have qualia. (The problem is, that is exactly what RF believes.)\r\n\r\nSo, Brent and I are not even trying to convert each other. We are just trying to figure out what can go in the RQT camp statement, and the only remaining problem is that one paragraph rejecting Dennett\'s philosophy.\r\n\r\nIt would be great to make other improvements as well, including fix our defintion of qualia, repair inaccuracies about optics and vision, and proselyte each other to our respective philosophies, but it would really help us to finish the current task if we could do these things in appropriately titled threads. Again, this is all welcome, it is just off-topic in this thread.\r\n\r\nReturning to the topic of Dennett\'s philosophy, I think that his philosophy characterizes RF so closely that any statement rejecting it really belongs in the PD camp, rather than in the RQT camp.','2012-06-05 13:28:31','2012-06-05 13:28:31'),(1740,96,48,'Fair enough - I\'m just a little unsure what is meant by \'It only seems we have qualia\' in the first place. To me, this is no better than saying \'It only seems like we have a sense of seeming [therefore we do not have a sense of seeming]\'. This comes from my interpretation of  what qualia are, the \'raw feels\' often talked about by philosophers. Qualia, in my mind at least, are the subjective aspects of experience - so to say that it only \'seems\' there are qualia is a little absurd. \'Seeming\' is a subjective notion, which is the whole thing you are striving to claim is an illusion. ','2012-06-05 13:46:58','2012-06-05 13:46:58'),(1743,96,48,'\"Seeming\' is a subjective notion, which is the whole thing you are striving to claim is an illusion.\"\r\n\r\nExactly, and the fact that this isn\'t glaringly obvious to everyone shows either people fundamentally have a different way of approaching consciousness or they don\'t understand what qualia refers to.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-06-05 14:03:51','2012-06-05 14:03:51'),(1746,96,48,'>>>\r\n\r\nthe fact that this isn\'t glaringly obvious to everyone\r\nshows either people fundamentally have a different way of approaching\r\nconsciousness or they don\'t understand what qualia refers to.\r\n\r\n<<<\r\n\r\nPeople do indeed have a fundamentally different way of approaching consciousness -- its it is a common malady called Naive Realism, and Daniel Dennett for example has it real bad!\r\n\r\nThe symptom is a failure to make a distinction between the objects of perception and the perception itself. The distinction is perfectly clear in the case of dreams and hallucinations, which naive realists take to be a special case. In normal perception they are not aware of any \"qualia\" because what WE call qualia, THEY just call properties of the world itself, experienced directly out where it lies beyond the sensory surface.\r\n\r\nRepresentationalists understand the distinction, and understand that our experience of the world is not direct, but is mediated by the \'sense data\' of perception, a 3-D moving colored image-like experience that looks so much like the world itself, that most people are fooled by this Grand Illusion.\r\n\r\nAnd thus debates on the topic go round and round in futile circles as people argue at cross-purposes without even a common understanding of what they are debating.','2012-06-05 14:14:47','2012-06-05 14:14:47'),(1749,96,48,'Several of Dennett\'s arguments involve optical illusions that show how things can seem different from how they really are. This directly indicates an acceptance of represenationalism, because the term \'seem\' refers to the state of some mental representation. No person of any consequence thinks that an object of perception is the same as the perception itself. That would just be ridiculous.\r\n\r\nThe issue that keeps coming up here is whether representationalism includes or excludes the kind of realism that believes plain-old-simple-physics is sufficient to implement consciousness. (By \'plain-old-simple-physics\', I mean the stuff we knew about in the 19th century, including particles, chemistry, electrostatic potentials, etc.) I am both a representationalist and a realist (by the above definition), and Dennett seems to fall in that category too. If we define representationalism in a manner that excludes realism, then we need to move the RF camp elsewhere.\r\n\r\nI have no problem with dualism, which thinks there is still some kind of important physics necessary for consciousness that has not yet been discovered. I am just trying to move that stuff out of RQT into a child camp, so I can abide within RQT.\r\n','2012-06-05 16:18:19','2012-06-05 16:18:19'),(1752,96,48,'People keep asking how believers in RF interpret Dennett\'s statement \"we don\'t have qualia, it just seems like we do.\" I feel like I have made this SAME statement many many times, but I will do it one more time.\r\n\r\nIf you define qualia as experiences as we seem to have them, then \"we don\'t have qualia, it just seems like we do\" becomes by substitution: \"we don\'t have experiences as we seem to have them, it just seems like we do\"... which is of course tautologically utter nonsense, which is why everyone keeps dissing on Dennett\'s statement. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, the term \"qualia\" has historically been assigned to a certain TYPE of experience, one that is beyond the structure and dynamics of physics, one that is epiphenomenal, or one that requires a Chalmersian extension of our ontology. Now, the statement: \"we don\'t have qualia, it just seems like we do\" becomes by substitution: \"we don\'t have experience that is beyond the structure and dynamics of physics, one that is epiphenomenal, or one that requires a Chalmersian extension of our ontology, it just seems like we do\", which is NOT tautologically nonsensical. This latter is indeed what I believe. \r\n\r\nNot only is the latter view what I think that Dennett meant, it is certainly what I believe. I think that the wording of Dennett\'s statement is confusing (see all the confusion it has produced here for example). But I think that the general idea is quite right. \r\n\r\nSO, all that is needed in the RQT camp statement so that I can accept it, is the admission that we are defining qualia as the experiences which we seem to have, as we seem to have them, and that there is no NECESSARY implications of anything \"extra\" in the term qualia, like property dualism, or epiphenomenalism. Because if those extra things are implied by the term qualia, then I don\'t think that we have qualia. If those extra things are NOT implied by the term qualia, then I think that we have them (and I think that Dennett does too actually). That\'s not to say that you can\'t belong to this camp and believe in these \"extra\" things, you can... but I want it clear that THIS super camp is agnostic on such issues, leaving them to the sub-camps. \r\n\r\nSo long as that is accomplished, I think we can move on writing the other arguments that have been made here into our sub-camp statements, where RF and PD can argue to their hearts content. ','2012-06-05 17:59:06','2012-06-05 17:59:06'),(1755,96,48,'People keep asking how believers in RF interpret Dennett\'s statement \"we don\'t have qualia, it just seems like we do.\" I feel like I have made this SAME statement many many times, but I will do it one more time.\r\n\r\nIf you define qualia as experiences as we seem to have them, then \"we don\'t have qualia, it just seems like we do\" becomes by substitution: \"we don\'t have experiences as we seem to have them, it just seems like we do\"... which is of course tautologically utter nonsense, which is why everyone keeps dissing on Dennett\'s statement. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, the term \"qualia\" has historically been assigned to a certain TYPE of experience, one that is beyond the structure and dynamics of physics, one that is epiphenomenal, or one that requires a Chalmersian extension of our ontology. Now, the statement: \"we don\'t have qualia, it just seems like we do\" becomes by substitution: \"we don\'t have experience that is beyond the structure and dynamics of physics, one that is epiphenomenal, or one that requires a Chalmersian extension of our ontology, it just seems like we do\", which is NOT tautologically nonsensical. This latter is indeed what I believe. \r\n\r\nNot only is the latter view what I think that Dennett meant, it is certainly what I believe. I think that the wording of Dennett\'s statement is confusing (see all the confusion it has produced here for example). But I think that the general idea is quite right. \r\n\r\nSO, all that is needed in the RQT camp statement so that I can accept it, is the admission that we are defining qualia as the experiences which we seem to have, as we seem to have them, and that there is no NECESSARY implications of anything \"extra\" in the term qualia, like property dualism, or epiphenomenalism. Because if those extra things are implied by the term qualia, then I don\'t think that we have qualia. If those extra things are NOT implied by the term qualia, then I think that we have them (and I think that Dennett does too actually). That\'s not to say that you can\'t belong to this camp and believe in these \"extra\" things, you can... but I want it clear that THIS super camp is agnostic on such issues, leaving them to the sub-camps. \r\n\r\nSo long as that is accomplished, I think we can move on writing the other arguments that have been made here into our sub-camp statements, where RF and PD can argue to their hearts content. ','2012-06-05 17:59:38','2012-06-05 17:59:38'),(1758,96,48,'I think that the whole point of the term qualia is to differentiate between experiences as they are presented to us directly and any knowledge that we think we have about how physics or biology relates to them.\r\n\r\nTo talk about qualia necessarily opens the door to an extension of ontology since they are clearly not physical qua physics. They have no melting point, specific gravity, they aren\'t present as miniature dioramas inside of the tissues of the brain, etc.\r\n\r\nThe explanatory gap remains; if the physics and information exists and performs all of the functions of the organism, how do experiences arise out of that? The hard problem remains; Why is there qualia at all? \r\n\r\nTo say that qualia exists but that fact can\'t change physics is just an arbitrary assertion. It\'s sentimental attachment to a particular era of physics that prohibits the progress of physics in embracing all phenomenological processes - sensation, feeling, imagination, creativity, etc.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-06-05 18:49:59','2012-06-05 18:49:59'),(1761,96,48,'Craig said: \'...they are clearly not physical qua physics\'\r\n\r\nWell, that\'s not clear to me, as I believe they are physical qua physics.\r\n\r\nCraig said: \'The explanatory gap remains ...how do experiences arise out of that?\'\r\n\r\nAccording to representationalism, our brain makes a representation (or model) of the world. According to the awareness axiom (see post 2), this representation defines how things \'seems to be\'. If our model says the pencil is bent, then the pencil seems to be bent. If it says the strawberry is red, then the strawberry seems red. It is just a matter of the brain querying its model to see how things seem to be. All of your certainty that something magical (beyond physics) happens, arises from you querying your model and it tells you that something magical happened. But nothing magical ever happens. Your model is inaccurate and over-confident.','2012-06-05 19:55:54','2012-06-05 19:55:54'),(1764,96,48,'I like and agree with what Craig is saying in post #25.\r\n\r\nSo, James, let me know if the following is different than what you are saying?:\r\n\r\n* â€œWe think a particular seeming, like a redness quale, canâ€™t be represented by abstract symbols like ones and zeros, but thinking about a seeming in this way is wrong.  Our seemingâ€™s can be fully realized and represented by abstract symbols without any additional interpretation of such being required.â€\r\n\r\nThis is all so hard to say, because, I believe all qualia can be represented, it\'s just that, in my world/theory, you need to know how to interpret them to get to the phenomenal/fundamental meaning or what they are like, from any set of ones and zeros.\r\n\r\nAnd of course, basically, you also must then be saying the term â€˜ineffableâ€™ is basically a meaningless term and should probably be removed from the English language, since it causes us to have false beliefs like redness is ineffable, or that the taste of salt canâ€™t be communicated by abstract symbols, without knowing how to interpret them.\r\n\r\n\r\nI apologize for taking so long to fully digest this, which I now remember you having stated this multiple times.\r\n\r\nSo, I guess we would both agree that material property dualism is predicting that gradual substitution of neurons, with any abstract system like one based on silicone, will not be possible, without the person noticing a big difference in his redness, while you are predicting it will be possible, and that it will be possible to entirely replace the brain with any abstract silicone, or any other system, and this mind will still be experiencing the same redness.  And this is what the experimental neuro scientists need to seek to do to convert us all to the same camp.\r\n\r\nAnd tell me, again, how you would know if my redness is the same as your redness, or if it is more like your greenness, or how you would tell such, from any other particular sets of bits of functionality?  And what might the bits/functitonality be, which I\'d need to duplicate in your mind for you to experience my redness, if you have never experienced my redness before in your life...?\r\n\r\nAlso, Material Property Dualism basically predicts that, like there are a finite number of atomic elements, there is likely a finite number of possible fundamental quale.  (thought they can obviously be put together to make or paint an infinite number of diverse experiences.)  But your theory predicts there would be an infinite number of possible fundamental qualia, only bounded by the complexity of the machine?\r\n\r\nIt sure would be great to get Dr. Dennett\'s take on all this to see if he sees things the same way.\r\n\r\n','2012-06-05 20:13:06','2012-06-05 20:13:06'),(1767,96,48,'\"Well, that\'s not clear to me, as I believe they are physical qua\r\nphysics.\"\r\n\r\nYou\'re certainly entitled to believe that, but what part of physics would or could predict the feeling of pain or the amusement of comedy? Just to say that you believe that physics doesn\'t mean anything to me. Why are they part of physics other than to satisfy the compulsion to make physics primary?\r\n\r\n\"According to representationalism, our brain makes a representation (or model) of the world\"\r\n\r\nThat\'s my point. What is a \'model\' physically made of? If we are experiencing a representation, where is that representation located? Why is it in this particular form and not in the forms in which it seems to physically exist? Why don\'t we experience ourselves as neurons responding to conditions represented as they physically are - neurotransmitter molecules, action potentials, etc? Why mask them and how could such a thing take place within physics as we understand it?\r\n\r\n\"All of your certainty that something magical (beyond physics) happens, arises from you querying your model and it tells you that something magical happened.\"\r\n\r\nNot at all. I have never once claimed that awareness is magical or literally non-physical. It is RQT that posits a metaphysical \'model\' which seems magical to me. I only say that our physics is a legacy system which, (like classical mechanics before it in failing to foresee relativity and QM), is correct except for a few small details it can\'t account for: all feeling, experience, and meaning in the cosmos.','2012-06-05 20:19:09','2012-06-05 20:19:09'),(1770,96,48,'If Craig\'s definition of qualia carries the day, then RF will have to leave RQT, because we don\'t believe in qualia (of that sort). ','2012-06-05 20:19:14','2012-06-05 20:19:14'),(1773,96,48,'@Brent: I will try to reply to your long set of questions:\r\n\r\n\" * â€œWe think a particular seeming, like a redness quale, canâ€™t be represented by abstract symbols like ones and zeros, but thinking about a seeming in this way is wrong. Our seemingâ€™s can be fully realized and represented by abstract symbols without any additional interpretation of such being required.â€\r\n\r\n\r\nSomething like that, but to distinguish RF from FPD, I like to talk in terms of the structure and dynamics of physics, NOT in terms of ones and zero\'s. Because RF says that there is nothing more than the structure and dynamics of physics. FPD says that there IS something more, but that this \"more\" lives in the information (like the ones and zero\'s). BOTH RF and FPD think that you can simulate qualia on a computer, JUST by simulating the functionality of the system. But FPD things that this simulation carries the \"MORE\" stuff, and RF thinks that there IS no MORE to have. \r\n\r\n\"This is all so hard to say, because, I believe all qualia can be\r\nrepresented, it\'s just that, in my world/theory, you need to know how to interpret them to get to the phenomenal/fundamental meaning or what they are like, from any set of ones and zeros.\"\r\n\r\nAnd my theory is that there IS nothing more to interpret. If the right behavior is produced, then there IS nothing else to interpret. The qualia are there, in the system that produces the behavior. If it produces the right behavior, then it MUST have been interpreted correctly. \r\n\r\nAnd of course, basically, you also must then be saying the term â€˜ineffableâ€™ is basically a meaningless term\"\r\n\r\nYUP!\r\n\r\n\"and should probably be removed from the English language, since it causes us to have false beliefs like redness is ineffable, or that the taste of salt canâ€™t be communicated by abstract symbols, without knowing how to interpret them.\"\r\n\r\nYUP. I don\'t believe in the explanitory gap. The only gap appears because of the limitations of our language... BUT if I communicated all the sates of all the neurons in your brain, I DID communicate the experience (if you can follow all that information). Thus, I just effed the \"SEEMINGLY ineffable\". \r\n\r\n\"So, I guess we would both agree that material property dualism is predicting that gradual substitution of neurons, with any abstract system like one based on silicone, will not be possible, without the person noticing a big difference in his redness\" \r\n\r\nThat\'s your baby, you tell me what MPD predicts. I have no idea, because if the qualia are epiphenomenal, the person would notice the difference, but BEHAVE no differently... which is a contradiction as far as I am concerned. If the qualia are NOT epiphenomenal, then I challenge you to produce a mathematically rigorous example of how this would work. To date you have failed to produce such a model. As fare as I can tell, there is no consistent way of formalizing PD that doesn\'t produce epiphenomenalism. If I am wrong, then by all means, SHOW ME A MATHEMATICALLY RIGOROUS EXAMPLE THEORY.\r\n\r\n\"while you are predicting it will be possible, and that it will be possible to entirely replace the brain with any abstract silicone, or any other system, and this mind will still be experiencing the same redness.\"\r\n\r\nYES, but RF and FPD predict this. \r\n\r\n\"And this is what the experimental neuro scientists need to seek to do to convert us all to the same camp.\"\r\n\r\nWell, if someone\'s qualia is epiphenomenal, I don\'t see how you can ever be converted. As far as I can tell, you are completely irrational, and no amount of evidence could change your mind. \r\n\r\nYOU claim that your qualia is not epiphenomenal... so I hope to eventually formalize a proof that you can\'t produce non-epiphenomenal qualia from PD, and I hope that THAT will convert you to my camp. \r\n\r\n\"And tell me, again, how you would know if my redness is the same as your redness, or if it is more like your greenness, or how you would tell such, from any other particular sets of bits of functionality?\"\r\n\r\nBecause the bits and functionality ARE the qualia, so I tell by looking at the bits and functionality, and seeing if they are equivalent. If you can have the same functionality and behavior, but still have inverted or missing qualia, THEN that qualia MUST be epiphenomenal. In which case, I argue that they don\'t really exist. \r\n\r\n\"And what might the bits/functitonality be, which I\'d need to duplicate in your mind for you to experience my redness, if you have never experienced my redness before in your life...?\"\r\n\r\nWhatever bits produce the qualia in your brain, I reproduce them, and walla, the same CLAIMS of qualia, the same BELIEFS of qualia, the same MEMORIES of qualia, and thus... the same FEELINGS of qualia. \r\n\r\n\"Also, Material Property Dualism basically predicts that, like there are a finite number of atomic elements, there is likely a finite number of possible fundamental quale. (thought they can obviously be put together to make or paint an infinite number of diverse experiences.) But your theory predicts there would be an infinite number of possible fundamental qualia, only bounded by the complexity of the machine?\"\r\n\r\nYes, my theory predicts a countably infinite number of qualia, while yours predicts a finite number of qualia. Thus, the universe will be a FAR more interesting place to be if I am right than if you are. \r\n\r\n\"It sure would be great to get Dr. Dennett\'s take on all this to see if he sees things the same way.\"\r\n\r\nIf we write good camp statements, with GOOD references, then he might be more interested in joining in the conversation. ','2012-06-05 20:35:11','2012-06-05 20:35:11'),(1776,96,48,'Craig, it seems the term \'model\' must mean something a lot more specific to you than it does to me. To me, it is not a very meaningful concept. I am not saying the brain builds a cohesive replica of the world. I am merely saying it remembers stuff. If you can close your eyes and imagine the room you are in, I think that proves you have built a mental \'model\'. What this model is made out of, or where it is located, are not really relevant, as long as your brain somehow has the ability to retrieve memories and piece them together.\r\n\r\nRegarding which part of physics is responsible for the experiences of pain or amusement: Well, according to my theory, you do not really experience those things, you just think you do =). If we assume that your model is encoded in electrostatic potentials between neurons, then the physics of electrostatics is sufficient to make you think you experienced pain or amusement.','2012-06-05 20:48:13','2012-06-05 20:48:13'),(1779,96,48,'Mike, you\'re only confirming that you aren\'t willing to address the objections I\'m bringing up. What are models? Just that the brain remembers. Where are they? It doesn\'t matter.\r\n\r\nDon\'t forget that our every experience is made of nothing but these disembodied meaningless nothings that seem like everything we have ever known.\r\n\r\nIf you want qualia to be physical, then it has to matter how exactly they are physical, otherwise it\'s just \'handwaving and wishful thinking\' as some like to say. If I make a computer program that models one set of data as another set of data, why would some third representation arise to mediate the two? More importantly how could it arise? It doesn\'t make sense. A bent spring can remember what shape it was in without, presumably, some kind of \'representation\' model appearing out of nowhere.','2012-06-05 21:39:37','2012-06-05 21:39:37'),(1782,96,48,'\" If I make a computer program that models one set of data as another set of data, why would some third representation arise to mediate the two? More importantly how could it arise? It doesn\'t make sense.\"\r\n\r\nI can\'t even follow this objection/question. I model the world, and experience my model. I write AI algorithms that do that all the time. Then I have an identity theorem that says that the model IS the experience. Done. What\'s the problem? What doesn\'t make sense?\r\n\r\nIn any event, while interesting, this conversation needs to be tabled while we work out the camp hierarchy. You can try to convert me to a different place in the hierarchy after we work out what the hierarchy should look like. \r\n\r\nSpecifically, we need to come to a conclusion about how we are going to define qualia in the RQT camp, so that us RF\'s can decide if we belong in RQT, or if we need to make our own representational experience theory camp. If you guys really want to define qualia as some extra physical stuff, and if you think that matches common usage best, then that\'s ok, we will just create a RT or RET (Representational Experience Theory) camp, that doesn\'t involve these extra things, and join that. Eventually, RQT would also join this new super camp. But if we go that route, then it seems to me that there is no difference between RQT and PD... since it is PD that specifically tries to suppose that there is something EXTRA involved in qualia. The purpose of splitting them was to push all that belief in \"extra stuff\" down into the PD camp, so that there is a place for those like myself, Mike, and Dennett, that don\'t believe in the extra stuff. ','2012-06-06 15:06:54','2012-06-06 15:06:54'),(1785,96,48,'\r\nHi James,\r\n\r\nYes, itâ€™s very tempting to get lost in the controversial details, and fall down these lessor important rat holes, like this â€“ so thanks for pointing this out, and keeping us on task.\r\n\r\nAlso, another priority is consensus, and doing anything possible to allow anyone in the camp, possible, if there is anything at all we can agree on.  So, if you want to define qualia in a diet way, at the RQT level, what you want is our highest priority.  Weâ€™ll push a classic quale definition down to the Property Dualism level, and that is far less important than having your support of RQT.\r\n\r\nYou diet qualia guys are the minority, so we will always tend to push toward classic qualia, so we desperately need your help to keep us straight, so we never let anything in the camp you minority guys disagree with.  I know thatâ€™s lots of extra work, when you are the minority, but everyone will greatly appreciate your helping us, to accomplish what everyone wants, as much as possible.\r\n\r\nOther people have mentioned moving discussions to other camp forums, so if you want to have a convert someone conversation, that would be a good place for that, as not everyone in the entire topic is interested in that.  Letâ€™s try and focus on the new version of the RQT camp statement, for now, and keep the chatter to other specific camp forums.\r\n\r\nThanks All!  Seeing this new theoretically revolutionary structure form, and the new RQT statement (and the shocking amount of consensus it maintain, even increasing) is really getting exciting â€“ letâ€™s get this finished.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-06 16:02:01','2012-06-06 16:02:01'),(1786,261,41,'> \" If I make a computer program that models one set of data as another\r\n\r\n> set of data, why would some third representation arise to mediate the\r\n\r\n> two? More importantly how could it arise? It doesn\'t make sense.\"\r\n\r\n>\r\n\r\n> I can\'t even follow this objection/question.\r\n\r\nA good reason to consider it more closely.\r\n\r\n>I model the world, and\r\n\r\n> experience my model.\r\n\r\nIf you model the world directly, then you are experiencing the world and don\'t need a model. If you mean that your brain models the world then it is your model that is experiencing your brain and your brain that is experiencing the world (without a model). It all doesn\'t matter since at some point you have to experience something. If you don\'t need a model to experience your model of the brain\'s experience of the world, then why would you need any model at all to experience anything? What is it about the brain that requires an intermediary model for it to be what it already is and make it seem like it is doing something other than what it is already doing?\r\n\r\n> I write AI algorithms that do that all the time.\r\n\r\n> Then I have an identity theorem that says that the model IS the\r\n\r\n> experience. Done. What\'s the problem? What doesn\'t make sense?\r\n\r\nYour algorithms only model information for your benefit. The computer doesn\'t model anything. All the computer knows is \'if x byte at m memory location is n value, then change y bytes at ym memory locations to n values. It is entirely dependent upon a material substrate that can be used to detect, change, and detect changes within it.\r\n\r\nIn a computer program there is no model because it\'s not literal to begin with. It\'s all a model - for our eyes and fingers and minds, not for the computer. The experience of the computer is only the microelectronic phase transitions (and whatever qualia might be associated with them from the inside...certainly nothing like the software GUI we see with out eyes and understand with our mind on the outside.)\r\n\r\nModels don\'t ex-ist. They in-sist as part of the sense-making experience of a sophisticated organism which has evolved cognitive elaboration to its sense channels. A sign that says STOP is a model of the experience of being warned to decelerate immediately and avoid oncoming traffic and moving violations. It\'s only a model to us, because we know how to read it. If the model ex-isted, then deer would obey stop signs and be better off.\r\n\r\n>\r\n\r\n> In any event, while interesting, this conversation needs to be tabled\r\n\r\n> while we work out the camp hierarchy. You can try to convert me to a\r\n\r\n> different place in the hierarchy after we work out what the hierarchy\r\n\r\n> should look like. >\r\n\r\nOk, but I don\'t know what is the rush to crash this train into the brick wall it\'s headed for. I\'m trying to show you how to switch tracks.\r\n\r\n> Specifically, we need to come to a conclusion about how we are going to\r\n\r\n> define qualia in the RQT camp, so that us RF\'s can decide if we belong\r\n\r\n> in RQT, or if we need to make our own representational experience\r\n\r\n> theory camp. If you guys really want to define qualia as some extra\r\n\r\n> physical stuff, and if you think that matches common usage best, then\r\n\r\n> that\'s ok, we will just create a RT or RET (Representational Experience\r\n\r\n> Theory) camp, that doesn\'t involve these extra things, and join that.\r\n\r\n> Eventually, RQT would also join this new super camp. But if we go that\r\n\r\n> route, then it seems to me that there is no difference between RQT and\r\n\r\n> PD... since it is PD that specifically tries to suppose that there is\r\n\r\n> something EXTRA involved in qualia. The purpose of splitting them was\r\n\r\n> to push all that belief in \"extra stuff\" down into the PD camp, so that\r\n\r\n> there is a place for those like myself, Mike, and Dennett, that don\'t\r\n\r\n> believe in the extra stuff.\r\n\r\nI gave it a shot earlier playing devil\'s advocate, but no matter how I try to make RQT into a plausible and defensible position, it can only unravel itself like the weightless, ungrounded approach that it seems to be. ','2012-06-06 16:44:57','2012-06-06 16:44:57'),(1789,96,48,'Given the loaded connotations the word \'qualia\' has for many people, it might be terminology worth avoiding for people in Mike Gashler et al\'s shoes - surely?','2012-06-06 16:45:18','2012-06-06 16:45:18'),(1792,96,48,'Or else just go with the explanation of qualia that you know is wrong to complete the camp statement.\r\n\r\nIf anyone is interested in the conversion thread, my reply to jlcarroll is here...\r\n\r\nhttp://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/50/1/1#1','2012-06-06 16:48:28','2012-06-06 16:48:28'),(1795,96,48,'omgpop wrote: \"Given the loaded connotations the word \'qualia\' has for many people, it might be terminology worth avoiding for people in Mike Gashler et al\'s shoes - surely?\"\r\n\r\nThat is a good point. Perhaps it would be best to re-name RQT to something like RET, (E for Experience) and then name PD something like QPD... I don\'t know. \r\n\r\nWhat does everyone think?','2012-06-06 17:27:15','2012-06-06 17:27:15'),(1798,96,48,'Great idea! Had we only thought to do that sooner, many fruitless terminology battles could have been avoided.','2012-06-06 17:41:35','2012-06-06 17:41:35'),(1801,96,48,'Mike wrote: \"Great idea! Had we only thought to do that sooner, many fruitless terminology battles could have been avoided.\"\r\n\r\nWell... I DID think of it sooner. I just had hopes that I could shift people\'s perception of what is acceptable as a qualia. I really do want people to understand that qualia are our experiences as we really do have them, for whatever reason... I think that is the best definition, and then the debate can be not about whether we have qualia or not, but about where our qualia really come form (and whether they are magical or not). I prefer this IF IT CAN BE DONE WITHOUT CONFUSION. And that last I guess is the real question here. \r\n\r\nOur previous discussions on this topic may indeed indicate that my hope was un-founded. My previous message giving up on this re-definition of qualia was actually something of an act of desperation. ','2012-06-06 17:52:06','2012-06-06 17:52:06'),(1804,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nNooo!!   Iâ€™ll give up almost anything to maintain the word qualia and as much consensus as possible for it.  Craig, are you the only one the disagrees with something in their diet qualia definition?  I agree with everyone in the definition, Iâ€™d just like to add a bunch more.  Weâ€™ve got to be able to find a way to achieve consensus on this?  Can you help me better understand your thinking, if there is something, specific, that you disagree with?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-06 19:01:41','2012-06-06 19:01:41'),(1807,96,48,'I will work with whatever terms you guys prefer, as long as someone makes a glossary somewhere, so I can use it to parse pedantic diatribes, and point at it whenever a debate reduces to dogmatic fighting over the true nuances of a particular term. It would be nice if we kept it mostly in sync with the corresponding Wikipedia pages, but I don\'t want to ask for too much.','2012-06-06 19:41:01','2012-06-06 19:41:01'),(1810,96,48,'Mike,\r\n\r\nGreat, thanks.  The â€˜glossaryâ€™, and meanings everyone uses, should be canonized camps.  We had some controversy over the word [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/102/2 effing] the ineffable, so we started a topic to determine the best word to use for that.  If we need to we should do the same for qualia.  Also, where as, with these expert theoretical topics, we should probably use expert consensus to make structural camp consensus decisions, and so on.  Iâ€™m thinking we should use the popular consensus for terminology, which is consistent with Mikeâ€™s Idea of staying consistent with Wikipedia.  This is because the experts at the top can work within whatever terminology they are provided, while communication and moral education of the masses and people at the bottom is the most important.  If there is a popular revolution for a better meaning of a word, everyone should switch their camps to use the new state of the art popular definitions.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-06-06 20:08:19','2012-06-06 20:08:19'),(1813,96,48,'It\'s not the term qualia I have a problem with, it\'s the term representation. If representation included the concept of presentation with it to begin with, then it would make sense to define qualia that way. Qualia is all about the entanglement of presentation and representation (aka sense).','2012-06-06 20:09:13','2012-06-06 20:09:13'),(1816,96,48,'Brent, I will give an overview of my understanding of qualia, and you can see for yourself whether that is compatible with what you think of.\r\n\r\nThe way I model this whole debate is based on what I perceive to be as a huge distinction between the subjective character of conscious experience, and the physical brain events which appear to bring it about. So on the one hand I understand the brain to be this physical object which can be measured and quantified. I picture it as a type of complex computer which has inputs, processes and outputs, all of which are causally determined and explicable. I think there are aspects of this complex computer which directly correlate with conscious experience, but are not one and the same as it. For example, when reflecting nostalgically on a happy memory, the warm feeling one gets is very much real and physical in one sense - in that your brain may be in a state of releasing oxytocin in certain pertinent areas or what have you - but in another sense, there is something else there which the purely neurophysiological description does not capture, and that is the feeling itself. \r\n\r\nAnother way of relating this paradigm is as follows: A blind man dedicates half of his life studying advanced level optics, gaining a more thorough understanding of the physics and processes of how light works than perhaps anyone else. He then spends the remaining half of his life taking on the study of neuroscience to a similarly high level - by now maybe you guess the blind man is trying to gain an understanding of what it is like to have visual experience for himself.But try as he might, and though he studies every day and attains a great deal of knowledge, at the end of the it all he lies in his deathbed feeling only as though he has led his life in vein (probably wishing he\'d dedicated all his braininess to neuprosthesis research), for he still does not have the first clue what it is like to see. \r\n\r\nThis thing, this \'what it is like\' which is not captured by any physical model, no matter how granular, is how I define qualia. Another way to illustrate the presence of some logical dichotomy between that and the physical stuff we can model is by applying the method of radical doubt. Our knowledge about the objective existence of things we perceive may be subject to doubt, as shown by the dream argument and many others. Since the brain has been identified - ultimately - through the senses, it is an objective which model may be subject to some doubt. However, we can\'t doubt that experiences themselves exist, clearly. So therefore, the more certain and intimate knowledge we have about the subjective aspects of our experience is an indicator of a distinction between those and the physical systems which we associate with them. So the argument goes.I am not trying to persuade anyone of this notion, just merely for people to have an idea what at least *I* mean by qualia, and maybe it applies to others.\r\n\r\nJordan T ','2012-06-06 20:10:17','2012-06-06 20:10:17'),(1819,96,48,'And to tie that up, I don\'t see that as being compatible with a lot of the arguments being made here - ergo, unless my definition of qualia is a marginal one, those arguments should seek different terminology.','2012-06-06 20:20:23','2012-06-06 20:20:23'),(1822,96,48,'Why are we even trying to figure out consciousness anyway? Is it not because we hope to lay some sort of theoretical foundation that may eventually enable people build a better world? So what might be the value of defining qualia in terms of its incomprehensibility, its unreachability, or its ineffability?\r\n\r\nSomewhere in the future:\r\n\r\nScience: Eureka! We succeeded at uploading consciousness!\r\nMTA: It doesn\'t count--you didn\'t eff qualia.\r\nScience: But it works! We can store consciousness on a thumb drive. We can transmit consciousness via light--this will change everything!\r\nMTA: Nope, you still didn\'t eff qualia because we define qualia as that which cannot be effed. Whatever you effed, therefore, was not qualia. We are still right, nanny noo noo.\r\nScience: Whatever. Thanks for all your help figuring this out. ...NOT!\r\n','2012-06-06 20:44:26','2012-06-06 20:44:26'),(1825,96,48,'You\'re missing the point though - no one is arbitrarily defining qualia that way for no apparent reason. We\'re doing it because we genuinely perceive there to exist mental properties which are ineffable, in the real actual world - I think it is pretty clear that if we\'re right, it would be a pretty big obstacle to the actual production of the theoretical framework you\'re talking about. We\'re not pedants, you\'re just not getting it why what we\'re saying is relevant to the philosophical pursuit of understanding the mind.','2012-06-06 21:01:49','2012-06-06 21:01:49'),(1828,96,48,'\r\nI propose we start a new topic to â€˜canonizeâ€™ the definition of qualia.  I propose it has the same structure we are talking about here.  James, would you care to provide the definition for the top level consensus camp?  And then we can add a classical qualia definition, for a sub camp, and point out that we refer to the parent camp definition as â€˜diet qualiaâ€™ and so on, since diet is a somewhat derogatory termâ€¦\r\n\r\nThe whole idea of consensus, is to provide a platform so the moral and scientific experts have a way to communicate, better, and to be heard, in a unified consensus voice, above the crowd, including the ability to track what the masses still believe, and measure the progress, and find out what it will take to convert them to a more moral behaviorâ€¦  The goal is to literally amplify the moral wisdom of the crowd, including the experts.  We want to find a way so the morality of the world can finally get out of being stuck in the biblical dark ages, and start progressing, exponentially, and hopefully finally keeping up with our technical abilities.\r\n\r\nOh, and thatâ€™s a great fictional story, Mike, but I think, one that is impossible.  Since long before that occurs, one of our camps will be falsified by science, and weâ€™ll all be in the same camp.  But, if it is the effing classical qualia, or the spiritual if you will, camp, spirits (as defined in the current version of RQT), will be escaping beyond this ineffable veil of spiritual perception, the mortal prison walls that is our skull, and traversing / sharing each otherâ€™s ever expanding spirit worlds, and ushering in the Millennium, as described in \r\n[http://home.comcast.net/~brent.allsop/1229.htm#_Toc22030743 this capter] of the fictional 1229 story.\r\n\r\nPeopleâ€™s eternal salvation is dependent on spiritually understanding all this, and they will fail to be free, and choosing eternal damnation, rotting everyone in the hell, that is the grave, till they all can understand these kinds of things, and see what today, only a few experts can see.\r\n\r\n','2012-06-06 21:15:47','2012-06-06 21:15:47'),(1831,96,48,'omgpop, You are right. I concede that identifying impossible obstacles can be useful and important. My post was a bit rash.','2012-06-06 21:19:27','2012-06-06 21:19:27'),(1834,96,48,'omgpop:\r\n\r\nHere\'s my question for you... you THINK that experiences are ineffable. I don\'t. But would it bother you if I used the term \"qualia\" to describe my experiences, as I have them, for WHATEVER reason, effable or ineffable? Or do I need to pick another term, because you have locked in this \"ineffable\" meaning as part of the term qualia?\r\n\r\nI have a response to the \"Mary\'s Room\" theory you just re-phrased as a blind man, and I have a reason why I find it completely un-convincing. But again, THIS part of the discussion isn\'t about whether I am right or you are about qualia being ineffable, the existence of the explanatory gap etc. The question is whether you think that there is a communication problem with someone who doesn\'t believe that qualia are epiphenomenal, doesn\'t believe that Robo-Mary learns anything, and doesn\'t believe in the explanitory gap, still describing their experiences (as they have them, for whatever reason) as \"qualia\"? \r\n\r\nWhat say you on this? I want to communicate as effectively as possible. Therefore, if using the term qualia to describe a reductionist explanation for subjective experiences causes confusion, I would be happy to abandon RQT, and create my own RET. \r\n\r\nAs for wikipedia, they currently define qualia as follows: \"from a Latin word meaning for \"what sort\" or \"what kind,\" is a term used in philosophy to refer to subjective conscious experiences as \'raw feels\'. Daniel Dennett writes that qualia is \"an unfamiliar term for something that could not be more familiar to each of us: the ways things seem to us.\"\"\r\n\r\nI have no problem with ANY of that definition... but then they immediate jump down the rabbit hole and say: \"Erwin SchrÃ¶dinger had this counter-materialist take: \"The sensation of colour cannot be accounted for by the physicist\'s objective picture of light-waves. Could the physiologist account for it, if he had fuller knowledge than he has of the processes in the retina and the nervous processes set up by them in the optical nerve bundles and in the brain? I do not think so.\"[2]\"\r\n\r\nWhich I disagree with mightily. \r\n\r\nSo, what do you think, can anyone call subjective experiences  \"qualia\" or can you only call them that if you believe something SPECIFIC about subjective experiences?','2012-06-06 21:43:34','2012-06-06 21:43:34'),(1837,96,48,'Or, to put this more clearly, can a materialist talk of having qualia? Or is that a mis-use of the term?\r\n\r\nWhen I read your excellent description of what you believe, I was thinking... I KNOW that\'s what you think about qualia. I know that\'s how YOU think qualia come about. But I don\'t know if you think that someone who disagrees with you can still use the term qualia, and be understood. That\'s the heart of the matter as far as I can tell. ','2012-06-06 21:47:08','2012-06-06 21:47:08'),(1840,96,48,'James,\r\n\r\nCould you provide, what is in your opinion, the best definition of quale?  I bet we can get that canonized, and we can all work with that.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2012-06-06 21:58:40','2012-06-06 21:58:40'),(1843,96,48,'James, \r\n\r\nWhat is your read on the Blind Man. You\'re not saying that he will eventually see when he understands enough about optics and vision, right?\r\n\r\nIt\'s fine with me if you use qualia in a way that serves eliminative materialism or functionalism, but how does it work? Why does function or substance develop experience? (Not to mention the question of how or when or where.)','2012-06-06 22:04:43','2012-06-06 22:04:43'),(1846,96,48,'My definition of qualia is \"subjective experiences, as we really do have them, for whatever reason\". Then epiphenomenal garbage is qualia, and real qualia are qualia too. \r\n\r\nMy take on the Jackson Mary\'s room tragedy is going to be the subject of an upcoming paper. \r\n\r\nShort answer, we store one type of data in one part of the brain, and another type in another part... so Mary stores what she learns about neurons and vision in one part of her brain (brain region 1), but she stores memories of her experiences with vision in another part (brain region 2). If we define \"learning\" as a change in neural patterns, then Mary learns something, because brain region 2 changes when she first sees color. But those changes are completely predictable form the information she had stored in brain region 1. It is this separation in how we store information that makes it SEEM like there is something \"else\" that Mary learns, and that makes qualia appear \"magical\" and which makes the explanitory gap APPEAR wide. However, if you conclude from this that qualia are epiphenomenal, as does Jackson, you jump off a rather deep cliff into stupidity. I have several reasons to think that epiphenomenalism is completely, utterly, and in all other ways, a non-starter impossibility. \r\n\r\nIf my qualia are not causally active, then they don\'t exist, or if they do, I don\'t care about them AT ALL, nor do I actually experience them in any meaningful way, because what I experience is causally active, inasmuch as I can describe what I am experiencing. For my qualia to be meaningful, my qualia must CAUSE these responses, they can\'t just accompany them. \r\n\r\nI talk about this here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lxzSyLAj3NI','2012-06-06 22:21:40','2012-06-06 22:21:40'),(1849,96,48,'James,\r\n\r\nWell, I wouldn\'t want to be didactic about it - I\'m by no means an expert on anything, and I don\'t want to be taken too seriously here, but I\'m just thinking in terms of if my opinion is a commonly held one. I totally get it by the by, I\'m not trying to persuade you on to my understanding of the mind-body problem at all. But if my interpretation is common, then I think it\'s only natural that the most healthy option for those who propound your school of thought to seek different words. To answer your question, no, in my definition a materialist could not have qualia. Or, well... I don\'t really know. \r\n\r\nI find it mighty strange how you can accept subjective experience, but not its interpersonal ineffability. I see ineffability as a direct consequence of subjectivity. I accept the core meaning of qualia is basically subjective experience, but I think me and a lot of others take implicit within that the idea of interpersonal ineffability. So at the bottom line I\'m not sure. I don\'t know how a materialist could have subjective experience, but you are free to have that theory if you like. I just think using the term qualia may cause more confusion than it is ultimately worth for your cause. ','2012-06-06 22:32:29','2012-06-06 22:32:29'),(1852,96,48,'James,\r\n\r\n\"Short answer, we store one type of data in one part of the brain, and another type in another part.\"\r\n\r\nPeople who are blind have their V1 area light up from tactile sensation, so that isn\'t how it works in reality. If it was though, it still wouldn\'t mean anything. Putting ears in the front of your head doesn\'t make them eyes, and binary data in one area of memory doesn\'t give it a different feel than another.\r\n\r\nI don\'t think that anyone here is talking about epiphenomenalism or magic, so I\'m not sure why you bring it up.\r\n\r\nYou didn\'t address the blind man question, which I think probably means you don\'t have an answer that makes sense. That\'s ok, nobody else does either. There is no way to generate the experience of seeing or feeling or any kind of experience whatsoever out of nothing but information processing. Information is epiphenomenal. It doesn\'t do anything by itself. We inform and are informed but information is not an independent phenomenon of real subjects-objects in the universe of space-time they create.','2012-06-06 23:05:53','2012-06-06 23:05:53'),(1855,96,48,'I think James\' response to the blind man is actually pretty valid Craig. Of course, whether or not epiphenomenal qualia exist (and I take issue with the instant dismissal of epiphenomenalism as irrational somehow), it would be impossible for abstract modelling using words or mathematics to stimulate the visual centres of the brain. Of course. But I have no where near processed the implications of this or gathered myself sufficiently to truly rebutt it - but that is a very valid idea.','2012-06-06 23:31:33','2012-06-06 23:31:33'),(1858,96,48,'I don\'t understand the idea of \'seeming\' at all as a functionalist concept. Do the bytes of an mp3 seem different than the bytes of a jpeg? If I change the file extender on  them do the bytes change from seeming like sound to image?\r\n\r\nWhen we see color or images, that experience can make us think of descriptive words, but those words can\'t evoke the actual experience unless you are capable of seeing color yourself. In the same way, I can look at some fragment of a lost language on an alien planet, and even if I could deduce what the language might refer to, there is no way that I could deduce what the language was supposed to sound like when spoken. All data is not created equal.\r\n\r\nA computer however, only computes binary data, which is by definition equal. Not only does it not discriminate against data grouped as sound or words, it has no capacity to understand either one. It doesn\'t even know machine language or hexadecimal code. That\'s all our human way of controlling the machine. It knows only how to open and close switches and see whether they are open or closed. Everything else is human pattern recognition.','2012-06-07 00:12:26','2012-06-07 00:12:26'),(1861,96,48,'I\'ve now [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/110/2 Canonized] Jame\'s definition of qualia.  So I hope everyone will support and contribute your feeling on this.  And hopefully help improve my needs LOTS of improvement [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/110/3 classic qualia] definition statement, or anything else in the topic.\r\n\r\nCraig,\r\n\r\nFunctionally, a seeming is a representation of information that doesn\'t accurately represent it\'s referent or is \'non veridical\'.  A seeming can also be a dream, or a hallucination, or a spirit, that may not have any referent at all, they just are.\r\n\r\nYou indicated:  \"If you model the world directly, then you are experiencing the world and don\'t need a model.\"  I remember the last time I had that thought!  It was back when I was taking my first AI classes as an undergraduate.  We were learning how to build 3D models from edges of blocks in 2D images.\r\n\r\n\"Why the heck do we have to learn this\", I remember thinking as I struggled with the very hard problem.  Then, suddenly, representationalism hit me with a tone of bricks.  It was the most life changing, eye opening, religious conversion experience I have had in my life.  Most people that truly understand representationalism have a similar life changing experience with when they first realized this.  I always love hearing others stories of this first realization.\r\n\r\nIncidentally, it seems to me, from all I\'ve read of Dennett, that he still struggles with this.  He still shows lots of evidence of thinking we don\'t need complete models of what we know, that we are some how aware of the surface of the strawberry, or have multiple drafts of such, or something.  I bet he has never done any AI programming..\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-07 02:29:20','2012-06-07 02:29:20'),(1864,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nI don\'t think that Information can represent anything except to whoever or whatever finally cares about what it means to them. Representation and presentation are both experiences that have no function outside of awareness.\r\n\r\nYou can program \'LET X=Y\' but not \'LET X seem like it equals Y\'. Seems has no functional meaning at all.\r\n\r\nI agree that representationalism can be a legitimate and exciting revelation. A lot of people at a certain age have that revelation from watching The Matrix or getting stoned. The post-representational revelations that I have been experiencing are more significant to me, but in a different way. Instead of the thrill of the possibility that the universe is all truly inside my brain and that I am an avatar in this world, I feel strangely calm and curious about the actual world of the here and now. What if the world isn\'t a simulation? What if simulation is illusion? What if there is no representation without presentation?\r\n\r\nWith representationalism there will always be struggling to fit the last square peg in the remaining round hole. It will always paint itself into a corner, just like a manual on how to listen to music will never allow someone who is deaf to hear it. There is a tiny hole in representationalism, and there is nothing that is not ultimately swallowed up by it.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-06-07 03:07:19','2012-06-07 03:07:19'),(1867,96,48,'\r\nCraig,\r\n\r\nYou can exactly functionally program let X seem like it equals Y.  That\'s exactly what I\'d do with my robot, as he looked at the pencil, in a glass of water.  He\'d notice his visual knowledge was \'bent\', and thereby know the pencil only \'seemed\' bent, to him, because it was in a glass of water.  Using his higher cognitive functions, he\'d know the pencil is really not bent, and thereby only a seeming.\r\n\r\nAlso, I don\'t see any problems at all with Representational Qualia Theory.  It explains everything from out of body experiences, intentionality and everything, in a very functional and phenomenal way.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-06-07 03:26:29','2012-06-07 03:26:29'),(1870,96,48,'\r\nCraig,\r\n\r\nYou indicated your issue was with representationalism, not qualia.  If that is the case, then like Mike said, you are making extraordinary claims, going against such a significant expert consensus.  10 years ago, and more, I\'d say representationalism wasn\'t in the consensus majority at all.  But there is a significant expert consensus revolution taking place as most experts now considered any non representational theory of perception long since falsified and suffering from critical errors.  So changing this would require significant evidence, not to mention support from other experts, before we can bring to pass a theoretical revolution that significant.\r\n\r\nIt seems to me, the best thing for you to do is to start a competing camp, with Representational Qualia Theory, and get started at such?  Like the \"Representational Functional Camp\" that is not in the consensus \"Mind Brain Identity\" camp, it has to point out that it agrees with those doctrines.  So you could, similarly, point out that you agree with the doctrines in, say Material Property Dualism, so we could count you there, the way we count Representational Functionalism as Mind Brain Identity theorists, even though they aren\'t in the consensus Property Dualism Mind Brain Identity camp.  I\'m betting their non consensus camp is also on the way out - but we shall see, I could be \'proven\' wrong.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-06-07 03:44:58','2012-06-07 03:44:58'),(1873,96,48,'James,\r\n\r\nI know this isn\'t the place, but I felt the need. I slept on it, and a rebuttal came to me. \r\n\r\nWell firstly, your argument against the blind man thought experiment is very good, and it tells me that that isn\'t a good poster boy for explaining my kind of qualia. As I see it, you have identified a general inability for the brain to convert physical models in to sensory models - and that is an interesting point in its own right. \r\n\r\nBut there still remains some dualism. Because your whole project as soon as you reject solipsism becomes to accept the validity of your physical models, and whether it is a limitation of the brain or not, thus far no *physical model* has been able to successfully model qualitative experience. Whether or not it is a property of the brain, it is still a limit on what we can know, because qualia do exist (at least to me), and if you suppose that your physical model is fully reliable, then there does exist an explanatory gap. No matter what, you are physically modelling physical processes, and you can\'t escape aspect dualism when it comes to qualia, because at the end of the day you are always saying that the qualia are a *property* of the neuronal events you model, that is, a subjective property. \r\n\r\nAs long as you implicitly accept physical models as revealing some truths about the world, you\'re always going to have a hard to accommodating something subjective, because subjectivity is by definition not objective. \r\n\r\nSorry, I haven\'t done a PhD or even a bachelors yet, so I\'m not as good as others here at expressing my ideas - I\'m just trying to contribute to the flow of ideas, so don\'t take me to be dissing.\r\n\r\nJordan T','2012-06-07 11:50:19','2012-06-07 11:50:19'),(1876,96,48,'Comment to James:\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nAs long as you implicitly accept physical models as revealing some\r\ntruths about the world, you\'re always going to have a hard to\r\naccommodating something subjective, because subjectivity is by\r\ndefinition not objective.\r\n\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nQuite to the contrary! You have the whole thing backwards!\r\n\r\nSubjective conscious experience is the *ONLY* thing we can ever really know. It is objective external reality which is forever hidden from our direct view, you are always going to have a hard time accomodating something *objective* when all you have available to you is subjective experience.  It is the goal of the enterprise of Science to discover the real truth behind objective reality, even though we view it indirectly, through subjective experience.\r\n\r\nRead Chapter 1 of this book to discover an epistemology founded on subjective experience, the world formulated upside-down and backwards to your understanding of it.\r\n\r\nThe Boundaries of Human Knowledge\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/book2/Boundaries.html\r\n','2012-06-07 12:18:46','2012-06-07 12:18:46'),(1879,96,48,'Don\'t get me wrong Mr. Lehar, I completely agree with you. My point is that *because* of what you are saying, any model which assumes a \'physics first\' rather than \'qualia first\' picture of the world, will absolutely have trouble when it comes to the subjective stuff.','2012-06-07 12:25:12','2012-06-07 12:25:12'),(1882,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\n\"You can exactly functionally program let X seem like it equals Y.\r\nThat\'s exactly what I\'d do with my robot, as he looked at the pencil,\r\nin a glass of water. He\'d notice his visual knowledge was \'bent\', and thereby know the pencil only \'seemed\' bent, to him, because it was in a glass of water. Using his higher cognitive functions, he\'d know the pencil is really not bent, and thereby only a seeming.\"\r\n\r\nSeeming isn\'t like that though. What you describe is a process of elimination based on a tree of successive True-False criteria. It doesn\'t seem like anything, it just adds up to have more of one pre-established category of \'True\' than \'False\'. At no point is there a \'Maybe\', just a computation that has not yet halted. That isn\'t what I mean by seeming. We can have an experience like \'That car honk seems like it is reminding me of something\' or \'He seems dishonest but I can\'t put my finger on why\'. It\'s teleological. Seeming projects a semantic whole onto incomplete fragments. Machines can\'t do that. They have to be told what to do in each case. \r\n\r\nWhat you are talking about assumes a privileged status of \'reality\' over a \'model\' rather than two data sets being imperfectly matched. If you tell the robot that the bent pencil is real then it will assume that the straight pencil only looks that way because it\'s sitting in air, instead of half in water like it\'s \'supposed to be\'.\r\n\r\nAre you familiar with Alexa Meade? She does these amazing anti-trompe l\'oeil presentations (http://alexameade.com/_img/portfolio_timmy1.jpg) which illustrate how, unlike trompe l\'oeil which fools the eye, the illusion is that the experience is figurative art and not literally real. The bent pencil seems bent in one sense, but no more than the straight pencil seems straight in another sense. \r\n\r\n\"Also, I don\'t see any problems at all with Representational Qualia\r\nTheory. It explains everything from out of body experiences,\r\nintentionality and everything, in a very functional and phenomenal way.\"\r\n\r\nIt doesn\'t explain anything to me. It just gives a magic a bunch of names, \'representation, emergent property, illusion, interpretation\'. Bah. Obviously if the brain doesn\'t look like a chocolate shake inside there has to be some way that one thing relates to the other. Calling it representation only points out the black box in between them and keeps shouting \'it\'s a box! it\'s a box!\'\r\n\r\n\"You indicated your issue was with representationalism, not qualia. If that is the case, then like Mike said, you are making extraordinary claims, going against such a significant expert consensus.\"\r\n\r\nThere is no expert consensus regarding consciousness. We have no idea how or why a neurochemical event seems to us like a chocolate milkshake, or why anything could, from a functional-mechanistic-literalist pespective \'seem like\' anything. For a million plus years before 2002, hominids have lived in a real world. The claims of a small group of (if I was being unkind) cloistered academicians in an intellectual echo chamber.\r\n\r\n\"10 years ago, and more, I\'d say representationalism wasn\'t in the consensus majority at all. \"\r\n\r\n10 years ago the consensus majority of TV shows wasn\'t fake reality TV. For a thousand years before Copernicus the consensus was Ptolemaic astronomy. \r\n\r\n\"But there is a significant expert consensus revolution taking place as most experts now considered any non representational theory of perception long since falsified and suffering from critical errors. So changing this would require significant evidence, not to mention support from other experts, before we can bring to pass a theoretical revolution that significant.\"\r\n\r\nWe are the evidence already. There will never be enough evidence to convince those who do not see it plainly and readily.\r\n\r\n\"It seems to me, the best thing for you to do is to start a competing camp, with Representational Qualia Theory, and get started at such? Like the \"Representational Functional Camp\" that is not in the consensus \"Mind Brain Identity\" camp, it has to point out that it agrees with those doctrines. So you could, similarly, point out that you agree with the doctrines in, say Material Property Dualism, so we could count you there, the way we count Representational Functionalism as Mind Brain Identity theorists, even though they aren\'t in the consensus Property Dualism Mind Brain Identity camp. I\'m betting their non consensus camp is also on the way out - but we shall see, I could be \'proven\' wrong. \"\r\n\r\nBecause of the way Canonizer is structured, I can only afford to have Multisense Realism show up at all to be seen \'from the street\' so to speak (and with it divided into the other camp under Ideal Monism, I don\'t even get a single vote on the main page).\r\n\r\nIf I could add another camp I would call it Presentational Qualia Theory.','2012-06-07 13:14:51','2012-06-07 13:14:51'),(1885,96,48,'omgpop said \'thus far no *physical model* has been able to successfully model\r\nqualitative experience\'\r\n\r\nAgreed. However, even humans cannot demonstrate that they have qualitative experiences. It is not fair to ask more of the machine than a human can do. A human might say \'I really just had a qualitative experience\', but it would be trivial to make a machine do the same:\r\n\r\nSystem.out.println(\'I really just had a qualitative experience.\');\r\n\r\nA human can only convince himself that he has ever had a qualitative experience. (Isn\'t that why we keep repeating that qualia is ineffable?) So, can a machine convince itself that it has had a qualitative experience? Well, that only depends on whether machines even have the ability to develop confidence or certainty or belief at all. If they do, then we can build a machine that is confident that it had a qualitative experiences. Perhaps we could make it even more confident that it had a qualitative experience than you are confident that you have qualitative experiences.\r\n\r\nYou might say \'I don\'t care if it is confident that it had a qualitative experience--I care whether it really really had a qualitative experience\'. What\'s the difference? Did you really have one, or are you just falsely confident that you had one? You don\'t even know. You are confident that you have them. My machine is confident that it has them. As far as I can tell, you and my machine are identical. As far as anyone can tell, you are identical.\r\n\r\nSo, can a machine have \'real\' confidence in something? Sure, they can do confidence even better than humans can. If you doubt that, try playing a gambling game against a well-designed computer program. You will find that it is able to compute exact probabilities that blow your fuzzy confidences out of the water.\r\n\r\nYou can keep repeating \'There is a difference\', and I can keep repeating \'Where is the difference?\'. Until someone identifies an actual difference, which has not yet happened, we\'re just waiting for one to be discovered. After enough searching, it certainly seems reasonable to at least suggest, \'maybe there is no difference\'. Saying \'the difference is in something magical that cannot be empirically tested\' is just dodging the issue.','2012-06-07 13:29:33','2012-06-07 13:29:33'),(1888,96,48,'I think the difference is quite clear, almost tautologically so - the difference is between what it means for a thing to be subjective, and what it means to be objective. The most you can do is construct a model which tries to make these two coexist, which the various dualisms attempt to do, or equate them, which monists do. I find that equation dubious however, since they are clearly polar opposites. \r\n\r\nBut no, I\'m not trying to say that you should get a robot to demonstrate that it has qualia. I can\'t demonstrate it, and neither can you or the robot - this is one of the routes to solipsism. But *I* know *I* have qualitative experience, and that is enough for me - the problem is, can I know (if I\'m about to upload my consciousness) with deductive certainty that the computer which will survive me will continue having my qualitative experience? I don\'t think so. \r\n\r\nTo even begin the (essentially inductivist) project of correlating physical states with qualitative ones, you have to assume first and foremost that the subjects do indeed have qualitative states. But as you just recognised, that\'s impossible. So you wont have learned anything. But even if you had, you wouldn\'t have done it in such a way as to give me a guarantee that a computational machine could continue my conscious experience. Even if you knew the exact neural correlates of conciousness and how to reproduce them, all you could guarantee is the creation of \'a\' consciousness, which would functionally be exactly the same as me, but with no way to know whether or not *my* experience of the world had died or persisted. \r\n\r\nOf course it wouldn\'t matter to you, or the robot, or anyone else, but to me - the whole point is for me to avoid the death of my consciousness, so it\'s a pretty major doubt.\r\n\r\nJordan T','2012-06-07 13:59:45','2012-06-07 13:59:45'),(1891,96,48,'Mike and Jordan,\r\n\r\nWe do have more to go on than just intellectual abstractions that compel us to yield the benefit of the doubt to machine consciousness. We have sense. \r\n\r\nMachines that have been created thus far are almost universally considered to be \'cold\', \'unfeeling\', and fundamentally different , opposite actually - from living organisms. Why does \'robotic\' and \'mechanical\' mean something different from \'wild\' or \'wise\'.\r\n\r\nThis is not proof on the level of intellectual-verbal logic, but it suggests that the matter bears closer consideration than just assuming there is no difference. We place considerable significance on the difference between being alive and dying, yet machines have no way to identify personally with that distinction. I have no reason to believe that all of our awareness does not stem from that distinction. All of our consciousness is a function of being a living body, not just a body capable of living in theory.\r\n\r\nJordan is talking about many of the points I have brought up here (but doing a better job of communicating it), about the continuity of consciousness being not necessarily transferable. Who we are may be a phenomenology of events in time which extends back to the Big Bang, and not just a local biochemical configuration or function of information processing.\r\n\r\nMachine sentience is also not completely unknowable given sufficiently advanced technology. If we can put a network cable into our brain and then shut off parts with TMS, then we can get an idea of whether we can change physical locations outside of our brain and then return. Copy the right hemisphere of the brain down to the quark onto a hard drive, shut off the hemisphere, see if you can walk yourself on to the hard drive, then shut off the left hemisphere, then walk yourself back... you could do it all magnetically and not even need implants or neurosurgery in theory. Lots of possibilities.','2012-06-07 14:50:38','2012-06-07 14:50:38'),(1894,96,48,'Regarding the notion of the Cartesian subjective/objective  split,  I think it is helpful to notice that these are not polar categories, but, in fact, all of the objective items and elements do have a particular subjective \"feel\", but that \"feel\", or dial reading, or measurement is repeatable.  Thus, all of what we\'re experiencing is various forms of repeatable subjectivity.    There is just the one category or spectrum.\r\n\r\nThus readers may recognize the strongly repeatable subjective artifacts and processes as being classically objective.  Then we have the stochastically repeatable and the rare to extremely rarely repeatable subjectivity.  \r\n\r\nThink about it.  I think you will discover this perspective and no other permits forward development.\r\n\r\nBest regards,\r\nRalph Frost\r\n\r\nWith joy you will draw water\r\nfrom the wells of salvation.  Isaiah 12:3\r\n\r\nhttp://structuredduality.blogspot.com\r\n\r\n','2012-06-07 14:57:59','2012-06-07 14:57:59'),(1897,96,48,'Craig, I think you solved it, sort of! If I were given the job of assuring Jordan that his uploaded consciousness would still \'be him\', I would not have very much to stand on. I could only assure him of my personal belief that if he behaves the same, then he must be the same in every way. If that is not enough for him, there is not much else I could do (except repeat myself a lot).\r\n\r\nBut your idea of doing it incrementally seems to solve this. If we slowly converted Jordan to a cyborg, one cell at-a-time (assuming the technology allowed for this), then he could see for himself (using the remaining biological portion of him brain) whether his subjective experiences were being diminished. He could then be the one to make the call about whether to proceed or revert, and would not need to rely on my belief that anything important would ultimately affect behavior.\r\n\r\nIt is too bad we are nowhere near ready to perform this experiment. I hate waiting for results.','2012-06-07 15:43:38','2012-06-07 15:43:38'),(1900,96,48,'Jordan T, (omgpop):\n\nyou are asking some GREAT questions. And don\'t worry about your education. A piece of paper with a PhD on it doesn\'t mean that much. (And I have one, and it still doesn\'t mean that much). What YOU know and understand is what matters. \n\nNow, your question, does my upload have my qualia. You say that we can\'t know that, but *I* say that we can.\n\nFor me the answer to this question (will my upload have my qualia) is quite simple. Answer the following questions: \n\n1. Does it have my behavior?\n2. Does it have my behavior FOR THE SAME REASONS. \n\nIf the answer to these two questions is yes, then it has my qualia. And I am sure that it does. Why? Because if it didn\'t, then the qualia that it doesn\'t have aren\'t up the causal chain of my behavior. THEREFORE they are epiphenomenal qualia, and I don\'t care about them anyway, and neither should you (see: http://lesswrong.com/lw/pn/zombies_the_movie/). \n\nI say \"I see red\" BECAUSE I see red. And I claim \"that experience was moving\" BECAUSE of the moving experience, in other words, because of the qualia. So whatever my subjective experience of seeing red is, however it happens, it MUST be somewhere up the causal chain of my statement \"I see red\". ANY qualia NOT up that causal chain, are qualia that I don\'t really remember, believe, and claim to have. How do I know this? Because belief has neural correlates... so if qualia CAUSES a belief that I have qualia, it has to move neurons around. Thus, the qualia that I believe that I have must be up the causal chain of whatever moved my neurons around. The same for memories, AND for claims. Anything not in the causal chain is epiphenomenal... and the causal chain in its entirety is simulatable on a computer. \n\nQualia are the experiences that I \"believe\" that I have, that I \"remember\" having had, and that I \"claim\" to have. THOSE are the qualia that I care about, and those are the qualia that I KNOW will be preserved if I preserve the causal chain. So I KNOW that my uploaded self will have my qualia, because it will have my causal chain. WHERE EVER qualia live, they MUST be in that chain somewhere. Since the chain is preserved, the qualia must be as well. \n\nQED','2012-06-07 19:18:57','2012-06-07 19:18:57'),(1901,116,44,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nI indicated earlier, that I had a question for Steven Lehar.  I finally got around to formulating and posting it.\r\n\r\nAs many of you know, James Carroll has been working on formulating what he believes will be a proof that does something like prove â€œproperty dualismâ€ is epiphenomenal.  James, is that the right way to say / formulate this issue we have?  Itâ€™s surprising how hard this is to even ask the right question, let alone provide some kind of proof / disproof.  Can you help out with concisely stating what it is you think you can prove?  How can my mind so clearly represent and understand so much about something that is so hard to state?\r\n\r\nJames has also been taunting me to provide one theoretical possibility to demonstrate that it is possible to have classic qualia, and for it not to be epiphenomenal.  How about this formulation?:\r\n\r\n* Is it in any way theoretically possible to have full ineffable classical qualia (i.e. implying there is an â€˜explanatory gapâ€™â€¦), as defined in Property Dualism, that is both not epiphinominal (i.e. it is objectively or causally detectible) and it also does not expand the known laws of causal physics.\r\n\r\nI have in my mind how something can fit all the above constraints, but since I donâ€™t know enough about neurons, gestalt, and wave theory, and such, Iâ€™m having troubles coming up with any specific theoretical example to prove it is possible, and enable James to stop working on his I believe to be futile effort to find his proof that it isnâ€™t possible.\r\n\r\nSo, thatâ€™s my question to you Steve.  Any idea how all the above constraints might be met, given what you know of neurons, wave theory, gestalt, and all that?\r\n\r\nSteve, basically, this is the question of what happens when we start replacing neurons, one at a time, with simulated equivalents/transducers?  Does qualia disappear or anything, as we switch back and forth between the real and simulated neurons?  Is it possible to do such, without loosing any quale experiences, as Chalmers argues is possible, in an at least \'hard\' way?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-08 21:23:15','2012-06-08 21:23:15'),(1904,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nWow, this tangent, unlike many of the other tangents in this thread, is very interesting.\r\n\r\nMike said:  \"I could only assure him of my personal belief that if he behaves the same, then he must be the same in every way. If that is not enough for him, there is not much else I could do (except repeat myself a lot).\"\r\n\r\nNOT MUCH ELSE WE COULD DO?  At least you mentioned one other possibility in \"incrementally uploading\".\r\n\r\nYou guys need to think a LOT more about the full implications of effing the ineffable, even merging conscious worlds, our spirits freely traversing between these phenomenal worlds, made of qualia  (can I simply say in these spiritual worlds, it works so much better!)  Have you guys red the [http://home.comcast.net/~brent.allsop/1229.htm#_Toc22030743 uploading chapter in the 1229 story] yet where some of these possibilities are explored in a fictional narrative of an upload?\r\n\r\nAre you guys still not stuck in the clueless,  primitive, don\'t understand effing mode?\r\n\r\nContinuity, like EVERYTHING else, is critically important to identity.  The more of all of it, the better, and there is no reason it all can\'t be achieved perfectly.\r\n\r\nWe all need to all realize and get a real vision of what a spiritual place the world will be like once we start effing the ineffable and usher in the millennium.  Disimbodies spirits freely traversing independent hugely expanding and far less lonely spirit worlds.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\nP.S.  James, you added a leading space to a paragraph in your last comment, which I removed.  That\'s why this page\'s formatting got messed up till I fixed it.  Leading spaces basically turn off all formatting, and wrapping, putting the entire paragraph on one non breaking line.  Leading spaced are primarily for quotes and stuff:\r\n\r\n  \"like this very\r\n  short quote.\"\r\n\r\nA good rule of thumb is to make sure you preview and look at the rendering, before actually submitting your post.  If it doesn\'t look right, edit it till it doesn\'t mess things up, before you actually submit it.\r\n\r\n','2012-06-09 00:34:33','2012-06-09 00:34:33'),(1907,96,48,'\r\nSo, back on the topic of this thread,\r\n\r\nMike what else is required to send a query to Dr. Dennett?  I\'m chomp\'n at the bit to find out what he thinks.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-09 00:59:59','2012-06-09 00:59:59'),(1910,96,48,'Regarding asking Dan Dennett, I don\'t have anything to ask. The more I tried to formulate a question, the more everything just cleared itself up. If you want to ask him a question, don\'t let me stop you. If you would like me to ask, then I guess I need to know what questions you have. The last discussion we had about it (before all these tangents) gave me the impression that he never really made the exact statements that we have been all worked up about, and I seem to agree with most of what I have heard him say in YouTube videos.\r\n\r\nRegarding effing the ineffable, it sounds like you are saying qualia is only currently ineffable, but with advances in technology it might become effable. Is that what you are saying? That was the reason I tried to give for not defining qualia in terms of its ineffability in the RQT camp statement, that I thought you disagreed with. I wonder how much else we agree on modulo terminology. I know there was once a big debate about the precise meaning of \'ineffable\'. So what was decided? Does the \'in-able\' part refer to \'now\', or \'ever\'?','2012-06-09 01:20:38','2012-06-09 01:20:38'),(1913,96,48,'Brent wrote \"You can exactly functionally program let X seem like it equals Y.\"\r\n\r\nWell, yes, but this is not the same use of the word \"seem\" as we\'ve been referring to in the it-only-seems-like-it claim. All you are doing in software is to relate one database object to another: the bent stick pattern is labelled with \"seems\" in relation to the unbent stick pattern. This enables the correct response to a database query but entails not one iota of quale.','2012-06-12 16:50:01','2012-06-12 16:50:01'),(1916,96,48,'Hi Richard,\r\n\r\nYou bring up a good point.  Iâ€™ve been working on another way to describe all this, along the lines youâ€™re talking about, so let me see if this way of thinking about it helps.\r\n\r\nAs you indicated, with computer knowledge, there is no phenomenal â€˜seemingâ€™, just abstract information which doesnâ€™t accurately represent its referent.  But the important fact is, you must have something that is the incorrect â€˜seemingâ€™, you canâ€™t just pretend it doesnâ€™t exist, or that it isnâ€™t needed, to have knowledge of any kind.\r\n\r\nMaterial Property Dualism predicts nature has both of the following real fundamental natures:\r\n\r\n* Fundamental Causal Properties.\r\n* Fundamental Phenomenal Qualities.\r\n\r\nCausal Properties include any properties like those the surface of a strawberry has, in that it causes light to reflect in a particular pattern and wavelength.  Phenomenal qualities are a categorically different fundamental nature, and include qualities such as redness or a red quale.\r\n\r\nWhen we consider abstracted information, like ones and zeros, we must realize that such isnâ€™t anything real.  Such is merely a label we apply to fundamental natures.  For example, a fundamental causal property like +5 volts can be given the abstracted label of â€˜oneâ€™.  Magnetic flux, of a particular orientation on a hard disk, can also be given the same abstracted label of one.  These abstracted ones and zeros donâ€™t exist anywhere in computers; they are just the abstracted symbols we are giving to the various fundamental things that are being interpreted as representing them, so we can better think about what is going on in a more abstracted or higher level way.\r\n\r\nIt is intuitive for us to tend to think of redness as this same kind of abstracted information.  We tend to label the surface of the strawberry as having redness; we tend to label 650 NM light as having a redness quality, and so on, just as we do when we think of abstracted ones and zeros in a computer.\r\n\r\nBut Material Property Dualism predicts this naÃ¯ve way of modeling fundamental natures is mistaken.  Redness is not some abstracted not real label we can simply apply to anything, no matter what its properties or qualities might be like.  Redness is fundamental and more real than voltages or magnetic flux.  A redness quality can be interpreted has having an abstract label, like one, or the abstracted word â€˜redâ€™, but such an abstracted label is not real, while a redness quality itself is at least as fundamentally real as any other fundamental causal property.\r\n\r\nJames is arguing that what Dr. Dennett really means, when he says we donâ€™t have fundamental phenomenal qualities, â€œit just seems like we do.â€ Is really something more like â€œwe are mistaken to think the knowledge we do have is anything more than this kind of abstracted informationâ€.  But of course Material Property Dualism is predicting that both of these naÃ¯ve versions are very wrong.  One just slightly less so obviously wrong than the other.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-06-12 23:37:28','2012-06-12 23:37:28'),(1919,96,48,'\r\nHi Mike,\r\n\r\nI still like the original version I proposed sending to Dr. Dennett in the [http://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/32/1#1 first post to this thread].  It\'d probably good to provide a URL to this thread, especially my post before this one, in case he wants to get up to speed on everything we\'ve discussed, before he attempts to respond?\r\n\r\nLet me know if you\'re not interested in sending such a letter, and I\'ll attempt to send it.\r\n\r\nMy prediction is that he\'ll start to realize his mistake, and like most other people, lose interest in attempting to think about it enough to respond.  But it would be fantastic to get more from him than that.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2012-06-13 03:15:40','2012-06-13 03:15:40'),(1922,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nAlthough we have worked on this for a long time, I have never yet been able to figure out the intended meaning of this sentence:\r\n\r\n    \'if you know something, there must be something that is this knowledge\'\r\n\r\nThe rest of your question refers back to this sentence, so its incomprehensibility renders the entire question incomprehensible. Because I cannot understand it, I cannot determine whether or not I agree with the question. I am also skeptical that the \'growing consensus\' to which you refer consists of people who understand what they are agreeing with. If we send Dr. Dennet this question, I would expect his response to be some form of:\r\n\r\n    \'Wha?\'.\r\n\r\nThis time, you have added the clause:\r\n\r\n    \', or there must be something that is or has this phenomenal seeming\'\r\n\r\nbut that just isn\'t any clearer to me. Perhaps, Dr. Dennett will be able to understand the intended meaning of your question because of his familiarity with the communication styles of philosopher types. If he is a technical person like me, however, I predict he will just get all tangled up in the technical problems with that expression. I am confident that whatever you are trying to ask can be worded more clearly. Is the intended meaning of this question clear to anyone else out there? If it is, then I will bow out and leave that person to help revise the wording.\r\n\r\nmike\r\n','2012-06-13 15:12:57','2012-06-13 15:12:57'),(1925,96,48,'no, it\'s still not clear at all. At least not to me. \r\n\r\nFurthermore, Brent thinks that he will realize his obvious mistake, but if his mistake is so obvious, then why haven\'t *I* been convinced of his mistake? I still think that he is right after all. ','2012-06-13 16:27:24','2012-06-13 16:27:24'),(1928,96,48,'In a good-faith attempt to be helpful, I will try to be very specific about what confuses me. Here is what it literally sounds like you are saying when I read your question:\n\nShannon\'s information theory states that abstract information cannot exist without a physical representation. Brains process information. One example of brains processing information is when we have an experience that seems real. It follows that humans must have physical brains, not just abstract ones. We theorize that if we cut open someone\'s skull, we will find a real physical brain, except perhaps in the case of Dr. Dennett.\n\nOf course, I know that is not what you meant. So, here is what I (currently) honestly think you are trying to say:\n\nShannon\'s information theory states that abstract information cannot exist without a physical representation. We take it for granted that whenever a phenomenal experience seems to be real, information has been processed by a brain. It follows that brains must use something physical to represent phenomenal experiences. We call this \'phenomenal information\'.\n\nHere is a list of unacceptable flying leaps that I made in the preceding paragraph. (I acknowledge that this is a straw-man attack, so I will refer to the flying leaps as my own, rather than as yours.)\n\n# The relationship between abstract information and experiences-that-seem-real is not obvious. If I take this relationship for granted, without giving additional explanation, I have lost my reader already.\n# I did not explain why abstract information is insufficient to represent phenomenal-experiences-that-seem-real. Without such an explanation, there is no need to suppose that phenomenal information is needed. This would be a significant oversight when addressing Daniel Dennett, because he believes that abstract information is sufficient to represent experiences-that-seem-real.\n# I falsely assumed that phenomenal information is also subject to Shannon\'s information theory. Shannon\'s information theory only characterizes abstract information. If abstract information is not sufficient to represent experiences-that-seem-real, and phenomenal information is sufficient to represent experiences-that-seem-real, then it follows that abstract information and phenomenal information have different properties. It is a fallacy, therefore, to use Shannon\'s information theory to conclude that phenomenal information requires a physical representation.\n\nHere is what I derive from Shannon\'s information theory about consciousness. Perhaps you could morph this fit with your philosophy, or else try to articulate precisely where are philosophies diverge:\n\nShannon\'s information theory states that abstract information cannot exist without a physical representation. Neuroscientists use the term \'neural correlate\' to refer to the physical representation of the information in our brains. By definition, a neural correlate is sufficient to represent everything that the brain knows or thinks to be true or real. All beliefs, therefore, can be explained by a neural correlate. Although phenomenal experiences seem real, no quantifiable evidence has ever been found to suggest that phenomenal experiences are more than a belief. Therefore, electrostatic signals, synaptic potentials, and various chemicals are probably sufficient to constitute a neural correlate. Since all such things can be simulated, it follows that beliefs (including the belief that some specific phenomenal experience was real) consist of nothing more than abstract information represented by a neural correlate. It also follows that the reason qualia are so difficult to express (a.k.a. the quale interpretation problem) is because qualia are imaginary.\n\n','2012-06-13 18:24:15','2012-06-13 18:24:15'),(1931,96,48,'Reply to Mike Gashler:\r\n\r\nIn a good faith attempt to be helpful, let me try to explain.\r\n\r\nThere is one central sticking point that causes confusion on this issue that some people just don\'t \"get\" no matter how many times it is explained.\r\n\r\nThe relationship between abstract information and experiences-that-seem-real is *perfectly* obvious once you acknowledge that the red bulgy thing that you take to be the strawberry, is not the strawberry itself, but is a replica of the strawberry in your brain. The real strawberry is out in the world beyond possible experience.\r\n\r\nIn information-theoretic terms, it does not even matter whether the strawberry actually exists, your experience can be a dream or hallucination of a strawberry, and the information content of that experienced strawberry is expressed as the red bulgy patch in your experience.\r\n\r\nThis is analogous to viewing a strawberry indirectly, on a television monitor connected to a remote camera in front of the strawberry. The information content of that strawberry is a red patch on the screen shaped like a 2-D projection of a strawberry.\r\n\r\nDennetts objection is that there is no red bulgy thing in your experience, that red bulgy thing is the strawberry itself, and my experience of that strawberry is an abstract thought such as \"there\'s a strawberry!\".  Its as if Dennet were objecting that there is no red patch on the screen because he believes the screen to be an open window providing a direct view of the strawberry itself, so he believes the redness is a property of its surface, not of the glowing pixels on the TV monitor.\r\n\r\nThat is why Dennett complains that there is no such thing as experience as such, the qualia are merely a property of the object itself, viewed directly where it lies out in the world.\r\n\r\nOnce you recognize that the television picture is a replica of the strawberry, you can distinguish between the redness on the screen, and the redness of the original strawberry that it attempts to duplicate in effigy.\r\n\r\nAnd likewise, taking another step backwards, once you realize that the red bulgy thing that looks so much like a strawberry, is a patch of red \"experience\" inside your brain, which is distinct from the strawberry itself, which you cannot see directly, and which may or may not actually exist.\r\n\r\nThe information of experience is expressed as modulations of the qualia across space and time, i.e. where you see the strawberry, your brain has painted a red quale in the shape of a strawberry, and the abstract information \"there\'s a strawberry!\" is separate and distinct from the red bulgy thing that you may or may not recognize as a strawberry.\r\n\r\nSome people will never understand this explanation because like Dennett, they believe their experience of the world to be direct, and that is the source of the whole confusion.\r\n\r\nIf you are really interested in understanding this issue (as opposed to Dennett, who has already made up his mind and refuses to consider the alternative because it seems to him so patently absurd that it is not even a serious proposition to be considered and rejected!) read this chapter:\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/book/chap1.html\r\n\r\nor read this quick illustrated summary\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/epist/epist.html\r\n\r\nor you can read the debate in cartoon form here:\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/cartoonepist/cartoonepist.html\r\n\r\n  Steve Lehar\r\n\r\n','2012-06-13 20:28:27','2012-06-13 20:28:27'),(1934,96,48,'@Steve Lehar:\r\n\r\nThanks for the thoughtful and clear response. \r\n\r\nFrom what I have heard of Dennett\'s argument, he isn\'t opposed to representationalism, nor is he a naieve realist as you paint him. On the contrary, he seems (pun intended) to admit that we don\'t experience reality directly in his many optical illusion examples that he uses. Instead, he seems to think that we experience our models of reality, and that our models are often wrong... therefore, he thinks that we don\'t really have any qualia/experience BEYOND the structure and dynamics of physics, it just SEEMS like we do. \r\n\r\nWhether or not that is what Dennett believes it is what I believe. So all your arguments for experiencing something other than the real strawberry aren\'t something that I disagree with (and I THINK that Dennett wouldn\'t either, but I don\'t want to speak for him). \r\n\r\nIn any event, it is property dualism that I reject as epiphenomenal, because I believe that our experience must live up the causal chain of our behavior, and therefore, must be reductionally explainable by nothing more than the structure and dynamics of physics. Anything \"more\" than the structure and dynamics of physics would of necessity be \"other\" than the structure and dynamics of physics, in order to be \"more\". And the result of that is epiphenomenalism, which is a non-starter for me. \r\n\r\nI recognize that my experiences don\'t SEEM to be reducible to the structure and dynamics of physics, but I argue that there is a lot about our experience that doesn\'t match reality (Dennett\'s optical illusions being an example). \r\n\r\nOur experiences are as we experience them tautologically, but they may not correspond to reality (as you have admitted I believe).','2012-06-13 20:51:43','2012-06-13 20:51:43'),(1937,96,48,'Steve,\r\n\r\nYou have done a great job of describing representationalism, which I accept and believe. I completely agree that we only experience our representations, and cannot experience the world directly. If I ever implied anything to the contrary, it was unintentional. You have accused Daniel Dennett of rejecting representationalism. I did not know he rejected representationalism. If that is true, then I disagree with him.\r\n\r\nmike','2012-06-13 21:03:27','2012-06-13 21:03:27'),(1940,96,48,'Reply to Mike Gashler:\n\nIf you agree with representationalism, do you still have trouble with information theory? The qualia are the carriers of the information of experience, and that information is expressed as the modulations of that carrier. Is that at least clear now?\n\nThis is why qualia are defined as \'ineffable\'. By analogy with a computer, the computer \"knows\" the value of a number stored as \"x = 5\", for example, but there is no way for the computer to tell me whether that value \"5\" is stored internally as a voltage in a memory register, magnetic domains on a tape or disk drive, optical pits on a DVD, or holes in a punch card. The information itself is perfectly \"effable\" from one machine to the next. What remains \"ineffable\" is the carrier itself, whose modulations express that stored information.\n\nDennett\'s interpretation of the many illusions he cites is the opposite to a representationalist interpretation. His argument is that our experience, which appears as a surrounding 3-D \"picture\" of reality, is an illusion, it only \"seems\" as if its a 3-D \"picture\", in reality it is merely a sequence of glimpses and impressions as we glance around the scene, and there is no actual \"picture\" anywhere in the brain. If you can examine the world around you and NOT see it as a 3-D \"picture\" then Dennett\'s argument is plausible. But I see a 3-D world in my experience, and I don\'t just \"seem\" to see it, I see it with such clarity and certainty that it is hard not to be fooled by the Grand Illusion and believe it to be the world itself.\n\nIn Ned Block\'s book \"Imagery\" Dennett\'s Chapter 4 is devoted to refuting the notion of mental imagery as actual \"pictures in the brain\" as follows:\n\n(quote taken from my rebuttal to reviewers\' objections here\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubw2/rebut2-2.html\nscroll down to point 14)\n\n>>>>\n\nChapter 4 is written again by Daniel Dennett. This time he \"defeats\" the notion of mental imagery by constructing a fanciful analogy. He asks the reader to imagine that anthropologists have discovered a native tribe that believes in a hitherto unheard-of God of the forest, named \"Feenoman\" (this will stand in for the supposedly fictitious \"phenomenal experience\" whose existence Dennett so forcefully denies). Some of the anthropologists begin to believe in Feenoman as an objectively real deity (the \"Feenomanists\"), while others retain their scientific rigor, and study the native religion while remaining agnostic themselves (the \"Feenomanologists\"). On page 102 Dennett concludes that:\n\n    \"Phenomenal space is Mental Image Heaven ... [mental images] can reside,\n    with Santa Claus, in the logical space of fiction.\"\n\nBut analogies only work when the analogy is analogous. In this case nobody has ever actually seen Feenoman, and therefore it is reasonable to question His existence. The phenomenal world on the other hand is right before our eyes, if only we can recognize it for what it is. Dennett\'s argument works better against mental imagery than perception, because it is easier to deny the existence of those...\n\n    \"...entirely mythical species of mental images: the various non-physical,\n    phenomenal or epiphenomenal, self-intimating, transparent to cognition,\n    unmisapprehensible, pseudo-extended, quasi-imagistic phantasms that\n    have often been presented as mental images in the past.\" (page 104)\n\nHowever this argument does not work so well against perception. For to deny a spatial representation in the brain is to deny the vivid spatial structure so plainly evident in the world we see around us. \n\n<<<<','2012-06-13 21:26:42','2012-06-13 21:26:42'),(1943,96,48,'To sum up representationalism I would say this:\r\n\r\nEverything you have ever known to be real is only an arbitrary make-believe system.\r\n\r\nEverything that is real is something that you will never possibly have any experience of.\r\n\r\nThe exception is this idea of representationalism, which somehow is not make believe but reflects the real reality.','2012-06-13 22:00:16','2012-06-13 22:00:16'),(1946,96,48,'Not to be nitpicky, but are you sure that Shannon\'s Theory says that information has to be physical?\r\n\r\nhttp://cm.bell-labs.com/cm/ms/what/shannonday/shannon1948.pdf\r\n\r\nFrom what I can tell, he makes no hard assertion of physicality, and to the contrary tends to specify \'physical or conceptual entities\' or \'stochastic processes\' which can be \"A physical system, or a mathematical model of a system which produces such a sequence of symbols governed by a set of probabilities...\"\r\n\r\nHe does mention that physical correlates to information, but not in a way that suggests that it cannot \'exist\' them, as far as I can tell. It seems to me that Shannon\'s work in general is misapplied as a theory of metaphysics or consciousness. I\'m no expert but my exposure so far gives me the impression that Shannon is only trying to pragmatically analyze efficiency in information compression.\r\n\r\nThere seems to be a lot of confusion as well resulting from Shannon\'s use of the term entropy, which I maintain is closer to the inverse of thermodynamic entropy than a synonym for it. Shannon entropy is the dissipation of information processing efficiency in the context of data compression, not a general property that equates to materials involved. If information is highly compressible, ie, 10,000 zeros in a row, then it has a very low Shannon entropy - it is easy to compress and not a lot of *extra* information needs to be added on top of the text to allow the text to be reconstituted. This is the opposite of thermodynamic entropy, in which a box of half hot coals and half ice cubes has lower entropy than that same box when it has reached equilibrium as warm coal mud.\r\n\r\nThen we throw in QM and get a different idea of information...it\'s kind of a mess, and I think it takes us away from the more relevant issue of information\'s relation to consciousness and consciousness\'s relation to physics. When you put a subject in the mix, there is a body of semiotic work to approach it with - semantics, syntactics, and pragmatics. Trying to link \'information\' with physics directly I think destroys any possibility of understanding awareness. It is like trying to build a car out of exhaust.','2012-06-13 22:01:30','2012-06-13 22:01:30'),(1949,96,48,'\"This is the opposite of thermodynamic entropy, in which a box of half hot coals and half ice cubes has lower entropy than that same box when it has reached equilibrium as warm coal mud.\"\r\n\r\nHow is it opposite? Both have to do with a measure of \"uncertainty\" and there are tantalizing hints in physics that hint at informational entropy and thermodynamical entropy being actually the same thing (or at least tightly connected). For a popular account of some of these ideas, see Sean Carroll\'s book, \"From Eternity to Here, the Quest for the Ultimate Theory of Time\". For a more mathematical look at information theory, see Cover and Thomas \"Elements of Information Theory.\" \r\n\r\nWhile it is true that Shannon\'s papers don\'t indicate in and of themselves that information MUST have a physical instantiation to carry the information, that IS an (unproven, but almost universally accepted) conjecture of computer science\'s take on information theory. ','2012-06-13 22:21:52','2012-06-13 22:21:52'),(1952,96,48,'> \"How is it opposite?\"\r\n\r\nThat\'s what I was explaining. Shannon entropy sees uniformity and equilibrium as a low entropy state, and physics entropy sees uniformity and equilibrium as the high energy state.\r\n\r\nIt\'s not obvious to me that either of them relate to uncertainty. Shannon entropy would not change based on the degree of certainty that any particular observer/receiver of information and physics need to calculate how much work it will take to fight the tendency toward equilibrium doesn\'t seem to hinge on certainty or uncertainty either.\r\n\r\nI understand that the unity of physical and informational unity is a popular conjecture, and I agree \'tantalizing hints\' is a good way to describe it, but again, I am not persuaded at all. That isn\'t to say that information isn\'t indirectly physical, it\'s just that I think it is clearly a mistake to say that it can be physical independently of awareness or sense of some kind.\r\n\r\nSure, I agree that information must have a physical substrate, but only because physics is a process and all process can only occur through awareness. Time arises out of a continuity of awareness rooted in memory, and all process necessarily supervenes on temporal sequence.','2012-06-13 23:08:59','2012-06-13 23:08:59'),(1955,96,48,'I don\'t see any real distinction between gradual versus instantaneous consciousness uploading. I believe that the most sound materialist conception of conscious experience is property dualism (and all property dualisms entail epiphenomena). So it seems, under this model, what would happen with a gradual upload is that you would gradually lose qualitative experience, but since your brain is physical, it wouldn\'t actually notice. Of course that\'s absurd. The whole notion of property dualism is absurd. \r\n\r\nBut it\'s the only materialist theory that close to makes sense. James talks about our idea of qualia arising because different parts of the brain are responsible for different types of processing, and we\'re trying to understand one in terms of the other. Fair enough. So let\'s break it down. \r\n\r\nOne proposes a material, physical computational machine such as the brain, which is capable of receiving dynamic inputs which inform it in its own language about the world - it then responds to the information appropriately, all in a pretty deterministic framework. (I\'m no neuroscientist and maybe some of you are, but this is accurate, no?). \r\n\r\nNow, if you are a materialist, that is pretty much how you\'ve got to model the brain. It doesn\'t matter that you are forming that conception in one part of your brain, and doing the experiencing in the other - the fact is, if you\'re a materialist you have got to have real belief in your model. The model you have is an objective one. Qualitative experience doesn\'t fit in with that model, and it\'s nothing to do with brain areas or what have you. The very act of making and understanding a physical model has a qualitative aspect, and is anyone going to tell me that I\'m experiencing that model in a different part of the brain from the one I\'m making it in? Hello infinite regress.\r\n\r\nNo matter what you say, as long as you\'re only explaining qualia in terms of its physical neural correlates, you\'ve always got to state (implicitly or explicitly) that qualia are a *property* of those correlates, and that is exactly what property dualism is.','2012-06-13 23:11:53','2012-06-13 23:11:53'),(1958,96,48,'@Multisense, you wrote: \"That\'s what I was explaining. Shannon entropy sees uniformity and equilibrium as a low entropy state, and physics entropy sees uniformity and equilibrium as the high energy state.\"\r\n\r\nThis misunderstands what is going on here I think. \r\n\r\nLet\'s start with entropy from physics. Boltzman\'s definition of entropy is \"Entropy is a measure of the number of particular microscopic arrangements of atoms that appear indistinguishable from a macroscopic perspective.\" In other words, it involves our \"uncertainty\" with regard to the potential arrangements of atoms given our macroscopic measurement. In Gibbs\' formulation, entropy is explicitly a measure of what we know. \"We could choose to think of entropy as characterizing what we know about the state. In the Boltzmann way of thinking about entropy, the knowledge of which macrostate we are in tells us less and less about the microstate as entropy increases; the Gibbs approach inverts this perspective and defines entropy in terms of how much we know. Instead of starting with a course-graining on the space of states, we start with a probability distribution; the percentage chance, for each possible microstate, that the system is actually in that microstate right now. Then Gibbs gives us a formula, analogous to Boltzmann\'s, for calculating the entropy associated with that probability distribution.\" Coarse-graining never comes into the game.\" (Sean Carroll \"From Eternity to Here\" p. 170.) Incidentally, his formula just happens to be identical to Shannon\'s formula. \r\n\r\n\"Shannon entropy would not change based on the degree of certainty that any particular observer/receiver of information\"\r\n\r\nActually it does. The formulas are identical, and informational entropy IS a measure of uncertainty. To see how this relates to compression, understand, if I can predict the value of the bits in an information stream, then I can encode it such that the more common values have the shortest encoding length, and the less common values have the longer encoding lengths (I can do far better than that actually, but this will give you the intuitive connection between entropy, uncertainty, and compressability). It turns out that the compressability of a data stream is related to your uncertainty about the values of the data stream in a manner related to the formula we call \"entropy\". (To understand this mathematically, read Cover and Thomas\'s \"Elements of Information Theory\"). \r\n\r\nNote here that in both cases, the entropy is a measure of \"uncertainty\", and that the formula for that uncertainty is naturally the same. Now take a look at Jaynes book Probability Theory, the Logic of Science (available online here: http://omega.albany.edu:8008/JaynesBook.html). He shows that entropy is the only measure of uncertainty that is consistent, and that matches a set of \"common sense\" axioms. He actually derives Shannon entropy FROM these axioms. \r\n\r\nIf you add to that what Hawking radiation says about entropy, information, and black holes, and add the holographic principle, and then add the Maxwell\'s demon thought experiment, where we learn that information carries energy (which solves the Maxwell\'s demon paradox), and if you assume that E=mc^2, then WALLA, you realize that information is quite closely tied to what we call \"matter\" and \"energy\" in a rather tight fashion. It does indeed appear that it is impossible for information to be carried without there being energy and/or mass associated with the information.\r\n\r\nIn other words, there appears to be no such thing as immaterial information. \r\n\r\nAnd we can go one step further: \"[Because of] digital communication in the last 25 or 30 years, physicists, many physicists, especially those dealing with quantum mechanics and cosmology, have come to believe that the universe itself is actually made out of information, and that every object in the universe, including you and me, every object is made out of information, and the interaction of the information within our bodies, and the interaction of the information exchanged between our bodies and the world actually explains who we are, and what we are, and what we are capable of doing.\" \r\n(Professor Terrell Ward Bynum, Director, Research Center on Computing and Society, Southern Connecticut State University).  http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded&v=pMh8oBdKkK4#!','2012-06-14 00:08:44','2012-06-14 00:08:44'),(1961,96,48,'@jcarroll Let\'s put this in common sense terms.\r\n\r\nThere is no measure of particular microscopic arrangements of atoms that applies to the McDonalds logo. The McDonalds logo is information, and it can exist in any visual medium on any scale or number of atoms.\r\n\r\nGolden arches built out of titanium steel allow 500 feet tall are going to require much more physical work to make indistinguishable from the macroscopic view of it\'s context than would a small drawing made with colored pencil.\r\n\r\nShannon entropy says to me that the description of the golden arches logo - at any size or material composition, can be mathematically compressed as a single parabola repeated, a color value, and some other custom details. Since the vector-based compression would be faster and less resource intensive than say a bitmap of the whole logo, the vector compression has lower entropy - less drag on the process.\r\n\r\nI don\'t think that there can be any distinction between microcosmic and macrocosmic levels of description in the context of claiming an objective property. If you mean uncertainty, then why say entropy? We may be unable to distinguish the differences between atomic states but that doesn\'t imply that we are uncertain. To the contrary, we are certain that there is no distinction at the macrocosmic level. If microcosmic differences were to enter into the macrocosm, it would be noise.\r\n\r\nBoltzmann\'s ideas are interesting, but I see them as related to the transition between levels, or what I am calling castes of perceptual relativity. Entropy in the Boltzmann sense seems to refer to the loss of perceptual integrity when the range of observable castes of the object moves further to the periphery of the subject\'s detectable range of castes, so that there is less overlap.\r\n\r\nI posted an idea today about this, and how it relates to qualia and quanta: http://s33light.org/post/25044974260\r\n\r\nI appreciate your taking the time to try to educate me on the current state of information theory. It is interesting for me to learn about it, but I feel that my ideas (and I recognize exactly how deluded this sounds) pick up where our current popular theories leave off - only I am not building my ideas from the present and moving forward, I am stabbing at the future and working my way back, and (again not to sound like the very stereotype of crackpot) I think it\'s working. I don\'t have the skills to tie up all of the connections with every intellectual school in existence, but I am confident that those who really understand the core principles of my ideas will be able to if they choose to make the effort.\r\n\r\n\"The formulas are identical, and informational entropy\r\nIS a measure of uncertainty\"\r\n\r\nIf I close my eyes, I become uncertain of the optical environment outside of my head, yes? What entropy is increased for other people in the room?\r\n\r\nIn physical entropy, if an ice cube melts, it melts for everyone who experiences it. Opening your eyes doesn\'t make the ice melt slower.\r\n\r\nI feel like contemporary informaiton theory is wayyy too navel gazing and has lost all contact with the realities of either physics or consciousness. It is a purely syntactic echo chamber that is approaching angels-on-the-head-of-a-pin levels of esoterica. It\'s great for computation, but just as \"the knowledge of which macrostate we are in tells us less and less about the microstate as entropy increases\", it is clear to me that the more knowledge of which information process we are using, the less and less we know about the semantic reality which those processes pertain to.\r\n\r\nAs for uncertainty and compression, I can see, for example how there is a tradeoff between UDP and TCP protocols, with the former being a broadcast protocol that is cheap and buggy but useful where you have large data streams that can tolerate a lot of missing bits, and the latter having transmission control and error correction. This inversely related quantity vs quality principle I think ties into my \'full spectrum\' information theory, but to say that entropy is strictly tied to uncertainty I think is a bias of computation and not experience. For a human mind, uncertainty can be a teleological attractor, a problem to solve, or a hunch to explore...the opposite of entropy and surrender to the forces of inevitable decay.\r\n\r\nI agree with you completely that there is no such thing as immaterial information, because I don\'t think there is any such thing as information at all. It is a way of undertstanding common sense on a low caste, and therefore horizontally pervasive level. From that level however, no higher caste experience can be reconstituted without that higher caste encoding the text to begin with. Low level carriers of information would never evolve vertically to higher castes on their own. The universe is not information. Oak trees do not grow out of acorn shadows.','2012-06-14 01:36:22','2012-06-14 01:36:22'),(1964,96,48,'Reply to Steve Lehar,\r\n\r\n> If you agree with representationalism, do you still have trouble with information theory? \r\n\r\nI have no trouble with information theory. I have only struggled to understand what Brent was trying to show with information theory.\r\n\r\n> The qualia are the carriers of the information of experience, and that information is expressed as the modulations of that carrier. Is that at least clear now?\r\n\r\nThis is a new idea for me. Is this the same camp as Brent, or is it a different camp? Anyway, this is independent of the notion that we experience our representations. While I believe that we experience our representations, I do not believe that our representations are encoded in modulations of something phenomenal. I believe they are encoded in modulations of something material. Specifically, I believe they are encoded in electrical spikes and synaptic potentials. So, I am a representationalist, but not a dualist.\r\n\r\n> This is why qualia are defined as \'ineffable\'. By analogy with a computer...\r\n\r\nGreat analogy. Now I understand why you believe qualia are inherently ineffable.\r\n\r\n> Dennett\'s interpretation of the many illusions he cites is the opposite to a representationalist interpretation...\r\n\r\nI see that Dennett does indeed argue against what he calls \'picture-in-the-head theories\'. His primary argument against these is to ask the question, \'who is watching the picture in the head?\' He says that picture-in-the-head theories reduce to the absurd suggestion that there is a conscious homunculus in our heads giving us consciousness. I do not see any evidence that he thinks we lack a model of the world in our heads, but he definitely does argue that a model is not sufficient to explain consciousness. In that respect, I think he makes a correct point. In addition to a model, our brains must also have the ability to query the model and respond to it.\r\n\r\nMike','2012-06-14 02:53:59','2012-06-14 02:53:59'),(1967,96,48,'Reply to Mike Gashler\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nWhile I believe that we experience our representations, I do not believe that our representations are encoded in modulations of something phenomenal. I believe they are encoded in modulations of something material. Specifically, I believe they are encoded in electrical spikes and synaptic potentials. So, I am a representationalist, but not a dualist.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nThen we agree on the central issues, epistemological dualism (our knowledge of the world is indirect, mediated by a representation) but ontological monism (the world of experience is one and the same as certain physical processes in the physical brain). That is indeed the most reasonable hypothesis given the facts.\r\n\r\nOur representations *ARE* encoded by the modulations of something phenomenal, its just that that phenomenal entity is one and the same as some physical process in the brain.\r\n\r\nBut now consider the implications: Do you see electrical spikes and synaptic potentials in your experience? I do see certain little sparkles and flashes, but generally, what I see is a spatial continuum containing solid objects bounded by colored surfaces, in what is clearly an *analogical* representation, an actual 3-D model, at least in my experience. \r\n\r\nThat in turn implicates a continuous spatially extended analogical representation in the brain. Whats the point of doing all this philosophy if you\'re not going to believe what it shows us? It show us that there is a three-dimensional real-time moving colored imaging mechanism in the brain, capable of generating images as rich and complex as the one you see around you now. THAT is the profound message that philosophy tells us about the brain, and it is high time that neuroscientists begin to LOOK for that imaging mechanism in the brain that we know for a FACT to be in there!\r\n\r\nIf you take the implications of this philosophy seriously, you will propose neurophysiological theories like THIS one:\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/ConstructiveAspect/ConstructiveAspect.html\r\n\r\nor THIS one:\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/HRezBook/HRezBook.html\r\n\r\nThis is a rare case where philosophy can inform neuroscience, if only neuroscience is willing to listen! Trouble is they have their noses buried so deeply into neurons and synapses that they are missing the big picture!\r\n','2012-06-14 11:08:27','2012-06-14 11:08:27'),(1970,96,48,'Continuing response to Mike Gashler\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nI do not see any evidence that he thinks we lack a model of the world in our heads, but he definitely does argue that a model is not sufficient to explain consciousness. In that respect, I think he makes a correct point. In addition to a model, our brains must also have the ability to query the model and respond to it.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nAnyone familiar with modern neuroscience must be a representationalist at some level. Dennett\'s position is confused and conflicted because he is both a representationalist and a naive realist, like those people who believe in God, and in evolution at the same time. He argues very forcefully that what we see is the world itself, not an image of the world in our heads. But he refuses to debate the  issue, just as many believers in God feel uncomfortable having to defend that belief.\r\n\r\nYou and Dennett are right on one point though, that it is not sufficient of an explanation of consciousness that there is a model in your head, although that part is at least *necessary* (there MUST be a model in my head) even if not sufficient. There remains the profound question -- How does the model become conscious of its own structure? THAT is the \"magic\" that Dennett argues so forcefully against. \r\n\r\nBut that objection is not unique to representationalism, it is even more profoundly paradoxical that we should become conscious of objects and surfaces OUT IN THE WORLD, beyond the sensory surface! The existence of consciousness is a profound mystery for BOTH positions, but so is the existence of the universe, or the existence of matter and energy. Science simply moves on beyond such profound ontological questions, and gets busy with the question of HOW the brain does it, and we will have to be satisfied with that.\r\n\r\nIf you want to hear my own explanation of that profound issue of the ultimate nature of consciousness, you can read it here:\r\n\r\nThe Ultimate Question of Consciousness\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubw3/bubw3.html#ULTIMATE\r\n\r\nThat goes beyond mere representationalism, but if you give it serious thought, I believe that is the incredible conclusion toward which all the facts point.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-14 11:49:49','2012-06-14 11:49:49'),(1973,96,48,'Continuing response to Mike Gashler\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nI do not see any evidence that he thinks we lack a model of the world in our heads, but he definitely does argue that a model is not sufficient to explain consciousness. In that respect, I think he makes a correct point. In addition to a model, our brains must also have the ability to query the model and respond to it.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nAnyone familiar with modern neuroscience must be a representationalist at some level. Dennett\'s position is confused and conflicted because he is both a representationalist and a naive realist, like those people who believe in God, and in evolution at the same time. He argues very forcefully that what we see is the world itself, not an image of the world in our heads. But he refuses to debate the  issue, just as many believers in God feel uncomfortable having to defend that belief.\r\n\r\nYou and Dennett are right on one point though, that it is not sufficient of an explanation of consciousness that there is a model in your head, although that part is at least *necessary* (there MUST be a model in my head) even if not sufficient. There remains the profound question -- How does the model become conscious of its own structure? THAT is the \"magic\" that Dennett argues so forcefully against. \r\n\r\nBut that objection is not unique to representationalism, it is even more profoundly paradoxical that we should become conscious of objects and surfaces OUT IN THE WORLD, beyond the sensory surface! The existence of consciousness is a profound mystery for BOTH positions, but so is the existence of the universe, or the existence of matter and energy. Science simply moves on beyond such profound ontological questions, and gets busy with the question of HOW the brain does it, and we will have to be satisfied with that.\r\n\r\nIf you want to hear my own explanation of that profound issue of the ultimate nature of consciousness, you can read it here:\r\n\r\nThe Ultimate Question of Consciousness\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubw3/bubw3.html#ULTIMATE\r\n\r\nThat goes beyond mere representationalism, but if you give it serious thought, I believe that is the incredible conclusion toward which all the facts point.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-14 11:53:51','2012-06-14 11:53:51'),(1976,96,48,'Response to omgpop,\r\n\r\n> ...you\'ve always got to state (implicitly or explicitly) that qualia are a *property* of those correlates, and that is exactly what property dualism is.\r\n\r\nOkay, so can these \'properties\' be read by unconscious scientific instruments? Does property dualism take a stand on this question? If not, then what does it take a stand on?\r\n\r\n\r\nResponse to Steve Lehar,\r\n\r\n> Our representations *ARE* encoded by the modulations of something phenomenal\r\n\r\nCan unconscious scientific instruments read these modulations? If yes, then what does it mean to be called \'phenomenal\'? If no, then we have identified the precise point where our opinions differ, and I will then be interested to know the source of your certainty.','2012-06-14 13:29:46','2012-06-14 13:29:46'),(1979,96,48,'Reply to Mike Gashler\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nCan unconscious scientific instruments read these modulations? If yes, then what does it mean to be called \'phenomenal\'? If no, then we have identified the precise point where our opinions differ, and I will then be interested to know the source of your certainty.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nIf unconscious scientific instruments could NOT read the modulations of the medium or carrier of conscious experience in the brain, then that medium would be by definition beyond the bounds of science, like the immaterial spirits that some people claim to animate our bodies, which are by definition undetectable to scientific means, rendering that an extra-scientific or super-natural explanation.\r\n\r\nThe remarkable history of the success of science at explaining reality in purely physical terms gives me confidence that conscious too will eventually succumb to scientific explanation. I will be willing to accept a supernatural or extra-scientific explanation ONLY when all other possibilities have been exhausted.\r\n\r\nI believe the images in the brain are encoded by a phase sweeping system like analog television technology that transforms an image into a time-modulated signal, which is transmitted from camera to screen, where it is swept back out again as a spatial image. I propose that our micro-electrodes are picking up the time-varying signal, analogous to an oscilloscope trace of the TV signal, it remains for us to figure out how to read that signal as an image, and I believe in the future we will be able to sweep out a picture of what the animal under micro-electrodes is currently experiencing.\r\n\r\n>>> then what does it mean to be phenomenal? <<<\r\n\r\nWe are all trapped inside our own head, everything we think and experience is phenomenal, taking place within our heads. If someone planted electrodes in my visual cortex and viewed my experiences on a screen, mine would be the phenomenal experience, his would be a phenomenal experience of a screen that duplicated some aspects of my phenomenal experience as an image on the monitor.\r\n\r\nThe same would be true of a robot -- anything it could think or \'see\' must be expressed as patterns of states in its electronic \'brain\', and anyone who knew the encoding of those patterns could in principle tap in to them and \'read\' the information encoded in them.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-14 15:12:44','2012-06-14 15:12:44'),(1982,96,48,'reply to slehar\r\n\r\n\"I believe the images in the brain are encoded by a phase sweeping\r\nsystem like analog television technology that transforms an image into a time-modulated signal, which is transmitted from camera to screen, where it is swept back out again as a spatial image.\"\r\n\r\nThe problem is that images exist in the perception of the viewer and not in the pixels, screen or hsync sweeping of an electron gun. No people, no image on the screen. There is no information there. Try watching a TV show with your hands and nose rather than your eyes and ears.\r\n\r\nNo amount of representational formatting of objects can compensate for the lack of a genuine subjective presentation. There is nothing to format, just abstract quantitative measurement fragments with nothing to experience them in any particular way.','2012-06-14 16:31:58','2012-06-14 16:31:58'),(1985,96,48,'I don\'t speak for all property dualists, but Mike, as I see it - unconscious measurement devices would only ever be able to detect the presence of neural correlates, just as they currently do. Property dualism sees the qualitative aspect of experience to be a fundamental aspect of physical brain events. So you could have a physical measuring device which is able to identify to a high level of precision certain neural correlates of experience, and from there we could *infer* what qualia an individual was undergoing, but only in an inductivist way - it\'s not as if you could ever put subjective experience on to a digital reading. The whole point of subjectivity, the whole point of \'a point of view\' is that it is private. I suggest reading the famous Thomas Nagel paper \'What is it like to be a bat?\' for some insight on that. But basically, any time you make an observation about someone elseâ€™s subjective experience, it has to go through the filter of your own subjective experience, thus losing something along the way. No matter how precisely you can look in to the workings of the brain, you wonâ€™t be able to answer fundamental questions in the philosophy of mind such as \'How do I know my red isn\'t your green?\' and so on. Trying to fit subjective experience in to objective information is just a non-starter.','2012-06-14 16:48:42','2012-06-14 16:48:42'),(1988,96,48,'Reply to omgpop\r\n\r\nIt is true that a physical measuring device could only measure the correlates of the experience, not the experience itself, thats why we say it is ineffable. Nagel is right, we can never know what it is like to be a bat. But as I explain here\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubw3/bubw3.html\r\n\r\n(Section 4: A Perceptual Modeling Approach)\r\n\r\nNagel himself proposed an \'objective phenomenology\', i.e. to quantify the structural features of the subjective experience in  objective terms, without regard to the \'ineffable\' qualia component. For example if we quantify the experience of vision as a three-dimensional data structure, like a model of volumes and surfaces in a surrounding space to a certain perceptual resolution, this description could be meaningful even to a congenitally blind person, or an alien creature who had never personally experienced the phenomenon of human vision. While this description could never capture everything of that experience, such as the qualia of color experience, it does at least capture the structural characteristics of that subjective experience in an objective form that would be comprehensible to beings incapable of having those experiences. \r\n\r\nAnd that, after all, is the most important part. I don\'t care if you see red where I see green, what is important to me is that your experience must be like mine, a three-dimensional volumetric world surrounding your three-dimensional body, with that peculiar warp of perspective that packs an infinite universe into a finite spherical space.\r\n\r\nA blind man could \'braille\' this diorama with his hands, \r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubblemodel/diorama.html\r\n\r\nand bat could probe the diorama with its sonar, and both the blind man and the bat would experience the three-dimensional information content of the diorama, although expressed in totally different qualia in their own experience. That is exactly the kind of information we could in principle read from the \'neural correlates\' of experience. But we could figure out the mapping to qualia easily enough, if the subject reports an experience of red for this correlate, and green for that one.  No problem.\r\n','2012-06-14 17:50:21','2012-06-14 17:50:21'),(1991,96,48,'@omgpop:\r\n\r\nYou very accurately describe the very theory that I so vehemently reject. \r\n\r\nYou wrote: \r\n\r\n\"So you could have a physical measuring device which is able to identify to a high level of precision certain neural correlates of experience, and from there we could *infer* what qualia an individual was undergoing, but only in an inductivist way - it\'s not as if you could ever put subjective experience on to a digital reading. The whole point of subjectivity, the whole point of \'a point of view\' is that it is private...No matter how precisely you can look in to the workings of the brain, you wonâ€™t be able to answer fundamental questions in the philosophy of mind such as \'How do I know my red isn\'t your green?\' and so on. Trying to fit subjective experience in to objective information is just a non-starter.\"\r\n\r\nThis is exactly what I reject. If there is anything (information, experience, or anything else) in the first person perspective that isn\'t COMPLETELY deducible by the third person observation, then that \"extra\" stuff must be epiphenomenal, and thus not really exist (or if it does, then I don\'t care about it, and neither should you). \r\n\r\n\"I suggest reading the famous Thomas Nagel paper \'What is it like to be a bat?\' for some insight on that.\"\r\n\r\nI have read it, and find it completely non-convincing. \r\n\r\nThe problem for me is the problem of epiphenomenalism. Any \"extra\" stuff must be epiphenomenal almost by definition. But my consciousness is causally active. The conscious experience that needs to be explained is all causal consciousness. So any proposed extra stuff must not be where my consciousness comes from... the result? Consciousness must be fully explainable from the third person perspective through a reductionist approach with the laws of physics. \r\n\r\nConclusion: Consciousness must be an emergent phenomenon of the causal laws of physics. \r\n\r\nI am well aware that this conclusion is counter-intuitive. But lots of reality is counter intuitive. That doesn\'t make it less true. ','2012-06-14 17:58:11','2012-06-14 17:58:11'),(1994,96,48,'Reply to James:\r\n\r\nThanks for the thoughtful reply. I think I have an idea of where you are coming from now. Basically, you are saying that, while property dualism seems intuitive, it leads to obviously erroneous beliefs such as epiphenomenalism. Now, I don\'t necessarily see the immediate problem with epiphenomena, but I do agree that property dualism as a whole leads to many paradoxes. For example, if qualia are fundamental properties of all particles, how do they get synthesised up in to experience? In real life, in the \'world out there\' picture of things, there is not really any such thing as an \'object\'. There are just bundles of fundamental particles which just happen to be coming together as a result of various forces acting upon them. Unless I have it all wrong (possible), fundamental particles don\'t communicate with each other. So how is it, I ask again, that qualia get built up in to continuous whole entities, when their physical correlates are often discrete or even disparate? Well I reckon that\'s one problem with property dualism. \r\n\r\nI suppose epiphenomena do create issues in a way, because the question arises \'How would ever know about them in the first place if they are non-causal?â€™ So yeah, I agree, I see some logical problems with property dualism, and have done since the idea first came to me. If you look in the camp about 5th dimensional consciousness - that was my first attempt at a solution. I tried to resolve the first problem by postulating that the seat of consciousness was in the electromagnetic field of the brain, and hence could be continuous. But I think now that was a little bold, since I don\'t know much beyond high school physics about EM fields (and knew even less then). I also had no solution to the epiphenomenal problem. Getting back on track though, let me consider the alternative to property dualism which you seem to propose.\r\n\r\nUnless I am mistaken, you are in agreement with the Dan Dennett quotation which everyone is getting themselves worked up about on this thread, right? Well, I have a problem with that statement too. There are two ways I could interpret it, and I\'d like to know which interpretation best fits your own. The first has \'seeming\' to be an objective notion, along the lines of what someone else here talked about, i.e. a database reference. Here our idea of having qualia simply comes from our thought processes becoming confused and over-analysing the sensory ones, but in reality nothing weird or different like subjective experience is actually going on. I think this would be the perfect theory if we were actually robots studying the denizens of this little forum, wondering what in the devil they were on about. But Iâ€™m not a robot, and whether or not I analyse anything, I am always aware of experiencing things, and having feelings. And I donâ€™t really see how a simple one off causal process could give rise to this whole notion of subjective experience. I think itâ€™s fair to say that you donâ€™t need to have read David Chalmers in order to have qualia â€“ and I seriously doubt anyone here is asserting that the vast majority of the human population are nothing more than philosophical zombies, or functionalist machines. In a lot of ways, I donâ€™t think that argument makes much sense â€“ youâ€™ve got to be â€˜awareâ€™ of your thoughts and cognitive processes for it to begin to work, for example, which would be entirely circular. The second notion is one that has been argued against in this thread before, where â€˜seemsâ€™ is simply interpreted as a subjective experience from the get go, and the argument is immediately seen as circular. Essentially the two positions are equivalent, but I entertained the first idea for a little while and was almost convinced by it before I realised that both interpretation were logically equivalent. \r\n\r\nI know my argument isnâ€™t following a very precise train right now, but the concepts are difficult. I am just curious as to what mechanism you suggest for qualia coming about without ever including any non-physical components. I think itâ€™s impossible, because as soon as you allow for qualia - illusion or otherwise - you have allowed for a subjective experience, which is different entirely from objective existence and therefore dualistic. \r\nBrent is aware that I have proposed to start a solipsism camp, but I donâ€™t think it would be very popular here. Essentially though, thatâ€™s where all of my thoughts are leading me. \r\n','2012-06-15 07:52:32','2012-06-15 07:52:32'),(1997,96,48,'Theoreticians,\n\nMike [http://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/32/79#79 said] he has been working very long and hard but still failing to understand this trivial and easy statement:\n\n    \"If you know something, there must be something that is this knowledge\"\n\nTo which James agrees, saying such is [http://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/32/80#80 \"not clear at all\"].\n\nYou guys are making this WAY too hard.  If a computer program does something, you must have written code to make it do what it is doing, and there must be some fundamental natures of reality that is configured so that it can be interpreted as the abstract label that is the information you programmed.  You can\'t get any functionality out of the system, without all of that.  That is all that statement is saying.  Don\'t make it so hard.  If you know something, there must be something physically real that is able to be that knowledge.\n\nWhat I hear you guys  saying is: you can get our redness and greenness seemings, without them being anything fundamentally real.  Which is completely absurd to property dualists that experience classical qualia.\n\nDr. Dennett says we don\'t have qualia: \"It just seems like we do\".  Even you guys can see what an obvious mistake this is.\n\nSo, to try to preserve your, to me, absurd theories, you end up making an even worse mistake by saying our seeming, itself is what is mistaken.  In other words, you are saying we have redness and greenness seemings, but we are mistaken to think these are the absolute fundamental qualities they are.  You are claiming, despite what we absolutely experience them as, they are nothing more than meaningless, unreal, abstracted information, mere labels we give to various fundamental causal properties, like ones and zeros.\n\nRedness and Greenness, are what they are.  I, at least, know that more absolutely than we know anything else science has taught us.  I seriously doubt that you guys know this, like I do, for if you did, it would be trivially easy for you to understand all this.  To test for this, can you guys answer a question for me:  What is the difference between a real red quale, and your memory of the same (what you remember of quale, when your eyes are closed.)  Perhaps your redness is more like my mere memory of redness?\n\nWhat you guys are doing, by claiming they are not what they seem, or can \'arise\' from or be mere abstracted information, or fundamentally meaningless symbols, like ones and zeros, - mere labels we give to interpretations of fundamental causal reality, is just absurd, given what my redness and greenness are like.\n\n[http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=143 Jordan (AKA omgpop)] said:\n\n    \"property dualism as a whole leads to many paradoxes. For example,\n    if qualia are fundamental properties of all particles, how do they get\n    synthesized up in to experience?\"\n\nand he said he fails to understand the problems with epiphenomenalism.  The problem with epiphenomenalism, is it isn\'t observable or testable, or effable.  Even if epiphenomenal qualia did exist, like invisible unicorns, why would anyone care, even if they did, since nobody can provide any evidence that they do exist.  (for a very comical illustration of how absurd epiphenomenalism is see [http://lesswrong.com/lw/pn/zombies_the_movie/ \"Zombies: The Movie\"].\n\nThere are no such problems with macro material property dualism, that simply predicts there are two categorically different types of fundamental natures to reality:\n\n* Causal Properties\n* Phenomenal Qualities\n\nWhich are simply both different fundamental natures of the same physical things.  The only difference is how you are observing / experiencing them.  They don\'t, as Jordan said: \"get synthesized up in to experience\", they are simply fundamental natures of reality our brain paints our conscious knowledge with.  The testable prediction is there is something in nature that has these qualities.  An idealized theoretical example being the neuro transmitter Glutamate has a phenomenal redness quality and Aspartate has a greenness quality.  When neurons want to paint a strawberry in our consciousness, it fires with Glutamate.  When it paints the leaves - Aspartate.  Just because all of our only cause and effected based scientific instruments can \'see\' of glutamate, are its causal properties, doesn\'t mean that they also can\'t have ineffable qualities that simply suffer from the quale interpretation problem, making them ineffable.\n\nObviously, if science bears out Material Property Dualism, and we finally eff to you guys that have no idea what my redness is like, and you never find some other way to get redness, without glutamate, you guys must admit how wrong you guys were, right?  We can all agree with this?\n\nHow might Representational Functionalism, do the same?  Given your theory, how could I ever know if my redness is your greenness, or something you have never experienced before in your life?  How might your theory falsify our beliefs, and force us to be Representational Functionalists?\n\nIf you know something ineffable/phenomenal, what is that knowledge, and how might you know if mine is different?\n\nBrent Allsop\n','2012-06-15 10:23:31','2012-06-15 10:23:31'),(2000,96,48,'> I seriously doubt anyone here is asserting that the vast majority of the human population are nothing more than philosophical zombies, or functionalist machines.\r\n\r\nThank you for finding such a clear and simple way to put it! Yes. I am asserting that all humans are all functionalist machines. I think that is what Dennett is ultimately saying too (although perhaps he is wise enough to avoid saying it directly). If we are ever going to articulate this question for him, I think this is precisely the assertion that we need to formalize an issue with.\r\n\r\nAdmittedly, I sometimes take on a position just so I can argue it for a while and come to understand it better. To some extent, that is how I ended up taking this position, but although it has made me an outcast and a target for flinging adjectives (such as \'absurd\', \'cold\', \'rigid\', \'mechanical\', \'sterile\', \'undead\', etc.), I have completely failed to discover a coherent issue with this position that I could use as an excuse to move on. I do not require a fully-developed argument, just something worth pondering for a while--something we can ask Daniel Dennett about--something that is not ultimately based on a circular testimony of how real our experiences seem to be.\r\n\r\nBut I am increasingly convinced that no such argument exists. Dennett has correctly identified the root of the issue. The only basis to suggest that we are anything more than functionalist machines is that our experiences \'just seem real\', and every explanation for this phenomenon involving magic can be restated without the magical component with no reduction in the quality of the explanation. Representationalism is the perfect example of this. It is a pretty good explanation for experiences, but it explains experience *JUST AS WELL* with all non-functionalist components removed. If anyone can come up with a reason why representationalism needs a magical component, this debate is over. I would even be happy with a reason why a magical component makes representationalism ever-so-slightly better.\r\n\r\n(And yes, if I am going to accept the label \'zombie\', you all have to accept the label \'magic\' for the non-functionalist components of your explanations. Let\'s call this the \'magicians versus zombies\' debate. Perhaps this will spare us from wasting any more words articulating precisely what bothers us about the opposing philosophy.)\r\n','2012-06-15 13:18:11','2012-06-15 13:18:11'),(2003,96,48,'Reply to Mike Gashler\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nIf anyone can come up with a reason why representationalism needs a magical component, this debate is over. I would even be happy with a reason why a magical component makes representationalism ever-so-slightly better.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nViewed from the outside, Dennett\'s explanation, like that of the Behaviorists and naive realists, is perfectly consistent with the facts.\r\n\r\nIt is when observing conscious experience \"from the inside\" that Dennett\'s view becomes absurd, because he claims we cannot even view our experience \"from the inside\", all we are seeing is reality itself, directly, where it lies in the world. THAT assumption is DEMONSTABLY false, both practically and theoretically, all we can ever see is our representations of reality, not reality itself.\r\n\r\nThe distinction becomes perfectly clear when considering dreams and hallucinations, which are obviously internal representations in the absence of a corresponding external entity, the fact that we can \"see\" our hallucinations as colored spatial structures PROVES that our mind is capable of constructing whole virtual worlds painted in phenomenal color, embedded in a phenomenal space that is clearly distinct from Euclidean space in having a nonlinear warped spherical geometry.\r\n\r\nCase closed! (Nobody convinced? Nobody surprised! Circle on endlessy, debate!)','2012-06-15 14:11:44','2012-06-15 14:11:44'),(2006,96,48,'Mike,\r\n\r\n\"although it has made me an outcast and a target for flinging adjectives (such as \'absurd\', \'cold\', \'rigid\', \'mechanical\', \'sterile\', \'undead\', etc.), I have completely failed to discover a coherent issue with this position that I could use as an excuse to move on. I do not require a fully-developed argument, just something worth pondering for a while--\"\r\n\r\nI wouldn\'t say that embracing an eliminative materialist or functionalist worldview makes someone cold or sterile, but I do suspect that being defensive about being accused of such suggests that there are personal sentiments driving the opinion rather than empirical evaluation of the facts.\r\n\r\nTo me the obvious coherent issue that needs discovering here is the Hard Problem: Why would there be any kind of experience at all? It has nothing to do with how real we feel our experience to be, but the fact that it is possible to conceive of even the hint of the possibility of \'real\' is 100% impossible in a functionalist universe. What does \'real\' mean? As opposed to what?\r\n\r\nThen to say \"If anyone can come up with a reason why representationalism needs a magical component, this debate is over. \" adds a loaded question fallacy. If you assert that either you are right or you are an idiot who believes in magic, then you have not considered the other alternatives and want to discourage anyone else from daring to do so. One does not have to believe that reality is a dream or dreams are reality in order to see that there is in fact a difference. Both dreams and reality cannot exist in a purely functionalist universe...why would they? how could they?\r\n\r\n\r\nSlehar, I don\'t think that Dennett believes that hallucinations are impossible or reality, I think he believes that they are just the representation of brain activity of one area of the brain to another area of the brain. The problem of course is, what is the \'representation\' made of? What is it doing there and what are we doing in it? None of it makes sense in a universe where we are machines. Machines that do what? Reproduce their own uselessness?','2012-06-15 15:05:24','2012-06-15 15:05:24'),(2009,96,48,'@omgpop:\r\n\r\n\"I think itâ€™s impossible, because as soon as you allow for qualia - illusion or otherwise - you have allowed for a subjective experience, which is different entirely from objective existence and therefore dualistic.\"\r\n\r\nBut that\'s exactly where I jump ship. I claim that there must be no difference between subjective experiences and objective reality, or else you produce epiphenomenalism. So subjective experiences must be equivalent to objective states through a STRONG equivalence principle. Anything weakly connecting them (like property dualism) produces a belief that subjective experience and behavior have a shared cause, That isn\'t good enough, the experience must cause the behavior, not just share a cause with the behavior. \r\n\r\n\"Now, I don\'t necessarily see the immediate problem\r\nwith epiphenomena\"\r\n\r\nWell, I say \"I see red\" because I experience the qualia of red. The qualia CAUSES the response. It doesn\'t share a common cause with the response, it directly causes the response. Let\'s assume that sex carries an epiphenomenal qualia of intense pain, while stabbing yourself in the hand with a knife has the epiphenomenal qualia of intense pleasure. How would you refute this claim to reversed epiphenomenal qualia? You would still say \"OH YES\" when having sex and \"OH NO\" whne stabbing yourself in the hand with a knife. You say \"well, I don\'t FEEL or BELIEVE that I have these reversed qualia form the first person perspective\" but your beliefs involve third person states in your brain, and so a belief about a qualia must come form the causal properties of the qualia, not its epiphenomenal properties, so not believing that these \"reversed\" epiphenomenal qualia exist from the first person perspective is no proof that they don\'t. \r\n\r\nIn other words, people have assumed that the first person perspective somehow provides a window into the non-objective epiphenomenal world. But this isn\'t true. If something has no causal properties, then it can\'t affect the neural correlates. And we know that first person experiences come with neural correlates. And that means that an epiphenomenal experience of red can\'t cause your claims of seeing red (that would make it causal) nor can it affect your beliefs (because it can\'t create or even effect the neural correlates that accompany that belief without being causal), and it can\'t affect your feelings (because it can\'t create the neural correlates without being causal).\r\n\r\nBut what if there was a shared cause between the experience and the causal acts. Let\'s call this shared cause the \"source\". Now the source causes the epiphenomenal experience of red, and it causes you to say \"I see red\". This is essentially what Chalmers proposes. But now, if we think about it, it is the source that is causing the claim, the belief, and the feeling, NOT the epiphenomenal qualia themselves. You could cut these qualia out of the equation entirely, and you would not change your claims, beliefs, and feelings! \r\n\r\nIn other words, epiphenomenal qualia are irrelevant, and aren\'t the subjective experiences that so desperately need to be explained. \r\n\r\nBrent and others have claimed that there is a way to produce a theory of property dualism that is not epiphenomenal. I have challenged them to write out such a theory formally in terms of random variables and their effect on other random variables  (like a Baysian Network), such that the final random variable (behavior) is directly causally linked to the phenomenal properties, in such a way that doesn\'t just turn the phenomenal properties back into fundamental causal laws of physics. So far, no one has met this challenge, while I have produced a similar network for PD that makes them epiphenomenal (the phenomenal random variables aren\'t directly linked to behavior). See: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lxzSyLAj3NI. Until someone meets this challenge, I can\'t believe in PD. \r\n\r\n@Brent: \r\n\r\n\"Mike said[1] he has been working very long and hard but still failing to understand this trivial and easy statement:\"\r\n\r\nWhen taking criticism of your writing, you don\'t get to claim that it is simple, easy, or clear. The point of communication is to produce a statement that is simple or clear to someone ELSE, not one that is simple or clear to the speaker. We all know what we mean, so what we say is clear to us. But that doesn\'t make it clear to someone else. \r\n\r\nAt this point, I do think that I know what you mean, but this understanding didn\'t come from your statement. It came form other conversations with you about what that statement was supposed to mean. And that means that the statement on its own is still unclear, and will likely not be understood by others (or by Dennett if you send it to him). Which just means that you need to work harder at making the thought clearer and more easily understood. \r\n\r\nI don\'t think that means that I am making it \"way too hard\", I think that it means that you still aren\'t communicating your thoughts effectively. \r\n\r\n\"Redness and Greenness, are what they are. I, at least, know that more absolutely than we know anything else science has taught us. I seriously doubt that you guys know this, like I do, for if you did, it would be trivially easy for you to understand all this. To test for this, can you guys answer a question for me: What is the difference between a real red quale, and your memory of the same (what you remember of quale, when your eyes are closed.) Perhaps your redness is more like my mere memory of redness?\"\r\n\r\nYou often make this claim that my experiences must not be as real as yours, or I would obviously believe what you beleive, but I just don\'t think so. My experiences are intense. I can\'t even begin to explain the difference between my imagination of red, and my experience of red, but there is a BIG difference. Red is real. Red FEELS fundamental. I admit as much as the next guy that this all FEELS fundamental, rich, and irreducible. But I also know that reality is often counter intuitive. The problem is that qualia can\'t be fundamental without being epiphenomenal... and I know that my qualia aren\'t epiphenomenal every bit as much as I know that they FEEL fundamental. I know for 100% certain that my experiences, whatever they are, and wherever they come from, affect my behavior. If any theory that makes them fundamental makes them epiphenomenal, then they can\'t be fundamental, they must just SEEM that way. You claim that\'s not true, that they can be fundamental and not be epiphenomenal... fine... show me. I WANT my experiences to be fundamental. That would be FAR more intuitively pleasing. But I am convinced that it can\'t be done without epiphenomenalism. So continuing to argue that experiences just feel so darn real/fundamental won\'t change my mind. I already agree that they feel that way. If you want to change my mind, then you need to produce an example of a formal system where experience is causally active, but not just another fundamental property of causal physics. You don\'t even have to produce the \"right\" system, just an example to show that some consistent and reasonable system for non epiphenomenal fundamental qualia might exist somewhere out there. \r\n\r\n\"There are no such problems with macro material property dualism\"\r\n\r\nBull feces, you read my paper draft, I already showed that this isn\'t true. MPD leads to epiphenomenalism. If you think otherwise, show me. You write: \r\n\r\n\"\r\n * Causal Properties\r\n * Phenomenal Qualities\r\n Which are simply both different fundamental natures of the same physical things.\"\r\n\r\nIn other words, they share a common SOURCE. Thus, the phenomenal properties are epiphenomenal. They don\'t directly effect the causal properties... of if they do, then suddenly they aren\'t different form the causal properties... it\'s one or the other, either the phenomenal properties are just causal properties, nothing more.... or else they are epiphenomenal. Either way, your causally active experience would arise as an emergent property of the causal properties alone, while your epiphenomenal experience would arise form teh phenomenal properties. \r\n\r\n\"An idealized theoretical example being the neuro transmitter Glutamate has a phenomenal redness quality and Aspartate has a greenness quality.\"\r\n\r\nBut it is the CAUSAL properties of your Glutamate and Aspartate that carry their causal effects. So any additional properties of Glutamate or Aspartate must be epiphenomenal properties. It\'s their causal properties that \"paint\" our active experience, because they also paint their causal activity in the brain, and thus their behavior producing properties, like claiming \"I see red\" or \"I see green\". \r\n\r\n\"Obviously, if science bears out Material Property Dualism, and we finally eff to you guys that have no idea what my redness is like, and that there is no other way to get redness, without glutamate, you guys must admit how worn you guys were, when we finally can eff to you what my redness is like right? We can all agree with this, right?\"\r\n\r\nNo. No. No. Absolutely not. No way!!!!!!!!!!\r\n\r\nIf you put a new neural transmitter into my head, and I have a brand new experience, I would still believe that it is the CAUSAL properties of that new neural transmitter that CAUSED the new experience. That would prove nothing about their having some magical phenomenal property. Nothing at all. \r\n\r\n\"How might Representational Functionalism, do the same? Given your theory, how could I ever know if my redness is your greenness, or something you have never experienced before in your life? How might your theory falsify our believes, and force us to me Representational Functionalists?\"\r\n\r\nBy proving two points. \r\n 1. the qualia you need to explain are causally active and\r\n 2. anything beyond the structure and dynamics of physics is epiphenomenal. \r\n therefore:\r\n 3. my qualia must be an emergent property of the structure and dynamics of physics. \r\n\r\nI am currently working on a mathematically formal proof of #2. But right now I just have a \"well, no one has been able to give a counter example\" strong conjecture, with an intuitive \"if it is \"beyond\" the structure and dynamics of physics, it must not contribute to the structure and dynamics of physics, and must therefore be epipheneomenal\". \r\n\r\nAll it takes to invalidate #2 is a formal example. Do it if you think your MPD is so obviously not epiphenomenal. ','2012-06-15 17:04:04','2012-06-15 17:04:04'),(2012,96,48,'@jcarroll\r\n\r\n\" 2. anything beyond the structure and dynamics of physics is epiphenomenal...\r\n\r\nAll it takes to invalidate #2 is a formal example\"\r\n\r\nIt sounds like by \'formal example\' you already refer to physics. \r\n\r\nYou aren\'t denying that qualia are phenomenal and you aren\'t saying that naive realism is objectively true, so what are you saying that the lack of an example of physical form that contradicts our formality of physics will prove about qualia?\r\n\r\n','2012-06-15 17:48:31','2012-06-15 17:48:31'),(2015,96,48,'I think me, Brent and James are all talking about different kinds of epiphenomena. \r\n\r\nJames, you are saying that the qualia is what causes the action. That is where I disagree with you, I don\'t think it is the subjective component of experience which does that at all. It is the firing of neurons which causes one action or another, and nothing more. My idea of qualia, or epiphenomena, is similar to Brent\'s Fundamental Phenomenal Properties (which is why I think Brent\'s idea of epiphenomena is different than mine). The idea is that you have fully causal physical processes which can be detected externally, and there is some qualitative aspect of those physical processes, which - it would appear - are consistent in their experienced quality with their functional role. But the experienced quality (the epiphenomenon, the quale, the raw feel) has no causal role. Taking away the causal role of subjective experience isn\'t particularly harmful, because we\'re saying (or *I\'m* saying, I don\'t know what other people think) that the quality of the subjective experience is \'as a result of\' its neural-functional correlate. Pain always feels painful because that is exactly the way your brain treats it, and the epiphenomena are simply aspects of that neurological \'treating\'.\r\n\r\nBrent, you see an issue with epiphenomena in that they can\'t be empircally verified. But how are we ever going to empirically verify the Fundamental phenomenal properties you are on about? You are starting off by axiomatically postulating that, for example, \'redness\' is a fundamental phenomenal property of Glutamate, and then you are telling me that simply witnessing Glutamate in action and hearing your test subject say \'Yup, that\'s red alright\' is evidence for the existence of the phenomenal property? But that doesn\'t really make any sense, because the test subject giving that response would be well covered by the fundamental causal properties of Glutamate, would it not? I can just as easily get James to program a little machine which says the word \'red\' out loud every time you type in the word \'shoe\' at an input. You\'ve still got the same problem you\'re finding in epiphenomena. Not that I think lack of empirical verification is particularly an objection to property dualism seen as it pretty much predicts a priori that such would be impossible.','2012-06-15 17:54:11','2012-06-15 17:54:11'),(2018,96,48,'reply to Steve,\r\n\r\nYour internal vs external view sounds like a promising direction. I can see that there is more to explain when viewed from the inside. I am also in agreement with you that there is an abundance of evidence to support that we build internal representations, and Dennett et al are wrong to reject it. The only part I am missing is what of value dualism adds to the explanation. Why does saying the model is painted with phenomenal paint explain what I feel on the inside? What can phenomenal paint do to my brain that abstract information cannot do?\r\n\r\nreply to Craig,\r\n\r\nI didn\'t realize how emotionally charged that sounded. That was unintentional. I was really just trying to point out that adjective-based arguments were not very effective.','2012-06-15 18:23:27','2012-06-15 18:23:27'),(2021,96,48,'Reply to Mike Gashler:\r\n\r\n>>>\r\n\r\nThe only part I am missing is what value does dualism add to the explanation. Why does saying the model is painted with phenomenal paint explain what I feel on the inside? What can phenomenal paint do to my brain that abstract information cannot do?\r\n\r\n<<<\r\n\r\nIt is not dualism, it is (ontological) monism, the phenomenal color is not in addition to its neural correlates, the phenomenal color is ***one and the same*** as the neural correlate. You are, in effect, seeing the neural correlates \"from the inside\" where they appear as solid volumes, bounded by colored surfaces, embedded in a spatial void.\r\n\r\nThe dualism is merely epistemological, like a television monitor that presents a copy of the scene before the camera, but the camera, monitor, and scene are all part of one physical universe.\r\n\r\nThis variation of representationalism is known as *identity theory*, i.e. the phenomenal experience is not only similar to the neural correlates, there is no distinction between them! I can say as an objective scientific FACT that a certain neural correlate in my brain IS currently RED, redness is a property of that correlate, although you have to be me to actually see that color property.\r\n\r\nI quote from my book \r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/book/chap1.html\r\n\r\nquote >>>\r\n\r\nIt follows therefore that a percept can be viewed in two different contexts, either from the objective external context, as a pattern of electrochemical activity in the physical brain expressed in terms of neurophysiological variables such as electrical voltages or neural spiking frequencies, and from the internal subjective context where that same percept is viewed as a subjective experience expressed in terms of subjective variables such as perceived color, shape, or motion, etc. Like the two faces of a coin, these very different entities can be identified as merely different manifestations of the same underlying structure. The dual nature of a percept is analogous to the representation of data in a digital computer, where a pattern of voltages present in a particular memory register can represent some meaningful information, either a numerical value, or a brightness value in an image, or a character of text, etc. when viewed from inside the appropriate software environment, while when viewed in external physical terms that same data takes the form of voltages or currents in particular parts of the machine. \r\n\r\n<<< quote\r\n\r\nSo for example a pattern of voltages in a computer register in this pattern \"0101\" represents the number \"5\" in binary. If you measure with a volt meter you read \"0101\". If you probe that register with software it will report the value \"5\". If you copy it onto your screen it will appear as a color, depending on what look-up table you have. The SAME DATA appear different from different perspectives, but there is one and only one register and it has the pattern \"0101\", the rest is interpretation by software depending on what you want to do with it.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-15 18:44:12','2012-06-15 18:44:12'),(2024,96,48,'@omgpop:\r\n\r\nyou wrote: \"you are saying that the qualia is what causes the action. That is where I disagree with you, I don\'t think it is the subjective component of experience which does that at all....The idea is that you have fully causal physical processes which can be detected externally, and there is some qualitative aspect of those physical processes, which - it would appear - are consistent in their experienced quality with their functional role. But the experienced quality (the epiphenomenon, the quale, the raw feel) has no causal role. \"\r\n\r\nThen the subjective part doesn\'t matter. When you say \"I have subjective experiences that are real\" but that statement is caused by your objective, causal, behavioral neural firings, then that statement wasn\'t made BECAUSE of your subjective experiences. In fact, it would be made, exactly as it was made, regardless of whether you even had subjective experiences accompanying your neural correlates!?!?!?!?!?!?!?!? This means that you are lying every time you tell me that you have subjective experiences Or, if you aren\'t, it\'s by accident. Because the statement didn\'t come from the subjective experience... it might or might not therefore be true, or even relate to your subjective experiences. In fact, it might be reverse-related, and you would never know. \r\n\r\n\"Brent, you see an issue with epiphenomena in that they can\'t be empircally verified. But how are we ever going to empirically verify the Fundamental phenomenal properties you are on about? You are starting off by axiomatically postulating that, for example, \'redness\' is a fundamental phenomenal property of Glutamate, and then you are telling me that simply witnessing Glutamate in action and hearing your test subject say \'Yup, that\'s red alright\' is evidence for the existence of the phenomenal property? But that doesn\'t really make any sense, because the test subject giving that response would be well covered by the fundamental causal properties of Glutamate, would it not? \"\r\n\r\nEXACTLY, It\'s exciting to see someone finally get what I have been trying to say for so long! I am sure that it is at least partly my fault for failing to communicate well,  I have been TRYING to say this to Brent for ages now, but he seems not to understand. But since you just said it better than I ever have, perhaps it will finally stick this time. \r\n','2012-06-15 21:51:17','2012-06-15 21:51:17'),(2027,96,48,'I\'m not sure that omgpop\'s message agrees with recent neuroscience. This makes a distinction between activity in the brain related to strength of signal and activity related to subjective evaluation. Thus the weaker of two signals in the somatosensory cortex may turn out to be the stronger of two consciously or subjectively registered signals in the prefrontal. Moreover, the orbitofrontal, the region of the prefrontal where this has been demonstrated is crucial to the evaluation of sensory inputs. It has important influences on the dorsolateral planning-related region and on the striatum where rational and emotional processing is thought to be integrated.\r\n\r\nJunius','2012-06-16 09:50:59','2012-06-16 09:50:59'),(2030,96,48,'reply to Steve,\r\n\r\n> the phenomenal color is ***one and the same*** as the neural correlate\r\n\r\nThen I cannot find any magical component in your theory. How do you separate conscious humans from functionalist machines? Are you a zombie or a magician? Or is that is a false dichotomy?\r\n\r\nmike\r\n','2012-06-16 12:13:06','2012-06-16 12:13:06'),(2031,1,49,'In post#100 in the Dennett discussion, omgpop writes:\r\n\r\n\"I don\'t speak for all property dualists, but Mike, as I see it - unconscious measurement devices would only ever be able to detect the presence of neural correlates, just as they currently do. Property dualism sees the qualitative aspect of experience to be a fundamental aspect of physical brain events.\"\r\n\r\nI can\'t see the difference between this and substance dualism. You are saying that there is measurable stuff - the NCC - and non-measurable stuff - subjective experience. Talk of properties and aspects seems to me just to clothe Cartesiam dualism, no?','2012-06-16 13:20:17','2012-06-16 13:20:17'),(2034,96,48,'Mike writes (post#81) that:\r\n\"...electrostatic signals, synaptic\r\npotentials, and various chemicals are probably sufficient to constitute\r\na neural correlate. Since all such things can be simulated, it follows\r\nthat beliefs (including the belief that some specific phenomenal\r\nexperience was real) consist of nothing more than abstract information represented by a neural correlate.\"\r\n\r\nYour conclusion is not valid because a simulation is not the same thing as the simulated. A computer simulation of a neuron, for example, is a set of equations that more or less accurately represents the relationship between measurements of physical quantities in the neuron such as post-synaptic potentals and firing rate. There are no chemicals or forces in a simulation, you just have the maths.','2012-06-16 13:35:18','2012-06-16 13:35:18'),(2037,96,48,'reply to richwil,\r\n\r\n> There are no chemicals or forces in a simulation, you just have the maths.\r\n\r\nAgreed. A simulated consciousness could only have simulated experiences. If a wetware man told a software man that his experiences were not real, and the software man replied, \'they seem real to me\', would it even matter who was right? Why?\r\n\r\n...(digression) Perhaps the wetware man might reply, \'because you are running within my hardware and I am tired of paying the electric bill\', then a voice from heaven calls down \'Thou hypocrite! You are running inside my Universe and I have a new video game that I want to play on it.\'','2012-06-16 14:05:25','2012-06-16 14:05:25'),(2040,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nSteve pointed out that: \"the phenomenal color is ***one and the same*** as the neural correlate\" to which Mike asked:\r\n\r\n    Then I cannot find any magical component in your theory.\r\n    How do you separate conscious humans from functionalist machines?\r\n    Are you a zombie or a magician? Or is that a false dichotomy?\"\r\n\r\nThis is exactly what we\'ve been attempting to explain - what is the difference.  As I indicated before MPD predicts there are two types of fundamental natures of reality:\r\n\r\n* causal properties\r\n* phenomenal qualities\r\n\r\nMike referred to \"...electrostatic signals, synaptic potentials, and various chemicals are probably sufficient to constitute a neural correlate.\"  and all of these are terms describing abstracted information describing \"causal properties\", and is completely absent of the corresponding \"phenomenal qualities\" that may or may not also be present in such.\r\n\r\nIn post #117, Mike made a clever joke about abstracted software running on a computer, and turned this around by  pointing out that we could be running on the universe..  Material Property Dualism predicts there must be some real or basement level that everything is running on.\r\n\r\nAbstracted information can be represented by something real, like +5 and 0 volts can represent a one and zero.  This abstracted information can be interpreted at another level as numbers, like 10 and 0, which can continue up to the next layer and be 0xFF0000, and 0x00FF00, which at the next level can be interpreted as the abstract words red and green, which can be interpreted at the next layer as stop and go.  And you can design a virtual simulation to run on top of this layer where the words stop and go represent +0 volts vs +5 volts, and start they cycle over again, as many times as you want, in any way you want.  The bottom line is, all these layers are abstracted interpretations from the lower layer, by interpreting it as such.  But, ultimately, there is the real physical +5 and 0 voltages which is doing the real representation, and requires no interpretation, it just is reality and what it is like.\r\n\r\nphenomenal qualities, like causal properties, are fundamental natures of reality, they are real, they are not abstracted interpretations of other things.  They can be interpreted as \"red\" vs \"green\" which can be interpreted as stop vs go, and forever up the chain as far as you want to go - but again, at the fundamental level, there is the redness and the greenness doing the representing, and it is like something, without having to be interpreted as being such.\r\n\r\nOne type of zombie system is any system which is running on, or being simulated by, it\'s knowledge being interpreted as something other than it really is.  While a non zombie\'s knowledge is represented by the fundamentally real thing, that is really like something, without requiring any interpretation to be such.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-16 14:54:17','2012-06-16 14:54:17'),(2043,96,48,'Reply to Mike Gashler:\r\n\r\n>>>\r\n\r\nHow do you separate conscious humans from functionalist machines? Are you a zombie or a magician? Or is that is a false dichotomy?\r\n\r\n<<<\r\n\r\nConsciousness and its correlates are one and the same thing, ontologically speaking, but it  appears dualized because it can be viewed from two different aspects, from the \"inside\", what it is like to BE that correlate, and from the outside, how that correlate appears to the outside world.\r\n\r\nIf they are one and the same entity, then they must carry the same information content. This is where Dennett trips up, because he claims that the \"neural vehicles\" (correlates) can have no resemblance whatsoever to their contents (the experiences), so supposedly the activation of a single neuron might represent the experience of an evening on a mountaintop at sunset! Thats absurd!\r\n\r\nPerhaps an excursion into the inanimate might clarify the issue. Have you seen a swollen stream after a big rainstorm? Have you seen the URGENCY of its gushing, the power of its determination, and the happy laughter of its many burbles and swirls and splashes, the breathless leap over a waterfall, the shattering crash at the bottom before pulling itself together again and adopting a more placid mood. Thats sure the way it looks from the *outside*. Would you deny that that water feels the passion on which it manifestly acts? Does it do all that gushing and spurting without the slightest hint of a desire, without a \"mental calculation\" deciding how much to spill this side of a rock instead of that? Is the water really a zombie, that has no awareness of its own capricious and energetic behavior? \r\n\r\nBecause if water had no awareness of its own dynamic processes, then so would we also, we would all be zombies! The very fact that I have experience tells me that a dynamic process (my mind) taking place in a physical mechanism (my brain) can under certain circumstances become conscious of its own internal dynamic processes.\r\n\r\nThe simplest, most parsimonious explanation is that all matter and energy feel the passion of their internal forces, even if they lack any memories, or aspirations, or any larger understanding of anything beyond their own selves. And the information content and computational algorithm of those physical processes is identically equal to the information content that they express by their modulations. The mind matches its neural correlate as this pattern of voltages\r\n\r\n[0, +5, 0, +5]  \r\n\r\nmatches this number\r\n\r\n[0,   1,  0, 1]\r\n\r\nbecause the number is PAINTED OUT IN VOLTAGES and thus it cannot in principle be any different than them, except their appearance, for example whether probed with a volt meter with a scale that goes to 5, or probed by a digital chip that \"reads\" that voltage as Boolean 1.\r\n\r\nThey are not two distinct entities, there is no magic involved, they are one and the same viewed from two different perspectives, and the only magic involved is the magic that makes matter and energy possible in the first place, because everything in the universe is magical, and has its own subjective perspective on the happenings in the world.\r\n\r\nThe perspective of perceptual experience is unique in that it is entirely internal to our brain, and yet it serves as a replica of external reality. Nevertheless, what you are seeing first and foremost is a physical pattern in your brain, and its observed properties are the properties of the neural correlates viewed directly from the perspective of being a correlate ourself, we can see our own brain from the inside, but it looks like a world to us instead.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-16 16:04:22','2012-06-16 16:04:22'),(2046,96,48,'James: I wrote out yet another big reply, but instead I just want to clarify, how do you actually propose subjective experience arises from neural events? Like, do you really and truly deny that there is any logical distinction between the objective stuff that we measure, and the subjective stuff that we feel? Or do you think that there is a difference, but it can be explained without positing a different fundamental material?\r\n\r\nJunius: I was just giving an account of the general idea of property dualism. I think you might be reading too much in to what I am saying. Basically, the stuff you described is causal, and physical. Someone who subscribes to a form of dualism thinks that this stuff is distinct entirely from the subjective experiences it gives rise to. ','2012-06-16 16:28:16','2012-06-16 16:28:16'),(2047,1,49,'Not necessarily, although I see why you might take that from what I said. For example, the solution I immediately hit on when I was first thinking about all this stuff is articulated in this camp http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/29 (excuse the clumsy expression - it was all new to me at that point and I was somewhat fumbling in the dark (still am mind you)). \r\n\r\nI have since distanced myself from the idea, but it is basically a property dualism of sorts, and quite distinct from Cartesian dualism. The idea of subjective experience existing as another - non-spatial, non-temporal -dimension, is at least intuitively appealing - and it\'s cool because it does account for us being unable to experimentally verify it. I\'m not trying to persuade you of that idea, but I think if you consider it in depth you will see it\'s quite distinct from Cartesian dualism - no one is saying, for example, that time is a separate \'substance\' from space. It is simply another dimension, or axis, of the universe. ','2012-06-16 16:42:11','2012-06-16 16:42:11'),(2048,1,49,'Reply to omgpop:\r\n\r\n>>>\r\n\r\nThe idea of subjective experience existing as another - non-spatial, non-temporal -dimension, is at least intuitively appealing - and it\'s cool because it does account for us being unable to experimentally verify it. \r\n\r\n<<<\r\n\r\nYou\'re not the only one who has proposed supernumery dimensions to explain conscious experience. \r\n\r\nI quote from my paper\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubw3/bubw3.html\r\n\r\nSection 4\r\n\r\nSome theorists have even proposed a kind of hidden dimension of physical reality to house the unaccounted information in conscious experience (Harrison 1989, Smythies 1994).\r\n\r\n\r\nHarrison S. (1989) A New Visualization on the Mind-Brain Problem: Naive Realism Transcended. In J. Smythies & J. Beloff (Eds.) The Case for Dualism. Charlottesville: University of Virginia.\r\n\r\nSmythies J. R. (1994) The Walls of Plato\'s Cave: the science and philosophy of brain, consciousness, , and perception. Aldershot UK: Avebury.\r\n\r\nI found Harrison\'s analysis of conscious experience, with his own hand-drawn illustrations, so compelling and insightful that I posted an illustrated summary on my own site.\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/quotes/harrison.html\r\n\r\n','2012-06-16 16:58:26','2012-06-16 16:58:26'),(2051,96,48,'Here is a post from today which I hope defines my solution to qualia and representation:\r\n\r\nhttp://s33light.org/post/25223690381\r\n\r\nIs light an electromagnetic phenomenon?\r\n\r\nI honestly think that it is the only solution which can ever completely make sense, whether or not I can articulate that in a way that people can understand enough of it to begin to think about it on their own is another story...','2012-06-16 17:22:22','2012-06-16 17:22:22'),(2054,96,48,'Steve,\r\n\r\nI really like your idea that dualism refers the the multiple possible perspectives of the viewer, rather than multiple properties of the thing being viewed. I could accept dualism in those terms. I am still uncertain, however, how (or whether) this differentiates humans from functionalist machines. Couldn\'t a simulated man view his simulated neural correlate from a phenomenal perspective, just like a wetware human, and thus have real phenomenal experiences?\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent,\r\n\r\nI think I am starting to build a reasonably accurate model of your theory. Let\'s test it by having me explain your position in my own words: You know that matter has a physical existence and math does not--math is only abstractly represented. A software man might behave precisely like a wetware man, but you think this tells us nothing about the subjective experiences they may have had. The wetware man\'s actions were influenced by real subjective experiences because he is implemented in chemicals that really exist. Even though the software man may behave as one who believes he has real experiences, you think it is nonsensical to even ask whether the software man believes he has real experiences because there is no real software man--he is just a bunch of actions that were calculated by some algorithm. You think the lack of a material existence deprives mathematical operations of the power to work together to form beliefs, certainty, knowledge, awareness, or experiences. Although you do not know precisely what gives chemicals this marvelous power that has been withheld from math, you know it must exist because you, as a wetware man, have subjective experiences, and the idea of using numbers to represent certainty in an abstract model is just not a satisfying substitute for having \'real awareness\'. How did I do? Am I starting to get it?','2012-06-16 19:15:30','2012-06-16 19:15:30'),(2055,116,44,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nAs he should, James keeps taunting me and pointing out the fact that I haven\'t yet adequately provided a falsifying example of what he claims he can \'prove\'.  (Even though in my mind, I\'ve successfully attempted such, many times, already.)\r\n\r\nI asked above for help with a rigorous formulation of what, exactly, we are working on proving / disproving.  As that, alone, seems a bit difficult.  Such would be a huge help in our efforts, I believe.\r\n\r\nI\'m betting that whatever formulation of initial fundamental conditions we come up with to base such a proof on, James proof will require an initial assumption that the only tools we have to work with are discrete units of computational operation.  Examples being neuron or transistor like discrete elements that take inputs from causally upstream units, and send signals to more of the same causally downstream units.  These discrete units are capable of detecting signals from multiple upstream units, and based on easily mathematically describable operations, such as \"Boolean logic\", or mathematical integration or amplification... and then sending the results to more of the same kind of downstream discrete units.\r\n\r\nGiven that fundamental assumption, I would completely agree with James, that he could be successful at coming up with a proof I would accept.  But, doing so would only miss the important theoretical possibility I think is critically important - that there are more than such discrete computational units possible in known physical reality.\r\n\r\nIt isn\'t possible to resolve the \'binding problem\' of philosophy, given only discrete computational units.  It isn\'t possible to make a system that is aware of something that must have redness in the left hemisphere, unified with something in the right hemisphere with greenness, in a way that we are aware of all of it at the same time.  and in a way so that our knowledge of redness, and how it is different than the greenness, can be the initial cause of our picking the strawberry.  My argument is that there is some system in the brain that can accomplish this achievement, that must be more than such simple discrete units of computation.\r\n\r\nWhen examined, with mere abstracted knowledge of the brain, such will look like a system that detects glutamate, and only glutamate, or at least the causal properties of glutamate.  Nothing else but glutamate causing the system to make the claim that it is redness.\r\n\r\nBut, the prediction is that when we discover the phenomenal qualities of the same, this will provide additional insight into why the particular causal behaviors behave the way they do, in a way that appears to cause the glutamate to cause us to select the strawberry.  The base fundamental reason we pick the red one, will no longer be just the abstracted information about glutamate, we will know, additionally, the reason glutamate behaves the way it does, is because it also has these phenomenal qualities the system knows about.  Again, not adding any additional causal laws, just greater understanding and effing vision of all that is involved with such.\r\n\r\n\r\nAlso, my claim that glutamate has redness, is only an idealized theoretical possibility, not meant to be anything like reality, which I\'d bet is much more complex than this.  The hope with this idealized example is just to show one simplified theoretical possibility, to communicate the basic effing ideas I\'m trying to understand, and to provide at least one falsifying theoretical example to your claim of what you can prove.  The hope being that experimental neuroscientists can gain an understanding of the effing ideas, and then apply them to real theories that might be validated by real effing scientific demonstrations.\r\n\r\nSteven Lehar, my repeated request for help to you or anyone is, can you provide your thoughts on this issue?  What do you mean, when you talk of \'unifying gestalt\' principles, how do your wave theories work, and so on?  How is it that our knowledge of redness can be unified together with our knowledge of greenness - and mustn\'t the underlying neural correlates of such be more than simple discrete computational units like I describe above, or something?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-06-17 17:52:59','2012-06-17 17:52:59'),(2056,116,44,'How do you plan on discovering your phenomenal properties if they are by definition non-causal? What objective detector could register their existence if they have no physical impact. Your theory seems to be hooked on this idea of discovering phenomenal properties, or \'effing the ineffable\' (from my understanding), so what I - and maybe others - would like to know is: how you propose doing it even in principle?','2012-06-17 18:51:30','2012-06-17 18:51:30'),(2057,116,44,'Hey Jordan,\r\n\r\nThanks for helping out.\r\n\r\nBy the methods of overcoming the quale interpretation problem and effing the ineffable currently described in the Representational Qualia Theory statement.\r\n\r\nBasically, By first discovering the necessary and sufficient conditions required to reliably predict someone is experiencing my redness, to the degree required to enable such things as knowing if someone\'s redness is my greenness, or something I\'ve never experienced before.  Material Property Dualism is predicting there is sum stuff required, and without it, my redness will not be possible.  Functional Property Dualism is predicting some function is all that is required, independent of whatever stuff is implementing that function.  (which of course begs the question, what is this function, and what all phenomenal qualities can be discovered / achieved / effed and so on...???)\r\n\r\nAnd ultimately, integrating minds together, as V.S. Ramachandran first proposed, enabling multiple minds to experience the same redness qualia, unified into their world of consciousness.  (the  strong method of effing the ineffable.)\r\n\r\nAlso, another testable prediction is that Hans Moravec\'s transmigration idea of replacing neurons, one at a time, will ultimately fail, at some point of some of the neurons being partially replaced.  The experiencing brain saying, that part of the strawberry that was once redness, is no longer my redness.  But, if you continue, you\'ll be able to eventually fully simulate the entire system, as long as the entire system is interpreting the thing that isn\'t really redness, as if it really was.  The prediction is that this will be very difficult to do, as telling lies is always more complex than telling the real fundamental truth, as it really and fundamentally is.  If this does not happen, as predicted by MPD, it will clearly falsify this theory.\r\n\r\nAnd in the far distant future, say, maybe, as little as 50 or so years, if you go according to Kurzweil\'s optimistic predictions, doing effing uploading things like are described in the fictional narrative in the [http://home.comcast.net/~brent.allsop/1229.htm#_Toc22030742 1229 story].\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-17 19:13:48','2012-06-17 19:13:48'),(2058,116,44,'Oh, and this theory is predicting that phenomenal qualities are most definitely causal, it\'s just that the causality is a subset of the laws of physics we already know.  In other words, the reason we choose what strawberry to pick is because of its redness (which will appear, when only watching causally, as just glutamate.)  Being able to see this with effing systems that don\'t suffer from the quale interpretation problem, will just give us greater insights as to why it is picking the strawberry, beyond just having the causal properties of glutamate.\r\n','2012-06-17 20:12:49','2012-06-17 20:12:49'),(2059,116,44,'Why is it glutamate though and not the atoms that make up the glutamate? How would it make any more sense that red comes from the arrangement-ness that C5H9NO4 represents, or from the atomness. Why would any level of description of red be any more likely to cause red than red is to cause the other descriptions?','2012-06-17 22:00:26','2012-06-17 22:00:26'),(2060,116,44,'Reply to Brent:\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nSteven Lehar, my repeated request for help to you or anyone is, can you provide your thoughts on this issue? What do you mean, when you talk of \'unifying gestalt\' principles, how do your wave theories work, and so on? \r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nThere are two distinct paradigms of computation, a discrete, sequential algorithm like that followed by a pendulum clock, or a digital computer, that slice time into discrete intervals, and an analog continuous wave-like algorithm much like that followed by waves of water in a confined vessel. If you plunge your fist into any part of the water, every water molecule will immediately readjust its position to a new equilibrium state, with propagating waves of energy due to time delays and feedback whenever the input conditions change abruptly.\r\n\r\nOur system of logical thought, arithmetic, counting, music and dance, appear to be somewhat sequential and discrete, and that is why our first attempt at replicating our own cognitive processes appeared in the form of pendulum clocks, and digital computers.  \r\n\r\nBut there is another alternative paradigm of thought, the \"right brained\" holistic, analogical paradigm, and that paradigm appears to dominate our \"here and now\" conscious perception of our selves in our environment, which appear, in our experience, as a single unitary perceptual structure in the form of a surrounding space, complete with a model of our own body at the center of our experienced space. As long as we don\'t mistake this analogical experience for the real world that it attempts to replicate in effigy, we can see that th properties of the world of experience are manifestly analogical and reified, like an actual painted 3-D model, as opposed to the abstracted logical deductions we make from our experience, which do indeed appear to occur in a discrete sequential fashion.\r\n\r\nThe principal difficulty most people have in understanding this argument, is that they mistake the analogical spatial component of conscious experience as the world itself, that it represents in effigy. Once we can view the \"world around us\" for what it is, an image in our brain, only then can we appreciate the analogical nature of that representation.','2012-06-17 22:21:56','2012-06-17 22:21:56'),(2061,116,44,'Steven,\r\n\r\n\"\"here and now\" conscious perception of our selves in our\r\nenvironment, which appear, in our experience, as a single unitary\r\nperceptual structure in the form of a surrounding space, complete with\r\na model of our own body at the center of our experienced space.\"\r\n\r\nThis perception depends on the state of consciousness. Lose a few days of sleep and the boundary between interior and exterior realism can begin to break down.\r\n\r\n\"As long as we don\'t mistake this analogical experience for the real world that it attempts to replicate in effigy\"\r\n\r\nThere is nothing to suggest to me that there is any attempt to replicate anything. This view assumes that there is something there to begin with to replicate...like what? Quintillions of atoms broadcasting octillions of photons? Quantum flux oscillating meaninglessly in and out of vacuum? What real reality could there possibly be to replicate independent of what it is that is actually sensed - bodies, objects, surfaces, coherent patterns and designs, signifying texts, etc. This is as real as it gets. More real than any possible description of existence independent of sense.\r\n\r\n\"Once we can view the \"world around us\" for what it is, an image in our brain, only then can we appreciate the analogical nature of that representation.\"\r\n\r\nThere are no images in our brain. Images are in the universe\'s experience as us. If there were images in the brain, we would still need a homunculus in there too to see those images, who of course would need images in his brain, etc.\r\n\r\nThe world around us is more real than any world that could possibly exist in any universe. It is a human reality experienced directly through the brain, but not by the brain. It is experienced by the temporal hub of phenomenology known as the self. This lifetime is a unified experience of molecules, cells, brain, body, family, history, etc, localized to a particular spatiotemporal inertial frame arising from the circumstances of human development from a fused zygote.\r\n\r\nOnce we can view the \"world within us\" for what it is, the authentic source of our being, then we can appreciate the world as a representation of nothing but itself, a self-evident presentation of concrete realism which, although profoundly incomplete in comparison with more sophisticated extensions of itself, nonetheless remains the only source of sanity, truth, and understanding that can possibly exist.\r\n','2012-06-17 23:23:25','2012-06-17 23:23:25'),(2062,116,44,'Reply to Multisense Realism:\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nThere are no images in our brain. Images are in the universe\'s experience as us. If there were images in the brain, we would still need a homunculus in there too to see those images, who of course would need images in his brain, etc.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nStated with the confident dogmatism of the true Naive Realist believer!\r\n\r\nNo images in the brain eh? Are there images on the retina? Are there eyes to see those images? Are there images in cameras, and in computers? Are there eyes to see those images, and eyes in those eyes to see them? \r\n\r\nThe homunculus objection is the last refuge of the desperate naive realist, which has been refuted many times over! \r\n\r\nThere is no future in debating a dogmatist.','2012-06-18 09:54:50','2012-06-18 09:54:50'),(2063,116,44,'Steven,\r\n\r\n> \"Stated with the confident dogmatism of the true Naive Realist believer!\"\r\n\r\nIf that\'s what you think my position is, then I\'m not making myself understood. I consider the assumption of \'images in the brain\' to be the most common view in contemporary thought, and therefore the consensus wisdom extension of naive realism. We believe this because we understand that the brain is the seat of consciousness, and since we see images, then images must be in the brain.\r\n\r\nWhat I propose is neither a retreat from neuroscience nor an affirmation of naive realism. I propose multisense realism. We see a part of what is real and what we know as real seems that way in part because we see. That doesn\'t mean that what we see is all that there is to see or that what we see is what we would see if we were looking at objectively as a hypothetical disembodied voyeur.\r\n\r\n> \"No images in the brain eh? Are there images on the retina?\r\n\r\nNot unless there is a person there looking at the retina who can see images. There might be a few other species that could recognize them the optical character of the retina as having an image of some kind, but probably not what we would expect.\r\n\r\n> Are there\r\neyes to see those images?\r\n\r\nSure there are eyes, but eyes don\'t see our images, they allow us to focus and direct our sensitivity to radiant forms of matter, as well as communicate with other animals (including people of course).\r\n\r\n> Are there images in cameras, and in\r\ncomputers?\r\n\r\nNope. Inside of cameras and computers are invisible formations of microelectronic materials which we can transcribe to our eyes through a screen that allows us to see images through it\'s relatively isomorphic designs. A cat could see a can of tuna on such a screen but not know what it is. The image of the can doesn\'t exist independently of our shared subjective human experience.\r\n\r\n> Are there eyes to see those images, and eyes in those eyes\r\nto see them?\r\n\r\nEyes don\'t see images. The mind sees images through the eyes, or, perhaps just as often, directly in the imagination.\r\n\r\n> The homunculus objection is the last refuge of the desperate naive\r\nrealist, which has been refuted many times over!\r\n\r\nI think you are projecting what you want my argument to be on to what I wrote. \"If there were images in the brain, we would still need a homunculus in there too to see those images, who of course would need images in his brain, etc. \". I\'m pointing out the absurdity of the \'images in the brain\' position by saying that there would be an infinite regress of things needing to see - which is oddly what I seem to be accusing me of. What I\'m saying is that if our brain can see images, then it wouldn\'t need to put them inside of itself, it could simply use the eyes to see them in the outside environment...which is what I would suggest is going on, except that there aren\'t any images in the outside environment. If there were, we could just cut a hole in a blind person\'s skull and they could see, and hallucinogens would make changes to the world that others could see too.\r\n\r\n> There is no future in debating a dogmatist.\r\n\r\nSounds like a dogmatic statement to me ;)','2012-06-18 11:28:07','2012-06-18 11:28:07'),(2064,116,44,'This conversation highlights a significant deficiency of the RQT camp statement: The figure with the picture inside a person\'s head strongly suggests the kind of \'image\' that Craig (correctly) says does not exist. We have mostly done a good job of avoiding the term \'image\' in the prose, but we need to explicitly state that our use of the term \'model\' is intended to imply the kind of information within a computer, or the kind of information necessary to facilitate dreams, imagination, planning, etc., and not the kind of construct that would require (or could even make sense to be examined by) a homunculus.\r\n\r\nAlso, we should directly address the homunculus argument in the RQT statement, since it is the most common objection to representationalism. Steve, you wrote a book about that, right? Would you add a paragraph or two?\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit?disco=AAAAAEYaN0s&pli=1\r\n','2012-06-18 12:47:26','2012-06-18 12:47:26'),(2065,116,44,'Reply to Multisense Realism:\r\n\r\nObserve the after-image seen after viewing a bright light or camera flash.\r\n\r\nDoes the after-image have color? Does it have spatial extent? Where is it located? On your retina, or does it float in space before your eyes as perceived directly where it lies?\r\n\r\nThe after-image is clearly an image, it has spatial extent and even color. We know it to originate from our retina, yet we see it floating in space. This is undeniable PROOF that images can exist in our experience independent of objects in the external world.\r\n\r\nWhen you begin to redefine the meaning of \"images\" from the normal definition that everyone understands, to a new definition which denies images in cameras and computers (because there are no \'eyes\' to see them) is a sure sign of dogmatic paradoxy, a fundamental paradoxical flaw in your understanding which must be covered over by re-defining terms until black is white, and up is down, and there are no images in my experience even when I am having a dream or hallucination.\r\n\r\nI\'ve been around this merry-go-round a time or two already. This is like debating evolution with someone who believes in Creationism. You have already made up your mind, you can have your theory all to yourself. But you won\'t convince me by redefining ordinary terms just in order to deny the undeniable, vision is a representationalist set-up with the eye as a camera, the optic nerve as a data pipeline, and the visual cortex as an internal representation at the end of the causal chain. \r\n\r\nIf you deny even that most basic fact of neurophysiological reality, I\'m not about to debate it with you, your mind is already made up, and the error of your thinking is revealed by the paradoxes embedded in it, where images are not images and representations do not represent.\r\n\r\nBeen there, done that, waste of time!','2012-06-18 12:58:35','2012-06-18 12:58:35'),(2066,116,44,'Reply to Mike Gashler:\r\n\r\n>>>\r\n\r\nAlso, we should directly address the homunculus argument in the RQT statement, since it is the most common objection to representationalism. Steve, you wrote a book about that, right? Would you add a paragraph or two?\r\n\r\n<<<\r\n\r\nI\'m not familiar with the protocol for editing the camp statement -- I see some changes pending in yellow hightlight? Can I direct you to my refutations of the homunculus argument? I have several versions.\r\n\r\nHere under The Epistemology of Conscious Experience\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/epist/epist4a.html\r\n\r\nThis \"picture-in-the-head\" or \"Cartesian theatre\" concept of visual representation has been criticized on the grounds that there would have to be a miniature observer to view this miniature internal scene, resulting in an infinite regress of observers within observers. But this argument is invalid. For in fact there is no need for an internal observer of the scene, since the internal representation is simply a data structure like any other data in a computer, except that this data is expressed in spatial form. For if a picture in the head required a homunculus to view it, then the same argument would hold for any other form of information in the brain, which would also require a homunculus to read or interpret that information. In fact any information encoded in the brain needs only to be available to other internal processes rather than to a miniature copy of the whole brain. The fact that the brain does go to the trouble of constructing a full spatial analog of the external environment merely suggests that it has ways to make use of this spatial data. In other words, the brain employes an analogical paradigm of perceptual computation to make use of the analogical data in spatial perception.\r\n\r\nHere in Chapter 1 of my book\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/book/chap1.html\r\n\r\n(under heading An Analogical Paradigm of Representation)\r\n\r\nThis raises the question of why the brain goes to the trouble of constructing an internal replica of the external world, and why that replica has to be presented as a vivid spatial structure instead of some kind of abstract symbolic code. It also raises the philosophical question of who is viewing that internal replica of the external world. For if the presence of an internal model of the world required a little man, or \"homunculus\" in your brain to observe it, that little man would itself have to have an even smaller man in its little head, resulting in an infinite regress of observers within observers. But the internal model of the external world is not constructed so as to be viewed by an internal observer, but rather, the internal model is a data structure in the brain, just like any data in a computer, with the sole exception that this data is expressed in explicit spatial form. If a picture in the head required a homunculus to view it, then the same argument would hold for any other form of information in the brain, which would also require a homunculus to read or interpret that information. In fact any internal representation need only be available to other internal processes rather than to a miniature copy of the whole brain. The reason why the brain expresses perceptual experience in explicit spatial form must be because the brain possesses spatial computational algorithms capable of processing that spatial information. In fact the nature of those spatial algorithms is itself open to phenomenological examination, as I will show shortly. \r\n\r\nOn p. 38 of the same book I cite Steven Pinker making the same argument\r\n\r\nPinker (1984, p. 38) pointed out, however, that there is no need for an internal observer of the scene, because the internal representation is merely a data structure like any other data in a computer, except that these data are expressed in spatial form. In fact any information in the brain needs only to be available to other internal processes, rather than to a miniature copy of the whole brain. To deny the spatial nature of the perceptual representation in the brain is to deny the spatial nature so clearly evident in the world we perceive around us.\r\n\r\nIn my Gestalt Isomorphism paper:\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/webstuff/bubw3/bubw3.html\r\n\r\n6.1 The Cartesian Theatre and the Homunculus Problem\r\n\r\nThis \"picture-in-the-head\" or \"Cartesian theatre\" concept of visual representation has been criticized on the grounds that there would have to be a miniature observer to view this miniature internal scene, resulting in an infinite regress of observers within observers (Dennett 1991, 1992, O\'Regan 1992, Pessoa et al. 1998). In fact there is no need for an internal observer of the scene, since the internal representation is simply a data structure like any other data in a computer, except that this data is expressed in spatial form (Earle 1998, Singh & Hoffman 1998, Lehar 2003). For if a picture in the head required a homunculus to view it, then the same argument would hold for any other form of information in the brain, which would also require a homunculus to read or interpret that information. In fact any information encoded in the brain needs only to be available to other internal processes rather than to a miniature copy of the whole brain. The fact that the brain does go to the trouble of constructing a full spatial analog of the external environment merely suggests that it has ways to make use of this spatial data. For example field theories of navigation have been proposed (Koffka 1935 pp 42-46, Gibson & Crooks, 1938) in which perceived objects in the perceived environment exert spatial field-like forces of attraction and repulsion, drawing the body towards attractive percepts, and repelling it from aversive percepts, as a spatial computation taking place in a spatial medium. If the idea of an explicit spatial representation in the brain seems to \"fly in the face of what we know about the neural substrates of space perception\" (Pessoa et al. 1998 author\'s response R3.2 p. 789), it is our theories of spatial representation that are in urgent need of revision. For to deny the spatial nature of the perceptual representation in the brain is to deny the spatial nature so clearly evident in the world we perceive around us. To paraphrase Descartes, it is not only the existence of myself that is verified by the fact that I think, but when I experience the vivid spatial presence of objects in the phenomenal world, those objects are certain to exist, at least in the form of a subjective experience, with properties as I experience them to have, i.e. location, spatial extension, color, and shape. I think them, therefore they exist (Price 1932, p. 3). All that remains uncertain is whether those percepts exist also as objective external objects as well as internal perceptual ones, and whether their perceived properties correspond to objective properties. But their existence and fully spatial nature in my internal perceptual world is beyond question if I experience them so, even if only as a hallucination.\r\n\r\n\r\nThat tired old argument keeps coming back like a bad penny, even though its been refuted again and again. Because even people who hear the refutation refuse to acknowledge it as a counter-argument, because no mere logical argument is sufficient to shake them free of their comfortable naive realism!\r\n','2012-06-18 15:19:23','2012-06-18 15:19:23'),(2067,116,44,'Continuing to Mike Gashler:\r\n\r\nOh yeah, and here it is in the Cartoon Epistemology:\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/cartoonepist/cartoonepist42.html\r\n\r\nBut who is the viewer of this internal theatre of the mind? For whose benefit is this internal performance produced? Is it the little man at the center who sees this scene? But then how does HE see? Is there yet another smaller man inside that little man\'s head, and so on to an infinite regress of observers within observers? \r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/cartoonepist/cartoonepist43.html\r\n\r\nNo of course not! It only goes in one level! Take a look! What do you see inside your phenomenal head? I see nothing! It is an empty void! There is no infinite series of heads within heads, there is just a fuzzy brown emptiness with nothing inside, that opens to the world through the eyes like two open windows. ','2012-06-18 15:29:08','2012-06-18 15:29:08'),(2068,116,44,'> \"This is undeniable PROOF that images can exist in our\r\nexperience independent of objects in the external world.\"\r\n\r\nOf course we can have visual experiences that correspond to conditions inside of our body rather than outside of our body. We are experiencing the fatigue of our optical system in that area (retinal cells? bipolar cells? ganglia? all of the above?) in the native way that we do - as a visual feeling. This doesn\'t mean that the visual feelings we have of the \'external world\' are not the genuine presentation of our view of the world, and the world\'s only visually meaningful presentation in our experience.\r\n\r\n> \"When you begin to redefine the meaning of \"images\" from the normal definition that everyone understands, to a new definition which denies images in cameras and computers (because there are no \'eyes\' to see them) is a sure sign of dogmatic paradoxy\"\r\n\r\nWhen you begin to accuse anyone who suggests a new understanding and expresses it with a correspondingly reconsidered definitions of familiar terms of dogmatic paradoxy, then you prejudice the possibility of new discovery by limiting it to definition in inadequate terms. Image is fine for casual use, but when we are really trying to get to the heart of what image is, what good is it to say that we already know?\r\n\r\n> \"a fundamental paradoxical\r\nflaw in your understanding which must be covered over by re-defining terms until black is white, and up is down, and there are no images in my experience even when I am having a dream or hallucination.\"\r\n\r\nI would never say that there are no images in our experience, only that experience is not in the brain. There aren\'t any images in the brain or in the world, only in our experience. There isn\'t any comedy in the TV set, or in the brain of the TV viewer, only in the experience of the viewer watching TV.\r\n\r\n> \"and the visual cortex as an internal representation at the end of the causal chain.\"\r\n\r\nThat may not even be factually correct:\r\n\r\nhttp://cercor.oxfordjournals.org/content/9/1/4.full#sec-2\r\n\r\n\"Afferent Activation of Neurons in V1 May Not Generate a Visual Experience\"\r\n\r\nhttp://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=consciousness-does-not-reside-here\r\n\r\n\"They achieved the latter two conditions by asking them to monitor a series of single letters that appeared on the ring and to report the presence of a particular letter. On the other half of the trials, subjects were told to ignore these letters. In total, four conditions were tested.\r\n\r\nNote that the layout on the monitor always contains the same elements with the ring being projected into the same eye as the moving grating or the opposite eye, et cetera. The key difference was in the minds of the volunteers whose brains were scannedâ€”whether or not they consciously saw the grating (which they had to report) and whether or not they attended to it.\r\n\r\nThe cognitive neuroscientists measured the brainâ€™s functional MRI response in the primary visual cortex (or V1) in the brainâ€™s posterior\"...\r\n\r\n...\"Paying attention to the target consistently and strongly increased the fMRI activity, regardless of whether the subject saw the target or not.\"\r\n\r\nVisual cortex activity may be nothing but how we function in a visual world, and *not at all* a simulation generating machine.\r\n\r\nEven if it were though... simulating to whom? Where? You would ALWAYS need another homunculus layer to read it. Sooner or later something has to detect and make sense of something. We know that the end result looks like both the world, images of the world, and a world of images - all seamlessly present simulataneously in our daily experience, but no hint of any conversion on any level of physiological description. Physiology is the wrong place to look. We should be looking at time, not place.\r\n\r\n\"If you deny even that most basic fact of neurophysiological reality,\r\n\r\nI don\'t though. My view of your view is that it confuses conventional assumptions about how neurophysiology should be interpreted with reality. I question that the correspondence, not the reality.\r\n\r\n\"I\'m not about to debate it with you, your mind is already made up, and the error of your thinking is revealed by the paradoxes embedded in it, where images are not images and representations do not represent.\"\r\n\r\nYour defensiveness reinforces my sense that your argument, though well informed lacks curiousity and courage. Images cannot be representations without presentations. Presentations cannot exist unless they are being presented in some sense format. It\'s a case of overthinking perception and then denying the infinite regress that it entails. Again - sooner or later something has to make sense of something. Miniaturizing it until we are so impressed with our understanding of microphysiology changes absolutely nothing. There is still no point of representing the world to something that can already see the world, and there is no point in seeing an image of a world that can\'t really be seen.\r\n\r\nThe only answer that I see is that experience and physics are two aspects of the same phenomenon. I see no flaw possible in it other than it is unfamiliar to us and we are stuck on explaining the universe from the view of a hypothetical objective voyeur.','2012-06-18 15:36:41','2012-06-18 15:36:41'),(2069,116,44,'\"If a picture in the head required a homunculus to view it, then the same argument would hold for any other form of information in the brain\"\r\n\r\nRight. It does hold for all forms of perception. That\'s why I say that \'information\' isn\'t in the brain. Molecules and cells are in the brain. The brain and the information aren\'t \'in\' anything except our life. Damage to the brain changes our ability to be informed about ourselves and the world, but the computations of the brain merely organize our perceptions and experiences, not generate them. Experience cannot absent - it is the ground of being.\r\n\r\n\"But this argument is invalid. For in fact there is no need for an internal observer of the scene, since the internal representation is simply a data structure like any other data in a computer, except that this data is expressed in spatial form. \"\r\n\r\nNo, that argument is invalid. There is no data structure in a computer, there are only physical microelectronic switching sensors. The computer doesn\'t need to represent it\'s data *in any way whatsoever* to itself. The computations are literal events happening to the substances being electronically stimulated, it has no need to project a magical \'vision-like-experience-of-space\' into it\'s functions.\r\n\r\nEven if it did, why pick vision? Space can be represented as a tactile experience, acoustic, vestibular, even olfactory. There is no conceivable purpose for, or mechanism of sense which would not be 100% redundant with blind, unconscious information transfer. Just unplug your monitor and see if your computer gets lost without it. Pull out the video card. Does it mind? Does it need a seeing eye dog now?\r\n','2012-06-18 16:28:19','2012-06-18 16:28:19'),(2072,96,48,'@omgpop:\r\n\r\n\"how do you actually propose subjective experience arises from\r\nneural events?\" \r\n\r\nI don\'t know. I just know how it DOESN\'T happen. It doesn\'t happy through any form of PD. If I had to guess, then I would predict that it has something to do with a recursive model, modeling itself. \r\n\r\n\"Like, do you really and truly deny that there is any logical distinction between the objective stuff that we measure, and the subjective stuff that we feel?\"\r\n\r\nI don\'t think that there can be any true or deep distinction. \r\n\r\n\"Or do you think that there is a difference, but it can be explained without positing a different fundamental material?\"\r\n\r\nAll I know is that causal laws explain behavior. And that experience lives up the causal chain from behavior. Therefore, experience must be an emergent property of the casual laws of nature and nothing more. Any \"MORE\" would be epiphenomenal, and my experiences aren\'t epiphenomenal. To pull a \"Brent\", then I would say that Brent\'s experiences might be epiphenominal, but mine aren\'t. I often wonder if Brent really has real experiences like mine, because I am convinced that if he did, he would understand that his experiences can\'t be epiphenomenal. :-P\r\n\r\n','2012-06-18 17:52:24','2012-06-18 17:52:24'),(2075,96,48,'In Post #119, Steve writes \"...if water had no awareness of its own dynamic processes, then so would we also, we would all be zombies!\"\r\n\r\nI don\'t see why; as it stands, this is a non sequitur. It is not necessary for all dynamic processes to be aware in order for some dynamic processes to be aware. \r\n\r\nHe goes on to identify voltages with numbers. This is a category mistake.\r\n\r\nI agree with the gist of Steve\'s last paragraph. The brain actively maintains a representation/model of the world. From outside we observe neural activity which is the NCC. From inside, it seems like we perceive the world but naive realism is false: we\'re actually part of the model.\r\n\r\nTo get back on topic, if we are deluded or hallucinating or dreaming then our perception is mistaken: it only seems as if we are chatting to a pink elephant about panexperientialism. Is this the use of \"seeming\" that Dennett is using when applied to qualia?\r\n\r\n','2012-06-18 18:28:43','2012-06-18 18:28:43'),(2076,116,44,'@Brent: \"As he should, James keeps taunting me and pointing out the fact that I haven\'t yet adequately provided a falsifying example of what he claims he can \'prove\'. (Even though in my mind, I\'ve successfully attempted such, many times, already.)\"\r\n\r\nIf you think that you have come anywhere close, then you have no idea what I am looking for. Before the rest of you get too far down the wrong path, let me explain. The universe consists of states of matter, s. Let the state of matter at time t be, s_t. The universe has a transition function f. Right? With me so far? Ok, the transition function, f, is either deterministic (if you believe in the MWI of QM), or else it is completely random with absolutely no pattern or intentionality (if you believe in the copenhagen interpretation of QM). Thus, in the deterministic case: So s_{t+1})=f(s_t); and in the non-deterministic case: So p(s_{t+1})=f(s_t).  Ok, still with me?\r\n\r\nNOW, let\'s posit something \"else\", anything \"else\". We will call it e, for \"else\" and \"experience\". Now, write down the function for the state transitions such that the else affects the state transitions, but can\'t be written as part of the state. What you immediately notice is that there is no way to do this. It can\'t be done. If you try (and I have tried), you end up creating a system that can always be re-written with a \"super\" state, that contains the old state and e, with a new transition function. \r\n\r\nIf you try and write it as a Bayesian network, you can try and write e in a manner similar to that of a hidden markov model, with e \"hidden\" from outside observers, but visible from the first person perspective only. But if you do that, then you have created something that is observable ONLY from the first person perspective, but that affects (and is affected by) the third person perspective. The problem here, is that we are pretty darn sure that the third person perspective is enought to account for all the causal behavior. Which means that we can observe all the objective state necessary to constrain the probability of the next state of the system. So if there is anything \"more\" going on here, that \"more\" doesn\'t constrain the next state of the system... that makes it epiphenomenal. I really don\'t understand why this rather obvious observation is so hard for people to grasp. \r\n\r\nFor example, Brent writes: \"But, doing so would only miss the important theoretical possibility I think is critically important - that there are more than such discrete computational units possible in known physical reality...My argument is that there is some system in the brain that can accomplish this achievement, that must be more than such simple discrete units of computation.\"  But this misses the point that these \"discrete computational units\" ARE sufficient to characterize the behavior of the system, and even to characterize and track the third person objective states of the matter making up the system! So what does that mean? It means, yet again, that if there actually is anything \"more\" than these computational units, then they don\'t affect the third person objective reality in any way, and thus are epiphenominal!!!!! I don\'t know why that remarkably obvious observation is so hard to understand, and I must admit to a certain bit of frustration in my attempts.\r\n\r\n\"But, the prediction is that when we discover the phenomenal qualities of the same, this will provide additional insight into why the particular causal behaviors behave the way they do, in a way that appears to cause the glutamate to cause us to select the strawberry.\"\r\n\r\nIn other words, Brent is proposing that e affects s through t... something like s_{t+1}=f(e_t,s_t) and e_{t+1}=f(e_t,s_t). Further, he is suggesting that, to date, we have been ignoring e, and mistakenly proposing s_{t+1}=f(s_t)... and that once we add this extra ingredient, we will suddenly realize how much simpler the equation with the \'e\' in it is, and we will better understand WHY things have the causal properties that they do. I WISH Brent would be formal about this, so I wouldn\'t have to guess what he is thinking from his ambiguous text, but this is at least what I THINK he is saying. In any event, this is essentually proposing that e is a hidden node in a network, at least hidden from the third person perspective. But this makes predictions about how the states of matter should behave. Information (that effects the next state) has to be pushed into e, and then flow out of e to affect the next s. If this were not the case, we could leave it out, and ignore it when computing the state transitions (meaning it would be epiphenomenal). To see why this flow of information is needed, just consider that the objective effects of the perception process needs to inform our experience of the strawberry (so information MUST flow INTO e form the previous states). Then note that for the experience to affect the future objective state (to avoid epiphenomenalism), this information must now be allowed to flow OUT of e, and back into s. There are two ways that this could happen... 1. in a straightforward deterministic way (where no \"processing\" happens hidden back in e), and 2 in a more complex way. \r\n\r\nIn the case of 1, we see that we can always simplify the equation by taking e out, and we get the same objective result. Therefore there is no reason to believe in e, not even our \"feelings\" of qualia, since we can account for all the motion of the atoms in our brains without it, and thus account for our claims, beliefs, and memories of qualia without it. If taking e out does impact the objective state, such that you can\'t predict the next state accurately without taking it into account, then we actually have case 2. \r\n\r\nIn case 2, we find that this theory has a very powerful objective prediction which is not met in our observations. We should SEE information appear to \"vanish\" form the objective third person reality, only to then impact future objective states in strange ways. Yet this prediction has not been observed in reality. That\'s not how matter and energy behaves. Instead, the third person state is enough to predict the probability of the future state, and Bells equation even tells us that there is no extra hidden state that accounts for the randomness of the Copenhagen interpretation of QM.  \r\n\r\nSo, it would seem that Brent\'s theory (if I understand it correctly) has already been falsified. If I don\'t understand it correctly, then by all means, explain it formally in stead of handwavey so that I can understand it better. ','2012-06-18 18:41:11','2012-06-18 18:41:11'),(2079,96,48,'Reply to richwill:\r\n\r\n>>>\r\n\r\nIn Post #119, Steve writes \"...if water had no awareness of its own\r\ndynamic processes, then so would we also, we would all be zombies!\"\r\n\r\nI don\'t see why; as it stands, this is a non sequitur. It is not\r\nnecessary for all dynamic processes to be aware in order for some\r\ndynamic processes to be aware.\r\n\r\n<<<\r\n\r\nBut then you will have to determine which processes do and which don\'t, with a plausible explanation of why. Consciousness appears on a continuum along the evolutionary hierarchy, and again during the gestation of the individual, with incremental progress from stage to stage. If you declare at some stage consciousness magically steps into existence, where there is only an incremental change in the neural architecture, you are saddled with the issue of epiphenomenal consciousness, there is no way to test from the outside whether consciousness is experienced on the inside.\r\n\r\nInstead, it is simpler to say that a primal form of qualia pre-existed sentient creatures, otherwise there would have been no \"raw material\" out of which evolution could have evolved conscious experience.\r\n\r\nIts like a painting composed of colored paint on canvas. The painting cannot exist unless the paint and canvas existed first, to make it possible to modulate the paint across the canvas in the pattern of the painting.\r\n\r\nPan-psychism resolves the profound issue of epiphenomenal consciousness.','2012-06-18 18:58:06','2012-06-18 18:58:06'),(2082,96,48,'#jlcarroll\r\n\r\n\"All I know is that causal laws explain behavior.\"\r\n\r\nSince the only function of \'causal laws\' is to explain behavior, how do you know that there are any causal laws at all? I would say that behavior causes lawful appearances to those who can perceive appearances of law. Any more than that would require some sort of cosmic legislation and enforcement system.\r\n\r\n\r\n\"And that experience lives up the causal chain from behavior.\"\r\n\r\nThough understandable and almost universally assumed (in scientific theory at least), there is no reason to assume that experience of some sort does not live on ever level of behavior, and that causality is not from low level behavior to high level experience, but between low and high level experiences seen from the outside as low and high level behaviors. Our behaviors don\'t cause an experience to manifest for the United States as a subjective entity, rather our experience as Americans contributes to the experience of ourselves and others around the world of what the US is like.\r\n\r\n\"Therefore, experience must be an emergent property of the casual laws of nature and nothing more. \"\r\n\r\nIf we make the wrong assumptions, then our erroneous conclusions will match perfectly.\r\n','2012-06-18 19:45:52','2012-06-18 19:45:52'),(2083,116,44,'Canonizer enforces its own protocol for edits. Unfortunately, it was too cumbersome for all of the changes necessary to separate dualism into child camp of RQT. We made that Google Doc so we could all just edit freely (ala Wikipedia). If some change goes back and forth a few times, then we should stop and discuss it, but we\'ll never get anything done unless we just start doing it. So there is deliberately no protocol beyond reasonable courtesy. I think the risk of vandalism should be pretty low in a group like this, and it wouldn\'t matter much anyway since it is not yet ready to be ported to Canonizer. So, I\'ll eventually get to it, if no one else does it first.','2012-06-19 00:44:56','2012-06-19 00:44:56'),(2084,116,44,'Ah, Thanks James,\r\n\r\nThat was what I was mainly asking for here, help in formalizing this stuff, so thanks a bunch for all this.  It is helping, but I feel I have a long way to go before Iâ€™m good at it.\r\n\r\nSo let me see if I can describe what I think of as the quale interpretation problem, in our perception process, in this formalized way?\r\n\r\nPerception process:\r\n# s_t		glutamate reflecting light.\r\n# s_{t+1}	light transducing to neural signals via retina.\r\n# s_{t+n}	multiple neural processing steps to build our knowledge.\r\n# s_{f-1}	Last abstracted building knowledge step before final knowledge.\r\n# s_f		final conscious experience of knowledge of glutamate redness.\r\n\r\ns_f = final_function(s_{f-1})\r\n\r\nBut of course, since glutamate reflects â€œwhiteâ€ light, our brain simply represents it, in this final state, with something that is very different than glutamate.  In other words, the final_function is where the problem is, as it determines what to use to represent it\'s referent, which is very different.\r\n\r\nAre there any hidden variables, or anything odd, in all that?\r\n\r\nAlso, weâ€™re saying it must have additional causes, or it must be epiphenomenal, but isnâ€™t there another possibility, in that it could be more fundamental?\r\n\r\nIf we take some other fundamental natural phenomenon, like say voltage generated across a wire, when it is moved through a magnetic field.  Maybe this magnetite field has some hidden quality, which is what is causing, the voltage.  Since it is â€˜hiddenâ€™ we just think there is no reason for the voltage.  Kind of a bad example, but isnâ€™t something like this a possibility?  Couldnâ€™t the reason glutamate behaves as it does, be because of its phenomenal qualities, if we could only observe such?\r\n\r\nBut I still think itâ€™s best to just think of phenomenal qualities as simply a different way to perceive a certain state of something, which has a specific set of causal properties.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\nP.S.  It looks like we are very close to having a new RQT statement everyone can agree with, yay!  Thanks, Mike for keeping us moving on this!!\r\n\r\n','2012-06-19 02:19:15','2012-06-19 02:19:15'),(2085,116,44,'Craig writes in post#15:\r\n\r\n\"I would never say that there are no images in our experience, only that\r\nexperience is not in the brain. There aren\'t any images in the brain or\r\nin the world, only in our experience. There isn\'t any comedy in the TV\r\nset, or in the brain of the TV viewer, only in the experience of the\r\nviewer watching TV. \"\r\n\r\nSo where is the experience and what is its relationship to the brain?','2012-06-22 15:06:07','2012-06-22 15:06:07'),(2088,96,48,'In post #117 Mike agrees with me that a computer simulation of a neuron is distinctly different from the neuron but then goes on to write, \"A simulated consciousness could only have simulated experiences. If a wetware man told a software man that his experiences were not real, and the software man replied, \'they seem real to me\', would it even matter who was right? Why?\"\r\n\r\nA simulated experience isn\'t an experience and that matters because we have experiences and computer simulations don\'t.\r\n\r\nMike: \"...then a voice from heaven calls down \'Thou hypocrite! You are running inside my Universe and I have a new video game that I want to play on it.\'\"\r\n\r\nNot possible because there are no experiences in a computer simulation so we could not be part of such a simulation.','2012-06-22 15:23:41','2012-06-22 15:23:41'),(2089,116,44,'\"So where is the experience and what is its relationship to the brain?\"\r\n\r\nExperience is always \'here\' and \'now\'. Human experience is a very complex and richly elaborated kind of experience which, when observed in all of the terms of the pre-human levels of zoology, biology, chemistry, and physics is represented as the activity of the nervous system. At that level, \'we\' do not exist.\r\n\r\nThink of objects-in-space as a flat horizontal plane which intersects a perpendicular vertical plane of experiences or subjects-through-time. In order to represent experience as an object, all of the qualitative depth must be flattened, like the whole history of botany and future of all apple tree orchards is condensed as an apple seed object.\r\n\r\nIt\'s all part of one continuum, but experience is to the brain what a story is to a book. One does not cause the other, they are just  embodying opposite ends of the universal continuum of presentation.','2012-06-22 15:25:02','2012-06-22 15:25:02'),(2090,1,49,'Jordan, i don\'t see that it matters whether you call it a property, an aspect, a dimension or a substance; this is Cartesian dualism: you have two ontologically distinct categories, the phenomenal and the physical. The main problem then is that never the twain shall meet. Descartes struggled to account for the interaction between mind and matter since it\'s logically impossible in the dualist scheme ;)\r\n\r\nYou write, \"...no one is saying, for example, that time is a separate \'substance\' from space. It is simply another dimension, or axis, of the universe.\"\r\n\r\nAgreed, because time and space are (deemed) physical, along with matter and forces. You say that your phenomenal dimension is not experimentally accessible, that means it\'s not physical and so you\'re in the same boat as Descartes.\r\n\r\nDoes it not seem odd to you that we experience events in sequence?\r\n','2012-06-22 16:22:38','2012-06-22 16:22:38'),(2093,96,48,'Steve, in your post #125 you write \"...Instead, it is simpler to say that a primal form of qualia pre-existed sentient creatures,\"\r\n\r\nEven if it were simpler, i don\'t think it\'s correct. Sentient creatures are conscious because of some activity of their brain. This means that consciousness is a property only of brains or similar structures. It arises during normal brain development in the foetus and individuals lose consciousness every time they fall asleep (or receive a blow to the head etc.) because that activity ceases. This account seems simple enough to me and is much more plausible than positing some mysterious \"primal form of qualia\".\r\n\r\nYou go on to write that \"Pan-psychism resolves the profound issue of epiphenomenal consciousness.\"\r\n\r\nQuite the opposite: the pansychic gap is unbreachable, rendering  consciousness logically epiphenomenal. Identity theory resolves the issue: if consciousness is neural then it is within the causal nexus.','2012-06-24 11:12:52','2012-06-24 11:12:52'),(2096,96,48,'Reply to richwil:\r\n\r\nWhy should consciousness be restricted to brains or similar structures? The electrical communication between neurons is just a special case of high amplitude communication that occurs at lower amplitude between all living cells.\r\n\r\nConsider the case of a paramecium, the tiny single-celled creature...\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/HRez/HRez22.html\r\n\r\nthat waves its tiny cilia in coherent wave-like motions\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/HRez/HRez24.html\r\n\r\nBeing of course a single cell, this creature has no nervous system at all. And yet it has coherent waves of undulation that sweep along the creature\'s body, it can modulate those oscillations to steer left or right in search of food, and it can even reverse them to back up and escape a dead end.\r\n\r\nI propose that this tiny creature has a tiny and simple consciousness that is experienced as waves of energy that it feels it has conscious control over. The creature has no real self-awareness besides the awareness of its cyclic undulations, and it certainly has neither memories nor aspirations, just this very simple primal swimming.\r\n\r\nIf you declare this creature to be totally unconscious, then our own consciousness is forever a profound paradoxical mystery. Why do we have consciousness at all? This invites a dualism that some minds are conscious, others are not, and there is no physical distinction between them! You can go ahead and believe that if you like. I have a simpler explanation.\r\n\r\nConsciousness is NOT an epi-phenomenon, it is simply the subjective feeling of normal physical processes, what it is like to BE those processes, as opposed to just observing them from the outside.\r\n\r\nThis would put to rest the endless and futile debates on this forum such as the recent...\r\n\r\n>>>\r\n\r\nJordan, i don\'t see that it matters whether you call it a property, an aspect, a dimension or a substance; this is Cartesian dualism: you have two ontologically distinct categories, the phenomenal and the physical. The main problem then is that never the twain shall meet. Descartes\r\nstruggled to account for the interaction between mind and matter since it\'s logically impossible in the dualist scheme ;)\r\n\r\n<<<\r\n\r\nThe twain need never meet because they were never separate, they always were an identity. Mind is nothing other than the physical processes of the physical brain.\r\n\r\nIt is only our antrocentric naive realism that makes us think consciousness is unique to brains.\r\n\r\nIf you are really interested in this topic (yeah yeah, sure sure, I\'m just saying IF you were really interested) you could read the whole story here:\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/GrandIllusion.pdf\r\n\r\nBut that takes too long. Besides your mind is already made up. I\'m just saying ... the answers are already out there if anyone wanted to hear them.','2012-06-24 11:48:34','2012-06-24 11:48:34'),(2099,96,48,'Steve,\r\n\r\nI agree with you completely. Now I invite you to go on to the next step and see that anthropomorphism extends to dualism itself. We are as much the subjective experiences of a human organism as a human organism is the objective vehicle for human-level phenomenology. \r\n\r\nThey are in fact one thing which seems like two because of our role as biased participant in this continuum. We are the head end, so we see the tail as different, but the universe has no such distinction. Without our \'mortal coil\' to insulate us from the universe of all times and experiences, to step it down into a diffracted beam of personal identity over a lifetime, a fleeting thought is as solid as the Grand Canyon. Our minds are as much of a place as supermarket or library.','2012-06-24 14:02:36','2012-06-24 14:02:36'),(2100,35,43,'Hi Rich,\r\n\r\nThanks so much for all your great contributions to canonizer.com.  I really like and agree with the very intelligent things you have to say.\r\n\r\nI just have one request though.  Most traditional op/ed, Blog, Forums and so on are designed to have everyone state their own opinion about what they believe.  The obvious problems with such systems is everyone doesn\'t have time to read a million individual posts, to find out what a million people believe.\r\n\r\nCanonizer.com is meant to overcome this problem, but in order to do so, the contributors need to work to push to switch from this traditional kind of thinking and individual posting.\r\n\r\nThis is all just my opinion, so take it only as such, and I recognize that you may disagree, so if you do, that is great.  Just take it as only my opinion.\r\n\r\nFor example, it seems to me much of the stuff in this Self-centred VR is duplicated from the Representational Qualia Statement.  So, in order for people to know what you believe, much of the stuff they need to read twice.\r\n\r\nAlso, you state many things in your camps that I, and I\'m sure the consensus agrees with, but it in a way which implies everyone else disagrees with you.  For example, my understanding of self-centred VR includes this doctrine that consciousness is: [http://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/32/127#127 \"Not possible because there are no experiences in a computer simulation so we could not be part of such a simulation.]\r\n\r\nI\'m sure most people in the property dualism camp would agree with this, but since you are stating as a competitor to that camp, it implies that nobody in that camp agrees with you.\r\n\r\nIt helps when everyone works most with the consensus camps, rather than lonely individual blog like camps, with the goal of having the fewest possible camps, making it that much easier for the general population to find out what everyone believes, while reading the fewest possible camps.\r\n\r\nSo, in general, rather than creating your own lonely camp, it\'s better to find the closest consensus camp, and start making it into what you think it should be, to perfectly represent what you believe.  And only then fork new camps, after you\'ve exhausted every possibility to build consensus on the most things possible.\r\n\r\nAnother example of this is regarding this same doctrine as the reason why [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/48/5 Uploading is not an option].  Again, I, and I\'m sure everyone in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/48/3 We would consider phenomenal uploading] agree with this doctrine.  But the way you\'ve created a competitor to this camp it implies that none of us agree with you, which is very misleading to readers to imply this by creating competitor camps like this.\r\n\r\nWhen you say \"uploading is not an option\", what exactly, do you mean?  Certainly you must believe that we will soon be architecting artificially conscious Self-centered VR beings, significantly more capable, in every phenomenal way, than our brain, and that we will also be doing the same to our own brain?  The way you have your comp position now, it seems to imply that you think none of this is possible?  Do you just not consider this kind of stuff as not \'uploading\'?  If so, the camp structure is currently very confusing to readers, or failing to communicate this kind of important stuff concisely and quantitatively.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-24 17:30:48','2012-06-24 17:30:48'),(2103,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nI cleaned up what I think was the last issues with the current draft of the statement by removing the paragraphs about Daniel Dennett, as was proposed.  I also added a small section about the homunculus argument that was proposed.  I think we are very close to a version of a statement we can all agree with, so thanks everyone for all the work.\r\n\r\nThere is one final issues I\'d like to proposing about \'effing\' of the ineffable.  I\'ve talked with various people about this, on both sides, and I believe we are all in agreement that, via various methods consistent with all of our theories, one way or another, that we all agree that effing of the ineffable will some day be possible.  So I\'ve proposed one more one paragraph section, labeled \"Effing of the Ineffable\", that basically says this.\r\n\r\nSo, I\'d ask that you\'d all review this, and the rest of the statement, and let us all know what you think - especially if there is anything anyone still objects to, any typos or anything.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-25 03:23:48','2012-06-25 03:23:48'),(2106,96,48,'\r\n\r\nOh, I intended on providing the link to the Google doc draft, for those who don\'t have it handy:\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit\r\n\r\nThanks\r\n\r\nBren tAllsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-25 03:25:21','2012-06-25 03:25:21'),(2109,96,48,'Reply to Multisense Realism:\r\n\r\n>> \r\n\r\nI agree with you completely. Now I invite you to go on to the next step ...\r\n\r\n<<\r\n\r\nWait a minute! Aren\'t you the guy who denies that there is an image on the retina, and that the visual cortex is a representation?\r\n\r\nI\'m sorry, but with respect, anyone who denies that there is an image on the retina, doesn\'t understand the FIRST THING about vision! This is the problem with debates on consciousness,  they seem to attract these extremists who try to persuade us of the absurd, and do it so dogmatically as to hijack the entire debate and turn it into a massive re-definition of terms such as an image is not an image and a representation is not a representation, and even a camera does not have an image in it and all that nonsense! \r\n\r\nAnd if you carve down through all the layers of denial, we find at the bottom a simple defense of naive realism! I\'m sorry, I\'m not going down that rabbit hole! I BEGIN with the assumption that there is an image on the retina, which is sent up  the optic nerve to the brain, where that image is elaborated to a full 3-d experience. If you accept that much to begin with, I can debate with you. But if you are in denial of even those basic facts, you are not in need of a proof, you are in need of a cure!\r\n\r\nSorry, can\'t help you!','2012-06-25 09:23:54','2012-06-25 09:23:54'),(2112,96,48,'I cannot understand this response to the homunculus argument. Can anyone explain the gist of it to me? Here\'s my attempt to respond to the homunculus argument in one paragraph--you can tell me if my attempt is flawed or no less confusing.\r\n\r\nThe homunculus argument is a common argument against representationalism. It demonstrates that a representation in a vacuum is insufficient to explain consciousness by asking the question, \'who experiences the representation?\'. This question implies that creating a representation makes no progress toward experiencing anything. We respond that it does make progress, which we now identify: The value of a representation is that the representation exists in the same information or thought form that the brain is able to interact with. (The brain cannot very well reach out and interact with the world, but it can easily operate on its own representation of the world.) Although we admit that creating a representation alone is insufficient to explain consciousness, we claim that creating a representation alone is sufficient to explain awareness, and we define consciousness as awareness coupled with the ability to act on it. Hence, representationalism explains the part of consciousness that is otherwise difficult to explain. The rest can be explained with a simple decision-making technique. To experience something is to be aware of it, and to be able to act on it. To the question raised by the homunculus argument, \'who experiences the representation?\', we answer that the same brain which creates the representation is able to act on it, and thus it meets the two components that define an experience.','2012-06-25 10:16:00','2012-06-25 10:16:00'),(2115,96,48,'Reply to Mike Gashler:\r\n\r\nRepresentationalism, while necessary to explain how we experience external entities, is not sufficient as an explanation of the mystery of consciousness, or how we can be conscious of anything.\r\n\r\nThe alternative, naive realism, does NOT resolve that mystery either, in fact it DEEPENS the mystery to give us direct conscious experience of objects outside of our head, beyond the sensory surface, which is DOUBLY magical and inexplicable, and STILL does not answer the question of how we can be conscious of anything.\r\n\r\nThe homunculus objection is invalid, because a representation does not require a complete copy of the brain to observe the representation, as we can see so clearly demonstrated in a digital computer, that can read the data of its internal images without use of a homunculus.\r\n\r\nThe response of the naive realists is to insist that there are no images in computers, because if there were, then that would show the homunculus argument is invalid, and would provide a concrete demonstration of the principle of representationalism, and that it actually works and can be built in real hardware, and that in turn is so damaging to the cause of naive realism that they have to DENY THE OBVIOUS and insist that an image is not an image UNLESS THERE IS A HOMUNCULUS TO OBSERVE IT, and since the homunculus is impossible, thus there are no images in the brain!\r\n\r\nIt is just plain MADNESS! And they are all so dogmatically passionate about it, it feels like arguing religion with a believer!\r\n\r\nThe homunculus issue is a ridiculous straw-man that has been refuted  many times over, why are we still wasting time over this one!','2012-06-25 12:02:16','2012-06-25 12:02:16'),(2118,96,48,'Reply to Steve,\r\n\r\n> \"Wait a minute! Aren\'t you the guy who denies that there is an image on the retina, and that the visual cortex is a representation? \"\r\n\r\nThat\'s a contradiction. If you believe that the visual cortex is the source of all visual representation, then all images belong there, \"in\" the cortex, and nowhere else. Not on retinas or TV sets, photographs, etc.\r\n\r\nWhat I am saying is that images are not things that exist as information-theoretic objects in space, but rather as interpretive subjective experiences through time (although those experiences can be carried to the subject by the arrangements of objects in space)\r\n\r\n> \"anyone who denies that there is an image on the retina, doesn\'t understand the FIRST THING about vision! This is the problem with debates on consciousness, they seem to attract these extremists who try to persuade us of the absurd, and do it so dogmatically as to hijack the entire debate and turn it into a massive re-definition of terms such as an image is not an image and a representation is not a representation, and even a camera does not have an image in it and all that nonsense! \"\r\n\r\nWhat you are saying sounds pretty dogmatic and extreme to me. Tell me, if all animals died on the planet, would cameras still have images in them? Would a world of plants and bacteria know what a human image looks like? Would an ant colony be able to find any similarity between a perfect picture of a flower and the real thing? I submit that they would find no similarity, and that this fact means that images are a subjective visual feeling and not an objective physical phenomenon.\r\n\r\nIf you doubt my familiarity with the physiology of visual sense, my post here: http://s33light.org/post/25223690381 might clarify that.\r\n\r\n> \"we find at the bottom a simple defense of naive realism\"\r\nNot at all. Multisense realism honors all experiences in their own contexts. Having a hallucination doesn\'t mean that there is some universe where the pink elephant is real, only that in this universe what you are can really hallucinate. In a way, it is the hallucination that exposes the reality of perception, not the unreality of subjectivity. Our waking life is the hallucination, drugs only expose the fact to us. At the same time, our subjective experience may seem private and ephemeral to us, but that too is a hallucination. We have no reason to assume that the universe has that same bias.\r\n\r\n> \"I BEGIN with the assumption that there is an image on the retina, which is sent up the optic nerve to the brain\"\r\n\r\nI assume that you know about studies where subjects wear glasses that invert the retina image? Eventually they begin to see it as right side up. Looking at ambiguous \'images\', like this: http://multisenserealism.files.wordpress.com/2012/01/aslide7.jpg we see that we can have a degree of voluntary control of our visual interpretation. We are not passive recipients of externally stable optical phenomena, we shape the optical phenomena into images. Who we are and what we have experienced influences the qualities and significance of the visual experience. It is not \'out there\' - not on pixels, not on paper, retina cells, or the visual cortex. No more than comedy or irony is encoded in the bits of an mpeg file. That is not to say that optical arrangements are not the vehicle or stage upon which visual images are projected - of course they are, but there is an ontological chasm separating them. These small images you are reading now do not exist if your eyes do not belong to someone who can read English. That is what I mean when I say there are not objectively images in cameras or retina. There are qualitative changes to substances which we interpret as images, nothing more.\r\n\r\n>\"Sorry, can\'t help you!\"\r\n\r\nOh I know, but it\'s ok I don\'t need any help. It\'s a shame too, because I respect your accomplishments, but it seems that you are no longer curious about what you think you know. You have your views neatly lined up so that they all agree with each other. So, as they say on the interwebz \"Why U Mad?\"','2012-06-25 12:46:05','2012-06-25 12:46:05'),(2121,96,48,'Re: Homunculus\r\n\r\nThe reason why representationalism creates an infinite regress is that Plato\'s Cavedwellers still need to be able to see shadows in the first place. It doesn\'t matter how beautifully represented your Chinese script is, I still can\'t read what you think it is supposed to mean.\r\n\r\nIf my brain can see anything at all, why doesn\'t it just see the patterns of the world \'out there\' directly instead of converting it into jiggling Vitamin A molecules, glutamate flow interruptions, and ganglion twitchings first? If the brain can learn its own vocabulary of billions of synaptic phonemes, why not just learn the vocabulary of photons directly as the retina does? Representation without presentation is a figment of our over-familiarity with symbols. We think that because computer data looks like a video game to us that the video game is made of computer data. It isn\'t. The computer no more knows what a basketball player looks like than I know how to read Chinese.\r\n\r\nI understand why representationalism seems to make so much sense, and I agree that it is almost exactly right, but once you can stop taking pattern recognition *ALL pattern recognition* for granted, then you will see why representation does nothing except move the hard problem from outside the body to inside the brain. There is still no plausible explanation for any experience to appear in connection to the brain if the brain already has all of the information that it is representing as that experience. Totally redundant and superfluous. Totally unexplainable as an evolutionary adaptation. It only makes sense the other way around. Not as naive realism, as Steve keeps non-dogmatically ASSERTING IN ALL CAPS, but as a multisense realism. \r\n\r\nWe are complex as hell. We are legions of phenomenological experiences acting as one, and one phenomenological experience acting as many. Naturally there is conflict among all of these layers. Different agendas which are hashed out through compromise that leaves some presentations to seem less real or significant than others. All representation is a presentation of meaning, but not all presentations represent something other than what they appear to be. Blue is blue. Pain is pain. They do not refer to any physiological mechanism, although it is through physiology that we come to know them. They are ours.','2012-06-25 13:08:24','2012-06-25 13:08:24'),(2124,96,48,'Well, when I made the suggestion, I thought addressing the homunculus argument would help to clarify RQT, since it is the only major objection I have ever encountered, but I will still be happy if the camp statement does not bring up the issue.','2012-06-25 19:26:56','2012-06-25 19:26:56'),(2127,96,48,'\r\nI tried to find who was proposing we add something about the homunculous argument, but couldn\'t find who it was.\r\n\r\nI think it at least deserves a small mention, even if only to point out that almost nobody accepts this as a good argument anymore.  Especially if whoever proposed this addition can explain why they think we should have this.  Like do you know of anyone in particular still throwing such an argument at you anyplace, recently?\r\n\r\nI shortened what I had there, and hopefully made it more clear.  Mike, is the new version any better?  I had troubles understanding you\'re proposed version.\r\n\r\nOther than this last issue, is everyone OK with everything else there?\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-27 00:58:23','2012-06-27 00:58:23'),(2130,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nYes, this version is much better. I am content with the whole thing.\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit?disco=AAAAAEM_LjA\r\n\r\nmike','2012-06-27 01:27:15','2012-06-27 01:27:15'),(2133,96,48,'In reply to post #129:\r\n\r\nSteve,\r\n\r\nI draw the line between conscious and non-conscious life forms in a different place. IMO cells - and that includes single cell life forms and neurons - are automata. The necessary activity for consciousness requires neural networks i.e. brains. \r\n\r\nYou write that my view that a brain (or similar) is necessary for consciousness \"invites a dualism that some minds are conscious, others are not, and there is no physical distinction between them!\" I don\'t claim this as it would be a contradiction ;) There is a clear physical distinction between organisms with brains and those without.\r\n\r\nI agree with you that consciousness is not epiphenomenal and is \"the subjective feeling of normal physical processes\". What we disagree on is *which* physical processes.\r\n\r\nI do not subscribe to naive realism: please explain why you think i do.\r\n\r\nYou misunderstand my comment to Jordan: i am objecting to dualism in the form of property dualism as i hold to identity theory.\r\n\r\n','2012-06-28 17:40:15','2012-06-28 17:40:15'),(2134,35,43,'Brent\r\n\r\nMuch as i enjoy intellectual debate, i am in favour of consensus and hope we can reach this through canonizer.\r\n\r\nI try to be concise ;) When the new RQ statement is finalised i\'ll review and revise this camp statement.\r\n\r\nAt present, i don\'t see compatibilty between this camp - which proposes an identity theory and is therefore monist - and property dualism. This is why i\'m discussing the issue in the property dualism camp forum.\r\n\r\nI need to contrast computer simulation with the VR i\'m talking about. There are plenty who believe computational functionalism and my opposition is to that.\r\n\r\nNot sure i understand your point about uploading. Why must i believe that we will soon be architecting artificial consciousness and what has that to do with real consciousness or uploading? This issue obviously requires more work :) \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-06-28 18:26:04','2012-06-28 18:26:04'),(2137,96,48,'Hi Rich,\r\n\r\nYou are making a mistake about what the new â€œproperty dualismâ€ camp is about.  From your perspective, maybe this is not a good name for this camp.  The only fundamental doctrine of the current â€œproperty dualismâ€ camp is simply what youâ€™ve stated with consciousness is â€œnot possible because there are no experiences in a computer simulationâ€ \r\n\r\nYou claim you are objecting to â€œdualismâ€ and hold to identity theory, but this is completely inaccurate.  You should be able to notice the consensus sub camp, under property dualism, is â€œMind Brain identity Theoryâ€.\r\n\r\nYouâ€™ve repeatedly said you agree with the fundamental doctrine in â€œProperty Dualismâ€ camp, you just disagree with what it is that has this consciousness.  And of course, that is the purpose of all the sub camps, underneath Property Dualism, mostly all proposing the different mechanism and levels which have this consciousness that canâ€™t exist in simulations running only on abstracted simulations.\r\n\r\nWhat name would you use for this idea that there is consciousness that cannot exist on a simulation running on purely abstracted data?  Perhaps we should rename the camp to whatever you think this is, rather than property dualism?\r\n\r\nThe bottom line is you are very much confusing readers, when you claim to be an identity person, and that property dualists are not.  So please help as get this straight, consistent, and help us show the fact that we (at least you with us property dualist identity people) agree.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-28 19:07:10','2012-06-28 19:07:10'),(2140,96,48,'\r\n\r\nWohoo!  It looks like we\'ve finally got a great statement everyone supports.\r\n\r\nI\'ve started a new Google doc proposal for a new Property Dualism camp statement here:\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1gginaif0YTvDVSwFF7V_wRei-SDZlelt0LPIc5I_gD8/edit\r\n\r\nI just wanted to throw that out there before we submit this new statement for RQT, to get everyone\'s thoughts, both pro and con.  For all supporters of Property Dualism, and for people like Rich Wilson, if you object to any of that, please let us know and I hope you\'ll all help us improve it.\r\n\r\nThanks All!!\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-06-29 02:23:37','2012-06-29 02:23:37'),(2143,96,48,'Brent Allsop\r\n\r\nI propose we send an e-mail something like the following to Dr. Dennett, before we canonizer this new proposed version of the Property Dualism statement.\r\n\r\n=================\r\n\r\nHello Dr Dennett,\r\n\r\nWe are working on the Consciousness Survey Project at Canonizer.com, which seeks to get a real time concise and quantitative description of the leading theories of consciousness, and to hopefully put an end to all the useless infinite back and forth bickering and failure to communicate on this issue.\r\n\r\nThere is a new emerging camp called Representational Functionalism with a significant number of proponents very supportive of your views on consciousness.  However, the current leading camp is attacking the view, usually attributed to you, that we don\'t have qualia, \"it just seems like we do\".\r\n\r\nThese people that support your view have proposed that you don\'t really mean what you seem to be saying with such.  Instead, they argue that perhaps you just mean we do have qualia, it\'s just that they aren\'t what they seem (such as something that can\'t be represented by abstracted ones and zeros).\r\n\r\nThe leading \"Property Dualism\" camp, is proposing a new version of its camp statement containing this attack against supporters of your view.\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1gginaif0YTvDVSwFF7V_wRei-SDZlelt0LPIc5I_gD8/edit\r\n\r\nBoth camps would very much like to know your true thoughts on this issue, in which case we could likely significantly improve the statements on both sides of this issue.\r\n\r\nRegards,\r\n\r\n  Brent Allsop\r\n  Volunteer - Consciousness Survey Project\r\n','2012-06-29 02:47:32','2012-06-29 02:47:32'),(2146,96,48,'Brent, re your post #134:\n\n\"You are making a mistake about what the new â€œproperty dualismâ€ camp is about.\"\n- The mistake i made was to support the propert dualist camp in the first place.\n\n\"From your perspective, maybe this is not a good name for this camp.\"\n- Seems a good name to me. Property dualism is the theory that there are phenomenal properties and there are physical properties: this is ontological dualism focussed on properties and so the term \"property dualism\" is appropriate.\n\n\"The only fundamental doctrine of the current â€œproperty dualismâ€ camp is simply what youâ€™ve stated with consciousness is â€œnot possible because there are no experiences in a computer simulationâ€.\"\n- A fundamental doctrine? Some property dualists (computational functionalists) believe that computers have, or can be programmed to have, phenomenal properties and some don\'t.\n\n\"You claim you are objecting to â€œdualismâ€ and hold to identity theory, but this is completely inaccurate.\"\n- No, this is accurate: i am a monist and don\'t agree with dualism.\n\n\"You should be able to notice the consensus sub camp, under property dualism, is â€œMind Brain identity Theoryâ€.\"\n- Of course i have noticed. It doesn\'t make sense to me: how can an identity theory, by definition monist, be compatible with a dualist theory?\n\n\"Youâ€™ve repeatedly said you agree with the fundamental doctrine in â€œProperty Dualismâ€ camp, you just disagree with what it is that has this consciousness.\"\n- Denying computational functionalism is not the fundamental doctrine of property dualism. I have considered dualism incorrect for many years longer than i\'ve been with canonizer. I had some misgivings when the camp was brought in but mistakenly went along with it because i was persuaded that property dualism wasn\'t really dualism at all. While i agree that the brain has mental and physical properties, i don\'t agree that there is any ontological distinction between the two.\n\n*Perhaps this is where i agree with Dennett: there isn\'t an ontological distinction between the physical and the mental though it seems that there is?\n\n\"The bottom line is you are very much confusing readers, when you claim to be an identity person, and that property dualists are not. So please help as get this straight, consistent, and help us show the fact that we (at least you with us property dualist identity people) agree.\"\n- The confusion arises from the contradiction in terms of \"dualist identity\". Identity denies duality, pure and simple.\n ','2012-07-02 16:06:56','2012-07-02 16:06:56'),(2149,96,48,'\r\nHi Rich,\r\n\r\nThanks for this.  This really helps amplify my wisdom on this issue to see it from this different perspective.\r\n\r\nBut I still think you are mistaken, on multiple issues.\r\n\r\nI think you are confusing substance dualism with property dualism.  If we ever get some substance dualists, we\'ll probably have to push property dualism down a level to make room for them in the \'dualism of all types\' camp.  But for now it is unanimously property dualists, and the clear expert consensus even amongst these is for mind brain identity.\r\n\r\nLet me ask you what you mean, when you say there is no conscious experience in a computer.  Because that difference (i.e. there are two types of things, things that can be simulated in a computer, and things that cannot.) which is the only \'dualist\' thing the supporters of property dualism are talking about.  It is just qualities of things, or different ways to look at the same stuff.\r\n\r\nWhen you are the only one that can\'t see what all these experts see, when they claim to be both \"mind brain identity\" and \"property dualists\", this is strong evidence that you are missing something.  You need strong evidence to make any such extraordinary claim if you expect anyone to trust you, or read your lonely single supported camp statement, going against that much of an expert consensus.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\nP.S.  Please don\'t lead lines longer than about 30 characters with spaces, as that messes up the formatting and puts the entire paragraph on one line.  And check things before you post them.  I cleaned your original post up.\r\n\r\nAlso, Multisense, please avoid the kind of picture formatting you did, as that much forced width also really messes things up for all the other posts in the thread, and it makes it hard to see the kind of errors Rich made, when they preview things.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-03 02:04:35','2012-07-03 02:04:35'),(2152,96,48,'Folks,\r\n\r\nWow, all the help from everyone is so helpful!  And it so amplifies my understanding of all this to see it in ways I can understand, from all the different perspectives.\r\n\r\nJames and Rich have made some very great suggestions and comments in the google doc that has really helped.\r\n\r\nJames pointed out that the argument against the \'it from bit\' doctrine doesn\'t belong in the Property Dualism camp because many Functional Property Dualist which are in a sporting sub camp, believe in this doctrine.\r\n\r\nSo I pushed this down to the Material Property Dualism level.  And I (at least in my opinion) greatly improved this argument and expanded it to include both the causal properties and phenomenal qualities of this \'it\'.  And I point out how mistaken it is to think that an abstracted \'bit\' can produce or \'carry\' anything that is in any way fundamental, whether such be a causal property or a phenomenal quality of \'it\'.  I point out how this is worse than saying it only seems like we have qualia.\r\n\r\nAt the same time, I also rewrote Macro Material Property Dualism, to include a simplified version of that theory, referenced by the parent camps, to better communicate the more general effing ideas that should also work in competing / more complicated theories.\r\n\r\nAlso, here is a final draft of the letter I intend on sending to more than Just Dr. Dennett.  See the list contained in that letter for links to the Google doc proposed statements.\r\n\r\nAs always, let me know what you think - especially if you are a supporter of any of the camps of these proposed new statements that would object to any of these proposed changes.\r\n\r\nThese are all huge and revolutionary theoretical leaps forward, and I\'m very much looking forward to them going live - and I bet with some press releases about such we can make some significant noise with all this, far beyond the noise we\'ve accomplished with previous press releases about achievement in the past.\r\n\r\n=====================\r\n\r\n\r\n* To: Daniel Dennett, Keith Frankish\r\n* Cc: Richard Brown\r\n* Subject: Clarification about some speculation by some experts about your thinking on consciousness?\r\n\r\nHello Dr.s Daniel Dennett and Keith Frankish,\r\n\r\nWe are working on the Consciousness Survey Project at Canonizer.com, which seeks to amplify the wisdom of participating experts by collaboratively developing a real time concise and quantitative description of the leading theories of consciousness, and to put an end to all the useless infinite yes / no / yes / no back and forth bickering and failure to communicate on the important issues.\r\n\r\nThere is a new emerging camp being called Representational Functionalism (see: http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/18 ) with a significant number of expert proponents very supportive of the views on consciousness supported by both of you.  However, the current leading consensus camp at that level is attacking the view, usually attributed to Dr Dennett, that we don\'t have qualia, \"it just seems like we do\" [Consciousness Explained P. 375].\r\n\r\nThese experts that support your view have proposed that you don\'t really mean what you seem to be saying.  Instead, they respond by saying that perhaps you just mean we do have qualia or phenomenal knowledge, it\'s just that this knowledge isn\'t what it seems (such as something more fundamental than what can be represented by abstracted ones and zeros).\r\n\r\nThe leading \"Property Dualism\" camp, (for the current canonized version of this camp see: http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/19) is proposing a new version of its camp statement containing this attack against supporters of your view.  Here are some links to the proposed Google doc versions of this, and related sub camp statements containing this attack.\r\n\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gginaif0YTvDVSwFF7V_wRei-SDZlelt0LPIc5I_gD8/edit Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1dogSoCsouz2RhQ-CTNjtnYJ8Xr6JILNDki5Kn_met_o/edit Material Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V03WBMSY5cKf97NoM6KPZSKtxEEHg5MZJfb6FPq0Ui0/edit Macro Material Property Dualism]\r\n\r\nYou can also see the public forum thread with subject: \"Asking Dan Dennett\" where we\'ve developed this proposal to ask you for clarification on these issues here:\r\n\r\nhttp://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/32/138#138\r\n\r\nBoth camps would very much like to know both your true thoughts on this issue, in which case we could likely significantly improve the statements by removing all the current speculation going on about what you might really be thinking.\r\n\r\nHopefully,\r\n\r\n  Brent Allsop\r\n  Volunteer - Consciousness Survey Project\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-05 04:32:07','2012-07-05 04:32:07'),(2155,96,48,'\r\nOh, and I\'m also going to CC my old friend Marvin Minsky, to try to get his thoughts, also.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-05 05:06:01','2012-07-05 05:06:01'),(2158,96,48,'\r\nAnd my other old Friend Hans Moravec.\r\n\r\n','2012-07-05 05:08:40','2012-07-05 05:08:40'),(2161,96,48,'You proposed that we write: \r\n\r\n\"These experts that support your view have proposed that you don\'t really mean what you seem to be saying. Instead, they respond by saying that perhaps you just mean we do have qualia or phenomenal knowledge, it\'s just that this knowledge isn\'t what it seems (such as something more fundamental than what can be represented by abstracted ones and zeros).\"\r\n\r\nI would say this differently. I would say instead:\r\n\r\nThese experts that support your view have proposed that you don\'t mean that we don\'t have some subjective experiences. It would be tautologically false to say, \"we don\'t have the experiences that we seem to have, we just seem to have them.\" Instead, they suggest that you are saying something like \"we don\'t have experiences that have any magical properties beyond the causal structure and dynamics of physics, it just seems like we do.\" Is this an accurate expression of your theory? If not, how would you simply word your theory?\r\n\r\nWhat do you all think about replacing the original paragraph with this one? It more accurately represents what us in RF think that he is claiming. \r\n\r\nJames','2012-07-05 19:53:13','2012-07-05 19:53:13'),(2164,96,48,'jlcarroll,\r\n\r\nIf the causal dynamics of physics had any of the qualities (ie qualia) that we actually experience, then we would not be having this discussion. \r\n\r\nThe use of the word \'magical\' to describe qualia reveals the intention to straw man the issue rather than address or understand it.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-05 20:10:45','2012-07-05 20:10:45'),(2167,96,48,'You wrote: \r\n\r\n\"If the causal dynamics of physics had any of the qualities (ie qualia) that we actually experience, then we would not be having this discussion.\"\r\n\r\nI disagree, obviously. The theory here is that qualia SEEM to require something more, but don\'t actually require something more. \r\n\r\n\"The use of the word \'magical\' to describe qualia reveals the intention to straw man the issue rather than address or understand it.\"\r\n\r\nYes, I know, but the point of the email in question is to capture Dr. Dennett\'s theory... and HE thinks that proposing something \"more\" is \"magical\", he even uses optical illusions from magic to make the point. So if we are trying to produce a sentence that accurately captures his view, the use of the term \"magical\" is highly appropriate. \r\n\r\nIt also just so happens that I agree with him. But that\'s not the point here. \r\n\r\nBut if you want to wander off point, here we go. I don\'t think that my use of the term \"magical\" actually is a strawman. I am well aware that people like Chalmers think that these extra properties aren\'t magical, that\'s why he calls PD \"natural dualism\". But *I* think that I can show that if there is anything beyond the structure and dynamics of physics involved in consciousness, then that extra ingredient is epiphenomenal. I KNOW that people like Brent don\'t think that it is... but I think that it is impossible to find a theory that matches what they describe that isn\'t epiphenomenal. So what *I* believe, is that anything \"more\" must indeed be epiphenomenal (and thus, magical). In other words, it\'s not a straw man in the sense of picking something that my opponent doesn\'t believe, and beating that down... rather, I am picking what my opponent believes, attempting to show that it inexorably produces something they don\'t believe, and then beating that down. That\'s not a strawman argument. \r\n','2012-07-05 20:20:49','2012-07-05 20:20:49'),(2170,96,48,'\"The theory here is that qualia SEEM to require\r\nsomething more, but don\'t actually require something more.\"\r\n\r\nHow is SEEMing possible in physics alone? That alone requires something more. Seem to whom? Quantum?\r\n\r\n\"I am well aware that\r\npeople like Chalmers think that these extra properties aren\'t magical\"\r\n\r\nNobody thinks that these properties are magical. The word qualia exists to make that explicit. Whether they can be tied to physics directly or not, they are not in directly recognizable as what we think of as physics.\r\n\r\nEven if qualia, or anything else for that matter, was epiphenomenal, how does physics allow for that either? What physical law causes any possibility of epiphenomena?\r\n\r\nThink of it this way: \r\nIf qualia were nothing but epiphenomenal representations of brain states then every drug would be a hallucinogen. Your morning cup of coffee would have to transport you into a world where there is an objectively stimulating series of precise events to justify your change in brain chemistry. You could not just \'feel happy\' because that would invoke a forbidden layer of qualia in between neurochemistry and the contents of our experience.\r\n\r\nMy idea is this. Physics is the inside of Plato\'s Cave. When we leave the cave we have access to our full complement of human sensitivities and motives, well beyond the range of those which can be detected and understood using inanimate objects as instruments. What you and Dennett are doing is pointing to the fact that since we see shadows both inside and outside the cave, that all of the bright color and crisp 3-D images we \'seem\' to see \'outside\' are merely epiphenomena and the only true reality is in the interplay of shadows. Mathematical forms rendered to us without bias or sentiment.\r\n\r\nThis would be making a case for naive realism though - which I don\'t. It turns out that the shadows seem to make a sense of their own, which extend our understanding far beyond the colors outside. The cave is good and real too, just in a very different way. In fact, the shadows tell us everything about what we *are not* and what we think is the inside of the cave is really just another kind of outside, and the outside is really just another kind of cave. Both caves are inside and outside of each other, and everything in the entire universe is made of this caving-uncaving anomalous symmetry (anomalous since the inside is \'vertical\': infinitely personal, temporal, and signifying while the outside is \'horizontal\': infinitely impersonal, spatial, and generic.)','2012-07-05 21:09:12','2012-07-05 21:09:12'),(2173,96,48,'\"How is SEEMing possible in physics alone? That alone requires something more.\"\r\n\r\nAre you sure? Or does it just seem that way?\r\n\r\nJames','2012-07-05 21:31:49','2012-07-05 21:31:49'),(2176,96,48,'\"Are you sure? Or does it just seem that way?\"\r\n\r\nYes. Physics is designed specifically not to be able to seem like anything except what we have actually proved it be. You have to decide whether you want to amputate consciousness, as Dennett does, so that everything fits into your mold of naive materialism or whether your physics includes magical epiphenomena and seeming emergent properties.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-05 22:15:56','2012-07-05 22:15:56'),(2179,96,48,'\"Yes. Physics is designed specifically not to be able to seem like\r\nanything except what we have actually proved it be.\"\r\n\r\nWe don\'t get to design reality. \r\n\r\n\"You have to decide whether you want to amputate consciousness, as Dennett does, so that everything fits into your mold of naive materialism or whether your physics includes magical epiphenomena and seeming emergent properties.\"\r\n\r\nYour only evidence for that is that by introspection your own consciousness SEEMS like it is something more than structure and dynamics. But this introspection may not be accurate. And \"emergent properties\" may be more powerful than you thing. \r\n\r\nAnd to suppose ANYTHING else, is to suppose epiphenomena. So I reject it. ','2012-07-05 22:20:01','2012-07-05 22:20:01'),(2182,96,48,'\"We don\'t get to design reality. \"\r\n\r\n1. Physics is not the only reality.\r\n2. We design reality all the time, including physical realities. The internet for example is a physical reality that is designed.\r\n\r\n\"Your only evidence for that is that by introspection your own consciousness SEEMS like it is something more than structure and dynamics. But this introspection may not be accurate. And \"emergent properties\" may be more powerful than you thing. \"\r\n\r\nEvidence is nothing more than that which persuades us introspectively. My point is that if you claim physics or materialism then you have no right to use the word \'seem\'. Seem doesn\'t physically exist. When you doubt introspection, you only believe in your own disbelief. Ultimately you have only your own word to take for the existence of anything.\r\n\r\nEmergent properties are ridiculous to me. Anything that doesn\'t fit naive materialism can be be swept into that category - but for what? What explanatory power does it have to use that term. How is \'emergent\' different from \'magically emergent\'?\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-06 02:30:09','2012-07-06 02:30:09'),(2185,96,48,'>>>>\r\n\r\nEmergent properties are ridiculous to me. Anything that doesn\'t fit naive materialism can be be swept into that category - but for what? What explanatory power does it have to use that term. How is \'emergent\' different from \'magically emergent\'?\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nEmergence is indeed the key to the consciousness problem. It is the un-magical \"magic\" that makes emergent wholes emerge out of seemingly nowhere.\r\n\r\nThe most impressive examples of emergence is seen in the Chladni figures (pronounced \"kladnee\") where sand or powder on vibrating steel plates reveals the emergent patterns of resonance.\r\n\r\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_Chladni\r\n\r\nThat is EXACTLY the way that consciousness emerges from the otherwise random patterns of activation in the brain.\r\n\r\nAnd it is for exactly that reason that we find periodic patterns to be aesthetically pleasing, whether patterns on our clothing, wallpaper, pots, the rhythmic beating of drums, the harmonies and melodies of music, the symmetrical and periodic movements of dance, and even the periodicity evident in our number system and throughout math, are all evidence for a resonance principle in neurocomputation, and that resonance principle is an emergent entity that seems to appear \"out of nowhere\", and yet this magical holistic emergence can be replicated by simple physical systems.\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nIf the causal dynamics of physics had any of the qualities (ie qualia) that we actually experience, then we would not be having this discussion.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nThey do, but we still are.\r\n\r\nThats what you get from arguing with a guy who denies that there is an image on the retina!\r\n\r\nIf the causal dynamics of physics did NOT have any of the qualities that we experience, then WE WOULD EXPERIENCE NOTHING!\r\n\r\nThe fact that I do experience something is final and conclusive proof that a physical process (mind) taking place in a physical mechanism (brain) can be conscious.\r\n\r\nQuad erat demonstrandum.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-06 12:40:40','2012-07-06 12:40:40'),(2188,96,48,'\"The most impressive examples of emergence is seen in the Chladni\r\nfigures (pronounced \"kladnee\") where sand or powder on vibrating steel\r\nplates reveals the emergent patterns of resonance.\r\n\r\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_Chladni\r\n\r\nThat is EXACTLY the way that consciousness emerges from the otherwise\r\nrandom patterns of activation in the brain.\"\r\n\r\nBut the patterns only \'emerge\' to us because we are conscious. If you have certain parts of your visual cortex damaged or compromised chemically, those patterns will not emerge for you, and indeed without specifying an a priori sense of awareness in the sand or powder itself, there can be no pattern at all. Even the most basic pattern of one grain touching or not touching another assumes some kind of sense that can tell that particular difference. Can they hear each other? Can they see the group from a distance of several (human) inches? \r\n\r\nWithout consciousness of some kind to recognize it *there is no such thing as pattern of any kind*. This isn\'t debatable in my view. It is ontological. We are so used to thinking in terms of visual-tactile sensation that we literally cannot imagine that it is not a given. I don\'t make that mistake but I have to constantly remember to be aware of it.\r\n\r\nEmergence is indeed the magic that makes the de-presentation of awareness seem palatable. It makes the disappearance of appearance seem plausible with an intellectual sleight of hand that takes the very awareness we are trying to plumb entirely for granted.\r\n\r\n\"yet this magical holistic emergence can be replicated by\r\nsimple physical systems.\"\r\n\r\nYou are implying that a movie of John Wayne means that the actor is being replicated by celluloid frames. It\'s a problem, and not one that can be resolved. This is what Searle\'s Chinese Room and Leibniz Windmill are saying. Detecting a pattern does not mean that the pattern exists independently of detection. Forms can inform but they are not information in and of themselves. Qualia is in the eye of the beholder(s), and ultimately there is nothing that is not qualia to some category of beholders. What we see of patterns in sand is not what sand sees, any more than a statistical map of energy consumption in the world is what consumers of energy experience, but I think that behind all pattern is a sense relation that extends before the beginning of time and throughout all forms in space.','2012-07-06 13:38:13','2012-07-06 13:38:13'),(2191,96,48,'\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nQualia is in the eye of the beholder(s), and ultimately there is nothing that is not qualia to some category of beholders. \r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nThat there is your paradigmatic initial assumption. You believe this to be the primary fact of vision, and you shoe-horn the rest of your understanding to fit in that shoe.\r\n\r\nAnd thats why ultimately you are forced to even deny that there is an image on the retina.\r\n\r\nThe rest of us open-minded seekers of the truth, begin with the FACTS of the case: The eye works like a camera, the retina a photosensor array, the optic nerve a data pipeline, the visual cortex a representation. Thats where you find yourself when you follow the obvious and verifiable FACTS of the case. \r\n\r\nIf you take that line of reasoning one step farther (and this is the step-too-far for most) the world that you see around you IS the image in your brain. THAT is what you so forcefully deny, for you it is inconceivable, because you refuse to let go of your naive realist illusion that you can see the world directly. That leads to a truly magical view of vision, one that could never in principle be replicated in hardware, because people and their consciousness is MAGIC, whereas machines are just machines.\r\n\r\nBut you have to deny factual reality to preserve that initial assumption which you refuse to ever question, it is the one \"fact\" (false) that you are absolutely certain of, all else is open  to negotiation.\r\n\r\nI\'ve been around this merry-go-round a time or two already, I now make it a policy not to debate with people who deny that there is an image on the retina, or that the cortex is a representation. That is a dogmatic quasi-religious belief, people who hold it refuse to let go. I am only responding here, not to try to convince you otherwise, that is a lost cause. But as an example to others on this forum (is anybody listening?) of how totally futile it is to debate with people who don\'t know the FIRST THING about how vision works, because they are NOT honest seekers of the truth, they are missionaries bent on propagating their nonsensical self-contradictory beliefs on everyone else WITHOUT ever giving the other party the respect of ENTERTAINING THE POSSIBILITY that your initial assumption might be in error, and to discuss the possibility of how things would be if we temporarily and provisionally suspend that belief, and consider, just for a moment, that maybe the world around you IS the image in your brain, and THEN explain why that could not possibly be WITHOUT recourse to your absurd claim that there are no images in the brain, which in turn forces you to claim the ABSURD, that there is not even an image on the retina because there is no homunculus there to observe it!\r\n\r\nThis is always what happens in these debates on consciousness, there is always a naive realist TROLL who takes over the debate and tries to convince everyone else that there is no image on the retina!\r\n\r\nIf you want to see how these futile debates go round and round, check out this:\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/cartoonepist/discussion.html\r\n\r\nIn particular, this Debate with Bill Adams\r\n\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/cartoonepist/AdamsDebate.html\r\n\r\nBill is a thoughtful and articulate psychologist who seemed to have an earnest desire to come to agreement over this issue, but if you follow the debate you will see how he refused again and again to consider EVEN AS A THEORETICAL POSSIBILITY that his initial assumption might be in error. That one point he would refuse to negotiate, and thus the whole debate was futile. Go read Bill\'s arguments -- there is no image on the retina, there are no images in cameras, I\'ve been through the whole thing, and in the end, it is just a defense of naive realism. Pure and simple! Like the flat-earthers who refuse to believe that the whole world is spinning in space, and thus the Apollo moon landings must have been faked, and on and on to ever increasing absurdity if someone is fool enough to debate them.\r\n\r\n','2012-07-06 14:35:49','2012-07-06 14:35:49'),(2194,96,48,'\"And thats why ultimately you are forced to even deny that there is an\nimage on the retina.\"\n\nThere isn\'t even a retina on the retina without something to make sense of it in exactly that way. We can make sense of \'a\' retina as an ocean of molecules, or quantum state fluctuations, living cells, layers of tissue, parts of an animal organ, or our own eye. There is no retina that simply exists - it\'s a cartoon of reality.\n\n\"The eye works like a camera, the retina a photosensor\narray, the optic nerve a data pipeline, the visual cortex a\nrepresentation. Thats where you find yourself when you follow the\nobvious and verifiable FACTS of the case.\"\n\nIt is not the eye that works like a camera, it\'s the camera works like an eye - only a camera doesn\'t see, it only stores a reflection event so that we can see it later.\n\nThe optic nerve is a community of human cells, as is the visual cortex. There are no representations that physically exist in the system - only presentations experienced by ourselves through many specialized and generalized parts of the nervous system.  I don\'t see any facts in your description, only a reductive opinion that misrepresents a biological reality with an information-theoretic fantasy.\n\n\"because you refuse to let go of your naive realist\nillusion that you can see the world directly\"\n\nNot at all. I have never said that we see *the* world directly, only that we see whatever there is for us to see as human beings and individuals having a human life. That we see directly, and it is our world, but it isn\'t THE world. Nothing can see THE world, because it doesn\'t exist independently of sight. It is you who refuses to let go of your naive abstractionist illusion that nothing has ever been seen directly.\n\nHow is it that we see these representations in the visual cortex, and why are they any more acceptable than simply seeing the presentations of the world?\n\n\"But you have to deny factual reality to preserve that initial\nassumption which you refuse to ever question\"\n\nNot at all. I have always questioned it until recently, when I see that disbelief in our own sense is really nothing but belief in another layer of abstracted sense. Our senses are not universal, but neither are they solipsistic simulations. They are absolutely genuine - even in delusion or hallucination, they still are authentic experiences which cannot be meaningfully reduced or substituted.\n\n\"futile it is to debate with people who don\'t\nknow the FIRST THING about how vision works\"\n\nIt is equally futile to debate with people who turn every debate about ideas into a string of personal accusations. I don\'t know how vision works? I guess you don\'t read my blog. http://s33light.org/post/25223690381\n\n\"WITHOUT ever giving the other party the respect of ENTERTAINING THE POSSIBILITY that your initial assumption might be in error\"\n\nI don\'t have an initial assumption - I AM an initial assumption and I am not \'in error\'.\n\n\"and consider, just for a moment, that maybe the\nworld around you IS the image in your brain\"\n\nI have considered that comforting assumption for most of my life - probably 30 years. How is the simple fact that there are no visible images inside the tissue of the brain an \'absurd claim\'? If I am a missionary it is because I understand now that there IS NO IMAGE in your brain but only in the experience of something who can see. If there were actual images in the brain, we wouldn\'t need a brain to store them in the first place, we could just drill a hole in our empty skull and let the images flow directly into our body, which would respond mechanically to what it sees. Why convert an image into a non-image and then back into an (invisible) image which can now somehow be seen? You don\'t find anything odd about that system?\n\n\"in the end, it is just a defense of naive realism. Pure and\nsimple!\"\n\nUm, no. My view is multisense realism and there is nothing naive about it at all. I specifically identify naive realism (ACME) as a pathologically extreme potential of consciousness, with naive functionalism (OMMM) as the conjugate monosense unrealism.\n\nWhat you hold up as the pinnacle of scientific sophistication I view as well intentioned but ultimately childish reliance on assumptions about how physical mechanisms seem to work and nothing to do with what awareness actually is.','2012-07-06 15:48:20','2012-07-06 15:48:20'),(2197,96,48,'\r\nCraig asked:\r\n\r\n    How is it that we see these representations in the visual cortex,\r\n    and why are they any more acceptable than simply seeing the\r\n    presentations of the world?\r\n\r\nThe answer to this is contained in an idealized theoretical description of the visual cortex contained in the proposed new version of the Macro Material Property Dualism statement.\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1V03WBMSY5cKf97NoM6KPZSKtxEEHg5MZJfb6FPq0Ui0/edit\r\n\r\nIn the visual cortex there is a 3D array of neurons representing the 3D space we are â€˜seeingâ€™.  These voxel neurons have a pallet of neurotransmitters they can fire with, which have the various phenomenal colors like redness and greenness.  In other words, these neurons phenomenally paint our knowledge of what we see.  There is also a binding system which enables all these pixels of phenomenal paint to be unified together into one experience.  In this idealized description, a single large binding neuron is considered.\r\n\r\nOf course, this is an idealized view, and reality will be a bit more complicated than this, but the general effing possibility that exists in this idealized and simplified theoretical world will also be possible in reality.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\nP. S.  Craig, you also lead a very long paragraph with a space in your last post, messing up the formatting for everyone.  Iâ€™ll fix this, but please, in the future, check how things look before you submit them, so we can avoid these problems.\r\n','2012-07-06 18:00:09','2012-07-06 18:00:09'),(2200,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nSorry about the formatting issue. I\'ll make sure no paragraphs start with spaces.\r\n\r\nThe problem with the voxel idea is that then you need something that can see the neurotransmitters as color and you have an infinite regress. Why not just use the palette of neurotransmitters coming straight off of the retina? Why use a palette at all - just have your retina \'be\' your visual cortex and use the light itself as your palette. We can talk ourselves into ideas of representation if we smuggle consciousness in using a retrospective view but none of it makes any sense from a prospective view of consciousness. If you have no presentation to begin with then having a re-presentation won\'t give you one. If you have a presentation then you don\'t need a representation.\r\n\r\nBesides, I don\'t think that explanation is even physiologically accurate. People who are blind from birth experience stimulation to their visual cortex as tactile rather than visual so that even though they have the same cells with the same palette of neurotransmitters firing, they have never seen color or images so they do not experience them. \r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-06 19:06:09','2012-07-06 19:06:09'),(2203,96,48,'multisense realism wrote:\r\n\r\n>>>\r\n\r\nIt is not the eye that works like a camera, it\'s the camera works like an eye - only a camera doesn\'t see, it only stores a reflection event so that we can see it later.\r\n\r\n<<<\r\n\r\nAnd could a camera and a robotic brain EVER be designed see anything the way we do?\r\n\r\nOf course not, you will say, because they are just machines. You have to be a human to see anything.\r\n\r\nThats the problem with your viewpoint, you are like a creationist at an evolution convention trying to convince everyone else that evolution is wrong! \r\n\r\nThe reason why this group is interested in consciousness, and why that topic is so topical now, is because we DO believe that vision is a mechanical process performed by the mechanism of the brain, and that it IS possible at least in principle to replicate the magic of vision in an ordinary physical device, and that is a very interesting problem that appears almost within our grasp given modern computer technology.\r\n\r\nYou, in the meantime, are stuck back in medieval times, as if you haven\'t even heard of Kepler\'s discovery of the eye as a camera, and DesCartes discovery that the optic nerve is a data pipeline, or if you\'ve heard, you refuse to accept it. You are still stuck in the pre-scientific notion that man is NOT just a machine, there is something magical about vision that will never be replicated. \r\n\r\nSo you believe we are all \"wasting our time\" trying to understand the computational principles behind biological vision, while you are telling us it is impossible in principle, so we should all go home and give it up.\r\n\r\nYou belong in a medieval convention where people still believe in the magic of the human spirit as a pre-requsite for vision, so you are wasting everybody\'s time here at the evolutionary convention where we all believe that the eye is a camera, the optic nerve a data pipeline, and the visual cortex is a representation.\r\n\r\nAm I wrong? What do you others say on this? Am I wrong to chastise this man for promulgating his arguments in this forum? Or is it *I* who am out of place rejecting a perfectly reasonable scientific hypothesis? What is the consensus of this group?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-06 21:38:36','2012-07-06 21:38:36'),(2206,96,48,'\r\nCraig, the reason many of the doctrines you use are no longer popular, is because they have been demonstrably proven not possible by AI systems.  While the representational consensus theories work exactly as has been demonstrably proven possible with AI systems.  Much of the stuff you propose simply isnâ€™t possible, even in a simulated world.  While the consensus camps have been demonstrably proved by artificial AI systems.\r\n\r\nFor example you ask: â€œWhy not just use the palette of neurotransmitters coming straight off of the retina?â€  I would suspect, many people can see the obvious mistake you are making with such, and you need to work much harder to see how silly some of the things like this you say are.  MMPD predicts you could use the neurotransmitters coming off of the retina, but in order for such to be bound into our knowledge, the dendrites of the theorized â€˜bindingâ€™ neuron would have to reach out to, and have synapses detecting these pallets.  Also, the other problem is knowledge would only be 2D, and have none of the other cognitive knowledge bound in (why itâ€™s all done in the visual cortex, not in the retina).  So when you constantly make mistakes like this, and use up bandwidth on topic wide forums proposing such, it kind of wastes everyoneâ€™s time.  It would be helpful, especially for your reputation, if you would work harder to see things from another point of view, and better understand the expert consensus, by making these kinds of mistakes and proposing things that are clearly not possible to reproduce in any kind of reality AI system or simulation.\r\n\r\nHave you ever thought about writing a computer simulation that would work according to some of the way you are proposing?  If so, youâ€™d quickly find how most of it simply would not be possible to work in any kind of real working intelligent way.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-06 21:43:55','2012-07-06 21:43:55'),(2209,96,48,'I\'m sorry that my occasional presence here causes irritatation, but while it is not my purpose to troll, neither do I have any interest in making my views popular. I speak up in this forum only because I see that you cannot and will not resolve the problem of defining the fundamentals of RQT honestly.\r\n\r\nI know this not because I am Nostradamus, but because it is a problem which I faced myself just a few years ago when I still thought that the idea of consciousness-as-pure-neural-simulation was obviously and demonstrably true. I know where you are and I know how to get past the obstacle you face now.\r\n\r\nNo matter how many times I say that, I don\'t think that it is being understood here (let alone believed - which I would not expect). I understand everything that all of you are saying completely, and I know exactly why you are wrong and why you can\'t see that you are wrong and why that makes you respond in an unscientific and emotional way - with ad hominem accusations that really have little to do with my actual positions.\r\n\r\nBelieve it or not, I don\'t care what anyone thinks of me or my positions, but I will defend my positions, especially when they are rejected on the basis of misinterpretation.\r\n\r\n\"Of course not, you will say, because they are just machines. You have to be a human to see anything.\"\r\n\r\nNo. I would not say that at all. All animals with eyes can see. Insects with eyes can see. Sea Urchins function like an eye: http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2011/05/110502-sea-urchins-eyes-science-animals/ \r\n\r\nThey don\'t see exactly like a human being, but they probably see in some way that we might recognize. What doesn\'t see? TV sets. Cameras. Mirrors. The surface of water. CDC cells. Photomultipliers. Bubble chambers. Particle accelerators. They may detect and react, but that is a sensorimotive experience of a lower qualitative range or caste than living organisms who have evolved to devote organs to the task of detect the deeper qualitative possibilities of optical presentation.\r\n\r\nThe further something is from being an organism of roughly the same scale and composition of a human - and this is my conjecture - the less likely it is to be capable of seeing like a human being sees, even if you attach eyes to it. Is that so hard to swallow? \r\n\r\nThe reason that a robotic brain can\'t see anything is because it isn\'t made of anything that has evolved by itself to see. Just like a trash can will never learn to feel polite just by having the word THANK YOU stamped in its lid. This is not just me who understands this. In fact I just read a book \'Aping Mankind\' by Raymond Tallis which expresses the exact same positions that I do (until about halfway through, interestingly, where he assumes human exceptionalism and rules out panpsychism...the two areas where my ideas begin)\r\n\r\n\"Thats the problem with your viewpoint...you are like a creationist...You, in the meantime, are stuck back in medieval times...you are still stuck in the pre-scientific...\"\r\n\r\nIt sounds like my ideas are of no threat to you all, yet you seem personally invested in discrediting me. That doesn\'t seem very scientific to me. Don\'t you know that science often progresses by picking up on insights which were assumed long dead? Don\'t you understand that intellectual revolutions are not made by incrementally \'adding epicycles\' to the existing orthodoxy?\r\n\r\n\"So you believe we are all \"wasting our time\" trying to understand the computational principles behind biological vision\"\r\n\r\nNo, I don\'t think you are wasting your time, I think you\'re mistaken in believing that qualia is a representation. Qualia is a presentation, and as such, can present other presentations - but how it works (and this is my conjecture) is only partially computational - what it is that is actually being computed is not itself a computation - it is real feeling, thinking, and doing in a real world...not THE world but A real part of THE world. RQT is almost right - and that\'s why I sympathize so much with what you are doing here, really I do - but connecting the last mile is never going to happen and you have no idea why. I, and some other people do know exactly why though.\r\n\r\n\"so we should all go home and give it up.\"\r\nNo. The opposite. You are soo close to figuring it out. All you have to do is turn it upside down. We aren\'t the GUI, physics is the GUI. We aren\'t in Plato\'s Cave, we are seeing through layers of many caves, with no one of them being the ultimate reality but all of them together are.\r\n\r\n\"Or is it *I* who am out of place rejecting a perfectly reasonable scientific hypothesis? What is the consensus of this group?\"\r\n\r\nHaha, what do you think the consensus will be? What would the consensus be in the church in considering Copernicus or Galileo?\r\n\r\nBrent, you said: \"the reason many of the doctrines you use are no longer popular, is because they have been demonstrably proven not possible by AI systems.\"\r\n\r\nIf an AI system is unconscious, how could it demonstrate something about consciousness? If you assume from the beginning that AI is conscious and that consciousness is just biochemical AI, then any proof you have is begging the question. \r\n\r\n\"MMPD predicts you could use the\r\nneurotransmitters coming off of the retina, but in order for such to be bound into our knowledge, the dendrites of the theorized â€˜bindingâ€™ neuron would have to reach out to, and have synapses detecting these pallets\"\r\n\r\nFirst you are saying I am ridiculous, but then say that its only ridiculous because the dendrites can\'t reach? That\'s the reason that the brain can\'t use the retina as its visual cortex directly is because the visual cortex is over here and the eyeballs are over here? \r\n\r\n\"Also, the other problem is knowledge would only be 2D, and\r\nhave none of the other cognitive knowledge bound in (why itâ€™s all\r\ndone in the visual cortex, not in the retina).\"\r\n\r\nI would be willing to bet that the sea urchin body \'sees\' in 3D without a visual cortex. You kind of need that when you are surviving on the floor of the ocean. All of these objections are just-so stories. There is no reason at all that a dataset would be created at one end of our skull and recreated at another end of our skull. Once you have data, it needs no further representation. Why would it?\r\n\r\n\"So when you constantly make mistakes like this\"\r\n\r\nI haven\'t made any mistakes, but I can see clearly why it seems to you like I am in error. I can\'t make you see why your view is almost right but not quite. Maybe its like those Magic Eye pictures and not everyone can see them. All I can tell you is that I have been where you are now and it\'s better where I am now.\r\n\r\n\"It would be helpful, especially for your reputation..\"\r\nNo, it would be helpful for your reputation to have the foresight to see the ultimate failure of RQT and to consider the solutions I suggest.\r\n\r\n\"if you would work harder to see things from another point of view,\"\r\n\r\nI know the point of view you speak of like the back of my hand.\r\n\r\n\"Have you ever thought about writing a computer simulation that would work according to some of the way you are proposing?\"\r\n\r\nThat\'s the point, I understand exactly why experience cannot be simulated. Something that already has an experience can have a simulated experience, but you can\'t simulate something that doesn\'t exist in the first place. No matter how nice of a plastic plant I make it\'s not going to fool the microorganisms in the soil. It\'s not going to make edible berries. You can\'t eat a simulation. I can have imitation sugar, but it isn\'t really imitation anything, it\'s another chemical that gives an experience that is similar to sugar. \r\n\r\nIt\'s no use though. I don\'t think there is any hope that you will understand what I am saying. Your ego will compensate before the meaning of my words even form in your mind and you will gird your loins for another tiresome salvo of epithets and accusations. Meanwhile, some of us are interested in what the hard problem and explanatory gap are really about.','2012-07-07 00:24:07','2012-07-07 00:24:07'),(2212,96,48,'\r\nHi Craig,\r\n\r\nI should probably apologize for the harsh nature of my posts (including this one?).  I hope nobody, especially you, ever feels like they are not welcome here.  We want to know what EVERYONE believes.  I know there is just as much chance that \"THE ONE\" true theory is one held by just one person that nobody can see yet.  Everyone\'s goal should be to help that one person do what is required so the rest of us can understand what you are saying, even if we don\'t have time to help every still lonely camp.\r\n\r\nA big part of that is helping you to understand how the current expert consensus sees things, and what kinds of things are mistakes from within that view.  Because when you say things that appear to us to be mistakes, that just makes us not want to spend time on any of your posts in the future, or on making any more of an effort to understand your camp.\r\n\r\nYou indicated you\'re not the only one that feels the way you do.  If so, perhaps you should reach out to them, so they can help with your effort to canonize and further spread these ideas.  Having a camp with multiple supporters would go a long way.\r\n\r\nYou say that we \"cannot and will not resolve the problem of defining the fundamentals of RQT honestly.\"  But, all the supporters see nothing \"dishonest\" in any of this.  Even many of the competitor camps don\'t see anything \'dishonest\'.\r\n\r\nYou repeatedly assume and accuse me of thinking there is a \'hard problem\'.  But, from my perspective, there is no hard problem.  I\'ve tried to tell you this many times, but you still make the same mistake, over and over again, as if I think there is a hard problem.  I believe something like Macro Material Property Dualism explains everything we need to know about consciousness in a very objectively demonstrable (as in effing) way.\r\n\r\nWhen you assert that a \"sea urchin body \'sees\' in 3D without a visual cortex\", in our world that\'s just absurd irrationality.  Any process must have a huge amount of complex computational capacity, phenomenal or not, to derive any kind of 3D knowledge from 2D images.  So you need to know how stupid saying such is, from our point of view - and how things like that make some of us unwilling, even feeling unwise to waste more time listening to anything you are trying to say.\r\n\r\nIn other words, I\'m just trying to help you see how you might be able to better communicate, if you can first better understand how we see things, and how dumb some of the things you are saying to us, and also find more people that agree with you, and so on.  You need to learn to fully understand our world, and help us see things your way, from within our world.  That\'s the entire reason we created Canonizer.com, in the first place, so we could better do that - at least with any of the leading consensus camps, as no human has enough time in one life time to fully understand all lonely camps in the world.\r\n\r\nI apologize for not being able to do that any better than I am, and appreciate your patience with us.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n','2012-07-07 01:36:01','2012-07-07 01:36:01'),(2215,96,48,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\nThanks for the apology but no worries, I don\'t take it personally. I\'m not trying to be right so it doesn\'t bother me when people feel like they have to assert that I\'m wrong.\r\n\r\n\"A big part of that is helping you to understand how the current expert\r\nconsensus sees things\"\r\nI don\'t see that as my job. I feel that those who understand my ideas can work backwards and see how the current consensus fits in if they entertain the new model hypothetically. If the last 40 years has been essentially \'adding epicycles\' to physics, then we need to go back to a much more primitive consensus of reality than that. From there we can make more sense of why indirect observations and measurements relate to different aspects of the universe than direct experiences.\r\n\r\n\"perhaps you should reach out to them, so they can help with your effort\"\r\nMaybe, but all I really care about is reaching those who can make use of what I\'m saying. If people aren\'t ready to hear it, then I\'m not going to sell them on it.\r\n\r\n\"I believe something like Macro Material Property Dualism explains everything we need to know about consciousness\"\r\n\r\nI know that you believe that, but if that were true I would be able to see your memories by just looking at your brain with a powerful enough lens. There is no port which translates qualia into any material property at all. No Cartesian theater or homunculus, so that any phenomenal property that can be experienced must be generated as it is inside the tissue of the brain. You are saying that the memory of the smell of fried chicken actually smells like fried chicken inside of the cells of your brain. It doesn\'t. Without doing brain surgery first hand I can tell you that nothing in the brain smells very delicious. I suggest that you try completely banishing all traces of visual or auditory qualia in your thinking for a few minutes. Consider that Helen Keller lived a human life and learned to communicate without seeing or hearing. How does that fit into MMPD? Do the memories of her teacher touching her hand or whatever exist in glutamate? It\'s just a non-starter, and going back to billiard ball anything is, not to sound surly, a joke. Behaviorism and 19th century materialism are dead. We tried that already. It doesn\'t work.\r\n\r\n\"When you assert that a \"sea urchin body \'sees\' in 3D without a visual cortex\", in our world that\'s just absurd irrationality. Any process must have a huge amount of complex computational capacity, phenomenal or not, to derive any kind of 3D knowledge from 2D images\"\r\n\r\nWhy do you assume it has 2D images. A sea urchin has spines all over its body. It may have a panoramic 3D awareness with no computation at all. If you assume a background of senseless nothingness then you have to assemble a composite awareness from the bottom up with bits somehow merging together, I think that is a mistake and all merging comes from inference that is inherent in matter. Matter is all one thing, its only our fragmented status within a sliver of space, time, and human sense which produces the illusion of separation. Perception pokes holes in the separation, that is how we sense and make sense of ourselves and our world.\r\n\r\n\"So you need to know how stupid saying such is, from our point of view \"\r\n\r\nBut that would mean that you need to know how stupid what you are saying is from my point of view. Why is it important?\r\n\r\n\"if you can first better understand how we see things, and how dumb some of the things you are saying to us, and also\r\nfind more people that agree with you, and so on. \"\r\n\r\nI wish that were true, but unfortunately I understand exactly how you see things. If people want to understand my ideas, they will have to step outside of their certainty and prejudice.\r\n\r\n\"You need to learn to fully understand our world, and help us see things your way, from within our world.\"\r\n\r\nTo understand my world, I am afraid that you must shatter your own world utterly. It must be beaten down to the bricks and rebuilt from scratch. When you accept that, you will find that nothing was lost at all and in fact, makes more sense viewed from the inside out. If there was another way, then I would be open to that, but this isn\'t like learning a new fact or theory, it is about discovering that you are alive and what that actually means scientifically.\r\n\r\nI appreciate your patience with me too. I\'m torn between not wanting to keep bothering you all and being compelled to keep at it. It\'s especially difficult because I am not at all sure that it is possible for people to turn their entire worldview inside out. I did it but I didn\'t really have a choice. I\'m not sure it can be done voluntarily. Still, if not here, where and if not now, when? If you want to know what awareness really is, I am more than happy to answer questions, draw pictures, talk on the phone, collaborate, etc but I can only come to where you are at from where I am now. I can\'t go back to the world you see - just like those ambiguous pictures, I can\'t unsee consciousness now. I can\'t put the self in a glass box and draw a picture of a brain on top of it. It isn\'t that way, and it never has been.\r\n','2012-07-07 05:14:41','2012-07-07 05:14:41'),(2218,96,48,'The current account in neuroscience and cognitive science of consciousness is somewhat confused. These confusions may be tabulated as follows:\r\n1.	The simultaneous use of two incompatible theories of perceptionâ€”representative theory (in the lab) and naÃ¯ve realism (at home): as when Crick (1994) said that the stimulus field is identical to the visual field. This is linked to the widespread confusion between the physical body (which we do not experience) and the neurological body-image (which we do).\r\n2.	Adherence to the incoherent theory of mind-brain identity. This theory fails to conform to Leibnizâ€™s Law of the Identity of Indiscernibles.\r\n3.	The muddle over the â€˜ homunculusâ€™ (a.k.a â€˜the little green man in the headâ€™). This is based on the confusion between sensing and perceiving. Just because we need an image to perceive a physical object, this does not entail that we need an image to have (examine) a sensation.\r\n4.	The muddle over â€˜qualiaâ€™. â€˜Qualiaâ€™ is a misleading term invented by philosophers to describe what IT IS LIKE to have a sensation. What we should be discussing is WHAT IT IS to have a sensation: vide Adrian 1928.\r\n5.	 The almost universal assumption that Cartesian Dualism is the only form of dualism there is: whereas in fact other forms of material dualism based in ideas in modern physics (e.g. hyperspace) are being developed.\r\n6.	The problem raised when we substitute the Special Theory of Relativity for Newtonian cosmology as the foundation of the theory of brain-consciousness relations. As de Broglie (1959) noted, the block universe of Special Relativity requires an extraneous consciousness to supply both the â€˜nowâ€™ and the passage of time.\r\n7.	The problem raised by the fact that sensations of different modalities have very different phenomenal properties, whereas the electrochemical events in their respective sensory cortices are very similar to each other.\r\n\r\nAdrian E.D. The Basis of Sensations. New York: Norton; 1928\r\nCrick, F. The Astonishing Hypothesis. 1994\r\nde Broglie, L. (1959), â€˜A general survey of the scientific work of Albert Einsteinâ€™, in Albert Einstein Philosopher-Scientist, ed. P.A. Schlipp.\r\n','2012-07-07 17:34:53','2012-07-07 17:34:53'),(2221,96,48,'Thanks to John Locke for those seven points, even though they posted seven times for some reason, they are very good ones to have repeated. Hopefully this will only post once.\r\n\r\n\"1. The simultaneous use of two incompatible theories of perceptionâ€”representative theory (in the lab) and naÃ¯ve realism (at home):\"\r\n\r\nYes! It is tricky to avoid doing this, I think partly because we are now used to computers having a GUI that displays a spatial field of digital bits so that we don\'t realize that this display exists for a human user and has no conceivable use within a computation device that already has all of the information that it would display to itself.\r\n\r\n\"the physical body (which we do not experience) and the neurological body-image (which we do).\"\r\n\r\nYes, although I would say that we have an indirect experience of the body as a collection of material forms and a direct experience of the body as a history of sense-motive participation. My conjecture here is that these categories of experience are a dual aspect ontology, both being equally \'physical\' but the former has a physicality which is fragmented across space and the latter has a physicality which is condensed through time. This is a new way of looking at physics but I think that it will prove to be essential for understanding consciousness.\r\n\r\n\"2. Adherence to the incoherent theory of mind-brain identity. This theory fails to conform to Leibnizâ€™s Law of the Identity of Indiscernibles.\"\r\n\r\nRight. I think this problem goes away when we understand the nature of the dual aspect ontology - the what+how aspect and the who+why aspect which intersect as a place+time localization-synchronization. This is what brain activity and mind activity have in common - the place of the former can be positively correlated with the time of the latter. The further we get from that intersection in the moment, the less possible it is to relate the two aspects directly. Think of two perpendicular Turing machines, one that is a literal machine cranking out a tape of binary numbers, and one a figurative tape cranking out numbered Turing machines. There is an anomalous symmetry which requires one to know not just physiology and function but the cumulative sense and motives of any particular individual and the world they come out of.\r\n\r\n\" 3. The muddle over the â€˜ homunculusâ€™ (a.k.a â€˜the little green man in the headâ€™). This is based on the confusion between sensing and perceiving. Just because we need an image to perceive a physical object, this does not entail that we need an image to have (examine) a sensation.\"\r\n\r\nI don\'t so much see an important distinction between sensing and perceiving. They are vague colloquial terms which probably don\'t help us discern what they are supposed to stand for. As for the homunculus, I don\'t think it\'s confused, I think it makes the point that having a model of any kind in the brain would not resolve any of the problems of mind vs matter. Saying that the brain makes a model of matter and the mind reads the model doesn\'t explain, if the brain can access matter and be accessed by the mind, why would any \'model\' be necessary and how does it exist as a formless entity that mediates two opposite experiences of form (world experienced directly and brain experienced indirectly in the world).\r\n\r\n\" 4. The muddle over â€˜qualiaâ€™. â€˜Qualiaâ€™ is a misleading term invented by philosophers to describe what IT IS LIKE to have a sensation. What we should be discussing is WHAT IT IS to have a sensation: vide Adrian 1928. \"\r\n\r\nI feel that qualia is misleading because it deals only with the presentation layer of our naive realism without allowing us to rationalize it in any way. I think that what it is to have a sensation is both a \'what it is like\' and \'what it is\' and that in fact this is the same dual aspect as direct (seems like) and indirect (seems like it is ) experience of physical realism. With this diagram http://multisenserealism.files.wordpress.com/2012/01/aslide13.jpg I suggest a relationship between layer or caste proximity to the subject and the strength of the \'seems like\' vs \'simply is\' perceptual bias.\r\n\r\n\"5. The almost universal assumption that Cartesian Dualism is the only form of dualism there is: whereas in fact other forms of material dualism based in ideas in modern physics (e.g. hyperspace) are being developed.\"\r\n\r\nSure, yeah. I see many dualisms, dialectics, trinities, quadruplicities etc. All of them are under the aegis of what I call, for the lack of a better term, sense. Symmetry is a key part of sense...foreground, background, stop/go, literal/figurative, etc. Mind-matter is just the tip of the iceberg, and a very anthropomorphic tip at that.\r\n\r\n\" 6. The problem raised when we substitute the Special Theory of Relativity for Newtonian cosmology as the foundation of the theory of brain-consciousness relations. As de Broglie (1959) noted, the block universe of Special Relativity requires an extraneous consciousness to supply both the â€˜nowâ€™ and the passage of time. \"\r\n\r\nThis gets pretty esoteric, but I think that because we are complex entities, we are defined in different frames of time passage - biological time, neurological scale time, geological time, social time, etc. We are anchored in both the eternal and the instantaneous and our world is defined by the continuum in between - the same continuum mentioned above. The more \'dilated\' your perceptual bias can be toward the \'seems like\' the more your perception of time is fluid and seen as a returning cycle within eternity and the less you experience the \'simply is\' definition of discrete instants of linear duration - an arithmetic emptiness of dimension x+1 within which physical events are contained.\r\n\r\n\"7. The problem raised by the fact that sensations of different modalities have very different phenomenal properties, whereas the electrochemical events in their respective sensory cortices are very similar to each other. \"\r\n\r\nYes, an excellent point that really throws a wrench into any possible information-theoretic-functionalist scheme to explain consciousness. It would be like having some parts of your computer store machine code as plumbing and weaving and a dozen other unrelated forms. To smell something we would have to have a virtual restaurant in our brain cook up olfactory fields.','2012-07-07 19:34:57','2012-07-07 19:34:57'),(2224,96,48,'Glad you liked my post!\r\nSorry for the multiple posting! In one interpretation, it got posted seven times because I was unfamiliar with the posting system, and repeated it when it did not seem to be sending anything. On another interpretation my computer was responding to the archetype of Seven Pillars of Wisdom!\r\nTo take up some of your points:\r\n1. re the body-image. The neurological point is that the experience of a body part continues even if the body part is amputated. The phenomenon of the phantom limb is of course widely known. What may not be widely known is that a phantom limb can often be moved both voluntarily as well as automaticallyâ€”as when a patient\'s phantom limb extends to \'catch\' a ball thrown at her. Furthermore, in many cases of arm amputation, if the patient is touched on the face, she will feel the touch on her fingers. In these cases the face touch system has taken over the now inactive finger touch neurons.\r\nI would say that we have no phenomenal experience of the body, but that we experience the body image (phenomenal body) linked to its NCCs in the brain (shades of Ludwigâ€”Jonathan Harrison\'s infamous brain-in-a-vat).\r\n2. You say \" This is what brain activity and mind activity have in common - the place of the former can be positively correlated with the time of the latter.\" Undoubtedlyâ€”but I think that we can go further. I suggest that he mind has its own \'place\' (its visual and somatic sensations, as we experience them, are extended in phenomenal space (think also of the space of a dream). Phenomenal space has its own geometry and topology (vide Robert French\'s work), and can thus be related to physical space. Either one\'s own phenomenal space is that small part of physical space in which one\'s  brain is extended: or it lies outside the brain in a space of its own. Here is where the hyper dimensional theories come in.\r\n3. I am using \'sensing\' and \'perceiving\' in the technical sense introduced by C. D. Broad and H. H. Price. We can be said to perceive physical objects using the entire physiological chain of perception. We sense only its end productsâ€”as when we examine an after-image and observe what color it is.\r\n6. I agree that the passage of time is a very complex subject. But that does not account for the embarrassing fact that contemporary physics, which claims to be the Theory of Everything, can account neither for the \'now\' nor the passage of time.\r\n7. You say \"Yes, an excellent point that really throws a wrench into any possible information-theoretic-functionalist scheme to explain consciousness.\" \r\nAbsolutely! Some of the details get even more interesting. \r\nHere\'s one: If you look with both eyes open at a light flickering at 6-18 Hz you will experience (\'sense\') simple geometric hallucinations in your visual field (parallel lines, checkerboards, grids, mazes, families of circles, etc. in several colors). These are produced by interactions between the brain\'s own electrical rhythms and the electrical rhythms induced by the flickering stimulus. However, if only one eye is stimulated, something quite different happens. You see at first the geometrical patterns but these soon get replaced by quite a different phenomenon. These are patterns constructed of continuous oily swirls, like oil on water or boiling mud, in two colors, usually red and green. These two (geometrical flickering patters and continuous oily swirls) then proceed to alternate in retinal rivalry. This indicates that the oily swirls are arising in the inactive cortical neurons connected only to the closed eye. If we examine the neuroanatomy involved, we find that the two are connected by a continuous syncytium of GABAergic inhibitory neurons that use both chemical and electrical junctions: and it is the continuous swirling activity of direct currents in these inhibitory neurons (or the interaction of this electrical activity with the attached pyramidal visual neurons) that \'appears\' as the oily swirls in consciousness. (In this regards contemporary neuroscience thinks almost entirely in terms of binary action potentials (spikes), rather that direct currents). I think that this is the first demonstration of a detailed link between a specific sensation and a specific brain activity. So how can a swirling mass of electrons in a neural syncytium be identical with an oily swirl of green and red colors???','2012-07-07 21:57:44','2012-07-07 21:57:44'),(2227,96,48,'John,\r\n\r\nOutstanding perceptual info. About perceptual illusions, my view takes into account the following:\r\n\r\n1. Although I maintain that the underlying reality is not computation, using a computation model is useful because:\r\n\r\na. we are dealing with an event which directly exposes sub-self level experiences to the top level self.\r\n\r\nb. quanta is the flattest qualia; the inter-qualitative protocols governing how experiences are divided up publicly and privately.\r\n\r\nc. this means that in cases where the whole-self systems are broken or fooled, we are automatically looking more at the objective side of things than the balanced view. If you cut a book in half, you learn more about paper than you do about writing.\r\n\r\nWhat I am trying to get at is that who we are is a physical reality through time rather than space, and it is defined more by the totality of our life experience when we are healthy and whole than when our life is impacted by a medical event. The more impacted we are by illness or dysfunction, the more we are reduced to a collection of objective systems. When our top level awareness is pushed beyond its specifications, as in an optical illusion, we learn a lot about perception, but mainly the physiological end of it. It is our access to sense which is being interrupted, not the production of sense. To learn about the meaningful end of perception, we should turn to cross-cultural and etymological patterns in language and first hand accounts.\r\n\r\nFor things like optical illusions and phantom limbs, I to try to understand them not only in terms of a failure of our private realism to map accurately to public realism - which is the obvious but deceptive reading, but as the success of our perceptual inertial frame to maintain its narratives (perceptual momentum). \r\n\r\nOne way of thinking about the amputation is that the outermost sense of the body is compromised, so that the well developed awareness associated with the limb shares the bandwidth of the equally well developed awareness associated with the face. There a law of conservation of qualitative significance. \r\n\r\nThis sharing of multiple private forms (figurative fingers and face) with a single public form (literal face) goes against a representation model in that we would not expect the model to effortlessly convert itself to represent a completely different part of the body by default. To the contrary, RQT implies an epiphenomenal modeling of hard sense data. What we see instead is that the publicly real face is actually better understood as the software and the privately real fingers are more like the hardware. Naturally we could see it the opposite way, and that again is the obvious, but I think ultimately inverted characterization of what has happened. \r\n\r\nTo understand consciousness, we have to stop looking at the brain as a device that produces consciousness and look instead at the totality of a human lifetime in the context of the history of the universe as the relevant physical system. The brain is nothing but a complex cursor into the GUI of physical realism. It is the physical realism that is lowest common denominator shadows of concrete awareness, which is what the universe can only be \'made of.\'\r\n\r\n\"think that we can go further. I suggest that he mind has its own \'place\' (its visual and somatic sensations, as we experience them, are extended in phenomenal space (think also of the space of a dream). Phenomenal space has its own geometry and topology (vide Robert French\'s work), and can thus be related to physical space.\"\r\n\r\nThis gets tricky too. In general it is shocking enough to say that the self is a phenomenology through private time and its shadow is the the phenomenology across public space. That is the basic truth. The more advanced considerations are that public space is really space-time and private time is really time-space. The difference is this: You have an experience of phenomenal space in dreams or the mind but they have no object constancy. You can\'t come back to a dream and reliably find your glasses where you left them. You might find a pterodactyl there instead. What I suggest is that space is a subtly different presentation than place. We have no phenomenal space qua space, only a buffer of temporarily persistent placement. This is similar to our phenomenal experience of time, which is not really time qua time, but narrative continuity of experience. Phenomenal space and time is really more like scene and plot. To get at objective public realism, you need generic multiplicity - gears and teeth behind the presentation which reliably synchronize agreement among inter-qualitative phenomena among the various participants and layers/frames/scales of participation.\r\n\r\n\"I agree that the passage of time is a very complex subject. But that does not account for the embarrassing fact that contemporary physics, which claims to be the Theory of Everything, can account neither for the \'now\' nor the passage of time. \"\r\n\r\nAbsolutely. I first came across what you are talking about after doing this crazy mural relating the continuum of public and private realism (...stationlink.com/art/comp7.jpg) and reading into it deeply. On the left side there is a suggestion of a large lower case \"i\" (which contrasts to a large, wild i that fractures the picture plane on the right). I apologize for most people reading this who will not know what I am talking about - but anyways, the thing is that it gave me an understanding of the failure of physics to ground the sense of I into a here and now. You have relativity with its inertial frames, but no theory of anything to initiate perception in the first place. The \"i\" appears as a an arbitrarily inverted transparent window into nothing special. A random collection of evolved mechanisms of self reference. This is a problem. It is the equal and opposite problem that ideal monism/naive realism has where the \"i\" cannot be reigned in to a persistent sensible context. Physics has the context, but no text and no reader. It is all flat black and white flat quanta trying to explain away full spectrum color qualia.\r\n\r\n\"So how can a swirling mass of electrons in a neural syncytium be identical with an oily swirl of green and red colors???\"\r\n\r\nRight. Only if the colors and the electrons are opposite presentations (one public quanta and the other private qualia) of a common neutral monism - which I call sense. What we see as the colors is the agreement between the part of us we identify with normally as the observer and the part of us whose experience we feel visually as color. All that we see is the embodied change in ourselves which is the local filtration of the global change events in which we participate. We are seeing part of ourselves change. \"We\" are the body, the brain, the neurons, the molecules, the electrons. We are the culture, the species, the biosphere, the planet, the solar system, etc. Not literally as objects - that is the opposite presentation of disunity - but figuratively as subjects through time.\r\n\r\nI\'m not trying to be mystical about this at all, I think that is is the only legitimate scientific approach to understanding consciousness completely. Other models will take us far, but only the one which fully integrates phenomenological awareness into the universe as a whole will ultimately satisfy us.','2012-07-08 01:33:58','2012-07-08 01:33:58'),(2230,96,48,'Multisense Realism writes:\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nThe reason that a robotic brain can\'t see anything is because it isn\'t made of anything that has evolved by itself to see.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nAnd the reason why machines can\'t fly is because they have not evolved to fly. And machines can\'t drive around autonomously because they did not evolve to drive around. And robots can\'t move because they did not evolve to move. Is that so hard to swallow? About as hard as a ten pound pineapple!\r\n\r\nThe un-stated hidden assumption behind your theory is that like the \"Vitalists\" of the last century, you propose that there is something magical and mystical in living systems that cannot be reduced to mere biochemistry, and there is something magical in vision that allows only animals to see, not inanimate machines.\r\n\r\nThat is an extraordinary anti-scientific hypothesis that if true, would require extraordinary evidence for it to be accepted by reasonable men. But to a dogmatist it is simply self-evidently true and requires no proof, because they are stuck in the mystery of naive realism where vision truly IS a magical mystery.\r\n\r\nFor the rest of us scientifically-minded seekers of the truth, if a sea scallop http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scallop can see with its primitive eyes sufficient to slam the shell closed to a looming movement, then an automatic door-opener can \"see\" too, at least in a primitive way.\r\n\r\nFor scientists from Kepler to Descartes on to today, the obvious parallels between the eye and a camera, the retina and a photosensitive array, and the optic nerve as a data pipeline, are inescapable clues to the mechanism of vision, and that much we have ALREADY REPLICATED in machines, all the way to robots that can navigate autonomously by sight. The principle of representationalism has been demonstrated again and again, only an anti-scientific dogmatist would deny that this is a primitive form of vision, that the automaton can \"see\" even if only dimly and stupidly. \r\n\r\nWe are on a totally different quest than you are. You are wasting everybody\'s time with your vitalistic nonsense and re-definition of well accepted meaning of common terms like \"image\" to mean something completely different than what everybody already understands. You are like the creationist at an evolutionary convention hijacking the whole debate and arguing that evolution is wrong. Why don\'t you go to the Vitalist Dogmatist\'s convention with other naive realists who lack images on their retinas, and leave us alone to discuss science in peace amongst those who believe in it.\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nIt sounds like my ideas are of no threat to you all, yet you seem personally invested in discrediting me. That doesn\'t seem very scientific to me. \r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nIt is not you personally that I am targeting, but that whole nonsense that comes around again and again wherever consciousness is discussed, that an image is not an image, and a camera does not have an image, and that machines can never see, and on and on with the same old nonsense, and they always hijack the debate with long intense diatribes that waste everybody\'s time over issues that are ALREADY LONG SETTLED among reasonable people!\r\n\r\nIt\'s no use though. I don\'t think there is any hope that you will understand what I am saying. Your ego will compensate before the meaning of my words even form in your mind and you will gird your loins for another tiresome salvo of redefinition of terms and hocus-pocus nonsense. Meanwhile, some of us are interested in how vision really works, and how the brain makes a spatial experience out of a sensory image.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-08 13:01:27','2012-07-08 13:01:27'),(2233,96,48,'slehar writes:\r\n\r\n\"And the reason why machines can\'t fly is because they have not evolved to fly. And machines can\'t drive around autonomously because they did not evolve to drive around.\"\r\n\r\nA machine can\'t know or care that it\'s flying or driving. When we assemble inanimate objects to fulfill our own human purposes, it is easy to forget that these are puppets rather than beings in their own right. It is telling that the machines we have developed to fly did not succeed in imitating the flight of birds or bees but through the novelties of propellers and jets, fixed wing aerodynamics, etc. What we have in machines is passive flight; unconscious, automatic, dependent on human motivations for their existence.\r\n\r\n\"And robots can\'t move because they did not evolve to move. Is that so hard to swallow? About as hard as a ten pound pineapple!\"\r\n\r\nBy that logic we should be able to teach a slug to play the violin. There has never been a byte of information that has given the slightest indication that it feels something. Feeling cannot arise from a collection of inanimate objects - unless they aren\'t really inanimate.\r\n\r\n\"you propose that there is something magical and mystical in living systems that cannot be reduced to mere\"\r\n\r\nI have never proposed anything more or less than the ordinary feeling and living that we undeniably experience ourselves. No magic. You are confusing my argument with some straw man in your mind.\r\n\r\n\"there is something magical in vision that allows only animals to see, not inanimate machines\"\r\n\r\nWhat we mean by \'seeing\' would certainly be magical for a non-animal to experience. Detecting optical conditions like a CDC cell is not the same thing as seeing full color panoramic scenes that make narrative sense. I can make a pinhole camera by poking a hole in a cardboard box. Are you suggesting that the hole sees? Does the emulsion coated celluloid see?\r\n\r\n\"if a sea scallop http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scallop can see with its primitive eyes sufficient to slam the shell closed to a looming movement, then an automatic door-opener can \"see\" too, at least in a primitive way.\"\r\n\r\nI find it hard to believe that this argument sounds reasonable to anyone, so I don\'t know that anything I can say will rouse you out of your naive materialism here, but let me see - if a corpse falls off of a slab in the morgue, does that mean they have reanimated themselves? If a bowling ball falls on my foot does that mean it is a predator of human beings? Symbol Grounding Problem. There is no way I can make you understand it, you have to be able to doubt your own certainty first.\r\n\r\n\"are inescapable clues to the mechanism of vision\"\r\nThey are clues to the mechanism of optics. They have nothing whatsoever with any kind of visual experience. To the contrary, a data pipeline has no sensory preference at all - not only could it just as easily be aural or olfactory qualia which was produced by a camera, but it would be much more likely to not require any sensory forms at all. Until you can tell me why a camera is more likely to produce a seeable image than a smellable image there is really nothing to talk about - your accusations and hand-waving are just your own sentiment and irritation with me personally. Your insistence on mechanistic visual qualia has no explanatory power.\r\n\r\n\"only an anti-scientific dogmatist would deny that this is a\r\nprimitive form of vision, that the automaton can \"see\" even if only\r\ndimly and stupidly.\"\r\n\r\nThat isn\'t true though. It\'s nothing but an ad hominem argument from authority. Two, two, two fallacies in one. Of course the automaton doesn\'t see. Pinhole camera. What sees? Us. We see. The film itself sees no images. It\'s not anti-scientific at all. In fact mine is a significantly more nuanced, more scientific approach. I understand the distinction between form and being informed, between mechanistic detection-response, sentient sensation-appreciation, and the continuum of qualitative possibilities in between. There is no point in discussing these issues with you if you refuse to acknowledge them and keep pointing in the direction of naive mechanism. I\'ve been there before and I know why it doesn\'t work.\r\n\r\n\"We are on a totally different quest than you are.\"\r\nYes. You are on the alchemists quest of trying to turn lead into gold. I am pointing out that it doesn\'t work that way.\r\n\r\n\"You are wasting everybody\'s time with your vitalistic nonsense and re-definition of well accepted meaning of common terms like \"image\" to mean something completely different than what everybody already understands\"\r\n\r\nReally? I am really wasting your time. How much time does it take to notice that I have posted something and to ignore it? Less than a second I would think. If you choose to engage with me than you are wasting your own time. It\'s much more of a waste of everyone\'s time to have to wade through this ad hominem garbage to get to the part where you address my (and now John Locke\'s as well) criticisms of neuro-mechanistic dogma. As for \"image\", why don\'t you describe to me precisely what neurology or physics has to say about an \"image\". What magical ingredient turns a non-image into an image? What did images evolve from? How did they aquire \'meaning\' and what is meaning. Why don\'t computers need to have images in their programming? To me, you have not even begun to formulate a definition of image, yet you accuse me of tainting it with an actual understanding. Not so scientific.\r\n\r\n\"Why don\'t you go to the Vitalist Dogmatist\'s convention with other naive realists who lack images on their retinas, and leave us alone to discuss science in peace amongst those who believe in it.\"\r\n\r\nHaha. You are really personally threatened by my ideas. Science is nothing without curiosity. Well, it isn\'t nothing, I suppose it is a blunt instrument for dominating others with your intellect too.\r\n\r\n\"It is not you personally that I am targeting, but that whole nonsense that comes around again and again wherever consciousness is discussed\"\r\n\r\nIf you don\'t intend to target me personally then telling me to go away and stop wasting everyone\'s time would not really be the way to express that. The reason that this whole nonsense \'comes around again and again\' is because your view fails to address the reality of consciousness. It will always keep coming around because naive mechanism can never work to explain even the most primitive forms of awareness (especially the most primitive forms...complex awareness is easier to get lost in and fool ourselves with AI puppetry).\r\n\r\n\"It\'s no use though. I don\'t think there is any hope that you will\r\nunderstand what I am saying\"\r\n\r\nI understand every word and syllable of what you are saying.\r\n\r\n\"that waste everybody\'s time over issues that are ALREADY LONG SETTLED among\r\nreasonable people!\"\r\n\r\nI must have missed the part where any issue about consciousness has been settled. Please direct me to the formulas from which meaningful personal perceptions and aesthetics are derived from generic optical phenomena.\r\n\r\n\"Meanwhile, some of us are interested in how vision really\r\nworks, and how the brain makes a spatial experience out of a sensory image.\"\r\n\r\nYou are interested in how your idea of vision works, not the reality. A sensory image is already a spatial experience. If you have one, there is nothing that needs to be done to make the other. The problem is, neither image nor experience exists independently of the subject.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-08 16:52:47','2012-07-08 16:52:47'),(2236,96,48,'Brent\r\n\r\nI appreciate your searching questions.\r\n\r\nYou say that property dualism is not substance dualism. I am not arguing that they are identical but i think they come down to the same idea. How do you distinguish property from substance?\r\n\r\n \"..it is unanimously property dualists, and the clear expert consensus even amongst these is for mind brain identity.\"\r\nHave you seen the diagram at the top of the Wikipedia article on property dualism? You see 3 coloured circles: 2 are blue and one is not. The colour distinction represents an ontological divide, hence the name \"dualism\". The blue circles fit with identity theory but the other does not and so we need mental gymnastics to try to fit dualism into monism.\r\n\r\n\"Let me ask you what you mean, when you say there is no conscious experience in a computer\"\r\nSimply that. Looked at another way, a computer fits the blue scheme: it has no phenomenal properties, aspect or substance. The waking brain does, by virtue of the NCC.\r\n\r\n\"Because that difference (i.e. there are two types of things, things that can be simulated in a computer, and things that cannot.) which is the only \'dualist\' thing the supporters of property dualism are talking about. It is just qualities of things, or different ways to look at the same stuff.\"\r\nThere is partial consensus: i agree with property dualists who hold the view that computers can\'t be conscious but not with those property dualists who believe computational functionalism. A further problem is the claim that phenomenal properties are fundamental properties of the universe, a position that leads Chalmers into panexperientialism.\r\n\r\n\"When you are the only one that can\'t see what all these experts see, when they claim to be both \"mind brain identity\" and \"property dualists\", this is strong evidence that you are missing something. You need strong evidence to make any such extraordinary claim if you expect anyone to trust you, or read your lonely single supported camp statement, going against that much of an expert consensus.\"\r\nNo pressure, then.\r\n','2012-07-08 18:09:40','2012-07-08 18:09:40'),(2239,96,48,'I see valid points in both perspectives and get what each side is struggling with and trying to resolve. I found resolution with the Penrose-Hameroff \"Orch OR\" model. Read some of Hameroff\'s papers or watch some of his videos if you don\'t know. To me it accounts for the issues of a slug\'s consciousness (or paramecium more specifically) and qualia. Hameroff\'s recent post on his page interpreting the newest psilocybin research (http://www.quantumconsciousness.org/upsidedown.htm) makes a lot of sense to me and gives me a favorable impression of the model. I just wanted to add that for people who haven\'t looked at the Penrose-Hameroff \"Orch OR\" model yet. ','2012-07-08 18:33:18','2012-07-08 18:33:18');
INSERT INTO `replies` VALUES (2242,96,48,'\r\n\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nWhat does everyone think about making this an open letter to Dr Dennett with the goal of finding out what everyone thinks on this issue?  I\'ve included a list of people and forums I participate on that I think would be interested in this.  Would anyone else have any other friends or forums they would feel comfortable sending such an open letter to?\r\n\r\n\r\n* e-mail to:\r\n** Daniel Dennett\r\n** Keith Frankish\r\n* e-mail cc:\r\n** Richard Brown\r\n** Marvin Minsky\r\n** Hans Moravec\r\n** Linda Chamberlin\r\n\r\n* [http://philpapers.org/bbs/subject.html philpapers forum]\r\n\r\n* Yahoo Groups\r\n** MindBrain\r\n** jcs-online\r\n** extrobritannia\r\n\r\n* Google Groups:\r\n** Artificial General Intelligence\r\n** comp.ai.philosophy\r\n** sci.cognitive\r\n** transifurism.com (MTA e-mail list)\r\n** turingchurch\r\n\r\n* Other e-mail lists:\r\n** extropy-chat\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSubject: \'\'\'Currently leading â€œqualiaâ€ camp attacking Dennettâ€™s â€œmistakeâ€\'\'\'.\r\n\r\n\r\nOpen letter to Dr.s Daniel Dennett and Keith Frankish,\r\n\r\nThere is a newly emerging camp, at Canonizer.com, very supportive of Daniel Dennettâ€™s ideas about consciousness called [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/18 Representational Functionalism].  Despite this rapid achievement of some significant consensus for this new camp, it still lags behind the leading expert consensus [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/19 Property Dualism] camp at that level.\r\n\r\nIn response to the theoretically revolutionary success of this new emerging camp, the experts supporting the currently leading â€œclassic qualiaâ€ camp are working to canonize a new version of their camp statement containing a significant attack against this upstart.  This attack is against the â€˜mistakeâ€™ most often attributed to Daniel Dennett, when people claim we donâ€™t have qualia \"it just seems like we do.\" [Consciousness Explained P. 375].\r\n\r\nThe experts in this upstart camp, in response to this pending attack, have proposed that Daniel Dennett doesnâ€™t mean that we don\'t have some subjective experiences. It would be tautologically false to say, \"We don\'t have the experiences that we seem to have, we just seem to have them.\"  Instead, they suggest that Dennett is saying something like \"we don\'t have experiences that have any magical properties beyond the causal structure and dynamics of physics, it just seems like we do.\"\r\n\r\nIs this response being taken by this upstart camp the best consensus thinking by the most experts?  How many other experts are there that think this is a completely inadequate response, for the reasons being given in the newly proposed Property Dualism statement containing this attack?  Is this really a mistake?  Are there any other better ways to think about this issue out there, and how much consensus might there be for such?  Both camps would like to know, what Dr. Dennett thinks, so we can avoid this kind of speculation in any statements that end up making it through the canonization process.\r\n\r\nThis is an open letter in that we are seeking to survey for what everyone thinks on this issue.  How many people will be in the camp Dennett will ultimately end up in, before he is, after all the arguments and science are said and done?\r\n\r\nThe new version of Property Dualism camp statement, and related sub camp statements, containing this attack are being collaboratively developed by everyone in a wiki way on Google docs, to eventually be \'canonized\' once finalized by everyone.  We invite any and everyone to help improve this process, whatever your current working hypothesis is regarding consciousness.\r\n\r\nAs always, the goal of this open survey process is to collaboratively develop concise and quantitative descriptions of the best theories of consciousness, and to rigorously measure and track such in as we approach w hat could turn out to be the greatest and most consensus building discovery of all time.\r\n\r\nHere are the links to the new Goggle doc statements being wiki developed by everyone for eventual canonization by each camp:\r\n\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gginaif0YTvDVSwFF7V_wRei-SDZlelt0LPIc5I_gD8/edit Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1dogSoCsouz2RhQ-CTNjtnYJ8Xr6JILNDki5Kn_met_o/edit Material Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V03WBMSY5cKf97NoM6KPZSKtxEEHg5MZJfb6FPq0Ui0/edit Macro Material Property Dualism]\r\n\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\n  Brent Allsop\r\n  Volunteer Consciousness Survey Project\r\n','2012-07-08 19:05:37','2012-07-08 19:05:37'),(2245,96,48,'Hi Henry,\r\n\r\nWelcome to the survey topic as the newest supporter of Orch OR theory.\r\n\r\nPerhaps you could provide an introductory letter in this [http://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/28 welcome thread for the topicd] so we can all know who you are?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-08 19:10:08','2012-07-08 19:10:08'),(2248,96,48,'\r\nHi Rich,\r\n\r\nYou replied to my assertion that you need extraordinary evidence to challenge expert consensus with \"No pressure then.\"\r\n\r\nNo!!  You are obviously a brilliant expert in this field, and we\'d love to have your support at any level, more than just \"RQT\".  So, the pressure is on our camps to \'improve them\' in your view, to win you to our camps.  We desperately want to capture much more of the agreement that exists between our views, than is currently represented.  In my mind, the literal salvation of the world is dependent on such, - so, yes, for me, the pressure is on! ;)\r\n\r\nYou said:\r\n\r\n    \"There is partial consensus: i agree with property dualists\r\n    who hold the view that computers can\'t be conscious\r\n    but not with those property dualists who believe\r\n    computational functionalism. A further problem is the claim\r\n    that phenomenal properties are fundamental properties of the\r\n    universe, a position that leads Chalmers into panexperientialism.\"\r\n\r\nThis appears to be the same issue that lead James to lead the theoretical revolution splitting \"Representational Functionalism\" away from \"Property Dualism\".  James asserts something like he can prove any additional \'magic\' to what he calls \"structure and dynamics\" of reality must be epiphenomenal, or as you say, related to the NCC.  So it sounds like you, me, and James agree that [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/9 Computational functionalism], under Functional Property Dualism is epiphenomenal, and thereby falsified?\r\n\r\nThe new [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V03WBMSY5cKf97NoM6KPZSKtxEEHg5MZJfb6FPq0Ui0/edit proposed version of the Macro Material Property Dualism statement] has the following statement, distinguishing it from Panexperientialism:\r\n\r\n    \"Panpsychism is the view that minds are a universal\r\n    part of everything in nature.  Panexperientialism is\r\n    slightly less drastic, and is just the idea that: \"subjective\r\n    experience is more ubiquitous than we think\".  Macro\r\n    Material Property Dualism is even more basic than this.\r\n    It is simply the idea that there are phenomenal qualities\r\n    of at least something in nature.  It is agnostic as to whether\r\n    things outside our brain might have them, but it is certainly\r\n    open to the possibility.  All that is necessary, is that something\r\n    in our brain has, or is responsible for the phenomenal qualities\r\n    we know, absolutely, exist in our minds.\"\r\n\r\nYou obviously share my disdain for Panexperientialism, but given this, what do you think of macro material property dualism?\r\n\r\nOr, do you, like James, still agree that reality can\'t have any additional qualities to it, without them being tied to the NCC, whether material or functional, in an epiphenomenal way?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-07-08 21:49:40','2012-07-08 21:49:40'),(2251,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nI\'d like to welcome [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/81/17 John Smythies], (aka [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=97 john locke] ) of the famed [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/14 Smythies-Carr Hypothothesis] back.  He has indicated that he was away, very busy with editing and contributing to the first book on the functional neuroanatomy of the claustrum (now in press).  John, perhaps you could provide more information on how we might access this as I\'m sure I\'m not the only one here that would be interested in such.\r\n\r\nJohn was one of the first world class people in this field to \'canonize\' his view and contribute significantly to the survey.  Much which we have  today, is largely due to his early help.  I\'ve attempted to keep his views maintained in the \"Property Dualism\" camps that he still supports, but fear we\'ve let some things creep in that he may not agree with?  I look forward to any proposals he may have to improve such, so all the parent camps of the Smythies-Carr Hypothesis will be consistent with that theory.\r\n\r\nJust an operational note.  I apologize for the way the system takes so long to make post to topic forums with lots of supporters.  This has led to John and others to press the submit button multiple times resulting in occasional multiple posts.  The first thing the system does is make the DB entry, then it takes time to send e-mail to each supporter, before it returns a success response.  The correct way would be to cue up the e-mail sending, and let some post process handle the sending of the e-mail.  It\'s just that nobody has had time to implement such a feature, yet.  (Anyone care to help out with such, and other critical fixes - such will earn \'shares\' in Canonizer.com).\r\n\r\nI\'m going to be manually cleaning some things up, such as the multiple posts, so you may notice some strange behavior like the numbers of posts, after multiple posts, will change.  So this is just FYI, so you know I\'m cleaning a few thinks like this up.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-08 22:47:25','2012-07-08 22:47:25'),(2254,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nWhat really are phenomenal qualities other than subjective experiences? Isn\'t it tautological to say that \'something in our brain\' has subjectivity? Why not the entire brain?\r\n\r\nDoes it really make sense that all of the possible subjective qualities of the universe are confined to this particular grouping of cell membranes, lipids, fatty acids, etc but nothing else anywhere in the universe experiences anything? Where would these properties suddenly come from, especially when they have no function?\r\n\r\nCall it panphenomenalism if it goes down better, but whatever way you slice it, subjectivity appearing suddenly at some arbitrary level of description; a person > brain > neuron > microtubule > molecule > quantum ensemble really has no more or less credibility than any other level. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, if we try it my way, we see that phenomenology makes *perfect* sense as the private-temporal-holistic-signifying branch of physics while what we have previously considered physics is only the public-spatial-reductive-generic branch. Physics is the intersubjective GUI, not the program. The program is made of qualia, all the way up and down the microcosm-macrocosm. To assume otherwise I think is anthropocentric.','2012-07-08 22:48:14','2012-07-08 22:48:14'),(2257,96,48,'Hi Craig,\r\n\r\nAh, Craig, very good questions!!\r\n\r\nMMPD predicts Phenomenal qualities are simply the redness, we naively think are qualities of the strawberry.  We naively think of them as being causal, as if they are why the strawberry reflects 650 NM light.  MMPD thinks this is the right way to think of redness, we just need to know that these qualities are of something in our brain, causing the actions of our mind, not a property of the strawberry, causing 650 NM light to be reflected.\r\n\r\nMMPD is agnostic to anything called \"panphenemenalism\", it is just open to the idea that the surface of the strawberry, and anything else in nature may have ineffable phenomenal qualities.  The only thing MMPD predicts for sure, is something in the brain does have these ineffable properties, blind to traditional abstracted observation, because of the quale interpretation problem.\r\n\r\nMMPD also predicts the other important part is the natural binding process, done by at least the corpus callosum, which enables the brain to use things with these phenomenal properties to build or \'bind\' or phenomenally paint our conscious knowledge with.  Obviously, things outside of the brain are beyond this binding process, so can\'t be part of what we experience as our unified / painted phenomenal knowledge.\r\n\r\nAh, your theory is an \"intersubjective\" theory?  Multiple people in the past have started various other camps with \"intersubjective\" doctrines, such this abandoned [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/12 Consciousness is Subjective, Though Real] camp (need to set the filter to 0 to see it).  I\'ve always tried to get these camps to merge together, to show everyone what they agree on, and define what they could possibly mean by \'intersubjective\', but they never seem to be able to do that, and they always seem to eventually abandon their effort to support their ideas at here.  To me such is very telling of the quality of such ideas?\r\n\r\nAlso, all the camps that had \'intersubjective\' doctrines, also predicted that effing of the ineffable would be impossible.  Obviously, I think their camps are about to be falsified in a BIG way, especially on this prediction.\r\n\r\nTell me again if you think we will be able to ever \'eff\' the ineffable, and how/why?\r\n\r\nCould you, possibly, define what you mean by \'intersubjective\' hopefully in a way that is mechanically definitive enough so that one could simulate such in a computer, or artificial brain, or anything?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-07-09 00:39:57','2012-07-09 00:39:57'),(2260,96,48,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\nYou said: \"MMPD predicts Phenomenal qualities are simply the redness, we naively think are qualities of the strawberry\"\r\n\r\nIt sounds like you are saying that MMPD predicts that red is red.\r\n\r\n\"it is just open to the idea that the surface of the strawberry,\"\r\n\r\nThe idea that the strawberry has a surface is contingent upon a certain perspective, scale, and range of sensory capacities. There is nothing that can exist or be defined in any way outside of some form-detecting experience. If there were, what would it be? How would it be different from nothing?\r\n\r\n\"Obviously, things outside of the brain are beyond this binding process\"\r\n\r\nIf that were true, then you could not bind your argument to what you think is the real world outside of your brain. Everything you say here could only be relevant to your corpus callosum and nothing else.\r\n\r\n\"Ah, your theory is an \"intersubjective\" theory?\"\r\nYes, in the sense that it is not solipsism. If you say red, I know exactly what you mean. Voila - intersubjectivity. With my theory I mainly try to describe what consciousness actually is, and not try to shoehorn it into some made up category. Once we accept that all categories and notions of reality can only be knowable to us through consciousness, we are freed of the impossible task of converting consciousness into aggregates of unconsciousness.\r\n\r\n\"Tell me again if you think we will be able to ever \'eff\' the ineffable,\r\nand how/why?\"\r\n\r\nEffing the ineffable is easy with sufficient technology. All you have to do is connect your brain to a device that can connect to other brains. Could be a transcranial magnetic appliance or a surgical implant. If you are talking about some kind of way of mathematically describing red that will enable blind people to see red just by understanding the description, then no, that is never going to happen.\r\n\r\n\"Could you, possibly, define what you mean by \'intersubjective\'\r\nhopefully in a way that is mechanically definitive enough so that one could simulate such in a computer, or artificial brain, or anything?\"\r\n\r\nNothing can simulate subjectivity, for the same reason that you cannot make a blind person see red by doing anything other than actually manipulating their brain to see red. It is not even clear that this is possible without a real experience of seeing red in the world - ie, you may have to cure their blindness in order for them to experience red in any way. That is something that could be experimentally shown one way or another. As far as I know there has never been a case of someone blind from birth who has gained sight later and verified that visual sense was in any way familiar to them. It may not be a potential of the brain alone, but an interaction of the brain, eye, and optical environment of the outside world.\r\n\r\nIntersubjective means that we share the same experiences. Whether they are exactly the same is not the point. Consciousness itself is made of \'seems like\'...jumping to conclusions, filling the gaps, etc, so just as heart cells synchronize their rhythm in close proximity, subjects can dance, communicate, co-operate, commune, etc and they do so routinely. Living organisms are social by definition - ie quorum sensing, plant communication, insect hives, etc. We share common sense and motives. This is not accomplished by any magical substance that flies through the air between us, rather it is that the separation between us is only real on some levels of description but not others. \r\n\r\nThe universe outside of our own consciousness can only be, on some level, one thing. A single moment. Consciousness is what divides that moment into smaller nested recapitulations of the whole. Physics-wise, there is really no support for any other possibility. Physics has no way of delineating any possible \"now\" or range of coherent temporal divisions. There are no beginnings and endings in physics, no place for an observer to arise from. Relativity works, once you assume an observer, but without that assumption, you are looking at one eternal indivisible moment.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-09 02:20:31','2012-07-09 02:20:31'),(2263,96,48,'\r\nHi Craig,\r\n\r\nThere is lots of evidence here that you are still failing to understand much of the consensus theories  The worst problem is your ambiguous usage of the term \'red\'.  I have no idea if you are talking about causal red, or a redness quale.  In other words, to me, this is just strong evidence that even you don\'t really understand very clearly what \'red\' is.  And things like this  makes it very hard to talk to you.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2012-07-09 02:52:53','2012-07-09 02:52:53'),(2266,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure what evidence you are referring to, but I can assure you that I understand the theories being discussed here. I don\'t focus on them because I can see why they can never work.\r\n\r\n\"The worst problem is your ambiguous usage of the term \'red\'. I have no idea if you are talking about causal red, or a redness quale. \"\r\n\r\nThere is no \'causal red\'. Red is a visual quale and nothing but a visual quale. Nothing other than the quale of red is red in any way. This is not evidence that I don\'t understand what you are talking about - I do know that you assume that redness must correspond to a mechanical event which produces it and that this assumption is a deep and abiding, unquestioned aspect of how you understand the relation between brain, mind, and perception. I recognize that It is very popular at this time in history but my understanding is that this is clearly and glaringly mistaken. \r\n\r\nYou think that of course there is a process in the brain and that we experience that process as red. I am saying that the process in the brain represents the events during which we make sense of things that are red - how we access and reveal the real-world relation between who we are and what our experience is. Not a solipsistic simulation, not naive realism, not naive materialism: multisense realism. Sense that is semi-permeable to objective realism. Red is not inside the brain, nor outside the brain. It has no location but our access to is governed through material relationships which do have locations. The brain is the vehicle through which red is experienced. Red is a visual feeling, which for us, is made of \'human lifetime\'. \r\n\r\nIt may seem strange and stupid to think of it this way, but instead of assuming that I am an idiot, just for fun consider that I might be years ahead of you. Pretend that I am from the future and telling you something new that is far superior to anything that is being discussed here. I know that sounds over the top ridiculous and wacko, believe me. I know that how I describe it is not appealing. Again, I\'ve heard. None of that matters to me. It\'s hard to talk to me? Get over it or give up. If you are interested in really getting to what consciousness is about, you have to go back to square one and start over. Everything that you think you know about perception is wrong, or more precisely, upside down.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-09 04:02:10','2012-07-09 04:02:10'),(2269,96,48,'Thanks for your nice comments Brent! In reply to your request for more details about our book  â€œThe Functional Neuroanatomy of the Claustrumâ€, this is \"in press\" and will be published by Elsevier early next year. \r\nHere is a list of the chapters\r\n\r\nPrologue: Christof Koch, \r\nHistory and Nomenclature: Jack Johnson, \r\nPhylogeny and Ontogeny: Luis Puelles,\r\nAnatomy: Rastislav Druga, \r\nPhysiology: Christoph Kayser, and Ryan Remedios, \r\nNeurochemistry: Joan Baizer, \r\nFunctional and Structural lmaging Studies (non-clinical): Juan Fernandez-Miranda, \r\nBinding and Multisensory Integration: Ramachandran,\r\nNeurocomputation and Coding: Klaus Stiefel, \r\nClinical Relationships [individual authors for each sub-section]\r\nâ€¢	Autism: Jerzy Wegiel, \r\nâ€¢	Schizophrenia: Nicola Cascella \r\nâ€¢	Alzheimer\'s disease: Annalena Venneri, \r\nâ€¢	Parkinson\'s disease: Michail Kalaitzakis, \r\nâ€¢	Epilepsy: Michael Corcoran, \r\nâ€¢	Other disorders: to be determined (e.g. multiple sclerosis, lissencephaly, Huntingtonâ€™s disease).\r\nHypotheses: John, Rama and Larry,\r\nEpilogue: Denis Noble.\r\n\r\nHere is the epilogue to our chapter, which puts it all in a nutshell.\r\n\r\nThe function of the claustrum in a nutshell: the brainâ€™s War Room.\r\n\r\nAny large organization, composed of many modules that process incoming information, and has an output in the form of intelligent behavior, will have a problem with internal information flow. Each module is busy processing its own input and providing an output, but how does one module know what another is doing, and how does the organism as a whole know what is going on, and what best to do next? Intercommunication between the modules soon leads to overload. Direct intermodular connections, however extensive, and non-linear dynamics can only go so far. \r\nFor example, in an army, one unit can make judgments about what to do next by observing what other units beside it in the line are doing, and making rational decisions. These may be right in the local context, but wrong in the context of the overall war plan. In the Napoleonic wars this is what generals in charge of brigades had to do during the time it took a galloping horse to get from Paris to Madrid. Another example is the battle of New Orleans, which was fought after the War of 1812 had ended. The advent of wireless telegraphy changed the situation. During WW2 Churchill set up a control room in the basement of 10 Downing Street. This was equipped with a large map in the center of the room, where small models of the planes, ships, tanks, etc. involved could be moved about in response to telegraphed reports from the front. The generals could review the whole situation at a glance, and make instant decisions about what orders to send back. We suggest that the claustrum, with its own internal maps, is doing the same thing. It not only â€˜bindsâ€™ sensory information, as Crick and Koch proposed, but it is receives edited incoming information (evaluated for novelty and salience) from five different channels (via thalamoclaustral afferents). It then calls in further reports and analyses, when needed, from areas of cortex it activates (by means of a web of synchronized oscillations and axon bursts). Lastly the claustrum circuits integrate all this activity (via intraclaustral synchronized oscillations), to come up with a series of executive orders transmitted to the motor cortex. In other words, the claustrum may do for its brain what Churchillâ€™s War Room did for the Allied armies. We do not imply that this model requires the infamous little green man in the War Room reading all this incoming data and making decisions based on it. The evaluation of the data and the decisions are both  functions of the interacting rhythms.\r\n\r\nHere is the last paragraph that provides a poetic finale: \r\n\r\nIn a study of sparse and dense codes in the brain during exposure to language passages and music Lloyd (2011) found that the resulting fMRI activity has properties more similar to music than to language. Crick and Koch (2005) famously likened the claustrum to the conductor of the orchestra. We agree that the evidence points to this role for the claustrum, as the conductor of an orchestra that plays a symphony woven out of a continual shimmering interplay of information-laden harmonies built out of synchronized potentials oscillating at many different frequencies.\r\n\r\n','2012-07-09 05:48:27','2012-07-09 05:48:27'),(2272,96,48,'Multisense Realism writes:\r\n\r\n>>>>\r\n\r\nIt may seem strange and stupid to think of it this way, but instead of assuming that I am an idiot, just for fun consider that I might be years ahead of you. Pretend that I am from the future and telling you something new that is far superior to anything that is being discussed here.\r\n\r\n<<<<\r\n\r\nHahahaha! Well there you have it! Say no more!\r\n\r\nStunning new discovery on the frontiers of science: The eye does NOT work like a camera, the retina is NOT a photosensor array, and there are NO IMAGES ON THE RETINA, and no images in our brain when we dream a dream of images!\r\n\r\nAnd our experience of the world is DIRECT, experienced out there where it lies, by some magical process projected out of our heads in a manner that will never be replicated in an artificial device.\r\n\r\nWe can all go home, the problem is solved!  \r\n\r\nJust for fun, consider that I may be years behind you! Pretend that I am from the past, and telling you something far superior to anything being discussed here. \r\n\r\nRevolutionary breakthrough in science! Kepler discovers the eye works like a camera! The retina is a photosensory array that records images! And Descartes discovers the optic nerve as a data pipeline from the eye to the brain!\r\n\r\nBut thats impossible! If that were true, then everything I see around me must be a picture in my head!\r\n\r\nIf you can wrap your head around this one, then you have caught up with the rest of us here. If not, then you are back in medieval times where vision is a magical miracle that can never be replicated in machines.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-09 14:57:57','2012-07-09 14:57:57'),(2275,96,48,'John Locke said: \"The evaluation of the data and the decisions are both functions of the interacting rhythms\"\r\n\r\nIsn\'t that just a homunculus by another name though? I agree with what you are saying about the need for intelligence to have a claustrum-like architecture but my concern is in what we really mean by data and thalamoclaustral afferents. If you are saying that the claustrum has a priori afferents, and what it is doing really amounts to coordinating feelings into other, more semantically rich afferents (thoughts, higher order perceptual wholes), then I have no problem with that. If you are saying that the claustrum takes \'data\' and turns it into afferents (actual incoming sensation experiences - not necessarily conscious to the top level of consciousness), then I would ask, why would it do such a thing? Why not perform whatever operations are useful on the data without any kind of afferent experience at all?\r\n\r\nAs for slehar, your hackusations are the same as before, so I refer you to my prior responses. Your view seems to be that the visual cortex exists to invisibly recreate an image over hundreds of millions of neurons, what already exists a few inches away on the surface of the inside of your eyeball. Why? To make the visible invisible so that we can then somehow see it? As long as you take consciousness for granted, and try to reverse engineer what you already assume, you are only going to end up with more and more complex descriptions of structures which have no business seeing or experiencing anything.\r\n\r\n\"But thats impossible! If that were true, then everything I see around me must be a picture in my head!\"\r\n\r\nYeah, I remember when I thought that there must be pictures in my head. I\'m just in your head too. Wee!','2012-07-09 16:30:51','2012-07-09 16:30:51'),(2278,96,48,'Good point! Of your two interpretations the first is what I mean. \r\nA great deal of information processing in the brain is effected by synchronized oscillations at a wide range of different frequencies. The claustrum has bilateral connections with almost all the cortex and many subcortical areas, including much of the limbic system that deals with motivation and emotions. The interior of the claustrum consists of a fairly uniform and dense array of pyramidal cells and a syncytium of GABAergic interneurons, all packed together like sardines. Its afferent inflow is topographically distributed thoughout this syncytium. Most neurocomputations related to consciousness are based on extended neural networks that need to talk to each other in a dynamic system of NCCs that underwrite the swift and ever-changing flow of sensations, thoughts, feelings and actions that form a consciousness. \r\n(Remember that the brain generates only  NCCs. The relation of these NCCs to experiential events is another story. Phenomenal events may be identical to NCCs (as in the Identity Theory): or they may be non-identical correlates (as in the Smythies-Carr hypothesis) .\r\n\r\nThe interaction of all these NCCs is effected in the first instance by weak intracortical connections. For example, in a task that involves audiovisual coordination, the neurons in each cortex carrying this task-related activity start to synchronize their oscillations and to align their frequencies. This synchronization in the first instance depends on weak corticocortical connections between two areas of cortex that are widely separated. However, each cortical area also sends axons to the claustrum. Here the â€˜auditory task â€™ neurons are packed close to the â€˜visual taskâ€™ neurons. This makes the synchronization more powerful. This process extends to any cortical areas that are conjointly involved in any task. This includes the emotional, motivational and motor systems. \r\n\r\nLong distance information transfer in the brain is carried by vastly complex spatiotemporal patterns of spikes in axons. These patterns reflect inter alia the patterns of synchronization of the parent neurons of these axons. The information to and from the claustrum is carried by these spike trains. However, inside the claustrum, the information is carried largely by dendrodendritic connections, as well as by the GABAergic syncytium that uses electrical synapses. Both support a population of complex intraclaustral synchronized oscillations that compete for dominance. It is important to realize that the claustrum does not â€˜readâ€™ the incoming axonal codes. It merely provides a forum and mechanism for their competitive interaction that determines the content of the final executive signal sent to the motor cortex. No little green man!\r\n','2012-07-09 17:52:40','2012-07-09 17:52:40'),(2281,96,48,'Thanks John,\r\n\r\nVery intriguing. Let me throw out a few questions to you and pose a couple of ideas (because some folks here can\'t seem to get enough of my ideas :D). I ask these perception-neurology questions of you only because I\'m lazy and am hoping to get answers closer to the \'equine oral cavity\' as it were if you happen to know them.\r\n\r\n1. In the recent study on psilocybin http://www.nature.com/news/psychedelic-chemical-subdues-brain-activity-1.9878 (and others like it if there are any), do you know if the overall activity is decreased in the brain or whether the decrease in the activity in core areas is partially compensated for by increases in other areas less frequently used?\r\n\r\nEither way I think the experiments give credence to Huxley\'s intuition that the brain is a reducing valve, but I think that an overall decrease would have implications for the hard problem - namely that the brain is involved only in the organization of consciousness, the spatiotemporal splitting and eliding of whole experiences (which could extend over large ranges of time - lifetimes even, allowing for synchronicity and more exotic phenomenal occurrences).\r\n\r\n2. Do you know if the processing of 3-D images (stereoptically observed external objects and or intentionally imagined 3-D visual experiences) is associated with more NCC activity or less than that of comparable 2-D images? \r\n\r\nThe reason that I ask is that I have noticed that if I close one eye and look at a flat photo, soon I will begin to see 3-D depth to it. I have a fairly substantial astigmatism so I don\'t know if my experience is common or not (some people who I ask say they have the same effect, but not everyone).\r\n\r\nIs the 3-D effect an example of my brain working harder to give everything depth that it can in the absence of the other eye, or is it actually easier for the brain to assume everything has depth and that this is really a default volumetric projection qualia of human vision which takes work to inhibit in the perception of flat surfaces? Just curious, but again, if the 3-D is easier for the brain, that would support more of a holistic top-down meta-correlate of neurology (MCM) in addition to the interplay of discrete bottom-up NCCs.\r\n\r\nI like your Smythies-Carr hypothesis quite a bit - actually I feel like I can plug it in seamlessly to my own (I can hear the groans in advance). Not that you asked, but here are some possibilities that I would be interested to see if you have considered.\r\n\r\nIn your description it says \"These organized events, for one individual person, are located in a 3D space of their own (\"phenomenal space\") (A) external to common physical space (B). A and B are different cross-sections (or branes) of a higher-dimensional space (the bulk).\"\r\n\r\nWhat I suggest here is a radical reformulation which is anchored in the orthogonal symmetry of A and B rather than the mere separation of the two as nominally distinct but otherwise arbitrarily divided cross-sections. How this goes is that (A) is not a phenomenal space, but rather it is (Ab) - phenomenal time (space) and (B) is not common physical space but inter-phenomenal space(time) or (Ba). \r\n\r\nWhat this does is provide a path from the figurative motives we experience consciously to the literal behaviors which are orchestrated throughout the nervous system in efferent control (of mental attention, intention, volition, etc - again over long periods of time, as in \'I\'m trying to become a doctor\' is a long term phenomenological motive which is expressed in many efferent events over many years). That explains part of how free will works - it is feelings, being, doing as serial translations into public space what is subjectively manifested as a temporal-participatory fugue - ie a pure semantic narrative having limited or no spatial dimension (even figuratively there is no meaningful role that space plays - but \'place\' does play a role metaphorically...but that\'s a whole other kettle of fish). This narrative is concretely and physically real, only orthogonal to public matter-energy-space descriptions. It is the private sense-motive-time origination of descriptions; a warm soft fiction from which cold hard facts emerge (and vice versa...Abâ†”Ba).\r\n\r\nWhat all this means is that while we can productively look as synchronizations of oscillations of NCC, if we want to understand consciousness itself, we should flip it upside down and see the NCCs not as synchronizations that bind data streams but as the end result of experientially coherent solitude that is being broken out across space in many different levels of (Ba) description: Molecules, cells, tissues, the brain as a whole, the body, and body\'s environment. Does this make any sense at all to you?\r\n\r\nIf it does, I think it is the tip of the iceberg which has real implications for psychology, physics and information theory which I can only begin to scratch the surface. Even so, I think that flipping perception around like this is key. This way NCCs are not merely a feed forward system that has an inexplicably conscious target (which I still see as being a homunculus in what you are describing...you\'re just calling it a motor cortex instead) but a bi-directional, involuted (mind in brain and brain in mind) nested dual aspect (Ab mind = non-dual, Ba matter = dualistic, mind looking at matter, mind looking at mind) monism based in \'sense\'.\r\n\r\nThe parallel universe you describe is right here, only we experience it directly and privately rather than the universe of public space which we experience indirectly as a quantitatively flattened (objectified) observation. This means that it is not colliding branes but eliding stories which can have brane-like shadows in the (Ba) interphenomenal representation.','2012-07-09 22:07:30','2012-07-09 22:07:30'),(2284,96,48,'Hi M.R.\r\nIn answer to your two questions, in a system as modular as the brain overall activity may not be a good guide as to what is going on. One has to focus on what the bits are doing. \r\n\r\nI have suggested elsewhere (in the SPR journal) that Bergsonâ€™s filter is constituted by the brainâ€™s glutaminergic NMDA receptors. This is based on the fact that ketamine (an NMDA receptor blocker) can produce all the phenomena of an NDE. So is the NDE merely a set of drug-induced hallucinations? If so, we have to ask why does it produce just those very specific NDE experiences? There is no plausible physiological answer to that question. The alternative explanation is that one normal function of NDE-mediated activity in the brain is to inhibit the spontaneous activity of the psyche, as Huxley suggested. This hypothesis can be tested by seeing if subjects under ketamine develop the 5th dimensional perceptions described by the French physician Jean-Pierre Jourdan. He found that some of his subjects, during an ordinary NDE, saw the physical world from a 5th dimensional perspective: just as we see Flatland from a 3 dimensional perspective. This enabled them to see inside closed boxes and what was going on in the next room, etc..  His fascinating book (Near Death Experiences) describing these experiments is available on Amazon.com kindle.\r\n','2012-07-10 04:33:44','2012-07-10 04:33:44'),(2287,96,48,'Hi John,\r\n\r\nWow, this is all very great educational stuff about the claustrum.  I have some specific questions for you, Steve, and any other neuroscientists out there, so I wanted to start up a new thread on this topic, if thatâ€™s OK.\r\n\r\nYou talk about the Neural Correlates of Consciousness, or NCCs.  Iâ€™m wondering, in your experience with all these neural scientists, how much do they understand about these NCCs, and how much interest is there in such?  For what interest there is in them, what is it, exactly, that they think they are looking for, or testing for and how are they looking for or testing for these NCCs?\r\n\r\nFor example, when I heard about the now famous [http://newscenter.berkeley.edu/2011/09/22/brain-movies/ Jack Gallant, making color movies, reading the minds of people watching movies], I contacted him to find out exactly what their movies of the brain were seeing.  I was totally surprised and disappointed that the movies were false colored by them.  Basically Jack Gallant had no idea about color quale theory, as we are capturing in this survey, and he admitted that he had no interest in such.  Like most neural scientists, they seem only interested in stuff they can test for, and immediately turn off when you mention the word qualia.\r\n\r\nSimilarly, Stuart Hameroff (the anesthesiologist), only seems to be looking for experience, as a hole (what disappears, when he puts people to sleep on the operating table.)  His interest in NCCs seems to be at this level, not at something much more specific like what is it that is the NCC for redness vs. greenness, and is there any diversity in such between, us, for example.\r\n\r\nIt seems to me that nobody really knows how to look for or test for NCCs, and nobody is even attempting, or even thinking about such?\r\n\r\nThere seems to already be clear expert consensus out there (for which there is emerging evidence for here at Canonizer.com) for a lot of things like qualia are important, and qualia are properties of the final result of the perception process.  The only remaining controversial issue is what is the relationship between these NCCs, and the experiences of things like redness vs greenness.\r\n\r\nIt seems to me that the only major expert consensus disagreement is split between a few major competing theories about this relationship between what we experience and the NCCs of such.  As you pointed out:\r\n\r\n    â€œPhenomenal events may be identical to NCCs\r\n    (as in the Identity Theory): or they may be non-identical\r\n    correlates (as in the Smythies-Carr hypothesis)â€\r\n\r\nwhich is the major split.  Also, within mind brain identity, the two competing major sub theories are [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/8 â€œFunctional Property Dualismâ€], favored by Chalmers, and [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/7 Material Property Dualism], favored by Hameroff.  In other words, there is consensus on everything except deciding between these 3 main yet to be falsified theories.\r\n\r\nThe current [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/6 RQT camp statement] describes 3 different ways to â€˜effâ€™ the ineffable, or ways to know if my redness is anything like your redness.  In other words, it is predicting that this is the way to look for NCCs, which nobody seems to realize yet?\r\n\r\nWe are in the process of moving these â€˜effingâ€™ ideas, and describing them in more detail in new versions of the following camps:\r\n\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gginaif0YTvDVSwFF7V_wRei-SDZlelt0LPIc5I_gD8/edit Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1dogSoCsouz2RhQ-CTNjtnYJ8Xr6JILNDki5Kn_met_o/edit Material Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V03WBMSY5cKf97NoM6KPZSKtxEEHg5MZJfb6FPq0Ui0/edit Macro Material Property Dualism]\r\n\r\nGiven such methods of â€˜effingâ€™ the ineffable, it seems to me it should be trivially easy to test for which of these 3 main theories is the correct one, and eventually find the real NCCs of redness, and so on â€“ falsifying and forcing all mistaken experts into whatever theoryâ€™s camp is the one.\r\n\r\nHave you seen any evidence that anyone is thinking about looking for what it is, in the brain, that is responsible for my redness, and how to tell if my redness is more like someone elseâ€™s greenness, or possibly someoneâ€™s redness is nothing like someone else has ever experienced before?  In other words, is anyone thinking of testing for any possible diversity of ways our brain experiences something like â€˜redâ€™, and so on?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-10 21:30:47','2012-07-10 21:30:47'),(2290,96,48,'Brent,\r\n\r\nIt seems to me that the effability issue is a red herring. How do you know that your red is the same as your red was a week ago, or twenty years ago? What would it matter? Might not physicists imagine concepts like charge and force differently? Even the structure of atoms and molecules are awfully ineffable when it comes down to it. What is really completely effable?\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-11 01:44:48','2012-07-11 01:44:48'),(2293,96,48,'\r\nHi Craig,\r\n\r\n\r\nJust the way you talk about this makes it seem like to me you don\'t really fully understand what a quale like \'redness\' is, how this is drastically different from something like 650 NM light, and so on, or even what consciousness really is or what is important about it?  Lots of people ask me questions like this - and to me this is a strong indicator of how intelligent they are about what consciousness really is.\r\n\r\nRecently, there was a Barbara Walters special on people\'s beliefs about \"Heaven\" on TV.  In that program a person related a \'near death experience\' where she went up a stair way into heaven.  As she ascended the stairway, she noticed that the sky was a color blue she had never experienced before, and she has looked for such in all the \"color palates\" but has never found it.\r\n\r\nOf course MPD predicts it\'s not heaven, just some other neural transmitter her brain was using to build here near death experience with.\r\n\r\nAnd of course, the whole effing point is I want to know phenomenally what she experienced.  And there are \"tetra chromats\" that experience 4 primary colors, where you and I experience 3.  I want to know what all these extra colors are like for them.  And how are \'color blind\' people color experiences different than mine....  And what do dogs smell crap like - as it surely must be different than what I smell it like.....\r\n\r\nAnd of course, I want to know, phenomenally, what the surface of the strawberry is really like, if anything, beyond just the abstracted information I know about how it behaves.  I want to experience and discover all possible phenomenal properties, not just my current limited set.  In other words, I want to significantly expand my mind, not just intelligently, but phenomenally also.\r\n\r\nEvidently, within your theory, nothing like that is possible, or worth considering, or is just all a \'red herring\'?\r\n\r\nAnd of course RQT is predicting achieving the ability to eff the ineffable, or the discovery of the relationship between our Neural Consciousnes Corelates, and how we experience them, will be the greatest scientific discovery of all time.  And the only thing holding us back is lack of our ability to communicate concisely, quantitatively and effingly.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-11 02:05:40','2012-07-11 02:05:40'),(2296,96,48,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\n\"Just the way you talk about this makes it seem like to me you don\'t\r\nreally fully understand what a quale like \'redness\' is\"\r\n\r\nI don\'t understand why you say that. To me nothing could be simpler than understanding what a quale like redness is. An infant knows what red is, even if they don\'t know what the word that their parents use for it. What I am saying is that just as your memory of the size of your desk in elementary school may not jibe with your experience of it\'s size were you to encounter it now, you can\'t be sure that your quale of redness has not drifted through your life, dragging your memory of it with you. You have only your own word to take that red is still the same. How is that really much different from doubting that my red is the same now as your red is the same now? Maybe I have the red now that you had as an infant..who ultimately cares and why would it matter?\r\n\r\n\"Barbara Walters special on people\'s beliefs about\r\n\"Heaven\" on TV.\"\r\n\r\nI saw that. It was interesting to me that she could remember the color clearly long after the experience. Although she still described it as a kind of blue and not a new primary color.\r\n\r\n\"want to know what all these extra colors are like for them.\"\r\n\r\nSure, yes, but you can\'t because you aren\'t them. If you could neurologically bind your brain with theirs, or electromagnetically tweak your brain to match some of the patterns in the particular sense cortices, you might get a taste of it - or you might not...you might have to have been born a dog and lived as a dog to smell what a dog smells. All of these things can only be determined experimentally though, what is the point of theorizing about them?\r\n\r\n\"I want to significantly expand my mind, not just intelligently, but phenomenally also.\"\r\n\r\nThat\'s what psychedelics are for, my friend. Or, if you aren\'t into that, you can try avoiding food and sleep for a few days. Meditate. Go on a silent retreat. Chant. Lots of ways to open the doors of perception. I would suggest to you though, that what the strawberry is \'really\' like is not \'really\' an askable question, as the strawberry itself is only presented as a strawberry to certain kinds of perceivers. Any animal may perceive a berry in roughly the same way that you do - a sweet juicy blob that smells fruity. Other organisms may not perceive that at all - bacteria, other plants, etc. An inanimate object that we use as an instrument is only detecting resistance to velocity, temperature, etc. The berry is a qualitatively flat field of purely physical characteristics. At least, that\'s what it seems like would be detected by inanimate objects - who knows, maybe every popsicle stick is like the Dalai Lama and has a nice conversation with every piece of trash in the trash can...but I doubt that.\r\n\r\n\"Evidently, within your theory, nothing like that is possible, or worth\r\nconsidering, or is just all a \'red herring\'?\"\r\n\r\nI consider those to be some of the most elementary questions about qualia. Not that they aren\'t worth considering, but that they are not materially important to the hard problem and explanatory gap. It\'s a given that subjectivity is in some important sense, private. Your approach is to try to think of ways to open the locked door, by banging on it and jiggling the knob, while my conjecture explains exactly why the door is there and why it must, by definition, appear locked to the extent that sanity and identity can be maintained.\r\n\r\n\"And of course RQT is predicting achieving the ability to eff the\r\nineffable, or the discovery of the relationship between our Neural\r\nConsciousnes Corelates, and how we experience them, will be the\r\ngreatest scientific discovery of all time. And the only thing holding\r\nus back is lack of our ability to communicate concisely, quantitatively\r\nand effingly.\"\r\n\r\nThe problem with that is that there are no NCCs, any more than particular shadows are correlates of trees and houses. There is no possible theory of NCCs that will ever predict something like a new primary color quale. Neuroscience can tell us how many primary colors we see, or why colors might appear complementary or opposite, or any number of quantitative measures about color, but none of those will *ever* be able to predict exactly what the color xellow might look like. Until you understand why that is not a speculation but a clear statement of fact, I am certain that I am not the one who doesn\'t fully understand qualia.\r\n\r\nCraig Weinberg','2012-07-11 12:14:50','2012-07-11 12:14:50'),(2299,96,48,'Hi Craig,\r\n\r\nYou say nothing could be simpler, yet always talk in ambiguous ways such as \"an infant can know what red is\".\r\n\r\n650NM light is reflected off of the strawberry, whether we are there or not.  Redness, can be there, whether the strawberry is there or not.  As is proved, by the fact that a \"red\" / \"green\" inverter can be added anywhere along the perception process, proves that the two are completely arbitrary, and to talk model any perception process as if they were the same thing is just irrational.\r\n\r\nAlso, you indicated that you think \'effing\' of the ineffable will be possible, within your theory, then you contradict this with things like: \"you can\'t\" know what the near death person experienced \"you aren\'t them\".  So is effing possible or not?\r\n\r\nAlso, I addressed this issue of not being able to experience everything any one person experiences with a quale, like redness, when all the memory of, and attached emotions and everything are bound into the experience to make it complete, in the \"Reduction to the Right Fundamental Level\" section of the [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1I94L7QW4STfLlAm2OXYWQVhVfNmKduASBgf3hySy8DM/edit Effing of the ineffable] paper.  Of course, in order to experience the entire thing, including all the memory, and semantic meaning, you\'d have to duplicate much of the other person\'s brain, and as you say, become that person\'s experience.  But prediction is that these complete pictures of experiences can all be broken down, and reduced to fundamental qualities which our brain uses to \'paint\' them with.  And this is what we\'ll be able to easily share / eff, not the entire experience. (at least not without duplication of everything that makes the entire picture/experience)\r\n\r\nYou say: \"there are no NCCs\" and \"There is no possible theory of NCCs that will ever predict something like a new primary color quale.\", which is good to know.  Because MPD is predicting the opposite.  Of course, if science demonstrates this to be the case, you\'ll have to eat your words, to say nothing of your claim that your being right is already a \'fact\', even before there is any demonstrable evidence one way or the other.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-12 02:03:39','2012-07-12 02:03:39'),(2302,96,48,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\n\"You say nothing could be simpler, yet always talk in ambiguous ways such as \"an infant can know what red is\". \"\r\n\r\nWhy is that ambiguous? Infants know simple things. Red is simple and direct. The concept of frequency modulation and electromagnetism are abstract cognitive experiences which an infant would not know. They cannot have the direct experience of 650nm light but they have the experience of red, which is what we can call a visual qualia.\r\n\r\n\"650NM light is reflected off of the strawberry, whether we are there or not. \"\r\n\r\nYes but it\'s not that simple. I agree that there is something physically occurring whether *we* are there or not, but I don\'t think that it is \'light\' any more than it is \'heat\'. Those terms refer to experiential qualia, not objective characteristics. What is objective is unclear as anything that we use to measure electromagnetic oscillations in matter is also made of matter so it is impossible to say whether there is actually an emission of photons from a source and a collision to the sensor or whether it just looks like that because there is a mathematical continuity between what we observe of the behavior of both the emitter and sensor. We have no first hand experience of what a nanometer scale detection instrument \'sees\', we only know what is seems to do.\r\n\r\nThat\'s my conjecture though - I don\'t ask you to consider that as a possibility if you don\'t want to, although I think it makes a lot more sense than the consensus model of literal particle interaction and solves the explanatory gap. If you look at it my way, there is no reflection of light unless there is something to receive and interpret the event as a reflection. If you felt the 650nm \'light\' as heat or as sweetness instead, there would be no sense of reflection and it would be impossible to tell whether the strawberry was warm from the sun/light bulb or generating the heat by itself non-reflectively. \r\n\r\nWe agree that qualia cannot be assumed to be immutably bound to an physical referents or automatically generated consequences of them..data has no sensory preference as we know from computer files. You say the relation is completely arbitrary, and I almost agree, but I only say that they are not directly related - they may very well be indirectly related through sense. Sense allows us the possibility of penetrating our solipsistic bubble, not to contact an absolute reality, but to internalize greater and more inclusively true experiences than just the self, mind, or brain, can generate.\r\n\r\nLet\'s look at it your way though and say that 650nm \"light\" does not require any receiver and independently exists in a way that red does not. What would be the point, from a functional perspective, of turning that light into something other than what it is? If your visual system can capture the pattern of light to begin with, why turn it into some magical modeling in a new dimension of \'color\'? In order to generate a coherent spectrum of color, where red plus blue equals purple for example, and red light plus green light equals yellow light but red paint plus green paint equals grey-brown paint. That is a lot of sense to make out of a \'completely arbitrary\' hocus pocus. It\'s rather a stretch to imagine that this is a pin-the-tail-on-the-quanta \'representation\' - clearly important truths about light on many levels are revealed with an effectiveness and elegance that our quantitative models have not equaled. If you had to choose whether to understand everything about what your eyes are seeing from a scientific perspective but be blind, ie if you could have X-ray vision and infrared vision, radio vision, etc but have to have that vision only as understood knowledge and information, would you choose that instead of being able to see? Would you go blind in order to have superhuman blindsight? If not, why not? The answer explains the difference between qualia and quanta.\r\n\r\n\"Also, you indicated that you think \'effing\' of the ineffable will be possible, within your theory, then you contradict this with things like: \"you can\'t\" know what the near death person experienced \"you aren\'t them\". So is effing possible or not? \"\r\n\r\nYes, it is probably possible if you connect your brain to another person\'s brain. I never said that is isn\'t possible at some point to merge with another person, just as brain conjoined twins are merged. Sense provides with something even better though - intuition, inference, imagination. Infinitely richer for the universe. Instead of one set of qualia per universe, or one per person, you have each person being able to imagine what others qualia might be like if they want to - and they might even be right, or have valid insights about it.\r\n\r\n\"But prediction is that these complete pictures of experiences can all be broken down, and reduced to fundamental qualities which our brain uses to \'paint\' them with. \"\r\n\r\nThat contradicts what you just said though, which I agree with, that qualia is shaped by experience. Proof: http://medicalxpress.com/news/2012-07-deaf-brain-differently.html\r\n\r\nIf there were complete pictures of experiences which could be reduced, then we would expect to just give an ordinary five year old a calculus book and give them a heavy dose of the neurotransmitters associated with understanding in the areas of the brain associated with mathematics and expect the calculus to become understood without benefit of any experience to get from ignorance to expertise. That is not going to happen. Symbol grounding problem is the key to why. Forms do not automatically generate contents. Formation is not information without sense to interpret it as such. That interpretation is a physical event through time which is experiential and private for which no substitute will suffice. You might be able to speed it up relative to external inertial frames of time measurement so that you can experience something like a slowdown of time while you spend a month learning calculus in your experience with only five minutes elapsed time...maybe that can happen, but not because we force feed the brain a finished configuration. It would be like trying to heat a house by turning logs in the fireplace into ashes directly. You can\'t skip the subjective experience.\r\n\r\n\"There is no possible theory of NCCs that will ever predict something like a new primary color quale.\", which is good to know. Because MPD is predicting the opposite. \"\r\n\r\nIt\'s like a drunk in a bar predicting that he is going to win a fight though. MPD has no way of even defining the actual content of a color (or any other) quale, so there is no danger of it ever being able to predict what a new one would or could look like. What is the prediction based on? Promissory vapor. Why does MPD have any credibility whatsoever in delivering anything more than it already has? What progress can a blind person make in discovering the blueness of blue? To avoid the straightforward reality of that I think can only be wishful thinking and sentimental attachment to naive materialism.\r\n\r\nCraig\r\n','2012-07-12 03:39:14','2012-07-12 03:39:14'),(2305,96,48,'Craig - a point of information.\r\n\r\nYou write in post #179 that Steve\'s \"view seems to be that the visual cortex exists to invisibly recreate an image over hundreds of millions of neurons, what already exists a few inches away on the surface of the inside of your eyeball.\"\r\n\r\nThe image on the retina is radically distorted and in focus only towards the centre. This is further degraded by transduction into nerve impulses by the retina. The visual cortex makes the best of the stream of low quality information about the scene from the eyes to update our somewhat richer visual experience.','2012-07-12 14:36:44','2012-07-12 14:36:44'),(2308,96,48,'Brent, in reply to your post#177\r\n\r\n\"You replied to my assertion that you need extraordinary evidence to\r\nchallenge expert consensus with \"No pressure then.\" \"\r\nNo, i agree that an extraordinary hypothesis requires substantial evidence to back it up. My comment referred to the pressure of apparently being alone in holding a position at variance with \"all these experts\".\r\n\r\nYou didn\'t answer my query with respect to distinguishing dualisms: how do you distinguish property from substance? \r\n\r\n\"So it sounds like you, me, and James agree that Computational functionalism[1], under Functional Property Dualism is epiphenomenal, and thereby falsified? \"\r\nIf a theory entails epiphenomenalism then that counts against it IMO but i don\'t see that as falsification. I have the same objection to computational functionalism as Searle not least because, in a former life, i was a software engineer.\r\n\r\nI think i\'m with James re your new version of PD. You say MMPD is agnostic wrt to panexperientialsim whereas i\'m atheist. The claim \"Macro Material Property Dualism... is simply the idea that there are phenomenal qualities of at least something in nature.\" is too vague. I agree if the something is the brain or any system like it.','2012-07-12 15:02:42','2012-07-12 15:02:42'),(2309,1,32,'I\'m interested to know whether Orch OR camp supporters consider quantum computation to have special attributes over and above non-quantum computation.\r\n\r\nIn an article in the Journal of Consciousness Studies (i forget the ref), Stuart Hameroff claimed that Orch OR saves free will from determinism because quantum events are indeterministic. We quickly came to a disagreement on this issue in email discussion as i recall. I don\'t see that randomness has anything to do with free will - perhaps camp supporters have a view on this?\r\n\r\nIMO the function of microtubules (present in all our cells) is limited to cellular scaffolding and transport - they provide tracks along which molecular motors ferry cellular cargo. The idea that they provide the home for quantum computation that somehow usefully connects with the electrochemical functioning of the neuron seems far-fetched speculation to me. While studying intracellular transport in neurons, i managed to talk to Jack Tuszynski about this issue but could find no grounds for agreement and very little in the way of evidence. Can i ask why it seems convincing to honourable members of this camp?','2012-07-12 15:59:29','2012-07-12 15:59:29'),(2312,96,48,'Richwil,\r\n\r\nThat is a very good point, and does give us guidance as far as the \'Easy Problem\' of Consciousness. There is a mechanism which expands the sense that the retina makes of its optical environment. It still does not get us any closer to imaging why or how there could be an image that must become invisible in the brain to become visible to us though. That is what I am interested in...the Hard Problem. Why have an image at all? If a brain has the data, is certainly needs no magical \'image\' to \'represent\' it. \r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-12 17:59:06','2012-07-12 17:59:06'),(2313,1,32,'Penrose himself points out that randomness is not of much use for neural processes. It leads on from here that he proposes the idea of objective reduction - the reduction of wave functions that are isolated from the environment. He suggests that this form of reduction accesses the \'fundamental geometry of spacetime\'. This may or may not seem far fetched, but at any rate he does not base his ideas for the mind on randomess. In Q&A sessions he has actually rated himself a \'don\'t know\' on freewill. ','2012-07-12 19:21:43','2012-07-12 19:21:43'),(2316,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nThere was a one paragraph section in the new RQT statement entitled \'Effing the Ineffable\'.  There is a popular naive objection to the idea that people use to think we won\'t be able to eff the ineffable which I think we should address.  So I added two new paragraph to this \'effing of the ineffable section.\r\n\r\nLet me know if anyone has any issues with this 2 paragraph addition.\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-14 15:58:36','2012-07-14 15:58:36'),(2319,96,48,'\r\nReply to Rich\'s post #184\r\n\r\nAh, great question, Rich, about how do you tell the difference between property and substance dualism.  Iâ€™ve always just naively waived my hand over that issue, and you noticed I even  ignored you asking about it â€“ so thanks for perusing this issue further as I definitely need to think about this more thoroughly.  This amplification of the wisdom of all of us process is so helpful along these lines.  Itâ€™s launching us all, collectively, way beyond anything the Ivory Tower and their already more than 20K pile of \"peer reviewed\" publication is producing â€“ donâ€™t you think?\r\n\r\nMy previous naive thinking was there is some kind of spiritual stuff in some other spiritual dimension â€“ or something.  And that this stuff has spiritual causes and effects that communicate back and forth with the brain in some way.  Descartes idea was that this communication takes place through the penal gland.  Modern versions usually postulate some kind of quantum weirdness or string theory brane causes and effects, or something, for this causal interface.\r\n\r\nBut I guess, if you think of it rigorously, the best way to define it is â€œDo qualia, or whatever has these phenomenal qualities, have any cause/effect behavior in reality, beyond classical causal physics, or beyond what is observable via objective or abstracted cause and effect based observation?â€\r\n\r\nProperty dualism, and especially Material Property Dualism, says no.  Qualities are just ineffable fundamental qualities of something we already know, behaviorally, and abstractedly, all about.  Its all the same stuff, just two ways to know about it: abstracted information about it\'s behavior, and fundamental qualitative or quale information.\r\n\r\nSo you are saying that you are \"atheist\" about any type or quality of consciousness existing outside the brain, or is it just \"consciousness in its entirety\" existing outside of the brain?  I agree with you, and am also \"atheist\" about \"pansychism\", but only with that.\r\n\r\nLet me ask you if you think there is any possibility that there is more to the surface of the strawberry, than just its ability to behave in a way that it reflects 650 NM light?  Is the strawberry in any way ineffably qualitative or phenomenal?  Obviously, we both agree that something in the brain has more than just behavior which can be simulated, right?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-07-14 17:42:54','2012-07-14 17:42:54'),(2322,96,48,'I don\'t understand Brent\'s reference to \"spiritual stuff\" and \"spiritual dimensions\".  The Smythies-Carr hypothesis says nothing about Cartesian spirits. This theory posits a real hyper-dimensional space filled with real stuff. A phenomenal consciousness in this theory is composed, in part, of its constituent material sensations, that are extended in a real existential, geometric, topological space  This space is topologically outside the 4D physical space-time continuum. Use of the misleading term \'qualia\' obscures this simple notion. The relations between the events in the physical brain and the phenomenal events in a consciousness are spatial (higher-dimensional) and causal. Thus the visual field that you experience, with its constituent visual sensations that present you with a picture of the external world, is literally part of your own organismâ€”and functions just like the screen of a TV set. This simple fact is obscured in the case of most people who mistake their own body-image (the body as experienced) with their own physical body (which they never experience). ','2012-07-14 21:47:33','2012-07-14 21:47:33'),(2325,96,48,'Hi John,\r\n\r\nThere is a reference to \"spiritual stuff\" in the religious section at the end of the proposed new \"Property Dualism\" camp statement.  But I don\'t see a reference to \"spiritual dimensions\".  I appreciate your bringing this up, as we don\'t want to have anything in the Property Dualism statement you disagree with or that is contradictory to the Smythies Carr Hypothosis sub camp.\r\n\r\nEven though we intend on keeping the property dualism open enough to hopefully have a place holder for any \'substance dualism\' or \"cartesian dualism\" camps that show up as sub camps.  But it  should be very obvious to anyone that we (all current supporters of property dualism unanimously) are not talking about cartesian dualism, or even substance dualism here.  Perhaps we need a statement saying as much in the new property dualism statement?  After all, others have mentioned this issue - thinking that property duailsm is the same as substance dualism.\r\n\r\nMy working hypothesis is that \'qualia\', like redness and greenness are ineffable \'spiritual\' qualities.  And that the world in our head is much like any \'spirit world\' talked about in any religious beliefs / assumptions.\r\n\r\nI also think it is critically important to at least integrate our theoretical / scientific terminology with religious terminology as much as possible.  For example, one of the main reasons there is so much popular chatter about \"the GOD particle\" is because of this religious terminology,  I bet they would have never received as much continued funding for the large hadron collider, without this kind of religious terminology.\r\n\r\nMy understanding of the Smythies Carr Hypothesis, is that redness is still a property of the strawberry, not of something in our brain?  If this is the case, would you object to referring to these ineffable redness qualities of the strawberry as \'spiritual\' qualities?  If you do object, I guess we\'ll have to push this terminology yet further down to a lower level sub camp.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-14 22:14:48','2012-07-14 22:14:48'),(2326,1,32,'\r\nOrch OR supporters,\r\n\r\nI wanted to send the below letter, to thank Stuart Hamerof, regarding the recent revolution, of sourts, that placed our camp in the top \'latter\' of expert consensus.\r\n\r\nLet me know what you think, or if you\'re willing to add your name to the letter before I send it.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n====================\r\n\r\n\r\nHello Stuart Hameroff,\r\n\r\nI just wanted to let you know of some significant recent news regarding the consensus level of the \"Penrose-Hameroff Orchestrated Objective Reduction(Orch OR) theory\" (see: http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/20 ) at Canonizer.com for which you authored the current camp statement.\r\n\r\nThere has recently been a theoretical \'revolution\' of sorts, where many of the supporters of David Chalmers \"Functional Property Dualism\" camp (see: http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/8 ) realized they are not \"Property Dualists\".  They, thereby, abandoned this camp, and joined with several others that think like Dennett (as in anti \"classic qualia\"), to create the new quickly emerging Representational Functionalism camp (see: http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/18) to compete with the significant consensus \"Property Dualism\" camp.\r\n\r\nAlso, we recently had some new supporters of \"Orch OR\" effectively \'sign\' your online camp statement by explicitly supporting it.\r\n\r\nAs you can see, there is a clear emerging \'ladder\' of top consensus camps forming on the best theories of consciousness.  This consensus starts with \"Approachable Via Science\" (37/40), then \"Representational Qualia Theory\" (30/40), then \"Property Dualism\" (20/40) and \"Mind-Brain Identity Theory\"(15/40).  After this level, Chalmers \"Functional Property Dualism\" camp was until now leading our competing \"Material Property Dualism\" camp, putting them in this top \'ladder\' of consensus theories.\r\n\r\nHowever these two theoretical \'revolutions\' have enabled \"Material Property Dualism\" (see: http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/7 ) to surpass this camp in how much consensus it has at that level, enabling it to take this spot in the top consensus ladder.  And since \"Orch Or\" is the top supported sub camp of \"Material Property Dualism\", it also ended up on this top consensus ladder level, as you can now see.\r\n\r\nSo I just wanted to say thanks for your work and your support, that helped lead to this, and it will be very exciting to see where it goes from here, as ever more scientific data, and better arguments, continue to get canonized, and as this open survey continues to be ever more comprehensive.  There is an obvious advantage to early emerging camps in this race.  It takes some convincing scientific data / powerful arguments, to lead to these kinds of theoretical revolutions against well established expert consensus theories.  Any additional support would surely cement our camps in this top position, and extend our current lead, as ever more people continue to participate in this open survey, and as we continue to approach THE ONE camp that will not be falsified by the scientific data, forcing all experts to ultimately accept it as THE scientific consensus camp.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop and the other supporters of Orch OR theory.','2012-07-14 23:47:04','2012-07-14 23:47:04'),(2329,96,48,'Hi John,\r\n\r\nHave you considered that our own native everyday biographical experience may be valid in its own right without having to be translated into a hyperdimensional topology? Why can\'t it be exactly what it seems to be?\r\n\r\nNot to say that it can\'t be both, but why does it need to be? What compels us to objectify subjectivity and why isn\'t that considered an aspect of naive realism?\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-15 01:40:25','2012-07-15 01:40:25'),(2332,96,48,'Hi Brent, I think that I may be in the wrong camp since I support substance dualism, not property dualism.  Nor do I think that \'redness\' is a property of the surface of a strawberry. Whereas English usage makes it correct to say \"I see a red strawberry\", neuroscience shows that phenomenal red is not a property of a red physical object, but is the end result of a complex process that includes neurocomputations. The Smythies-Carr hypothesis merely extends this representative mechanism to include the TV-like system outside the brain that actually constructs the visual field. If you are in the complete dark this visual field is a 2D expanse of blackness extended in phenomenal space. However, if your visual cortex is damaged in a accident, you become cortically blind and no longer experience this black fieldâ€”in fact you do not see at all.\r\njohn','2012-07-15 05:01:52','2012-07-15 05:01:52'),(2335,96,48,'Hi Craig,\r\nI would say that the answer to your question is that neuroscience has shown conclusively that we do not experience the world as it is, but only as the brain computes what it is most probably is. So our experience has no validity beyond what the brain gives it. The need for hyper-dimensional theories arises because the events in the phenomenal world are located in a space of their own, and cannot be identical with the events in the brain that form their casual antecedents.\r\nJohn','2012-07-15 05:11:49','2012-07-15 05:11:49'),(2338,96,48,'Hi John,\r\n\r\nYou said \"neuroscience has shown conclusively that we do not experience the world as it is\"\r\n\r\nThe problem that I have is, why should we assume that what neuroscience shows conclusively is not another one of our experienced worlds? Why is our experience of neuroscience *the world as it is* rather than the world as it is when we use neuroscientific instruments that extend the external realism capacities of our bodies?\r\n\r\nWhat I see is that the nature of consciousness is such that cognitive bias extends from whatever our original assumptions are, and will be reinforced by the techniques and chains of associations that we call on to guide us to the truths about the original thesis. In doing this, we foreground one system of thought and background the antithesis system of thought into a caricature.\r\n\r\nIf the conclusions of neuroscience were actually true, then neuroscience itself must also be a delusion. If neuroscience is to have any relation to the world as it is, then we must have a theory of how we get to that point using only the solipsitic simulations that we have. My conjectures provide exactly that. By beginning with the very assumption that both materialism and idealism lead to self-fulfilling pathologies that mischaracterize each other, I build a self-conscious hypothesis of the precise relation between interior and exterior realism.\r\n\r\nMy conclusions at this point is that our interior realism is not a hyperdimensional space which exists in a separate realm but is actually a single deep dimension which \'insists\' in the same universe as neuroscience\'s does, but it is not a dimension of spaces but rather *the* dimension of time. Who we are is time makers. Our experiences charge temporal vectors with perceptual-participatory (sense-motive) significance that could not be achieved otherwise, transforming the relentlessly granular and meaningless snapshots of meaningless structure into holistic narratives. This represents a ground level shift in our interpretation of physics, but not one that requires us to discard any of its observations.\r\n\r\nIf I look at it your way, and tried to create a phenomenology that was all hyperdimensional spaces and structures, I would wind up with nothing at all that feels like this conversation, these fingers tapping on \'my\' keyboard to \'you\'. Instead there would only be a psychotic unrealism of isolated geometric forms and processes. This is not a sentimental hankering for naive realism, this is an opened-eyed, emperor\'s-new-clothes critique of a naive materialism that will not let go of its abiding distrust of feeling, its true belief in the disbelief of non-Cartesian topologies.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-15 11:58:17','2012-07-15 11:58:17'),(2341,96,48,'Hi Craig, \r\nYou ask â€œThe problem that I have is, why should we assume that what neuroscience shows conclusively is not another one of our experienced worlds?â€ \r\nFor a reply I refer you to my paperâ€” \r\n\r\nSmythies, J. â€˜Realityâ€™ and â€˜Virtual Realityâ€™ Mechanisms in the Brain and their Significance.\r\n Journal of Consciousness Studies, 16, No. 4, 2009, pp. ??â€“??\r\n\r\nHere is a bit of it (from the page proof)\r\n\r\nâ€œThen we now have a body of evidence that supports a TV-like theory of perception, by which I mean a theory in which the visual field is built up by a representative mechanism. This evidence comes from a series of experiments that show that, as I said earlier, we perceive a mixture of what us actually â€˜out thereâ€™ and what the brain computes is most probably â€˜out thereâ€™.\r\nRamachandran and his colleagues carried out the first set of these experiments. They showed that scotomata â€” the blind patches caused by local injury if not too large â€” are not perceived as patches of nothing, but that the brain fills them in with a continuation of whatever pattern surrounds them (Ramachandran and Blakeslee, 1998). In addition KovÃ¡cs, Papathomas, Yand and FehÃ©r (1996) have produced further evidence. These workers took two photographs, one of a mon- keyâ€™s face and the second of a leafy tropical jungle. They converted these into two pastiches each composed of portions of each photo, so that in the location where one photo showed part of the monkeyâ€™s face the other showed leafy jungle. Then each pastiche was shown separately to each retina, so that retinal rivalry occurred. Under these circumstances, the subject did not see what was actually there â€” that is the two pastiches alternating â€” but rather a complete monkey face alternating with a complete leafy jungle. Clearly the brain had suppressed the improbable mixed pastiche in favor of what it was familiar with (and thus computed to be more probable). Many other experiments, based on stimuli such as moving plaid patterns, have shown this phenomenon, where the perception of an improbable input is suppressed by the brain, and replaced with the perception of what it computes to be a more probable one (see e.g. Ramachandran and Anstis, 1983).\r\nOther crucial experiments (Kleiser, Seitz and Krekelberg, 2004) have shown that, during a saccade (rapid movement of the eye), information coming from the eye is suppressed, and what we see is largely virtual reality created by the brain with little recourse to the retinal input. These authors expressed it thus: â€˜When you look into a mirror and move your eyes left to right, you will see that you cannot observe your own eye movements. This demonstrates the phenomenon of saccadic suppression: during saccadic eye movements, visual sensitivity is much reduced.â€™ In other words, â€˜filling inâ€™ has a temporal as well as a spatial dimension. This function is based on a widespread neural network, which includes the superior colliculus and parts of the thalamus. The purpose of this would appear to be to suppress the violent swings in the visual input (the world swirling round one) and resulting severe vertigo that would otherwise result. Since saccades occur very frequently, this means that virtual reality plays a role in normal everyday seeing.â€\r\n\r\nThese experimental results are easily explicable in terms of the Representative Theory, but not, I suggest, by any â€œalternative worldsâ€ theory.\r\n\r\nJohn\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-15 16:49:31','2012-07-15 16:49:31'),(2344,96,48,'Hi John,\r\n\r\nYou indicated you support Substance Dualism, and possibly belong in a different camp.  Now that I think about it, this makes a lot of sense.  When you think about all \"Higher Dimensional\" theories, the stuff in these higher dimensions, is the additional dual substance.  I appreciate your further clarifications about the Smythies Carr Hypothosis as that really helps me better understand.\r\n\r\nSo, towards this end, I propose we replace the current \"Property Dualism\" camp, with a more general \"Dualism\" camp.  And we push \"Property Dualism\" down to be a specific type of dualism.  And we move the \"Higher Dimensional Theories\" camp, out from under Property Dualism, and put it under a new competing \"Substance Dualism\" camp.  As follows:\r\n\r\nRepresentational Qualia Theory\r\n* Dualism\r\n** Property Dualism\r\n*** Mind-Brain Identity\r\n*** Panexperientialism\r\n** Substance Dualism\r\n*** Higher-dimensional Theories\r\n**** Consciousness is a 5th dimension of the brain.\r\n**** Calabi-Yau-Ruquist Hypothesis\r\n**** Smythis-Carr Hypothesis\r\n* Representational Functionalism\r\n\r\nWould there be any objections to this kind of a structure change?\r\n\r\nSo, the next question would be how much can we include in the new more general \"Dualism\" camp, and how much must be pushed down?  I\'ll list some of the major doctrines currently in the property dualism camp.  Everyone please let me know if you object to any of these.\r\n\r\n* Classic Qualia Definition (That which cannot be simulated by a computer)\r\n* Ineffable qualities suffer from the \"Quale Interpretation Problem\"\r\n* 3 different strong and weak forms of effing the ineffable.\r\n* Religious terminology.  (thinking of phenomenal qualities, like redness, as spiritual properties)\r\n\r\nIf nobody specifically objects, we\'ll keep these doctrines in the general \"Dualism\" camp, otherwise we\'ll push them down with \"Property Dualism\".\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-15 18:10:44','2012-07-15 18:10:44'),(2347,96,48,'\r\nWelcome, [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=212 Mark Waser],\r\n\r\nAs the newest supporter of Representational Functionalism.\r\n\r\nFeel free to introduce yourself in a topic thread like this one, so everyone can know who you are.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-15 20:56:27','2012-07-15 20:56:27'),(2350,96,48,'Hi John,\r\n\r\nI don\'t think that there is any doubt that external perceptions are a mixture of real-time public experience and accumulated private experiences, but I question the assumption that this constitutes evidence that the private experience is necessarily a failure to approximate a public reality. \r\n\r\nSince looking at a picture of a monkey is already a leap of representation (we know there is no actual monkey inside of our brain or on the screen), we are already breaking the holism of total human perception, which, by my understanding, automatically swings the bias of the experiment toward mechanistic exteriors of our sub-selves rather than matching the natural scope and extent of our individual interior sense.\r\n\r\nIf you want to find the edges where human perception breaks down into computation-like events, then you can do just that by focusing on the granular aspects of a single sense channel, or even fracturing a single sense channel as in binocular rivalry. My view is that this should not by itself be construed as evidence that top-down contributions to perception are computationally derived or are in any way less \'real\' than bottom up processes.\r\n\r\nIn particular, when you say \"Clearly the brain had suppressed the improbable mixed pastiche in favor of what it was familiar with (and thus computed to be more probable).\" I do not see that the kinds of experiments you mention (and forgive me if there is a counterfactual to what I am about to say) positively point specifically to a computation of probabilities or that such a computation is being performed by the brain. I am not opposed to the idea that could be part of what is going on, I just don\'t see how it helps us get from a brain process which matches invisible data criteria to a presentation of whole visual experiences.\r\n\r\nPersonally, I would not jump to any conclusions about computation based on the fact that our perception favors established signal content over unsolicited noise content, only that we have a nose for what matters which is reflected on all levels of our perception. If pushed to decide between signal and noise, we have the latitude to drop spatial or temporal realism in favor of preserving the signal. This does not, in my book, mean that our perception is not a direct realism, only that it has limitations, especially when presenting a fragmented environment that has been contrived to defeat the unity of subjectivity.\r\n\r\nFor neuroscience and the Easy Problem of Consciousness, I agree this kind of research is important to tease out the capacities of our brain\'s ability to deliver a properly conditioned presentation of interior and exterior realism, however I don\'t think it helps us with the Hard Problem. We are assuming representation from the start by using what we know to be optical representations to begin with. We are already taking our own word for the fact that a picture of something is a copy of that thing in some objective and universal way. Especially if our perception were, as I think you are suggesting, mere representation, that assumed universality would be a scientific loose end. \r\n\r\nJust as our perception elides the obstacles presented by noise to extract signal, our assumption that images are actually tied to their referents independently of subjectivity is not strong enough to justify conclusions about consciousness overall. By hiding our cognitive bias with one hand so that we can expose it bias with the other, we are ultimately chasing out tail and missing what I call the Elephant in Every Room. Neuroscience can only be a chain of perceptions grouped together by analytical perceptions, so that anything it says that can be used to cast doubt on the fundamental realism of perception must also cast doubt on our own ability to use neuroscience to learn anything fundamentally real about anything. As Raymond Tallis might say, it saws off the limb it is sitting on.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-16 00:46:44','2012-07-16 00:46:44'),(2353,96,48,'Excellent idea all round Brent! \r\n\r\nJohn','2012-07-16 04:41:26','2012-07-16 04:41:26'),(2356,96,48,'Brent\r\n\r\nSo, as i understand you (post #186), you started off with substance dualism and proceeded to property dualism via Cartesian dualism?\r\n\r\nYes, i believe that the NCC is exclusively brain (or similar system) activity so all the varieties of panpsychism are mistaken IMO.\r\n\r\n\"Let me ask you if you think there is any possibility that there is more to the surface of the strawberry, than just its ability to behave in a way that it reflects 650 NM light?\"\r\nOf course: it has many properties, not just interaction with light.\r\n\r\n\"Is the strawberry in any way ineffably qualitative or phenomenal?\"\r\nNo. It is a delectable fruit composed of water, sugars and so on.\r\n\r\n\"Obviously, we both agree that something in the brain has more than just behavior which can be simulated, right?\"\r\nSo we agree that computational functionalism - the theory that consciousness is some form of computation - is false?\r\n\r\nThere is a range of computer simulations of aspects of neurons and neural networks which more or less replicate measurements taken from the brain and they are being improved all the time as are the instruments of measurement. A simulation, however accurate and comprehensive, is just a bunch of equations churning out numbers that match the numbers coming out of measuring instruments. The point is that simulation is not the system being simulated: only the system has qualia.','2012-07-16 13:45:36','2012-07-16 13:45:36'),(2357,1,32,'Hi Junius\r\n\r\nI would go further than Penrose, randomness is not just useless, it has a negative effect. Hameroff\'s idea, as i recall, was that quantum indeterminacy allows for or supports free will: that\'s always been a mystery to me - how can a random process have anything but a destructive effect on a free choice? \r\n\r\nI don\'t understand what Penrose is proposing - is it panpsychism: is the \"fundamental geometry of spacetime\" conscious?\r\n\r\nI do, however, understand computation. The camp statement says that \"In 1989 Sir Roger Penrose proposed that consciousness is a sequence of quantum computations\". I don\'t see that quantum computation makes programs conscious, hence the question at the start of my previous post.','2012-07-16 14:30:22','2012-07-16 14:30:22'),(2360,96,48,'Richwil,\r\n\r\nWe seem to be on the same page as far as a simulation not being able to experience the qualia of the system that it is supposed to simulate. \r\n\r\nWhere I differ is that while you say of a strawberry\'s proposed non-qualitative nature, you say  \"No. It is a delectable fruit composed of water, sugars and so on. \", I see that this is an arbitrary distinction.\r\n\r\nWhat I mean by that is that when you say that something is delectable or that it is a fruit, we are looking at the thing retrospectively from our own human/mammalian/animal view of the world. Not everything can eat fruit, so there is no reason to believe that the distinction between fruit, vegetable, mineral, delectableness, etc could exist in the absence of an entity which could potentially be interested in eating the thing. In a universe where strawberries were the only living organisms, it would be much more likely IMO that soil would be delectable and the idea of a fruit would have no meaning. If we are to understand consciousness we cannot fail to include the prospective view - starting from the ground up of a universe without consciousness.\r\n\r\nAs to the next level of description of \'water\' and \'sugars\', this is a bit more challenging to view prospectively but the idea is the same. Water and sugar are molecular arrangements of atoms which have no particular meaning unless they are part of some view of the world which reads them as meaningfully patterned atoms. Otherwise they are nothing but nano-pinpoints of mass clinging together out of mathematical habit, with no macro level of description at all. They move around at different speeds, break apart, stick together, etc, but at no point does it become a given that these \'arrangements\' exist as identifiable wholes in and of themselves. \r\n\r\nGoing down further of course, the atoms themselves are what? Charged tendencies to exist? Exist as what? Potentials for qualitative elaboration?\r\n\r\nMy conclusion then is that all possible descriptions and identities on all levels can be nothing other than qualia. Nothing is anything except the total of all possible experiences of what it seems to be (to itself and to everything else). Panpsychism, or pan-experientialism is the only way I can see that really makes sense as we can get an appearance of dumbed down reality by inhibiting sensitivity or flattening qualitative depth, but we cannot make reality more intelligent by moving dumb components around in more elaborate circles.\r\n\r\nAnyone getting more of an idea of what I am talking about?\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-07-16 15:01:26','2012-07-16 15:01:26'),(2361,1,37,'John\r\n\r\nI agree with Mark - why take the phenomenal space literally and so invoke higher dimensions when it fits within the brain as an EM phenomenon?\r\n\r\n','2012-07-16 15:05:42','2012-07-16 15:05:42'),(2362,1,32,'In his 1989 book Penrose says that he also sees randomness as useless for human understanding. This is why he distinguishes between the \'normal\' random wave function collapse and what he calls objective reduction (OR) which is proposed to happen to quanta that are isolated from the environment for a sufficiently long time. It is only this type of collpase which is proposed to access the \'fundamental spacetime geometry.\r\n\r\nThe camp statement you quote is a bit misleading if that is what it says. Quantum computation, in the form that researchers are trying to develop, has wave functions collapsing as a result of interaction with the environment, which relates to randomness. It\'s not really clear from Penrose\'s theory if all or only some quantum computation in the brain would be linked to objective reduction.\r\n\r\nThis post is not about whether the Penrose stuff is a good idea, but just what is actually proposed in the theory.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n ','2012-07-16 17:50:47','2012-07-16 17:50:47'),(2363,1,37,'For the answer to this question I refer you to my book \"The Walls of Plato\'s Cave\" published by Avebury Press. \r\nJohn','2012-07-16 19:36:04','2012-07-16 19:36:04'),(2366,96,48,'Rich,\r\n\r\nThis is interesting.  You stated: â€œcomputational functionalism - the theory that consciousness is some form of computation - is false.â€\r\n\r\nI think I disagree with this, but Iâ€™m not sure what this implies you think consciousness is so let me see if I can get you to help me understand your thinking on this.\r\n\r\nI think computation can be done on top of any fundamental natures of reality; â€˜causal propertiesâ€™ being one of the two types of fundamental natures.  Current Computers all run on these types of properties, exclusively (as in nothing is dependent on any phenomenal natures), in abstracted ways.  In other words, a set of causal properties, such as a group of wires with either zero or 5 volts can be interpreted as a string of bits, which in turn can be interpreted as a pattern of 0xFF0000, which in turn can be interpreted as â€˜redâ€™ which in turn can be interpreted as a property of a strawberry.  And this pattern of causal properties, can then, because of this interpretation, cause the robot to choose to pick the strawberry.\r\n\r\nTo me, that is all computation.\r\n\r\nWe, on the other hand, are still doing similar computation.  Our brain is just also running our computations on top of phenomenal natures, not just causal natures exclusively.  In other words, in the last example, it was the set of wires with 0xFF0000 pattern of voltages that was causing the computational system to choose to pick the strawberry.  While we, on the other hand, are choosing to pick the strawberry because of its redness phenomenal quality.  In other words, it is this redness nature that is causing the computational system to pick the strawberry.\r\n\r\nRobot computation is entirely based on abstracted information.  The only thing that needs to know anything about fundamental natures, are the transducers that cause one representation to transducer to the next causally downstream abstracted representation.  While for us, the fundamental natures are part of the algorithm, and it is because we know what it is fundamentally like, i.e. redness, that we make the computational action of picking it.\r\n\r\nIt sounds like you think differently, in that consciousness is something, different, entirely, from any kind of computation?  While I think there are fundamental natures that systems can use to build consciousness and computation out of, while perhaps you think consciousness somehow arises from some causal process very different than any kind of computation or something?\r\n\r\nWhat, exactly, do you think this â€˜virtual realityâ€™ world of your theory is made of, and what causes it to choose the red ones over the green ones, and how is this not computation â€“ though it is phenomenal computation, not just abstracted causal computation?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-16 23:18:44','2012-07-16 23:18:44'),(2369,96,48,'Brent\r\n\r\nI vote to take the new paras out.\r\n\r\nI don\'t think talking about naive zero-point is helpful or meaningful. What does \"thereby ceasing to be nothing like it originally was\" mean?\r\n\r\nI\'m familiar with the neurological deficit conditions you mention in the second para but don\'t see what your point is.\r\n\r\nThe first para is ok by itself IMO.','2012-07-17 17:17:12','2012-07-17 17:17:12'),(2372,96,48,'Rich,\r\n\r\nSo help me know how to respond to the many competitor camp people that claim we will not be able to eff the ineffable, because they think all a quale as including all the memories and Symantec information, like love, warmth, sweetness... that binds to them.  And how do we respond to people that claim consciousness is one single quale, and so on?\r\n\r\nI could agree that using the term \'zero point\' may not be good, so how about we find something else?  Perhaps you could propose another term or some other way to say all this?\r\n\r\nRemember, the goal is to get as much as possible that everyone agrees in, so help me out here, to come up with a counter proposal which allows me to get what I want, while still getting what you want, rather than just destroying what I want?\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-19 02:09:12','2012-07-19 02:09:12'),(2375,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nAs you probably noticed, I\'ve submitted the proposals for the \"Dualism\" camp structure changes as we discussed.  I\'ve also submitted a quick and dirty draft of a statement for the \"Substance Dualism\" camp.  You substance dualism people can probably do a much better job at a statement, than me.  You can see how these proposed changes will appear once they go live, if you set the \"As of\" value on the side bar to include review.\r\n\r\nAnd here are the links to all of the Google docs statements being proposed, which we can submit once they are agreed on, and after the structural changes go live.\r\n\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit Representational Qualia Theory]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1aDRRFW_lr7FMwSqOQHTP02Rd7za5lvQG3cdhQ69Ya5Q/edit Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gginaif0YTvDVSwFF7V_wRei-SDZlelt0LPIc5I_gD8/edit Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Dii95g7CYV04fe2jMzwLNHk2E68bfIor8HqAaouDrAM/edit Substance Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1dogSoCsouz2RhQ-CTNjtnYJ8Xr6JILNDki5Kn_met_o/edit Material Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V03WBMSY5cKf97NoM6KPZSKtxEEHg5MZJfb6FPq0Ui0/edit Macro Material Property Dualism]\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-19 02:12:18','2012-07-19 02:12:18'),(2376,271,38,'\r\n\r\nHi Mark,\r\n\r\nI\'ve been working on reading your theory, but I get kind of lost.\r\n\r\nIt goes on and on, describing other theories, saying what HST does, but I can\'t find where it actually does what it claims.  It gives it names I\"m not familiar with \"class C\", you talk about ways to think about consciousness, and then you go into lots of what seems like to me are easy problems - comparing the difference between hierarchical and other systems, how and why it evolved, where it is going, all easy stuff it seems to me, and so on.  All that may be good stuff, but I don\'t really have time to read it all since it is to me completely unrelated to what is important.\r\n\r\nIs there some place where you simply describe just what, where, and how  a simple redness quale is, and how I might now if your redness quale is like mine?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-20 03:12:33','2012-07-20 03:12:33'),(2379,96,48,'Craig\r\n\r\nYes, we both think computational functionalism is false.\r\n\r\n\"when you say that something is delectable\r\nor that it is a fruit, we are looking at the thing retrospectively from\r\nour own human/mammalian/animal view of the world.\"\r\nI agree. These are subjective - in our minds, not in the strawberry.\r\n\r\n\"In a universe where strawberries were the only living\r\norganisms, it would be much more likely IMO that soil would be\r\ndelectable...\"\r\nI don\'t agree that the strawberry plant finds nutrients from the soil delectable as it is not conscious.\r\n\r\n\"Water and sugar are molecular arrangements of atoms which have no\r\nparticular meaning unless they are part of some view of the world which\r\nreads them as meaningfully patterned atoms.\"\r\nWell, i agree that meaning is something for us and not molecules but the tree is in the quad whether we observe it or not.\r\n\r\n\"Otherwise they are nothing\r\nbut nano-pinpoints of mass clinging together out of mathematical habit,\"\r\nNo, maths is our doing.\r\n\r\n\"...with no macro level of description at all. They move around at\r\ndifferent speeds, break apart, stick together, etc, but at no point\r\ndoes it become a given that these \'arrangements\' exist as identifiable\r\nwholes in and of themselves.\"\r\nI don\'t understand what you mean.\r\n\r\n\"My conclusion then is that all possible descriptions and identities on\r\nall levels can be nothing other than qualia.\"\r\nSo, you\'re a follower of Berkeley.','2012-07-21 16:08:47','2012-07-21 16:08:47'),(2382,96,48,'Brent\r\n\r\n\"I think computation can ... cause the robot to choose to pick the strawberry.\"\r\nIndeed, but what has this to do with consciousness?\r\n\r\n\"We, on the other hand, are still doing similar computation.\"\r\nNo, the brain is not a computer: look at the construction and activity of each - very different. Yes, both i and a suitable equipped robot can distinguish a strawberry from the background but the process is radically different. If it looks like a duck and quacks like a duck but is a robot then it\'s a robot and not a duck.\r\n\r\n\"Our brain is just also running our computations on top of phenomenal natures...\"\r\nI don\'t believe in a phenomenal substrate to the world: as i\'ve said before, my view is that consciousness arises in brains or similar systems and so panpsychism is false.\r\n\r\n\"It sounds like you think differently, in that consciousness is something, different, entirely, from any kind of computation?\"\r\nTrue. If you consult my camp statement you\'ll see that i differentiate between computer VR and brain VR: \'The brain is not a computer running software that represents the world. Computational functionalism is false: nothing in or about a computer simulation could be conscious.\'\r\n\r\n\"What, exactly, do you think this â€˜virtual realityâ€™ world of your theory is made of,\"\r\nI am working on the theory that it is an electro-magnetic phenomenon.\r\n\r\n\"and what causes it to choose the red ones over the green ones,\"\r\nI choose, it doesn\'t. The clue is in the camp title: \"Self-centred virtual reality in the brain\".\r\n\r\n\"and how is this not computation â€“ though it is phenomenal computation, not just abstracted causal computation?\"\r\nWhat is phenomenal about computation? Surely phenomenal computation is a contradiction in terms?','2012-07-21 17:03:49','2012-07-21 17:03:49'),(2385,96,48,'Brent\r\n\r\nI don\'t like the phrase effing the ineffable but no matter as the core statement is the assertion in the first para that there will be some way for us to know what someone else\'s qualia is like.\r\n\r\nThe potential for accessibility seems to me a consequence of RQT since qualia are, or are derived from, our internal representation of the world. Qualia therefore become accessible when you connect representations.\r\n\r\nSo, if people think that qualia are forever hidden from others then they\'re not in the RQT camp.\r\n\r\nI don\'t see how the zero-point idea is compatible with RQT. RQT is not any sort of point, it is 3D.\r\n\r\nWhat\'s the problem with memory, semantics, sensation and emotion? Why wouldn\'t they be accessible?\r\n\r\nI don\'t understand single quale theory but why is it a challenge? In what way does it entail inaccessibility?','2012-07-21 18:01:51','2012-07-21 18:01:51'),(2388,96,48,'Hi Rich,\r\n\r\n\r\nIn your [http://canonizer.com/thread.asp/88/1/32/202#202 other post] you said you are working on the theory that a quale is \"an electromagnetic phenomenon\".  To me, this is a subset of Material Property Dualism.  If what you say is validated by science, it would be the electromagnetic phenomenon that is the physical stuff or material, that has the redness quale - and without that right \"electromagnetic phenomenon\" no quale.  Also, you must admit that this same \'electromagnetic phenomenon\' going on outside of your brain, with no memory, or intentional system, or anything present with it, the same \"electomagnetic phenomenon\" would still always have the same quality, whether inside the brain or not, would it not?\r\n\r\nAnd certainly you must agree that our scientific instruments would be blind to the quality, because such qualities suffer from the quale interpretation problem.  All our abstracted senses can tell us of this \'electromagnetic phenomenon\' NCC in our brain, is abstracted information of the causal behavior - something different - entirely - than it\'s true phenomenal nature we can experience when it is our brain.\r\n\r\nAnd you seem to agree that we will be able to discover these qualities of various different types of such \'electromagnetic phenomenon\' despite this quale interpretation problem?  And if so, would you think there is some better way to refer to achieving, and knowing what they are like, than \'effing the ineffable\'?\r\n\r\n\'effing the ineffable\' is just one doctrine of RQT.  Currently, everyone in the comp unanimously supports it - and it\'s been in the camp for some time.  All I did was add two additional paragraphs to support the idea against a particular attack.  If someone did show up that believe in everything in RQT, but effing of the ineffable, like many other doctrines of the past that were once part of RQT, we\'d just push this particular doctrine to a sub camp of RQT.\r\n\r\nI don\'t know how you got I was saying a \'zero point idea is compatible with RQT\', I was pointing out how naive and mistaken any \"consciousness is a zero point idea\" is.  But, no worries, I rewrote those two paragraphs without that.  Let me know if that is not any better.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-07-21 22:24:45','2012-07-21 22:24:45'),(2391,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nThe new dualism structure went live last week, so thanks all, for the help.  I think this is a big step forward in more comprehensively representing what all experts believe.\r\n\r\nAnd I believe we are ready to submit the below new statements for this structure:\r\n\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit Representational Qualia Theory]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1aDRRFW_lr7FMwSqOQHTP02Rd7za5lvQG3cdhQ69Ya5Q/edit Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Dii95g7CYV04fe2jMzwLNHk2E68bfIor8HqAaouDrAM/edit Substance Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gginaif0YTvDVSwFF7V_wRei-SDZlelt0LPIc5I_gD8/edit Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1dogSoCsouz2RhQ-CTNjtnYJ8Xr6JILNDki5Kn_met_o/edit Material Property Dualism]\r\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V03WBMSY5cKf97NoM6KPZSKtxEEHg5MZJfb6FPq0Ui0/edit Macro Material Property Dualism]\r\n\r\nMike, you did most of the work on the RQT statement, would you like to take credit for this by submitting the current version?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-07-28 18:56:30','2012-07-28 18:56:30'),(2394,96,48,'Brent\r\n\r\nMy theory does not fit MPD. At the top of the camp statement, it states that MPD is the same as Chalmers\' F-type monism. To quote Chalmers: \"The type-F view is ... to suppose that fundamental physical systems have phenomenal properties: e.g. that there is something it is like to be an electron\"\r\nThis is neither monism nor is it correct IMO.\r\n\r\n\"If what you say is validated by science, it would be the electromagnetic phenomenon that is the physical stuff or material, that has the redness quale - and without that right \"electromagnetic phenomenon\" no quale.\"\r\nI\'m not sure what you mean by \"having a redness quale\" but i agree with the second part: no representation means no quale.\r\n\r\n\"Also, you must admit that this same \'electromagnetic phenomenon\' going on outside of your brain, with no memory, or intentional system, or anything present with it, the same \"electomagnetic phenomenon\" would still always have the same quality, whether inside the brain or not, would it not?\"\r\nNo, i don\'t see that you can divorce the NCC from the brain or similar device and, anyway, there must be an experiencer to have experiences so, if you remove the former you also lose the latter. Hence the name i use for my theory.\r\n\r\n\"And certainly you must agree that our scientific instruments would be blind to the quality, because such qualities suffer from the quale interpretation problem.\"\r\nYes, qualia are not detectable by scientific instruments but this has nothing to do with interpretation. The reason is that the instruments 1) are not conscious and 2) are making measurements of electrical potential and the like. The latter is what stops us from observing qualia: all we see are e.g. the pictures displaying blood flow contours.\r\n\r\n\"And you seem to agree that we will be able to discover these qualities of various different types of such \'electromagnetic phenomenon\' despite this quale interpretation problem?\"\r\nIf you\'re trying to tell me that a quale is a bit pattern then forget it.\r\n\r\n\"And if so, would you think there is some better way to refer to achieving, and knowing what they are like, than \'effing the ineffable\'?\"\r\nLook, the way to see through another\'s eyes is to connect the brains appropriately. This achieves your \"effing the ineffable\", right? I would call this \"experiencing anothers\' qualia\". What\'s ineffable about qualia? We talk about them all the time!\r\n\r\n','2012-07-29 16:28:28','2012-07-29 16:28:28'),(2397,96,48,'http://www.stationlink.com/art/ellipsis_comic1.jpg','2012-08-02 16:27:06','2012-08-02 16:27:06'),(2400,96,48,'Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nHow about that, we have received some gracious responses from Daniel Dennett.  In one he provided a reference to [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AaCedh4Dfs4 his recent talk] at the \"Evolution and Function of Consciousness\" conference.  He indicated that he talks about the issue we raised in the open letter in that talk.  He also describes there an update to his multiple drafts model, which I think is enough to start a \'camp\' with - especially since James (and others) seem to agree that this is very much like their way of thinking about consciousness.\r\n\r\nThis talk is very convincing to me, that he is (at least now, thanks to Lehar\'s work?)  very much a representationalist, not a direct perceptionist as some of us have assumed (I point a few of the time references in the video which prove such in the proposed Dennett statement google doc below).  He very much accepts how powerful arguments are for Dualism, yet just like James, warns us against going down that path, for not quite as good as reasons as James provides (in my opinion)  \r\n\r\nI think we could get his camp started just like we started Hameroff\'s Orch OR theory camp.  Just like you gracious supporters of Hameroff showed up to help his noble effort.  Hameroff thought his camp was far less popular than it now demonstrably is, and it seems that Dennett thinks his camp has become far less popular than I bet it is, despite his up till now disinterest.  I\'m betting that more supporters will soon show up to support what is surely a far more popular camp than he thinks, despite his absence.\r\n\r\nDennett also talks about tactics in this field, that losing interest in publishing for a time was a tactical mistake.  I\'m hoping we can quickly demonstrate to him the power of the amplification of the wisdom of the crowd canonizer tactics.  Whenever I give a talk, I always ask what people think.  If they support the ideas, I ask them to support the camps that represent them.  And if they think differently, I ask everyone to \'canonize\' such, so if there really is something to such, we can all better understand, concisely and quantitatively, just what that is.  Surely, if anyone as popular as Dennett did anything like this, as they gave talks and published papers, (instead of wasting so much time focusing on non consensus sloppy thinking like \"access vs phenomenal consciousness\") they could likely quickly push their camp to the top of the consensus ladder, at least for a time, since ultimately everything depends on scientific reality.\r\n\r\n\r\nAnyway, towards that end, I propose we start a sub camp of Representational Functionalism called \"Dennett\'s Predictive Bayesian Coding Theory\" and I have started a proposed Google doc statement here:\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1RFwEiuJ2VI_NQOJd3DfkUGifo6L0GGq1z46z4T4i5wc/edit\r\n\r\nI\'m betting that James will think about as much of this proposed camp statement (and name?) as I thought of one of his proposal of property dualism (though such was a great help for me in concisely formulating what we have now).  So I\'m hoping he and others can turn this into a much better version from their perspective.\r\n\r\nThen, hopefully, we can run this by Dennett, one final time, before we canonize it?\r\n\r\nJames and or Michal or anyone, would you be willing to support such a camp to at least get it started?\r\n\r\nLooking forward to finding out what everyone thinks.  It\'s so great to finally get some real support in this very important camp!!  Thanks all!!\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-08-05 03:39:58','2012-08-05 03:39:58'),(2403,96,48,'Hi Brent!\r\n\r\nGlad to hear that Dan Dennett is with us again! Now may be the time to comment on his dictum that \"There is no place in the brain where it all comes together.\" Recent advances in neuroscience suggest that this is not the case. All members are referred to a paper we have just published in \"Frontiers in Integrative Neuroscience\" that may be accessed on line as \r\n\r\nSmythies J, Edelstein L and Ramachandran V (2012) Hypotheses relating to the function of the claustrum. Front. Integr. Neurosci. 6:53. doi: 10.3389/fnint.2012.00053\r\n\r\nThis paper further develops the theory put forward by Francis Crick and Christof Koch in 2005 that it is the claustrum that provides this \'place\'. They suggested that the claustrum integrates the NCCs \"like the conductor of an orchestra\", but they did not detail a specific mechanism that does this. Our hypothesis supplies this detailed mechanism, that has to do with the integration of synchronized gamma oscillations (see our paper for details). These may be the long sought after NCCs.\r\n John','2012-08-05 05:49:10','2012-08-05 05:49:10'),(2406,96,48,'\r\nHi John,\r\n\r\nLooks like an exciting paper.  I\'m just getting started digesting it.  For those interested, here is a direct link to the abstract:\r\n\r\nhttp://www.frontiersin.org/Integrative_Neuroscience/10.3389/fnint.2012.00053/abstract\r\n\r\nI\'m not the greatest in brain anatomy, so as I get started on this, I\'m wishing for a good online graphical anatomy source that will help me see the locations of the structures in the brain that are being referred to here.  Does anyone have a favorite online source they go to for such purposes?\r\n\r\nThanks\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-08-05 16:18:01','2012-08-05 16:18:01'),(2407,1,10,'=P\r\n\r\nI finally got around to working the numbers on the size I\'ve spent most of my time fantasizing about recently... They actually come out to somewhere in the neighborhood of 130 tons........... each; assuming I\'m using Google\'s unit conversion feature correctly and that I\'m using the correct approximations and general parameters. ','2012-09-25 05:05:52','2012-09-25 05:05:52'),(2410,96,48,'Hello moral experts and theoretical world leaders,\r\n\r\nI know I\'m not the only one here that is frustrated with the bleating of so many herding people by using such confusing words as our conscious models are \'transparent\' and or popular so called \'experts\' claiming we don\'t have a \'self\'.\r\n\r\nSomeone [http://www.facebook.com/groups/carboncopies/504349212927435/ here] was throwing this [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZFjY1fAcESs popular tripe] (in Tedx, no less) at me last week.  I think we are in desperate need of canonizing as much expert consensus as possible to fight this, which is so destroying the reputation of this entire theoretical field.\r\n\r\nTowards this end, I propose we add something like the two sections I\'ve added to the [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1yKglpMLAzagRghpCNSzZzxS9FJ-uhg96nb1kBnBk9AA/edit?disco=AAAAAEXe_vo Google doc for the Representational Qualia super camp].\r\n\r\nI\'m hoping that all of you can help me significantly improve the draft I\'m proposing.  And most importantly, if anyone at the Representational Qualia Level objects, please help us negotiate something you can accept.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-09-30 04:10:14','2012-09-30 04:10:14'),(2413,96,48,'I think that to move forward in any kind of deep understanding of consciousness it is important to understand how our reasoning is inherently biased by brain lateralization. Anyone here who cares about scientific curiosity more than deterministic ideology should watch this excellent brief talk by Iain McGilchrist.\r\n\r\nhttp://youtu.be/SbUHxC4wiWk\r\n\r\nHis observations as a psychiatrist and researcher are very much in line with my own views of what reductionist approaches fail to grasp and how readily they employ denial to rationalize even the most obvious gaps in common sense.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-09-30 04:40:08','2012-09-30 04:40:08'),(2416,96,48,'I can see both sides of the \"self\" vs. \"no self\" issue -- and, indeed, favored the \"self\" side -- until I saw your comments, Brent.\r\n\r\nBrent said \"We are all in unanimous agreement that the best term for this \"I\", or \"self\" is simply the traditional word \"spirit\" . . . . \"\r\n\r\nI disagree vehemently.  If you are going to translate self into spirit, I am immediately in the \"no self\" camp (and strongly suspect that this is why Metzinger is where he is, as well).\r\n\r\nThe debate is NOT whether there is something there.  Everyone in this debate agrees that there is something there.  The argument is over what to call it.  Metzinger feels that even the term \"self\" is too baggage-laden to use.  I normally disagree.  Brent feels that not only is the term \"self\" useful but then conflates it with \"spirit\".  I so vehemently disagree with that conflation that I now am in Metzinger\'s camp.','2012-09-30 13:39:40','2012-09-30 13:39:40'),(2419,96,48,'I think it is most important not to conflate the \'self\' with the spirit, if spirit equates to the more modern usage of consciousness. If we view the self as the narrative memory, the distinction between the body/us and the external world plus proprioception, then the self is only part of the contents of consciousness. A notorious \'get out of jail free\' card in consciousness studies has been to deconstruct the self, and then claim to have solved the problem of consciousness.\r\n\r\nAltered states of consciousness often involve states in which the self disappears or is diminished, but consciousness, often in a heightened form, remains. A while ago this latter might have been regarded as rather \'new age\' in a perjorative sense. However, recent peer reviewed studies show that deactivation of brain regions associated with the self and heightened sensory consciousness occur in response to particular chemicals. Other studies show that even watching an engrossing film can lead to deactivation of some areas while sensory consciousness remains robust.\r\n\r\nSimon \r\n','2012-09-30 15:17:40','2012-09-30 15:17:40'),(2422,96,48,'Besides the religious baggage of terms like spirit and soul, my view is that these words carry connotations which actually distort and mischaracterize what is actually there. I think that this mischaracterization stems from the application of object oriented assumptions to what is non-objective by nature. Not non-physical, but non-objective, as in, a capacity of presence through private experience rather than a representation as functions of bodies in space or pseudo-substantial concepts which take metaphors like ether and energy literally to be subjectively charged spatial fields in a vacuum.\r\n\r\nWhat I suggest is that our native experience of consciousness, though perhaps a difficult example to try to use as a basis to model awareness or sense in general, is irreducibly correct in it\'s presentation. The self is neither a thing nor not a thing, but rather the participation in and perception of particular things. Rather than presuming to reduce this personal state to impersonal micro-states of cellular and molecular bodies, or impersonal macro-states of evolutionary process, I propose a perpendicular axis which capitulates a spectrum of sub-personal and super-personal experiences. \r\n\r\nThis means that our emotions or thoughts are not \'made of\' neurological \'signals\' or neurotransmitter activity, but rather those impersonal micro and macro layers of description are the public extension in space of what is privately \'intended\' through personal, sub-personal, and super-personal convergences through time. No glowing energy fields or incorporeal ghosts, just signifying experiences. Stories in which irreducibly direct participation takes place on many levels at the same time. These stories are concretely physical in the sense of being associated with physical bodies on every scale, and causally so. We can cause the chemistry of our brain to change and our body to move at will, but are directly influenced by our brain and body as well. There is bi-directional interaction on all levels, so that micro-impersonal cellular states influence super-personal states of consciousness, and vice versa, etc. \r\n\r\nEach category of states defines itself in its own terms as well as in the terms defined by its place in the continuum of all of the other states and modalities. This is not quite parallelism or dualism as there is no redundancy or distinct separation between presentations and representations. This is a recognition of nature as a multiplicity of interactive, mutually semi-defining aspects of perception and participation. A meta-juxtaposition of sensory-motive sequential intentions and matter-energy parallel extensions.\r\n\r\nCraig\r\n','2012-09-30 22:37:07','2012-09-30 22:37:07'),(2425,96,48,'reductionism\r\ndisparity in terms\r\nTypically, i must redefine words for specific applications. This may seem arrogant but is required by necessity. For instance, i have needed to redefine responsibility in a document about cooperatives.. What does this have to do with our current discussion? We can redefine mind/spirit to mean anything we want (as long as we can have consensus which seems impossible here). Let\'s not waste time arguing about definitions which change with time anyways. Let\'s attempt to make a consensus about terms. Then we can decide whether or not we can agree on reductionism as applied to mind.','2012-09-30 23:25:05','2012-09-30 23:25:05'),(2428,96,48,'\r\nIt\'s great to get so many responses, and to find out what other think on this issue.\r\n\r\nI\'m with Sam and I guess my only top priority, is that we come up with some consistent terminology, and whichever is the most agreed on, I\'ll be happy to use that.\r\n\r\nI\'m looking forward to hearing what everyone thinks is the best terminology to communicate to the widest audience.  so how about everyone make their best proposal, and we\'ll see which achieves the most consensus.\r\n\r\nI think we should continue to monitor and abide by this consensus, as the survey become more comprehensive, and all things continue to progress.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-10-01 04:22:07','2012-10-01 04:22:07'),(2431,96,48,'All right, sounds a good idea. As a first shot, I suggest:-\r\n\r\nMind = all brain processing both conscious and unconscious\r\n\r\nSpirit = the same thing as consciousness, which enables discussion with those who don\'t like anything that sound a bit religious or mystical.\r\n\r\nConsciousness variously defined as being \'like something it is like\' to exist and have experiences, including the external world, our bodies, our thoughts and our emotions. These are also defined as qualia. The consciousness problem can be a bit simplified if qualia are seen as the only thing that needs explaining.\r\n\r\nSelf: This is part of the contents of conscious, one of the things we experience. It comprises our narrative memory, the distinction between the body and the rest of the world and the body\'s sense of position and effort.\r\n\r\nSimon\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-10-01 11:43:00','2012-10-01 11:43:00'),(2434,96,48,'I agree generally with Simon\'s definition of spirit as almost \'the same thing\' as consciousness, but I would say that Self and Mind are also that as well, having only distinctions in the degree of proprietary qualities present and the extent to which awareness is experienced in cognitive-linguistic ranges of qualia.\r\n\r\nI disagree that Mind is brain processing. That really confuses things. The mind is accessed subjectively through private experience, not through monitoring of brain processes. Brain processing is inferred through an examination of a body structure in public space and would look the same as any other complex organ\'s functioning except for our association of it with phenomenology.\r\n\r\nI disagree that qualia is the only thing that needs explaining - not so much with the literal wording of the statement, but the minimizing of the problem. Qualia, in my view, is at least as large as the rest of the universe put together.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-10-01 13:02:52','2012-10-01 13:02:52'),(2437,96,48,'Brent\r\n\r\nI agree that those who dismiss the self as illusory are wrong but conscious models are transparent: we see (a reconstruction of aspects of) the world not the model.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard','2012-10-01 18:50:03','2012-10-01 18:50:03'),(2440,96,48,'Another suggestion for the totality of brain processing might be mental. One needs something to cover the whole system, particularly as there is so much scope for disagreement as to what the conscious bit is, and what its role is.\r\n\r\nI don\'t quite follow the qualia bit. Do you refer to consciousness being fundamental in, or pervading throughout the universe? Attractive options but not exactly uncontroversial. Or is it to say that qualia can refer to the experience of anything that may be in the universe?\r\n\r\nSimon','2012-10-01 21:42:21','2012-10-01 21:42:21'),(2443,96,48,'Brain processes are biological as far as I can see. If we wanted to characterize the experiences which are associated with all of those processes of the brain (cells? molecules?) I would think we would have to include all human experiences, not just mental ones. Phenomena like sensation, perception, and emotion I would not describe as being mental, but like everything with subjectivity it is not really something which can be defined meaningfully in neat partitions.\r\n\r\n\"Do you refer to consciousness being fundamental in, or pervading throughout the universe?\"\r\n\r\nYes. Or to be exact, the universe is what pervades throughout consciousness or experience (not human experience of course, but experience in general).\r\n\r\n\"Or is it to say that qualia can refer to the experience of anything that may be in the universe? \"\r\n\r\nIt depends what we mean by \'anything\'. Bugs Bunny does not have any experiences. Computer programs do not have any experiences. Computer components have experiences which we exploit mechanically, but those micro level experiences do not scale up to the assembly as a whole. We consider a machine a thing, but it doesn\'t consider itself anything because it didn\'t put itself together out of its own sense and motives.\r\n\r\nCraig','2012-10-01 22:25:59','2012-10-01 22:25:59'),(2446,96,48,'Thought some of you might enjoy:\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboeqxC0Vl1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboih6q3e11qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboik9Wcp91qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboihhg9Lp1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboikjKxfd1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboikzU4rP1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboil5yEId1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboilft6Wi1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboilptoRi1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboim1cLHr1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboima3XH41qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboimmJjml1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboimu6PLu1qe3q3v.jpg\r\n\r\nhttp://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mboin0ueLw1qe3q3v.jpg','2012-10-10 15:00:17','2012-10-10 15:00:17'),(2447,1,24,'\r\nI propose that this camp be changed from a competing position to the Yes camp, and that it be moved into a supporting sub camp of the yes camp.\r\n\r\nThe \'Transhumanist\' canonization algorithm only considers you a Transhumanist if you support, the YES camp, or are a supporter of such, so this is extra important.\r\n\r\nIf you object, let me know, otherwise I\'ll be making this change soon.\r\n\r\n','2012-10-17 01:31:24','2012-10-17 01:31:24'),(2450,96,48,'I have been a bit out of this loop for some time. But I certainly don\'t wish to be seen as agreeing that \'spirit\' = consciousness. I have no use for the word spirit except as a colloquial usage in some different contexts, for example \"a spirited performance\", or \"That\'s the spirit!\";  \"Meths\" or \"grog\"  are alternative directions of course  :-) \r\n\r\nWhatever was intended through use of the world spirit by denizens of the pre scientific universe, that has all been superseded by _self assertion_ or _self assertiveness_.  \r\n\r\nIn parallel with this of course the word \'soul\' is now covered by empathy or empathising. \r\n\r\nMind of course is simply \"what the brain does\". ','2012-10-22 16:00:10','2012-10-22 16:00:10'),(2453,96,48,'\r\nHi Xodowrap,\r\n\r\nMetzinger talks of a \"Phenomenal Self Model\" or \"PSM\".  If one has an out of body experience, this is what leaves the knowledge of their body, right?  It is this PSM that has oneâ€™s personalities, memories, identity, and everything, right?\r\n\r\nSo if you were to talk to a religious person, who knew all about out of body experiences, and so on â€“ yet knew nothing of philosophy of mind, and especially nothing of Metzinger, â€œPSMâ€ or any of that.\r\n\r\nIf you wanted to talk about this PSM, out of body experiences, and so on, with a religious person, what terminology would you use that would best communicate to such a person?\r\n\r\nYour theory is entitled â€œupdating model of self in the worldâ€, so I assume you like the term â€œselfâ€.  It seems to me that most people would consider oneâ€™s body as a part of what you were talking about when you use the term â€˜selfâ€™?  What terminology would you use, so that such religious people that consider the body to be part of the self, knew you were only talking about the PSM, and not about the body, or the knowledge of the body, in the world, and so on?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-10-22 19:12:24','2012-10-22 19:12:24'),(2456,96,48,'Brent, \r\nSorry I missed your response, I had to lodge our tax returns then got distracted with bulk other family stuff. \r\n\r\nIf people of religious persuasions wish to sustain a reasonable and productive dialogue about brain, mind, consciousness, emotion and behaviour, and all the various relationships between these then they have to make an effort.  They have to start to understand what modern  scientific research and clinical studies have revealed already about what makes people tick. They have to work at understanding the basics of what neurons do, how the brain mediates perception and actions. \r\n\r\nAs far as I can see there is just no point in getting into conversations about something as complex as the human brain and what it does, if the other person has not been spending time honestly trying to find out what is known or hypothesised about our psyche and its physical instantiation within the head of each person. \r\n\r\nI would encourage them very strongly to look up Steve Lehar\'s web site with his Cartoon Epistemology. I think he provides there a very good exposition of how it is most reasonable to acknowledge that all of what we see, hear and smell, etc, is made within the brain.\r\nhttp://cns-alumni.bu.edu/~slehar/cartoonepist/cartoonepist.html\r\n\r\n','2012-11-07 16:40:37','2012-11-07 16:40:37'),(2457,284,14,'\r\nHi Sam123,\r\n\r\nWelcome to Canonizer.com, and thanks for this great new topic contribution.\r\n\r\nFeel free to include an introduction thread on this topic forum, where you and everyone, as they join, can introduce themselves.  You probably know me as the founder of Canonizaer.com.  Iâ€™d love to know more about who you are and your interests.\r\n\r\nIâ€™m also very interested in this topic, and agree with everything in the â€œMachine thinking patterns using AI toolsâ€ so am now supporting this camp with you.\r\n\r\nOne thing I noticed is you have the following statement in the camp statement:\r\n\r\nâ€œThis topic forum is dedicated to such discussions which would likely open to some new directions in thought simulation in machines.â€\r\n\r\nI think this kind of stuff belongs in the root â€œagreement statementâ€.  Typically, it is in the root statement where the purpose and methods of the survey are described.  A good way to think about it is the root camp, which all camps support, is where the topic survey question is asked, and all the sub camps are the various possible different points of view or answers to this question are stated and measured for how much expert consensus they have.\r\n\r\nAlso when you talk about the â€œunified model of an artificial mind is aimed to explain the working of different elements of the mindâ€ and such I wonder if you agree the phenomenal properties, or qualia, like redness and greenness are included in this? (As described in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/28 dualism] camp.\r\n\r\nIf you agree, would you mind adding a doctrine statement to the camp including something like this?  If not, I can create a supporting sub camp of the â€œMachine thinking patterns using AI toolsâ€ camp.\r\n\r\n\r\nThanks!!\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-11-09 15:35:51','2012-11-09 15:35:51'),(2458,284,14,'Dear All Members, \r\n\r\nBasically as an independent researcher, a graduate student with a background in biomedical science, I am from India, having wide ranging interests in the domain of AI, Cognitive sciences, Philosophy of Mind, and certain interest allied to other social science disciplines including Behavioral Economics, Behavioral Finance, and Cognitive Economics. Having certain contributions in other scientific social networks, I was in search of such a network which is itself motivating, intellectually prominent, and free of homophily and social discrimination as well encompassing a wide ranging audience discussing every possible issues which can be found till I got the reference of Canonizer.com which genuinely suited my quest. I believe my deep rooted interest would definitely find some good audience and support, and in turn, I would genuinely extend my full support to this wonderful platform and the people behind this initiative who have created such a wonderful knowledge propagating podium to express whatever comes in my mind and taps my aptitude, and to those active participants who bring in new knowledge to illuminate our inquisitive mind.\r\n\r\nThe first thing I noted while joining this knowledge network is that, it is though much like wiki, but with a different savor which is truly innovative where one is free to put down anything on mind and no matter whatever on the paper to further the cause of knowledge generation and value creation by engaging, or agreeing on what that is justifiable, or have much freedom to put forth argument for any such disagreement. The platform seems open to contention and through further agreement or disagreement, the pure refinement of the theories would filter and purify the knowledge shared by and among us, the active members.\r\n\r\nThe topic which I have proposed is regarding a very contentious issue relating to the theory of machine thinking which I believe is now at its formative years where there is much to do and a great deal of things to explore. On the realms of hedonistic imperatives of AI, the philosophy of this subject had a wonderful beginning as we know from the contributions from Turing, Herbert Simon and Allen Newell, McCarthy, Minsky and other great stalwarts to what it is today, a more matured field wide open for further exploration and development. The marriage of different domains of knowledge including cognitive sciences, psychology, computer science, anthropology, and neuroscience has not only strengthened this particular field, but as also, extended the deeper horizon of AI philosophy to aim for something big as \"Machine Thinking\" to bridge the gap between human beings and their machine counterparts using the tools of science. To this end, we dream of something novel like hybrid human-artificial mind or a co-processor for our own brain or even brain augmentation technology, the opportunities are abounding as well interestingly open for exploration both by novice and experts. In the longer run, I hope we would be able to address these critical issues in much wider details for a greater number of audience and experts alike and of certain, to quest further to answer â€œwhat itsâ€™ need and what is needed?â€\r\n\r\nOn this endeavor, I believe Canonizer.com can provide us with that right advantage to excel at our collective quest for deeper knowledge.\r\n\r\nMany Thanks,\r\n\r\nSidharta Chatterjee,\r\nVisiting Researcher,\r\nAndhra University, Visakhapatnam,\r\nIndia.\r\n','2012-11-10 03:51:03','2012-11-10 03:51:03'),(2459,284,14,'Sidharta Chatterjee\r\n\r\nMachine Minds: The Blueprint for Artificial Consciousness\r\nhttp://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2061949\r\n\r\nAt the Crossroads of Consciousness\r\nhttp://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2079597\r\n\r\nIdeas RePec\r\nhttp://ideas.repec.org/f/pch767.html\r\n\r\nssrn.com\r\nhttp://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2079597\r\n\r\nEconPapers\r\nhttp://econpapers.repec.org/RAS/pch767.htm\r\n\r\nMPRA\r\nhttp://mpra.ub.uni-muenchen.de/28883/\r\n\r\nOpendepot\r\nhttp://opendepot.org/483/','2012-11-10 04:48:31','2012-11-10 04:48:31'),(2460,1,64,'\r\nMoral Theoreticians,\r\n\r\nIâ€™d like to welcome theyogre as a contributor to this survey topic; itâ€™s exciting to see this topic grow.  The early lead consensus is still saying compatibleism is the superior moral value, but itâ€™s great to see theyogre add significantly to the â€œit is realâ€ camp.  Itâ€™ll be exciting to see where things go from here.\r\n\r\nThe current structure seems mixed up and confusing to me.  I think we could improve things by finally getting to the change originally proposed in this thread, and also making a similar change by moving Richwelâ€™s original â€œis realâ€ camp and merging it with theyogreâ€™s new camp with the same name under the new [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/128/6 incompatible supper camp].  This would make a very nice and symmetrical structure that would be easy for everyone to understand, in a way that accurately represents everyoneâ€™s beliefs.  And I would like to support the illusion camp, like Mike is.\r\n\r\n* Compatible\r\n** Free Will is an Illusion\r\n* Incompatible\r\n** Free Will is Real\r\n\r\nRichwil, if you do the move of your â€œFree will is realâ€ camp, before theyogre joins (abandoning his version of the camp), your change will go live instantly since you are still the only supporter.  That way we wonâ€™t have to wait for the 1 week review period.  Would you be willing to do that, Rich?  Otherwise one of us can do it, if we donâ€™t hear any objections.  Same with you, Mike;  if you move your â€œillusionâ€ camp, before I join, it will take place immediately (and Iâ€™d recommend you remove your support from the super compatible camp before this change, as it should be illegal to â€˜stackâ€™ support in parent/child camps, and I canâ€™t remember how well the checking for that issue code to prevent such, works.)\r\n\r\nWhat are otherâ€™s thoughts?  If nobody gets around to these changes, and if nobody objects, I can just make the changes.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-11-13 20:50:57','2012-11-13 20:50:57'),(2461,1,64,'The Illusion Doctrine fits in the incompatible camp, too. Possibly better. The conclusion is different--i.e. free will is completely illusion AND there is no free will--but it fits there, too. While there is overlap, I don\'t think you can just make it a subset. You could have it appear twice, and that might be useful. I like Compatibilism and Incompatibilism OR Free Will Is Real and Free Will Doesn\'t Exist as the super camps. In the second formulation, I could agree with Compatibilists that free will exists and that some formulations of free will are illusory and contrary to evidence, but not accept Determinism (or Determinism plus random quantum events) as the ultimate word on causation in the universe.','2012-11-16 14:42:31','2012-11-16 14:42:31'),(2462,114,90,'I believe free will is real, but that your joke doesn\'t constitute any sort of proof. I will give one response to your joke. Saying that you are giving up your free will and letting someone else tell you what to do has zero bearing on whether you are really giving up your free will or not. Any sort of proof that we have free will can\'t go in the agreement camp. I think we can only say that free will is at least a perceptual reality. Some choices commonly held to be actions of our will are demonstrably determined. Free will must act within the bounds of a variety of deterministic laws that control all matter.','2012-11-16 14:42:53','2012-11-16 14:42:53'),(2463,1,64,'I like inverting the organization, and moving the whole thing to the Free Will heading. Then we can all agree that there is free will and argue about its definition and constraints. I can\'t support Libertarianism inasmuch as it claims to have disproven the deterministic universe. I don\'t think that is a logical claim. (I reject an absolutely deterministic universe on other grounds, but those grounds don\'t prove free will.)','2012-11-16 14:48:29','2012-11-16 14:48:29'),(2464,1,39,'This is my first day on Canonizer. Several people encouraged me to join so I could throw my support behind their models. While I acknowledged the descriptive power of their models they always seemed to have blind spots. And the promoters seemed quite adept at not noticing those blind spots.\r\n\r\nI found it quite easy to relate to the straight-forward statement of the â€œAdvaita and Consciousnessâ€ camp. Even so, I\'ve had decades of barking up the wrong tree. So I visited the blog of Ramesam Vemuri â€” the person who initially set up this camp. This led me to an interview with that person in Nonduality Magazine. \r\n\r\nI was ... flabbergasted. Although RV\'s terminology was different from that which I generally use, everything was explained in accessible terms. And to my astonishment, the explanations seemed to reflect my realizations and experiences. Despite the differences in terminology, the correspondence was jaw-dropping. \r\n\r\nI am leery of jumping on any bandwagon, having been disappointed in so many cases to find that the driver of the bandwagon was (in my estimation) ignoring inadequacies in their models. But I didn\'t get that impression from what I read from RV. This happens so rarely that I was (so to speak) glued to my monitor for quite a while.\r\n\r\nIf the past is any guide, I\'ll eventually abandon this camp. Still, when it comes to this kind of topic, sometimes my cynicism is not justified.  Perhaps this is one of those times. \r\n\r\nSo I\'ve put my tentative (and dare I say it, hopeful) support behind the â€œAdvaita and Consciousnessâ€ camp. ','2012-11-24 17:35:34','2012-11-24 17:35:34'),(2465,1,39,'Dear Timothy,\r\n\r\nWelcome.\r\n\r\nThank you for the kind words and support for the Camp.\r\n\r\nregards,\r\n\r\nramesam\r\n\r\nP.S. Paula did an Interview with all her questions based only on Physics. The link is available at the Blog. Maybe you had already taken a look.','2012-11-24 20:13:59','2012-11-24 20:13:59'),(2466,1,39,'I don\'t know who â€œPaulaâ€ is. Perhaps that was the interviewer from Nonduality Magazine. If there are questions based on physics, that\'s great, and I\'d appreciate it if you could post the link here.\r\n\r\nI support this particular camp because I\'m impressed by the observations of people of olden times like The Buddha and the more recent sages such as Adyashanti. Yet it occurs to me that many of these people speak largely in ancient terms. \r\n\r\nMy personal grasp of liberation has been bolstered by the discoveries of the scientific mindset. In particular, I\'m moved by the theory of evolution, which (for obvious reasons) was not available to The Buddha. The same goes for memetics, quantum mechanics, relativity, cosmology, game theory, hard data (such as we get from fMRI\'s) and so on.\r\n\r\nI\'m not saying such data is indispensable for liberation. It obviously is NOT indispensable, since many people have become liberated without it. However, my â€œquestâ€ for the past 7 years has been to discover if there\'s a way that liberation can be made attainable to a reasonably well-informed person whose main tool is deep honesty, starting with the statement that (it seems to me) is at the heart of the best kinds of scientific inquiry: â€œI might be wrong!â€\r\n\r\nI have noticed that it\'s possible to get too deep into this point of view, attempting to concoct explanations for that which is not explainable from  the vantage point of ape descendants with puny brains. Nonetheless, if the honesty of scientific inquiry, along with the models it produces, can open a door, that would really be something!\r\n\r\nI don\'t know if this is something I should be doing, but I am very much aware that the average seeker is running at top speed to GET AWAY from suffering. If there\'s any chance that the path away from delusion can be mapped out (or at least illuminated a bit) by science then I\'m keen to work to that end, even if doing so prolongs my suffering.\r\n\r\n(I\'m not entirely happy with the phrasing of what I wrote above, but I hope you get the gist of what I\'m saying.)','2012-11-25 03:40:35','2012-11-25 03:40:35'),(2467,1,39,'Thanks again.\r\n\r\nThe Interview at the Non-duality Magazine was not by Paula. She was with the Advaita Academy, UK at the time of the Interivew. The link is:\r\n\r\nhttp://advaita-academy.org/interviews/Dr-Ramesam-Vemuri.ashx\r\n\r\n2.  It is quite interesting that you mention about liberation through scientific inquiry.  In this context, you may like to take a look at:\r\n\r\n\"Neuronal Correlates of a Jivanmukta\'s Mind -- Identification of \'Markers\' in the Brain\" at:\r\n\r\nhttp://www.nondualitymagazine.org/nonduality_magazine.4.jivanmuktarevised_27_apr_2011.htm\r\n\r\nI shall mail to you separately a copy of the PowerPointPresentation and Transcript in MSWord on \"Inquiry in Science and Vedanta.\"\r\n\r\nLiberation will end the \'sufferer\' but not \'suffering\' per se, as I pointed out in the PPt.\r\n\r\nregards','2012-11-25 09:52:25','2012-11-25 09:52:25'),(2468,1,39,'Thank you for those links, which I have bookmarked. At the moment I am going through the 11-part video you have on YouTube. I find your explanations amazingly clear. I sometimes find myself thinking, â€œYes, but what about...â€ and then you fill in the blank. For example, I enjoyed the distinction you made about the â€œhorn of the hare.â€ If you hadn\'t taken the extra moment to clarify that then the overall explanation would have seemed to have a hole in it. \r\n\r\n(For people who would also like to watch, the first video can be found here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=czHb1oqT_7k )\r\n\r\nP.S. As you may already know, the microphone in those videos tended to cut out when you leaned forward. Fortunately the audio outages in the video are brief and they didn\'t affect my comprehension much (except, of course, when my comprehension was sullied by the thought, â€œDarn that microphone!â€).','2012-11-25 19:25:40','2012-11-25 19:25:40'),(2469,1,39,'Vemuri Ramesam, thank you! It is with immense gratitude that I thank you for sharing with me the file â€œTranscript for PPt at the Blog Sep 2012.docâ€ and the associated Powerpoint slides. \r\n\r\nThe more I read and hear of what you say, the more my heart leaps with joy, because after years of searching I\'ve finally found someone who speaks about such matters with clarity. Far too many people on the net have a vested interest in proving to themselves that their realization is the correct one. Those few who do not have that vested interest are incapable of expressing themselves in ordinary language using non-esoteric concepts. \r\n\r\nBack in 2006, when I was 49 years old, I took my first genuinely serious step in my ongoing quest for the truth. At that time I vowed I would not simply look for a way out of suffering. I figured that even if I did find the truth it would only highlight my initial selfishness if I could not also show people how I got there, in a way that any honest person could replicate.\r\n\r\nI called this vow \"The Trail of Breadcrumbs.\" In western literature there\'s a famous tale of a child who ventured into a dark forest and left a trail of breadcrumbs so he could find his way back. This also meant that people could follow the trail and join him. \r\n\r\nThis approach was the only way I could seek after enlightenment. Any other approach seemed like the self seeking to rescue only the self. What was the point of that, since this body was going to die eventually?\r\n\r\nThis is why I supported your camp here on Canonizer. You are the first person I\'ve encountered who seems like they could understand what I called The Trail of Breadcrumbs. \r\n\r\nIt appears that my initial hunch was correct. As I looked at Slide # 57 in your PowerPoint presentation I saw these words:\r\n\r\nâ€œTruth has to be Simple, Universal. Not private, Mystical, Secretive, Inaccessibleâ€\r\n\r\nYes! Yes! Exactly so! That\'s what I\'ve been saying all these years! And all the while, many purportedly enlightened people have responded, â€œOh, that\'s just your mind playing tricks on you. You\'re trying to understand that which cannot be understood.â€\r\n\r\nMy mind does play many tricks on me, but in perhaps in this case they were wrong. I realize that there must be a leap away from understanding, but understanding CAN be used to dissolve the fictions that drag us away from that leap.\r\n\r\nI was astonished when I saw that your Slide # 57 also included this:\r\n\r\n\"Probability of Success <3 in 10^6 - S. Sobottka (2008) Can science help increase the probability?\"\r\n\r\nI knew the chances were low, but I never put a number on it. All I knew is that we humans now have the ability to destroy ourselves and most other life. Several gurus told me I shouldn\'t worry about that. I walked away from them.\r\n\r\nPerhaps I was wrong. Perhaps you\'re wrong. But if that\'s so, perhaps we\'re wrong in the same way. I have no desire to rescue myself from delusion only to leave everybody else behind. I simply can\'t put my mind in a state that would accept that.\r\n\r\nIf I had any doubts before about supporting your camp here on Canonizer, they\'re now hugely diminished.','2012-11-26 13:46:39','2012-11-26 13:46:39'),(2470,35,71,'The statement for this camp seems credible to me, but there\'s one point that perhaps I do not understand:\r\n\r\nQuote: [As has] been proved experimentally by the Aspect twin particle effect, where once entangled atomic particles (photons) remain as if one even while they are separated by great distances. A computer will not be connected to this source in a meaningful way. That is why I think a computer will never be \"conscious.\"\r\n\r\nA quantum computer is a device that does various things with particles in superposition. Calling it a â€œcomputerâ€ might be a bit of a stretch, but the actual device called a Quantum Computer is almost certainly hooked up to and managed by a regular computer. Where does the Quantum Computer start and where does it end? Is the electrical power plant, located miles away, part of the Quantum Computer?\r\n\r\nIf we say that \"a computer will never be conscious,\" what are we saying, exactly? Do we mean that a microprocessor chip can never be conscious? What if that chip included a small region lowered to near absolute zero, where superposition could happen â€” a QC on the chip? Could it be a bit conscious then?\r\n\r\nI\'m open to supporting this camp but that statement about computers being incapable of consciousness is a sticking point. ','2012-11-27 12:07:39','2012-11-27 12:07:39'),(2471,1,67,'It is with slight reluctance that I support the Atheism camp. The camp statement is fairly open-ended:\r\n\r\nQuote: Atheism is the position that deities do not exist. Atheists may hold a spectrum of views from a general disbelief in any supernatural phenomenon to a specific disbelief in a personal god.\r\n\r\nI have two quibbles. They\'re minor, but they matter to me. Here they are:\r\n\r\nâ€”\r\n\r\n(1) I have â€œa specific disbelief in a personal god,â€ but I find it a bit problematic to utter the blanket statement \"deities do not exist.\" Some traditions (such as Sufi, Kabbalah, Hinduism) have ultimate definitions of God that are, roughly speaking, \"Whatever it was that produced the Big Bang\" or â€œthe ground of beingâ€ â€” in other words, a conception  vastly different from what most people mean by \"God.â€ Yet these mystics still call it God (example: look up Ein Sof or Brahman on Wikipedia). Some of them even call it Nothing (i.e. no-thing), or attributeless â€” hardly a personal god!\r\n\r\nâ€”\r\n\r\n(2) While I don\'t believe in personal gods, I do accept that gods can have a memetic quasi-reality. This means much more than \"People share the same belief.\" \r\n\r\nFor more about this, please see my video \"Jesus Bits: Christianity for Atheists\" on YouTube. This argues that gods can be as real as you or I THINK we are. That is to say, the â€œselfâ€ we take ourselves to be is grounded in a correlation of memes and personal memories. Those memes become an integral part of what we take ourselves to be. A big part of that might include a convenient fiction called God. While the details are fictional, a large group of people can create a memetic meta-entity that is just as valid as our belief in our â€œself.â€\r\n\r\nâ€”\r\n\r\nI apologize if my explanations are not crystal clear because I\'m really digging deep to highlight an objection I have with â€œatheismâ€ in the form that it often takes on the internet. \r\n\r\nI don\'t believe in conventional gods (and haven\'t done so since the 1980). However, I do not want to join those people who define themselves by what they DON\'T believe. There are people out there who spend hours per day preaching the gospel of atheism. These people have not only made atheism their quasi-religion (!) but they\'ve also given it a bad name!\r\n\r\nThe Atheism camp has my support for now. I suspect it might have more support if it (or a sub-camp?) was clearly disassociated from the kind of fire-breathing atheism that can make us non-believers look bad.','2012-11-27 12:41:45','2012-11-27 12:41:45'),(2472,35,71,'Hi TimX,\r\n\r\nThanks for all you contributions, and these great comments.\r\n\r\nThis â€œhard problemâ€ topic is kind of the predecessor to the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88 â€œTheories of Consciousnessâ€] topic.  Most people have just changed their camps to reference the newer versions in the other camp where all the work is done these days, or just no longer contributing here.\r\n\r\nI think the camp over there, most similar to this older â€œprior to brainâ€ camp, is the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/48  â€œSubstance Dualismâ€] or [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/35 â€œHigher Demensionalâ€] theories.  In other words, this prior stuff is some kind of different â€˜substanceâ€™, in a higher, possibly spiritual dimension.\r\n\r\nAlso, I donâ€™t see any responses to what you think is a sticking point.  So, remember, the canonizer way is, if nobody responds or objects, itâ€™s up to you to feel free to fix any sticking points and improve any camp (usually a crude draft to get things started) to make it the best you think it can be, either here or over there.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-11-27 17:05:23','2012-11-27 17:05:23'),(2473,283,82,'\r\nHi Sam,\r\n\r\nInteresting work.  Thanks for submitting this.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-11-30 17:08:16','2012-11-30 17:08:16'),(2474,1,98,'\r\nHi David (AKA [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=286 atypican]),\r\n\r\nI think the doctrines in the new camps you submitted are fantastic, even morally revolutionary.  Especially the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/2/31 A Metaphor] camp and it\'s morally superior statement.  I\'m  betting that nobody here would object to the moral superiority of that Metaphor doctrine about God.\r\n\r\nFor example, I one time met a person that claimed to me that he believed God was not perfectly benevolent.  My opinion was that such thinking was clearly morally inferior, and I believe all moral experts would agree.  And even if he did admit that God was malevolent, even he should not seek to become like that, and that no malevolence should ever be worshipped.\r\n\r\nOther than these new camps you just submitted, there are currently only two top level consensus camps [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/2/20 Mother Nature], and [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/2/2 God Does Not Exist].  I propose that David\'s revolutionary new [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/2/31 \"Metaphore\"] become a new unanimously agreed on supper camp - and that both the \"Mother Nature\" and \"God Does Not Exist\" supper camps be moved into a supporting position of this consensus morally important doctrine camp.\r\n\r\n\r\nI also propose that the doctrines contained in the \"Worshipped Being\" and the \"One\'s Ruling Logic\" could be combined into this one unanimous supper camp via something like the below combined new statement for the camp:  David, would you agree that these camps could be combined, and would you be willing to combine your currently split vote into one new combined and unanimous supper camp, as being proposed?\r\n\r\nI\'m hoping David or anyone, can improve the proposed enhanced draft version of this statement for this new combined unanimous \"Metaphor\" camp below?\r\n\r\nAnd remember, if anyone is going to object to these changes being proposed, please let us know before any of us attempt to make them, so we can understand and start negotiating the best way to fully represent what everyone does believe, if you do not agree with what is being proposed.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n------------------\r\n\r\n= A Metaphor = \r\n\r\nGod is a metaphor for a person\'s concept of greater good or what they believe is most important.\r\n\r\nSome people believe in a benevolent God, and that his attributes are worthy of worship, and to the degree possible, they seek to become like him.  In this way one\'s idea of moral perfection, whether as just a metaphor, or more than this, this moral ideal concept should become one\'s ruling logic or a kind goal or moral compass that guides one in their efforts to first understand what is morally superior, and then to seek to become more like such.\r\n\r\nRegardless of whether one is an atheist, or a theists, or whatever, there is clear near unanimous consensus here, that this is a morally important doctrine about any Idea of God.\r\n\r\n','2012-12-02 10:03:51','2012-12-02 10:03:51'),(2475,1,98,'Brent\r\n\r\nYou propose that \" ...David\'s revolutionary new \"Metaphore\" become a new unanimously agreed on supper camp - and that both the \"Mother Nature\" and \"God Does Not Exist\" supper camps be moved into a supporting position of this consensus morally important doctrine camp.\"\r\n\r\nI do not agree to this change. \"God\" refers to a supernatural being or force which many believers claim is good though they do not seem to me to account for the evils of this world.\r\n\r\nThe metaphor camp denies the existence of a being or force and should thus be a subcamp of \"God does not exist\" and not vice versa.\r\n\r\n','2012-12-02 20:41:59','2012-12-02 20:41:59'),(2476,1,98,'\r\nHi Richwil,\r\n\r\nThanks for your quick response on this.\r\n\r\nPerhaps David and I are saying things wrong, but I did not intend for the proposed new camp to be about any kind of real God, or have anything to do with whether anyone believes there is a real God or not.\r\n\r\nI\'m thinking of this as kind of a meta doctrine, which says nothing about what God may or may not be.  It is only about a \"Metaphor\" idea.  It is simply the idea that one can think of what is the best possible, or benevolent God, (regardless of whether such exists or not) and treat this as kind of a goal, for what we should strive to be like.  And it also only says that if one does believe that there is a real God, that it should not deviate from this ideal metaphor of God.  And also, any God, regardless of whether it exists or not, is only deserving of worship, to the degree that it approaches this ideal - whatever this ideal is.\r\n\r\nDoes that make more sense, and would you agree with just that?\r\n\r\nMaybe David can say this better than I am?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-12-02 21:10:05','2012-12-02 21:10:05'),(2477,1,98,'My two cents..\r\n\r\nNo one denys that God is a term. It may be that god also exists as an almighty being that loves everyone, or it may be that god exists as a meme complex, or only a figment of our imagination. The point I guess is that there is room for disagreement about \"what the term god describes\" in this camp, but admitting god\'s existence is logically necessary to discussing the qualities of god, so (IMO) I don\'t think \"god doesn\'t exist\" should be a supporting camp.\r\n\r\nI have a belief that \"everything exists, well understood or not\". Should I create this camp, there could be no supporting \"X does not exist\" camps. I think it\'s a waste of time having discussions with people who believe in non-existent things...lol','2012-12-02 22:09:52','2012-12-02 22:09:52'),(2478,1,98,'Dear all,\r\n\r\n\r\nI tentatively agree with notion that the concept of God is metaphor for something else --- basically how we should live our lives --- with thoughts about our afterlife in the background. I will, therefore, remind you of Pascalâ€™s Wager: The bet that there is God is safer. If he does not --- we lose nothing. If he does, we may earn eternal life...\r\n\r\n\r\nThe main idea is that there is The Ultimate Judge --- able to judge our deeds on the same principles (absolute truths or dogmas) for eternity. This is, unfortunately, unacceptable to me. Throughout history, we saw how quickly dogmas degenerated --- not because we are sinful --- but simply because our societies, thoughts, technology etc. evolved. For example, our planet simply cannot support energy consumption of six billion people. How to defend then, fierce opposition to birth control? How to defend then, our living standards? Etc. etc...\r\n\r\n\r\nIf there is The Ultimate Judge --- I doubt that we will ever learn what his ultimate criteria are. I have, therefore, accepted a Lesser Judge: Our kids and the life on this planet in general. They are, ultimately, the ones that will judge our deeds. And if I manage to leave them a bit better place than the one I was born into --- I do hope that there will be little slices of heaven in their hearts for me...\r\n\r\n\r\nThis brings me to the topic (The Joke) I opened here. Interestingly, nobody found worthwhile to take sides there. And having free will is crucial to the all of the above. Only if we have free will --- we can be responsible for our deeds. Without free will --- all our musings about God, afterlife in heavens etc. etc. --- are useless!\r\n\r\n\r\nIn practice, I often find that people do not wish to have free will. It is simpler. We can always blame others or other things --- and spend our lives as leaves pushed around by wind...\r\n\r\n\r\nHaving free will comes with heavy strings attached. Without dogmas, each of our deeds needs to be considered very carefully. And not only by an individual. Often, many more needs to put their heads together. While the past can be a guide --- the present and the future must always be taken into account...\r\n\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-12-03 00:22:51','2012-12-03 00:22:51'),(2479,1,98,'A person who does not believe that god exists cannot logically participate in discussions about the characteristics of god.','2012-12-03 03:07:25','2012-12-03 03:07:25'),(2480,1,98,'Dear atypican,\r\n\r\n\r\nA concept of God implies many things. (Please note that I used â€œa conceptâ€, not â€œthe conceptâ€ --- since there is so many concepts of God and we would not argue here if there was one only.)\r\n\r\n\r\nConsequently, a negative approach (God does not exist) --- has some relevance in this topic. It would also be --- a kind of --- dictatorial. In effect, denying atheists a say could be extended further: Only Catholics have right to speak about existence of God, for example. Do you really wish this?\r\n\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-12-03 05:33:45','2012-12-03 05:33:45'),(2481,1,98,'In response to atypican, i challenge the assertion that there is any logical contradiction in discussing the nature of a concept which one doesn\'t believe refers to a real being. We can discuss the nature of Santa Claus, can we not?','2012-12-05 14:05:28','2012-12-05 14:05:28'),(2482,1,98,'Brent, no, i stand by what i said: the atheist camp does not belong under the metaphor camp; it is a direct response to the question \"What is God?\".\r\n\r\nDamir, i would point out that Pascal\'s wager is not a good bet because it naively relies on a lack of omniscience - one of the characteristics claimed by believers for God.','2012-12-05 14:16:16','2012-12-05 14:16:16'),(2483,1,98,'\r\nAtypican said:\r\n\r\nâ€œMy two cents worth.â€\r\n\r\nIn my view this kind of critically important revolutionary moral theory which is way ahead of the masses is worth way more than just two cents.\r\n\r\nBut it does appear that I was taking it a bit too far, hoping that we could have unanimous consensus from all camps.\r\n\r\nThanks, everyone, for helping me understand this, and for all the great contribution, to date, from all sides.\r\n\r\nSo would anyone object to adding these critically important morally revolutionary doctrines to the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/2/20 â€œMother Natureâ€] camp?  Atypican, is there anything in the Mother Nature Camp that you disagree with?  Could we win you, and the doctrines contained in your revolutionary camps, into the currently leading moral consensus camp?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-12-05 15:03:48','2012-12-05 15:03:48'),(2484,1,98,'\r\nIâ€™m in the â€œeverything including usâ€ is God (at least in embryo) camp, but also in the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/2/5 camp that hopes smart powerful guys donâ€™t have to hide from anyone].  So, even though I donâ€™t abandon my faith and accept that hiding gods exist YET, I can still talk about and discuss what an idealized god is or should be, in a metaphorical way.  I can believe that anything that deviates from the attributes of this metaphorical god, (as in a God that hides from evil) should be considered a devil and you should be thought of as evil, or at best primitive, to the degree you still worship such, and so on.\r\n\r\n','2012-12-05 15:29:24','2012-12-05 15:29:24'),(2485,1,98,'\r\nRichwil said an atheist can talk about Santa Claus, but I believe it is much more than that.  An atheist can point out that a vengeful God, is really a devil, not a god, and if you idealize any such, or are even OK with becoming such, and most importantly, if you seek to act like such by doing such things as flying planes into towers, you are still an evil, faithless devil.  You are devilish if you make immoral cries like â€œGod works in mysterious ways.â€ to justify any evil, rather than hoping to overcome all such.  So even if an atheist doesnâ€™t believe such exist, it is still critically important for them to engage in conversations about what kinds of Godly attributes are good, leading man kind to be the same, and what kinds of metaphorical attributes are bad, leading man to be a devilâ€¦.\r\n\r\n','2012-12-05 16:10:38','2012-12-05 16:10:38'),(2486,1,98,'richwil,\r\n\r\nWhether discussing the nature of God or Santa Claus, one must logically start with admitting that the term describes something real, even if perhaps misunderstood. An imaginary problem is a real problem.\r\n\r\nGod exists, and if our ideas about what god is don\'t mature at a healthy rate, I\'ll say it\'s largely because we haven\'t through sound logic described what god is.\r\n\r\nI suspect that you would admit that god exists conceptually. This moves you out of the \"God doesn\'t exist\" camp into the camp discussing the characteristics of god. The position that there are \"non-existent\" or \"unreal\" things or beings is illogical to begin with.','2012-12-05 17:17:01','2012-12-05 17:17:01'),(2487,1,98,'I\'m not convinced that the camp(s) I created should be moved.\r\n\r\nThe camp name is \"What is God?\" and I think it should be changed to something like \"Truths about God\"\r\n\r\nSometimes I entertain a notion of god analogous to what I suppose are universal immutable laws and forces of nature, or inescapable reality, but I\'m not entirely convinced that calling two poorly defined terms synonymous is worthwhile.\r\n\r\nIt may very well be that general benefit would result if the term god was more and more used and understood in the pantheistic sense. If I thought that the vast majority of people had a pantheistic view of god, or even if I thought that god and love had the same meaning, I\'d stop identifying as atheist.\r\n\r\nBut from my perspective, true statements about god should correspond with what currently is. And currently when theists speak of god, they are referring to a being they can communicate with that is imagined to be worthy of worship and infallible.  So while there are many people who think of god as \"Mother nature\" (and I don\'t find that particularly objectionable) I understand god as something quite different, so I am not in the God=Mother Nature Camp','2012-12-06 06:23:27','2012-12-06 06:23:27'),(2488,1,98,'Brent\r\n\r\nThe mother nature camp statement portrays nature as some form of deity and invokes religion. This seems to me antithetical to atheism. Perhaps the idea of those in the \'atheist\' subcamp is that they do not believe in a supreme being as creator but do believe in the strong version of Gaia?\r\n\r\nYou say that \"Mother Nature is â€˜sentientâ€™ in that it includes humanity and very intelligent animals.\" I have 2 problems with this.\r\n\r\n1) That a class of things includes items that have a particular attribute, in this case sentience, does not entail that all members of the class have this attribute or that you can further claim that the class has that attribute.\r\n\r\n2) The natural world is not maternal (or paternal). To use the term \"mother nature\" begs the question since it implies sentience if taken literally or is misleading if taken metaphorically.\r\n\r\nI would also venture that that intelligence does not imply sentience, it is just that they appear together in the natural world.\r\n','2012-12-06 10:26:00','2012-12-06 10:26:00'),(2489,1,98,'atypican\r\n\r\nYou claim that \"Whether discussing the nature of God or Santa Claus, one must logically start with admitting that the term describes something real\". Not at all, Mr Claus is as fictional as god/s i.e. not real.\r\n\r\nYou suspect that i \"..would admit that god exists conceptually.\" No i do not. My position is that there are concepts of imaginary beings and it is the concepts that exist and not the beings. I do not see how imaginary beings exist conceptually: your assertion is confused or meaningless.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard','2012-12-07 14:10:15','2012-12-07 14:10:15'),(2490,1,98,'Richard,\r\n\r\nThis camp is for establishing consensus about -what god is-. It\'s starting to seem like you aren\'t too confused to recognize that god exists as a useful literary device.\r\n\r\nSince you can\'t see how imaginary beings exist conceptually, it\'s not all that surprising that you refuse to even admit that god exists as a concept. If you can admit that god exists as a fictional character, at least I\'ve got you talking in terms of \"what is\", as opposed to the illogical practice of discussing things supposed not to exist.\r\n\r\nBesides the possibility of my assertion being confused or meaningless, there is also the possibility that you poorly understand it.\r\n\r\natypican','2012-12-07 17:57:04','2012-12-07 17:57:04'),(2491,1,98,'Hi atypican,\r\n\r\nThe \"Truths about God\" name for this topic certainly sounds like an improvement to me, I\'d imagine nobody would object to you making that improvement  (If I\'m wrong, anyone, speak up now).\r\n\r\nYou identify as an atheist?  Sweet!  I was very dumb to initially assume otherwise.\r\n\r\nThe \"Mother Nature\" camp isn\'t pantheism, Gaia, or any other specific set of doctrines.  The set of all \'Gaia\' beliefs includes the idea that the world, itself, outside of humanity, is sentient, doesn\'t it?  I certainly wouldn\'t allow that doctrine to be included in the \"Mother Nature\" camp, but it would go nicely in a supporting sub camp named \"Gaia\" where I wouldn\'t have to support those kinds of doctrines.  Pantheism... also includes similar additional doctrines, I, and lots of people would disagree with, right?\r\n\r\nThe Mother Nature camp only includes, as it states in the first statement: \"All that we can all agree really exists.\" and that\'s all.  And it is the basic idea that all that is progressing, as in survivability is progress, sentience is progress, joy is progress, mother nature is progressing towards all such or in general towards that which is best (all powerful, all knowing, all quale experiencing, infallible...), and so on.  And so this giant computer, evolutionary searching algorithm, or whatever you want to call it, \'god\' or \'gaia\' - only if you\'d like, loves and cares for us, in so far as our parents (part of it) created, love and care for us, and so on.\r\n\r\nThere are obviously two drastically different types of atheists - those that think Nature has a purpose, and is progressing, and those that don\'t.  That\'s the difference between the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/2/4 atheist branch that supports this general camp], and the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/2/2 parallel branch that doesn\'t].  There could also be theists, of various types, that don\'t agree with this mother nature has a direction or purpose doctrine, and they could also create a parallel branch of whatever type of theism they believe in that excludes this doctrine.\r\n\r\n\r\nYou stated in the \"Worshipped Being\" camp:  \"Other distinguishing characteristics of god, or whether or not any being ought to be worshiped is open for debate under this camp.\".  If you want to survey for something different than stated in the \'agreement statement\' of this topic, it\'d probably be best to start another survey topic, and state the question / purpose of that, in the agreement statement in the new topic.  Usually, that is the purpose of the agreement statement - to include the question of what the topic is about, in a way that everyone agrees with and supports it - and any improvements to it.  Adding this kind of purpose or question stuff in sub camps, makes it hard for people in different camps, to participate in such (i.e. they need to split and dilute their vote between camps, and so on)\r\n\r\nSo, given all that, would you agree with everything currently in the \"Mother Nature\" camp, and be willing to support it, instead of competing with the idea - as if you disagree with it - implied by only supporting competing camps?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2012-12-07 23:16:03','2012-12-07 23:16:03'),(2492,1,98,'Dear Brent,\r\n\r\nI suggest that â€œBelieves about Godâ€ would be better than â€œTruths about Godâ€. Some might firmly believe that something about God is true, but even they cannot provide evidence to justify the use of word truth.\r\n\r\nI believe that those who support that Mother Nature has a purpose --- should not be classified as atheists. Certainly, purpose is one of believes about God.\r\n\r\nI would also caution about too many sub-camps. I am well aware that there are so many different believes about God --- that reaching an agreement will be made very difficult. I, therefore, suggest that we start thinking about how to merge some of the sub-camps.\r\n\r\nWe also need to make clear that we can agree that we donâ€™t agree. I, therefore, encourage atheists to start articulating their disagreements. If they cannot --- that automatically means that they only believe that they are atheists. In essence, if only one belief about God does not have an articulated opposition --- we will have to agree that there is an entity we may call God.\r\n\r\nI also suggest anthropomorphic camp. It is clear and simple: Does God represents our own, human, aspirations?\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-12-08 02:21:25','2012-12-08 02:21:25'),(2493,1,98,'Hi Damir,\r\n\r\nYou said:\r\n\r\n    \"I suggest that â€œBelieves about Godâ€ would be better\r\n    than â€œTruths about Godâ€. Some might firmly believe\r\n    that something about God is true, but even they\r\n    cannot provide evidence to justify the use of word truth.\"\r\n\r\nSweet, things just keep getting better and better.  atypican, would you agree - that this is better?  Although \"Beliefs about God\" would be better grammatically?  I like \"working hypothesis about God\"\' or \"theories about God\", but \"Beliefs about God\" probably captures that in a better way?\r\n\r\n    \"I believe that those who support that Mother Nature\r\n    has a purpose --- should not be classified as atheists.\"\r\n\r\nIt sounds like you\'re telling someone what they should believe, or what they should call themselves or how they should name their camp?\r\n\r\n    \"Certainly, purpose [is a belief] about God.\"\r\n\r\nIt is very frustrating to me that you would say this, because I feel a terrible communication fail is taking place with this.  I think I understand what you are saying, and completely agree with it, but it is something very different than what I\'m trying to talk about, by saying \'purpose\'.\r\n\r\nYou\'re talking about some kind of top down, declared by God \'purpose\' or what some would call \'intelligent design\' and so on.  I am talking about something diametrically the opposite of this.  I\'m  am talking about a bottom up purpose, the kind of purpose that would result in a genetic search computer algorithm, and so on.  For example, survival of the fittest is better, so that is the bottom up purpose of evolution, to select for such things that are better.  I\'m talking about the kind of purpose that spontaneously self organizes or is discovered, out of nothing, not something that is directed from above.\r\n\r\nHow could I better say the above, to avoid this kind of communication fail?  I really struggle with this all the time, because this kind of communication fail almost always occurs when I say that.\r\n\r\n    \"I would also caution about too many sub-camps.\r\n    I am well aware that there are so many different\r\n    believes about God --- that reaching an agreement\r\n    will be made very difficult.  I, therefore, suggest\r\n    that we start thinking about how to merge some of\r\n    the sub-camps.\"\r\n\r\nAbsolutely!  It\'s nice to have other stressing this, besides just me.  We should always be working to have the most consensus, with the fewest camps possible - to make it easier on the reader - but not too few, as we still want to capture the essence of what everyone believes, without compromise, and the most efficient easy for all to understand camp structure.\r\n\r\nBuilding as much consensus, and having as few camps as possible is what this site is all about.  Too many people treat this as some kind of blog, where millions of everyone can have their own camp or statement about what they believe, with a lonely my way or the highway thinking, and they could care less about working or understanding what anyone else, besides themselves believes, or to try to build or work towards a consensus.\r\n\r\n    \"We also need to make clear that we can agree\r\n    that we donâ€™t agree. I, therefore, encourage\r\n    atheists to start articulating their disagreements.\r\n    If they cannot --- that automatically means that\r\n    they only believe that they are atheists.\"\r\n\r\nIt seems to me, that is exactly what we are doing.  I like calling myself an Atheist, as I hope no powerful beings ever have to hide from anyone or or any evil.  But, I totally hate it because most people classify me with the type of atheists that believe evolution is not progressing towards anything, and other terrible beliefs, like \'my way or the highway\' and so on.  I like the current structure, because it shows that most atheist are, to me the good kind of atheists, unlike those to me bad kind that don\'t think evolution is progressing.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2012-12-08 04:21:22','2012-12-08 04:21:22'),(2494,1,98,'Dear Brent,\r\n\r\nWe may have a semantic issue with word â€œpurposeâ€. In my vocabulary, purpose can only be described as predetermined goal. Now, letâ€™s have a look at your expression:\r\n\r\nâ€œI\'m am talking about a bottom up purpose, the kind of purpose that would result in a genetic search computer algorithm, and so on. For example, survival of the fittest is better, so that is the bottom up purpose of evolution, to select for such things that are better. I\'m talking about the kind of purpose that spontaneously self organizes or is discovered, out of nothing, not something that is directed from above.â€\r\n\r\nTo me, this sounds like self-improvement --- a kind of eternal self-discovery. Each time we add something new to our knowledge (creativity) --- we add new qualitative complexities that we need to discover. And that means never-ending or eternal self-discovery. For this reason alone, I would leave â€œMother Nature has a purposeâ€ (for those who think top-down) and add camp â€œEternal maturation of Mother Natureâ€ or something similar (for those who think bottom-up). In both cases, I would not suggest references to computer algorithms, even when we are talking about evolution of genetic code. I suggest references to Complex Adaptive Systems theory. To get a better picture, there are few relatively good articles on Wikipedia. I also recommend articles on n-body problem and many-body problem. They are essentially referring to the same phenomenon --- but reading both gives more complete picture.\r\n\r\nI would also caution against survival of the fittest as the only evolutionary criterion. This is a gross misinterpretation of Darwin himself. According to Darwin, there is a second criterion: survival of the kin, group etc. that often leads individual organisms to sacrifice themselves. This criterion is also now accepted by evolutionary biologists. In addition, I believe that in both camps proposed above, many theists and atheists may find a common ground and surprisingly agree about something.\r\n\r\nSince you did not mention my suggestion about anthropomorphic camp, I will assume that you tentatively agree. I will, therefore, contemplate a bit how to articulate it and add it unless I receive suggestions to the contrary. Iâ€™m also open to suggestions for different articulations. I also expect here some theists and atheists to find some common ground and surprisingly agree.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-12-08 07:39:16','2012-12-08 07:39:16'),(2495,1,98,'Dear Brent,\r\n\r\nThe current tree of â€œWhat is God?â€ is complete mess (see below). Some sub-camps are simple rewording of others. There are also wrongly placed sub-camps and the general feeling is that people created them often without giving them a serious thought. I will, therefore, give some thought to a general outline for â€œBeliefs about Godâ€. However, Iâ€™m a bit of novice in theology and will need help here.\r\n\r\n42.13 What is God?\r\n\r\n--31.75 Mother Nature\r\n\r\n----11.75 Atheist: There is No Good Evidence that God Exists.\r\n\r\n------2 If God already exists while there is evil, there can be no hope.\r\n\r\n----11.25 God does exist.\r\n\r\n------9.25 There is only one God.\r\n\r\n--------5.25 Jesus is the Son of God.\r\n\r\n----------5 As taught by the LDS Prophet.\r\n\r\n------------2 God created everything.\r\n\r\n--------3 We are all God\r\n\r\n--------1 There is only one Goddess (Merlin Stone, _When_God_Was_A_Woman_)\r\n\r\n------2 There is more than one God\r\n\r\n--------1 The Chuch Of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints\r\n\r\n----3.5 \"God\" and \"existence\" are synonymous, \"God exists\" is redundant\r\n\r\n----2.25 The question whether God exist doesn\'t matter\r\n\r\n----1 God may or may not exist.\r\n\r\n--9.5 God does not exist.\r\n\r\n----1 If God already exists while there is evil, there can be no hope.\r\n\r\n--0.5 Worshipped Being\r\n\r\n----0.5 Outgrowing Worship â€“ Good\r\n\r\n--0.25 A metaphor\r\n\r\n--0.13 One\'s Ruling Logic\r\n\r\nAny thoughts?\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-12-08 09:31:26','2012-12-08 09:31:26'),(2496,1,98,'atypican---\r\n\r\nYou claim that \"admitting god\'s existence is logically necessary to discussing the qualities of god...\" This is simply false: describing the attributes or qualities of x does not entail or require that x exists. For example, i can easily describe Father Christmas or the present king of England.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, if the attributes of x are logically inconsistent with reality then x cannot exist. For example, if x is omniscient, omnipotent and loving yet there is unavoidable suffering then x does not exist.\r\n\r\nBrent---\r\n\r\nI object to changing the title to \'Truths about God\' because the proposed title lacks neutrality. \'Beliefs about God\' would be ok by the same token.\r\n\r\n','2012-12-09 10:18:02','2012-12-09 10:18:02'),(2497,1,98,'richwil---\r\n\r\nYou and I have a fundamental disagreement here. I\'d like to avoid a back and forth \"yes it is/no it isn\'t\" session or reusing basically the exact same arguments that weren\'t convincing the first time.\r\n\r\nYou say that you can easily describe attributes or qualities of the present king of England. If you would please humor me and attempt to do so (even briefly) I think this would help me illustrate my point.\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent & richwil and whomever else it may concern\r\n\r\nI find \"Beliefs about God\" to be acceptable. Should this change be effected, I will create a subcamp \"Truths can be known about god\" which would be a good place for my other camps. ','2012-12-12 03:04:34','2012-12-12 03:04:34'),(2498,1,98,'atypican---\r\n\r\nYou ask me to describe the present king of England. Well, Brian\'s a stout fellow with a military bearing, being a Navy man, married to the the second cousin of the queen of Prussia... What point would you care to make?\r\n\r\nMy point is the same as Russell\'s. What i am doing above is describing a fictitious person as if they existed - we are well aware that there is no present king of England but we have no problem writing about him as if he did. You say that \"admitting god\'s existence is logically necessary to discussing the qualities of god..\" You can surely see your claim is false if we substitute \"Brian\" for \"god\"?\r\n\r\nPerhaps you mean to say that admitting the *possibility* of the existence of x is necessary to discuss x\'s qualities? Even this isn\'t right as we can discuss the attributes of impossible things such as square circles.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard','2012-12-13 09:51:38','2012-12-13 09:51:38'),(2499,1,98,'You DID NOT describe the present King of England, because as we are aware, England currently has no king. You DID describe a fictional person that EXISTS only imaginatively. This imaginary person you call Brian, is not the king of England, so I am sorry, but you were unable to describe the present king of England because to do so there would have to currently be a king of England to describe.\r\n\r\nIf your position is that god exists only imaginatively, THAT is sufficient for logical discussion. Premise 1: God exists, Premise 2: Only imaginatively\r\n\r\nThe point I am trying to make is an attack on the ubiquitous misconception, the (IMO) false dichotomy that some things are real and other things are not real. It seems to me that you are in the camp that says \"some things are real, some things are not\". I am in the camp that says \"everything is real\"\r\n\r\nAs to your challenge: --You say that \"admitting god\'s existence is logically necessary to discussing the qualities of god..\" You can surely see your claim is false if we substitute \"Brian\" for \"god\"?--\r\n\r\nWhen you talk about Brian, you are describing a being that you imagine. A being that exists only imaginatively CAN be described and logically discussed. But supposing something or someone who doesn\'t exist at all, precludes the illogically supposed \"non-thing\" or \"non-being\" from having any properties at all to describe, therefore any discussion is logically baseless.','2012-12-13 19:57:52','2012-12-13 19:57:52'),(2500,1,98,'\r\nI\'m an atheist and I usually point such out before starting a religious conversation with anyone.\r\n\r\nI often want to say things to a theist like the following when someone is suffering:\r\n   \"Do you think God is enjoying watching that?\"\r\nand they\'ll sometimes reply with something like:\r\n    \"why do you hate God\"\r\nto which I like to reply with something like:\r\n    \"I don\'t hate God or anyone - I just don\'t want to be like (or worship) any such God.\"\r\n\r\nWould all of you agree that good communication was talking place, with the above conversation?\r\n\r\n','2012-12-14 03:19:13','2012-12-14 03:19:13'),(2501,1,98,'Dear Brent,\r\n\r\nI think both, theists and atheists, would conclude the same from your question. If you are atheist simply because you think that God would, inevitably, be a sadist - then, I suggest that your motivation is wrong.\r\n\r\nI will also suggest contemplating some verses of William Blake.\r\n\r\nHave a nice day,\r\nDamir','2012-12-14 03:48:23','2012-12-14 03:48:23'),(2502,1,98,'\"God\" is a meme, that is to say it is a type of human behaviour pattern. \r\n\r\nStrictly speaking it is better to say that the word \"God\" is manifest and entailed in patterns of human behaviour which, generally speaking, fall into either one, but not both, of two rather different types of behaviour pattern. I say types of behaviour pattern because, us people being what we are, variability is normal. \r\n\r\nAs an ex Christian I have real experience of both sides of the divide.\r\n\r\nTrue believers take the word God, or some particular name of their favoured deity, to be the real name of a person-like entity which really does exist. An atheist such as myself is more or less bound to describe the beliefs of true believers as a set of behaviours many of which are private mental behaviours of a particular kind. \r\n\r\nIt is too hard and probably not worth the effort for me to try and pin down the most crucial aspects of true belief, but  I think it is fair to say that naive realism is involved and, necessarily, a set of algorithms which are memes which the believer has taken in at some stage either consciously or not as the case may be. \r\n\r\nAtheists on the other hand do not take the word God, or some ...blah blah .. as real; it is just a concept that is taken far too seriously by the true believers. What atheists believe about the universe in general is not prescribed by any law, and almost none of it is irrefutably provable, except the logical necessity of _not_ engaging in the same kind of true beliefs as the true believers do. \r\n\r\nIt is arguable that an atheist has access to more opportunities to be truly free. I base this assertion on my own assessment of what is critically involved in being human; the summary includes the following: The human universe is always potentially infinite, so long as it exists and we believe it to be so. I think that is possibly the most liberating thought a person can have. It works for me anyway.  It is paradoxical however to the extent that our freedom, the very freedom I think is at issue, depends on our individual courage and willingness to stand by what we believe in. \r\n\r\nThe true believer is likely to say at this point: \"Ha ha! You see!  You have to believe in something! \"  which is true enough but the true believers then seem unable to refrain from inferring that just because it is _possible_ to believe in a divine being therefore it is _better_ to do so. That proposition is pure guesswork however. I would say it is more reasonable not to fetter one\'s imagination with allegiance to unprovable yet unfalsifiable projections of someone else\'s power concept.\r\n','2012-12-20 14:00:56','2012-12-20 14:00:56'),(2503,284,14,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\nHope you are doing fine. Wish you a very happy new year!\r\n\r\nI am trying to put up my best thoughts on issues and topics that interests me. Just need to keep up with the references, so i need to place hypertext links. \r\n\r\nAlso, if you help me with images and taglines that i want to put within the article/statements. any special codes for that?\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\nSam123 (Sidharta)','2012-12-30 05:46:35','2012-12-30 05:46:35'),(2504,284,14,'Hi Sam123,\r\n\r\nYea, your stuff is looking good.\r\n\r\nRemember that Canonizer.com is all about finding others that at least agree with you on some things, and building as much consensus as possible as camps supported by only one person are usually filtered or ignored by most, and certainly don\'t rise to the top.\r\n\r\nAs far as how to add images and such, when you are on the camp statement edit page there is a link to a [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/73 purple wiki text cheat sheet] page describing how to use the open source purple wiki wiki text parser we use.\r\n\r\nThanks for all your great contributions!!  It\'s great to have a good reference to how you currently think on all this.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-12-30 17:02:00','2012-12-30 17:02:00'),(2505,283,22,'\r\n\r\nHi Sam123,\r\n\r\nI agree with much that is described in this topic and set of camps, but not sure how to best support this.  For example, you seem to have added a survey questions as a sub camp of the main agreement statement.  If there is a survey question, the best place to put that is usually in the agreement statement, where the purpose of the topic is defined.  The problem is, if I support either the yes or no camp, it implies I don\'t agree with anything in the sibling (i.e. competing) \"Artificial Minds and Synthetic Thoughts\" camp - yet I agree with most of what is over there?\r\n\r\nFinally, it\'s not good to make assumptions about camps that might be competitor ideas to your camp.  It usually best to just start with one petition like camp which you think is the best theory, and start recruiting new supporters - only creating new camps when absolutely necessary.\r\n\r\nAs an example, to me a \'robot\' is, by definition, just an abstracted or non phenomenal system.  So, since phenomenal knowledge is required for true \'self consciousness\', it makes it hard for me to join any of the camps.  And I do believe it is possible to create artificial consciousness, I just wouldn\'t call it a robot.  Also, it is possible for a robot to be \'self aware\' in a non phenomenal or non conscious way, but all this kind of detail and such is not possible to specify or survey for in this structure as you currently have it?\r\n\r\nPerhaps you can more concisely state the purpose (remove as much unnecessary stuff as possible) of the topic in the agreement statement, and then just add one camp describing exactly what you currently believe.  Then, if I agree with all that, I can also sign your petition, or join your camp.  Only if there is something we disagree on, (probably some very minor issues) will we need to then negotiate to create two sub camps below the supper camp, representing these minor differences.  That way all the most important stuff and definitions we agree on can be in the supper experts consensus petition camp, along with a good concisely stated survey of the lessor things we disagree with, if any?\r\n\r\nThanks for your continued work to add all this great content to the system!\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-01-01 16:22:58','2013-01-01 16:22:58'),(2506,283,22,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\nThanks for your guidance, I am now able to get easy with the system, initially I thought its bit complicated but now having some  understanding of what it is like.\r\n\r\nJust need to get clear about these things first:\r\n\r\n1. I must know the system first, how it works and then plan accordingly.\r\n\r\n2. The agreement statement should be a short one, to get consensus and support/contention anyway. So it should simply be a statement\r\n\r\n3. The camp statement supporting the agreement statement it is where i could push my thoughts up there, be elaborate or descriptive, and perhaps can put in some original ideas, WHICH, I suppose could again be contended by someone else who might have something else to say, in a \"no\" camp.\r\n\r\n4. Now, what if I would like to continue with the discussion under research/new findings or anything other supporting my agreement statement? Shall I create more camps with subheadings as subtopics or start with a new topic?\r\n\r\n5. and finally, how can i recruit new supporters? who are the new supporters who can support me, and how do i get to them?\r\n\r\nThanks for your help Brent.\r\n\r\nBest Regards,\r\nSidharta Chatterjee','2013-01-02 02:28:18','2013-01-02 02:28:18'),(2509,96,48,'\r\nFolks,\r\n\r\nI only just today heard about the annual [http://consciousnessonline.com/program-2013/ Consciousness Online Conference] being put on by Richard Brown.\r\n\r\nSo today, I quickly put together a crude draft that I\'m attempting to submit for presentation and discussion using goggle docs:\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1xLlEk2OXca-ciEaNfUM5iaAtPxNkikPKZ29uWc2cd4g/edit\r\n\r\nAs you can see, I\'ve listed many of you as contributors, so let me know if you have a problem with your name being used for this.\r\n\r\nAnd of course, this document is set so anyone can wiki edit it, so of course, any and all help and/or comments, or adding your name, is greatly appreciated!!!!\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2013-02-03 19:30:52','2013-02-03 19:30:52'),(2512,96,48,'Nice find Brent. I\'ll check that out. \r\n\r\nI had an idea for reworking my Chalmeroff scale idea if anyone is interested:\r\n\r\nhttp://multisenserealism.com/2013/02/04/chalmeroff-scale-revisited/\r\n\r\nCraig','2013-02-04 03:36:43','2013-02-04 03:36:43'),(2515,96,48,'[http://transhumanity.net/authors/n/mark-waser Mark Waser] got his interesting paper entitled [http://transhumanity.net/articles/entry/dissolving-the-hard-problem-of-consciousness \'Disolving the \"Hard Problem\" of Consciousness\' published over on Transhumanity.org].\r\n\r\nA great conversation ensued over there between the readers, but evidently things broke down and people\'s comments are no longer being posted.\r\n\r\nSo I\'ve proposed moving the conversation over here, on this thread at Canonizer.com, where I hope we can get some additional input.\r\n\r\n\r\nI saw a post go by, via e-mail, but I have no idea who posted it.  I\'d like to reply, so I\'m going to include the entire post here, and then reply in a subsequent post to this thread.  I hope who ever posted this will identify himself, here.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n=================================\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent,\r\n\r\nI\'ve been meaning to follow up with your \"so we agree\" post to see if we\r\nreally agree, but I\'ve been busy.\r\n\r\nSo you seemed to ask that if my brain used some glutamate molecule to\r\nrepresent redness, and some computer used electrons, they would at least be\r\ndifferent, right?\r\n\r\nAnd the answer is of course. They use different hardware in their map so\r\nthey are different.\r\n\r\nIf you have two systems, that used all the same abstract information\r\nprocessing, so that it\'s information output was the same for same inputs,\r\nbut used different internal coding, would our qualia be different?\r\n\r\nOr, to make the question easier to understand, lets say you and I had nearly\r\nidentical brains, but due to a genetic difference, my brain encoded redness\r\nwith a glutamate molecule, and your brain used that molecule to encode\r\ngreenness. Would that mean our qualia were inverted?\r\n\r\nSeems intuitively that the answer would be yes. But, the answer, sad to say\r\n(for you), is NO. It can\'t be in that case.\r\n\r\nThis is because if the information processing is the same, then we could\r\nchange the encoding, and the person would then be unable to report that\r\nencoding had changed. If we move software from one computer that encodes 1\'s\r\nwith a +5, to a second computer that encodes the 1\'s with +3, could the\r\nsoftware report that encoding had changed? Not if the information processing\r\nhad stayed the same in the move. The software could not tell us, \"yes I can\r\ntell I\'m running on the +5 version of my qualia now\".\r\n\r\nLikewise, if we switch your brain, to encode red the way my brain encodes\r\nred, would you be able to say, \"I see, your red looks like my green\"? The\r\nanswer is NO you couldn\'t. If we swapped your encoding, it means you would\r\nhave no memory of how it was, to compare to how it is now, to detect the\r\ndifference.\r\n\r\n','2013-03-06 00:25:30','2013-03-06 00:25:30'),(2518,96,48,'Suppose a child is a born, and he has some sort of permanent set of glasses or cybernetics placed on him so that he sees green when we see red and vice versa...\r\n\r\nHe has this since growing up... so when we see red... he sees green, but he calls it red, because he has no idea our experience is different.... We likewise do not know that his experience is different.\r\n\r\nAs an information processing system is the child with his glasses or cybernetics different from an ordinary human being? remember, we\'re only looking at input output mechanisms... There is no difference right? So according to the hard materialist position, there is no difference in qualia between him and ordinary humans.\r\n\r\nAt 30 years of age his cybernetics are removed... now are his qualia different? Are they closer to our qualia? Or were they closer when the cybernetics were on him?','2013-03-06 01:25:59','2013-03-06 01:25:59'),(2521,96,48,'The problem that I have with all of these discussions is that the begin from flawed assumptions, so that however rationally they proceed from there, it ultimately leads back, in a circular fashion, to the original bad assumptions.\r\n\r\nThe first is that, as Mark Waser writes in his article:\r\n\r\nâ€œ1. There really is an external reality composed of physical objects (and their movements extending to the extent of complete processes like orbiting a star, etc.).â€\r\n\r\nThere is no support for this from a completely objective point of view. While we can judge that there certainly seems to be a universe which goes on without us being present, there is no reason why we should jump to the conclusion that there is a such a universe which is independent of all beings - of all perception and experience. \r\n\r\nIt should be a clue that when we imagine the universe without perception, we cannot help but imagine a universe exactly as it is from our experience. Atoms are very small, a thousand years is very long, stars are bright, rocks on planets are heavy, etc. Of course, this is complete nonsense. Without a human sized, lifetime scaled phenomenon to serve as the orienting frame of reference, there is no qualitative presentation which can have precedence over any other. Past, future, fast, slow, enormous, tiny, etc... all meaningless. There is no here or there, no way to recognize any distribution of particles as a pattern or any pattern of energy as a particle. Indeed, a universe without an observer is indiscernible from nothing at all. It could only be silent, invisible, intangible. In short, there can be no â€œexternal realityâ€.\r\n\r\nThe second great mistaken assumption about the Hard Problem is that qualia has something to do with representation. It does not. Qualia is presentation. It is the source of all presence. Representation does not need qualia at all. As we have seen, any kind of quality which can be detected by an instrument can be digitized into a generic representation. Qualia would not only be superfluous and unexplainable, it would be an impediment to the transfer of information. \r\n\r\nThe third false assumption in the Hard Problem discussion is derived from the second - after jumping to the conclusion of qualia as representation, the next premature jump extends the metaphor to conscious experience as a model or simulation. If qualia were a representation, an encoded symbol, then it would make sense indeed that a network of symbols (a model) is a good way of describing our experience. \r\n\r\nQuoting Waser:\r\n\r\nâ€œPer Hofstadater [2007], Damasio [2010], and others Llinas [2001], consciousness/self is simply a process running on a physical (â€œstrangeâ€) loop/feedback network created per Richard Dawkinsâ€™ [1976] speculation that â€œperhaps consciousness arises when the brainâ€™s simulation of the world becomes so complete that it must include a model of itselfâ€.â€\r\n\r\nA natural speculation if you are approaching consciousness from the outside, where it has no qualia or presence and can only be inferred by smuggling in our own knowledge of our own consciousness. Consciousness does rely heavily on feedback loops, but feedback of what? Loopness? Thereâ€™s no physics there, no participation or presence. \r\n\r\nIn reality, what is being looped can only be something which is already sensory or proto-sensory for it to conceivably scale up to the full blown human interiority which we experience. A model need not have any more or an experienced presence than a symbol does. It is simply processed from one encoded form to another and never is there any decoding into a significant experience. Inputs are compared with logical expectations, outputs are produced. I doesn\'t matter whether those outputs are hunting a wild boar or incrementing a memory register. There is no way to assign any visceral realism or qualia to differentiate the two, and of course, none are needed. Critical processes need only be assigned higher priority, not some kind of fireworks display of flavors and colors.\r\n\r\nAs far as the \'is my red your green?\' conversation goes, the confusion is because visual qualia is unusual in that it is presented as the most object-like feeling that we can experience. Red is still a feeling, but it is a visual feeling, which seems to be scoped or tuned toward experiences which convey the third person perspective - detached, fully available to examination as a knowable shape/design/color. It is a feeling which in the most public facing way.\r\n\r\nWhat this means is that visual qualia is actually a second order qualia, the first being the feelings that we have *about* the color, or through the color. It is very confusing indeed if we don\'t realize this and conflate both qualia as a single one. From optical experiments we have seen that our visual sense is highly resilient to experimental manipulation, and will quickly route around tricks, such as flipping the image upside down or pushing the chroma median away from true yellow. We get used to it and our visual presentation returns to its inertial norm despite having altered optics.\r\n\r\nCombine these two and we can understand that it is a two way street, with our first order feelings driving the perceptual inertia from the inside out and the second order visual feelings being partially driven by optics. I don\'t know if we all have the same green and red, but if I had to guess, I would say that we have first order feeling qualia which are both more human-universal and personal-idiosyncratic, and second order visual qualia which is more local-physiological-cultural.\r\n\r\nCraig','2013-03-06 02:13:39','2013-03-06 02:13:39'),(2524,96,48,'Talk of encoding qualia in bit patterns assumes that the computational functionalism theory (CF) is true. In addition to physicalism - the mind is instantiated in the brain - CF holds that  the brain is just an information processing system.\r\n\r\nIf CF were true then you could encode a quale as a bit pattern in a computer. Simply envisaged, you could use 1 for red and 2 for blue so a computer system with normal colour processing would output 1 for colour input from a UK post box and 2 for a clear sky. One with an inverted system would output 2 for the box and 1 for sky. But this is arbitrary. Functionally, the two systems are identical yet they output different values for the same input. Therefore CF is false; qualia cannot be data.\r\n\r\nThe inverted qualia argument does not defeat non-functionalist physicalism, however. Yes, the conscious brain is not at all like a computer: qualia are not data, colours are not encoded by bit patterns in the brain. This does not rule out the possibility that consciousness is brain activity, just that it is not information processing.\r\n\r\nI would add that the notion it would be possible to encode information in a glutamate molecule is silly. You can, of course, encode information in DNA sequences but that is because you can change the sequence of bases whereas one glutamate molecule is the same as any other.\r\n\r\n','2013-03-06 09:26:33','2013-03-06 09:26:33'),(2527,96,48,'Proposed consolidation of open Philosophy of Mind issues as aspects of the \"Presentation Problem\" or Unified Presentation Problem (UPP).\r\n\r\nI propose that the Hard Problem, the Explanatory Gap, the Binding Problem, the Symbol Grounding Problem should all be understood as aspects of the same Unified Presentation Problem.\r\n\r\n1. Hard Problem = Why is X presented as an experience?\r\n\r\n(X = â€œinformationâ€, logical or physical functions, calcium waves, action potentials, Bayesian integrations, etc.)\r\n\r\n2. Explanatory Gap = How and where is presentation accomplished with respect to X?\r\n\r\n3. Binding Problem = How are presented experiences segregated and combined with each other? How do presentations cohere?\r\n\r\n4. Symbol Grounding = How are experiences associated with each other on multiple levels of presentation? How do presentations adhere?\r\n\r\n5. Mind Body Problem = Why do public facing presences and private facing presences seem ontologically exclusive and aesthetically opposite to each other?\r\n\r\nMy own proposed answers to these problems can be found here: http://s33light.org/post/46246847025\r\n\r\nThank you,\r\nCraig','2013-03-25 15:50:34','2013-03-25 15:50:34'),(2528,1,69,'\r\n\r\nWe\'ve started a Google doc to help develop draft new version of this camp.\r\n\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1ocUpwBIy-OI2YYYMSKs6nucF5aqa7_syAGxEl93GSgU/edit?usp=sharing\r\n\r\n','2013-06-23 22:35:46','2013-06-23 22:35:46'),(2531,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nAnyone planning on attending [http://www.consciousness.arizona.edu/ TSC 2014] in Tucson?  James, I heard you were interested in attending?\r\n\r\nThey are accepting proposals for \"Workshops\", that require 2 or more presenters.  Would any of you be willing to do a presentation with me, on amplifying the wisdom of the crowd and the results to date on this Consciousness Survey Project?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-06-28 00:46:49','2013-06-28 00:46:49'),(2532,1,105,'\r\nHello.\r\n\r\n','2013-07-08 02:20:15','2013-07-08 02:20:15'),(2533,1,70,'\r\nHi Dawie,\r\n\r\nThanks for your great contribution to the survey project!  Would you mind providing some more information about who you are?  I\'m sure interested.\r\n\r\nI really like, and agree with what you are saying.  Also, Canonizer.com is all about building as much consensus as possible, rather than everyone creating their own lonely camps.  (That\'s what is required for lots of people to communicate, concisely and quantitatively.)  Also, since your camp is competing with the Crypto Coin Law camp, it appears that you disagree with what it contains?  Do you really disagree with it?\r\n\r\nI bet we can merge the World Debt camp with the Crypto Coin Law camp.  Towards this end, if we added something like the below, to the Crypto Coin Law camp, would that be enough to get you to merge with / join our camp?\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n================================\r\n\r\n== World Indebtedness ==\r\nSee wikipedia for a good description of this problem:  http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_debt .  These types of risks are expounded upon in sights like this: http://www.zerohedge.com/news/2013-07-05/opportunity-squandered-we-blew-it .  All such risks to currencies and economies amplify the chances of the leading crypto currencies will continue to increase in value exponentially.\r\n\r\n','2013-07-11 22:20:56','2013-07-11 22:20:56'),(2534,1,70,'Hi Brent\r\n\r\nI stumbled across this interesting project during my liberating discovery of Bitcoins lately.\r\nI am an industrial engineer from South Africa.  I am also a fond follower of Max Keizer\'s shows on RT.com\r\n\r\nI agree with the predictions under Crypto Coin Law in principle.  I would be happy to join your camp for consensus sake. I just found the site a bit tricky to navigate.   I am sure I will learn as I get more familiar.  \r\n\r\nYou can merge is as you\'ve suggested.  \r\nGlad to be joining in.\r\nRegards\r\nDawie Poolman','2013-07-12 17:53:37','2013-07-12 17:53:37'),(2535,1,70,'\r\nHi Dawie,\r\n\r\nInteresting.   Thanks for the info.  Thanks for picking things up, and figuring out how to use things.  You obviously get it way better and faster than most.\r\n\r\nI added a section to the Law of Bitcion camp about risks and debts.  I hope it is to your liking.\r\n\r\nHow about you change the parent of your $10,000/BTC camp to this Law of Bitcoin camp.\r\n\r\nAlso, till we hit a $1000 valuation, we would like to focus all expert predictions around when that valuation will be achieved.  Then we will use how well people made this prediction to determine how well we can trust them to accurately predict when we will reach the $10,000 level, and so on.\r\n\r\nSo would you mind changing your camp to be something like possibly \"$1000/BTC in 2014\" or something?\r\n\r\nVery glad to make your acquaintance!\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-07-13 21:54:14','2013-07-13 21:54:14'),(2536,1,70,'Hi Brent\r\nUpdated!  I think this is much neater now.  Thx for the help.\r\nDawie','2013-07-13 22:10:24','2013-07-13 22:10:24'),(2537,1,70,'\r\n\r\nI\'m thinking \"Law of the Crypto Coin\" rolls off the tongue and could catch on much easier than \"Crypto Coin Law\".\r\n\r\nWhat does everyone else think?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-08-04 17:41:22','2013-08-04 17:41:22'),(2538,1,70,'Sounds good.  Im in for the update','2013-08-04 17:51:39','2013-08-04 17:51:39'),(2539,1,70,'\r\n\r\nWelcome [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=307 Kipp Watson] (AKA SwapperMall),\r\n\r\nThanks for contributing to the crypto currency survey project, especially the great new camp statement you provided for the emerging expert consensus [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/154/6 $1000/BTC] camp currently in review.  (Note: anyone can see the statement before it goes live next week, by selecting the \"Include Review\" option on the side bar)\r\n\r\nFeel free to include a post to this \"Welcome new Supporters\" thread, introducing yourself.  We\'re always interested in how you heard about this survey.  It\'s so great that you were able to figure out the canonization process, so fast, already making significant contributions, with no help.  It seems that most people fail to get it, even after many hours of coaching.\r\n\r\n','2013-08-21 14:18:31','2013-08-21 14:18:31'),(2540,1,70,'Brent,\r\n\r\nThanks for your kind words and your role in canonizer.com.  I\'m not sure if I found out about this website through twitter or bitcointalk, but I\'m glad I found out about this website.\r\n\r\nI remember reading \"Wisdom of the Crowd\" and I like the idea of organizing camps on topics such as Bitcoin and alternative currencies.\r\n\r\nI\'m currently involved in http://swappermall.com, which is being designed to be the go to website for the social network/collaboration needs of  local Bitcoin users/entrepeneurs/swappers.  Drupal 7 themers and developers who would like to get in on the ground floor are invited to contact me about pushing this concept to the next level.\r\n\r\n','2013-08-21 22:09:49','2013-08-21 22:09:49'),(2541,1,70,'Hi Swappermail,\r\n\r\nVery interesting.  I\'ve got a bunch of questions about this.\r\n\r\nWhat are \"Drupal 7 themers\"?\r\n\r\nVery interesting article about [http://swappermall.com/node/5 What do Bitcoins have to do with the IMF?]  Could you tell me how attacks on weak nations currencies take place, as I\'m not familiar with this possibility and how the IMF could intervene?  I know the US, and most of the world is attacking Iran\'s currency.  Is it similar to this?\r\n\r\nIt says: \"Transition to a non-inflationary official national Bitcoin usage by a country could prove to be extremely advantageous for first nation adopters.\"  I could see some ways in which this could be advantageous, such as simply the more any country get\'s in before Bitcoins inflate too much, could increase the wealth of that nation.  But I also see significant possible negatives for a country.  For example, Japan\'s economy has been decimated, for the last 10+ years, because it\'s currency has inflated in value, instead of deflated, like the rest of the world.  They are finally only now recovering, after they are deflating the value of their currency.\r\n\r\nYou mentioned \"Thousand fold\" increases, should the IMF start to hold Bitcoins to help protect member nations, and \"Million Fold\" increases, should it encourage the entire world to adopt Bitcoin is it\'s currency.  Do you realize that \"thousand fold increases\"  make the market cap of Bitcoins more than the Market Cap of all the gold in the world, and the \"Million Fold Increases\" make Bitcoin Market Valuations start to approach the value of all real estate, in the world?  That almost seems tooo aggressive of a prediction to me.  Did you just pull these numbers out of the air, or do you have some solid quantitative rational behind them?\r\n\r\nAlso, I\'m interested in more of what you can do and what you have planned for swapper mail.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-08-23 02:09:09','2013-08-23 02:09:09'),(2544,96,48,'Hi guys, newbie here. I\'ve created a new camp with links to my spirited defence of panexperientialism. My aim is to elicit constructive criticism, so to anybody that takes the time to read through it and offer their comments, much gratitude and respect. Andy.','2013-10-02 10:43:02','2013-10-02 10:43:02'),(2545,1,1,'Hi guys, newbie here. I\'ve added a new camp giving a link to my argument that there is a use of the word \"consciousness\" that is unapproachable via science. The essay is entitled \"In Defence of Panexperientialism\" but don\'t let that put you off. I believe the arguments that I make are sound and I would be thrilled if anybody can undermine this belief. My gratitude and respect goes to anybody that takes the time and trouble to read and provide constructive criticism. Rregards, Andy.','2013-10-02 11:58:05','2013-10-02 11:58:05'),(2546,1,73,'Hi guys, newbie here. I\'ve added a new camp giving a link to my argument that there is a use of the word \"consciousness\" that is unapproachable via science. The essay is entitled \"In Defence of Panexperientialism\" but don\'t let that put you off. I believe the arguments that I make are sound and I would be thrilled if anybody can undermine this belief. My gratitude and respect goes to anybody that takes the time and trouble to read and provide constructive criticism. Rregards, Andy.','2013-10-02 11:58:05','2013-10-02 11:58:05'),(2547,1,1,'Hi guys, newbie here. I\'ve added a new camp giving a link to my argument that there is a use of the word \"consciousness\" that is unapproachable via science. The essay is entitled \"In Defence of Panexperientialism\" but don\'t let that put you off. I believe the arguments that I make are sound and I would be thrilled if anybody can undermine this belief. My gratitude and respect goes to anybody that takes the time and trouble to read and provide constructive criticism. Rregards, Andy.','2013-10-02 11:59:40','2013-10-02 11:59:40'),(2548,1,73,'Hi guys, newbie here. I\'ve added a new camp giving a link to my argument that there is a use of the word \"consciousness\" that is unapproachable via science. The essay is entitled \"In Defence of Panexperientialism\" but don\'t let that put you off. I believe the arguments that I make are sound and I would be thrilled if anybody can undermine this belief. My gratitude and respect goes to anybody that takes the time and trouble to read and provide constructive criticism. Rregards, Andy.','2013-10-02 11:59:40','2013-10-02 11:59:40'),(2549,1,1,'Andy\r\n\r\nI skimmed through your paper but cannot find a formal statement of your argument for panexperientialism. I was expecting a summary of your argument in the introduction or conclusion pointing to a section setting this out in detail.\r\n\r\nIt would help us all if you outlined your argument in your camp statement.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard\r\n\r\n','2013-10-03 09:40:21','2013-10-03 09:40:21'),(2550,1,73,'Andy\r\n\r\nI skimmed through your paper but cannot find a formal statement of your argument for panexperientialism. I was expecting a summary of your argument in the introduction or conclusion pointing to a section setting this out in detail.\r\n\r\nIt would help us all if you outlined your argument in your camp statement.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard\r\n\r\n','2013-10-03 09:40:21','2013-10-03 09:40:21'),(2551,1,1,'Thank you Richard. I have reorganized the section and included statements that I hope will be to your satisfaction. I have also privately mailed you on your alumni account.\r\n\r\nRegards,\r\nAndy.','2013-10-05 07:03:42','2013-10-05 07:03:42'),(2552,1,73,'Thank you Richard. I have reorganized the section and included statements that I hope will be to your satisfaction. I have also privately mailed you on your alumni account.\r\n\r\nRegards,\r\nAndy.','2013-10-05 07:03:42','2013-10-05 07:03:42'),(2555,96,48,'Welcome [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=309 Andy Kay].\r\n\r\nYour new [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/58 Panexperientialism] camp is exciting to see, and it\'s great to have someone start to organize the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/57 Unapproachable Via Science] camp.  I propose that we move all other camps that are currently competing with the [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/2 Approachable Via Science] camp to show what they all agree on.  Including moving the following:\r\n\r\n* [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/25 Advaita and Consciousness]\r\n* [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/41 Consciousness is of Divine Origin and Unfathomable Apart from God]\r\n* [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/26 Consciousness is structurally coded]\r\n\r\nAndy, would you like to move all these camps into supporting positions of your new Unapproachable via science camp?  If you\'d rather, I can do this.  And of course, if anyone objects to such an improvement in the structure, let us know so we can collaboratively work to find what works best for everyone.\r\n\r\nAndy, I have some questions about your new camp and paper, so I\'ll post them to the forum for your [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/58 Panexperientialism] camp.  Note: I\'m focusing on the \"Theories of Mind\" versions, since the \"Hard Problem\" survey topic is now mostly out of date.  Most supporters have abandoned that, and are now only working on this leading version.  There is no need to duplicate all of this effort in both survey topics.\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2013-10-06 17:32:26','2013-10-06 17:32:26'),(2556,309,40,'\r\nHi Andy,\r\n\r\nI like what you have to say about the \"problem of other minds\" and the \"combination problem\".  It sounds like you would agree that there are elemental qualities of mind that can be \'combined\' to create a unified conscious experience.  So, given this assumption, would it not be possible to first, discover what this relationship is, between elements of consciousness, and their underlying correlates, and thereby reliably predict when they exist in other minds?  (in other words, the week form of effing the ineffable as described [http://canonizer.com/topic.asp/88/28 in this camp]).  And secondly, just as these parts of the mind in the left hemisphere are joined together with parts of the mind in the right hemisphere, would it not be possible to use the same merging mechanism, to artificially merge multiple minds, so both were aware of the other, just as our right and left hemispheres are aware of the other, and so on?  This being the stronger version of effing the ineffable.\r\n\r\nAnd if you can do that, as I believe you are predicting, would not consciousness be both very predictable, approachable via science, and so on?\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n','2013-10-06 17:49:01','2013-10-06 17:49:01'),(2559,96,48,'\"the \"Hard Problem\" survey topic is now mostly out of date. Most supporters have abandoned that, and are now only working on this leading version\"\r\n\r\nI\'m curious to what you mean by that. Is there someone who supported a Hard Problem position that abandoned it, or are you just saying that the nomenclature has changed within Canonizer?\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\nCraig\r\n\r\nPS Not to be inflammatory, but IMO, If someone doesn\'t think that the Hard Problem is the most important problem in studying consciousness as a whole, then they cannot possibly understand the Hard Problem.','2013-10-06 21:46:43','2013-10-06 21:46:43'),(2562,96,48,'\r\nHi Multisense,\r\n\r\nIt\'s just that quite some time ago, people proposed that \"Theories of Consciousness\" would be more encompassing than just the \'hard problem\'.  I objected for quite some time, for the very reasons you are mentioning, here.  But then I eventually came around as more and more people spent more time on the \"Theories of Consciousness\" topic, and more and more people just didn\'t keep the older \"Hard Problem\" survey topic up to date, mostly because we don\'t need to have all the information and work duplicated.\r\n\r\n','2013-10-06 22:19:41','2013-10-06 22:19:41'),(2565,96,48,'Ah, thanks Brent. I\'m not sure I was here when it was the old topic.','2013-10-06 23:22:37','2013-10-06 23:22:37'),(2566,309,40,'Brent,\r\n\r\nThe main issue here clearly pertains to any claim that we can discover the nature of the relationship between elements in consciousness and their neural correlates (I have deliberately avoided using the phrase â€œunderlying correlatesâ€ as that priority has yet to be established). I donâ€™t think that prediction is the issue here, but rather explanation. Because of the non-empirical nature of consciousness I argue that whatever explanation we might propose, we cannot test that explanation along scientific lines, and so we cannot conduct a scientific investigation into the mechanism for that correlation. All we are left with is metaphysical conjecture. Do you feel there is a weak point in my argument?\r\n\r\nAndy.','2013-10-07 06:45:45','2013-10-07 06:45:45'),(2567,1,1,'Andy\r\n\r\nGreat stuff: interesting panexperientialism camp statement. I\'ll be considering the points you make in due course and post a reply under that statement rather than here. I\'m sure your words will attract more contributions...\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard','2013-10-10 17:00:41','2013-10-10 17:00:41'),(2568,1,73,'Andy\r\n\r\nGreat stuff: interesting panexperientialism camp statement. I\'ll be considering the points you make in due course and post a reply under that statement rather than here. I\'m sure your words will attract more contributions...\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard','2013-10-10 17:00:41','2013-10-10 17:00:41'),(2569,309,40,'Andy\r\n\r\nIt is not a matter of logic but of fact.\r\n\r\nLogic only rules out impossibilities such as square circles, it doesn\'t tell you whether unicorns exist, or whether brains are the only known organisations of matter that support consciousness.\r\n\r\nThe same error is made by Chalmers: just because a state of affairs is logically possible doesn\'t tell you whether it is in fact the case.\r\n\r\ncheers\r\n\r\nRichard','2013-10-13 07:25:12','2013-10-13 07:25:12'),(2570,309,40,'Richard,\r\n\r\nWhen you say \"it\'s not a matter of logic but of fact\", I presume you\'re addressing the comment in my camp description that \"if there are no logically consistent grounds for denying minds to animal cells then why not to plant cells?\"\r\n\r\nWhat I\'m trying to say is that the claim that individual cells might be associated with minds does not conflict with any known evidence. What are you saying the facts are in this case?\r\n\r\nAndy.','2013-10-14 07:24:27','2013-10-14 07:24:27'),(2571,1,70,'Hi Larry (aka [http://canonizer.com/support_list.asp?nick_name_id=310 xandari]),\r\n\r\nWelcome to the price of Bitcoin survey topic!  Thanks for the support.\r\n\r\nFeel free to introduce yourself on this thread so we can know who you are and understand what kind of Bitcoin expert you are.\r\n\r\nOh, and another question I have is when do you think we will first hit $1000/BTC?\r\n\r\n','2013-10-25 18:48:31','2013-10-25 18:48:31'),(2572,1,70,'\r\n\r\nFolks,\r\n\r\nIn case you are interested, Laura Etudes is doing a global survey of Bitcoiners:\r\n\r\nhttps://www.facebook.com/groups/256406324441664/permalink/538789936203300/\r\n\r\n\r\nUpwards\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2013-11-02 11:35:58','2013-11-02 11:35:58'),(2575,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nWe\'re working on a paper we intend to submit to the 2014 Towards A Science of Consciousness conference.  The title is: \"Neural Substitution Fallacy\"\r\n\r\nOnce you understand, and then eliminate the fallacy, the so called \"hard problem\' of consciousness goes with it.\r\n\r\nThe working draft Google doc is here:\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1fQeWrCjXp-kO18NRfrNJrropqaLMdaBrMq7c9KbqtdE/edit?usp=sharing\r\n\r\nI\'d love to hear anyone\'s thoughts on this.\r\n\r\n','2013-11-03 23:38:12','2013-11-03 23:38:12'),(2578,96,48,'I don\'t understand what the argument has to do with the hard problem. You have a glutamate detector, ok, so what universe does \"red\" come from? Why not \"dizzy #7\" or just the intuitive presence of \"glutamate\", just as we would intuitively know what number comes after 12. \r\n\r\nAs far as I can tell, red has no plausible functional value or material definition - it is purely aesthetic. There is no function whose complexity, upon exceeding some threshold, would be able to find expression as a flavor or color. Why would it, when ordinary quantitative compression techniques have any limitations that qualitative compression would surpass.\r\n\r\nNow that we know that neurons themselves have nervous systems (http://medicalxpress.com/news/2013-10-neuroscientists-mini-neural-brain.html), I think that the whole premise of consciousness as simply neural computation is beginning to unravel.','2013-11-04 00:20:20','2013-11-04 00:20:20'),(2581,96,48,'Also, not to be overly critical, but the paper begins with an argument from authority fallacy. If you have already decided that only functionalism or materialism can be valid on the basis of popularity, the entire potential of the hard problem to transform our understanding of consciousness is amputated from the start.','2013-11-04 00:38:13','2013-11-04 00:38:13'),(2584,96,48,'Hi Craig,\r\n\r\nFirst off, we are just pointing out the consensus, in the opening line, just to say where we are going, and that we agree with this consensus.  As you can see, we also point out that a functionalist view is the consensus view, and we are pointing out that we think this is wrong, and based on the fallacy we are pointing out.\r\n\r\nAs far as what \'red\' is, you need to realize that there are two important parts to red.  There is the initial cause of a perception of red, which is when something reflects something like 650 NM light.  Very different form this is you knowledge of the strawberry, or the final result of the perception process.  So you must realize that when you say \'red\' the way you are, you are revealing your ignorance on this issue, and it seems to me not talking nor thinking clearly about things.\r\n\r\nA \'redness quality\' is something very different than a causal property, like reflecting 650 NM light.  Our brain merely uses our \'redness quality\' to represent the latter.  And of course, you could have inverted qualia, by inverting the read green signal anywhere in the perception process.  In other words, if you invert it, your brain will then represent the strawberry with greenness, and the leaves with redness.\r\n\r\nIf you fully understand that, we can move on to better understand this neuro substitution fallacy, and why the causal properties of glutamate could be one and the same as the qualitative properties of redness, which we experience, and represent the strawberry with (that is unless we have inverted color glasses).\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2013-11-04 18:14:12','2013-11-04 18:14:12'),(2587,96,48,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\nI only mention my view to give some indication of how it might be received by those do not subscribe to popular views on the subject. Certainly, there is room for everyone to express their own take on it, and I don\'t mean to imply that every view be exhaustively argued before it can be voiced.\r\n\r\nAs far as red corresponding to a wavelength of electromagnetic radiation, this may not be especially meaningful. Indeed, we can mechanically press on our own eyeball, or dream in color to produce color without having a corresponding photon release. This is easier to think about with the other senses. If we imagine the flavors of a Thanksgiving dinner, we do not expect that there is anything which can be found in the brain that literally smells like turkey, stuffing, cranberries, etc.\r\n\r\nEven in the most materialistic perspective, the existence of color would be much more likely to be rooted in biology than electromagnetism. There was a study recently which shows this in the way that people\'s perception of yellow is independent from the number of yellow-biased cone cells.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.rochester.edu/news/show.php?id=2299\r\n\r\nAs far as being ignorant about the issue, I can assure you that is not the case:\r\n\r\nhttp://multisenserealism.com/thesis/light-revisited/is-visible-light-electromagnetic/\r\n\r\n\"Our brain merely uses our \'redness quality\' to represent the latter.\"\r\n\r\nI think that\'s most likely circular reasoning. There is no evidence of anything turning red, or tasting like cranberries in the brain. If our brain represents anything, it would most likely use the many quantitative channels available to it - electrical signals, chemical secretions, biological mechanisms. The brain no more needs red than the liver or lungs do.\r\n\r\n\" why the causal properties of glutamate could be one and the same as the qualitative properties of redness, which we experience\"\r\n\r\nWhat does it mean though for a colorless microphysical structure - a molecular body in space, to be \'one and the same\' with redness, or dizzyness, or the sound of a rain drop? What would be the point functionally or materially of this unexplainable united dualism?\r\n\r\nIt confuses me because it seems somewhat obvious that all it does is shrink the mind body problem to become a molecular scale mind-body problem. We are no closer to explaining where the redness is, what it is made of, why we prefer it to invisible data, etc. We are just announcing that there is no problem, since whatever we want could be called a causal property of glutamate.\r\n','2013-11-04 19:24:53','2013-11-04 19:24:53'),(2590,96,48,'\r\nHi Craig,\r\n\r\nIn your paper, what do you mean by \"directly\" when you say?:\r\n\r\n\"our experience of directly seeing natural sources of color\"\r\n\r\nIn that statement what where and how is a redness quality experience?\r\n\r\nYou have lots of information about how the retina works, but that really has nothing to do with a redness quality, as a redness quality is a quality of the final result of the perception process.  It has nothing to do with light, the retina, or even the optic nerve.  it is a quality we can experience, that exists in the visual cortex.  The proof of this, is that you can experience and dream, even if your eyes have been cut out. and you are in a pitch black room with no light at all.\r\n\r\nwhen you talk about things \'turning red\' or  when you ask:\r\n\r\n\"What does it mean though for a colorless microphysical structure - a molecular body in space, to be \'one and the same\' with redness?\"\r\n\r\nthat\'s not the best way to think about it.\r\n\r\nLet\'s assume you are in the theoretical \"Idealized Effing Theory World\" for a bit.  In that world it is glutamate that has a redness quality we can experience as knowledge of something like a strawberry we are looking at.\r\n\r\nGlutamate reflects \"white\" light.  So let us say this set of neurons is producing an experience of a red strawberry with glutamate.  Now, when you look at it, you see the white light reflecting off the glutamate, that is responsible for the redness quality experience.  So, if I say that glutamate is \'White\', simply because my brain decides to represent it with knowledge that has a whiteness property, is there a problem with that assumption?\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\n','2013-11-04 21:42:19','2013-11-04 21:42:19'),(2593,96,48,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\n\"In that statement what where and how is a redness quality experience?\"\r\n\r\nI think that all experience takes place \"here\". The \"what\" and \"how\" of redness would be as meaningless as asking \"who\" and \"why\" about the existence of electromagnetism. If we attach body mechanisms to our definition of qualia, then we are not addressing qualia.\r\n\r\nWe cannot say that vision exists in the visual cortex, since people who are blind from birth experience stimulation of their visual cortex as tactile sensations.\r\n\r\n\"So, if I say that glutamate is \'White\', simply because my brain decides to represent it with knowledge that has a whiteness property, is there a problem with that assumption?\"\r\n\r\nYes, it\'s a problem because all you are doing is pushing the problem down a level. Instead of me seeing a white cloud in the world with my eyes, I am now seeing a white ensemble of glutamate in my brain with my homunculus eyes. If I need to have this representational medium stand between the world and my model of it, why wouldn\'t I also need another medium to stand between myself and my model? If I can see glutamate as white, and my brain can see clouds and produce glutamate to represent them, how am I able to see the white of glutamate (which is invisible to inspection of the brain) but not what my eyes are seeing?\r\n\r\nIt all comes down to circular reasoning, where we say \"Beauty exists because we have evolved to see what we are attracted to as beautiful.\" and \"Beauty is beautiful because we are attracted to it.\" We are laying claim to the principle that we are trying to describe. \"What is red?\", \"It is that which is produced by inherently red processes or materials.\"','2013-11-04 22:36:54','2013-11-04 22:36:54'),(2596,96,48,'Brent and Steven: The proposed statement starts off by reflecting the main debate but talk of neurotransmitters being the source of qualia is rubbish IMO. Such speculation is unnecessary and would, i suggest, cause many readers to take a dim view of canonizer. Why not keep the account at the general level?\r\n\r\nI also think that your speculation that there is a binding neuron will compound the readers\' scepticism of our project.','2013-11-05 09:43:01','2013-11-05 09:43:01'),(2599,96,48,'Craig\r\n\r\n\"We cannot say that vision exists in the visual cortex, since people who are blind from birth experience stimulation of their visual cortex as tactile sensations.\" is a non-sequitur. There is no contradiction in the idea that the part of the cortex which provides vision in sighted people can provide touch in the blind.','2013-11-05 10:00:41','2013-11-05 10:00:41'),(2602,96,48,'\r\nHi Rich,\r\n\r\nThanks for this comment and all your help.  Perhaps you can help me understand what you are saying?\r\n\r\nThanks to Jame\'s continued objection, and eternal effort to help me understand things from a functionalist\'s point of view, I think I finally figured out how to say what it is I\'m trying to say, so that functionalists can understand.  I just recently added the required additional paragraph to the end of the abstract:\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1fQeWrCjXp-kO18NRfrNJrropqaLMdaBrMq7c9KbqtdE/edit?usp=sharing\r\n\r\nSo I say the same thing to you, Rich.  Do you agree that the neural substitution argument is problematic, and that this argument is a big reason for why so many functionalists, are functionalists?\r\n\r\nCertainly you must agree that there is some neural correlate, that includes some necessary and sufficient physical conditions, in order for one to experience an elemental redness quality?  Certainly, you must be able to reliably detect whatever this is, if you assume consciousness is approachable via science.  And certainly, we  must be able to find a way to avoid the quale interpretation problem, and represent the same thing in someone else\'s brain, whatever it is, and thereby reliably eff the ineffable, solve the problem of other minds, and so on.\r\n\r\nIf you remove the binding mechanism from the picture, then the functionalists will go right back to their neural substitution argument that has the fallacy which is keeping them from understanding what is important.  Remember, think of glutamate as just the idealized or symbolic representation.  Feel free to interpret it as whatever you could think are the necessary and sufficient set of physical properties that is the neural correlate to an elemental redness quality we can reliably experience.\r\n\r\nIf I\'m still missing what you are getting at, perhaps you can help me understand what you mean by \"Why not keep the account at the general level?\"\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2013-11-05 11:36:52','2013-11-05 11:36:52'),(2605,96,48,'Rich,\r\n\r\n\"There is no contradiction in the idea that the part of the cortex which provides vision in sighted people can provide touch in the blind.\"\r\n\r\nMy point was that whether activity is in the visual cortex or not cannot be the determining factor in whether vision is provided. Providing access to certain sense modalities is not the same thing as saying that they are \"in\" a certain part of the brain, anymore than I can say that Canonizer is \"in\" certain parts of my computer or screen.\r\n\r\nCraig','2013-11-05 12:38:54','2013-11-05 12:38:54'),(2608,96,48,'Brent\r\n\r\nYou ask \" Do you agree that the neural substitution argument is problematic, and that this argument is a big reason for why so many functionalists, are functionalists?\"\r\n\r\nYes, i agree. If functionalism were true then it is obvious that substitution of any or all neurons with functional equivalents would result in no change. The prevalent view is that neurons are computational devices and so you could program a suitably powerful computer to emulate the brain, consciousness included. This is wrong IMO.\r\n\r\nYes i agree that there is an NCC and so consciousness is approachable via scientific investigation.\r\n\r\nAs someone who knows a thing or two about molecular biology, the idea that glutamate could represent the the experience of red is absurd and incoherent and so should be dropped from the statement.\r\n\r\nThe single neuron theory of binding is IMO fanciful and should also be dropped. By all means talk about the binding problem but why cite this specific theory? Is there is a lot of support for it on canonizer?\r\n\r\nI advise keeping it more general because these specifics - the neurotransmitter example and the single neuron theory - will, i suspect, cause many scientists to simply dismiss canonizer as fringe.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-11-15 11:11:46','2013-11-15 11:11:46'),(2611,96,48,'Craig\r\n\r\nAgreed that mere detection of some activity cannot tell you what type of experience is occurring, indeed cannot even tell if any is occurring - it could be unconscious.\r\n\r\nThis is, however, a limitation of our current brain scanning techniques.  When we can detect the NCC this will be possible. In your example, a future brain scan will show whether visual experience or touch experience is occurring.\r\n','2013-11-15 11:23:29','2013-11-15 11:23:29'),(2614,96,48,'Rich, \r\n\r\nYou said,\r\n\r\n\"a future brain scan will show whether visual experience or\r\ntouch experience is occurring.\"\r\n\r\nThat may be, but still only retrospectively. The brain scan is showing only that a the brain activity belongs to one pre-established category or another. These categories are mathematical descriptions so that any connection between them and the actual aesthetic difference between subjective visual or tactile modes must be inferred by human beings. \r\n\r\nIt is a bit like saying \"a future analysis of ballot boxes will show whether Republican or Democrats take more pride in their candidate.\"\r\n\r\nIn both cases, what is lacking is the prospective view. The brain scan cannot tell what a new kind of sense looks like, because it has no familiarity with sense at all, only a mathematical description of brain activity. The voting booth can\'t really know what pride is, it can only deduce statistically what chad belongs to which inferred category.\r\n\r\n','2013-11-15 14:26:46','2013-11-15 14:26:46'),(2617,96,48,'Hi Craig,\r\n\r\nThis conversation is the greatest!  Everything you say is correct, but you are still missing a critically important \'effing\' possibility.\r\n\r\nYou are right, if you detect the neural correlate of your redness, all such detection will be is abstract information that suffers from the \"quale interpretation problem\".\r\n\r\nSo, in order to overcome this quale interpretation problem, we simply need to direct that same detector to my brain, and show me different colored objects until it detects the neural correlate for your redness.\r\n\r\nInverted qualia is a definite possibility such as your redness could be what my brain uses for greenness.  So I would say: \"Wow, that\'s not my redness, that\'s my greenness!\"\r\n\r\nAnd surely there will be various types of diversity and variability between people such as different types of tetrachromats and trichromats, (even if only artificially modified).  This will make it possible to validate that you reliably have consistent and reliable map of neural correlates to the set of all possible elemental qualities, enabling one to fully know how to properly interpreted any detected neural correlates.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n','2013-11-15 22:44:25','2013-11-15 22:44:25'),(2620,96,48,'Hi Brent,\r\n\r\nThe example of color is actually a little deceiving, compared to something like flavor. It is easy to make an unsupported leap from abstract information to color because we can visualize the data as some kind of code or arrangement of bits and color as the same kind of thing, only with colored pixels. Of all the senses, visual sense is most isomorphic to public forms and functions. We can picture an (inverted) physical image on our retina that then is simply moved into the visual cortex as some kind of Fourier transform. Just as the fragmentation of sectors on a hard drive or memory paging through RAM does not give us an isomorphic image of the user content, we are still very comfortable with the idea of the user experience being reconstituted somehow, without having to be formally represented. The formal representation, while still somewhat mysteriously absent, plays a very conventional role of being simply a particular encoding format. Visual qualia can just be a compression algorithm and we leave it at that.\r\n\r\nTactile qualia also has a lot of easy-isomorphism that we can treat that way without much thought. Something like olfactory qualia, or auditory qualia present a better example of why the explanatory gap/quale interpretation problem goes far beyond data encoding. The entire issue of effability seems beside the point to me. Qualia is ineffable because it is private, but privacy or uniqueness in and of itself doesn\'t challenge our view of physics. It is not that my green may be your red, but that our Thanksgiving turkey flavor is an experience of flavor rather than a quantitatively compressed data set. The elephant in the room, for me, is not the quale interpretation problem, but the need for any additional aesthetic \"interpretation\" at all.\r\n\r\nCraig','2013-11-16 00:08:36','2013-11-16 00:08:36'),(2623,96,48,'\r\n\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nThanks to the help of James Carroll, and many others, I think I\'ve significantly improved the 500 word abstract, and made it much more clear.\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1fQeWrCjXp-kO18NRfrNJrropqaLMdaBrMq7c9KbqtdE/edit?usp=sharing\r\n\r\nI\'d love to know if you guys agree that it is better.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-11-24 20:07:29','2013-11-24 20:07:29'),(2624,1,70,'\r\n\r\nNeener, Neener, Neener.  I, the lone supporter of the 2013 camp was right, and all you expert consensus duds saying 2014 were wrong! ;)\r\n\r\n\r\nOK, I admit, when we started this, I was predicting 2015.  But I was the first to jump to the 2013 camp.\r\n\r\nRemember, if you stay active, you can increase the value of the information in this survey, and increase your reputation for the next %1000 increase predictions.\r\n\r\nAnyway, back to business.  We now need to convert the camps to when we all think we will make $10,000/BTC.  Could everyone post something to this thread indicating their prediction, and we\'ll convert the 2014 consensus camp, to whatever is the new consensus prediction, keeping to a minimum, the number of people that will have to change their camp.\r\n\r\nThanks all, for the help!\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-11-30 15:47:24','2013-11-30 15:47:24'),(2627,96,48,'Craig\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure what you\'re getting at. Future brain scanners, able to monitor the neural correlates of conscious experiences, would be calibrated to known experiences such as seeing red or experiencing pride. Of course we have to perform the calibration and i assume this would require adjustment for individual differences.\r\n\r\nIn your example, such a scanner will reliably report what is going on in the brain of blind and sighted people because that is how it would be designed and calibrated. Quite how this is done we have yet to discover, of course, but don\'t you see that this is inevitable unless the astonishing hypothesis is wrong?','2013-12-01 11:24:55','2013-12-01 11:24:55'),(2630,96,48,'Brent and Craig\r\n\r\nI think the concept of inverted qualia is misconceived. The problem only arises if you believe in computational functionalism. I agree with Craig that qualia cannot be represented as bit patterns. The colours you see on a computer display do indeed correspond to bit patterns but this has nothing to do with how the brain\'s visual system works: there is no bit pattern in the brain for red and a different one for green since the brain is not a digital computer.\r\n\r\nCraig: perhaps this is what you are getting at when you challenge my idea of future brain scanning? To me it is daft to envision such devices as correlating bit patterns with experiences: this is not the NCC at all :)','2013-12-01 11:48:31','2013-12-01 11:48:31'),(2633,96,48,'reply to post 18\r\n\r\nBrent\r\n\r\nNot sure i understand the final paragraph but then i\'m in neither of the mainstream camps ;)\r\n\r\nMy primary objection remains the same: your talk of glutamate in relation to experience is IMO incoherent, off the wall, and invites ridicule from anyone with knowledge of molecular biology..','2013-12-01 12:01:34','2013-12-01 12:01:34'),(2636,96,48,'Rich,\r\n\r\nI do think that the astonishing hypothesis is half wrong (well, half wrong for human beings, completely wrong for matter in general, in that matter is a sensory experience, not the other way around.) but yes it sounds like we agree on the non-computational, or trans-computational nature of qualia.\r\n\r\nSomething like a brain scanner is only giving us a view of certain conditions, like magnetic resonance and blood oxygen levels, through which we can infer the brain or conscious experience. It would be like programming a Google car to drive through Paris, taking pictures of all of the road signs, and by putting these signs in order and correlating them with our visits to Paris, we can imagine that the signs play a key role in the functioning of French culture. \r\n\r\nWe could find all kinds of interesting patterns about where and when certain cultural events happen by sending more Google cars into Paris, comparing maps of the road signs to Tweets and blog posts on the internet. The goal is to come out with a master list which correlates each road sign and each position to the specific functions of French society - the fashion, the food, the language, the art, etc. The fact that this can be done, while useful in actually being able to fix French cities more effectively if they are damaged, does not mean that the assumption of a causal connection between road signs and culture exists. In reality, road signs refer to narrow, local conditions related to driving, not mechanisms for building the Louvre.\r\n\r\nCraig','2013-12-01 12:44:56','2013-12-01 12:44:56'),(2639,96,48,'\r\nHi Rich,\r\n\r\nYou are missing the point we\'re trying to communicate.  Glutamate is not intended to be a theoretical description of reality, just an example of a reality in a simplified world that makes it easier to understand what is important with the neuro substitution argument.\r\n\r\nGlutamate is just a simplified icon that represents any set of necessary and sufficient causal properties, that is the causal properties of redness.  If you don\'t like glutamate, for this icon, then pick any other set of causes that could be the cases of a redness experience.\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-12-02 14:57:18','2013-12-02 14:57:18'),(2642,96,48,'\r\nTheoreticians,\r\n\r\nThanks, all, for the many contributions to our abstract!  Thanks to all of your help we\'ve rewritten and improved it many times.\r\n\r\nThe abstract is Due Dec 20th, so we\'re considering it to be in its final draft form.  It\'d be great if everyone could give it a quick once over to see if there are any other possible improvements.\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1fQeWrCjXp-kO18NRfrNJrropqaLMdaBrMq7c9KbqtdE/edit?usp=sharing\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-12-15 12:17:30','2013-12-15 12:17:30'),(2643,1,70,'\r\nFolks,\r\n\r\nI\'ve started a Google doc to develop a new consensus version of the \"Law of the Crypto Coin\" camp statement.\r\n\r\nI\'d like to propose the contained new section titled\r\n\r\n    \"Predicted Crypto Currency End Game\".\r\n\r\nI\'d love to have some help improving this statement!\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1G2NaqU2ut1yZOd-AT9an6OPlGZJMVGvr214JWtJ373k/edit?usp=sharing\r\n\r\nUpwards,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2013-12-17 10:40:56','2013-12-17 10:40:56'),(2644,179,12,'Having a \'reason\' for war is paradoxical because war occurs in the absence of reason, certainly when viewed from a broad perspective. The true purpose of war is always concealed behind layers of lies and one cannot reason without truth. Even when the objective of those who incite war are accomplished (dominion,) only a madman would value such an objective.  Only a madman would think that any technological breakthrough accomplished during war was worth the lives and suffering it cost, or that such innovations could not be accomplished in peace.\r\n\r\nIf one were to go to war in defense of one\'s family, that would be understandable.  But has it ever accomplished a true victory against the forces of dominion and war?  The present world is enthralled to the most corrupt, invasive, destructive force of dominion that the earth has ever known in the World Bank.  Our only chance of salvation lies in peace, in non-participation, in innovation, in education, in communication and in truth.','2014-07-24 15:34:22','2014-07-24 15:34:22'),(2645,179,12,'\r\nHi benjojomojo,\r\n\r\nInteresting take on war.\r\n\r\nWelcome to canonizer.com, and it\'s nice to see what you currently believe.\r\n\r\nThanks for the contributions,\r\n\r\nBrent Allsop\r\n\r\n\r\n','2014-07-27 17:23:23','2014-07-27 17:23:23');
